<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
Sept. 07. If you have any questions, please call Patricia Hardin on
the Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4753.
</P>
<P>
   TONE-PRINCESS: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Is it possible to be a
billionaire Saudi princess, an aspiring sports mogul, a Kansas City
businesswoman with a string of bad debts and a fugitive from a
felony arrest warrant all at once? &QL; 
Yes. If you believe ``Princess Thara Baselia Saud.''But publicity
surrounding Saud's bid this summer to buy two Colorado sports teams
and a Denver arena has raised questions about her royal title. It
also has spotlighted her checkered business career in Kansas City,
where she's known as Latonett ``Tone'' Hollander. By MARK MORRIS
and JOYCE SMITH. Story will move in the ``a'' category.PRATT-EVOL:
PRATT, Kan. _ If state biologist Chris Mammoliti is successful,
public school students in this small Kansas community won't be
getting the same old Darwin next year. Mammoliti, who works for the
Kansas Wildlife and Parks Department, has asked two Pratt County
school boards to add ``intelligent design'' to their science
classes as a supplement to Darwin's theory of evolution and natural
selection. That is something no other school district in the nation
has done, according to the National Center for Science Education.
By JIM SULLINGER. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
PARKS-CONTAM _ EUREKA, Mo. _ For years, barricades protected the
curious from Times Beach's toxic threats. The guards at a
contaminated former Army plant in Weldon Spring were just as
foreboding. But soon, planners will complete an almost unimaginable
transformation, turning these danger zones into lush playgrounds
that welcome visitors. The Times Beach site, where more than
265,000 tons of dioxin-tainted dirt and debris were incinerated,
will be home to the 409-acre Route 66 State Park. The park will
open to the public on Saturday. The Weldon Spring plant, where the
Department of Energy is burying debris contaminated with
radioactive waste, will link to the popular Katy Trail and the
August A. Busch Conservation Area. By OSCAR AVILA. Story will move
in the ``a'' category.
</P>
