u s BC-FBC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-07 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IT was 1995, and the Rice Owls were doing the smart thing, which
might be redundant.
</P>
<P>
   But as Rice now is at a crossroads in its athletic history _ and
if you think it's anything but a crossroads, you're wrong _ the
moment deserves to be remembered again.
</P>
<P>
   The Southwest Conference had gone defunct, as Texas A&AMP;M, Texas,
Baylor and Texas Tech decided it was time they started spending
their football weekends eating at the big table. Rice and others
were left to fight over scraps at some rickety card table in the
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Few could blame the SWC's bigger powers for bolting, although
few also thought those big boys would immediately enjoy bright days
in the new Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   But the Owls latched onto the Western Athletic Conference and
promised never to let go. It seemed this high-integrity institution
was having the last laugh and taking quite a good turn for its
football program, all things considered.
</P>
<P>
   While the Aggies and Longhorns would bop around Waco, Ames and
Lincoln trying to find their way, the Owls would have to make do in
San Diego and Honolulu.
</P>
<P>
   While cross-town rival Houston was in the midst of NCAA
probation and something called Conference USA, of which little was
known and even less expected, the Owls seemed to have solid footing
and a heck of a travel itinerary. Darn the luck, and pass the
SPF-25.
</P>
<P>
   But then the Owls were spurned again. The only truly attractive
television commodities that WAC football ever had _ Brigham Young
and Air Force _ decided the conference suddenly was beneath them.
They bolted out of the league to form the Mountain West Conference
with other defectors.
</P>
<P>
   So there were the Owls again. Ditched.
</P>
<P>
   And now come more whispers in the wind, with TCU and SMU
apparently on their way to Conference USA. This latest WAC shake-up
could be devastating for the Owls, certainly putting the Rice
athletic programs in tough financial straits. It also would all but
guarantee more check-cashing bloodlettings like the upcoming Rice
trips to Michigan and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   By now, the Owls probably have heard every excuse short of
``It's not you; it's me'' in all these breakups. They have been
mistreated, used, abused and then mistreated again.
</P>
<P>
   But as Rice athletic director Bobby May has said, ``What matters
is how you react.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes. And what might matter most at this point is that Rice stops
reacting like a revered institution of higher learning and starts
acting like a school that cares about its football program. That
is, if it cares.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible not to respect Rice president Malcolm Gillis for
always wanting to do everything ``in honorable fashion,'' as he
said amid the TCU and SMU news.
</P>
<P>
   But why can't you be honorable and also start burning the phone
lines trying to make your way into C-USA, which seems like the most
logical choice for the Owls?
</P>
<P>
   The Owls need to look out for themselves, because clearly no one
else is looking out for them. Sure, Rice made a commitment to the
WAC and promised to be true, but how true has the WAC been to the
Owls?
</P>
<P>
   The Rice faithful needn't look any further than Saturday night's
game against Houston and the weekend's other area football results
to see how close things are to slipping away.
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars didn't just belt the Owls. They showed them a
quaint, colorful revamped stadium and an energy around the program
that hadn't been felt in years.
</P>
<P>
   Among other C-USA wins over the weekend were impressive starts
by East Carolina, which beat West Virginia, and Louisville, which
knocked off Kentucky. Alabama-Birmingham also narrowly lost to
Missouri, and Memphis dropped a tough one to Ole Miss 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   C-USA is doing fine, thank you. In fact, it has the second-best
non-conference record in the nation after two weekends of football
(4-2), trailing only the Atlantic Coast Conference.
</P>
<P>
   At game's end Saturday, the Coogs might as well have held up a
banner to the Owls fans that read, ``This could be you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Owls also can see that the Aggies and Longhorns are in fact
doing fine in the Big 12, having won a couple of conference
championships already. And among those former WAC teams that
departed this year for the Mountain West, Colorado State upset
Colorado, and Utah blasted Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls need to react to all this and react quickly. Find a
conference. Call C-USA. Start acting like a school with a big-time
football program, assuming you still want one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
