<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS FAILS, YANKS LOSE TO ANGELS, 5-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ If you believe in omens, this figured to be a
good day for the Yankees' Roger Clemens. His teammate Allen Watson
heard the song ``Rocket Man'' on three radio stations while driving
to Edison Field, and Joe Girardi cheerily returned after the birth
of his first child to catch Clemens, intending to pass out cigars
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   And everybody recalled what great stuff Clemens had in his last
outing, his 98 mph fastball and his hard-bending slider. Surely
Clemens was ready for lasting excellence, some of his teammates
felt.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe not. Clemens had one of his worst outings of the
season, surviving just 4 2/3 innings Monday night with a decidedly
mediocre repertory and the same inconsistent command in a 5-3 loss
to Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this is the way it is going to be in 1999. With less than
a month to go in the regular season, there is not enough time for a
true breakout from Clemens. The Yankees expected the Santa Claus of
pitching, and instead they are getting the plaid tie from Aunt
Mildred.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is not going to get any Cy Young award votes. He is not
going to win 20 games. He is not going to lead the league in
strikeouts. With about five starts remaining, he will probably not
generate any more than 15 victories.
</P>
<P>
   It is all about the postseason now. The Yankees' lead in the
American League East has been shaved to 6 1/2 games, but barring a
complete collapse, they are headed to the playoffs. At that time,
Clemens will be judged wholly on how he performs in October.
</P>
<P>
   By struggling this season, he has been unable to establish
credibility with Yankee fans. If he pitches effectively in the
postseason and the Yankees win, then he will have passed the
ultimate test of their fans. If he pitches poorly and the Yankees
lose, however, then the trade of David Wells to Toronto for Clemens
will be seen as the move that sank a team coming off a season of
125 victories and a championship. That is an unfair perception,
considering all the other circumstances of this season. But this is
the reality facing Clemens now.
</P>
<P>
   This is probably not a daunting prospect to him. Mel
Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach, has been surprised at how
much Clemens likes challenges like this: He thrives on the prospect
of having runners on base, of pitching on the edge. And as
Stottlemyre has got to know Clemens, he is sure this is part of the
reason the right-hander has been so successful.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the season, however, Clemens has been unable to pitch
out of the trouble he creates. He had few real weapons to do so
Monday night. His fastball, so good last week when he pitched
against Oakland, was perhaps 4 to 5 mph slower than it was last
week, and his command in the first inning was awful. Darin Erstad
forced Clemens to a full count before grounding out, and then
Clemens walked the next two hitters, Jim Edmonds and Tim Salmon, on
a total of nine pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Facing his former Boston teammate Mo Vaughn, Clemens threw a
fastball and Vaughn popped out foul. But then Clemens appeared to
hang a slider to the hulking third baseman Troy Glaus, who swung
and bashed the ball into the back of the Angels' bullpen beyond the
left-field fence. It was 3-0, just like that. About a third of the
88 runs Clemens has allowed this year have been scored in the first
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens walked Jeff Huson to lead off the second inning, walking
about halfway between the mound and home plate to scream at umpire
Bill Miller over a ball-strike interpretation, perhaps the most
animated Clemens has been all year. He shut out the Angels through
the second, third and fourth innings.
</P>
<P>
   But his pitch count was staggering _ 24 in the first, 19 in the
second and 26 in the third. He was near 100 in the fifth. Clemens
fell behind Erstad, two balls and no strikes, and allowed a single.
He threw two straight balls to Edmonds followed by a fastball that
Edmonds expected, and the Angels' center fielder launched it for a
two-run home run. Shortly thereafter, Clemens was relieved, having
allowed six hits, four walks and five runs.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens did not pitch well and his record fell to 12-8, but he
probably would not have won in any event for want of run support.
Jarrod Washburn, who was 0-3 with a 9.15 earned run average coming
into the game, stifled the Yankees' lineup. Shane Spencer got a run
back for the Yankees in the fifth inning, by slamming his first
home run since June, and in the seventh, Chili Davis pounded his
17th home run, his first since early August.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scored again in the eighth, when Derek Jeter hit a
run-scoring single, but Troy Percival closed out matters in the
ninth.
</P>
</TEXT>
