<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 PRINCESS OR PRETENDER? fORMER KC BUSINESSWOMAN DODGES DEBTS, (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS and JOYCE SMITH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Is it possible to be a billionaire Saudi
princess, an aspiring sports mogul, a Kansas City businesswoman
with bad debts and a fugitive from a felony arrest warrant all at
once?
</P>
<P>
   Yes. If you believe Princess Thara Baselia Saud.
</P>
<P>
   But publicity surrounding her bid this summer to buy two
Colorado sports teams and a Denver arena has raised questions about
her royal title. It also has spotlighted her checkered business
career in Kansas City, where she's known as Latonett ``Tone''
Hollander.
</P>
<P>
   In late July the self-proclaimed princess mystified Denver when
she announced she was making a $450 million bid for a sports arena,
the Denver Nuggets basketball franchise and the Colorado Avalanche
hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   She backed up the bid attempt with a resume that claimed a
doctorate from the London School of Economics. She later claimed an
additional doctorate from the University of California-Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief period in late July, she was a fixture in the Denver
media. Columnists hooted at the prospect of a Saudi princess owning
an NBA team, and she was a featured item on cable sports channels.
</P>
<P>
   Her bid never was in serious contention, according to those
familiar with the sale. It fell $11 million short of the winning
proposal, and she never submitted financial statements or bank
guarantees to document her purported oil wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Other problems have since surfaced. Schools where she claimed to
have done her doctoral work could not confirm that she earned the
degrees under the names she provided.
</P>
<P>
   Questions have arisen about her claims to a Saudi royal title.
They rest, she said, on her marriage two decades ago to a dashing
Saudi test pilot she met in a club at an Air Force base in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   She said that before his death in a plane crash, they had a son.
That son, she said, is 20 years old today and worth more than $3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent telephone interview with The Kanas City Star,
Hollander, 47, defended her claim to a royal title but also
acknowledged that she once was a Kansas City businesswoman who
scooted out of town in 1994, facing lawsuits from angry creditors
and a felony bad check warrant from Jackson County.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never hidden the fact that I am ... Hollander. I have
never denied that,'' she said. ``I have not always lived as a
princess. I've only used the `princess' since my son came back in
1996.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Saudi Arabian Embassy in Washington said
diplomats there were unaware of a Princess Thara Baselia Saud or
any links to the kingdom's royal family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We checked on the situation, and the name is not familiar,''
said Jamel Nasef, director of the embassy's information office.
``We'd pay attention to the wife of a prince. I've never heard of
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasef also said the embassy had no knowledge of a royal prince
coming to the United States, marrying Hollander or having a child.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hollander says her son is in the United States now,
attending college, she refused to say anything about him other than
his first name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was married to a prince....And I got my son back in 1996,''
she said. ``His first name is Jamal, and I can't give any more
information.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saudi embassy doubts her claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one thing for sure: If there is a prince here in the
United States or living in the United States, we would know right
away, because they come through us,'' Nasef said.
</P>
<P>
   Hollander's claims to a royal title haven't made much of a
splash with the Saudi government, but her work in Kansas City
created ripples in the business and arts communities.
</P>
<P>
   Little is known of her life before 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Her four-page biography says she was born in the early 1950s in
the Rosedale area of Kansas City, Kan., and taken as an infant to
live with unidentified relatives in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Hollander said her life's brightest moments came in Europe and
in her 1970s marriage to the Saudi prince after she had returned to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   She said her darkest moments were tied to a series of failed
marriages and persistent ill health.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hollander offered few details that could be verified. She
acknowledged and defended the vagueness that permeated her own
accounts of her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a devoted friend who respects the sanctity of private
relationships, I will always protect those with whom I have shared
my life,'' she said in a written statement to The Star. ``If this
may call into question the veracity of my identity, so be it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
