<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI POSES QUESTION FOR MRS. CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Continuing a skirmish with his potential opponent for
the Senate, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Monday that first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton should be asked why she had belatedly called
on her husband to withdraw his clemency offer to imprisoned members
of a Puerto Rican terrorist group.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the mayor offered another round of sharp
condemnation of the president's decision last month to offer
clemency to 16 members of the Puerto Rican organization, the Armed
Forces of National Liberation. The group, known by its Spanish
initials FALN, was said to have been involved in more than 100
bombings in the United States during the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make sense to give clemency to people who are not
remorseful,'' Giuliani said. He pointed out that the president has
only rarely offered clemency in the past and said he should explain
his rationale more fully to both ``the American people and
Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Mrs. Clinton, the mayor said: ``I know she originally
strongly supported it, but now she strongly opposes it. She'll have
to answer questions on why she changed her position.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton triggered criticism over the weekend from Hispanic
political leaders in New York by calling on the president to
rescind the offer of clemency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
