<SLUG> BC-TONE-PRINCESS-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN  
 PRINCESS OR PRETENDER? fORMER KC BUSINESSWOMAN DODGES DEBTS, (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS and JOYCE SMITH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After what she said was a serious illness in 1989, Hollander
returned to Kansas City from Europe to visit her grandmother. It
was then she met and began living with classical pianist David Y.
Hollander, whose name she now shares, and began planning an
ambitious new business venture.
</P>
<P>
   Acquaintances in Kansas City said Hollander was a vivacious,
larger-than-life character who helped her husband manage his Kansas
City Chamber Soloists music series and often introduced the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gordon, whose wife, Nina, played cello in some of David
Hollander's programs, said Tone Hollander's flamboyance always
seemed genuine.
</P>
<P>
   ``She liked attention, but not on a fraudulent scale,'' Gordon
said.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1992 the Hollanders bought a home on Greenway Drive
near that of David Hollander's father, cellist Norman Hollander,
and began winning over the neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were great neighbors, very friendly,'' recalled
bassoonist Marita Abner of the Kansas City Symphony. ``They
entertained a little. They were wonderful and entertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Repeated attempts to reach Norman Hollander were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Tone Hollander began laying the groundwork for a new
venture _ a nationally distributed opinion journal to be published
in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   In an article in The Star, she outlined a proposal to publish a
newspaper consisting entirely of paid advertising containing the
opinions of the advertisers. Her promotional material included
glowing tributes from Lee Iaccoca, Barbara Jordan and former first
lady Barbara Bush. Spokesmen for each, however, said they were not
acquainted with Hollander.
</P>
<P>
   Within three weeks signs of trouble began to surface. The
newspaper never got off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1994, David Hollander postponed a concert at the Folly
Theater, saying Tone Hollander had undergone heart surgery, a
newspaper item reported.
</P>
<P>
   In the next several months the Hollanders faced seven lawsuits
in Jackson County, alleging at least $33,415 in unpaid bills and
employee wages.
</P>
<P>
   That July the Jackson County prosecutors office issued a felony
warrant for Tone Hollander's arrest related to at least $1,400 in
bad checks.
</P>
<P>
   The Hollanders responded by disappearing, court records show.
</P>
<P>
   Process servers trying to serve notice of the lawsuits on the
Hollanders found nobody at home on Greenway Drive. In one instance,
neighbors told the servers they thought the couple had moved to
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   By February the couple had defaulted on their $40,000 home loan,
and by March the home had been sold at auction.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, six of the seven lawsuits were dismissed by the
courts because the suing companies could not find the Hollanders.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Associate Circuit Judge Anthony Romano said state
courts were required to purge inactive lawsuits from their dockets
periodically. The lawsuits could, however, be refiled if the
Hollanders returned to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Tone Hollander is no longer in danger of being arrested on the
bad check warrant. The statute of limitations on that charge
expired in July, said Philip LeVota, an assistant prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Only Sears, Roebuck and Co. secured a court judgment against the
Hollanders, for $13,054. Court records show that has not been paid.
</P>
<P>
   In her biography, Hollander summed up this period in her life:
</P>
<P>
   ``We hosted a wonderful concert series and started a Kansas City
newspaper.''
Tone Hollander blames the financial trouble she and David Hollander
faced in Kansas City on a group of disloyal executives from their
newspaper who improperly gave themselves pay raises, draining the
company's resources.
</P>
<P>
   Asked recently about multiple surnames and Social Security
numbers linked to her in credit and real estate records, Hollander
responded that she had been married many times, so confusion over
names was inevitable. She blamed the multiple Social Security
numbers on relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different Social Security numbers have resulted from siblings
who are, sadly, victims of drug abuse and who, unfortunately, have
abused my kindness,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hollander, who says she ``hasn't been living like a princess,''
now lives with David Hollander in Wilton, Conn. She understands
that some might ask why she doesn't pay off relatively small debts,
if she, indeed, is an oil-rich Saudi princess.
</P>
<P>
   The issue first arose, she said, after she learned in 1996 that
her dead fighter-pilot husband had established a substantial trust
fund to care for her and their son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I had more than $200,000 in medical-related debts, I
was extremely hesitant to access this trust _ wanting my son to
know unequivocally that he, not any financial legacy, was most
important to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
