<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARKS-CONTAM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURIOSITY WILL DRAW VISITORS TO RENEWED MISSOURI PARKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUREKA, Mo. _ For years barricades protected the curious from
Times Beach's toxic threats.
</P>
<P>
   The guards at a contaminated former Army plant in Weldon Spring
were just as foreboding.
</P>
<P>
   But soon planners will complete an almost unimaginable
transformation, turning these danger zones into lush playgrounds
that welcome visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Beach site, where more than 265,000 tons of
dioxin-tainted dirt and debris were incinerated, will be home to
the 409-acre Route 66 State Park. The park will open to the public
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Weldon Spring plant, where the Department of Energy is
burying debris contaminated with radioactive waste, will link to
the popular Katy Trail and the Busch Conservation Area.
</P>
<P>
   Planners know the projects will be a tough sell to residents who
have grown up wary of the sites and skeptical of government
promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deer are plentiful; the birds are plentiful. It's very
green. I want to enjoy it,'' said Diane Warhover, superintendent
for the Route 66 State Park. ``But some people probably aren't
going to let their kids play here. Some people you're never going
to convince.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to avoid the ghosts of Times Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The town once served as a working-class resort on the Meramec
River. Only floods interrupted the town's tranquil existence off
Interstate 44.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s a waste hauler used a chemical mix to oil the
streets of Times Beach and other Missouri sites to control dust.
</P>
<P>
   The oil contained dioxin, a chemical that some scientists
believe can cause cancer and developmental disorders.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982 federal officials evacuated Times Beach's 2,242
residents. Many did not even have a chance to take their
belongings. Some doubted the chemical's danger and begged to stay.
The dispute over the buyout reached the White House and sparked
congressional hearings.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990 planners agreed to incinerate dioxin-contaminated
material from more than 20 Missouri sites at Times Beach. The
cleanup, which cost an estimated $200 million, ended in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   When the Department of Natural Resources took over the land,
officials promised to turn the site into a state park.
</P>
<P>
   The town is abandoned now. Daffodils and peonies grow, leftovers
from home gardens. Oak, maple and white pine trees reach to the
skies. Treetops were lopped off to avoid hitting power lines and
interfering with the incinerator. New trees are being planted.
</P>
<P>
   As Warhover drives on the park's winding roads, a deer emerges
from the vegetation near a grass-covered mound of incinerated dirt.
A picnic area is planned near a mound of crushed debris buried
underground.
</P>
<P>
   Park planners do not plan to hide Times Beach's past.
</P>
<P>
   In a visitors center once home to Environmental Protection
Agency staffers, photographs of the cleanup hang near pictures of
the blue heron and other wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Planners also will install a few old street signs as reminders
of the addresses residents once called home. The park also will
contain a restaurant, a gift shop and seven miles of trails that
will connect with other paths in the Meramec Greenway and city
trails in Eureka.
</P>
<P>
   Route 66 will be the star of the park.
</P>
<P>
   The park will be Missouri's largest monument to the historic
highway known for stretching from Chicago to Los Angeles. Devotees
have donated signs and photos, and the park has received worldwide
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Route 66 spans the Meramec River inside the park.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Powell, founder of the Route 66 Association of Missouri,
remembers when Times Beach made national news like Three Mile
Island and Love Canal.
</P>
<P>
   But he said his members will flock to the park, despite that
history. If anything, they feel more secure because of the
environmental monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the cleanest ground in the United States,''
he said. ``I'm convinced you could eat that dirt and it wouldn't
hurt you.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental officials discovered new dioxin sites in eastern
Missouri, but they say Times Beach has been thoroughly searched.
The new dioxin was transported to an incinerator in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Some environmentalists also raised concerns about dioxin
emissions from the Times Beach incinerator, but EPA officials say
there is no risk.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Leistner, the last mayor of Times Beach, has seen
neighbors suffer cancer and lose babies. Others blame the dioxin.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents say they believe the park is safe, but Leistner
did not want to say whether she agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather not answer that question,'' she said. ``I'm pleased
for the people who want to go back. I'm just not quite sure how I
feel about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's time to turn the page, time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   The plant at Weldon Spring is another toxic scar on a lush
countryside.
</P>
<P>
   The Busch Conservation Area nearby is home to hawks, foxes,
beavers and other wildlife. The Katy Trail, a statewide path for
bikers and hikers, winds through south St. Louis County, connecting
with local exercise paths.
</P>
<P>
   The plant's paths are cordoned off so bulldozers can move
contaminated dirt. Visitors must pass through tight security.
</P>
<P>
   In World War II the Army produced TNT here. In 1955 the U.S.
Atomic Energy Commission began processing uranium ore for nuclear
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the plant closed in 1969, a variety of chemicals had
contaminated soil and buildings.
</P>
<P>
   After the EPA declared Weldon Spring a ``superfund'' site, the
Department of Energy in 1986 began a cleanup that will not end
until 2002. A private firm is dismantling buildings, storing rubble
and treating contaminated water.
</P>
<P>
   The price tag is creeping toward $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The cleanup has created what project manager Steve McCracken
calls ``the stigma of glow-in-the-dark, two-headed frogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than defensively fight the perception, the Energy
Department is confronting it. Instead of abandoning the site,
officials are launching a public-relations effort to bring in
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary Bill Richardson went to Weldon Spring and proclaimed
it a ``Department of Energy success story.''
</P>
<P>
   One environmentalist agrees that Times Beach and Weldon Spring
planners are making the best out of a bad situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an ideal world, we wouldn't have pollution. Realistically,
we have it,'' said Claralyn Price-Bollinger of the Eastern Missouri
Sierra Club. ``We're glad to see these areas being re-used for a
good purpose, but in a way, the cows are already out of the barn.''
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Energy plans to leave one building at Weldon
Spring and make it an interpretive center. Detailed accounts of the
cleanup will share space in the center with exhibits on the area's
history.
</P>
<P>
   Planners, working with the state Department of Natural
Resources, also plan a new trail to connect the 250-acre site with
nearby trails.
</P>
<P>
   In the department's boldest plan, visitors will be able to walk
to the top of a facility that will store 1.5 million cubic yards of
radioactive waste, layered with 8 feet of clay and aggregate
material.
</P>
<P>
   When finished, the vault will resemble a small hill, covered
with rocks. Visitors will enjoy a vantage point to rival any in the
county.
</P>
<P>
   As with Times Beach, planners will have to convince a skeptical
public that they should not worry about climbing a vault of
radioactive waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure at first thought, they'll think there must be
something about it that isn't right,'' McCracken said. ``But I'm
willing to bet that most people will go up. Even if they're not
sure, they'll do it out of curiosity.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Leistner hopes Times Beach residents can leave the past
behind, Glenn Hachey looks forward to riding his bike from his St.
Charles County home, down the Katy Trail to the top of the waste
vault.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the Weldon Springs Citizens Commission, a
watchdog group, Hachey has prodded the government to leave the
plant site in good shape. Now instead of seeing waste pits, he will
see green countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put a big fence around something and cordon it off,
there's always going to be a sense, rational or not, that there's
something dangerous about it. Well, it's not. We just want to put
it behind us.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long road. What people need to recognize is that
this is a historic point,'' he said. ``It's a happy ending.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
