<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRANNY-WALK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUNION NOTWITHSTANDING, PERIPATETIC `GRANNY' EN ROUTE TO MEMPHIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Echoes of the civil rights movement have spurred
Doris ``Granny D.'' Haddock along the Arkansas stretch of her
cross-country trek for campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   The 89-year-old, who set off from Pasadena on New Year's Day,
spoke from the steps of Central High School in Little Rock, where
in 1957 African-American students broke the segregation barrier.
She spoke to the congregation of the city's First Baptist Church,
where the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. inspired many.
</P>
<P>
   Still modest despite gaining national attention since setting
out on her journey, Haddock's next major appearance is Tuesday in
Memphis, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   After leading a walk joined by activists, including comedian and
hunger striker Dick Gregory, Haddock will join a program at the
National Civil Rights Museum. The museum is housed in the motel
where King was felled by an assassin's bullet 31 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is civil rights territory. That's why we thought it might
be a chance to do something,'' said Haddock, who is from southern
New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Like King and other civil rights leaders, Haddock said she is
walking to Washington, D.C., to seek justice for Americans. Haddock
cares about the many people she says don't have the money to gain
access to government and suffer economically from subsidies and tax
breaks favoring special interests.
</P>
<P>
   She said as much to the Little Rock congregation: ``We are
walking together on the high road of history. We are on even ground
now because so many sacrifices have been made behind us. We have
nothing to lose that we care about, and our shared freedom to
gain.''
</P>
<P>
   Haddock's journey attracted interest long before her speeches
sharpened over more than eight months on the road.
</P>
<P>
   One fan who began following accounts of her journey before she
strode into the South was Gregory. The 67-year-old
comedian-activist-nutrition guru said he will be in Memphis to
support her _ ``one agitator to another.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She is the real Super Bowl. And she won't have 100,000 people
in the stands cheering for her. There's one person, God, in the
stands clapping and saying thank you,'' he said. ``It's right
against wrong, and there's no contest there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory appreciates the struggles Haddock faces, having crossed
the country himself on a 1976 run from Los Angeles to Washington,
D.C., to raise awareness about hunger in the United States and the
rest of the world. He has urged her to change socks and shoes often
to battle sweaty feet, drink plenty of water and eat lots of fruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her age, that's the amazing thing. She's not 89, she's a year
from 90. Them is basketball scores,'' Gregory said. ``I think she
will make it.''
</P>
<P>
   So do the people who have offered Haddock meals, lodging and
good wishes in towns and cities from Texarkana on the
Texas-Arkansas border to West Memphis near the Arkansas-Tennessee
border.
</P>
<P>
   Drugstore get-togethers in Hope and Arkadelphia were memorable
occasions for Haddock to meet Arkansans. Haddock also recalled a
huge turnout in front of a Benton auto dealership.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's amazing. I thought it was a real rare opportunity,''
said Nancy Mashburn.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Ralph, welcomed Haddock and walk
coordinator John Anthony into their home on a cotton farm east of
Little Rock for three days and two nights. The couple also had
Haddock's support crew, then numbering three, over for a spaghetti
dinner and homemade vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   How they met is another tale of recognition and hospitality
Haddock has counted on during her journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son and his family in Little Rock were coming out here for
breakfast, and he passed her on the street. He had heard her
interviewed on the radio, and he stopped and talked with them and
said you've just got to stay with my mom and dad,'' Nancy Mashburn
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had seen her on `Good Morning America,' but I had forgotten
who she was. I didn't realize she was in Arkansas,'' she said. ``I
didn't think she would make it, but I have no doubt she will make
it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people far from Haddock's route who would love to join her
but probably won't meet her have been inspired to lead solidarity
walks.
</P>
<P>
   Marian Cooley organized a group of concerned taxpayers in
Muncie, Ind., for a recent 10-mile walk _ matching the length
Haddock completes daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, man, this gal was really something. I liked her
statement that sometimes you just have to put your body there for
some causes,'' Cooley said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 people turned out for the walk along a railway bed
converted to a walking trail. Cooley said it gave the group energy
for future activism, and campaign finance reform will be one of
their issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, she did give that effort energy,'' Cooley said.
``One person can make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even a nagging bunion on Haddock's left big toe can slow
her. She acknowledges some trouble with it, but heavy taping and
massage ease the pain.
</P>
<P>
   Haddock, on her third pair of supportive walking shoes, isn't
going to stop after walking more than 2,000 miles through mostly
rural reaches of the nation's Sunbelt.
</P>
<P>
   Passing the minnow ponds, rice and cotton fields, and woods of
Arkansas, Haddock has enjoyed the green and yellow expanses. Even
the sometimes stifling heat, which has her on the road by 5:30 a.m.
and calling it a day about five hours later, hasn't been the
relentless brand she faced in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lovely walk. Arkansas is flat, flat, flat. Their roads
are good,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
