<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-STREET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALSUP GETS BY WITH HELP FROM HIS FRIENDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A.J. Alsup drove all the way from his North
Carolina home and hired a pit crew of racing novices to compete on
the streets of Los Angeles this weekend, so he figured that one
more gamble couldn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our motto all weekend was `Roll the dice' '' said Alsup, whose
final risky move resulted in his first NASCAR Southwest Series
victory Monday in the featured event of the Ford L.A. Street Race.
</P>
<P>
   Alsup, who started 19th, took his pit stop on lap 38 of the
125-lap race, hoping that a yellow flag would soon follow, keeping
him close to the leaders and allowing him to make a move once the
other drivers pitted later in the race. The move played out
perfectly as Alsup took the lead on lap 58, when a full-course
yellow flag sent the rest of the drivers to the pits for their only
stops of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Alsup came out shead and never surrendered the lead in the final
68 laps, holding off Craig Raudman in the final laps to claim
victory and a $17,715 check. Series rookie Eric Holmes finished
third, followed by R.K. Smith and pole-sitter Greg Pursley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided early on to pit under the green flag and just take
two tires and gas,'' Alsup said. ``We knew it would cost us a lot
of track position right then, but we thought we could make it up
and grab the lead once everybody had their stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some buddies come out and help me on the pit crew, and
some of them had never even touched an air gun for the tires
before. It's a good thing we won, because otherwise I'd probably
have some credit-card companies at my door tomorrow morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Pursley led the early part of the race but was passed on lap 20
by Kevin Harvick, who led the next 35 laps until Pursley regained
the lead. Pursley stayed in front until the pit stops, when Alsup
took over.
</P>
<P>
   Most drivers handled the two hairpin turns near the start/finish
line without incident, but a sharp turn 1, coming off the longest
straightaway on the course, claimed several cars. Fifty-one of the
125 laps were run under caution.
</P>
<P>
   A potentially embarrassing situation for event organizers was
resolved before the race. Ken Schrader and Kenny Irwin, the two
Winston Cup drivers flown in to compete in the Southwest event,
apparently decided Monday morning that they would not race.
</P>
<P>
   Their cars were qualified in the morning by Ross Thompson and
Jon Zaretzky, respectively, but before race time Schrader and Irwin
changed their minds, although both started at the back of the field
as a penalty for changing drivers after qualifying. Schrader never
contended and crashed on lap 64, but Irwin took the lead briefly on
lap 79 before falling back to fourth and later hitting the wall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
