<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2784 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     09-07 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO EASY CURE FOR MONDESI'S WOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Long after the Dodgers had accepted Monday's 8-6 loss to
Florida and gone home, Raul Mondesi sat alone in the clubhouse, the
unhappiest guy to ever hit two home runs in a game.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, the only player in Dodgers history to get 30 homers and
steal 30 bases in a season, is not concerned that he is approaching
those numbers for the second time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   All he thinks about is getting away from a year that has gone so
terribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The player Latin scout Ralph Avila called ``quite a loner'' now
seems more alone than ever. He won't talk about the tirade he threw
three weeks ago at management. He won't say if he has rescinded his
loud request to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have ruined my season,'' he said. ``All I want to do now is
finish up, try to relax and worry about the future later.''
</P>
<P>
   The second of Mondesi's two home runs, a two-run shot that cut
the Marlins' lead to 7-6 with one out in the eighth, was his 28th
of the season. He also has 27 stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, Mondesi has broken out of an offensive
slump that lasted almost three months.
</P>
<P>
   He has run the bases aggressively and has three home runs in the
first four games of the Dodgers' six-game trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of that matters now,'' he said quietly. ``What has
happened cannot be put aside. It would just be nice to win a few
games and forget about everything else until after the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi sat on a clubhouse sofa for more than an hour as
teammates filed by and into the Florida night.
</P>
<P>
   At this point in a 65-72 season, dwelling on losses seems almost
foolish, except for maybe manager Davey Johnson, who looked as
though he still was anguishing through a rain delay that held up
the game for two hours and 26 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was the target for much of Mondesi's anger. Johnson
moved the slumping right fielder around in the lineup until Mondesi
figured he was being blamed for the Dodgers' lousy season.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also was put in charge by club president Bob Graziano of
nurturing Mondesi through the low spots, even though the two have
known each other for less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sense his mood has improved,'' Johnson said. ``I think the
recent success (12 wins in 17 games) has picked up everyone. No,
I've liked what I've seen in Mondy. I think things have improved.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi's teammates disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that two home runs is not going to change,''
said Eric Karros, who also hit a home run. ``This is something
between Mondy and management and only they can work it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Reserve outfielder Trenidad Hubbard, who dresses next to Mondesi
at home and on the road, is probably closer to him than anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard worried last month when Mondesi became unnerved by
reports that he might be traded at the July 31 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time Hubbard had seen the usually cheerful
Mondesi so sad. And the boos by the once adoring home fans still
stung Monday even though Mondesi was playing 3,000 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a lot of hurt there,'' Hubbard said. ``You
would think hitting two homers after all he's been through would
help. But maybe time is the only way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
