u a BC-NY-ENCEPHALITIS-2NDLD     09-07 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ENCEPHALITIS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-1050(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY EXPANDS PESTICIDE CAMPAIGN AGAINST DANGEROUS MOSQUITOES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (CHANGES `suspected' to `possible' in 2nd graf) (mk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ City officials battling an outbreak of St. Louis
encephalitis expanded their campaign of aerial pesticide spraying
Monday to hundreds of acres of Bronx parkland along the East River
and Long Island Sound up to Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   The expanded spraying effort, which until Monday had included
the scattering of pesticides across parts of northern Queens and
the South Bronx, came as the number of possible cases of St. Louis
encephalitis in the city rose Monday to 37 from 34, and the number
of confirmed cases held at five.
</P>
<P>
   Two elderly people have died of the mosquito-borne viral disease
and three other elderly people stricken with it remain in serious
but stable condition in city hospitals, city health officials said.
So far, the virus has afflicted people only in northern Queens. It
is possible that cases exist in the Bronx, but no cases have been
confirmed there, or in any other parts of the city or nearby
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani tried to ease residents' concerns about
the spread of both the virus and the spraying on Monday, calling
the broadened effort a preventive step.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the next couple of days we'll be doing some additional
spraying in the northern part of the Bronx,'' the mayor announced
at the emergency center the city has established near the
Bronx-Whitestone Bridge to help residents of the area. ``Caution
dictates that it would be better to continue to go further north
toward the Westchester border along the water.''
</P>
<P>
   But anecdotal evidence suggested Monday that public unease about
the spread of the virus was growing as people returned to the city
from the holiday weekend. City officials said an emergency phone
number they established to answer questions about the outbreak has
received over 11,000 calls _ the most of any such number in the
city's history.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM STARTS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The virus also became a political issue Monday with the Bronx
borough president, Fernando Ferrer, blaming budget cuts by the
Giuliani administration for eliminating mosquito spraying that
might have prevented the current outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of years ago there was spraying that was stopped in
the Soundview section of the Bronx,'' said Clint Roswell, a
spokesman for Ferrer.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Mullin, a city Health Department spokeswoman, said that
officials with knowledge of past spraying in the Bronx were not
available Monday. But she said that the Giuliani administration had
made efforts to control the mosquito population with pellets that
release a bacteria that kills the larvae in stagnant water.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Health Department does respond to complaints about
mosquito problems,'' she said. ``Pellets are dropped in pools of
stagnant water.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that most mosquitoes did not carry the virus and
that the illness was not always fatal. In general, it was the very
young and the elderly who were most susceptible to the virus, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   The new aerial spraying in the Bronx on Monday night focused on
all parks between the Hutchinson River Parkway and the East River
and Long Island Sound, Giuliani said. By far the most spraying
occurred in the sprawling, 2,764-acre Pelham Bay Park, which
borders Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   Although city officials said that malathion, the pesticide being
used, posed almost no health threat to people or pets, they
instructed residents of areas bordering the parks not to go outside
during the spraying, from 6 p.m. to 10 p.m. Residents were to turn
off their fans and set their air conditioners so that air only
exits their home.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM STARTS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   In the northern Queens and Bronx neighborhoods where aerial
spraying took place Friday and Saturday _ Whitestone, Auburndale
and College Point in Queens and Soundview, Classons Point, Harding
Park and Ferry Point Park in the Bronx _ city officials directed
their attack Monday against pools of stagnant groundwater where
mosquito larvae can hatch.
</P>
<P>
   Helicopters surveyed the area for stagnant family swimming pools
and officials offered to haul away used tires, in which water can
also pool and stagnate. Officials said that water should be emptied
from lawn decorations, jars, cans and clogged gutters and that
window screens should be checked for holes.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of anxious residents streamed into the command center
Monday that the city's Department of Emergency Management has set
up in College Point to explain the outbreak and hand out mosquito
repellent. By late afternoon, a tent that had held hundreds of
cases of repellent was nearly empty as city officials handed out
instructions in English, Chinese, Korean and Arabic on how to
combat the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have been bitten by mosquitoes will not know for 10 to
15 days whether they have contracted the virus, according to city
officials. The symptoms can involve only a slight fever and a
headache. Or they can be far more serious, with severe headaches,
high fever, coma, convulsions, paralysis and even death.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said they were frightened by both the disease-carrying
mosquitoes and the pesticides sprayed across the neighborhood. John
Didio, 43, who grew up in College Point and has a 7-year-old
daughter and a 5-year-old son, said he was frightened by the
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turn off your fans and stay inside,'' he said, paraphrasing
instructions residents were given during the spraying. ``It's kind
of like germ warfare.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A nervous Enrica Naccarato, 45, a sixth-grade schoolteacher who
moved to the neighborhood last summer, said she was having her
8-year-old daughter stay at her mother-in-law's house in Long
Island until school begins on Thursday. ``It's a little scary,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another worried mother asked whether the bug repellent she had
put on her children in the morning would last through their
recesses at school. (City officials said it would.)
</P>
<P>
   Marie Cantatore, who arrived with her daughter Diane to pick up
bug spray and instructions, said she was bitten twice on Saturday.
``It's just scary,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter blamed the city for not stopping the outbreak
before it started. ``They never come to spray,'' she said. ``They
should've come a lot sooner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
