<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' COOPER HAS ROOTS AT SHORTSTOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ If Brian Cooper had his way, he'd be playing shortstop
for the Angels tonight instead of pitching. It's nothing against
the Angels' current shortstop, Gary DiSarcina, it's just that
Cooper misses playing every day.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, a 1992 graduate of Glendora High, will make his
major-league debut tonight against the Chicago White Sox. If all
goes as planned, Cooper could be in the Angels' starting rotation
next season.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, though, was a shortstop when he started as a freshman at
Citrus College, but Owls manager Skip Claprood moved him to the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not happy about it at all,'' Cooper said. ``I went from
an everyday player to once every five days. I liked getting my
uniform dirty. But I guess (Claprood) saw something in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper concedes Claprood was right. Cooper was a combined 12-6
at Double-A Erie and Triple-A Edmonton this season, earning his
promotion. But it hasn't always gone smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Last season at Double-A Midland, Cooper was 8-10 with a 7.13
ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I not only wondered if I'd even get here, but if I'd
play baseball again,'' Cooper, 25, said.
</P>
<P>
   But Cooper worked on his confidence and a mechanical flaw, and
here he is. He said he'll leave about 20 tickets for friends and
family but is leaving the distribution up to his parents, Brian and
Kathy, who have had season tickets in Anaheim over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been coming to games here for years,'' Cooper said. ``We
were 10 rows up, so now I'll just be 10 rows closer to the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a library: Interim manager Joe Maddon, who says he averages
reading one book a week, says he likes the atmosphere in the
clubhouse now that the televisions are gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're reading magazines, books on The New York Times
best-seller list, there are round-table discussions . . .'' Maddon
said, tongue-in-cheek. ``It's very stimulating right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Familiar line: Mario Mendoza, the longtime Angels coach who
managed at Single-A Lake Elsinore this season, has joined the
big-league staff to help with pregame preparation now that the
Storm's season is complete.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza has been made famous because of his hitting _ or lack
thereof. A batting average of .200 has become known throughout
baseball as the ``Mendoza Line.'' Those in the Angels organization
say Mendoza isn't particularly fond of the reference.
</P>
<P>
   Also: Leon Durham, a coach at Triple-A Edmonton, will join the
big-league staff today. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The MRI exams on pitcher Chuck Finley and right fielder Tim
Salmon were normal. Both have had sore backs. Finley is scheduled
to make his next start Friday at Minnesota. Salmon was in the
lineup Monday as the DH.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
