<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2789 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-PHILLIES-H     09-07 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PHILLIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PHILADELPHIA _ Phillies pitchers didn't strain their neck muscles
watching home runs sail over the wall with record frequency Monday
night.
<TEXT>
<P>
   One was enough.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Johnson capped a six-run rally with a three-run pinch-hit
homer as the Astros won their fourth straight game, beating
Philadelphia 6-5 before a Labor Day crowd of 12,223 at Veterans
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Missing for five innings Monday, the Astros' bats woke up just
long enough in the sixth to gift-wrap Jose Lima's National
League-best 19th victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros maintained a 2{-game lead over the Cincinnati Reds in
the NL Central. The Reds, who beat the Cubs 6-3, have not been able
to gain ground on the Astros in eight days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get anything tonight,'' said Astros manager Larry
Dierker, whose club fell behind 4-0 and had five of its six hits in
the sixth inning. ``We only hit in one inning.''
</P>
<P>
   That proved to be just enough. After the Astros took a 6-4 lead,
their bullpen limited the Phillies to one run over the final four
innings.
</P>
<P>
   As a team, the Astros hit for the cycle during the six-run
sixth. Six straight batters reached base in the inning, five via
hits off Phillies lefthander Randy Wolf (5-7).
</P>
<P>
   Ken Caminiti tripled, Derek Bell singled, Matt Mieske doubled,
Tony Eusebio singled and Ricky Gutierrez walked before Johnson,
hitting for Lima, sent a 1-1 hanging curve over the left-field
fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never pinch-hit until I got to the big leagues,'' said
Johnson. ``It's been a learning process in a hurry for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies' staff has allowed 15 homers in its last three
games, including an NL-record nine Saturday in a 22-3 loss to the
Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia took a 1-0 lead in the second when Marlon Anderson
hit a one-out triple and Alex Arias followed with a single to left
field. In the third, former Astro Bobby Abreu, second in the NL
batting race, added a towering bases-empty home run to the upper
deck in right field off Lima.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf, who allowed only one hit through five innings and had a
4-0 lead, unraveled in the sixth as the Astros matched their
highest one-inning output of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf allowed six runs and six hits over six innings. Since
beginning his career 5-0, the rookie has lost seven straight
decisions. He has an 8.73 ERA during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Lima, whose outing was his shortest in nearly a month, allowed
four runs and eight hits over five innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take it,'' said Lima (19-7), who moved within one victory
of becoming the first Astros pitcher to win 20 games since Mike
Scott in 1989. ``I didn't have my best stuff, but the team played
great defense behind me, the bullpen did a good job and Johnson hit
a great pinch-hit home run. Sometimes four-run (deficits) are
nothing for us.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Astros clinging to a two-run lead, reliever Brian
Williams immediately ran into trouble in the sixth inning when
Arias singled and pinch hitter Rob Ducey doubled him to third.
Williams battled back, striking out Doug Glanville looking and
getting Ron Gant to fly out to right field with the runners
holding. With Abreu at the plate, pitching coach Vern Ruhle met
with Williams and instructed the righthander to give the torrid
lefthanded hitter nothing to hit. Williams struck out Abreu on an
81-mph curveball to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right there in that situation, we just wanted to try and stay
away, make him hit my pitch,'' Williams said. ``I threw some good
pitches on the outer half (of the plate). When I got two strikes on
him, I tried to still stay out there and not give him anything to
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies had another scoring opportunity in the seventh when
Williams loaded the bases with nobody out. He hit Kevin Jordan to
lead off the inning before Rico Brogna singled up the middle and
Mike Lieberthal walked. Reliever Jose Cabrera retired Anderson on a
called third strike and nearly got out of the inning without
allowing a run. But Arias beat out what could have been a double
play, allowing Jordan to score and slice the lead to 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very nerve-racking game with the Phillies having so
many opportunities once they got the lead,'' Dierker said. ``It was
developing into a game that wouldn't have been that hard to lose,
the way things were going.''
</P>
<P>
   A baserunning blunder in the eighth cost the Phillies a scoring
opportunity. Glanville led off with a double into the right-field
corner but was gunned down trying to stretch it into a triple on a
perfect relay throw to third by Craig Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Wagner retired the side in order in the ninth for his 34th
save.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 0104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
