<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2791 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     09-07 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRAN BLINEBURY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PHILADELPHIA _ If it had been Olympic diving, he'd have done a
belly-flop off the high board. If it were figure skating, he'd have
been skidding across the ice with a cold, damp bottom. If he'd been
hammering nails, well, let's just say he'd have sore thumbs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jose Lima became the National League's first 19-game winner
Monday but did not show much in the way of style points. Or dugout
decorum.
</P>
<P>
   Through five rhythmless innings, Lima looked like a guy with two
left feet, giving up eight hits, four runs and a homer to the
Phillies' Bobby Abreu that probably showed up on some satellite
photographs at NASA.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Lima got to dance the merengue once more because
Russ Johnson put some jitterbug into a three-run pinch homer and
the Astros held on for a 6-5 win over the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Labor Day. How fitting.
</P>
<P>
   Here were the Astros, still mostly out of kilter at home plate
but able to come up with their fourth straight win because they
piled up all of their runs in one big inning.
</P>
<P>
   Here was Lima, never really bearing down during his short stint
on the mound and yet getting to put another notch on his belt when
Johnson bailed him out just moments after Lima threw another one of
his dugout tantrums over being lifted. He also snapped at Stan
Javier after a bloop double allowed a run to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``A win is a win,'' said manager Larry Dierker philosophically.
``He (Lima) was lucky. That's about all you can say. He's pitched
some good games and not given up much at times this year and come
away with no decision. Any time you have a year when you win a lot
of games, you're going to have some lucky ones. This fell into that
category. So you just put it away and figure that things have a way
of evening themselves out.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of the joy and spontaneity Lima brings to the game,
there are times when you wonder if he ever stops to try to figure
anything out. This was a night when he did not bring his best stuff
to a funereal Veterans Stadium against a Phillies team that has
plummeted in the standings in the last month.
</P>
<P>
   Lima was getting his pitches up in the strike zone and allowing
the Phillies to get in some good rips right from the start. None
more than the one Abreu took in the third inning to launch his solo
homer into the upper deck in right field. It was only the 15th time
in the 28-year history of the stadium a batter had reached those
heights in right field.
</P>
<P>
   Lima allowed the Phillies to pick up single runs in the second,
third, fourth and fifth innings and appeared unable to stop that
trend.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when the Astros' bats finally came around in the sixth
inning _ a triple by Ken Caminiti, a single by Derek Bell and a
double by Matt Mieske followed by Tony Eusebio's single and a walk
to Ricky Gutierrez _ Lima was not ready to admit he could use some
help when Dierker sent Johnson to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The dugout cameras once again caught Lima in a snit. He shook
his head and stomped his feet. He complained, and he protested and
did everything except a few flamenco steps to let everyone know he
was unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Lima, the live wire, the exposed nerve ending, who
has put together this wonderful season. But there could come a time
soon in the playoffs when somebody might wonder when a little bit
too much of livin' la vida loca isn't just that. Too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to help my team win,'' Lima said. ``I go to the
mound every time thinking that I have to get into the seventh or
the eighth inning and then turn the game over to Billy (Wagner). To
just go five, that isn't me. I don't like to come out. I didn't
like it tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, not until Johnson cleared the wall, finishing off his
teammates' rally from a 4-0 hole, and suddenly set him up with five
chances to win his 20th game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes, Mr. Stumpy, the Ice Cube, that's what we call him in
here,'' Lima said. ``This was his night to be the hero. I will have
other nights. If I get to 20, that will be mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Dierker thinks it might not be so much a case of
Lima putting too much pressure on himself to win 20 that bogs him
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might be thinking that he's on such a roll out there this
year that he gets too comfortable and doesn't concentrate enough,''
Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Lima, Brian Williams and Jose Cabrera did bear
down in the sixth and seventh when the Phillies put five runners on
base with no outs.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for Lima, Bell, Craig Biggio and Caminiti teamed up on a
perfect relay play after Doug Glanville opened the eighth with a
double into the right-field corner and tried to go to third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's a team game,'' Lima said.
</P>
<P>
   And the merengue dancer would be wise to remember that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
