<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
SOX PEN IN MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-RED SOX-MARINERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The contractor who was supposed to repair the rot in
the back of your house doesn't show up. Your babysitter cancels at
the last moment. The person driving your carpool oversleeps.
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   If you're Jimy Williams and the Red Sox, you call for pitcher
Bryce Florie. His credentials as a short-notice savior were
immortalized the day he stepped in for a tardy Pedro Martinez on
national TV three weeks ago. They were embellished Monday
afternoon, when he replaced an injured Kent Mercker and earned his
first win in a Red Sox uniform, a 3-2 decision over the Seattle
Mariners that gave the Sox the last three games of this four-game
set and a roaring start to this 12-game, four-city test.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at this trip coming in as make or break for us,''
said Florie, the first in a quartet of Sox relievers who held off
the Mariners in a game decided by a sixth-inning sacrifice fly by
Jason Varitek, who also singled and hit his third home run in two
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks on the road against four of the best teams out
there, so going 3-1 was huge,'' Florie said. ``It's not going to
get any easier, but they can't take these three wins away,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker's afternoon was suddenly shortened when he collided with
rookie third baseman Wilton Veras while they were in pursuit of
Charles Gipson's fouled bunt attempt in the third inning. Veras
caught the ball. Mercker caught a big piece of the husky Veras (not
to be confused with Butch Huskey, who doubled in the go-ahead run
and scored the game-winner). The lefty wound up with a bruised
chest that forced his exit an inning later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got hit in the ribs, it tightened up on me, and I was having
trouble following through,'' said Mercker, who was ahead, 1-0, but
had just given up a one-out double to Edgar Martinez and had a
2-and-1 count on Jay Buhner when Williams took him out. ``It was a
good decision. You don't want to change your mechanics there and
get hurt. It's not worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   The mechanics didn't change, but a pitcher almost as anonymous
as a plumber was called.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to think of myself as that,'' said Florie of his
emergency stints. ``Unfortunately, Kent got injured. And the time
before? Well, a swingman does it all, and I guess I can do that,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird. I've been here a month and a week, and I'll get
used in a situation like this, then not pitch for a week. I'm still
trying to figure out exactly what my spot is out there (in the
bullpen). But the guys are all throwing well, so I was just glad to
get into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Sox were glad to have him. Florie lost Buhner, finishing
the walk, but the sinkerballer induced pinch hitter Raul Ibanez to
roll into an inning-ending double play. The Mariners scored in the
fifth on a walk, infield out, and error by first baseman Mike
Stanley, and again in the sixth on a two-out infield hit, a wild
pitch, and Russ Davis's base hit, but Florie struck out Dan Wilson
to end the inning, his day's work done.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that the day before, the bullpen had been squeezed
for 6 2/3 innings of work, Florie's effort Monday not only led to a
win but kept Williams from having to overtax his relief corps.
</P>
<P>
   Rheal Cormier, whose back spasms were so bad Sunday he was
praying that Williams wouldn't have to use him, got the first two
outs in the seventh, aided by a running catch by Troy O'Leary that
may have been as fine a catch as the left fielder has made this
season. ``Got lucky again,'' said O'Leary, whose sixth-inning
single followed Huskey's double and put him in position to score on
Varitek's fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``That ball was headed for the gap for sure,'' said center
fielder Damon Buford. ``I knew I wasn't going to get it, and I
thought there was no way Troy was going to get there. A great
play.''
</P>
<P>
   When Cormier, working carefully, walked Ken Griffey, it was time
for another pitching change. Rod Beck, who had gotten last call in
his first two Sox appearances, this time answered a much earlier
summons, as Williams figured Beck was more rested than co-closer
Derek Lowe, who already had pitched twice in this series.
</P>
<P>
   After Griffey stole second, Beck walked Alex Rodriguez on a full
count, then fell behind Edgar Martinez, 3-and-0, before coming back
to strike him out. The Mariners, who stranded 11 runners, left two
more on in the eighth when rookie Donnie Sadler managed to glove
Tom Lampkin's smash that exploded at his feet and would have ripped
his head off if Sadler's leather hadn't intervened.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe required just nine pitches to finish off the Mariners on
three ground balls for his second save in two games and No. 12 this
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
