<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2797 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BBA-SHAUGHNESSYCOLUMN-BO     09-07 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 BBA-SHAUGHNESSY COLUMN-BOS 
HE'S AT THEIR BECK AND CALL &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Closer. Set-up guy. Middle man. Maybe Rod Beck can
start a game before this wild-card ride is over.
</P>
<P>
   He is the Walrus. He is the Eggman. Coo, coo, ca-choo.
</P>
<P>
   Beck is 31 years old and doesn't look a day over 40. All hair
and mustache, he's a widebody righty who has been in just about
every relief situation you, Bill James, or Bob Costas can imagine.
</P>
<P>
   So it really wasn't any big deal Monday when seat-of-the-pants
Red Sox manager Jimy Williams summoned newcomer Beck with one on
and two outs in the bottom of the seventh. The Sox were a little
strapped in the pen and Jimy needed an out. Beck isn't going to
turn down any opportunity to help.
</P>
<P>
   The big guy ambled in from the pen for the third time since the
Sox traded for him last week. He pitched to Alex Rodriguez while
Ken Griffey stood on first base, representing the tying run in the
final game of a four-game series. Beck walked A-Rod after Griff
stole second and then went to 3-and-0 on Edgar Martinez. Jay Buhner
was on deck.
</P>
<P>
   Beck may be new to the American League, but everyone in baseball
knows that the dysfunctional Mariners have a loaded lineup. You
have to be careful to every hitter or the game is over.
</P>
<P>
   The Walrus got out of it. He came back to throw three
consecutive strikes to Martinez, fanning him to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen these guys in spring training over the years,'' said
Beck. ``In that situation, a one-run game, I ain't going to let
them beat me with one swing. I had the shadows in my favor. I've
never seen Edgar swinging like that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, Beck hit Buhner with the first pitch. Brian
Hunter ran for Buhner. Beck induced a couple of ground outs, then
walked Dan Wilson to create more trouble. Pinch hitter Tom Lampkin
was next and hit a rocket one-hopper that exploded into the chest
of second baseman Donnie Sadler. Those are the kind of relief
appearances that made Oriole manager Earl Weaver smoke a full pack
when Don Stanhouse was on the hill.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, setup guy Beck turned it over to Derek Lowe.
1-2-3. Ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used five pitchers today,'' said Williams. ``I brought Beck
in before Lowe because I felt I only had one inning left in Lowe. I
thought Beck could maybe go more than an inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck was not offended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't closing in Chicago,'' he said. ``They were taking it
easy on me. On a day like this, you don't get the save, but games
are won or lost in that situation. I'm here to pitch when they want
me to pitch, and maybe help Derek Lowe. Whatever they want me to
do. It doesn't make any difference at this point. As long as we
have an opportunity to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Lowe was impressed by the veteran with more than 250
saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough situation, but he stuck to his game plan,''
said the man who got the save. ``He's not going to get rattled out
there late in the game. I don't think anybody cares who wins and
who gets the save.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it. Your 1999 Red Sox. You can almost hear Dan
Duquette singing, ``We Are Family.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that the Sox are tempting the fates by
bringing an ex-Cub into the mix at this juncture. In baseball lore,
it is written that the team with the most ex-Cubs on its roster
will always lose the World Series. Bill Buckner was an ex-Cub.
Remember?
</P>
<P>
   Rich Garces pitched seven games for the Cubbies in 1995. Beck's
presence gives the Sox two ex-Cubs, actually closer to three
ex-Cubs if you consider aggregate body mass.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe the Sox have figured out a way to counter the ex-Cub
factor. Jimy Williams had a Baby Ruth candy bar on his desk before
and after every game of the Seattle series. Jimy never unwrapped
the treat. He touched it only once, holding it in the air,
contemplating its meaning and announcing, ``This is the curse.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course. The Curse of Baby Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy should bring the candy bar to Oakland. For more good luck.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
