<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BRING OUT BEST IN ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The New York Yankees got on their team bus after
Monday's game and left town, and there wasn't a single Angels
player who attempted to let the air out of the tires.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have every reason to want the Yankees to stay,
considering their freakish behavior when playing the defending
World Series champions.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels actually play well against the Yankees. Monday's 5-3
victory at Edison Field completed the season series between the two
teams, with the Angels winning six of 10.
</P>
<P>
   Last season Anaheim was the only team in baseball with a winning
record against the Yankees. This year made it four seasons in the
past five the Angels have come out on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to have to have the boys visualize the
Yankees when other teams come in,'' Angels interim manager Joe
Maddon said. ``They bring out the best in us. Why? It's who they
are. But we have to maintain that attitude against other teams in
the league. The attitude was good the past four games.''
</P>
<P>
   Even stranger is the fact the Angels beat Roger Clemens,
knocking him out of the game after 42/3 innings, his shortest
outing in three months. Clemens (12-8) entered the game with a
lifetime record of 25-7 with a 2.37 ERA against the Angels but gave
up two big hits that cost him the game.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus hit his team-leading 25th homer of the year with two
on and two out in the first inning to give the Angels a 3-0 lead.
In the fifth, Jim Edmonds went the opposite way, hitting a two-run
homer _ his third of the year _ over the left-center-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens also had a big hit of his own _ he nailed his friend and
former Red Sox teammate Mo Vaughn with a pitch on the right
forearm. The pitch appeared headed for Vaughn's head, but he got
his arm _ covered with protective padding _ up in time to deflect
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no big deal,'' said Vaughn, who has been hit a team-high
10 times this season. ``I didn't feel it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The five runs were enough for starting pitcher Jarrod Washburn
(1-3), who had his best performance of the season and maybe of his
major-league career. Washburn gave up three runs and five hits in
72/3 innings, the longest outing of his career.
</P>
<P>
   It was a significant turnaround _ in his first four starts this
year he was 0-3 with a 11.57 ERA. He's a candidate for next
season's starting rotation, but he wasn't helping his cause until
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't be afraid if I get behind in the count to throw a
breaking ball or a changeup,'' Washburn said. ``That keeps the
hitters off balance. Before, I was throwing fastballs in those
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   He gave up solo homers to Shane Spencer in the fifth and Chili
Davis in the seventh. In the eighth, Derek Jeter drove in the third
run with an RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up I loved the Yankees,'' Washburn said. ``But I
really wanted to beat them. Right now it doesn't matter if it was
the Yankees, Twins or Indians, I just needed a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Magnante replaced Washburn and got the final out of the
eighth, setting the stage for Troy Percival in the ninth, who
finished it off by striking out Darryl Strawberry, who represented
the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Percival had been in a horrible stretch _ in his previous 10
appearances, he was 1-2 with a 12.91 ERA and four blown saves in
five opportunities. But he corrected the mechanical flaw in his
delivery and earned his 27th save, five of which have come against
the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Percival slowed down his delivery and was able to regain his
ability to pinpoint his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight I was definitely back to where I am when I'm on top of
my game,'' Percival said. ``I went back to working pitch by pitch
instead of trying to blow it by people. It was the first bad
stretch I've ever had in my career. I've had bad outings, but never
a bad streak.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
