<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOLEDO WON'T CHANGE QB PLAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ Bruins coach Bob Toledo watched the game film
and saw second-string quarterback Cory Paus outplay starter Drew
Bennett. He saw Paus' leadership skills, saw Paus make big plays
and direct two first-half touchdown drives. . . and yet, Toledo is
sticking with his plan to rotate the quarterbacks Saturday at Ohio
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both guys are going to play in the first two games,'' Toledo
said Monday. ``After we come home (from Ohio State), we'll evaluate
everything. We may or may not decide (on a starter). We may go into
the Fresno State game (Sept. 18) and have them compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to do this thing for the long haul. It'll be for
the league, and it may have a big impact on our future. . . . If I
pick one guy now, the other guy doesn't get game experience. And if
(the starter) falters or gets hurt, we have to start all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, though, Toledo is impressed with Paus, the redshirt
freshman who completed 12 of 18 passes against Boise State for 128
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's Paus' charisma.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's his tight spiral and soft touch.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps it's simple familiarity. Paus' leadership and
confidence _ and the mistakes that stem from his confidence _ are
reminiscent of a young Cade McNown.
</P>
<P>
   ``In scrimmages, I hear (Paus) talk, and I'm really impressed
with his leadership in the huddle,'' Toledo said. ``He'll say,
`Hey, it's third-and-1, let's get the first down.' Or, `I'm
changing the snap count.' He's constantly talking and saying, `Good
job.' I'm impressed with that.''
</P>
<P>
   But not impressed enough to make a change _ at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Turner update: Senior defensive end Travor Turner will miss the
rest of the season after tearing the anterior cruciate ligament in
his right knee in the third quarter Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Turner was the second-string weakside end (behind freshman Rusty
Williams) and UCLA's best pass rusher. To replace Turner, the
Bruins will use third-stringer Steve Sua, defensive tackle Pete
Holland and outside linebackers Santi Hall and Ali Abdul Azziz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Travor is a spiritual leader, that's why I made him captain
(for the opener),'' Toledo said. ``We'll miss him. Two years ago, I
wouldn't have said that.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmer update: Receiver Danny Farmer was in uniform Monday for
the first time since spraining his left ankle Aug. 21. He
participated in non-contact drills and was upgraded from doubtful
to questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting update: The Bruins received two oral commitments this
weekend, pushing their total to nine. The latest to commit are
Carlsbad High teammates Steve Vieira, an offensive lineman, and
linebacker Brandon Chillar.
</P>
<P>
   Who played well: Toledo cited the defensive line's
aggressiveness and pursuit as significant developments in the
opener. Sophomore tackle Ken Kocher was named defensive player of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Two first-time starters in the secondary, freshman cornerback
Joe Hunter and senior safety Joey Strycula, were impressive, as was
reserve cornerback Ricky Manning.
</P>
<P>
   Kicker Chris Griffith, who made a 37-yard field goal, was named
special teams player of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Randy Hakes was the standout offensive player.
</P>
<P>
   And who did not: As expected, the walk-on fullbacks and
inexperienced offensive line struggled with communication and
blocking assignments, which limited the running game.
</P>
<P>
   Two veterans, cornerback Jason Bell and safety Jason Stephens,
also performed poorly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Jason (Stephens) wants to keep his job, he needs to play
better,'' Toledo said. ``He missed a couple tackles.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 0148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
