<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2802 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TIMOR-UNREST-3RDLD-WR     09-07 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-UNREST-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS IN EAST TIMOR FLEEING AS MILITIAS ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS grafs   2 thru 6 with release of rebel leader, DELETES grafs
9-11 and 13th graf of 2nd take.) (See also TIMOR-U.N.) 
(th) 
 By SETH MYDANS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ In what is evidently a planned campaign of
savagery, militias backed by the Indonesian military continued
their attacks on the people of East Timor on Monday, burning homes,
killing residents and forcing many thousands to flee into the
barren hills for safety.
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday, President B.J. Habi-H bie brought East Timor
under mar- tial law, a move that would potential- ly allow the
military to deploy thou- sands of soldiers across the territo- ry.
The move raised hopes abroad that Indonesia would now act to bring
order in East Timor. But it is not clear whether the soldiers will
be used to quell the violence or to battle pro-independence forces
that have remained hunkered down in the hills.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, the Goverment re- leased Jose Alexandre Gusmao, the
rebel leader who was arrested seven years ago and who is seen as
the potential leader of a new East Ti- morese nation.
</P>
<P>
   After signing release papers at the Ministry of Justice he was
handed over to the protection of the United Nations in Jakarta.
Because of the situation in East Timor, a spokes- man said Gusmao
would not immediately travel to the territory, where he has been
warning of what he called genocide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promise as a free man I will do everything I can to bring
peace to East Timor,'' Gusmao said.
</P>
<P>
   One week after an overwhelming vote of independence from
Indonesia by the 800,000 people of the tiny territory, military
elements now in East Timor appear bent on leaving behind a
bloodied, ravaged, broken land, where the Indonesian military has
fought against a separatist insurgency since invading in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports reaching here, the militias burned the home
of Roman Catholic Bishop Carlos Belo, evicting 6,000 people who
were taking refuge there and forcing the bishop, who shared the
Nobel Peace Price in 1996, to flee. The militias fired at the
Australian Consulate and at the Australian ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   A major operation appeared to be under way to force many
thousands of people to flee into neighboring West Timor, which is
part of Indonesia. Unlike the rest of the Indonesian archipelago,
which won independence from the Dutch in 1949, East Timor was a
Portuguese colony until 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses reported that large numbers of people in Dili, East
Timor's capital, were being loaded onto trucks, and authorities
said 15,000 people had already arrived in West Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows every sign of being planned and coordinated
beforehand,'' said Sidney Jones, the Asian director for Human
Rights Watch, who is an expert on Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Indonesian army may be trying to teach a lesson not only
to the East Timorese but to the people of Aceh and Irian Jaya,''
Ms. Jones said, referring to two other provinces with strong
separatist movements. ``The lesson is: if you seek separation from
Indonesia, even if support for separation is overwhelming, we will
destroy you, and no outside power will come to your aid.''
</P>
<P>
   The violence in East Timor appears to reflect the reluctance of
the Indonesian military to let go of the territory after fighting a
guerrilla war against the independence movement there since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   As demands from around the world for foreign military
intervention mounted, given the failure of Indonesian forces to
keep order, representatives from the U.N. Security Council were
preparing to come to Jakarta to confer with the Indonesian
government.
</P>
<P>
   Australia put troops on emergency alert, reducing the time it
would take to send peacekeeping forces to East Timor from 72 hours
to 24, Defense Minister John Moore said. He said peacekeeping
forces could be deployed only with the agreement of the Indonesian
government.
</P>
<P>
   But Indonesia has taken an adamant position that it will not
accept foreign troops. For weeks, Indonesia has promised to take
action against the violence in East Timor, but it has done little.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's open defiance of international opinion was
particularly striking at a time when it is dependent on billions of
dollars of international aid to rescue it from a devastating
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund, which is heading a $43-billion
rescue program, issued a statement on Monday saying that it was
``closely watching the situation in East Timor'' and ``notes with
concern the violence that continues to mar the process.'' But much
of the aid has already been disbursed.
</P>
<P>
   Jamsheed Marker, the U.N. special envoy for East Timor, raised
the international concerns at a meeting on Monday with President
B.J. Habibie.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Marker said, ``It is very clear today that
the Indonesian government has failed in its responsibility to
maintain adequate security.''
</P>
<P>
   Challenged by reporters at a separate news conference, Habibie
said: ``Come on, come on. What we have achieved right now is one
thing: we have achieved the fact that we had a transparent,
peaceful ballot, and that _ don't take that for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Megawati Sukarnoputri, the front-runner to succeed Habibie when
Indonesia selects a new president in November, blamed Habibie's
government for the situation and apologized on Indonesia's behalf
to the people of East Timor for a quarter-century of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Ali Alatas told reporters the situation in East
Timor ``is not as simple as you have described it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Very often our police have to wait for reinforcements in the
face of an overwhelming presence of armed, unruly elements,'' he
said. ``They have continued to exercise great persuasive powers,
and in many cases they were able to prevent things.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with the military backing, and, according to some
accounts, taking part in the militia violence, police were
sometimes placed in an impossible position. In many cases in the
last two weeks, the police were observed to be working hand in hand
with the militias.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, the Indonesian military formed the irregular
militia groups, made up of local toughs and unemployed youths, to
conduct a campaign of intimidation that appeared to be aimed at
skewing or derailing the referendum on independence.
</P>
<P>
   That failed when nearly 99 percent of eligible East Timorese
turned out to vote on Aug. 30 and 78.5 percent of the voters chose
independence.
</P>
<P>
   It now seems evident that the next step in the strategy was to
remove foreign witnesses to the current wave of terror. Most
foreign reporters, election observers, aid groups and foreign
workers for the United Nations have now fled.
</P>
<P>
   ``This looks like a systematic attempt not to kill journalists
but to chase them away from the story, because without the media
there nobody will know what happens,'' said Lin Neumann, the Asia
representative for the New York-based Committee to Protect
Journalists.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations, which administered the referendum, was
evacuating nearly 200 members of its staff on Monday. A spokesman,
David Wimhurst, said shots had been fired at one of three
evacuation convoys heading for the airport.
</P>
<P>
   According to other reports from East Timor, virtually all of the
U.N. workers stationed outside the capital have fled to the town of
Baucau, in the eastern part of the territory, where the militias
seem to be less virulent.
</P>
<P>
   After the attack on his residence, Belo, who shared the Nobel
Peace Prize in 1996 with the pro-independence activist Jose Ramos
Horta, was also flown to Baucau in a police helicopter _ possibly
to remove him, as a respected figure for moderation, from the
center of action.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees who had sought protection in his home were taken to
police stations at gunpoint, witnesses said, along with about 2,000
people who had sought protection at the nearby headquarters of the
International Committee of the Red Cross, which was also attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Several reports said the military was trucking many thousands of
such refugees and others across the border to neighboring West
Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a deliberate forced displacement of people on
a very large scale,'' said Ian Martin, the director of the U.N.
mission in Dili.
</P>
<P>
   Some anti-independence leaders have spoken recently about the
possibility of creating a separate pro-Indonesian enclave adjacent
to West Timor. Although the United Nations and Indonesia have
dismissed that notion in the past, the current campaign could be
aimed at dividing the territory.
</P>
<P>
   For foreigners who remain in East Timor, the atmosphere of
threat is constant. Much of Dili is a ghost town, residents said,
apart from armed young men roaming about on motorcycles and groups
of refugees seeking safety.
</P>
<P>
   There is no certainty of protection in any quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Liam Phelan, a freelance reporter who has remained in Dili, said
that when armed men threatened the Turismo Hotel on Monday, he took
shelter with about 15 people in a bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard the military say: `Go in and get them. Go in and get
them,''' Phelan said. ``Those were the people who were supposed to
be guarding us.'' He said he had managed to escape and later flee
to the U.N. compound, where the only protection is provided by the
same security forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
