<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-PARADE-DEATHS-1STL     09-07 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PARADE-DEATHS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO CHILDREN DIE IN PARADE, PINNED BY VAN AND TRUCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (CLARIFIES sex of children in 6th graf; ADDS 2nd fatal accident in
grafs 15-18) (th) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two 11-year-old children were killed and another
child was injured Monday afternoon when a minivan lurched out of
control at the annual Caribbean parade in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The van, which was covered with feathers and was carrying
costumes and supplies, struck the children as they danced in the
streets, pinning them against a mammoth sound truck ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The accident came at the peak of a West Indian American Carnival
parade, casting a pall over a festival that offers the city's West
Indian immigrants a joyful release from the worries of daily life.
Police did not have a crowd estimate Monday night, but in previous
years the parade has drawn 2 million people, making it the largest
parade in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The fatalities delayed, but did not stop, the festivities.
</P>
<P>
   As the sky cleared Monday afternoon, nurses and cooks,
housekeepers and lawyers donned sequined and feathered costumes for
the procession along Eastern Parkway. Vendors served jerk chicken,
curried goat and the cool juice of sorrel while flags from every
Caribbean nation doubled as head scarves and sarongs. Spectators
squeezed against each other, mostly unaware of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The two 11-year-olds, a boy named Dawn Joseph and a girl named
Zacehel David, were taken to Kings County Hospital, where they were
pronounced dead. A third child, Kara Charles, 10, suffered neck and
back injuries and was in stable condition Monday night. Four others
suffered minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the crash, which occurred shortly before 2 p.m.,
appeared to have been an accident. The driver of the van and that
of the truck, carrying a soca band called Caribbean Magic, were
both tested for alcohol and were not intoxicated, said Inspector
Michael Collins, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The victims appeared to be dancing between the van and the
truck,'' he said. ``It doesn't appear to be alcohol-related or
mechanical failure. It just looks like an accident.''
</P>
<P>
   The van, a black Astro, was carrying costumes and supplies for
the dancers and performers ahead. Just before the accident, police
said, the driver, Ashton P. Gertton, 71, of Brooklyn, had stepped
out of the van to help some of the dancers with their costumes.
When he returned to the driver's seat, he apparently lost control.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the truck ahead, Winston G. Scott, also of
Brooklyn, was arrested for having a suspended driver's license, but
he was not cited in connection with the accident, police said.
</P>
<P>
   For a little more than two hours, police officers blocked the
westbound lanes of Eastern Parkway, near the corner of Nostrand
Avenue, where the accident had occurred. The parade continued on
the two other lanes, and a cadre of police officers tried to keep
an increasingly frustrated crowd within police barricades. Those
who witnessed the accident described it as a momentary flash of
horror, almost soundless in the boisterous celebration.
</P>
<P>
   James Charles, 43, of Paterson, N.J., was standing in the shade
of a tree near the intersection when, he said, he saw the minivan
inexplicably speed ahead. ``It just picked up speed all of a sudden
and rammed into the truck, said Charles, a maintenance man and a
native of Trinidad. ``The people were pinned in between.''
</P>
<P>
   Like dozens of others, he jumped over the barricade, he said, in
an effort to help. A woman was pumping a little girl's chest, he
said. Another was trying to give mouth-to-mouth resuscitation.
Paramedics arrived within minutes, he said, and police blocked off
the area.
</P>
<P>
   A jumble of white and pink feathers along with crushed plastic
bottles lay on the street Monday afternoon, marking the spot of the
accident. After police cleared the area and reopened the eastbound
lanes of the Parkway, a sound truck bearing the Trinidadian band,
Krosfyah, sang their version of Bob Marley's ``Redemption Song.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, as revelers were dispersing after the parade, an
18-year-old man was struck and killed by a sound truck along the
parade route, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The second fatal accident yesterday occurred about 8 p.m., after
the parade had ended but before all the sound trucks had been
cleared off the parkway, the police said. Kevon Donovan, 18,
apparently got his clothing caught in the wheel of a
tractor-trailer truck near the corner of Brooklyn Avenue and was
dragged under it, said Officer Valerie St. Rose, a police
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said that Donovan, of Clarkson Avenue in East
Flatbush, had backed into the street along with several other
people when someone in the crowd brought out a large yellow snake.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy came through with a snake and that's what I guess got
him shook,'' said Ryan Girard, a friend of Donovan's who was
mourning him outside Kings County Hospital, where he died at 9:25
p.m. ``Everybody started pushing. I tried to pull him out from
under the truck, but I couldn't do nothing. He looked at me and
called out my name.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not the first time the Caribbean parade has been marred
by fatal accidents. A parade spectator was struck by a vehicle and
killed in 1997, police said, and another man was crushed by the
wheels of a float in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   For the last several years, the parade has become the major
event for Labor Day in the city, eclipsing the procession organized
by union leaders, who this year held their Labor Day parade on the
Wednesday before Labor Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
