A2830 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v PM-BUDGET-NYT     09-07 2088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For TUESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, September 7.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE (Undated) _ American bomb makers visiting China in
1979 were startled by a series of questions that suggested the
Chinese were hot on the trail of the secret to building a modern
nuclear arsenal, miniaturization. China succeeded in September
1992. Was China's advance the result of espionage, hard work or
some mix of the two? Experts agree that spying occurred, but clash
on what impact it had on Beijing's advance, if any. A review of the
dispute, based on interviews and disclosures of weapon and
intelligence secrets, suggests that the congressional report went
beyond the evidence in asserting that stolen secrets were the main
reason for China's breakthrough. The review also bolsters a point
of agreement among feuding experts: that the federal investigation
focused too soon on the Los Alamos Laboratory and one worker there,
Wen Ho Lee. A Special Report by William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   Eds.: 5,700 words; an abridged version of 2,000 words has also
moved.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIABETES (Undated) _ With rates of diabetes soaring, experts
are studying patterns of prevention in people genetically
predisposed to the disease and looking at ways to control
cardiovascular problems in people who already have diabetes. By
Denise Grady. 1,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-POLICE-CHIEFS (Boston) _ Chiefs of police across the nation
are turning to gun control as a key factor in crime control
programs and are now pushing for tougher gun laws. A group of
chiefs will meet in Washington this week to lobby for gun laws. By
Fox Butterfield. 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ANCIENT-SKULL (New York) _ An intriguing fossil skull,
presumably from a Homo erectus and possibly a revealing piece of
evidence for understanding human evolution, has been found, not on
a parched hill in Africa or along a river in Java, but at a little
shop in Manhattan. Paleoanthropologists have concluded that it is a
genuine specimen from Indonesia and could be critical in
determining the place of the Homo erectus species in East Asia on
the human family tree. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-FUNT (Undated) _ Allen Funt, the creator and original host
of ``Candid Camera,'' network television's kindhearted snare for
the unwary, died Sunday at his home in Pebble Beach, Calif. He was
84. By Wolfgang Saxon. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TSIEN-MOUSE (Undated) _ A Scientist-at-Work profile: The
world has been frenetically beating on the door of Joe Z. Tsien,
the biologist who announced last week he had created a smarter
strain of mouse. Within this enveloping chaos, Tsien has spun
around himself a small bubble of protective serenity. He calmly
describes the remarkable journey that led him from Wu Shi, a small
town near Shanghai, to the position of having made a significant,
maybe decisive, contribution to understanding the nature of memory.
By Nicholas Wade. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ELECTRON-BONDS (Undated) _ Of the roughly 20 million
chemical substances scientists have catalogued, nearly all are
assemblages of atoms linked together by electronic bonds. The quest
to understand these tiny bonds _ the very glue of material
existence _ is the heart of chemical science. A step in this quest
was reported last week with the publication of the sharpest direct
images ever made of electronic bonds, known as orbitals. The shapes
revealed by these images _ doughnut-like rings, dumbbell-shaped
lobes and arrays suggestive of butterfly wings _ confirmed
theoretical predictions of what these bonds should look like in the
particular molecule under study. By Malcolm W. Browne. (1050 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEANDERTHALS (Undated) _ Based on detailed examination of
bone fragments from remains of Neanderthals found in Croatia,
scientists have determined that overall they were a healthy lot. By
John Noble Wilford. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CREATIVITY (Undated) _ Scientists trying to program
creativity discovered that when they fed a formula into a computer,
it generated advertising concepts judged more original and
appealing than equivalent advertisements spawned by a group of
humans. The program demonstrates what many creative people know
intuitively: that the land of the imagination is a country like any
other, with laws, rituals and a tireless police corps that must be
obeyed if one hopes to retain citizenship there. By Natalie Angier.
(1640 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items of the
way bees spread the word about food sources, how traffic moves, a
test of Cassini camers and the potency of catnip. By Henry
Fountain. (750 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column. Coffee
lovers take heed: For the sake of your health, you might consider
switching at least some of those daily cups of java for tea. Not
herbal tea but ``real'' tea _ green tea, black tea, Chinese tea,
fruit-flavored tea, with or without caffeine, lemon, milk or sugar.
As long as the leaves come from the plant Camellia sinensis, tea
will contain potent antioxidant chemicals that have been linked to
protection against major diseases like cancer and heart disease.
Even the caffeine in tea may be somewhat beneficial, emerging
evidence suggests. By Jane E. Brody. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DNA-VACCINE (Undated) _ Scientists at Stanford University
have found that a simple solution of DNA and water applied to the
skin of mice can induce an immune response comparable to one from
traditional intramuscular injection. The DNA vaccine was apparently
taken up through the hair follicles of the mice; nude mice (mice
without hair) did not show the same reaction. By Anne Eisenberg.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-INDIANS (Undated) _ Some health experts say they fear
that AIDS is about to explode among the 500 Indian tribes in the
United States. Last year on the Navajo reservation, AIDS cases grew
by 25 percent, health officials there said. By David France. (1000
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-WAKEBOARDING (Undated) _ Wakeboarding is the fastest
growing water sport, requiring skills similar to surfing,
skateboarding or snowboarding, combined with elements of water
skiing while being pulled behind a boat with a rope tow. By Julie
Walsh. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WEIGHT-LOSS Ads for two new diet supplements promise quick
and efficient weight loss without exercise. Experts say there may
be some small amount of fat absorption, but very small. By Liz
Neporent. (625 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and
fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Night eating syndrome afflicts an estimated 3.8 million
Americans and now is being linked to a vicious cycle of seratonin.
(350 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ No one is talking about a cure, or even any improvement in the
very near future, but researchers are reporting some promising
progress in the field of lupus, a serious autoimmune disease
affecting about 1.5 million people in the United States. (280
words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A new study from the American Psychological Association last
month indicates that under some circumstances otherwise reasonable
adults may adopt the karmic explanation of illness that what goes
around comes around and the an illness might be a punishment for
misdeeds. (255 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PAIN (Undated) _ Researchers at the University of
California/San Francisco think that in the case of an inflamed
joint, that ache may be the body's way of telling its most
aggressive defenders, ``Enough already, you're hurting me!'' By
John O'Neil.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: Since I seldom
see mosquitoes in daylight, can I avoid bites by going out only in
the sunshine? Unfortunately, no. (290 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS (Washington) _ As Congress returns this week from its
August recess, Republicans and the White House face the difficult
choice of compromise or confrontation on issues from tax cuts to
gun control to regulation of managed health care. By Eric Schmitt.
1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-FASHIONS (Undated) _ While very young children have always
used fashion to fit in with their peers, their desire to match the
clothing popular among older siblings and even adults is on the
rise. Their tastes are no longer for cute and innocent _ like
T-shirts with hearts and teddy bears. Instead, the desire is for
the culturally clued in _ like the henna-style tattoo necklaces
that ape the stencils worn by Madonna. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT2 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   IRIDIUM-OUTLOOK (Phoenix) _ Iridium LLC, the global satellite
telephone venture that was supposed to offer communications ``with
anyone, anytime, virtually anywhere in the world,'' is in trouble,
but don't tell that to Raymond Leopold. He and two colleagues at
Motorola Inc. dreamed up the global telephone service here in the
Arizona desert more than a dozen years ago. And now, even as the
venture hobbles through Chapter 11 bankruptcy, he remains
optimistic. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BANKS (Tokyo) _ For top executives of Dai-Ichi Kangyo
Bank, Fuji Bank and Industrial Bank of Japan, signing up to merge
their vast operations last month was far easier than the monumental
task they now face in consolidating three of the country's biggest
banks under one roof. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   D&AMP;B-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Since its founding in the 1840s, Dun
&AMP; Bradstreet Corp. has employed four men who became president and
built two of the more envied franchises in finance: Its
credit-information operation and Moody's Investors Service. Such
strong businesses have always attracted long-term shareholders. But
for the biggest of them, patience with D&AMP;B has run out. By Richard
A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   PATEK-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ In a new campaign for its latest
expensive timepiece, the Swiss luxury watchmaker Patek Philippe is
focusing on young, affluent women in hopes of broadening its
consumer base beyond well-to-do fathers and stately grandfathers.
By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (Undated) Anthony Lewis writes about the cost of
``realism'' in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (Moved in ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ART-MARKET (New York) _ Like Broadway, baseball and big-game
hunting, the art trade has always had a season. It began in
mid-September, rose to heights each fall and again each spring,
then tailed off at the end of June, when rich collectors headed for
a summer of leisure at their country homes. But not last year, and
especially not this year. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-THEATER (Beijing) _ Chinese officials have settled on a
stark modern French design for China's new national theater complex
here. The design is a titanium and glass bubble-shaped structure
that sits in the middle of a vast lake and is entered via an
underwater tunnel. It will quickly redefine the landscape in the
sedate, conservative political heart of Beijing, adding the first
touch of modern Western architecture. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   VELAZQUEZ-BONES (Madrid, Spain) _ Spain's celebration of the
400th anniversary of the birth of the painter Diego Velazquez de
Silva includes major exhibitions of his work at the Prado Museum,
but officials want something else for the festivities: his bones.
By Al Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   HITLER-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Hitler's Niece,'' by Ron Hansen
(HarperCollins). Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   TV-HANOI-REVIEW (Undated) _ On PBS, ``Pete Peterson: Assignment
Hanoi.'' Reviewed by Walter Goodman.
</P>
