<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2948 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-INDONESIA-REVIEW-AR     09-07 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-INDONESIA-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S MANY FACES REFLECT ONE NATION, DIVISIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ ``One country. One people. One language.''
</P>
<P>
   As a national credo, displayed on banners and placards, it
sounds simple enough.
</P>
<P>
   But in this scattered archipelago of 13,000 islands, roiling
with an untamed mix of cultures, ethnic groups, histories,
rivalries, gods and spoken tongues, it begins to seem almost
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   These days, some people say it is.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia, the world's fourth most populous nation with well
over 200 million people, is deep in a crisis of economics, politics
and national identity. Its leaders and institutions have lost much
of their popular standing and legitimacy. The forces that most
overtly held Indonesia together _ the grip of a dictator and the
harshness of his military _ have retreated since the forced
resignation 15 months ago of Suharto as president.
</P>
<P>
   A country so unsure of its unity that it has made oneness an
obsession is being forced to rediscover the logic of its
nationhood. The challenge as it steps gingerly into an era of
democracy is to want to be a nation.
</P>
<P>
   The violence that ravaged the former Portuguese colony of East
Timor last week as it was voting for independence from Indonesia
came as a reminder to the outside world of the diversity and
tenuousness of this scattered nation. Perhaps the fears it has
aroused _ of centrifugal forces that could pull Indonesia apart _
are exaggerated. Still, it points up the counterproductiveness of
enforced union.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are going to have an Indonesia in which the constituent
parts sit happily together as a republic and not because they are
held together by bayonets, you are going to have to have a system
where the constituent parts come together because they want to be
together,'' said James Dunn, a former Australian diplomat who is an
expert on Indonesia. ``Since the founding of Indonesia, the
military has seen itself as the guardian of national integrity. In
a democracy national integrity has to be held together by the
national will.''
</P>
<P>
   In recognition of this, the post-Suharto government _ which is
still taking shape _ is exploring ways to devolve some economic and
political control to the provinces. An extreme possibility, one
that would demand a constitutional amendment, would be to shift
power into a federal structure.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian rule has sometimes been likened to a colonial
structure, with the dominant Javanese on their relatively small
island asserting their rule over the larger and more resource-rich
outer islands. A fairer distribution of the national wealth along
with greater political empowerment could go a long way toward
mollifying Indonesia's restive provinces.
</P>
<P>
   But the loosening of a grip always carries the risk of loss of
control. After 32 years of Suharto's policy of enforced national
harmony, the vacuum created by his departure and the humbling of
the military has been quickly filled by all the repressed passions
of political, religious and ethnic differences that strain
Indonesia's fabric.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, separatist movements have been energized in
several areas, highlighted by East Timor, which Indonesia invaded
in 1975 but which never accepted integration as the country's 27th
province.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the Indonesian capital, Jakarta _ and particularly in
the military _ fear that freedom for East Timor could be the start
of a process of national disintegration. Other analysts point to
that territory's unique place as a national afterthought and argue
that a line can be drawn between East Timor and the rest of
Indonesia. It is the only part of the country to have been
colonized by the Portuguese rather than by the Dutch and it is the
only part to have been been dragged into union by invasion.
</P>
<P>
   The most potentially destabilizing separatist movement is in the
strongly Islamic, natural gas-rich province of Aceh, where the loss
of life this year has been far greater than in East Timor. A former
Islamic kingdom with its own proud past, Aceh is an integral part
of Indonesia's history and self-definition and its loss could deal
a severe blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very worried,'' a senior Western diplomat said. ``If
Aceh begins to take off, they will really have problems with the
integrity of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   A smaller, less unified separatist movement has flared in the
remote mountains of Irian Jaya, whose primitive people are as
strange and exotic to residents of modern Jakarta as they are to
New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Vicious bloodletting has also continued in the Moluccas (the
former Spice Islands that first attracted traders to the
archipelago) and in West Kalimantan on the island of Borneo. But
these eruptions, for the moment at least, have more to do with
local feuds, and with Jakarta's inability to impose order, than
with serious separatist threats.
</P>
<P>
   Though they may not pull the nation apart, the declarations of
individuality by the separatists offer a reminder that Indonesia is
an artificial geographical conglomeration inherited from its Dutch
colonizers.
</P>
<P>
   The elegant, taciturn princes of Java seem to have little in
common with the otherworldly dancers of Hindu Bali, the long-eared
Dayak tribesmen of Borneo, the seagoing pirates of the Spice
Islands or the Chinese traders who control the country's ports and
warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   What brings them all together as Indonesians?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is an idea, as in other big, diverse countries like
India and the United States,'' said James Clad, a professor of
Southeast Asian studies at Georgetown University. ``It is an idea
of an archipelagic country, a concept that goes back to pre-Islamic
times.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1751 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-INDONESIA-REVIEW-AR     09-07 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-INDONESIA-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S MANY FACES REFLECT ONE NATION, DIVISIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ ``One country. One people. One language.''
</P>
<P>
   As a national credo, displayed on banners and placards, it
sounds simple enough.
</P>
<P>
   But in this scattered archipelago of 13,000 islands, roiling
with an untamed mix of cultures, ethnic groups, histories,
rivalries, gods and spoken tongues, it begins to seem almost
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   These days, some people say it is.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia, the world's fourth most populous nation with well
over 200 million people, is deep in a crisis of economics, politics
and national identity. Its leaders and institutions have lost much
of their popular standing and legitimacy. The forces that most
overtly held Indonesia together _ the grip of a dictator and the
harshness of his military _ have retreated since the forced
resignation 15 months ago of Suharto as president.
</P>
