<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2983 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-DC-URBAN-FOSSILS-RE     09-07 0373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-DC-URBAN-FOSSILS-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PAVED PARADISE FOR URBAN FOSSILS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By SARAH BOXER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's more than one approach to Washington. There is the high
road. There is the low road. And there is what's stuck in the road.
Washington's hot asphalt streets happen to be just the right stuff
for turning the gleaming treasures that drop on them into instant
fossils.
</P>
<P>
   Well, OK, it isn't exactly the Great Rift Valley. The treasures
mashed into the streets tend to be the homely remnants of advanced
capitalist society: watch-strap buckles, combs and runaway baby
socks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when it comes to modern fossilization, the conditions
don't get much better than this. The asphalt in Washington is hot
and impressionable. The traffic is relentless. And the roads are
seldom repaved, which means an urban fossil has a good chance of
lasting a very long time.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Crowley, a staff photographer for The New York Times who
has made a hobby of documenting the city's flattened refuse, says
he regularly passes fossils he photographed years ago, including a
coffee stirrer from McDonald's pressed into I Street and an old
spoon planted on 16th Street that still clearly says ``Stainless
Taiwan.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the laws of fossilization is that the things that get
mired in the streets tend to be common objects. In other words, the
plastic comb and the family of pull-tabs from a six-pack represent
thousands more like them.
</P>
<P>
   So surely there must be signs of government crushed somewhere in
the streets. Alas, a tiny charm of the Capitol is the sole
governmental fossil, unless you count that plastic stirrer from
McDonald's, which could have been dropped by the president.
</P>
<P>
   But beware: overinterpretation is a hazard of archaeology. If
you think that little piece of plastic left after a car accident
looks like the Washington Monument, or you're imagining that the
hood ornament resembles something in the Air and Space Museum,
maybe you've been in Washington a little too long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0067 </DOCNO>
