<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Best bar mitzvah, bar none
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGELINA COUNTY, Texas _ I traveled to Austin on a recent
Saturday to attend a cousin's bar mitzvah.
</P>
<P>
   Distant cousin, that is.
</P>
<P>
   I read once that we're all at least 40th cousins, such is the
family of man.
</P>
<P>
   I feel special kinship to the parents of the young man who was
celebrating his bar mitzvah.
</P>
<P>
   They're Sharon and Ken Herman, both of whom write for the Austin
American-Statesman. When I was editor of the Lufkin Daily News,
more than 20 years ago, I gave Ken his first job as a reporter. He
in turn gave the newspaper a Pulitzer Prize for an investigation
into the recruitment death of a Lufkin Marine.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, I introduced Ken and Sharon. I was speaking at a press
club get-together in Dallas on how we'd won the Pulitzer Prize _
Ken and I split it right down the middle; he did all the work and I
took all the credit. At a reception afterwards, Sharon introduced
herself.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in the conversation she mentioned she was Jewish. I
told her, ``Have I got a deal for you,'' took her by the hand, led
her through the crowd and presented her with Ken.
</P>
<P>
   I was one of Ken's groomsmen when they married, which was the
first time I was ever in a synagogue, and their son Jeremy's bar
mitzvah was my first bar mitzvah. We Baptists don't get out that
much.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind I couldn't understand all of what was going on, most
of the ceremony being in Hebrew. But the psalms, which were
translated in English on facing pages of the Hebrew book of
prayers, read the same as the ones recited in Christian churches.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, how often do you have the opportunity to participate in
a ritual that dates back thousands of years? No doubt it's evolved
somewhat. For one thing, I doubt there were marshmallows in Old
Testament times.
</P>
<P>
   That's what we pelted the young man with at the conclusion of
the bar mitzvah, marshmallows individually wrapped in silver paper
and tied with a bow. It's to wish him a sweet life.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing the marshmallows was one of my favorite parts of the
service.
</P>
<P>
   But what I liked best, and what meant the most to me, came later
during the regular Sabbath worship when the rabbi read a letter he
had received from members of the University Baptist Church in
Austin. Here's what it said:
</P>
<P>
   ``We, the undersigned, gathered at the University Baptist Church
for worship this August 15, 1999, reach out in affection to our
Jewish brothers and sisters in Austin and around the world
</P>
<P>
   ``_ to deplore the violence committed in a California Jewish
community center this week by a man belonging to several hate
groups;
</P>
<P>
   ``_ to reject the hatred expressed and the violence committed
against the Jewish people through history by anyone, but especially
by those who did so in the name of Christianity;
</P>
<P>
   ``_ to speak our gratitude for the gifts and contributions the
Jewish people have brought to us, to our nation, and to all
humankind;
</P>
<P>
   ``_ to recognize that Judaism and Christianity are kindred
faiths and that we are all brothers and sisters, children of the
one God;
</P>
<P>
   ``_ and to express our solidarity with you, our desire for
friendship, and our commitment to your safety in the places where
you live, work, and worship. Because acts of violence have been
committed in the name of Jesus whom we call Christ, as Christians
we feel it important to make this expression of solidarity,
appreciation, and commitment to friendship in the name of Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   It made me proud to be a Baptist. It made me proud to be a
Baptist attending a Jewish service. Such is the family of God.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address is P.O. Box
151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915; e-mail, jmurray(AT)lcc.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
