<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Israelis perplexing about murderers
 &HT;    (For release Sept. 8, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The just-concluded agreement between the Israelis and
Palestinians _ another in an infinite number of agreements that
will be violated or ignored in various ways by one or both sides _
drew my attention, not so much for the brittle peace it is supposed
to bring, but for how the Israelis feel about murder.
</P>
<P>
   My conclusion: It all depends upon who gets murdered.
</P>
<P>
   An inflexible point of the Israeli position vis-a-vis an
agreement with the Palestinians was that it would not release any
Palestinians who had murdered Israelis. There are somewhere in the
vicinity of 45 in that category.
</P>
<P>
   And I wouldn't let them go, either _ no matter who they
murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Going into last weekend, this caveat appeared to be the singular
most bitter difference between the Israelis and Arabs, and for a
while it looked like the broader agreement would collapse as a
result.
</P>
<P>
   But the Palestinians blinked _ or were poked in the eye by a
visiting U.S. secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis prevailed on the murderer issue and negotiated on
others they felt negotiable to where they and the Palestinians
signed on the dotted line so that Madeleine Albright's big trip
would be a congenial photo-op.
</P>
<P>
   But here's my sticking point. Israel, which feels so strongly
about murderers of its own people, apparently does not feel that
strongly about murders of others. In this case an American.
</P>
<P>
   Not many days before Israel forced their hard line on murderers
of Israelis, a young American who fled to Israel two days after he
murdered, burned and dismembered a person in Maryland in 1997
admitted his guilt and appears headed for a 24-year sentence, with
release possible after just 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   What Samuel Sheinbein was running away from was the technicality
that Maryland has the death penalty; Israel does not, unless you
happen to be Adolf Eichmann or those of his ilk. While Maryland
sentences people to death _ 19 are under such judgment _ World
Almanac data shows it hasn't carried out any.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to Israelis, it must be noted that many of them,
including legislators, feel Sheinbein should have been extradited
to the United States. But the issue found its way to the Israeli
Supreme Court, which used a broad anti-extradition law to deny the
U.S. an opportunity to try this American for the murder of an
American in America.
</P>
<P>
   Sheinbein's ambiguous connection with Israel is that his father
has Israeli citizenship. Seventeen years old at the time, Samuel
beat it over to Israel and hid behind an Israeli law that says
17-year-olds cannot be tried as adults. In the U.S., especially in
the case of an appalling crime, they can.
</P>
<P>
   An example is the Georgia 15-year-old who shot six school
students but didn't kill anyone; he has been ordered by a judge to
be tried as an adult. The maximum a juvenile can serve in Georgia
is 60 months. As an adult, T.J. Solomon could be sentenced to life
in prison, which is a lot longer term than what Sheinbein, who
killed, burned and mutilated, is going to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Sheinbein and his father cleverly maneuvered Israeli law,
created _ the Israelis say _ not to safeguard juvenile murderers
but to protect Israelis from anti-Semitism elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Despite efforts to modify the law the Sheinbeins manipulated, it
stands. American authorities who energetically sought extradition
are enraged.
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea how long each of the Palestinian murderers of
Israelis have been in prison, but I've got a notion that many of
them have been there for more than the 14 years Sheinbein will
likely serve.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, Israel will reshape its extradition law so that it
cannot be used as a haven for young murderers who happen to be
Jewish. It also is my hope that Samuel Sheinbein, a savage murderer
with no stated remorse, won't be released after just 14 years but
will be required to remain in prison for the full term of his
sentence; then deported.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
