 Tuesday, Sept. 7, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TELEPHONE-FRAUD (San Francisco) _ Gone are the days when thieves
were just after your wallet or credit cards. Now, federal
authorities say, they're after your phone bill too. ``Some con
artists have found the telephone billing and collection system to
be a fertile area to defraud consumers,'' says the Federal Trade
Commission. They are arranging to put charges on a consumer's phone
bill for services that were never ordered, authorized, received or
used. By ERIN McCORMICK.
</P>
<P>
   NO-GUNS-TEXAS (Fort Worth, Texas) _ Admiring the success of a
Virginia program that funnels criminals caught with illegal guns
through the federal courts rather than the state system, Fort Worth
is preparing to launch a similar program called Safe City USA.
Community leaders in Richmond, Va., believe criminals are leaving
their guns at home rather than facing a highly publicized,
mandatory federal prison sentence. As a result, homicides are down
dramatically. By KIM COBB.
</P>
<P>
   POT-PATIENT (San Francisco) _ When 71-year-old Robert DeArkland
discovered he had prostate cancer in addition to his sciatica and
arthritis, he asked his psychiatrist to recommend marijuana to ease
the pain. But early one morning a few weeks after DeArkland bought
thirteen small pot plants from a medical marijuana club, sheriff's
deputies broke down the door of his home, handcuffed him, seized
the plants and charged him with cultivating pot for sale. By SETH
ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   APPLE-IMITATOR (San Francisco) _ Apparently, turnabout is not
fair play. Twenty years after Steve Jobs ripped off Xerox PARC's
graphical user interface technology, Apple Computer's ever-interim
CEO can't believe someone would have the nerve to knock off his
iMac. The alleged culprit: eMachines Inc., which recently
introduced an iMac look-alike dubbed the eOne. By ALAN T.
SARACEVIN.
</P>
<P>
   SARATOGA-WATER (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ Posing for a newspaper
photographer at the water bottling plant she oversees, Robin Prever
experiments with crossing her arms and legs just so, to exude
confidence. The chief executive of Saratoga Beverage Group
understands image and marketing. When you're selling water in a
bottle for as much as $1.85, marketing is critical. By CLAIRE
HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRIAL-DRUGS (San Francisco) _ After being diagnosed with kidney
cancer, Larry Williamson began waging a life-and-death battle to
gain access to an experimental drug available largely to people in
clinical trials. He is not alone in his quest. Many other
terminally ill patients in the United States fight similar battles
every day. Whether they can _ or should _ get special access to
these drugs is a subject of huge debate. By SARAH YANG.
</P>
<P>
   PERFECT-SATS (Albany, N.Y.) _ For Martina Hurwitz, who garnered
a perfect 1600 on her SATs (800 each in math and verbal) preparing
for the exam was a family affair. Her father, a college math
professor, would review math with her. Her mother, a linguistics
professor, would review the verbal exam with her. By RICK KARLIN.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A reader asks, ``On a recent trip my
wife purchased an interesting plant. She was told that it is called
the `bat-faced' plant. It has been a good conversation piece. Any
help would be appreciated.'' Assorted Q&AMP;As. By KATHY HUBER
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-BAD-BOY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Sloppy editing and a level of
writing that ranges from competent to amateurish mars Gary
Lavergne's book ``Bad boy from Rosebud: The murderous life of
Kenneth Allen McDuff (University of North Texas press, $29.95) By
MIKE SNYDER
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-SPACE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Robert Zubrin, the feisty
aeorspace engineer known for his bold $20 billion, 10-year strategy
he outlined in his 1996 book, has the imagination to claim the role
of unofficial space advocate. Zubrin's new book is ``Entering
Space: Creating a spacefaring civilization'' (J.P. Tarcher/Putnam,
$24.95). By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Low season means low prices at hotels,
doesn't it? Or does it mean less service and amenities? By HARRY
SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KNAPP-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Jim Payton could barely sleep the
night before, could barely keep his heart in his chest on the ride
over to Harding Park's golf course Monday morning. ``I kept
thinking: I'm going to get a lesson from Tiger Woods, I can't
believe it,'' said Payton, 16 years old and rarely a victim of
nerves. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Labor Day weekend was a good time
to think about all the lousy jobs we've had, especially for those
of us facing possible career changes. They don't make lousy jobs
like they used to. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Texans put a high priority on
education. Education accounts for the largest expenditure from the
state budget, and its administration at the state level is governed
by a small army of elected and appointed officials, including one
governor, 181 legislators, one state education commissioner and a
15-member State Board of Education. The educational bureaucracy is
rather top-heavy, to say the least. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   CREATIONISM-DEBATE (Oakland, Calif.) _ For years, Christian
fundamentalists have used pseudoscience to argue that creationism
should be reinstated as part of the public school science
curriculum. Thwarted by the courts, they have embarked on a new
approach If the Bible must go, then so must Darwin. By MICHAEL
MECHANIC.
</P>
</TEXT>
