<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Wednesday, September 9, 1999 are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The Samuel Sheinbein murder case has left a
bitter aftertaste for many in this country, the residue of friction
between two strikingly different criminal justice systems. It will
surprise most Americans that our system was no less out of step
with international norms in this mess than Israel's was. (Teepen,
Cox Newspapers.) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ The just-concluded agreement between the
Israelis and Palestinians _ another in an infinite number of
agreements that will be violated or ignored in various ways by one
or both sides _ drew my attention, not so much for the brittle
peace it is supposed to bring, but for how the Israelis feel about
murder. My conclusion: It all depends upon who gets murdered.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ I traveled to Austin on a recent Saturday to
attend a cousin's bar mitzvah. I read once that we're all at least
40th cousins, such is the family of man. (Murray, Cox News Service)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The government has gone and
shut down Reno, Nevada's Mustang Ranch. Uncle Horseface's
profession gets the last laugh. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Roni Lowe, who has resigned her
Miss Lubbock Teen USA title, was assigned to an alternative school
for three months for making a threat. She pulled out of school
rather than face this music. Maybe she deserved it. More evidence
could frame this matter better. However, nothing reported thus far
would indicate that what Roni said was anything more than
garden-variety lip-flapping. (Young, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DONTASK-EDITORIAL _ The Pentagon's recent refinements of the
``don't-ask, don't-tell'' policy regarding homosexuals in uniform
are the equivalent of slapping paint on an old wreck of a house. In
neither case does the prettifying hide the basic unsoundness
within. (Atlanta Constitution)
</P>
