<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3023 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN08-COX     09-07 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mustang Ranch news gives Uncle Horseface last laugh
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Now the government has gone and done it.
They've shut down the Mustang Ranch _ 440 acres and a brothel, just
east of Reno, Nev. The Feds say it's because the original owner
paid off local officials and skirted taxes. My Uncle Buddy would
say it's sour grapes because those IRS guys were so inept they
couldn't make out in a house of horizontal refreshment with a
hundred dollar bill and a search warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Buddy had nothing against the IRS personally, he just
didn't like Walton P., his brother-in-law who happened to work
there.
</P>
<P>
   Walton P. (or Uncle Horseface as the family had nicknamed him
due to his captivating manner) had married Edna Parker, Buddy's
older sister (my aunt), later in life. Before that, he'd been
living at home with his widowed momma, Mrs. Walton P. Sr., a dour
lady who appeared not to like any of us, (SET ITAL)particularly(END
ITAL) my Aunt Edna _ a divorced woman known to relish a good laugh
and a pitcher of martinis, and not necessarily in that order.
</P>
<P>
   Twice a year or so, the Parker family would have get-togethers
in their home. Everyone was expected to show up and stay a week: my
mother (their daughter, Doris), my father and I; Uncle Buddy (their
youngest son who seemed to spend an inordinate number of years in
one military school after another); Aunt Edna and Uncle Horseface
and, of course, Mother Walton P. Sr., who was always included in
the family outings (or maybe more appropriately, innings).
Grandmother Parker referred to it as a family appreciation week. My
father called it a re-enactment of the Civil War because it always
turned into one hell of a battle.
</P>
<P>
   The Parkers were not a close family, and to add to the misery,
nobody could ever tell when Mother Walton P. Sr., was having fun
because none of us had ever seen her smile. In fact we'd never seen
her do much of anything other than read the flip side of her dinner
plate to check out who made the china. Once my little cousin
Malcolm poked at her with a toy fire engine, but nothing happened.
His momma said it was because Mother Walton P. Sr., wore a cast
iron corset.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, Uncle Buddy would make an effort to liven up the
gatherings, but his ideas of fun left a lot of folks wondering why
his momma hadn't drowned him at birth.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy's favorite trick was to hide out in one of the closets
that connected many of the bedrooms in Mrs. Parker's old Riverside
house. He'd wait patiently in the dark for an unsuspecting victim
to come looking for either a change of clothes or a shortcut to the
next room and then, mid-closet, he'd whisk the hangars apart,
groan, and fall to the floor, gasping that ``Big Al'' and his boys
had gotten him.
</P>
<P>
   The family was pretty much used to Buddy's antics and had worked
up its own system for dealing with the closet troll. In fact, until
I was old enough to go to slumber parties at other girls' homes, I
thought it was perfectly normal to pick up the little broom from
beside the bedroom fireplace and bang on the closet door before I
opened it. It was kind of fun because Mrs. Parker had given us
permission to hit Buddy with the broomstick if we found him in our
closet.
</P>
<P>
   Once, at the height of WW2, my father was in the bathroom
shaving when Buddy, with his hair slicked back and wearing a phony
moustache and parts of Grandaddy's old WW1 uniform that he'd found
in the attic, kicked open the door and yelled, ``HEIL HITLER!''
Daddy swore he'd come that close to cutting his (own) throat and
that he'd get even.
</P>
<P>
   Payback came a few days later. It had something to do with
Buddy's favorite pudding and a bottle of ipecac.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Buddy was allowed to live to maturity, but he never got
over making jokes about Uncle Horseface's profession. Too bad he's
not around to savor the Mustang takeover. His comments would have
been choice.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
