<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3024 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN08-COX     09-07 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beauty queen's penalty sounds like Columbine-sized overreaction
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ It's mighty dangerous to be a Texas cheerleader.
</P>
<P>
   We digested with discomfort the case of the Channelview mom who
cooked up an aborted hit on a pompom rival of her daughter. Now we
have the whole cheering squad of Frenship High in Lubbock, Texas,
reportedly scurrying for cover from a menacing beauty queen. To
gauge the punishment, she must have borrowed her designs from
(ITALIC) Carrie. (END ITALIC)
</P>
<P>
   Roni Lowe, who has resigned her Miss Lubbock Teen USA title, was
assigned to an alternative school for three months for making a
threat. She pulled out of school rather than face this music.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she deserved it. More evidence could frame this matter
better. However, nothing reported thus far would indicate that what
Roni said was anything more than garden-variety lip-flapping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to kick your butt, and everybody's going to know
what happened'' is what Roni said she said to a cheerleader. That
was wrong and stupid.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the cheerleaders will disappear from the face of the
earth, and everyone will know who did it'' is how Frenship
officials paraphrased her.
</P>
<P>
   Frenship ISD said Roni's punishment was in keeping with its
zero-tolerance discipline policy, devised in light of the Columbine
shootings. Threats will be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   As a parent, one can only say, darned right. Bring students in
and have them account for their threats.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm also thinking: If every student who said, ``I'm going to
kick your butt'' or something similar went to the alternative
school for three months, we might have to shut some schools down.
</P>
<P>
   I can't believe that unless a girl like Roni, who obviously has
some worthy qualities, had a history of making threats, she
couldn't have been summoned by the assistant principal, ordered to
explain her statement and told, ``One more outburst like that,
Roni, and it's alternative for you.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago Waco schools realized that a
zero-tolerance policy that sent students to the alternative school
for a single fight was hard to defend. For one thing, it was
sometimes impossible to know if one child was simply defending
himself or herself in a scuffle. For another, sometimes the
incident was the result of a reflexive elbow, or low blood sugar,
or just kids being playful and getting too rough. Alternative
school for any and every fight? WISD thought better eventually, and
good for it.
</P>
<P>
   This year WISD continued to find degrees of reason in
alternative school placement. Students who previously were sent
there because of truancy now will be handled on campus with the
advisory that they and their parents will see a judge if it
continues. Students who previously were placed in alternative
school for offenses away from school _ underage drinking, say _
will be dealt with in the court system and kept on their campuses
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   The ironic result: While some school districts are packing more
students off to alternative campuses under heightened,
Columbine-inspired zero-tolerance, Waco likely will be sending
fewer students this year, reserving room for the most serious and
chronic problems. That's the way it should be.
</P>
<P>
   I asked WISD coordinator for special programs Marcia Anderson if
Roni Lowe would have gotten three months in alternative school in
Waco for what she said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said she wouldn't engage in conjecture or second
guessing, saying only that the WISD policy would be to get the
facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe it to everyone to investigate the situation and not
overreact, because you can ruin someone's life, or a good portion
of it, by overreacting.''
</P>
<P>
   Waco has a zero-tolerance plan, but no policy of automatically
removing someone from a campus for making a threat, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Roni Lowe got what she deserved. Or maybe a hair-trigger
system has made one more child pay too dearly for the acts of
Columbine's monsters.
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
