<HEADER>
A3027 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN08-CO     09-07 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Manager likes large companies for his fund
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best way to make money in the market is to stick with big
companies that have the power to grow even bigger, says Fritz
Meyer.
</P>
<P>
   He is co-manager of a 14-month-old, large growth mutual fund
that racked up a total return of 45.3 percent in the 12 months
ended July 31. The S&AMP;P 500 index was way behind, at 20.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   He set that record on a very short track, that's true. But his
record at the Invesco Growth and Income fund makes him worth
listening to when he talks about stock picking. It is a large
growth fund, despite the two-part name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the record high price-earnings ratio of the market, we
think growth stocks are logically valued,'' Meyer said last week.
``We're paying a richer price, but these companies are better
managed and faster growing. Corporate America has seemingly greater
growth opportunities than it ever had before.''
</P>
<P>
   The record of large growth funds tends to back him up. Sort of.
Over the last 10 years, the funds recorded an average annual return
of 16.4 percent. As Meyer notes, that beat the 14 percent
performance of large-company, value-oriented funds.
</P>
<P>
   But the same database from funds researcher Morningstar also
reports that the S&AMP;P 500 index topped both of them, with returns of
17.4 percent. The rankings are the same over five- and 15-year
periods.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer looks for his best stocks among about 200 with market
capitalization of more than $10 billion. Capitalization is the
number of shares of company stock times the price of each share,
which tells you how much the market thinks the company is worth.
</P>
<P>
   His fund keeps 70 percent to 80 percent of its money in stocks
of those big, big companies. The remainder goes into midsize
companies that Meyer and co-manager Trent E. May believe will grow
to big-cap size.
</P>
<P>
   The fund is concentrated. It owned only 55 stocks at the end of
July, indicating just how picky the two managers are.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer talked in an interview about the three factors he
considers in his search for the most promising stocks:
</P>
<P>
   _ Growing revenue. He means increases that are driven by unit
volume _ the number of products sold _ rather than price increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a sign that the company has something unique and
proprietary and is in an excellent place, at the right time, for
its industry,'' Meyer said. ``Therefore the chances are that the
company's growth is sustainable.''
</P>
<P>
   He looks for revenue growth substantially better than the
average for all companies in the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   _ Improving profit margins. He looks at after-tax profit
margins, searching for higher profit rates or at least for rates
that are steady and higher than the margins of comparable
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``That typically is a sign that management is good at holding
the line on costs while revenue increases,'' Meyer said. It also
indicates a strong demand for the company's products or services,
he said, and suggests continued, faster-than-average growth in
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Healthy cash flow. Meyer wants companies that bring in enough
money to cover the costs of building the business in the future.
The other options for growth capital are issuing more stock, which
hurts existing shareholders, or borrowing money, which increases
the risks that the company and its shareholders must cope with.
</P>
<P>
   So what are Meyer's favorites right now?
</P>
<P>
   The best indicator may be what the Growth and Income fund owns.
As of July 31, the biggest holdings were IBM, 4.4 percent of the
$61 million portfolio; Intel, 4.1 percent; Microsoft, 3.8 percent;
Harrah's Entertainment, 3.8 percent; and GE, 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those represent purchases in the past, of course. They don't
tell you whether those five stocks are still good buys. That's a
question an interested investor would have to answer for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
