<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3063 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-SLAVERY-TODAY-NYTSF &LR;      09-07 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAVERY-TODAY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HORRIFYING REALITY OF SLAVERY IN AFRICA TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DIANA BUTLER BASS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In September 1829, a black American named David Walker published
his ``Appeal to the Coloured Citizens of the World.'' In it, he
condemned the ``inhuman system of slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   Historians credit him with inspiring Americans to greater
radicalism in abolishing slavery.
</P>
<P>
   True freedom, Walker claimed, ``shall never be fully
consummated'' until ``the entire emancipation of (the) enslaved
brethren all over the world'' is accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, Walker's appeal is as relevant today as it
was 170 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This week, a United Nations committee is gathering to discuss
slavery. Not the slavery of David Walker's time, but slavery in
today's world, especially in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary slavery takes many forms-- forced prostitution and
sweatshops included. Few instances are as horrifying as Sudan's
slave trade, where women and children are sold as chattel.
</P>
<P>
   According to the human rights group Christian Solidarity
International (CSI), Sudanese slavery ``is not merely a fading
relic of the past, but has undergone a revival as a result of
encouragement from the ruling National Islamic Front.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1983, the largely Muslim north has waged a civil war
against the Christian and animist south. When the government tried
to Islamize the south, the southern Sudanese rebelled, forming
their own army.
</P>
<P>
   During the last sixteen years, 2 million people have died from
either famine or violence.
</P>
<P>
   As part of this military campaign, northern ``defense'' forces
have reintroduced the ancient practice of slavery in Sudan. As
war-booty, tens of thousands of women and children have been sold
into bondage. Human rights advocates report widespread
brutalityincluding torture, sexual abuse,and genital
mutilationamong the slaves. In addition, the slaves ``are forced by
their masters to change their cultural identity and become
Muslims.''
</P>
<P>
   The western media has been largely silent regarding contemporary
slavery. For years, however, conservative Christian journalists
have covered this story, inspiring their co-religionists to take up
the anti-slavery cause. As a result, organizations such as
Christian Solidarity International and Christian Freedom
International have developed sizable programs to free the slaves
and press for international awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream media outlets may have hesitated to report African
slavery because of the pro-Christian and anti-Islamic polemics of
these organizations. That bias, however, does not change the fact
that the northern Sudanese,no matter what their religion, appear to
have deprived thousands of citizens of basic human rights.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the apparent atrocities, according to A.M. Rosenthal
of The New York Times, the United Nations is not meeting to condemn
the Sudanese government. Instead, it plans to discuss penalties
against Christian Solidarity International for violating UN
procedural rules. Not surprisingly, Sudan brought charges against
CSI. CSI's credentials as a UN nongovernmental organization have
been suspended.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations response to CSI resembles,historically at
least, the American government's defense of southern slaveholders.
When a slave fled to freedom, American law punished the slave and
any persons offering help. The government refused to condemn
slavery or the slaveholders. Do not blame the ``inhuman system of
slavery.'' Blame its victims.
</P>
<P>
   CSI may not have followed the rules. Certainly, some of their
policies are controversial. They sponsor a ``slave redemption''
program through which contributors can buy slaves for $50 each.
Since the program's inception, CSI has freed almost 8,000 slaves,
with the most dramatic contribution coming from some elementary
school children in Aurora, Colo., who raised $50,000 to purchase
1,000 slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the human-rights efforts in Sudan, CSI's program has
finally raised international concern regarding slavery. No wonder
the Sudanese government would like CSI condemned by the UN.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever good CSI does, however, slave redemption is not a
solution. Other groups have accused CSI of unintentionally fuelling
market demand for slaves by giving money to an oppressive regime.
In 1829, David Walker accused the American Colonization Society
(founded in 1817) of doing the same.
</P>
<P>
   Like CSI, the ACS raised money to purchase slaves and send them
home. Although ACS freed nearly 2,000 slaves, they put cash into
the hands of slaveholders who, in turn, bought more. Slave
redemption does not work.
</P>
<P>
   In the long term, Christian Solidarity International best serves
the slaves by working for peace and reconciliation in Sudan between
the Arab north and the black African south. We can be grateful to
them for witnessing to these atrocities while most of the world
looked away. As with Muslims in Bosnia, Americans can ill afford
silence when religion is used to serve oppression.
</P>
<P>
   As David Walker wrote 170 years ago, slavery threatens God's
``WHOLE human family.'' Americans should appeal to the United
Nations -- indeed the world -- to remember his ``Appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
