<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING WORK IN A `KNOWLEDGE-BASED' WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Labor Day weekend was a good time to think
about all the lousy jobs we've had, especially for those of us
facing possible career changes.
</P>
<P>
   They don't make lousy jobs like they used to.
</P>
<P>
   I looked through the job ads last week and saw the demands of
our ``knowledge-based'' economy. Jobs called for knowledge of
mysterious things like Unix and HTML, as well as qualities like
being a ``self-starter'' and ``team player.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Self-starter'' seems to mean there won't be many of you on the
team, at least to judge by all the things required in the ads.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Webbies I know, my guess is that team members have to
self-start early in the morning 7 days a week, and not complain
about repetitive stress injury caused by cruddy keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   Looking through the want ads, I couldn't find anybody asking for
good old American qualities like ``willingness to follow arbitrary
and stupid orders.''
</P>
<P>
   Familiarity with ``Dilbert'' is assumed.
</P>
<P>
   There were only two ads for laborers, a job for which I have the
knowledge base, even though my muscle base has gone to pot. The ads
didn't ask for self-starters with shovels, but one had a typical
'90s demand, calling for a ``drug-free workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   The tough job must be handing little paper cups to laborers
outside the Port-a-Potty.
</P>
<P>
   My first job, at age 17, was as a laborer in a mill, sweeping
the floor and getting high on cotton dust while swaying to the beat
of power looms. You can't get weave-room jobs anymore, unless your
inner child laborer tells you to move to Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
   My next three summer jobs taught me valuable life skills:
</P>
<P>
   _ As a gold miner, I learned not to stand near guys crimping
blasting caps with their teeth.
</P>
<P>
   _ As a seaman, I overcame a fear of heights by chipping paint
from the mast.
</P>
<P>
   _ As a cab driver, I learned how to terrify Boston drivers even
at rotaries.
</P>
<P>
   They were all great lousy jobs.
</P>
<P>
   There were no gold-mining or mast-climbing jobs listed in the
newspaper classifieds, but there was one ad for cabdrivers. It
didn't call for a knowledge base of San Francisco streets but,
amazingly, it called for a ``neat appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a notable thing about the new economy: The newspaper was
full of ads offering worthy but low-paying jobs for teachers and
teachers' aides, and restaurant workers of all kinds.
</P>
<P>
   Classrooms are overflowing and so are dining rooms. Kids have to
be taught to read specials-of-the-day to diners to keep the Bay
Area economy booming. And there are many hard vocabulary words,
like ``foie gras,'' ``tiramisu'' and ``I wouldn't recommend that.''
</P>
<P>
   People can combine teaching and waiting on tables to make maybe
half the rent they need to live in the Bay Area. Think of the
psychic rewards of dealing with both kids and adults who treat you
like a doormat.
</P>
<P>
   I've had plenty of experience in both education and
food-service, as it's called in places where you don't want to
serve the food, much less eat it.
</P>
<P>
   In a fancy hotel kitchen I was forced to boil rotten chickens to
make chicken salad. I have the skills it takes to be a team player
in food service, and the stomach to patrol school cafeterias.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the teaching jobs called for computer skills and
teaching credentials, however. There wasn't anything about
knowledge of English, mathematics or history.
</P>
<P>
   Schools seem to want people who have sat through awful courses
on educational ``methodology,'' a word that should be red-penciled
for suggesting that an art is a science.
</P>
<P>
   No, I'm not bitter. I looked at ads for teachers' aides, where I
started in the education business 30 years ago. I saw the words
``supportive environment'' and knew what was coming: ``$9 per
hour.''
</P>
<P>
   That means about $300 a week before taxes to learn, on the job,
the methodology of keeping Johnny from crayoning walls.
</P>
<P>
   In my day, you only saw ads for busboys and dishwashers. All the
good jobs as waiters and bartenders were taken.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays the classifieds are crammed with ads for such skill
positions as head cooks, sous chefs, pastry chefs, line cooks,
managers, ``host(esses),'' ``servers'' and even ``barista.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that I see what jobs are available, I'm glad I can't afford
to dine out at all the great restaurants. I wouldn't want to eat in
a place that would hire me to work in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   But I was one heck of a good bartender. All that separates a
columnist from a bartender is a foot of varnished wood.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
