<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3069 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-CREATIONISM-DEBATE-HN     09-07 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREATIONISM-DEBATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATIONISM VS. EVOLUTION: SEPARATE AND NOT EQUAL 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL MECHANIC  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ For years, with little success, Christian
fundamentalists have used pseudoscience to argue that creationism
should be reinstated as part of the public school science
curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   Thwarted by the courts, they have embarked on a new tack: If the
Bible must go, then so must Darwin.
</P>
<P>
   First it was warning stickers like those on Alabama science
texts proclaiming that evolution is an unproven belief and ``should
be considered a theory.'' Then, recently, Steve Abrams, a
creationist member of the Kansas Board of Education, moved to
delete references to macroevolution from that state's science
curriculum, arguing that it, like the Biblical creation, is
``unproven.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, in an embarrassing affront to established science,
the Kansas board voted to no longer test children's knowledge of
evolution in statewide standardized tests. Although teachers may
still address the subject in class, the absence of testing on
evolution will make it a low teaching priority.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, lawsuits to quash this action are in the
works.
</P>
<P>
   The board, whose members have no scientific training, has
succeeded in publicly dismissing long-established theories of
evolution that are accepted by nearly every scientist on the
planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mind-numbing,'' says Ned Johnson, a professor of
integrative biology at the University of California at Berkeley who
specializes in the evolution of birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence for evolution is so overwhelming in every last
detail that it is severely retrogressive to deny its existence. I'm
really flabbergasted that this kind of thing could happen as we
approach the millennium. It's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson acknowledges that there are missing pieces to the puzzle
of how humans evolved from other species, but evolution from one
species to another is clearly demonstrable from the fossil record
and the powerful new dating techniques used to interpret it.
</P>
<P>
   Microevolution, a phenomenon even the Kansas board couldn't
discount, is used literally every day in science labs around the
country as the basis for experiments in molecular genetics.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, scientists can put selective pressures on
populations of fruit flies that will, over several generations,
lead to adaptive changes in the flies that are reflected in the
flies' DNA. Such changes can be observed in a variety of species _
from humans to moths, plants to bacteria _ both in the lab and in
the wild, where we can watch animal and insect populations evolve
to blend into their surroundings, making them less susceptible to
predators.
</P>
<P>
   The classic human case is the prevalence of the mutant gene that
causes sickle-cell anemia in areas where malaria is a major killer.
Sickle cell is common in these areas because carriers of a single
copy of the gene are protected from malaria, making them more
likely to survive to have children. It's the classic example of
Darwinian evolution _ a mutation that helps an individual adapt and
survive to reproduce under a given set of conditions.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be the first time the fundamentalists have
misinterpreted science. Creation proponents have long used a flimsy
argument based on the second law of thermodynamics to support the
idea of a supreme creator. This physical law says that, absent the
input of energy from the outside, all natural systems will proceed
toward a state of increasing disorder, or entropy.
</P>
<P>
   If you drop an egg, for instance, it'll break (increasing
disorder). But you can wait for a million years, and the egg will
never come together again.
</P>
<P>
   The faithful argue that creation of a human from raw materials _
molecules from air, water, and food _ proceeds from disorder to
order, violating the inscrutable second law. Clearly, they say,
this is due to the hand of The Creator.
</P>
<P>
   But any physics or chemistry student could render that argument
nonsense. This law applies to the overall system, not merely the
growing human body. During the apparent procession from chaos to
order, the system is actually becoming more chaotic. Energy is
expended to break down food, to convert it into usable building
blocks and to propel biochemical reactions; heat liberated from
chemical processes is expelled to the exterior; waste products are
released. No natural laws are being violated here.
</P>
<P>
   What the creationists don't seem to grasp is that there really
isn't competition between creation and evolution, nor do they
preclude one another. Creationism is a matter of faith; it cannot
be proven.
</P>
<P>
   Evolution, on the other hand, is provable as a matter of fact,
based on what human beings construe as fact. If an all-powerful
being created the universe, this creator also devised the process
of evolution, or at least created an unassailable body of evidence
that supports it, perhaps even as a test to the faithful.
</P>
<P>
   But if we allow such politicization of science to prevail, and
let other fundamentalist school board members discount sound
science and adopt retrogressive tactics to promote their own
religious beliefs, we might as well eliminate science from the
curriculum entirely.
</P>
<P>
   For if we discount fact in favor of faith, we will be no longer
have any rational basis to distinguish truth from falsehood.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Michael Mechanic, a free-lance writer and editor in the San
Francisco area, has a master's degree in cellular and developmental
biology from Harvard University.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
