<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-IMITATOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE LAWSUIT TARGETS A SPIFFY MACHINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN T. SARACEVIN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Apple Computer Inc., which once sued the
Microsoft Corp. for allegedly stealing the ``look and feel'' of the
seminal Macintosh, is now suing a company that recently introduced
an iMac look-alike.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged culprit is eMachines Inc. of Irvine, Calif., which
recently introduced the eOne that uses Microsoft's Windows
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in San Jose, accuses
eMachines of ``illegally copying the industrial design of Apple's
award-winning iMac computer.'' The lawsuit also seeks to enjoin
eMachines from distributing the eOne and seeks actual and punitive
damages resulting from such illegal conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an unlimited number of designs that eMachines could
have created for their computers, but instead they chose to copy
Apple's designs,'' Steve Jobs, the interim chief executive of
Apple, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Pattie Adams, a spokeswoman for eMachines, said: ``The eOne was
not designed to be a clone of the iMac. It's all-in-one, it's
translucent and it's blue. Other than that, it's an entirely
different system.''
</P>
<P>
   The iMac and the eOne both are all-in-one machines with their
silicon innards and monitors contained in a single, plastic shell.
In other words, no separate tower comes with the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Powered by a 433-MHz Celeron chip (with a 128-kilobyte cache)
and sporting 64 megabytes of RAM, the eOne has a retail price of
$799, after a mail-in rebate. The company has an exclusive sales
deal with Circuit City.
</P>
<P>
   Much like the iMac, the eOne offers plug-and-play accessibility.
It took me less than 10 minutes to pull it from the box, plug in
the keyboard and mouse and to start up.
</P>
<P>
   The eOne comes equipped with plenty of features, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ A front-loading 24x CD player that will play music whether or
not the computer is running
</P>
<P>
   _ Built-in stereo speakers
</P>
<P>
   _ A 56K modem
</P>
<P>
   _ A 15-inch monitor with 1024-by-768 resolution and a dot pitch
of .28
</P>
<P>
   _ A 3.5 floppy drive
</P>
<P>
   _ An 8-megabyte advanced graphics AGI board
</P>
<P>
   _ An Ethernet port for networking purposes
</P>
<P>
   _ Video and audio in/out cables that let you watch TV on the
monitor
</P>
<P>
   _ An ATI board for video editing.
</P>
<P>
   In the other corner, weighing in at 38.1 pounds, the iMac has
won rave reviews for its groundbreaking industrial design and
technical performance since its introduction in August 1998. The
company upgraded the machines in early 1999, leaving it with the
following specs:
</P>
<P>
   _ A 333-MHz PowerPC G3 processor
</P>
<P>
   _ An internal, 6-gig hard drive
</P>
<P>
   _ Two high-speed, USB ports
</P>
<P>
   _ A 15-inch, .28 dot pitch monitor
</P>
<P>
   _ Two built-in speakers
</P>
<P>
   _ An ATI Rage Pro Turbo graphics controller
</P>
<P>
   _ Tons of killer Apple software.
</P>
<P>
   Among the iMac's prime selling points are its cool colors:
strawberry, lime, tangerine, grape or blueberry. It costs $1,199.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to peripherals, the eOne actually offers more
flexibility than the iMac. While the iMac exclusively uses
universal serial bus (USB) technology to connect such things as
printers and scanners, the eOne comes equipped with two USB ports
(one on the front of the machine) as well as standard parallel
ports for extras such as hand-held organizers.
</P>
<P>
   The eOne has a nifty game/MIDI port so gamers can plug in their
joysticks, game pads, steering wheels and other goofy extras.
</P>
<P>
   The peripheral connections are all easily accessible on the
right side of the eOne. In other words, no blind groping behind
your computer when you're trying to plug in the printer.
</P>
<P>
   All-in-all, it's one of the best sub-$1,000 PCs.
</P>
<P>
   The only real negatives with the eOne are common to all-in-one
computers. Basically, with the hard drive and monitor confined in
one box, if one goes kaput you're out of luck. Why? If you open the
case, eMachines' warranty is void. Of course, you can always send
the whole thing in to be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   The other big question is: Will eMachines be able to weather
Apple's legal barrage? The experts are not too worried about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``All-in-one's have been around for a long time,'' said Stephen
Baker of PC Data, a market research firm in Reston, Va. ``To me,
all they've done is create an all-in-one and add color. I'm not
sure how that infringes on Apple.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Spadaccini, independent trademark business lawyer based
in San Francisco, questions whether Apple will be able to convince
a judge that eMachines has infringed on its ``trade dress,'' or
look and feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to prove a likelihood of confusion between the
primary user (the claimant) and the secondary user (the alleged
infringer).
</P>
<P>
   ``People who buy computers research the various models
carefully,'' Spadaccini said. ``To prove likelihood of confusion,
it becomes very difficult when the buyers are very thoughtful.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonplused by Apple's attack, eMachines announced recently that
it plans to raise as much as $200 million through an initial public
offering. EMachines is a joint venture funded by Korea's TriGem
Computer Inc. and Korea Data Systems America Inc. America Online
has also invested in the company and will own 8.7 percent of the
company's common shares before the offering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
