<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3105 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-JEKYLL-HYDE-LADN     09-07 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEKYLL-HYDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POP COMPOSER HAS HIS CRITICS AND A MUSICAL THEATER HIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: ``Today'' in factbox is Tuesday, Sept. 7  
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Frank Wildhorn is used to tough critics, but
typically they don't scream and carry on quite this loudly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll betcha this is the first interview you've ever done from
a hospital room,'' says the musical composer, speaking by phone
from the upstate New York maternity ward where his wife,
singer-actress Linda Eder, gave birth last week to Jake Ryan
Wildhorn, a squawking bundle of inchoate desires with enough lung
power to fill a small Broadway house.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Linda and (my) first (child),'' Wildhorn continues,
unperturbed by his son's atonal background interjections, ``and, as
always, it's a miracle and it reminds you of all the amazing and
wonderful possibilities in the world, you know? Which always brings
me back to the theater ...''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Broadway shows (BEGIN ITAL)are(END ITAL) sort of like
babies: Until they start walking around and making noise, you can't
be sure whether you've created a monster hit, or just a monster.
</P>
<P>
   Wildhorn, whose frighteningly successful ``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde'' opens
a two-week run tonight at the Pantages Theatre in Hollywood, would
know all about that.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably the hottest composer in the American musical theater
right now, Wildhorn was a commercially successful pop tunesmith,
whose songs had been recorded by the likes of Whitney Houston and
Julie Andrews, when he seemed to come out of right field three
years ago with his first big show, ``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde.''
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Robert Louis Stevenson's slim gothic novel about a
brilliant London physician whose backfiring medical experiments
turn him into a bestial alter ego, ``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde'' is now in its
third year on Broadway after opening in New York to some murderous
reviews. The New York Times described it as a ``plastic monster
assembly kit of a musical,'' along with such other choice
adjectives as ``leaden'' and ``solemnly campy.''
</P>
<P>
   But by that point, ``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde'' _ fresh off a pre-Broadway
national tour _ was already a cult phenomenon, with a score that
had sold some 250,000 copies. After originally developing the show
at the Alley Theatre in Houston, Wildhorn had overseen a recording
of ``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde'' that was released months before its Broadway
debut.
</P>
<P>
   With a book and lyrics by Broadway and Hollywood journeyman
Leslie Bricusse (``Victor/Victoria''), ``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde'' has
spawned the kind of musical-theater cult following usually reserved
for ``Les Miz'' and anything by Andrew Lloyd Webber (its most
passionate followers are known as ``Jeckies'').
</P>
<P>
   To Broadway audiences reared on Celine Dion and Garth Brooks
rather than Stephen Sondheim, Wildhorn has been a godsend, a young
(40) composer whose melodies traffic in larger-than-life emotions
and simple, catchy pop hooks. As evidence of the show's appeal, one
of its songs, ``This Is the Moment,'' was used at the Olympics, the
Miss America Pageant and the 1996 Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Wildhorn makes no bones that he wants his songs to be
``accessible'' to large audiences. His own musical influences were
eclectic, he says, and he sees nothing wrong with writing show
tunes that acknowledge the existence of rock 'n' roll and
electronic instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to pin me down to one thing,'' says Wildhorn, a
native New Yorker who studied at the University of Southern
California. ``I always loved theater as much as I loved classical
music, as much as I loved jazz, or as much as I loved Eric Clapton.
I don't have any particular influence. It really is kind of the
rainbow.''
</P>
<P>
   What first attracted him to musical theater, Wildhorn says, was
seeing the movie versions of ``Jesus Christ Superstar'' and ``West
Side Story'' one weekend when he was 15 and home with the flu.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just when I was getting into music and writing and
all that stuff,'' he recalls. ``And in that 4{ hours of those two
movies back-to-back, again the possibilities seemed endless to me.
The musical vocabularies that you heard in those two movies go from
jazz to classical, from rock 'n' roll to Latin. And I just felt
that, `Wow, this is amazing.' If I had to pinpoint something, it
really was seeing (those movies) back-to-back.''
</P>
<P>
   Wildhorn's decision to try writing a Broadway show himself
happily coincided with another blooming romance. When the composer
met his future second wife, in 1988, Linda Eder was wrapping up a
spectacular run on the national talent-show TV program ``Star
Search.'' A mutual friend who was a consultant on the show phoned
Wildhorn in Florida, where he was recording an album.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `There's a beautiful, tall girl who's literally off a
horse farm in Minnesota, and she keeps winning every week,' ''
Wildhorn recalls. ``And he said that she had a lot of pop in her
theater voice and a lot of theater in her pop voice. And he said,
`Frank, knowing your passions' _ because he knew obviously where I
was going _ he said, `I think you two should get together.' So we
did. That was 12 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Eder went on to star in her husband's work as Lucy, the
prostitute who brings out the animal in Jekyll-Hyde, winning strong
notices for her powerful voice and voluptuous stage presence.
</P>
<P>
   Scarcely half a year later, Wildhorn opened a second musical,
``The Scarlet Pimpernel,'' based on Baroness Orczy's tale of a
swashbuckling hero who rescues innocent victims of the Reign of
Terror from the guillotine. Again, the New York critics savaged the
show.
</P>
<P>
   But after ``Scarlet Pimpernel'' was stripped down and remounted
with different producers, several prominent scribes started
whistling a different tune, praising the revamped show's
lighthearted, operetta-like qualities.
</P>
<P>
   (``Scarlet Pimpernel'' will have its L.A. debut May 3 at the
Ahmanson Theatre.)
</P>
<P>
   By the time Wildhorn's third musical, ``The Civil War,'' opened
last April, the pattern was well-established. Most critics trashed
it, and the show closed after two months with a loss estimated at
$8 million. But two CD recordings of the score _ one country-based,
the other gospel and r&AMP;b _ attracted such artists as Hootie &AMP; the
Blowfish, Trisha Yearwood, Dr. John, Betty Buckley and Patti
LaBelle to perform cover versions.
</P>
<P>
   If Wildhorn minds the dual-faced treatment accorded his work,
he's not showing it. For now, it seems, the only voice that really
matters anyway is his son's high-pitched one, still going strong in
the background.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking to a guy who, if you asked me what is my least
favorite quality in a human being, I would say bitterness,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just turned 40, so I still feel very much of a baby in this
game. But there are older-generation writers I've met, so many of
them are so bitter about going through the (show-biz) wars and
stuff, and I write it because I love to, and I write it because of
the joy that it is. And you fight to hold onto those idealistic
things. And if you can win those battles and hold onto it, I think
the quality of your life is a lot better.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FACTBOX &QL; 
What: ``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde.'' &QL; 
Where: Pantages Theatre, 6233 Hollywood Blvd., Hollywood. &QL; 
When: Today through Sept. 19. Performances 8 p.m. Tuesdays through
Fridays, 2 and 8 p.m. Saturdays, 2 and 7:30 p.m. Sundays (no 7:30
p.m. performance Sept. 19), plus a special 2 p.m. performance Sept.
15. &QL; 
Tickets: $32 to $57. All seats $25 for Sept. 15 show only. Call
(213) 365-3500. &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
