<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WHIZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard and Motorola have recommended it to their
customers. At McKinsey &AMP; Co., it turned up last month on a list of
the four most-frequently ordered books. The second edition quickly
sold out its first 10,000 copies last summer; now it is riding high
at about 500th place on the Amazon.com list of bestsellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Essential Guide to Telecommunications'' is not exactly
bedside reading. But it has catapulted a Massachusetts woman into
prominence among authorities on the industrial organization of the
digital revolution.
</P>
<P>
   And it illustrates a comforting fact about the modern world: It
is still possible for a hard-working, plain-spoken reporter to
produce a supremely lucid overview of an industry in an advance
state of turmoil. To a sufficiently disciplined inquiring mind,
apparently there are answers for every question _ and more pointed
questions for every answer.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a reconnaissance that started out little more than a
decade ago as a course on voice mail at Northeastern University.
</P>
<P>
   Annabel Z. Dodd was fledgling consultant then, New England
Telephone-trained, with eight years behind her as
telecommunications manager for Dennison Manufacturing Co. In the
mid-1970s at Simmons College, with three school-age daughters at
home, she had retooled as an MBA. Now she was ready to strike out
on her own.
</P>
<P>
   A one-page newsletter sent regularly to a couple hundred clients
served Dodd as a marketing tool. (You can see for yourself at
www.doddontheline.com.) The NU course _ it produced a certificate,
not credit for a degree _ kept her attentive to changing demand.
</P>
<P>
   When voice mail technology became widely understood, for
example, she moved up to teaching data communications. ``I learned
what people want to know at Northeastern,'' she says. ``I would
say, `OK, list all the words you want to understand.' '' The number
of words was proliferating rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   At a certain point, an editor who had seen her newsletter asked
whether she wanted to write a book. Michael Meehan of Prentice Hall
PTR figured there was a place for a comprehensive nontechnical book
about telecommunications for a business audience. He commissioned
the book and Dodd produced it _ 18 months late, but clear as the
sound of one of those Sprint pins.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year or two, ``The Essential Guide'' had become a
runaway success.
</P>
<P>
   The second edition goes well beyond the first. It still begins
with the basics _ the differences between analog and digital
signals, the meaning of bauds, bits, bytes, and codes, significance
of bandwith, of protocols and architectures. Compression and
multiplexing are explained. LANs, MANs, and WANS (local-, wide- and
metropolitan-area networks) are sorted out. Various sorts of
switching apparatus are described.
</P>
<P>
   Then Dodd traces the evolution of the industry: the Bell System
before and after 1984; the strange twilight of local competition
that unfolded in the dozen years after divestiture; the complicated
consequences of the Telecommunications Act of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   (It helps that Dodd remains in close touch with the staff of US
Representative Edward J. Markey, a Democrat from Massachusetts and
principal architect of the telecommunications act. She never sinks
to sycophancy, though; she still has to talk to all those
companies. Markey, in turn, lauds the Framingham woman for ``having
cogently untangled the wires and switches and technobabble'' of the
digital revolution.)
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the book is its second half: a matter-of-fact tour
of the various advanced technologies _ frame relay, anyone? or
asyncronous transfer mode? _ that are changing present-day
telephony faster than citizens' ability to understand it, along
with surveys of the Internet and various wireless services that are
also driving the nearly mystical ``convergence'' of these traffic
types.
</P>
<P>
   So if you wondered, as I did, what it might have meant for
Bernard Schwartz's Globalstar when Motorola's Iridium project filed
for bankruptcy last month; or what exactly it is that a ``cookie''
or a ``bluetooth'' does; or whatever happened to Gopher and Archie,
it's all here. With jargon-free definitions, clear schematic
drawings, and its steady narrative drive, ``The Essential Guide to
Telecommunications'' is reassuring testament to the human ability
to comprehend and communicate at some fundamental level even the
most bewildering technology.
</P>
<P>
   Now if someone will just do the same for the American health
care system.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
