<HEADLINE>
HOW OFTEN DO CHICKENS LAY EGGS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Do chickens really lay an egg every day?
</P>
<P>
   D.D., Norfolk, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Just about. They average an egg every 25 hours. The average
laying hen produces 250 eggs a year.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know which came first, the chicken or the egg, but we
do know the first step in the egg-making process. The hen is born
with a supply of 3,000 or so ova. When she reaches chicken puberty
at about 20 weeks, one at a time each ovum develops into a fully
grown yolk. It grows in the ovary inside a little sac which feeds
the developing ovum.
</P>
<P>
   When the sac breaks, the yolk drops into the oviduct where the
albumen, the egg white, grows around the yolk. When that's done the
albumen-yolk drops further down, where two shell membranes grow
around it. That's not the hard shell yet. The membranes are the
thin transparent skin just inside the shell.
</P>
<P>
   It takes 5 or 6 hours to get to this point. Then the hen coats
the membranes with a protein matrix, like the grid of reinforcing
steel rods they lay in cement. Over the next 18 hours or so calcium
chloride builds up in layers around that protein matrix and the
shell forms.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, about 25 hours after the process started, the hen lays
the finished product, gives a little cluck, waits 15 to 30 minutes,
and goes back to work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do chickens get fertility drugs to enhance egg laying. If
not, why are we seeing more eggs with double yolks?
</P>
<P>
   Ames, Iowa &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Chickens get a diet of corn and soy, and a few vitamins, but
no fertility-enhancing hormones, according to the American Egg
Board. Their diet is enhanced only with food containing
xanthophyll, a yellowish pigment, to give the yolk a consistent
color. Sometimes they use marigold petals.
</P>
<P>
   Double yolk eggs come from young hens just starting to lay that
release two ova at a time down into the oviduct. As they get older,
they only release one ovum at a time. Only about percent of the
eggs produced are double yolked.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there any difference between brown and white eggs?
</P>
<P>
   G.F., Omaha, Neb. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Just the color, which is so thin on the outside of a brown
egg that you can rub the brown away with sandpaper.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quiz. Which came first, the brown egg, or New England?
Ours is the only region where brown eggs are preferred and common.
Of the 270 million laying hens in America, only about 10 -15
percent are the brown feathered birds that lay brown eggs. With
names like Rhode Island Reds, New Hampshires, even Plymouth Rocks,
these breeds are bigger and eat more than the White Leghorn that
lays most of the eggs in America. So brown eggs can cost more, but
taste tests and nutrition research shows thatinside the shell brown
and white eggs are identical.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3122 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-AMSTERDAM-BOS &LR;      09-07 1749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AMSTERDAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$25,000 FOR A TULIP? MAYBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM _ Would you pay $1,000 for a single tulip bulb?
</P>
<P>
   Not very likely, not if you've got a little Scottish blood in
your veins and common sense in your head. Nor if you're a
hard-boiled newspaperman. How to expense that?
</P>
<P>
   But during the great tulip fever of the 17th century, history
has it that at least one silly Dutchman gave that much for the
promise of a prize bloom represented in a dingy root.
</P>
<P>
   Then the fever broke and prices plummeted. But by then, tulips,
though originally imported from Turkey by Dutch diplomats, had
become the national flower.
</P>
<P>
   So would you pedal two hours to see acres of tulips ablaze in
color?
</P>
<P>
   This is a more interesting question. Perhaps you would if you
are obsessed with strange challenges. If, for example, you've ever
said to yourself: I wonder if there's a way to make my rear end so
sore I will barely be able to sit down on the plane ride home?
</P>
<P>
   Or, more likely, if some of the following conditions had been
obtained:
</P>
<P>
   1. You hadn't known ahead of time that the Dutch had already
harvested their vast fields of blossoms in the weeks before you
arrived; and
</P>
<P>
   2. Your wife were an aspiring water colorist who wanted to paint
tulips and whom you had promised to take on a pedal of the petals;
and
</P>
<P>
   3. You had previously assured the aspiring water colorist that
because she had planned most every previous trip you had been on
that you would take over the duties on this short vacation;
</P>
<P>
   4. She had previously expressed her doubts about your abilities
in that regard;
</P>
<P>
   5. You were already on a train to Leiden before you learned the
interesting and not inconsequential detail of the date of the tulip
harvest from a guidebook;
</P>
<P>
   6. You knew of Keukenhof, the famous tulip park, from the
``Eyewitness Travel Guide to Amsterdam,'' whose brilliant idea of
replacing long gray passages of text with pictures and terse
captions has won it the allegiance of the detail-impaired
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   And so we rented bikes at the Leiden train station and struck
out on the long winding path for the world's premier flower park.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting historical note before we leave Leiden behind:
From 1573-74, the Spanish laid siege to this city, a siege broken
only when William the Silent breached the dikes and came sailing
across the fields in his ships.
</P>
<P>
   Later, William offered the residents of the town a choice in
recompense for their troubles. They could be free from taxation or
they could have, in their town, Holland's first university. Today
the University of Leiden is one of the country's best.
</P>
<P>
   And now, a word about an infamous Dutch punishment. In the 17th
century, Dutch prisoners were put to hard labor, and those who
refused are said to have been subjected to a most Kafka-esque sort
of treatment. Englishman Thomas Bowrey, who came to Amsterdam in
1698, reported that laggardly knaves were ``put into a Cellar in
which the water runs and there is a Pump. If they will Pump Hard,
they will keep the water Low; if not, it rises and drowns them,''
Derek Blyth reports in ``Amsterdam Explored.''
</P>
<P>
   What, you ask, has this to do with a tulip tour? Is it a grand
metaphor for a nation that has painstakingly created itself in a
never-ending battle with the sea, a struggle that demands hard work
and eternal vigilance against an ever-present peril?
</P>
<P>
   Well, no. It's just that the very man who designed the drowning
room also seems to hold the patent on Dutch bicycles. Although the
rest of the mechanized world now enjoys approximately as many
bicycle gears as there are cable TV channels, Dutch bikes have one
speed. Pit that gear against the sort of wind that sweeps across
low, flat countries, and at times you have to pedal like the very
devil just to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the bike paths are wide and pleasant and generally
separate from the road itself, and once you arrive at Keukenhof,
which translates to kitchen garden, from its former function as a
royal herbal garden, it all becomes worthwhile. Once the herbal
garden of the Countess Jacqueline of Hainault, who married often
and died young, since 1949 it has been a garden park run by
Holland's bulb growers.
</P>
<P>
   This is the world's largest flower park, comprising almost 70
acres, with an estimated 6 million flowers planted each year, laid
out like a ramble in a wooded meadow. Mostly it is a tribute to
tulips, with numerous gardens and motifs, and more varieties of the
flower than one would have believed existed. At other points, the
gardens are formed around small pools and fountains. Almost 100 of
Holland's leading growers participate in planting the garden.
</P>
<P>
   Here you will find almost 1,000 types of tulips, from your
(American) garden-variety reds and whites and yellows to exotic
purples and blacks and striped reds and whites. Some stand straight
and erect as soldiers, while the stems of others snake and twist as
though hit by a windstorm. Some are classic tulip shape, rising in
a perfectly even cup, others looking as though they were the jaws
of a fox.
</P>
<P>
   And the park has done a fascinating job of juxtaposing the
colors, and you'll see them all here, side by side in different
combinations, contrasting and complementary colors and hues.
There's the Semper Augustus, the Aladdins, the China Pinks, the
Queen of the Nights, the Viceroys, and all their assorted cousins
and court, plus hyacinth, narcissus, and azalea. It's enough to
persuade you that a tulip by any other name would seem just as
lovely.
</P>
<P>
   And it's almost enough to fortify you for the ride home.
Alternatively, bus tours leave from Central Station in Amsterdam as
well as other locations. The gardens are open from late March until
late May, daily from 8 a.m. to 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tulips, of course, are not the only thing people come to Holland
seeking. The college kids in Amsterdam head for the coffeeshops
with their ubiquitous rastafarian emblems of the sweet smell of
marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Single men prowl the Red Light district, with its live sex shows
and bored prostitutes on display in the crimson glow of darkened
windows.
</P>
<P>
   Busloads of school kids congregate in front of Rembrandt's
``Night Watch'' in the Rijksmuseum.
</P>
<P>
   But most, of course, come here to contemplate the intersection
of the fine arts of revenue-raising and house-building. A city that
grew up along the canals and thrived on trade held its waterways
dear indeed. Taxes were levied according to the linear feet a home
or warehouse occupied on the canal.
</P>
<P>
   And everything flowed from there, in a succession of logical
steps that gave birth to some of Europe's most interesting
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Taxation based on width naturally discouraged wide homes, since
the revenue arm of the city rested more lightly on narrow
buildings. But with one dimension constrained, the others were
distorted. Wealthy merchants in search of suitably grand quarters
went deep and high.
</P>
<P>
   Those choices had just as logical ramifications. Building four-,
five-, and six-story homes on mushy canal land carries obvious
risks of settling. The huge floor-to-ceiling windows most canal
homes have were not just to transmit light, but to lighten the
structure by filling the front with glass, rather than heavier
bricks or sandstone.
</P>
<P>
   The windows had another purpose as well. A tall, narrow home
means steep, cramped stairways, making moving a nightmare. Now the
policy that limited the bottom of each home carried through in
effect to the top. A beam and pulley hook sits atop most every
facade, the better to hoist furniture through the home's wide
windows as an alternative to the narrow stairs.
</P>
<P>
   But that system meant bumping and scraping precious pieces on
the home front. Thus the houses started to cant toward the canals
to accommodate the use of rope and pulley. If the tilt canal-ward
is mostly planned, the lists in the other direction are not. That's
the result of tall homes settling in soft soil: The final
unintended consequence of a tax policy designed to preserve
precious canal frontage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Would that Petrus Josephus Hubertus Cuyper's Central Station
displayed the same tax-averse behavior. The station is so wide and
massive, it all but blocks any view of the IJ. Still, the traveler
who pops out the back can ride a free ferry across to the opposite
shore for a better view of what was once one of the world's leading
ports, a harbor that made the Dutch the world's preeminent maritime
power.
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday, Amsterdam was aswarm with sailors, and it had the
tolerant atmosphere of a port grown accustomed to the vices of men
suddenly ashore after long months at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Of the many vexing afflictions those vices caused, one of the
more mundane was fleas. One of the few remaining wooden houses in
the city, dating from the 1550s, was built as a seamen's hostel,
whose proprietor allowed broke roomers to pawn exotic pet monkeys
when they couldn't produce cash to square their accounts. Guests
there would leave scratching flea bites, and gave the city an
expression some guidebooks claim is current to this day. Someone
who looks particularly down on his luck is said to be ``staying in
the monkey.''
</P>
<P>
   For a better idea of a seafarer's lot, one should visit the
Maritime Museum, where a replica of the Amsterdam, a 17th-century
vessel that sank on its maiden voyage, lives on in replica. In its
small quarters, as many as 200 sailors would live during the long
months at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Sailing was then among the world's most dangerous professions.
Of a crew of 200, estimates are that from a quarter to as many as
two-thirds might never return, instead falling victim to the
clutches of the sea or the ravages of disease. No wonder, then,
Schreierstoren, the brick defense tower that is a remnant of an
early city wall, has lived in history as a widow's outpost known as
the Weepers' Tower. One story is that its name comes because wives
of sailors would come to its battlements to watch their husbands'
ships disappear over the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   The tower itself boasts a stone tablet of a woman looking
seaward and weeping. Or is she? Another interpretation is that the
artist was having a sly joke with the city, for some think the
woman's hand, drawn across her lower face, really hides a smile.
With her husband safely gone _ perhaps never to return _ she can
now take a lover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
