<HEADLINE>
BOARDING CARD EQUALS A MISSED FLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was just beginning to like Southwest Airlines when I got
bumped last week.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't thought through what the airline meant when it said
that besides low air fares it also provided seat assignments.
Southwest doesn't offer seat assignments; you just show up, stand
in line and receive a numbered boarding card. When it comes time to
board, those holding low numbers, say 1 through 25, are allowed to
board first, then others by the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   This worked fine for me the first time, in fact better than
expected. I was flying alone and found a seat right up front.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, though, and we were on a tight schedule. We couldn't
arrive at Green Airport in Rhode Island until 40 minutes before the
flight and we had to be on a cruise ship by 3:30 p.m., about an
hour and half after the plane would arrive at Orlando. We missed
the flight.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest oversold the flight by 14 people. Even though we had
valid tickets, and were in line in adequate time, when those
boarding passes are given out, that's it. We were among the 14
``overbooked'' passengers. Not enough people took Southwest up on
its volunteer offer to fly later for flight incentives. While
Southwest did work to find later flights for others who were
overbooked, for us, it was good bye cruise.
</P>
<P>
   The moral of this story is that if you are on a tight schedule
and cannot arrive early enough at the airport to gain a low number
boarding pass, don't fly Southwest, fly a line with a seat
assignment, we would have made it on that line. Southwest did give
us a choice of a voucher for a future flight or our money back. I
took the money. Our luggage, however, did make it to Orlando and
back all on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest has a 10-minute rule - if you're not there 10 minutes
before the flight they can give away your sea. Other airlines have
similar rules, but they have seat assignments and don't give away
your seat until that time.
</P>
<P>
