Senior deals
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Would you trade four hours of work a day for a free Caribbean
island stay? Maho Bay, a popular camping area, on St. John in the
Virgin Islands offers an off-season intern program of free lodging
in exchange for four hours of work a day. At present there are 32
of these ``workers.: ``Most are seniors with a variety of skills
and experiences we could never afford. Some might easily purchase
the entire resort but would rather pitch in and be a part of the
Maho Bay family than simply be paying guests,'' said Stanley
Selengut, camp president. If you prefer going in-season, a discount
work program is available. Guests committing to one day a week
during a three week stay get a 30 percent discount, which based on
the $105 nightly rate come out to a savings of $660. For
information, call Roland Kravats at Maho Bay Camps, 340-776-6226,
the New York office at 800-392-9004 or on the Web at www.maho.org.
</P>
<P>
   The Close Up Foundation's Life Long Learning educational travel
programs provides seniors with a front row seat to the national
scene with its week-long Washington programs. Seniors learn about
activities in the Capitol, visit a foreign embassy, take study
tours of monuments and museums and more. The programs, offered in
cooperation with the AARP, range in price from $1,029 to $1,099 and
include accommodations, most meals, excursions, and a night at the
theater. For information, write Close Up Foundation Lifelong
Learning Series, 44 Canal Center Plaza, Alexandria, VA 22314, call
800-363-4762 or on the Web at www.closeup.org/lifelong.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Eclectic festival
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Intervale Festival in Burlington, Vt. Is a harvest festival
with a twist. It boasts home-grown music, food, history and
inventions that highlight Vermonters' ingenuity. Visitors can ride
human-powered amusements, take hayride tours, visit the compost
project, enjoy hands-on archeology and more. The festival is free
to all who bike, take the bus or the ferry to the festival grounds,
otherwise its a $3 parking fee. For information, call 802-660-3500,
ext. 243
</P>
