<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3129 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-LISTENER-BOS &LR;      09-07 1372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LISTENER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TENDERNESS IN THE NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID MEHEGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE LISTENER 
A Psychoanalyst Examines His Life 
By Allen Wheelis. Norton. 256 pp. Illustrated. $25.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the appointed hour, the psychotherapist listens and says
little, except toward the end, usually, where some synthesis issues
forth in apercu. He or she withholds the self so as not to confuse
or distract the patient. It is so unlike the help one gets from a
friend, where one's knowledge of the friend's own agonies makes his
good will and wisdom even more valuable.
</P>
<P>
   In this strange, beautiful, awkward puzzle of a book, San
Francisco psychiatrist Allen Wheelis, 82, approximates the story of
his life. Not the life itself in close detail, except the childhood
parts, but the story; that is, a view of a sampling of meaningful
relationships and events, from great to small, with which he forges
his withering, bleak outlook on existence. Sex, death, and love, he
writes, ``is the text of my life, this unruly trio.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in a small town in West Texas, Wheelis and his mother
and sister lived under the iron thumb of his father, a country
doctor dying of tuberculosis. The father was the sort who thinks no
son of his should get any break he himself did not get, and he had
got none _ worked for everything he had. So any hint of weakness or
self-indulgence his son shows must be ruthlessly stamped out. When
Wheelis, age 7, brings home a poor report card, his punishment is
to cut the grass with a razor, and not to be able to play ball with
his friends until the job is done. It takes all summer.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Morris, died at age 43 in 1925, after the kind of
horrific decline no child should have to witness. When breath
stopped, Wheelis's mother let out a blood-curdling scream, and that
scream continued to sound and echo in her son's heart the rest of
his life. After his father's death, Wheelis grew up and went on to
medical school, served as a surgeon in the Pacific theater in World
War II, and eventually became a psychiatrist and writer (he has
written 12 other books, including his best known, ``How People
Change'').
</P>
<P>
   Olive Wheelis, a resourceful and sturdy wife and mother,
gradually slipped into a kind of infantilism: When her son became a
successful physician, she began to idealize him and denigrate his
less-accomplished sister, June. As the decades passed, his mother's
coquettish infatuation with her son became more pronounced on the
occasions when she would visit. She lived 100 years, and in the
last demented hours before her death, in about 1989 (the date isn't
made clear), she suggested to her son that they be married.
</P>
<P>
   The book is episodic, anecdotal, somewhat choppy. Wheelis leaps
from youth to middle age thus: ``Marriage, two children, Mark and
Vicki; Topeka, merciless sun, the streets melt in August; years,
Stockbridge, Massachusetts, the crimson woods, the deep snows, the
Austen Riggs Center, psychoanalytic training; years; divorce. A
second wife, another child, Joan, San Francisco, the far edge. A
new life.'' In the chapter entitled ``Wife,'' he reveals his own
self-preoccupation, his inability to connect with, be available to,
his life partner (Ilse, to whom the book is dedicated). He
acknowledges that he has a powerful kinship with his daughter Joan,
though this fact seems to puzzle him.
</P>
<P>
   The subtitle notwithstanding, Wheelis does not analyze himself
in this book, except to say in passing that ``I have always been
too guilty to be happy. Guilt such as mine threatens life itself.''
The amateur analyst, however, might suspect that the inability of
his parents to control or accept their fates drove into their son,
like a stake in the heart, a sense of futility, of the immovable
irony of human aspiration. His father's inflexible principles and
iron will could not save him from professional failure and early
death. And his mother, Wheelis writes, dedicated to her loved ones,
``enslaved herself to those who would leave her.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheelis, the listener, makes a career of hearing and trying to
mitigate the pain of others, but his own grievance with existence
is a raw sore that cannot heal. Over and over he coughs up the
unbearable. Of romantic relationships he writes, ``I believe that
we . . . are locked within the prison of self, that in this prison
we yearn for release by fusion with another. And I have come to
believe that this fusion, this transcendent love and oneness, is an
illusion, that it can be achieved, if at all, only briefly . . .
that we have to live in the solitary confinement of our tiny cell,
and that, should we briefly escape this cell, we will soon be back
in it.''
</P>
<P>
   He is old, but he has not learned the one thing he seeks to
know: how to live. And as for meaning in life: ``What we deny is
not death but the awareness that, before we die, nothing is going
to happen. That big vague thing, that redemptive fulfillment, is an
illusion, a beckoning bribe to keep us loyal. A symphony has a
climax, a poem builds to a burst of meaning, but we are unfinished
business. No coming together of strands. The game is called because
of darkness.'' He feels not a shred of religious consolation; the
possibility is not even considered.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the book, Wheelis imagines the old woman who
once owned the summer house he and his wife now own on an island in
Puget Sound, coming back after death and looking for familiar
faces, but finding only strangers. Then he imagines himself
returning after death, decades in the future, and likewise finding
strangers, including an old woman, ancient like his mother, in a
wheelchair; he realizes it is his daughter Joan.
</P>
<P>
   On and on: At his mother's graveside service, he sings her
praises, but thinks as he does so that most of it is sentimental
lies. When he uses his intellect to understand life, existence,
love, meaning, he finds nothing but vanity, dust, and futility.
</P>
<P>
   Grim as his outlook is, there is something beautiful and
touching about the heart of Allen Wheelis, at least as far as we
can see it in his own testimony. He assails the capacity of the
mind to master and understand life; in that case, why should the
bleak outlook be more credible than its opposite? His view is
paradoxical in the fashion of such a statement as ``I am lying.''
Some such pessimists are driven to cruelty, rage, or indifference.
Others, such as Mark Twain or Allen Wheelis, never lose their
tenderheartedness, their sense of the pathetic beauty of the human
desire for union and meaning.
</P>
<P>
   A horrifying childhood experience haunts the book: Wheelis once
saw a butcher at an outdoor market grab a pigeon, hold it down,
chop off its feet and toss it into the air. Late in the book he
imagines the bird trying to land, flying upward again desperately,
finally dying of shock and exhaustion. The poor bird appears to be
a figure of created life, perhaps Wheelis's own; it has the power
of flight, to strive, to rise. But it can never light, never find
rest. Elsewhere he holds a dialogue, apparently with himself, in
which one voice dismisses the butcher's act as insignificant
compared with the horrors of the Holocaust, argues that the butcher
probably went home that night and dandled his granddaughter on his
knee. But the other internal voice, the unintellectual one,
replies: ``He may dandle her on his knee till hell freezes over and
still I'll hate him for what he did to that bird. I will never
forget, will never forgive.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that voice, so full of pity and sadness and compassion,
not unlike the voices of Job or Ecclesiastes, that glimmers through
this poignant and unhappy book like an unquenchable ember: ``We
live by attachment,'' Wheelis writes in his final pages, ``not by
reason. That's why love is primary: there is no value without
caring, and caring is loving. . . . That's the point: one's own
life has value only because one cares for others. And one cares
without a reason! Without reflection, without the weighing of
profit or loss. The caring that justifies everything is itself
without justification. It is a leap.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Mehegan is the book editor of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
