<HEADER>
A3133 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-FALL-2TAKES-BOS &LR;      09-07 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALL TV: EXTREME YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someday, a scrupulous TV executive will launch the Fogey
Network, with programs skewed for the over-35 population, also
known as Generations S, U, and V. The lineup will include ``Muffy
the Credit Card Payer,'' a horror series about the working mom of
the high school fashion plate, and ``Dawson's Creek's Freaks,'' in
which a clique of Cape 50-somethings struggle with the alienation
of meaning less than zero to American advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, TV viewers of all ages will need to reckon with
prime time 1999, a Humbert Humbert of a season that is unabashedly
obsessed with youth. When the bell rings on the week of Sept. 20,
the networks will officially set loose some 13 new sitcoms and 21
new dramas, and an unprecedented predominance of them will depend
on characters who, like one teen on Fox's ``Get Real,'' put Paul
Newman in the same category as Mrs. Butterworth and Chef
Boy-ar-dee. The impulse that sparked in 1990 with ``Beverly Hills
90210'' and caught fire last year with ``Dawson's Creek'' is now
bringing us a veritable conflagration of baggy-jeaned dramas that
revel in the strains of being a teen or 20-something in America.
It's the season of Generation Gap.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there's anything wrong with that, creatively speaking.
Despite the copycat overtones, the fall youth series are not all
that bad. While ``young'' means shiny, happy coifs and expressions
like ``That is so fill in the blank,'' it can also mean innovative,
clever, playful. Remember: Lesson No. 1 in marketing to the
post-MTV, post-Internet generation is ``Don't talk down to them.''
That rule is why many of these shows are so keenly observed,
smartly written, and mercifully low in cheap, ``Afterschool
Special''-ized moralism. And, thanks to the success of ``Ally
McBeal,'' they confidently shake up the formal conventions of TV
drama with fantasy sequences, breaks through the fourth wall,
omniscient singers in the manner of Vonda Shepherd, and a hybrid
tone that has become known as dramedy. They may suffer from bouts
of precociousness, but that is far from the worst problem in an
entertainment world dominated by Adam Sandler. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Teen caste system &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fall's most imaginative youth pilots include NBC's
affectionate ``Freaks and Geeks,'' the WB's atmospheric
``Roswell,'' Fox's serpentine ``Manchester Prep,'' and the WB's
savvy ``Popular,'' which introduces this tart schoolyard putdown:
``Cancel my subscription: I'm over your issues.'' These shows are
overrun with children of divorce, children of narcissists, children
of money and no love. The heroes and heroines are traumatized by
the teen caste system, that timeless hierarchy of jocks, freaks,
geeks, and, now, goths. With shades of Columbine, a few of the
pilots portray high school as a front line where Teen Everyboy must
face down the School Bully, or Teen Everygirl must do battle with
the Blond Cheerleader Bitch. And there's no shortage of alienation,
of course, with ``Roswell'' literally turning its teens into aliens
in the way that ``Buffy'' appropriates horror conventions for its
teen torment. The truth is out there, dude.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the biggest misfire of the young guns is
``Wasteland,'' an ABC offering from Kevin Williamson, the
celebrated youth marketeer behind ``Dawson's Creek'' and
``Scream.'' His attempt to transform ``Friends'' into an hourlong
angst-a-thon is a forced product rigged to steal young viewers from
NBC on Thursdays at 9. A chronicle of ``the pre-30 wasteland,'' as
one character puts it, the show has the same self-conscious feel as
the film ``Reality Bites.'' ``Freaks and Geeks'' is a more natural
and charming hour, shunning the glamour of the ``Dawson's'' crowd
as it lays bare the internecine social wars of a suburban high
school in 1980. The casting is spot on _ particularly of the pimply
class outcasts _ and it giddily recaptures that dreaded walk
through the cafeteria in search of a table. Unwisely, NBC is
dumping ``Freaks and Geeks,'' which recalls ``Welcome to the
Dollhouse,'' into the TV wasteland known as Saturdays at 8.
</P>
<P>
   The less distinctive under-30 premieres include NBC's ``Cold
Feet,'' a punchy romantic comedy with three couples at different
stages of intimacy; Fox's uneven ``The Badland,'' about a hunky
19-year-old cop whose girlfriend is in college; and the WB's ``Jack
&AMP; Jill,'' an unfocused hour about a foiled love affair. Two youth
spinoffs with potential _ ``Angel'' with David Boreanaz from
``Buffy,'' and ``Time of Your Life'' with Jennifer Love Hewitt from
``Party of Five'' _ were unavailable for preview.
</P>
<P>
   Even the new family series have the scent of teen spirit about
them. And it's not just because they're as riddled with sexual
situations as the youth shows, or because they, too, depend on
soundtracks lifted from the Billboard Top 10. In 1999, family
product like Fox's fun, frenetically hip ``Get Real,'' the WB's
soggy Gregory Harrison vehicle ``Safe Harbor,'' and ABC's annoying
sitcom ``Odd Man Out'' are presented primarily from the kids' point
of view. The parents are on hand, but mostly as self-involved adult
children, or as comic relief. On Fox's ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' a
family sitcom that could flourish with less willfully anti-PC
humor, Dad does little more than stand naked in the kitchen so Mom
can shave his body hair. The heart of the show is the school daze
of middle child Malcolm, a certified genius. No Jan Brady, he.
</P>
<P>
   Is all this kid consciousness Hollywood's response to Columbine,
an attempt to offer electronic group therapy to America's
disenfranchised youth?
</P>
<P>
   Don't bet on it. In Hollywood, greedy minds think alike: Young
viewers spend millions of their parents' dollars every year, and
they're willing to blithely change brand names. The networks want
to deliver these purchase-happy people to advertisers, and they
also want to attract young viewers as an investment in their own
futures. Plus, shows starring unknowns are cheaper to produce,
because newer actors are more affordable. (They're also more likely
to become heavily hyped teen idols.) During the summer, when both
the NAACP and the annual TV critics' convention rightly blasted the
networks for previewing a profoundly vanilla TV season, they won a
promise for more characters of color as the fall unfolds. But
network honchos would surely be less malleable on the subject of
ageism, as the financial gains of youth programming are far too
immediate, and far too great.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
