<HEADER>
A3136 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     09-07 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
8 YEARS LATER, SELES STILL   TOO MUCH FOR CAPRIATI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Who are these two old ladies in tennis shoes? Haven't
we seen them before somewhere? They seem familiar. So familiar that
some curious bystanders (about 18,000 of them) decide to pass the
time by taking a look.
</P>
<P>
   It is 11 a.m. Monday as the two walk into a public park called
Flushing Meadow for a game. Maybe for old times' sake. Hit a few
and see what happens. After all, it's been eight years since they
last bumped into each other in New York. Eight years, and they've
put on a lot of mileage, gone through a few wringers, and could
compare horror stories.
</P>
<P>
   But here are Monica Seles and Jennifer Capriati, defying
decrepitude, moving without assistance at the advanced ages of 25
and 23, trying to see who will be thrown into the US Open kiddies
den, the quarterfinals, with the brassy basher, Serena Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Monica and Jennifer were the kiddies back in 1991, belting out
an electrifying semifinal of such dynamite shotmaking that it
echoed for years. It was a time when Desert Storm was fresh, the
Dow cow hadn't yet jumped over the moon, and the only famous Monica
was Seles. Capriati came within two points of winning that
screamer, but Seles took it, 6-3, 3-6, 7-6 (7-4), and went on to
the first of her pair of US titles.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve months later, Capriati arrived at Flushing clutching her
newly won Olympic gold medal, but her tailspin had begun. She faded
early against Patricia Hy, and was never a US Open presence again _
losing 1996-97-98 opening rounders _ until this year.
</P>
<P>
   She wept after the high-powered loss to Seles in 1991,
emotionally emptied by a magnificent performance. And she wept
again Monday, prematurely washing out a strange press conference
that followed another Seles victory: this time, 6-4, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were starting something,'' Seles is saying about the
budding, concussive teenage rivalry, the firepower that set them
apart. ``Jennifer had beat me the tournament before in California.
She beat me at the Lipton in '92, and then I beat her at the
French. But then you know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles got stabbed, and Capriati took a stab at drugs and
``mistakes I made by rebelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe an exciting rivalry has been rekindled and maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were both hitting the ball so hard then people were
amazed,'' said Seles. ``We're still hitting hard, but there are
five girls around now stronger than we are.''
</P>
<P>
   As a sequel, their battle gripped the crowd for an hour and a
quarter in Ashe Stadium. But, like many remakes, it didn't measure
up to the original, the thrilling thunder of '91 when you knew the
victor would claim the title in the final against a deteriorating
Martina Navratilova. Moanin' Monica is still grunting, big-time,
but as a woman in the audience said, ``It's a more mature grunt,
even sultry. Not the shriek of a demanding child.''
</P>
<P>
   True. Seles has grown up. She is a genuine, self-reliant 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got over the what-might-have-beens that haunted me for a
while,'' she said. ``I got stabbed when I was No. 1 (1993), winning
all the tournaments. No other player had that happen. For whatever
reason, that's what I got to deal with. I don't like to go back
there. But right now I'm happy where I am, and playing good tennis.
What's past is past.''
</P>
<P>
   Capriati is fragile, still having trouble getting past the past.
When she took the stand, to face us inquisitors, she couldn't quite
get through a present that she said she had thought about for a
long time.
</P>
<P>
   At the outset, she said she would read a prepared statement, one
that had been evolving, a sort of declaration of independence from
the past and her well-publicized troubles. Though a sincere mea
culpa, a cri de coeur, it was naive.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati asked that her past be tucked into an envelope and
buried. Totally impossible for a person in public life. You'd have
to hire an arsonist to do away with all the reference libraries in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   As someone with more comebacks on her resume than Nixon,
Capriati has done a terrific job this time with her latest coach,
the understanding but no-nonsense Harold Solomon, the human
grindstone of his era as a pro. She's seldom benefitted from much
thoughtful guidance. As a parentally pushed cash calf, she is a
monument to mangled childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was careful. I didn't want to wind up like Jennifer,'' the
champ, Lindsay Davenport, used to say on her way up.
</P>
<P>
   That stuff hurt. ``I'm tired of, like, every time I read
something about myself, I always read that little tidbit about my
past,'' said Capriati.
</P>
<P>
   The answer for her, as it should be for every athlete still in
competition: Don't read about yourself. Billie Jean King's father
gave her that good advice when she was a kid: ``They'll write
either too sweet or too sour. Your mother will make a scrapbook you
can read later.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect Monica,'' said Capriati. ``She had no control over
what happened to her. I did. Mine was self-inflicted. I have had a
lot of anxiety about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough already on her part. She's paid enough for really not
much transgression. She ought to read about Darryl Strawberry
sometime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you see the media as your adversary?'' someone asks.
</P>
<P>
   She begins to cry, and can't stop, mumbling, ``I just wish I
didn't have to talk about this stuff all the time . . .''
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't. ``No comment,'' will suffice at the private
moments. Does she need a little help? I think so, someone to
convince her that she's been forgiven by the public long ago.
People want her to succeed, to get on with life and become a happy
old lady in tennis shoes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
