<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FATHER-SUBSERVICE-1100(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTER TRIES TO LEARN WHAT DAD DIDN'T SAY ABOUT WWII SUB DUTY
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by info box, SUB SERVICE-HAMMERHEAD) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAX B. BAKER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ They knew him as ``Alby.''
</P>
<P>
   His real name was Arthur L. Baker. In 1942, he was 18 and
gangling, with dark, thick, wavy hair and an angular jaw. ``Alby''
is what his buddies called him, and my dad stenciled that name onto
his sailor's cap.
</P>
<P>
   He served about three years in the Navy as a torpedoman on the
USS Hammerhead, a 312-foot submarine, with about 70 other enlisted
men. Dad's job was to slide the torpedoes into the tubes and launch
them.
</P>
<P>
   As a kid, I romanticized my dad's years in the Navy and his
adventures beneath the South China Sea. I loved to open a glass
bank to look at the foreign currency and tiny wartime snapshots
he'd stuffed in there.
</P>
<P>
   It was heady stuff. My old man _ a Chevrolet dealer in Odessa,
Mo., a town on the edge of the tall-grass prairie, about 40 miles
east of Kansas City _ sinking Japanese ships, dodging depth charges
and swimming in the sea.
</P>
<P>
   But other than a few funny stories he liked to tell, all I had
from Dad's war years were those fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   He was a quiet, introspective man who didn't talk about the war.
When he died of lung cancer more than 11 years ago _ passing away
three hours after the birth of my son, Ben _ he took his stories
with him.
</P>
<P>
   Ben and my daughter, Johanna, who was born three years later,
ask about Grandpa Baker. To them, he's an abstraction _ a
photograph on a bookshelf, a guy my mom talks about when we visit
her in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   So when a friend told me the U.S. Submarine Veterans of World
War II were holding their annual convention in Fort Worth this
year, I decided to stop by _ to see if I could answer a few
questions about my dad for my kids.
</P>
<P>
   And for myself.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   During a stroll around the Radisson Plaza Hotel last week, a
visitor could pick up snatches of war stories from the more than
1,600 submariners who attended the convention.
</P>
<P>
   When they served nearly 50 years ago, they were young and strong
and in the prime of life. Now they are in their 70s and 80s, their
once-clear skin mottled with age spots, their hair silver or gray.
Two of the veterans were tethered to oxygen tanks. One used a cane.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing bright yellow-and-blue vests festooned with Navy
insignia and embroidered with their boats' names, the men scanned
the faces and the names on the vests, looking for long-lost
shipmates. There were gleams of recognition, slaps on the back,
emotion-heavy conversations as they recalled adventures and lost
friends of a half-century past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard stories about me in the Navy I haven't heard,''
joked Pete Cook, 78, of Eaton Rapid, Mich., who was a motor
machinist on the Sturgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to find someone who knew my dad, I went to a table that
held three-ring notebooks containing sign-in sheets for the boat
crews. No names appeared on the sheet for the Hammerhead.
</P>
<P>
   There were crew members from the Amberjack, Guardfish, Seacat,
Bowfish, Sculpin and Sailfish. But no one who sailed with my dad on
the Hammerhead's first three war patrols, from June 1944 to January
1945, had registered so far.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at the registration desk, Joe Allison of Fort Worth wore
a gimme cap emblazoned with the name of his boat, the Silversides.
Allison, a 75-year-old retired trucking company transportation
manager, wore a button on his vest showing him in his Navy uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was about 25 then,'' Allison laughed, lifting up his
hat. ``I had hair back then, too. It was a long time ago, you know
it. ...''
</P>
<P>
   From Allison and retired Rear Adm. Corwin ``Mendy'' Mendenhall
of Benbrook, Texas _ who was selling his book ``Submarine Diary'' _
I learned something of what my dad's life was like aboard the
Hammerhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The essence of submarine service was silence and secrecy; long
stretches of tedium and waiting, interrupted occasionally by brief
periods of excitement, terror and peril,'' Mendenhall writes in his
book. ``From the standpoint of public visibility and wartime
recognition, the role of the submarine navy was scarcely
glamorous.''
</P>
<P>
   They lived in steel tubes with passageways so narrow that
sailors had to sit down or flatten themselves against a bulkhead to
allow others to pass by. A submarine's groaning metal skin was so
thin that crewmen could hear the clicks of the firing pins in the
depth charges before they exploded.
</P>
<P>
   The subs' torpedoes were inferior and sometimes didn't work.
They didn't have advanced radar; equipment was known to jam or
malfunction. Most of the officers were in their 30s; many enlisted
men were still in their teens.
</P>
<P>
   One war correspondent wrote that submarines _ called boats from
the German word ``unterseeboot'' _ slid into harbor ``salt-caked,
battered and ugly.'' Personal hygiene was an expendable luxury. The
men reeked after months of washing _ and then infrequently _ with
oily-smelling water collected from the condensation on pipes.
</P>
<P>
   Handpicked and psychologically tested, 16,000 sailors served on
288 U.S. submarines during World War II. They made up about 2
percent of the nation's naval force but are credited with about 55
percent of the Japanese ships sunk during the war. Self-described
``night crawlers,'' they did most of their work in the dark,
without fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   They were a tight-knit, clannish bunch. And they died in record
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The fatality rate for the Navy overall was about 2 percent. But
on submarines, 22 percent of the sailors _ or more than one in
every five _ did not come home. Fifty-two submarines were lost; 375
officers and 3,131 enlisted men died.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people thought we were crazy. I don't know if it was
romantic,'' said Malcolm Cross, 76, of Fort Worth, an ensign on the
Tench. ``Once you left Pearl Harbor, you were going west and into
Japanese hunting grounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison served as a yeoman on the last four patrols of the
Silversides. He said there were many moments when he was ``scared
as hell,'' one of them when a ``running hot'' torpedo got stuck in
the launch tube.
</P>
<P>
   ``And about that time we got our first depth charge, and I
thought the torpedo went off,'' Allison recalled. ``I jumped out of
my wits.''
</P>
<P>
   Silversides safely ejected the torpedo later.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Fletcher, 74, who lives near San Antonio, told of a daring
daylight attack by his boat, the Blowfish. The sub followed a small
Japanese tanker into a harbor, waited for it to reach port, and
then fired two torpedoes into it.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   ``We sank a ship, a big crane and the dock,'' Fletcher said with
a laugh. ``And then we headed for deep water, so we could submerge
to avoid attacks by aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   When I asked these men why my father never told me his stories,
Allison recalled his time as a typist during shore duty on Midway
Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I typed the letters of commendation and condolences to the
next of kin for 75 to 80 men,'' Allison said, boasting of his
typing skills. ``It didn't mean as much to me then. I was young,
and it was a job.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he choked up and dabbed his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   He said he never told ``my own wife and my own child'' how he
feels now about typing the letters to the names on that list.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Allison shied away from joining veterans groups,
except the one for submarine vets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people ask me, `Did you see any action?' I tell them, `If
anyone served on one patrol, you saw all the action you wanted to
see.'''
</P>
<P>
   All of that made me want to know even more about my dad.
</P>
<P>
   But when I passed by the sign-in books again on my way out,
still, no one from the Hammerhead had registered.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   It's a habit I inherited from my father.
</P>
<P>
   I get up late at night to read and think. Dad did the same
thing. Many a time, I tried to sneak in late _ after a night of
doing things I shouldn't _ only to find him sitting at the kitchen
table.
</P>
<P>
   Three nights this past week, I read over the Hammerhead's war
patrol reports. A friend obtained them for me years ago from the
Navy's archives. The reports were written by Capt. J.C. ``Jack''
Martin, skipper of the Hammerhead on the first three of its seven
war patrols.
</P>
<P>
   I try to imagine my father in the torpedo room, or standing
watch on the conning tower, as he experienced the events recounted
in the archives.
</P>
<P>
   The first patrol lasted 72 days, including the voyage from Pearl
Harbor to Fremantle, Australia, and then 33 days in action near the
island of Formosa.
</P>
<P>
   On July 29, 1944, at 8:53 a.m., the submerged Hammerhead fired
three torpedoes from its stern tubes at an oiler. The torpedoes
missed, and the sub ``went deep'' to avoid bombs and depth charges
until the ``screws faded out.''
</P>
<P>
   Early the next day, the Hammerhead encountered a 15-ship convoy.
Sunup was only about an hour away, but Martin ordered a surface
attack. A large black rain cloud provided some cover; nevertheless,
Martin wrote, he had ``a very naked feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   After firing six torpedoes, and hearing four explosions, Martin
knew the Hammerhead had hit its target _ a large freighter. The sub
fired four more torpedoes from its stern tubes, probably sinking a
second ship, then submerged.
</P>
<P>
   The Hammerhead scored no more kills before returning to
Fremantle on Aug. 17. But there is a lighthearted entry about the
initiation rite administered to crewmen crossing the equator for
the first time: ``51 polliwogs entered the domain of Neptunus Rex
with appropriate costumes, haircuts and slight medical and
electrical treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hammerhead's second war patrol in the South China Sea lasted
54 days. Martin, my dad and the rest of the crew attacked two
Japanese convoys _ on Oct. 1 and Oct. 20. They sank five cargo
ships and damaged other vessels.
</P>
<P>
   The skipper writes that in the second attack, two ships ``broke
out in flames ... casting a bright glow over that portion of the
horizon. We started cheering, and the two ships started falling
back from the rest of the convoy.''
</P>
<P>
   On the next page, Martin notes: ``Incidentally, none of the
escorts helped the two crippled ships nor made any effort to pick
up what few survivors there might have been. I doubt if there were
any.''
</P>
<P>
   Dad's third war patrol lasted 53 days. The Hammerhead attacked
several convoys and damaged a Japanese oiler but sank no ships. The
seas were rough, and this may have hurt their chances of success.
</P>
<P>
   During a surface passage through the Lombok Strait in Indonesia,
Martin writes, a Japanese patrol boat attacked the submarine. ``It
was interesting watching all those of us left on the bridge trying
to dig foxholes in the decking as the shells landed,'' the skipper
recalls.
</P>
<P>
   The Hammerhead returned to Australia from its third patrol in
January 1945. My Dad had already left the boat at Subic Bay in the
Philippines and finally returned to the United States to marry my
mother. After the war ended in August, my parents lived briefly in
California, but they were back home in Missouri by Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   I telephoned my mom after reading the war patrol reports. She
recalled that my dad didn't join the submarine veterans
organization when it was established in 1955 and that he ``didn't
trade war stories much.'' But years later, after my dad retired, he
helped form a Missouri chapter of the submarine veterans
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes back to this,'' Mom said. ``They laugh about it among
themselves. ... But they don't tell war stories to other people. It
is hard to drag out of them. They don't care about sharing all
that.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Finally, two men who served on the Hammerhead signed the
registration book.
</P>
<P>
   But when I telephoned 80-year-old Art Rawson in his hotel room,
the Hammerhead's former executive officer said sadly that he and
the other man didn't serve with my dad. Nevertheless, he agreed to
meet me in the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good boat. They weren't as lucky as some of the other
subs. We didn't get some of the contacts that some did,'' said
Rawson, a tanned, impish, vivacious man, an Annapolis grad who also
commanded surface ships.
</P>
<P>
   Rawson said that my dad, as part of his job as a torpedoman,
would have checked the fuel level in the torpedoes, made sure the
propellers weren't sticking, and loaded them into the bow and stern
tubes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He also may have made what they called `gillie,' or alcohol,''
Rawson said with a laugh. ``When we wanted to have a party, they'd
take this torpedo alcohol and strain it through bread to take out
the impurities. It was awful stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Rawson said he could only guess why my dad didn't talk more
about his wartime experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at this as a team effort, rather than an individual
effort,'' Rawson said. ``We all stood watch.''
</P>
<P>
   (Max B. Baker is a reporter for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7714, or e-mail:
maxbbaker(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
