<HEADLINE>
IN NEW TOWN, PARKS ARE FOR ONE, NOT ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDINBURGH _ The New Town section here is widely admired for
containing the world's most impressive collection of Georgian
architecture, ornate buildings accentuated by a sprinkling of green
parks, their lawns finely trimmed, their trees offering shade on
those rare sunny days in Scotland's capital.
</P>
<P>
   But like the buildings, the bucolic parks that stretch from
Charlotte Square to St. Andrew Square can only be admired from the
outside. The parks, like the buildings, are privately owned.
</P>
<P>
   As a couple and their two young sons walked around the perimeter
of one of the parks recently, perplexed by the locked black
wrought-iron gates, Pat Cunningham, an Edinburgh resident, took
pity on them and stopped to explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get in. Those gardens belong to the people who live
there,'' she said, pointing to a row of Georgian townhouses
overlooking the park.
</P>
<P>
   In a society like Scotland that prides itself on its
egalitarianism, the dozen private parks in the capital are
something of an anachronism. But that may soon change with the
reinstatement of a Scottish parliament after nearly 300 years of
direct rule from London.
</P>
<P>
   Newly empowered members of the Scottish parliament, who are
determined to get rid of many of the feudal laws that guard
privilege, are demanding that the parks be opened up. The issue
will be one of the first tackled by the parliament when it
reconvenes this month.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the winding, narrow roads of the Old Town, the New Town
was laid out two centuries ago with neat, parallel streets, broken
up by a series of parks and squares, a tribute to the Scottish
Enlightenment. But the concept behind private parks, keeping the
riff-raff from the Old Town out so that the New Town rich could add
luster to the city, is now widely viewed as being less than
enlightened.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Sheridan, the Scottish Socialist who took his oath to
parliament with a raised fist rather than defer to the presence of
Queen Elizabeth II, is among those who say the parks should be
opened up or taken back by eminent domain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to be opened up,'' said Sheridan.
</P>
<P>
   St. Andrew Square Gardens is owned by the 15 financial firms
that line George Street, Scotland's Wall Street. Sheridan and
others think it is outrageous that bankers can stroll the gardens
and ordinary Scots cannot.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy, Robert Louis Stevenson sailed his toy boats in the
pond at Queen Street Gardens. But the public is barred from
admiring either the park or the pond island that was the
inspiration for Stevenson's ``Treasure Island.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the small private parks that dot parts of Manhattan, or
even Beacon Hill's Louisburg Square, Edinburgh's parks are in some
cases huge. Queen Street Gardens, for example, stretches across 28
acres of New Town.
</P>
<P>
   The parks are opened up for special occasions, but Sheridan and
other activists say that is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is somewhat embarrassing for Donald Dewar, Scotland's
new first minister. By law, the Charlotte Square Gardens are open
only to him. Dewar and the rest of the Labor Party majority in
parliament have yet to embrace the ``open the parks'' movement, but
there is growing pressure on them to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham admits she would love to see Queen Street Gardens
opened to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read `Treasure Island' as a girl, and my mother told me
about the island in the pond and all, but do you know, I've never
seen it?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kevin Cullen is chief of the Globe's London Bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
