<HEADLINE>
SOME FACTS ABOUT THE USS HAMMERHEAD
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies FATHER-SUB SERVICE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   USS Hammerhead, SS 364:
</P>
<P>
   Launched: Oct. 24, 1943, Manitowoc, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Built by: Manitowoc Shipbuilding Co.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioned: March 1, 1944, Cmdr. J.C. Martin in command
</P>
<P>
   Length: 312 feet
</P>
<P>
   Complement: 80
</P>
<P>
   Beam: 27 feet
</P>
<P>
   Speed: 20 knots surfaced, 9 knots submerged
</P>
<P>
   Displacement: 1,468 tons
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Facts about USS Hammerhead:
</P>
<P>
   _ The boat, a Balao-class submarine, is named after a type of
shark with a hammerlike head.
</P>
<P>
   _ After a month of sea trials and training on Lake Michigan, the
Hammerhead was placed in a floating dry dock and towed down the
Mississippi River to New Orleans, where it arrived April 8, 1944.
The sub then went to Balboa, Canal Zone, for further crew training,
and then to Pearl Harbor, Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beginning June 6, 1944, the Hammerhead participated in seven
combat patrols during World War II, sinking 11 vessels totaling
35,635 tons. The submarine received seven battle stars and a Navy
Unit Commendation.
</P>
<P>
   _ All seven patrols were designated successful by the War
Department.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Hammerhead was decommissioned in 1946 and placed in fleet
reserve at Mare Island, Calif. It was brought out of reserve in
1952, during the Korean War, for training duty on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   _ Earmarked for loan under the military assistance program, the
Hammerhead was recommissioned in 1954 and transferred to the
Turkish navy.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Hammerhead name returned to the Navy on April 14, 1967,
when SSN 663 was launched. The new vessel, a Sturgeon-class nuclear
submarine, was commissioned June 28, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
