<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3149 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CUOMO-SUIT-BOS &LR;      09-07 1451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUOMO-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON FIRM RIPS CUOMO IN SUIT VS. HUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- When two prominent Boston businessmen reached a deal
with the US Department of Housing and Urban Development in 1996,
their aim was to save the government $40 million a year in energy
costs. Now, the company run by Fred A. Siegel and Alan M. Leventhal
is suing HUD for more than $35 million over what they say was a
breach of contract.
</P>
<P>
   But the case, scheduled to go to trial next month in Boston, is
not just about a contract. It also paints a harsh portrait of HUD
Secretary Andrew Cuomo, accusing him of making verbal threats and
sacrificing efficiency at the agency for personal gain.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo has faced trouble in Boston before. In May, Cuomo released
a report accusing the city of racial discrimination, infuriating
Mayor Thomas M. Menino and prompting accusations of
headline-grabbing. This time, however, Cuomo is accused not only of
jeopardizing the goodwill of local leaders but also the good
standing of HUD, which could face severe costs if the plaintiffs
win their case.
</P>
<P>
   According to legal documents filed in the case last week in
Boston federal claims court, Cuomo abruptly canceled a contract
with Energy Capital Partners after an article in The Wall Street
Journal implied that the company's principals had won the contract
through political connections. Siegel and Leventhal are both major
fund-raisers for the Democratic Party and supporters of the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper ran a correction three days later, and HUD has
admitted it was liable for canceling the contract. But Cuomo, the
legal brief alleges, did not back down from his initial action and
at times resorted to verbal threats to rid himself of the
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Some time after Energy Capital filed its lawsuit in April 1997,
a HUD lawyer, Howard Glaser, called lawyers for the company and
``threatened to file a pleading that would falsely raise the
specter of a criminal investigation,'' the latest document charges.
Glaser also suggested that the plaintiffs ``consider the
ramifications publicly resulting from such an answer in deciding
whether to proceed with litigation,'' the filing says.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1998, Cuomo allegedly called Leventhal. ``Secretary
Cuomo threatened Mr. Leventhal, stating in the strongest possible
terms'' that Energy Capital ``should drop the litigation and
warning of potential adverse ramifications to him and his business
interests from any failure to do so,'' the court document says.
</P>
<P>
   HUD has consistently denied any wrongdoing, and the agency's
lawyer in the case declined to comment last week. HUD's director of
public affairs, Ginny Terzano, said the latest ``finding of fact''
filed with the court is ``undoubtedly frivolous,'' comparing it to
the plaintiffs' earlier failed attempts in the case to force Cuomo
to give a deposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a frivolous attempt to drag the secretary away from
his duties into a litigation matter,'' she said. ``They have tried
this before, and the judge quashed it. This is old hat, and this
new attempt by the lawyers will be treated the same way by the
judge.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Edward Damich is scheduled to begin hearing the case on
Oct. 5 in Boston federal claims court for a week, then the trial
will move to Washington the following week. The trial could move
back to Boston if it carries on longer.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether Cuomo will testify. Last week, the lawyers
for Energy Capital notified HUD by letter that Cuomo would be
subpoenaed to testify. Cuomo is expected to contest that subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the trial is expected to focus on Cuomo's actions
not only in canceling the contract but also by allegedly
threatening the plaintiffs. Throughout the court document, the
company's lawyers contend they hold Cuomo personally responsible
for the dispute, saying, ``The termination of the contract was a
cynical exercise in political maneuvering determined at the very
top of the agency with absolutely no regard being shown'' for the
rights of Energy Capital or the ``best interests of the taxpayers,
the tens of thousands of low-income residents of energy-inefficient
apartments, or the property owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This termination speaks volumes about the public's cynicism of
the operation of the federal government,'' the document says.
</P>
<P>
   The contract at the center of the case involved a program
designed by Energy Capital Partners, started in 1994 by The Beacon
Companies real estate development company and an affiliate of
Harvard Private Capital Group Inc., which manages Harvard
University's $13 billion endowment.
</P>
<P>
   The program, known as the Affordable Housing Energy Loan
Program, or AHELP, would have financed purchasing and installing
energy systems in some of the nation's 4 million publicly
subsidized units. HUD determined that thousands of units subsidized
by HUD or financed through the Federal Housing Authority are
``energy-inefficient and consume more energy'' than if they were
equipped with more modern systems used in commercial buildings, the
court filing says.
</P>
<P>
   According to the document, HUD and the Energy Department
concluded in 1996 that some $5 billion in energy costs for
subsidized housing were the result of inefficient systems. The plan
by Energy Capital would loan money to building owners so they could
modernize their energy systems, then repay the loan from the
savings in energy costs. Improvements ranged from replacing
electric heating with natural gas to installing water-saving
toilets and were expected to cost about $4,000 per apartment.
</P>
<P>
   HUD announced the program on Sept. 11, 1996, and Energy Capital
launched a marketing effort and training program. In the months
that followed, the company said it spent $1.3 million to put AHELP
together.
</P>
<P>
   But on Feb. 6, 1997, Cuomo learned that The Wall Street Journal
was planning to run an article about the Democratic fund-raising by
Leventhal and Siegal, implying they won the HUD contract as a
result of their efforts to assist Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo ordered the contract terminated one day before the article
appeared. Assistant HUD Secretary Nicolas P. Retsinas carried out
the order, writing a letter to Siegel a week later. Retsinas wrote
that the ``FHA entered into that agreement to promote the financing
of energy conservation measures in HUD-supported multifamily
housing'' _ not as the result of any political influence by Siegal
or Leventhal.
</P>
<P>
   According to the court document, Cuomo told Terry McAuliffe, a
fund-raiser and friend of President Clinton, that Energy Capital
``would have made tens of millions of dollars'' from the HUD
contract. The conversation occurred, the document says, while Cuomo
and McAuliffe, who is putting up $1.35 million to help the Clintons
buy a house in New York, were watching the Oscar awards ceremony at
Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Capital claims Cuomo refused to meet with company
officials regarding the contract cancellation, ignoring their
denials of wielding political influence. In fact, Energy Capital
says Cuomo had other motivations for canceling the deal. When the
Journal article appeared, Cuomo knew he was under investigation by
HUD's inspector general for awarding other contracts, the court
filing alleges. ``In order to advance his own political ambitions
and to forestall any heightened inquiry of his own actions,
Secretary Cuomo caused the AHELP contract to be terminated because
of the impending article,'' the document says.
</P>
<P>
   In the Journal's correction, the newspaper said it had ``failed
to note that no one has said that HUD officials knew that the two
men were major Democratic fund-raisers.''
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal and Siegel could not be reached for comment. But the
lawyer for Energy Capital Partners, Michael S. Gardener, said the
suit is in some ways as much for the public interest as for the
businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This program would have reduced energy costs by $40 million a
year for tens of thousands of residents of publicly subsidized and
insured housing,'' Gardener said. ``In fact, the program did not
require a penny of public funds and would have saved the taxpayers
millions.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Gardener said, the company was left with no choice
but to sue, having been ignored by HUD despite repeated attempts
for meetings, both immediately after the newspaper article ran and
after the filing of the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is never desirable to have to sue our government,'' he
said. ``But in this case, we were left with no other choice. Even
more regrettable is the loss to the residents and the taxpayers
caused by HUD's contract termination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
