<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3158 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-BUDGET-BOS &LR;      09-07 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET SHOWDOWN IS NOT ALL SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- While taxpayers do a slow burn, two powerful and
ambitious Democrats appear to fiddle on a State House balcony.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts budget is more than two months late, and the
battle-hardened egos of House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran and Senate
President Thomas F. Birmingham have become public enemy number one
for many.
</P>
<P>
   But issues are embedded along with ambition in the glacial
negotiations that occur above the hundreds of hassled bureaucrats
who scurry across Beacon Hill. And, in Birmingham's and Finneran's
minds, the decisions they make will set the state's course for
years to come.
</P>
<P>
   The issues are education funding, the MBTA, tax relief, the
senior pharmacy program, and how best to use the state's share of
the national tobacco settlement. Six delegates from the House and
Senate have met for hundreds of hours since late June, poring over
hundreds of line items in a $20.8 billion budget.
</P>
<P>
   But, their work largely done, they have not met for more than
two weeks. Instead, two men face each other in a political chess
match to advance, in each case, a philosophy of government and,
possibly, a winning gubernatorial campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The differences concern how to manage government in robust
economic times. In many ways, trying to reconcile those differences
may be more difficult than it would be in a fiscal crisis.
</P>
<P>
   For Finneran, the approach is a cautious one that uses the
swelling revenue stream to tame ``budget busters'' like the MBTA,
reduces the income-tax burden, and avoids the temptation to
dramatically expand social services. For the speaker, the lessons
of recession are still fresh a decade later.
</P>
<P>
   For Birmingham, flush economic times allow the state to offer
more services to those in need. Instead of cutting the tax rate,
Birmingham would use a substantial portion of that money for social
purposes, with dramatically increased drug benefits for seniors
being one example.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, morale is low among the staff who crunch the
numbers and await a Vatican-like smoke signal from Birmingham's
balcony. ``Without a high-tech listening device, it's tough to tell
what's happening,'' said one overworked State House source who can
see the meetings from his window.
</P>
<P>
   The endgame, however, might be near. The conference committee of
three negotiators each from the House and Senate is scheduled to
meet again this week, following optimistic comments from key
lawmakers last week that a breakthrough could be imminent.
</P>
<P>
   But to break the impasse, Birmingham and Finneran will have to
yield on one or more issues that each man has deemed crucial. For
the Senate president, that issue is education reform.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham and his Ways and Means chairman, Senator Mark C.
Montigny of New Bedford, have pledged $245 million to fully fund
the final year of the Education Reform Act of 1993. Such a
commitment is vital, the senators say, to maintain the momentum
that has narrowed the funding disparity among districts and has
bolstered education resources across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran and his Ways and Means chairman, Representative Paul R.
Haley of Weymouth, counter that the Education Reform Act was
intended to elevate every school district to a ``foundation level''
of funding. That has been accomplished, they say, and $70 million
of the Senate's proposal should be diverted instead to
early-childhood education.
</P>
<P>
   Taxes are another stumbling block. Finneran and the House have
approved a tax-rate reduction to 5.75 percent from 5.95 percent. No
such cut passed the Senate. Both chambers voted against an
incremental phase-out of the capital-gains tax, but approved
differing forms of tax relief for low- and moderate-income groups.
</P>
<P>
   On the Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority, Finneran is
holding firm to his position that now is the time to change the
MBTA's financing. Under the House's ``forward-funding'' plan, the
current 18-month gap between MBTA expenses and payment would be
abolished, $325 million in short-term debt would be paid off over
20 years, and a revenue stream of one-fifth of the sales tax would
be dedicated to the agency.
</P>
<P>
   One source close to the negotiations said Senate leaders believe
the plan is too expensive. But Haley counters that annual debt
payments would decrease and that the agency's funding sources would
be shared more equitably by the communities that actually use the
MBTA.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran and Birmingham also differ on pharmacy coverage for
elders. Montigny has told the Senate president he is committed to
doubling the current $750-a-year pharmacy benefit and raising
income-eligibility levels. The plan would double the program's cost
to $60 million. An additional $40 million would be used from the
tobacco settlement for higher-income elders hit with catastrophic
drug costs.
</P>
<P>
   The House would expand pharmacy benefits to $1,000 from $750 per
year, but would not commit new state funds. Haley also has branded
as irresponsible the budget's use of tobacco settlement money,
which may not arrive in fiscal 2000.
</P>
<P>
   If the state is to avoid emergency funding for October, the
impasse will have to be broken by next week. Five days are then
allowed to print the budget, followed by 10 days for Governor Paul
Cellucci to review the document and submit vetoes.
</P>
<P>
   Once movement occurs on the big issues, the rest of the budget
will fall into place, Montigny and Haley have said. In the
meantime, the balcony sessions are expected to continue. And lip
readers will be in greater demand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3159 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-SOCCER-HEADING-AR     09-07 1577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SOCCER-HEADING-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS RAISE CONCERNS OVER SOCCER HEADING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS AND KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's one of the sport's most arresting sights: A soccer player
lunges under a streaking ball and blasts it with her head into the
opponent's net.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also a practice attracting growing concern, especially
for younger players, with recent studies suggesting that the
repeated blows to the head can cause impairment in some mental
functions, such as concentration, memory, and verbal ability.
</P>
<P>
   However, as hundreds of thousands of children take the field for
a new season in America's fastest-growing team sport, especially
after the US women's World Cup title, the level of risk involved
has yet to be resolved to anyone's satisfaction. There's even less
agreement on what, if anything, schools, parents and coaches should
do about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cause for concern to those of us who are involved with
kids' sports safety,'' said Dr. Lyle Micheli, a sports medicine
specialist at Children's Hospital in Boston who has published
research on soccer injuries and has reviewed the scanty literature
to date. ``But the youth soccer organizations in the United States
are rather defensive about the whole subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Micheli said during the making of a video for the US Soccer
Federation he was asked to delete a section that raised the
possible link between the maneuver, called heading, and brain
damage.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some coaches and administrators in youth soccer
downplay the risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that heading the ball would cause head
injuries,'' said Ed Englander, a longtime coach and board member of
Newton (Mass.) Girls Soccer who has three daughters, all soccer
players. ``My 22-year-old daughter is in medical school and is an
accomplished musician, so if heading the ball caused any problems
it would be a surprise to me,'' he said, adding that he's heard
little if any concern from other parents.
</P>
<P>
   But in the same Boston suburb, an official of Newton Youth
Soccer says the organization takes the matter seriously. ``There's
obvious concern,'' said Gary Buchman, a vice president. ``And we
advocate that children under 11 should not be heading the ball. We
talk to coaches about it.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Journal of the American Medical Association is
scheduled to publish new findings on the issue, but they probably
won't settle the debate.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent study on the heading question was presented last
month at a meeting of the American Psychological Association. In
that report, neuropsychologist David Abwender of the State
University of New York at Brockport and Danielle Symons, a doctoral
student at the University of Florida, tested the mental performance
of 26 college soccer players and six current or former soccer
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   The soccer players did significantly less well on five of 11
tests than did a group of swimmers used for comparison, said
Abwender and Symons, contending that their study reinforces
previous findings about the long-term effects of soccer headers.
</P>
<P>
   Some other studies, however, have not found such a link.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Benjamin Kibler, an orthopedic surgeon in Lexington, Ky.,
said he and other physicians are preparing a position statement on
header safety for the US Soccer Federation. He said past studies
showing brain damage risk directly from heading have been flawed
due to their limitations. But the issue, he said, has ``some
merit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What bothers me the most is that we don't know how the force
was applied'' to the players' heads, Kibler said. ``How fast was
the ball going?'' Old leather balls, if saturated with moisture,
would be much heavier missiles than today's synthetic-covered
balls.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents also worry about coeducational play, in which boys'
more powerful kicks could put girls at greater risk.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Boyd of Bethesda, Md., said that last April a ball
hurtling off the foot of a boy struck his 12-year-old daughter,
Hollis, in the side of the head. She did not lose consciousness,
but later that day she could not read or write. Brain scans
detected no brain injury, and after 6 1/2 weeks she recovered.
Still, ``we have lingering concerns about long-term damage,'' said
Boyd.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, soccer has a low injury rate compared to other contact
sports, such as football. Among younger players, 85 percent of
injuries are minor and mainly affect feet and legs. Older players
suffer more serious injuries. Some studies have found that
soccer-playing girls are injured about twice as often as boys.
According to National Collegiate Athletic Association data, both
female and male soccer players have less than a 1 in 1,000 chance
of suffering a concussion during a game or practice.
</P>
<P>
   By one estimate, about 6 million children under the age of 12
play on some sort of soccer team annually.
</P>
<P>
   The soccer controversy comes at a time of growing concern about
head injuries in sports and how coaches and trainers handle them _
in many cases, sending players with concussions back into the game
too soon, say injury specialists.
</P>
<P>
   A concussion is the temporary confusion or loss of consciousness
that can follow a head injury, as a result of the jelly-like brain
being slammed against the inner skull. Heading the ball in soccer
doesn't usually cause a concussion: Collisions between players or a
kick to the head may do so, however.
</P>
<P>
   The studies on heading have been criticized for failing to
separate the effects of heading alone from more serious concussive
injuries the players may have suffered in collisions.
</P>
<P>
   In one study, however, almost half the young soccer players
complained of concussion-like symptoms _ ringing ears, nausea, or
double vision _ after heading the ball. An orthopedic surgeon, Dr.
David Janda, led the study for the Ann Arbor Institute for
Preventive Sports Medicine in which 57 children aged 11 to 14 were
followed for three years with neurological testing.
</P>
<P>
   By the second year, the researchers saw a statistical link
between the number of headers a player made and lower scores on
verbal tests. In light of this suggestive data, Janda, whose two
daughters play soccer, recommended that children use helmets and
lighter soccer balls while learning heading.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't abolish heading. But if you can make a ball that is
as light as a beach ball for practice drills, when the coach
bounces the ball off a head 10 times it won't have such an
impact,'' Janda said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hunt, director of the Warriors Soccer Club in Stoughton
and coach of under-11 boys, believes some of the damage may come
from players hitting the ball with the top of their head, and not
with the forehead, the strongest part of the skull. Children may
complain of headaches if they hit a ball with the top of their
heads, Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
   When they first learn to play soccer many girls close their eyes
so they can't see where they head the ball, said Warriors under-13
girl's coach Mario Cardoso. ``They hit the ball wrong, get hurt and
scared.''
</P>
<P>
   But just because a ball hits the forehead doesn't mean it won't
affect the rest of the head, said Lyn Turkstra, a head injury
researcher at Case Western Reserve University in Cleveland.
Turkstra said whether repetitive non-concussive heading is harmful
in the long term is still inconclusive. ``But we can't just relax.
We certainly don't have enough data that says it is or isn't
benign,'' Turkstra said.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Friedman of Stoughton, Mass. recalls that when her
children were younger, the coaches didn't even talk to the boys
about hitting the ball with the head. Her daughter, Bari Seronick,
13, and her son David, 9, play for the Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the difference is whether you are 8, 9 or
10. Your brain is still in there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lauren Richman of Newton said from her experience, the
coaches do encourage heading at a young age. Although her husband,
Joel Trachtman, is concerned about the reports, Richman said, ``I'm
always so proud of Hannah when she hits a header.'' She says she
wonders whether occasional heading would be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Although the reports make her anxious, Debby Stein-Sharpe said
she will not tell her children not to do headers. Her oldest son,
Nate, 11, plays for the Canton (Mass.) Green Machine, and hopes to
play collegiate or professional soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty good at headers. But I hate to see him do it. I
cringe,'' Stein-Sharpe said. ``If they outlawed headers, I truly
would welcome that. But until then, I can't ask him to forgo
them.'' Nate Sharpe said once every two weeks or so he and his
teammates practice heading the ball past the goalie.
</P>
<P>
   Micheli says that until further studies clarify the risks,
``there should be a yellow warning light signal going out.''
</P>
<P>
   His current recommendation is that heading not be taught until
age 12, when the young players' coordination and neck strength
makes it possible for them to learn the skill properly. ``I think
I'm becoming more cautious about this,'' he said. Noting that
coaches will say they haven't seen players injured while heading,
Micheli said, ``The coach isn't going to see it'' because the
damage is subtle, ``but I'm concerned about what the kids' IQ is
going to be 20 years from now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
