<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-APPETITE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEEDS OF DARING BY A CHAMPION EATER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER BONFANTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Hungry? How about a plump, juicy, three-pound
hamburger awash in cheese and garnished with five pounds of
toppling French fries.
</P>
<P>
   You're not that hungry? Well, Shaun Reilly is.
</P>
<P>
   At Eagle's Deli the platter is called the Reilly Burger, named
after the man, the legend, the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   About once a month, Reilly goes into Eagle's Deli and eats,
plenty. What began as a friendly competition with his cronies has
become local lore. In fact, eight pictures of Reilly's prodigious
eating accomplishments adorn the walls of the Cleveland Circle
deli. Reilly is the local guru of gluttony, holding the record for
the most food eaten there in one sitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally I thought it was pretty cool to have my pictures on
the wall,'' said Reilly. But the burgers got bigger, and the hunger
for more fame grew with them. ``I thought, `Wow, if I do it,
they'll name a hamburger after me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And so they did. What makes his feats intriguing is that Reilly
looks more like an everyman than a power fork lifter. Reilly, 21,
from Dracut, is 5 feet 9 inches tall and weighs 210 pounds. He's a
senior at Boston University, majoring in chemistry and mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of eating, I've never met his equal,'' said Andrew
Lemoff, who has repeatedly watched Reilly in action. ``He's the
only guy I've ever met who can spend $18 at Burger King to feed
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   At this deli near Boston College, Reilly racks up a victory for
Boston University. ``Not even the BC football players will try to
eat'' the Reilly burger, said Mark Seland, the deli manager, who
added, ``Reilly has a following here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You could probably feed a small village with this meal,'' said
Lemoff.
</P>
<P>
   To be more specific, the Reilly burger is six eight-ounce
hamburger patties, each with two slices of American cheese. One
pathetic bun tries to enclose all the beef. A separate tray of
fries flanks the 9-inch tall burger. To wash it all down, Reilly
drinks three 32-ounce orange sodas. He has calculated that his meal
has at least 20,000 calories, almost 10 times a normal daily
intake.
</P>
<P>
   Such mass consumption cannot be undertaken impetuously. Reilly
has techniques to get the food down. He says he stretches his
stomach by eating a lot the day before the big chow-down, and eats
little the day of the feat.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent sitting with a reporter in tow, Reilly took almost
two hours to knock back the namesake burger platter. He started
with the fries. Later, he strategically unfolded the burger and ate
the two halves like open-faced sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   When he started to get full and lost gusto, the going toughened.
``My jaw is starting to get tired,'' he said. But Reilly wasn't
done. He bounced back and forth between the fries and the burger,
paying equal attention to each. When he finished the burger, the
few remaining fries seemed like a whole plate, he said. Soon, they
too were downed.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly has been a big eater since his childhood. He recalls
going to Thanksgiving dinner at an aunt's house, who made sure to
cook another big turkey to supplement the 20-pounder she already
had. In his freshman year of high school, Reilly says he ate seven
large cheese pizzas in a local restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   At Eagle's Deli, burgers aren't his only target. He's eaten
eight chicken breasts, each with cheese and a slice of bacon, with
a couple of pounds of fries on the side _ for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in some ways, Reilly is a picky eater. He avoids
tomatoes, onions, and lettuce on his burgers, and he ignores the
pickles on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it must be said that eating this much food is not a great
idea. ``It's terrible for the digestive system,'' said Julie Seed,
nutritionist at the Frances Stern Nutrition Center at Tufts Medical
Center. ``To make room for the food, there's all kinds of
stretching . . . It's very unhealthy.'' Even Reilly said, ``I do
understand that eating a three-pound hamburger is not good for my
waistline.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as the Metallica song ``Sad but True'' played from the
speakers overhead, he popped the last French fry into his mouth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
