<HEADLINE>
WHAT A STATE THESE STATES ARE IN! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One problem with the Internet is that an author's name is often
dropped from an item that is widely circulated in cyberspace. For
instance, despite an exhaustive investigation (20 minutes at the
library), we don't know who concocted some funny state mottoes that
have been making the e-mail rounds. However, humor writer Dave
Barry is our prime suspect. Here are a few of the less-offensive
mottoes:
</P>
<P>
   --Arizona: ``But It's A Dry Heat.''
</P>
<P>
   --Florida: ``Ask Us About Our Grandkids.''
</P>
<P>
   --Idaho: ``More Than Just Potatoes. . . . Well OK, We're Not,
but the Potatoes Sure Are Real Good.''
</P>
<P>
   --Indiana: ``Two Billion Years, Tidal-Wave Free.''
</P>
<P>
   --Kansas: ``First Of The Rectangle States.''
</P>
<P>
   --Massachusetts: ``Our Taxes Are Lower Than Sweden's (for Most
Tax Brackets).''
</P>
<P>
   --New Mexico: ``Lizards Make Excellent Pets.''
</P>
<P>
   --Rhode Island: ``We're Not Really An Island.''
</P>
<P>
   --Vermont: ``Yep.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Let's continue with stately questions. Which is the
most frequent final letter of a state's name? And which letter
comes in second? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: A lighthouse in the waters off Burlington, Vt., is known
as the Phoney Baloney Lighthouse because it is unauthorized and
unofficial.
</P>
<P>
   Quotable: ``Trips start when the last familiar face recedes from
view, and end the instant one reappears'' _ author Lance Free. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Advice to go: You're a man on the road who's about to shave and
have just discovered you didn't pack your shaving cream. No time to
get another can? Slap some shampoo on your face: The key
ingredients are the same as in shaving cream. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: In Zion, Ill., it is illegal to give lighted
cigars to dogs, cats, or other pets. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good idea: Many Walt Disney World employees (or, in Disneyspeak,
``cast members'') and Disney Cruise Line members now wear badges
that list, in addition to their names, their home cities, states,
or countries. That often leads to conversations with visitors. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Net travelers: The National Travel Survey reports that 6.7 million
American adults used the Internet or an on-line service to book
travel reservations in 1998, up from 5.4 million in 1997. &QL; 
 &QL; 
That's a lotta people: India's population has broken through the 1
billion barrier. That means it has four times as many people than
the United States in a land that is only 40 percent as big. The
only other country to top 1 billion is China, with 1.27 billion
people. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Twenty-one states end in ``a.'' Coming in second
is the letter ``s,'' appearing at the end of Arkansas, Illinois,
Kansas, Massachusetts, Texas, and, if you use the official name,
State of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations. We thank Warren
Himmelberger of Littleton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
