<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SPA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND SHE THOUGHT SHE DIDN'T LIKE SPAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE HATFIELD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OJAI, Calif. _ With the husband off in Argentina on a trip with
The Boys, I figured it was time for a Girl trip. And, since I'm a
spa afficionado but don't like to go alone, I called my sister in
Indiana to see if she'd like to meet me for a whirlwind three days
of healthy California living.
</P>
<P>
   To explain how unusual this suggestion must have sounded to my
sister, I must present a little of her background. She is my elder
sister, wife of a Lutheran minister in a town with more churches
than filling stations, and mother of five. Not only has she never
been to a spa, but she has only heard vague, disturbing things
about what they do in those self-indulgent and possibly decadent
places.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, her first questions: ``Is it true that the women walk
around nude all the time? Will we have to do that?''
</P>
<P>
   I assured her that the only time I was nude together with other
women was when we all sunbathed at a Florida spa, surrounded by
four high walls and listening gleefully to the male spagoers
shouting and yelling as they played their daily nude water
volleyball game in their own private pool many walls away.
</P>
<P>
   Her next question: ``Will they weigh us?''
</P>
<P>
   Another explanation, for background: Sally has, over her 30
years of marriage _ how shall I put it _ made thousands of heavy
Midwestern stick-to-the-bones casseroles for thousands of church
suppers, and consumed a bit of those dishes herself. Given her
other duties as a mother and pastor's wife to a congregation of
4,000 members, she has sometimes neglected to get to the gym, the
tennis court, the treadmill, and the Nautilus. She is, shall we
say, aerobically challenged.
</P>
<P>
   I told her I didn't think they would have to weigh her, but I
didn't tell her that they would probably take her coffee away, and
to my sister, this could cause mutiny.
</P>
<P>
   But we hadn't seen each other in a long time, and she was game,
and her kids threatened that if she didn't take me up on my offer,
one of them would go in her place. So she made the elaborate
arrangements that a pastor's wife must make to leave town in the
middle of the week. First, she had to trade the Bible study she was
supposed to lead with another woman. ``I was supposed to start
Exodus Monday, but I got the research person for Exodus to change
with me for Genesis, and she'll do Exodus, and I'll do Genesis
later,'' she said. Fair enough. Then, she had to cancel out of a
luncheon for 33 women on Tuesday, for which she was supposed to
make the hot casserole. ``I'll take cheese curls and pickles over
to the house of the woman giving the lunch and tell her to just
make cold sandwiches this time,'' she said, with devil-may-care
abandon.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all was that she had to skip choir practice, and when
she told the choir members where she was going, they all laughed.
``No one in Fort Wayne,'' she explained, ``does spas.''
</P>
<P>
   She did, though, and we met at the airport in California and
drove together to the tiny, artsy town of Ojai located over a
35-mile stretch of brown mountains from Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   The Oaks at Ojai, we discovered, was the perfect spa for a
novice such as my sister. It is small and compact, re-created from
a funky old hotel in the center of town. We were not, thankfully,
greeted with a battery of scales and measurements and
official-looking athletes in neon Spandex showing off their lean
muscle mass. We were greeted with a basket of grapes that made us
realize why the fruit in our Eastern grocery stores that we call
grapes has nothing to do with California grapes. With these sweet
morsels, who needs candy?
</P>
<P>
   Everything but the swimming pool is snuggled compactly into the
ground floor of the hotel, including a huge exercise room with a
window overlooking the Topa Topa mountains, a whirlpool, a room of
weight machines, a dining room, a meeting room, and a front lobby
with a working fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   The spa is owned and run by Don and Sheila Cluff, who also own a
newer small spa in Palm Springs. Sheila Cluff, a vivacious little
dynamo, is the heart and spirit of the spa. She was a professional
figure skater with the late Sonja Henie while still a teenager, and
now, somewhere in her 60s, she looks like Henie did then, with the
same fit body she had when she skated. In her morning pep talk, she
tells guests that she weighed 95 pounds as a skater, but when she
started college ``I was depressed and I blew up to a massive 130
pounds!'' As she worked herself back to fighting weight, for her,
she picked up health tips and a philosophy that is inspiring to
those guests who need it. ``Make it an 80-20 proposition,'' she
says of the good and bad habits of eating.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're out for a big dinner, go ahead and have a cocktail,
but remember that that's your 20 percent bad food. I love
cheesecake, and when I eat a piece of it, I want it to be the best,
but I don't eat it every day,'' she tells people. ``My cheesecake
is part of the bad 20 percent of that day's diet.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things the spa offered Sally was a cup of
coffee. While some spas are adamant about eliminating caffeine from
the diet, this one, luckily, was not so rigid.
</P>
<P>
   We arrived in late evening, just in time for the relaxing and
restful yoga class that prepares one for sleep. After a long drive,
it was heaven. And easy.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of early morning walks are scheduled daily, and we
signed up for our respective hikes: Mine was a 7 a.m. ``brisk''
3-mile walk with Sheila Cluff leading and a promise of ``great
aerobic benefits.'' Sally's was the 7:30 a.m. ``leisurely 1
1/2-mile stroll through downtown Ojai,'' so that she could check
out the residential rose gardens and look into the shop windows and
galleries to see what she could buy to take home.
</P>
<P>
   Cluff keeps up a very brisk pace, just fast enough that you can
still talk while you walk, and she talks a blue streak but is so
entertaining that you forget when listening that you're walking for
a purpose. During our three miles we heard about the Cluff family
of four children and two grandchildren, the years on the pro
skating circuit and later as a skating Radio City Rockette, and the
frenetic pace of owning and running two spas, traveling back and
forth each week to both, in addition to attending fitness symposia,
lecturing all over the country, and taking a version of her spa on
a variety of Caribbean, Central American, and European cruises each
year.
</P>
<P>
   On her walk, Sally found out that the beautiful mission tower in
the center of Ojai is now the post office.
</P>
<P>
   Cluff teaches some of the classes; we took a most beneficial
stretch class from her, having missed by two minutes the power yoga
class taught by one of those tyrannical yogi dictators who refuses
to let latecomers in one minute after she has begun her session.
Perhaps it was better for Sally's sake. I didn't like the thought
of her getting twisted up in all the hanging ropes that the power
yoga class was rumored to use anyway. We took a low-back
conditioning class which, my sister said, helped her problem in
that area. We also found some fun fitness toys at these classes
that we've not seen in the East yet, namely the gigantic Flexaball,
around which you can strength-train your abdomen, rear end, and
thighs, if you can keep your balance on it, and the colorful rubber
snakes used in the pool for aquatoning. Sally had a little trouble
staying on top of hers, claiming that her body fat made her bounce
to the top of the water before she could do the requisite
movements. She enjoyed herself nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   No one demanded that we attend every class, so we eschewed the
more vigorous advanced step classes. In a similarly laissez-faire
attitude, guests at this spa, unlike at some of the tonier and
pricier spas, were dressed haphazardly in whatever sweats they wore
at home. They also came in all sizes and ages, and Sally was
thrilled to see that plenty of the guests were not only older, but
bigger, and flabbier, than she.
</P>
<P>
   On our final morning, with all the easy hikes she could have
chosen, my newly toned sister picked the 6-mile, 6 a.m. hike
straight up into the mountains overlooking this fertile valley, and
so I, with some trepidation, joined her. The only difference I
noticed between her and Sheila Cluff by this time was that Sally
took her camera along, to stop and shoot the sights. Cluff went on
at a brisker pace, but when I finally suggested turning back toward
the spa and breakfast, it was my spa-seasoned, newly invigorated
sister who balked. ``But we haven't gotten to the top of the
mountain yet!'' she complained.
</P>
<P>
   Then I remembered that she, for all her lack of visits to the
gym, is a born walker, once skied better and faster than I, and
still, out of boredom, runs over to her daughter's house to paint
and paper the walls between choir practice and Bible study. Her
stamina, I found, is intact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3168 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-CANYON-BOS &LR;      09-07 1446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CANYON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL ABOARD FOR A GRAND RAILWAY ADVENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE GRAND CANYON RAILWAY IN NORTHERN ARIZONA _ I have
seen the future, and it is nearly a century old.
</P>
<P>
   Perched in an observation car while watching the juniper trees
slip past, our three-person family is riding the rails 65 miles
northward from the city of Williams to the Grand Canyon. This is
the way most folks reached the canyon during the first quarter of
the 20th century, but it's also an experience that was slowly
killed off by the automobile following World War II. Now it's back
and thriving, to the point that it will likely attract about
175,000 camera-pointing passengers like us this year.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that's only about 3 percent of the people who annually visit
Grand Canyon National Park. But faced with roads and parking areas
that are often choked, The National Park Service beginning in 2002
plans to require canyon day-trippers to leave their cars outside
the front gates and board a light-rail system. That means
alternative forms of transportation to the park _ including the
Grand Canyon Railway _ will likely flourish. Ironically, the very
car that killed off the train is helping to resurrect it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people ask me how long it takes the train to reach
the bottom of the canyon,'' announces Chris Davis, one of the two
passenger-service attendants in our car. ``I tell them, `About 30
seconds from the time it jumps the track.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's a joke, see? We're traveling only as far as the South Rim.
Still, this isn't an inexpensive journey. The 630 people on the
12-car train this morning have paid anywhere from $24.95 to $119.95
per ticket round-trip, depending on their age and which of five
classes of travel they've chosen. What's more, the scenery we're
looking at is less than dramatic. It begins with the Ponderosa pine
of the Kaibab National Forest and ends with the gentle curves of
Coconino Canyon, but the flat miles of rangeland in between are
heavy on grass and sagebrush. The only view we'll get of the Grand
Canyon before we reach the rim will last 10, maybe 15, seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sell customer service,'' our engineer, Sam Lanter,
explained to us in Williams just before he climbed into the cab of
Engine Number 4960, a steam-powered locomotive that was built in
1923 but has been restored at a cost of $1.5 million. Indeed, the
GCR attracts riders by creating a theme-park atmosphere that
includes a hotel, restaurant, museum, two gift shops, a pre-trip
Wild West show, and musicians who stroll the aisles of the train.
There are more than two dozen crew and cast members traveling with
us today, all of whom can't seem to smile enough. The 50-year-old
Lanter is wearing an Oshkosh engineer's cap, the kind you see on
kids.
</P>
<P>
   The three of us have chosen to travel northward in the
comfortable and carpeted DeLuxe Observation Class of the
45-year-old Coconino Car. That means we paid top dollar to share
the best view with 17 other passengers, one of whom has had
balloons attached to the back of his seat by the crew because he's
celebrating his 78th birthday. Our 12-year-old son, Ethan,
occasionally takes a break from reading P. G. Wodehouse long enough
to scan the landscape as we roll along at our top speed of 40 miles
per hour. ``No elk yet,'' he murmurs as we pass dirt roads,
gurgling creeks, empty corrals, cattle tanks, former station sites,
small arroyos, and giant ant hills.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, I read the up-down-up history of Grand Canyon
railroading: how trains began hauling passengers from Williams to
the canyon in 1901 at $3.95 per head, how only three passengers
were carried on what appeared to be the final run to the canyon in
1968, and how the GCR was born in 1989 after owners Max and Thelma
Biegert acquired much of it when the fellow who was trying to
restart the enterprise defaulted on a loan they'd made to him.
</P>
<P>
   But enough reading. I decide to walk the train, from the plush
Victorian chairs of the 24-seat Parlor Car (complete with
complimentary continental breakfast) to the five coaches that each
seat 80 people in rows of four (complete with complimentary
Coca-Cola). We're a mixed band of travelers, from kids scooting
along the aisles to senior citizens warily eyeing the kids scooting
along the aisles. But we're also a heavily over-40 crowd. The GCR
reports that only a little over one-third of its passengers travel
with children under 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these people are reliving their past,'' conductor Ken
Stephenson tells me. ``And they like the idea of a train ride, of
going slowly and socializing.'' There have been birthday parties,
marriage proposals, and, according to Stephenson, two deaths from
heart attacks aboard the train.
</P>
<P>
   This, however, is an uneventful trip on a gorgeous summer day.
When we arrive at the log-and-wood-frame Grand Canyon Depot, built
in 1909-10, a five-man band toots its welcome as we mosey off the
train. More than 90 percent of the folks who take the CGR begin
their return trip to Williams 3 1/2 hours after arriving here, so
most of the other passengers make their way onto buses for a
narrated tour. Not us. Ethan, my wife, Margery, and I are spending
the night in a hotel room here on the South Rim, which is a short
walk from the depot.
</P>
<P>
   We'll take a bus tour, yes. But we'll also hike five miles along
the rim and have a leisurely and excellent dinner in the dining
room of El Tovar, the undisputed queen of the six-lodge fleet here.
We'll watch the sun set and rise over the canyon, visit two small
exhibitions on canyon history, and spend the rest of our time
simply staring at a sight that is arguably unmatched anywhere on
earth. And how good is the weather? We can see the buildings atop
the North Rim, 10 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   But when the whistle blows the next afternoon, we're ready to
board the Club Car for the return trip to Williams and its rebuilt
91-year-old station. The Club Car is a livelier place than the
Coconino Car _ it features a mahogany bar, after all _ but it lacks
the view. That means more time for talk. We're setting next to Jeff
Garrett of Berkeley, Calif., an Amtrak engineer who's riding with
his two teenage sons and their friend. When Kevin Johns, one of the
singers aboard the train, makes an appearance, Garrett requests
both ``Casey Jones'' and ``The Wreck of Old 97.'' Johns doesn't
miss a beat or word.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett is impressed by the GCR. ``A lot of people are fed up
with their cars,'' he says as we roll southward. ``I know I am. I
just didn't want to deal with my car at the canyon. If I could park
it and take public transportation, great. Plus,'' he adds, grinning
broadly, ``I love trains.''
</P>
<P>
   At the bar, a wiry fellow in exaggerated western garb is holding
court. He answers only to the name of Barge, and is the
``marshall'' aboard the train (a former electrician, actually).
When I ask him if he's expecting trouble this afternoon, he replies
that the Cataract Creek Gang is in the neighborhood and might try
to hold up the train _ say, at 4:55 p.m. And lo, at that exact
moment two masked men on horseback appear beside the track and
bring the train to a halt. Ambling through our car, they announce
that drinks are on the house. Barge is in hot pursuit. By the time
we reach Williams, of course, the good guy and the bad guys are
arm-in-arm at the bar.
</P>
<P>
   For Wiliams, a weary hamlet of 2,500 souls that once made much
of its living off long-gone Route 66 and is now bypassed by
Interstate 40, the CGR is a necessity of life. The city brightens a
little bit every time the railroad's empire grows: the 89-room
hotel that opened last year (and will more than double in size in
2000), the 300-seat restaurant that began operations this year, and
the 100-space RV park that will open next year. Meanwhile, a $15
million Arizona State Railroad Museum is being planned for the
city.
</P>
<P>
   In June of this year, the GCR carried 20,000 passengers during
its best month ever. In August, Amtrak began servicing Williams,
bringing with it a new source of passengers for canyon trips. And
Max Biegert, the onetime crop duster who inadvertently ended up
with a railroad when a loan when bad, recently fired up a new
airline, Phoenix-based FarWest, to fetch riders to his train via
package deals.
</P>
<P>
   When he first acquired the railroad, Biegert wasn't sure what to
do with it. ``But I hired some ex-Disney folks to look at it,'' he
recalls. ``They told me, `There's only one Grand Canyon. And
there's only one railroad that's ever gonna run to it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the future here looks about 100 years old.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
