<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS CAN'T GET ENOUGH OF BARRY WHITE _ AFTER 30 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barry White didn't invent love. He simply perfected it in song.
</P>
<P>
   First and foremost, there's The Voice, bottomless and rumbling
like something Cecil B. DeMille would have created for the Burning
Bush. It's an aphrodisiac swaddled in a jet-black, river-deep basso
profundo that settles into your bones and caresses you somewhere
down below. Just say his name _ go on, say it _ and you want to
coax your voice down a few octaves, to take it where it was never
meant to go, into the loverman lair of the man they call the
Maestro of Love.
</P>
<P>
   Barry White makes love songs _ steamy, sweaty songs that also
exude tenderness and romance. He's been singing love songs _
classics like ``Can't Get Enough of Your Love, Babe,'' ``You're The
First, The Last, My Everything,'' and ``Never, Never Gonna Give Ya
Up'' _ since Nixon was president, and bellbottoms were in style the
first time around.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly 30 years in a industry that chews up and spits out
its artists faster than you can say the Spin Doctors, White has
perservered by sticking to what he does best _ crafting lushly
produced songs, honey-thick with bass and passion. As evidenced by
his 1994 album ``The Icon is Love,'' which sold 3 million copies,
good love songs never go out of style. At 54, when many of his
1970s contemporaries are VH1's ``Where Are They Now?'' subjects,
White is garnering some of the best reviews of his career with a
sultry new CD, ``Staying Power,'' as he begins a concert tour with
Earth, Wind &AMP; Fire Friday in a sold-out show at Boston's
FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   As he sings on the CD's opening lines, ``I'm not going nowhere.
I'm staying, baby, I'm staying. You know why _ I've got staying
power.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No artist can tell you when they first start how long they're
gonna last,'' said White in an telephone interview from Los
Angeles. ``That's a secret. You have to find that out by living, by
doing what you're doing, by being committed to your work, and being
consistent in your work. That's the only way you find out. So I'm
very grateful that after all these years, they've still got room
for Barry White.''
</P>
<P>
   The CD, White's first in five years, includes duets with Chaka
Khan, Lisa Stansfield (who covered White's ``Never, Never Gonna
Give Ya Up'' a few years back), and Gerald Albright. Sean ``Puffy''
Combs remixed White's slow-funk version of Sly Stone's ``Thank You
(Falettinme Be Mice Elf Agin).''
</P>
<P>
   If not for the fact that he's never really gone away, it could
be said White is smack-dab in the midst of a career revival.
Recently, he's lent his voice to the reading of Top Ten lists on
``The Late Show with David Letterman,'' and, even more bizarre, to
a stuffed bunny encouraging ``love your salad'' in a Good Seasons
salad dressing commercial. His autobiography, ``Love Unlimited,''
is due in stores next month. And last season, he performed on
``Ally McBeal,'' as the rhythmically challenged cast performed a
line dance. His music, a favorite of John ``The Biscuit'' Cage,
played by Peter MacNicol, has long been used to season the
program's sexual politics and romantic jousting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd been playing my music, and they called to say they
wanted me to come do an episode of the show,'' White said. ``I
obliged them, did an episode, and really made some good friends
over there. The people are very respectful and professional, just
all-around good people.'' (After this interview, White returned to
the ``McBeal'' set to tape another episode for the upcoming
season.)
</P>
<P>
   Through the show, White is enjoying a host of new fans, many of
whom are too young to remember his original hits. But while some of
the fans are new, White insisted his approach to music has remained
the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still make music the way I've always made it,'' he said.
``When it's time to do an album, I go deep inside, and I try to
pull out the very best in myself _ lyrics, melodies, rhythms,
counter melodies _ whatever it is. It's no different on this album
than any other album. I use the same philosophies.''
</P>
<P>
   And the philosophy he preaches hails the joys of love and
romance. With a voice that fashions every murmured babybabybaby
into a undying declaration of love, he's been making the ladies
gooey long before Ginuwine or K-Ci &AMP; JoJo were even a twitch in
their mamas' tummies. In his songs, White is the old-fashioned wine
and candlelight kind of lover _ this is, after all, a man who
composed a four-minute disco symphony with his own 40-piece Love
Unlimited Orchestra and called it ``Love's Theme.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, singers like White owned the airwaves and charts. Love
seemed to ooze from every record groove. The Stylistics exclaimed
``You Are Everything,'' Al Green cooed ``Let's Stay Together,'' and
Marvin Gaye just plain testified with, ``Let's Get It On.'' R&AMP;B and
soul music were the soundtrack of love, moon-spoon-June sentiments
wrapped in silk sheets and rose petals, with the lights turned
down. It was what you popped into the 8-track or on the turntable
when the mood had to be right. And if you couldn't find passion
with White's ``It's Ecstacy When You Lay Down Next to Me or ``Oh
What A Night for Dancing,'' then it just wasn't meant to be.
</P>
<P>
   Today, what passes for R&AMP;B is just so much booty-slappin' ill na
na nonsense, where sex pretends to be love, and women have been
reduced to semen receptacles. The ``old concept of love and being
respectful has changed, and keeps changing,'' White lamented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate that the young people today don't know how to, or don't
try to write love songs like they used to. People talk about Barry
White singing love songs, but everybody used to sing love songs,''
he said. ``Now it seems the only way to get a good love song today
is if somebody takes a sample from somebody else's love song.''
</P>
<P>
   And even when they aren't sampling him, White's influence is
apparent in such current artists as Maxwell and D'Angelo, who, like
White, concentrate on the many moods of love.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there were other subjects White could have devoted
his music to. He could written gangsta-trippin' tales about the
hard, foolish ways that claimed his brother's life in 1983. Born in
Texas, White was raised in south-central Los Angeles where he got
involved in enough gang mess to land him in jail for six months in
1960.
</P>
<P>
   But those experiences which, White said, turned his life around,
won't be found in his music. Despite the occasional ``message''
song, such as 1983's prescient ``Change,'' and ``Sometimes'' on the
current CD, White sticks to love songs _ appropriate enough, since
few voices are as libido-inducing as his. Besides, he said, ``Love
is a subject the whole world understands, and I knew that long
before I started making music.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a better subject in the world to talk about,'' he
said with a smoky chuckle. ``Everybody's still doing it, baby, and
it hasn't gone out of style.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, neither has the Maestro.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
