r f BC-SARATOGA-WATER-HNS &LR;      09-07 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SARATOGA-WATER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTLING `BARRACUDA' TAKES HER WATER SERIOUSLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLAIRE HUGHES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Posing for a newspaper photographer at
the water bottling plant she oversees, Robin Prever experiments
with crossing her arms and legs just so, to exude confidence. She
stretches her arms out wide along a row of blue bottles and smiles,
her face turned upward, eyes closed.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of Saratoga Beverage Group understands image
and marketing. When you're selling water in a bottle for as much as
$1.85, marketing is critical. The hyperactive chief executive in
her late 30s has taken a company that was nearly dead in 1992 and
turned it into a profitable and growing enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very scary, in retrospect,'' she says of her decision
to take control of the company in her early 30s, with no experience
running a business. ``At the time, I always had a certain amount of
confidence. I would figure a way out.''
</P>
<P>
   Carmen De Crescente Sr., one of the group of investors who
bought Saratoga Beverage with Prever seven years ago, says it
didn't take him long to realize the petite woman had the tenacity
Saratoga needed to make it a viable brand again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call her a barracuda,'' says De Crescente, who is also
chairman of De Crescente Distributing Co. of Mechanicville.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll trade blows with ya,'' De Crescente says. ``She's a
fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Prever says she is so competitive by nature that she has a
difficult time relaxing. She remembers a time someone suggested she
not take golf so seriously. Her response: ``I'm not here to relax
and enjoy it. I'm here to conquer this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Conquering the game of business, she says, has been easier for
her. She's had marketing instinct since she was a kid.
</P>
<P>
   As a 7-year-old on Long Island, she biked to the local grocery
store, bought candy and resold it at a profit to the neighborhood
children, aware they were a captive market _ most had no bikes.
Later, she decided she would have an easier time selling bracelets
she made from free telephone wires if she gave half the money to
charity. She sold the bracelets for $1, pocketing 50 cents each.
</P>
<P>
   As a young woman, she saw her opportunity to get into the world
of finance not long after graduating from law school in 1985. She
met storied money manager Mario Gabelli at a party, and he hired
her to handle public relations at his Rye, N.Y., company.
</P>
<P>
   Prever realized on her first day that the action _ and the money
_ at Gabelli Asset Management Co. was not in PR. Her second day,
she told Gabelli she was moving herself into portfolio management.
</P>
<P>
   She did well there, she says, sharing in the prosperity that
characterized Wall Street in the late 1980s. In 1992, Anthony
Malatino, her boyfriend and a financial adviser at Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter in Albany, persuaded her to take some of the money
she'd made and join a group of investors to buy Saratoga Beverage,
after Evian Waters of France had idled the water-bottling
operation.
</P>
<P>
   It was never her intent to run the business. But a year later,
it was her idea to jump-start the company by raising capital
through an initial public offering of stock. Looking for an
underwriter for the offering, she went to a friend at Merrill
Lynch, who laughed because the company was too small and at the
time unprofitable. Unfazed, she moved on to D.H. Blair &AMP;
Associates, which was then underwriting IPOs for smaller companies.
She couldn't sell an underwriter there on the concept either _
until she agreed to run the operation.
</P>
<P>
   So she gave up Wall Street _ and the hefty commissions and
perks.
</P>
<P>
   Prever's new job provided a culture shock. Instead of meeting
clients for lunch at the Waldorf Astoria, as Saratoga Beverage's
new chief executive she was entering the hotel's rear entrance to
talk to the purchasing manager. Instead of walking into
well-appointed offices, she found herself in the front end of a
bottling plant, at a wood-veneer desk, in hearing range of the
perpetual kerplunk-chink of bottles moving down conveyor belts.
</P>
<P>
   These days, she boasts about her frugal ways, pointing out the
carpet remnants that change with each floor of the company's
offices. But she still looks like she could be transplanted to
tonier digs in her Ann Taylor suit, with her Yorkshire terrier,
Pebbles, always by her side.
</P>
<P>
   Always willing to trust her instincts, Prever leapt into product
development soon after taking over the company's reins. Pre-Prever,
the company had produced only carbonated water. But Prever hated
bubbles. So noncarbonated drinks with Saratoga labels hit store
shelves for the first time in over a century.
</P>
<P>
   De Crescente remembers thinking she was crazy. Plain old water,
even from springs as famous as Saratoga's, was not a big seller
then, he said. He ended up being wrong about that, and later about
the success of the company's sweet, clear fruit drinks called
Splash. He's since stopped doubting her.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lately, she's taken the offensive. Six months ago the company
purchased the Fresh Juice Co. for $19 million. The company plans to
introduce fresh-squeezed juice in a bottle and new iced-tea and
lemonade drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Another executive might steer clear of the latter category,
after the flop Saratoga Beverage had with iced-tea and lemonade
drinks called Toga.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers and business leaders in upstate New York
speculate Prever's management team has been able to put fizz back
in Saratoga Beverage because the little guys have focus the big
guys lacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really needed somebody like Robin and crew to say this is
our baby and this is going to be our main line, and really attack
the market with it,'' said Joseph Dalton, president of the Saratoga
County Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Prever hasn't licked every battle, though. She hasn't won over
Wall Street. The company's stock price has hovered between $2 and
$3 a share for months. At the company's annual meeting earlier this
month, Prever told shareholders that Saratoga Beverage needs to
work harder to sell its name _ not just to consumers, but
investors, too.
</P>
<P>
   And she hasn't found time for much of a personal life. Prever
concedes to having given up a family life in the pursuit of work.
Malatino, now at a Morgan Stanley Dean Witter office in Saratoga
Springs, remains a part of her life. After 10 years of dating, a
wedding may at last be in order, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, whatever the sacrifices, Prever is not one to regret. She
ignores friends who tell her the dumbest thing she did was leave
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought I wanted to build something,'' she says,
``leave a mark.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
