<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3174 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-LITERATURE-MAUGHAM-BO     09-07 1660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITERATURE-MAUGHAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ERASER'S EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- W. Somerset Maugham, once the world's best-selling
English-language author, would have hated it.
</P>
<P>
   His correspondence. On display. In Boston. It was wrong on all
counts. Or so he would have said.
</P>
<P>
   Late in his long life, Maugham urged his friends to destroy his
letters, and he and his secretary spent long evenings burning
anything that might help a biographer.
</P>
<P>
   And as for Boston? Maugham didn't care for the place. He once
told a friend that proper Bostonians looked upon on authors who
hadn't taken the precaution of dying 100 years ago as guilty of bad
taste.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, thousands of people have visited Boston University's
unheralded exhibit of Maugham-orabilia. Which is one reason a
Maugham fan can't help thinking that Howard Gotlieb, director of
BU's Special Collections, has done both the author and literature a
favor.
</P>
<P>
   A walk through the exhibit, with its letters of praise and
admiration from such luminaries as Winston Churchill, E.M. Forster
and Henry Miller, reminds you of the heights Maugham once commanded
in the literary world.
</P>
<P>
   No longer. Although his work is still popular enough in England
to sell at airport bookstalls, in this country Maugham has suffered
a long fall from favor since his death in 1965 at 91. ``He is not
talked about the way Henry James is or the way Conrad is,'' says
Ted Morgan, whose 1980 biography was the first to give a full look
at the complicated, curmudgeonly author. ``I think he went on
writing too long, and the later stuff is not that good.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when Gotlieb looked for experts to speak at the opening
of the Maugham exhibition, he searched in vain for an academic who
had made Maugham his specialty. ``It was as if I was searching for
a ghost from the past,'' he says. In death as in life, Maugham has
largely been ignored by the academy.
</P>
<P>
   That's a shame, for if Maugham's later work may have tarnished
his reputation, it's also true that part of what makes him
remarkable as a writer is his sheer longevity. He published his
first book in 1897, his last in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   As Morgan points out in his book, Maugham's early literary
contemporaries were James Joyce, D.H. Lawrence, and Theodore
Dreiser. When he finally laid down his pen, J.D. Salinger had
already quit writing, and John Updike was making his name. With
letters from figures as distant as Hardy and as recent as Tennessee
Williams, the papers Gotlieb bought at auction reflect that amazing
span.
</P>
<P>
   And if some of his later fiction is undeniably hackneyed, the
best of his work is just as clearly first rate.
</P>
<P>
   One of Maugham's books _ ``Of Human Bondage'' (1915), a
Proustian tale of love turned to obsession and misery _ qualifies
as a classic. Two others, ``The Moon and Sixpence'' (1919) and
``Cakes and Ale'' (1930), are witty, compelling romans a clef
(about Paul Gauguin and Thomas Hardy) mocking the way the world
makes saints of the sinners who are often its best artists. ``The
Razor's Edge'' (1944), which sold more than 500,000 copies in a
single month, anticipated widespread interest in Eastern philosophy
and mysticism.
</P>
<P>
   If Maugham managed to stay contemporary through more than half a
century of writing, his sensibility still makes him fascinating
more than three decades after his death.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Victorian novelists, he wasn't interested in didactic
moral tales designed to improve the individual.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike reform-minded writers such as John Galsworthy or George
Bernard Shaw, he wasn't interested in societal critiques aimed at
improving the lot of mankind.
</P>
<P>
   He was, as he said again and again, simply a storyteller. The
``greatest living short-story writer'' England's New Statesman
declared in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   Maugham, a homosexual, feared his sexual orientation made him
frivolous and superficial. In retrospect, one can argue its real
contribution was to lend his work the very features that help keep
it fresh. Unhappily married for a period, Maugham had a grim and
ungilded view of matrimony, and it's that stark outlook that
informs his best stories.
</P>
<P>
   His homosexuality also made him somewhat uncomfortable in
England. ``I have never felt entirely myself till I had put at
least the Channel between my native country and me,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He regularly did, traveling on long sojourns to remote corners
of the British Empire. The short stories he crafted from raw
material collected on his travels are riveting: tales of love and
lust and hypocrisy, of cowardice and betrayal, adultery, murder,
and parricide.
</P>
<P>
   Often denounced as a cynic by critics put off at the
dispassionate, even amused, way in which he presented human foible
and failing, Maugham pled not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I have done is bring into prominence certain traits that
many writers shut their eyes to,'' he wrote in ``The Summing Up,''
his 1938 retrospective. In the current era, that criticism seems
hopelessly dated, while the unvarnished candor for which Maugham
was often criticized keeps his stories as current as the flaws that
lurk in the hearts of men.
</P>
<P>
   But that's hardly the only reason he's a treat to read.
</P>
<P>
   In an age that often takes more interest in the literary
personality than in literature itself, Maugham is a catty delight.
The rapier of sarcasm was more effective than the bludgeon of
invective, he was fond of saying, and he employed the former weapon
so skillfully that no less nimble a tongue than Winston Churchill
struck a pact with his favorite novelist: He would promise to make
no sport of Maugham if the author would extend him the same
protection.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, felt the cut of the blade. Although he
professed not to be, Maugham was terribly envious of the critical
recognition awarded writers like Henry James, James Joyce, and D.H.
Lawrence, men deemed artists while critics too often relegated him
to the ranks of literary tradesman.
</P>
<P>
   When, ``In Cakes and Ale,'' Maugham created octogenarian
novelist Edward Driffield, about whom he wrote, ``If . . .
longevity is genius, few in our time have enjoyed it in a more
conspicuous degree than Edward Driffield,'' critics accused him of
trampling on Thomas Hardy's grave and denounced as a ``literary
ghoul.''
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, Maugham saved his worst for James, whom he
considered pretentious and ridiculous. In ``Some Novelists I Have
Known,'' he wrote: ``Henry James's fictions are like the cobwebs
which a spider may spin in the attic of some old house, intricate,
delicate and even beautiful, but which at any moment the
housemaid's broom with brutal common sense may sweep away.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, literature's housemaid has taken Maugham's own novels
and stories and stacked them in a dark cellar. Still, if the
critics tended to deride Maugham, and they did, and if the literary
world has tended to forget him, and it has, walking the Boston
University exhibit, one is struck by the writers who counted
Maugham an important influence.
</P>
<P>
   Siegfried Sasson wrote to declare himself delighted by Maugham's
``astringency and clear-cut writing.''
</P>
<P>
   V.S. Pritchett penned a note in praise of Maugham's short
stories, saying he had tried to follow that model in his own, only
to be left ``in impotent admiration'' of Maugham's mastery.
</P>
<P>
   Miller scrawled a long letter enthusing over ``The Razor's
Edge,'' adding: ``Before I had written a line, I had read `Of Human
Bondage.' It was one of the books that formed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan reports that when his biography of Maugham came out, both
V.S. Naipaul and Paul Theroux, now locked in a literary feud worthy
of Maugham, told him they had learned from Maugham the need to
travel the world in search of their subjects.
</P>
<P>
   John le Carre also belongs on the list. More than three decades
before le Carre, Maugham, too, had been a spy, in World War I, an
experience he fictionalized in his Ashenden stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``John le Carre . . . said Ashenden was a major influence in his
works,'' recalls Morgan. ``It was the first sort of modern
espionage story where the spy is a more complicated figure, not
always heroic.''
</P>
<P>
   And Kingsley Amis wrote to thank Maugham for all he had taught
him about narrative technique. ``You are one of the very few
authors I admired when I was in my teens and still admire _ even
more _ today,'' he said in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   Amis was onto something there. And yet, despite that eminent
re-readability, these days Maugham is rarely read at all.
</P>
<P>
   The author himself expected no less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no illusions about my literary position,'' he wrote
late in life. ``There are but two important critics in my own
country who have troubled to take me seriously and when clever
young men write essays they never think of considering me. I do not
resent it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ha! His bitterness and resentment bleed through that denial and
a dozen others. Writing ostensibly of Maupassant, he seemed to
plead his own case. ``An author,'' he said, ``has a right to be
judged by his best works.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Maugham's bad has overshadowed his good, nudging almost
his entire oeuvre into obscurity. Yet his best books certainly
deserve better. As do many of his short stories.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings one back to Maugham's correspondence on display at
BU. Protest as Maugham would have, would an author who owned his
era only to fall into ill-deserved eclipse really hate it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe it for one minute,'' declares Gotlieb.
``Authors want the cloak of immortality. . . . They adore the idea
that some graduate student will write a doctoral thesis on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Once you pierce the cloak of camouflage the author left behind,
it's hard not to think Gotlieb is right: If Maugham could see the
thousands who have wandered through the exhibit to look at his
manuscripts and letters and books and honors, he'd likely be
beaming. Even in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Scot Lehigh is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
