<HEADER>
A3178 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      09-07 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUT GOAL OF HOUSE AHEAD OF STOCK OPTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I have the opportunity to start buying stock
in his company at a 15 percent discount from market price. He can
purchase an amount representing 10 percent of his annual salary, or
$5,000. The only stipulation is that he must hold on to it for at
least four months. It is a growing company, and the stock has been
increasing in price over the past year that he has been with it,
but I am not sure if we should take advantage of the offer or not,
given our goal of buying a house. We are saving $1,300 a month
toward the down payment in a money market account that earns 5
percent. We currently have about $17,000 saved, or 6 percent of the
anticipated cost of the house. For retirement we fully fund Roth
IRAs for both of us and both contribute 10 percent of our salaries
to 401(k) plans. We would like to be in a house by this time next
year. What would you do?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; K.P., Maynard
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think I'd do just what you are doing and let the company
stock offer, however attractive it may seem, wait until you have
achieved your primary goal of buying the house. The value of shares
in small and growing companies can be very volatile, and most would
probably be very susceptible to any substantial downturn in the
stock markets, sometimes regardless of the performance of the
company.
</P>
<P>
   If you're still tempted to go for the stock offer, approach it
as you would approach any investment. That is to say, ask a lot of
tough questions, and don't let that fat 15 percent discount hold
too much sway.
</P>
<P>
   Is the company profitable, and are its prospects of continued
and growing profits strong? Does it have unique market niche that
is secure, or is it facing substantial competition? Is it in a
business in which a competitor could suddenly come up with an
improved product that blows your husband's company out of the
water? What is the price-to-earnings ratio relative to other
companies in the same industry? Do you have absolute faith in your
company's top management?
</P>
<P>
   There are also questions to ask that might make the idea of
gambling on the stock offer more attractive. Your husband is, of
course, an insider, so he is likely to know whether the company has
strong product or service offerings in the pipeline _ products or
services he feels are strong enough to cause a significant spike in
the stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you believe the prospects are strong enough so that
you're willing to take the gamble _ and don't fool yourself that
investing in a small company for a four-to-12-month profit isn't
gambling _ I would limit the contribution to less than the maximum.
</P>
<P>
   If you maintained your current savings schedule, you would have
accumulated $33,890 toward the mortgage down payment over a year's
time. If you cut contributions to $1,000 a month, you would have
$30,126 in the money market account, and you would have invested
$3,600 in stock that might or might not be worth more than you paid
for the shares.
</P>
<P>
   You might look at it this way: If you're attracted to the offer,
you could consider buying the stock as a gamble that, at the very
worst, could delay your home purchase. If you think the upside
potential outweighs that downside, by all means go ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But to answer your direct question _ what would you do? _ unless
I had some powerful inside information on the potential value of
this stock, I'd stick with the saving schedule you have established
and save the option of buying the stock until a time when you can
view the purchases as long-term investments.
</P>
<P>
   I should also note here that although the term ``inside
information'' has all kinds of negative associations lately, in
your situation, thinking hard about your husband's company is not
only wise, but entirely legal.
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
