<HEADLINE>
MOVIES REVIEWED RECENTLY IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 
! ``Chill Factor'' Notable only for Cuba Gooding Jr.'s worst choice
of a role yet. He plays a stereotype driving a stolen ice-cream
truck that will keep a canister of toxic chemicals cool while Skeet
Ulrich's watered-down James Dean loner chills his way through the
dumb chase stuff. (R) 
 
!! ``Floating'' Concord, Mass. native William Roth brings rich
atmosphere and a waste-free narrative style to the bittersweet
story of a teenager's summer of awakening, and Norman Reedus plays
the townie teen with natural grace. But some of the supporting
characters are cartoonish, and one edges into old-fashioned
tortured-homosexual stereotype. (Unrated) (Matthew Gilbert) 
 
! ``Outside Providence'' The Farrelly brothers (``There's Something
About Mary'') collaborate with Michael Corrente (``Federal Hill,''
``American Buffalo'') on a coming-of-age story that, while
familiar, steers clear of cliche. There's no ``American Pie''
glorying in dumbness here, just a tender, gritty honesty. Shawn
Hatosy brings unforced conviction to the role of a blue-collar
Rhode Island kid packed off to boarding school by his dad, played
with terrific control by Alec Baldwin. (R)
