<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3180 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-FALL-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-BOS     09-07 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... far too great.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only network that has been mindful of balancing youth with
age, if not of balancing pablum with quality, is, of course, CBS.
This season CBS has roles for veterans Betty White and Dixie Carter
in a dud of a sitcom called ``Ladies Man''; for Tyne Daly as a
retired judge whose daughter, Amy Brenneman, is a practicing judge
in a ``Providence'' knockoff called ``Judging Amy''; and for
Kathleen Quinlan in a bland legal drama called ``Family Law.'' Then
again, CBS also serves up one of the fall's most egregiously ageist
shows, the supernatural ``Now &AMP; Again.'' By the end of the pilot,
the brain of middle-aged shlep John Goodman winds up in the buff
young body of Eric Close, and the series becomes another
hunk-in-a-funk drama. Goodman, it turns out, is just a guest star. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Xerox effect &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many of the new titles are from the do-it-again school of TV
programming, as the networks, like sequel-crazed movie studios, try
to duplicate proven successes. It's not just ``Angel'' and ``Time
of Your Life'' or the three other spinoffs: Fox's ``Ally,'' a
half-hour of outtakes from ``Ally McBeal''; NBC's ``Law &AMP; Order:
Special Victims Unit,'' which will deal with more heinous crimes
than ``Law &AMP; Order''; and UPN's already-premiered ``The Parkers,''
with characters from ``Moesha.''
</P>
<P>
   The networks are busy going back to familiar wells for more
product from backstage creative players like Kevin Williamson. With
two of TV's strongest series _ ``The Practice'' and ``Ally McBeal''
_ under his belt, David E. Kelley is giving ABC yet another
probable hit this fall, called ``Snoops.'' About a PI firm that
uses high-tech spying gadgetry illegally, the dramedy exploits the
hot-button issue of privacy in America. In typical Kelley fashion,
it also exploits the tension between its female leads, the
street-smart Gina Gershon and the by-the-book Paula Marshall.
``Snoops'' has a winning, almost ``Avengers''-like whimsy.
</P>
<P>
   Happy with Steven Levitan's successful ``Just Shoot Me,'' NBC
has hit up the producer for another sitcom and scheduled it in the
golden slot after ``Frasier'' on Thursday nights. But, based on the
pilot, Levitan's ``Stark Raving Mad'' looks like a loser, despite
funny neurotic antics from Neil Patrick Harris as an editor saddled
with a prankish horror writer. Smitten with ``ER,'' and forgiving
of last year's ``Trinity,'' NBC is also trying out another hour
from series creator John Wells, called ``Third Watch.'' About
late-shift paramedics, firefighters, and cops, it's faster-paced,
younger, and ultimately less involving than ``ER.'' The busy pilot
depends on too much ambulance-side dating chatter, not to mention
vomiting in the name of ``gritty realism.'' NBC also has great
expectations of Aaron Sorkin, creator of ABC's acclaimed ``Sports
Night.'' With the White House dramedy ``The West Wing,'' Sorkin
delivers yet another set of high-strung characters in a charged
office setting. Martin Sheen is the president, and Rob Lowe is his
George Stephanopoulos-like adviser. Expect snappy dialogue, dashing
camerawork, and, alas, painfully earnest moral moments.
</P>
<P>
   Aiming for a new paranoia-themed hit, Fox is featuring a murky
sci-fi drama called ``Harsh Realm'' from ``X-Files'' creator Chris
Carter. Targeted to computer-game players, and potentially
monotonous, ``Harsh Realm'' traps a hunky war hero inside a video
game, where he must destroy a power-hungry player named Santiago.
Think ``Heart of Darkness'' meets ``Doom.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, the best do-it-again move may have been
by ABC, which looked to former hotshots Edward Zwick and Marshall
Herskovitz, the men behind ``thirtysomething'' and ``My So-Called
Life,'' for an hour of guaranteed quality. This time out, the pair
came up with the stylish character drama ``Once and Again,'' an
honest look at the hard-to-manage affair between divorced father
Bill Campbell and separated mother Sela Ward, as well as its impact
on their kids. It looks like a keeper.
</P>
<P>
   The sitcom roster is particularly grim this fall, with a group
of comedies as dull as their titles. ``Oh Grow Up'' (two guys, a
gay, and a bachelor pad) and ``Then Came You'' (he's 22, she's 33,
age jokes ensue) are on ABC; ``The Mike O'Malley Show'' (a Norm and
Drew wannabe) is on NBC; and ``Work With Me'' (the couple that
works together doesn't work) and ``Love and Money'' (super in a
superduper apartment building) are on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   The only original half-hour comedy is ``Action,'' a Fox show
that's already been rocked by controversy for its explicit
language, most of which is bleeped out, and for its sexual content,
which includes a Hollywood honcho with an exceedingly large penis.
First created for HBO, the sitcom stars Jay Mohr from ``Jerry
Maguire'' as a slimeball movie producer who sharks his way through
the studio waters with the help of hooker Illeana Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Wired with the spirit of Robert Altman's ``The Player,''
``Action'' is without doubt the most cynical new show on TV. And
guess what: It's made for adults.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
