<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SHORT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT LONG ON RISK AS TV TALK SHOW HOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The challenge of hosting a TV talk show might freeze the marrow
of your average performer, but Martin Short can truthfully say that
it's child's play to him.
</P>
<P>
   You see, when other kids in his Hamilton, Ontario, neighborhood
were slapping hockey pucks around, Short was up in his family's
attic, hosting an imaginary talk/variety program that he dubbed,
presciently enough, ``The Martin Short Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I alternated every other week with Andy Williams, which
allowed me to continue my film career,'' Short deadpanned. ``I
would interview Eldridge Cleaver, and then someone would call
`Dinner!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Short's fantasy gets real starting at 10 a.m. Sept. 13 as he
launches a daily, one-hour talk show called, what else, ``The
Martin Short Show.'' He is wading into treacherous waters: If Short
doubts that, he need only ask Howie Mandel, whose own syndicated
talker was swiftly canceled, or Roseanne, whose
forgotten-but-not-gone ratings disaster has been relegated to a
post-midnight slot in Boston to make room for Short.
</P>
<P>
   But Short seems to see only blue skies ahead, perhaps
justifiably, since he has proven his ability to charm many a
talk-show audience over the years. ``One of the reasons I'm not
daunted _ and I could be wrong, God knows I've been wrong before _
is the simple fact that when I would go out and promote a movie,
the reaction of the audience has been very warm, very receptive,''
said Short.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd been met with stone silence in the last 18 years, I
wouldn't in any way be proceeding with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason that Short's prospects seem relatively bright is
that he has vastly more performing range than most of the one-trick
ponies who try their hand as talk-show hosts, so he can add some
new ingredients to the overly familiar celebrity chitchat formula.
There's a chance his many-sided personality could light a fire
under the dullest guest, and indeed Short says he wants to see
``how loose and seat-of-the-pants you can be'' within a talk-show
format.
</P>
<P>
   Short has a rare gift for character sketches (as his stints on
``Saturday Night Live'' and ``SCTV'' attest), and he is clearly
nostalgic for the variety-show format. So his new show will make
plenty of room for parodies and taped comedy segments, featuring
himself and a troupe of young performers, along with musical spoofs
that will showcase Short's song-and-dance talents.
</P>
<P>
   After winning a Tony Award this year as best actor in a musical
for his appearance on Broadway in ``Little Me,'' Short, 48,
determined that he wanted to return to television, which he calls
``the most immediate, the most forgiving _ my favorite medium.'' He
was looking for ``a home to do what I do,'' but he'd done a sitcom,
he'd done sketch comedy _ how about a talk show?
</P>
<P>
   Short acknowledged in some Hollywood eyes, ``celebrity talk
wasn't the coolest thing to be doing.'' But the allure of the
untried thing proved strong for a performer who says of himself:
``Nothing is as intriguing to me as something I haven't attempted
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really dabbled in a lot of forms of show business; this
is one I haven't,'' Short said. (A talk show) allows me to do a
wide variety of different things as well as be in the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   With a lot of movies (``Innerspace,'' ``Father of the Bride,''
``The Three Amigos'') and television shows on his resume, Short
also has enough clout to book a few A-list guests who don't usually
traverse the daytime talk-show circuit. For instance, old pal Billy
Crystal agreed to appear on the premiere, Steve Martin is slated
the next day and Tom Hanks will be a guest later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   But Short makes clear he recoils at the thought of personally
ringing up his cronies and pressuring them to do guest stints.
</P>
<P>
   ``No money is worth that call,'' he said emphatically. ``I have
some old show-business friendships, but me phoning up and saying
`Hey, Nick Nolte, it's me, Marty! Are you busy on Friday the 13th?'
And he says `Sure,' but that is not what he says when he hangs up
the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Short's new program carries the same title as his short-lived
1994 sitcom for NBC. He said he envisioned that show as a series of
comedy sketches, but the network insisted on a traditional sitcom
storyline. ``Clearly, NBC wanted `Home Improvement,' '' he said.
``We reached a civil-war point.'' (He noted, however, that the
lowest-rated ``Martin Short Show'' still notched a 19 audience
share, which would be a solid hit in the current, cable-fragmented
TV universe).
</P>
<P>
   As a young TV viewer, Short admired the styles of Jack Paar and
Johnny Carson, but unlike them and most other talk-show hosts,
Short does not plan to sit at a desk while he interviews
celebrities. He also will eschew question cards, hoping for the
smooth-flowing give-and-take he likes best when he is a guest on
other talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   While some stations, such as WCVB-TV, Channel 5 in Boston, are
giving Short a morning slot, others in the country plan to air it
as a late-night or early-evening show. Short says he's not worried
about tailoring the show will play in different time periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really endlessly worry about the outcome of
anything,'' he said. ``If you worry too much about the outcome, you
probably get frozen, and start trying to please everyone, and
people can smell that.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude extends to his debut. From his longtime perch on
the guest couch, Short has learned that progress can be gradual in
the talk-show game, so he's not adopting any do-or-die attitude
about his first show.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I know so far,'' he said. ``There's no way I will
be as loose and as good (today) as I will be six months from now.
Nor was Johnny, nor was Conan, nor was Dave, nor was anybody who
ever existed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
