<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PBS ROLLS OUT ITS NEW SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pope, the apocalypse, the mysteries of the microbial world,
the search for extraterrestrial life: Yep, it's another season of
big themes on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   The occasional Yanni special notwithstanding, the Public
Broadcasting Service appears to be largely resisting the temptation
to dumb down. No bellowing pro wrestlers or shrieking game-show
contestants here.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, what quickens the pulse of PBS programmers _ and, they
hope, their viewers _ are high-minded explorations of history,
religion, urban life, women's emancipation, class, race, politics,
cinema, and space.
</P>
<P>
   PBS could use a little luster on the fall schedule, because off
the air it's been a bad year. Numerous public-television stations
became embroiled in an embarrassing contretemps involving the
swapping of membership lists with political parties.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for PBS, Ken Burns _ who recently alleviated his own
funding worries by reaching a long-term deal with corporate sponsor
General Motors _ is back on the schedule this fall.
</P>
<P>
   With the glorious ``Baseball'' and ``The Civil War,'' the New
Hampshire-based filmmaker has established himself as one of the
finest documentarians of our time. This season, Burns turns his
attention to the struggle for women's suffrage (a subject notably
shortchanged by ABC when it covered the past 100 years in ``The
Century''). Burns's ``Not for Ourselves Alone: The Story of
Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B. Anthony'' examines the
struggles faced by two early champions of women's rights, who
forged an unstoppable alliance. It clocks in at a brisk (for Burns)
four hours and is scheduled for Nov. 7 and 8.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers who crave a typically sprawling Burns epic will find it
supplied this fall by Ric Burns, Ken's brother. His 12-hour ``New
York: A Documentary Film'' will range across the history of New
York from its origins as a Dutch trading post in 1624 to its status
today as the de facto capital of the world. Co-produced by Channel
2 as part of ``The American Experience'' series, ``New York'' will
air Nov. 14-18.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 28, ``Frontline'' will try to get a handle on the
extraordinary, complicated figure of Pope John Paul II, who
reenergized the Catholic Church and helped smash communism (and has
proven no friend of capitalism, either). ``John Paul II: The
Millennial Pope'' is scheduled to run 2 1/2 hours. Not likely to be
enough.
</P>
<P>
   The team that produced the superb ``From Jesus to Christ: The
First Christians'' for ``Frontline'' is back with ``Apocalypse!''
(The un-PBS-like exclamation point is jarring, but at least they
didn't call it ``Old Testament Smackdown!'') The program, slated
for Nov. 22, examines the shifting interpretations of the idea of
apocalypse over the past 2,500 years.
</P>
<P>
   Writer, scholar, and now travel guide Henry Louis Gates Jr. of
Harvard will take viewers on a journey through modern Africa that
pauses in ancient towns and palaces for glimpses at the past. The
six-hour ``Wonders of the African World with Henry Louis Gates
Jr.'' will air Oct. 25-27.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteenth-century England is the setting, and four high-born
sisters who lived ``long and turbulent lives'' are the subjects, of
``Aristocrats,'' a three-part ``Mobil Masterpiece Theatre''
miniseries airing Oct. 10, 17, and 24. Speaking of turbulence:
``Hitchcock, Selznick and the End of Hollywood'' (Nov. 1) will
focus on the stormy relationship between genius filmmaker Alfred
Hitchcock and genius mogul David O. Selznick.
</P>
<P>
   From Sept. 12 through 16, American Playhouse raises the curtain
on ``An American Love Story,'' a documentary about a black man and
a white woman whose 30-year relationship has defied racial
prejudice and social conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, ``Greater Boston'' host Emily Rooney and a panel of
pundits will explore the future of journalism in ``Brave News
World: A Greater Boston Forum,'' on Oct. 1. ``Greater Boston Arts''
returns for a new season on Oct. 6. ``Basic Black'' kicks off a new
season on Nov. 4, featuring an interview with Rev. Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 6, the ``Nova'' team tries to get to the bottom of an
ill-fated 1924 attempt to scale the world's tallest mountain with
``Everest: The Mystery of Mallory and Irvine.'' Then, on Nov. 9,
``Nova'' goes back to World War II for ``Decoding Nazi Secrets''
(Nov. 9), a chronicle of the way Allied mathematicians and chess
champions helped win the war by cracking a crucial German code
machine.
</P>
<P>
   PBS is billing ``Intimate Strangers: Unseen Life on Earth'' as
the first series ``ever to focus exclusively on the microbial
world.'' On Nov. 9, 16, 23, and 30, the program will examine the
way DNA links all life, the riddles posed by infectious disease,
and whether microbial life can help fix environmental damage.
</P>
<P>
   If the microscopic view begins to pall, there's always the view
through a telescope. ``Life Beyond Earth,'' a two-hour special
about mankind's search for life on other planets, is hosted and
written by Timothy Ferris, author of ``Coming of Age in the Milky
Way.'' It's scheduled for Nov. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Diana Rigg celebrates her 10th anniversary as the host of
``Mystery!'', which kicks off Sept. 30 with ``Second Sight,'' a
thriller about a hard-boiled detective diagnosed with an eye
disorder that steadily robs him of his vision, with attendant job
complications.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, PBS is introducing a new animated program for
preschoolers called ``Dragon Tales.'' Produced by Children's
Television Workshop, it follows the adventures of two youngsters
who enlist some friendly dragons to help them cope with the
challenges they face.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3184 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-BAPTISTS-JEWS-TEX     09-07 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-JEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAPTISTS ASK MEMBERS TO PRAY FOR CONVERSION OF JEWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Southern Baptists have produced a ``Jewish
prayer guide'' urging members to pray for the conversion of Jews to
Christianity during the High Holy Days of Rosh Hashana and Yom
Kippur beginning Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Some Jewish leaders called the action arrogant and offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baptists have a right to believe what they believe,'' said
Mark Briskman, Southwest regional director for the Anti-Defamation
League of B'nai B'rith. ``But we find this offensive. It shows an
element of arrogance because they are specifically targeting Jews
during this holy season.''
</P>
<P>
   The prayer effort was announced in a news release by the
Southern Baptist International Mission Board in Richmond, Va. The
board has published a similar guide on praying for Muslims during
Ramadan; guides are planned focusing on Hindus and Buddhists, the
announcement states.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Rosh Hashana, when observant Jews around the world begin 10
days of seeking God, Southern Baptists will be praying they find
his Son,'' the release begins. The 10 days are called ``Days of
Awe.''
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist prayer strategy will begin at sundown Friday, the
beginning of Rosh Hashana, the Jewish New Year, and will continue
through Yom Kippur, the Day of Atonement, Sept. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist ``Days of Awe'' prayer guide explains the way Jews
celebrate High Holy Days, gives sketches of Jewish people in
different parts of the world and offers suggestions on how to pray
for Jewish people.
</P>
<P>
   The guide urges Baptists ``to pray for Jewish individuals you
know by name'' throughout the High Holy Days.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Jewish people attempt to purge themselves of spiritually
crippling attitudes, pray that they will find the spiritual
wholeness available through the Messiah, (Jesus)'' the guide
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pray for a realization among the Jewish people that their sins
can be transferred through belief to the One (meaning Jesus) sent
to bear them.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptists anticipated criticism of their prayer effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Jewish leaders reject such efforts as being wrongheaded,
arrogant or even contributing to the spiritual and cultural
equivalent of the Holocaust,'' Don Kammerdiener, executive vice
president of the International Mission Board, said in a statement.
``But the Bible is clear regarding the necessity of sharing the
Gospel with Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Sprinkle, director of the International Mission Board's
prayer strategy office, added, ``Because God loves the Jews as His
chosen people, Christians ought to mirror that love at the very
time Jews worldwide are seeking God.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Sibley of Dallas, who was named coordinator of the Baptist
North American Mission Board's mission efforts among Jews in 1996,
said last week that the prayers are an attempt to show love for the
Jewish people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't intend to be offensive or provocative,'' Sibley said.
``It is simply a matter of exercising our freedom of religion and
convictions. I wouldn't mind if the Jewish community prayed for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rabbi Ralph Mecklenburger, leader of Congregation Beth-El, a
Reform synagogue in Fort Worth, said he does not see the prayer
effort as so benign.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they come to my holiest day of the year and suggest God
is not listening, I think that is offensive and very
un-Christian,'' Mecklenburger said.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Albert Zeilocovich, leader of Congregation Ahavath Sholom,
a Conservative congregation in Fort Worth, said Baptists have a
right to pray for Jews to accept Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can do what they want in their churches,'' he said. ``But
if they try to contact somebody who is Jewish and try to take him
away from his faith, that is not respecting his belief.''
</P>
<P>
   Briskman said he understands and appreciates that many devout
evangelicals believe that it is their religious duty to share their
belief in Christ with others.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when they target Jews as we begin our 10 most serious
religious holidays, I think that is the height of arrogance,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first time Briskman has been asked to comment
about a controversy involving Southern Baptists and Jews. In 1980,
the Rev. Bailey Smith, then president of the Southern Baptist
Convention, announced that ``God does not hear the prayer of a
Jew'' during a speech in Dallas before religious conservatives who
included presidential candidate Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   After an uproar, Smith apologized and led efforts to improve
Baptist-Jewish relations, including accepting Briskman's invitation
to join a Seder with Briskman's family.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's comments came early in the conservatives' drive for
control of the Southern Baptist Convention. In the years since,
conservatives have consolidated power, taking over all convention
offices and seminaries. Baptists who are more moderate formed the
Cooperative Baptist Fellowship and slowly distanced themselves from
the denomination.
</P>
<P>
   Among recent conservative actions that moderates oppose are
boycotts of the Walt Disney Co. and the addition of a line to the
basic statement of faith requiring wives to submit to their
husbands. Another point of contention arose in 1996 when the
conservatives first targeted Jews for conversion and mapped out a
strategy to accomplish that.
</P>
<P>
   Mecklenburger said he knows many Southern Baptists who opposed
the 1996 resolution and would also oppose scheduling the prayer
effort during the most important religious holidays of the Jewish
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have many Southern Baptist friends and we have a mutual
respect for one another's beliefs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Dilday of Southlake northeast of Fort Worth, president
of the Baptist General Convention of Texas, which is led by
moderate Baptists, said he strongly favors sharing the Christian
faith with all. But he disagrees with the Baptist prayer effort
during the Jewish High Holy Days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think picking on the special days of the Jewish people to do
this is an intrusion,'' he said. ``We need to share our faith in a
Christlike way. This could drive people away from Jesus rather than
draw people to Him.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   To order the ``Days of Awe'' prayer guide, e-mail the Southern
Baptist International Mission Board at resource.center(at)imb.org
or call (800) 866-3621.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
