<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-RETURN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING THE PILOTS OF THE VIETNAM WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. _ This is the pitch: a war movie starring
10 real-life Harrison Fords, one as intense as ``Saving Private
Ryan,'' only true.
</P>
<P>
   Freida Lee Mock and Terry Sanders actually use those lines to
describe their latest project, ``Return With Honor.'' But the
Academy Award winners do it with small, knowing smiles. After all,
as documentary filmmakers they have learned that a catchy blurb can
put even the most reticent people in movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they're not stretching the truth all that much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Return With Honor,'' about American pilots shot down over
North Vietnam, is 102 minutes of harrowing heroism and undeniable
endurance. Grainy, archival footage from Hanoi recalls men who were
gaunt and grimacing, beaten and sometimes broken. Sketches they
made hint at their torture. Mostly, though, the prisoners of war
appear as themselves today, physically whole again, still
psychologically strong, heartwrenching, of course, but also
unexpectedly humorous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tells you, hey, there's more to this story than these guys
getting shot down and getting the crap beat out of them,'' said Ed
Mechenbier, who was a 24-year-old Air Force lieutenant when he was
shot down on June 14, 1967, the start of an ordeal that lasted, as
he put it, 2,093 days, or five years and eight months. ``It was a
chance to tell it the way we wanted to tell it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But this film's not about those of us who were lucky enough to
return with honor,'' added Mechenbier, now an executive with a San
Diego technology firm. ``It's really a tribute to the fellas who
didn't come home at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the movie ``Return With Honor,'' which opens at the Museum
of Fine Arts Wednesday at 8 p.m., and the expression the title is
taken from are layered with meaning for the Vietnam War veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Even amid the chaos of the camps, there was an unspoken order.
POWS struggled not to give up information, even when they were
suspended by their arms and their shoulders dislocated. They nursed
each other through. No matter how desperate, no matter what the
North Vietnamese offered, they were not to leave out of turn _
first the worst wounded, then the longest held. To this day, as the
film makes clear, the POWS who stayed do not speak to those who
accepted an offer to go home early while their fellow prisoners of
war were kept behind.
</P>
<P>
   The others keep in close touch, with reunions and emails, and an
understanding of each other's experiences that transcends words.
Paul Galanti, a former Navy pilot who was a POW for 6 1/2 years and
now maintains the group's Web site, said he would lend any one of
them money and never think to ask for it back.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary ends with Galanti's philosophy -- ``There's no
such thing as a bad day when there's a doorknob on the inside of
the door'' -- but in between it hardly glosses over the agony that
made that sort of simple optimism possible.
</P>
<P>
   With chilling friendliness over tea and cookies, Galanti
recalled, their captors informed one POW that his wife had left
him. Another learned of his divorce on the plane home. They were
kept up to date on the antiwar movement in the States, and marched
through the streets of Vietnam. Then there were the ropes. One
wrong move and, as former Navy Lt. John (Mike) McGrath puts it in
the movie, ``You'd choke yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You reach a point where you'd throw your own child in the fire
to get out of those ropes,'' said Galanti, who spent 10 months in
and out of the hospital after his release, was an executive in the
medical field, and is now starting a computer company. ``The first
time, my hands were turning black and it really hurt and I said,
``OK, I'll tell you.' So they untied me and it hurt worse when the
blood rushed back to my fingers and they put me right back in the
ropes. I had to answer before they'd take them off again. I don't
remember what I told them, my mind was so screwed up. I later
learned to tell them big lies and not get to the point where I was
irrational. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out I wasn't as tough as I thought I was,'' he
added, ``but that in a lot of ways I was tougher than I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   To stay sane and mentally strong, the POWS learned to
communicate from cell to cell by tapping out a code that was passed
from man to man. Mechenbier gave wine-tasting classes, pouring
imaginary glasses for the other men. They walked miles, back and
forth across their rooms, pretending they were outdoors. They
shared everything they brought with them, which was what they had
in their heads, and tried not to lose their senses of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Later Mechenbier even wrote a manuscript called ``Ho Ho Ho Chi
Minh,'' a lighter look at the camps. For instance, he said, the
POWS explained to their captors that fighter pilots greeted each
other with their middle fingers raised in respect. Years later,
when antiwar protesters came to Vietnam, the guards saluted them as
they had been taught.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the POWs we interviewed are professional POW
survivors,'' said Sanders. ``Many are asked to speak on Veterans
Day, but these are fighter pilots and they're always thinking ahead
of the crash. They're not guys who spend all their time looking
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Mock, ``We met them as very whole human beings. It was a
psychological question: How do you deal with what happened? Can you
get past it?''
</P>
<P>
   More than a quarter-century after the last prisoners were
released from Vietnam, Mock and Sanders attempt to answer those
questions. The idea for the project, in fact, came from three
Vietnam veterans who approached the pair after seeing their
documentary, ``Maya Lin: A Strong, Clear Vision,'' about the
architect who designed the Vietnam War Memorial in Washington. That
documentary won them an Oscar. ``Return with Honor'' opened in June
in selected cities to strong reviews in New York and Los Angeles.
The fighter pilots themselves gave it two standing ovations at
their 25th reunion a year ago in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   What Mock and Sanders, who work out of a Santa Monica bungalow,
said they found were men who were anything but sterotypically
military. Not everyone agreed with everything the US government
did, then or in later conflicts, including the most recent one in
the Balkans. Rather than damaged warriors, they discovered unsung
heroes -- men whose stories so moved actor Tom Hanks after he saw
it on video that he lent his name as ``presenter,'' although he
does not appear anywhere in the documentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``At its most basic, this is a story about people surviving,
about how you resist becoming a collaborator with the enemy,'' Mock
said. ``But these are also men who believed in their country, who
believed in their leaders, who signed up and have stuck to it. In
this day and age, there is interest in those attitudes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
