u e BC-MOVIES-COSTNER-2TAKES     09-07 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-COSTNER-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COSTNER'S GAME 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You could say that Kevin Costner is stepping up to the plate
again with ``For Love of the Game,'' except that this time he's
occupying the pitcher's mound. After reinvigorating the baseball
movie genre with ``Bull Durham'' and ``Field of Dreams,'' he's
returning to on-screen hardball as an aging Detroit Tigers ace
working on a perfect game against the Yankees, punctuated by
flashbacks from a less perfect personal life. In a timeout from his
participation in the ancillary festivities attached to July's
All-Star Game at Fenway Park, Costner previewed a rough cut of his
new film, due to open Sept. 17. He also delivered a couple of
surprise pitches in an interview on the eve of the game.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he says, withdrawing to a quiet room in a
downtown hotel suite where friends, associates, and his 15-year-old
daughter, Annie, come and go: ``I don't think you can make a sports
movie about sports. I think it always has to be about people. What
you need to do is honor the athleticism it requires to make such a
movie, because even nonathletes can tell what an unathletic
movement looks like. But there was no feeling on my part that now
was the time to make another baseball movie. These three movies are
like my three children. They're all my children, but they're wildly
different and they each can stand on their own. `Field of Dreams'
was a mystical mood piece. `Bull Durham' is about this minor
leaguer, with all the glory and hilarity and sensibility of that,
and ultimately it's about a man and a woman who were made for each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy Chapell, the pitcher at the end of his career in `For
Love of the Game,' is the greyhound in the group, this person on
his way to the Hall of Fame. He's almost a kind of throwback. And
as the game proceeds he's examining his life.'' (Much of what he
examines in flashback is his prickly but loving on-off relationship
with a Manhattan-based magazine writer and single mom played by
Kelly Preston.)
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got the script, what I wanted to do was make it
tougher, make him more blemished, because I think it's easy to make
him a golden boy. I think you like him better when he's fierce, at
least I do. It's more interesting to me that a guy can be like that
and then be weak at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For Love of the Game,'' with its view of American male
solitariness crafted into the inning-by-inning drama, is more than
just your usual baseball movie, in other words, and more than just
your usual boy-girl story. ``I would have had reservations about
making another movie with a baseball background if I were trying to
plan a career,'' Costner adds. ``But I'm not. When I read something
I like, I have a no-looking-back attitude, a real killer instinct
about here's what I want to do. I still haven't done a movie for a
paycheck. Professionally, nothing has changed. Hopefully, I'm
trying to do it better. I still approach it in an enthusiastic
way.'' That kind of enthusiasm extended, during Costner's Boston
stay, to doing some Kennedy-related homework for his upcoming film
set during the Cuban missile crisis, ``Thirteen Days.''
</P>
<P>
   What about personally? ``Personally, my thinking has had to
alter itself because I'm living a more independent life,'' Costner
says, referring to the six years since his divorce. As to ``how my
personal life has changed over the last few years, I don't really
have that wrapped up in the way that I have some of the other
questions I feel I can handle.'' Suffice it to say that Costner's
character in the movie is not portrayed as a paragon, and that he
brings some of his off-the-field troubles on himself _ just as
Costner in his own life has, as he always acknowledges. Although
he's loose and relaxed in the middle of a busy day, he says, ``I
mean, I'm a single man. I don't want to talk about this anymore. I
just have to go forward in my life without fear. Not without the
knowledge that something was going to be written, but without the
fear of it.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that makes Costner a throwback to such Hollywood
archetypes as, say, Gary Cooper is the fact that for better or
worse, he's unapologetically his own man. If he weren't, he'd have
folded his tent and walked away from ``Dances With Wolves,'' which
almost everyone told him would end in disaster, and never would
have undertaken such ambitious films as ``Waterworld'' and ``Wyatt
Earp.'' He's inner-directed, stubborn, but loyal to old friends and
associates and especially to family. He has cast not only his own
children in films, but his father as well. And there's more of him
than is immediately apparent in ``For Love of the Game,'' beyond
his genuine involvement with baseball as a game to which he came
late, but plays remarkably well, especially for a 44-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't play college baseball at his alma mater, Cal
State-Fullerton, but since has become involved with the nationally
ranked team, accompanying it to tournaments and even playing
shortstop this year in a spring-training exhibition game against
the Anaheim Angels. Cal State-Fullerton lost, 2-1, when Costner
lost a pop fly. He made no other errors, handling hot grounders,
and pitching to two batters in the eighth inning. He struck out a
minor leaguer, then got Angels manager Terry Collins on a grounder
to end the inning. Costner says he fell in love with Fenway when he
visited it for ``Field of Dreams.'' It and another old inner-city
park, Chicago's Wrigley Field, are his favorites, he says.
</P>
<P>
   He did OK in the All-Star sideshow, sending a few balls to the
warning track. For Costner, a lifelong fan of baseball no less than
a lifelong fan of movies, the highlight of the All-Star weekend was
being in the presence of Ted Williams. ``I don't know what it is,''
he says. ``It's almost like voodoo to talk about it. But everybody
recognizes it when it happens. When you see him, there's immediate
nobility in him, and nobody has to put a sign behind it. You just
recognize it. We don't fool ourselves. We're never going to be like
these ballplayers. We really don't kid ourselves. We were never
them. I just try to get as much of it to come out right as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
