<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3188 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-GESTURE-BOS &LR;      09-07 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GESTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMAINS OF A LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
A GESTURE LIFE 
By Chang-rae Lee. Riverhead. 356 pp. $23.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No other position on the playing field of literature has quite
the perplexing allure as that of the unreliable narrator. We don't
trust the voice but are captivated by its deceits, whether
self-deluded or intentionally mendacious. Observing the imagined
world through this skewed (even pathological) perspective, we begin
to envision something wider _ the way things ought to be, or could
have been, or indeed were. Thus are we granted the bracing task of
playing gumshoe and Diogenes both: In wrestling with the
half-truths and garbled recollections of the narrator in charge, we
have to use our own creative skills to flush out the real story.
</P>
<P>
   Modern fiction's most famous literary liar is the valor-ridden
madman of Ford Madox Ford's ``The Good Soldier,'' though certainly
Vladimir Nabokov's Humbert Humbert, arriving a half-century later,
alerts us pretty quickly that he's up to equal mischief. More
recently, Kazuo Ishiguro achieved a different sort of pathos with
the muted tragedy of the butler in ``The Remains of the Day'': Only
after being swayed by the delicate control of the narrator's story
do we begin to glimpse his frailties. So it is with Chang-rae Lee's
beautifully realized second novel, which delivers the poignant
complexities of an elderly Japanese-American man with an exquisite
sense of mystery.
</P>
<P>
   If Lee's first novel, ``Native Speaker,'' possessed a similarly
taut restraint, he has imagined a story both deeper and sadder in
``A Gesture Life.'' Franklin Hata _ known as good Doc Hata to his
neighbors in the comfortable suburb of Bedley Run, N.Y. _ is a man
for whom propriety is everything. Duty is larger than love, or
certainly more tangible, in Hata's world; and honor, or the face of
it, will always outlive passion. Like Ishiguro's butler, he's an
existential yes-man, someone who steps quietly in the margins of
his own life. This circumspect stance has caused as much harm as
good, of course, however unintended: In trying never to leave a
mess or raise a fuss, Hata has come across as cold and unyielding _
posted eternally in some other country _ to those who need him
most.
</P>
<P>
   What gave Hata this curse of elusiveness is the story of ``A
Gesture Life,'' which opens in the present in Bedley Run and
returns intermittently to Hata's service as a medic in the Japanese
Army during the Second World War. Having recently sold the
surgical-supply store he ran for three decades, Hata is facing the
expanding time of retirement by swimming endless laps in his pool
and pestering the store's new owners. Reluctantly, he begins to
face the ghosts and consequences of a deliberately peripheral life:
memories of the good-hearted Mary Burns, a woman, now dead, whom he
chose not to marry, and of his adopted Korean daughter, Sunny, who
hasn't spoken to him in years. While Doc Hata has been a beacon of
good citizenship to the residents of Bedley Run, taking care always
to take care, he has hardly fared so well in his own matters of the
heart and soul.
</P>
<P>
   We learn these things piecemeal, first by Hata's tentative
explanations, then by other people's reactions to him. If the new
owner of Sunny Medical Supply resents him for their business
dealings, is it that the man blames Hata for the store's recent
failures, or for something worse? Did Sunny leave because she was a
wild, ungrateful adolescent, or did Hata's exasperating coolness
dismantle the very bond he was trying to sustain? Layers of secrecy
accrue even as others unfold in ``A Gesture Life,'' for Hata has
spent much of the last 50 years trying to shoehorn certain
realities into an acceptable narrative _ his version of the stories
we all tell ourselves in order to make bearable the things we can't
control.
</P>
<P>
   Or, in some cases, to make sense of a senseless world. The
extent to which Hata's present is defined by his past reveals
itself slowly but continually through his formal, nuanced rendering
of his story _ his rationalizations, modest confidences, impeccable
explanations. All the acts that have made up Hata's life in Bedley
Run have been agonizingly correct, and yet the emotional silence
that accompanies them is more frightening than any howl in the
night. Remembering Mary Burns, he notes with surprise her curious
quality of being emotionally linked to other people _ adding,
politely, that ``there is nothing inherently wrong with this.
Indeed, there was a time that I held my own associations quite
close to who I was, in the years leading up to and during the
Pacific war, when in the course of events one naturally accepted
the wartime culture of shared sacrifice and military codes of
conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   This chilling non sequitur _ from bonds of affection to wartime
conduct, with barely a comma in between _ suggests the mystery at
the center of Hata's story, or why he has chosen a circumscribed
life over a full-blooded one. The narrative's eventual return to
those war years _ to Hata's posting in Burma, to the Korean comfort
women he was assigned to attend, to ``the black fires of the past''
_ is both riveting and horrifying; in masterful understatement, Lee
has managed to capture an abyss of human experience with laconic
dignity. The war narrative makes up nearly half of ``A Gesture
Life,'' but any more detail here would diminish its effect. (For
the same reason, I'd advise readers to avoid reading the jacket
copy.) It was there that Hata came face to face with what he might
call the blight of destiny: his over-reliance, according to a cruel
commanding officer, ``upon generous fate and gesture.'' Then as
now, Hata realized the cost of that gesture life, where paralysis
looked like nobility and where love, in the face of evil, had no
chance at all.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of his story, Lee opts for a mirroring effect
between past and present that seems unnecessary as well as
heavy-handed, particularly in a work of such delicacy. But
otherwise ``A Gesture Life'' is a hugely affecting novel, both for
what it delivers and for what it evokes, which is a kind of carpe
diem cry against the sorrows of an empty landscape. Immersed in his
routine of insularities, Hata ruminates on another man swimming
away from his life in John Cheever's ``The Swimmer,'' one of the
all-time great allegories of alienation and flight. But unlike the
endless strokes of Cheever's swimmer, Hata's journey has more to do
with history than with myth. His story belongs instead to the realm
of tragic compromise _ that of a man trying to live a
paint-by-numbers life by staying, no matter what, just inside the
lines.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is the chief book critic of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
