<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3190 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-LONG-FIRM-BOS &LR;      09-07 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LONG-FIRM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BLOODY GOOD LOOK AT 1960S ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE LONG FIRM 
By Jake Arnott 
Soho Press, 345 pp., $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a nasty piece of work that Harry Starks is.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, he's a lot of other things, too. He's charming, loyal to his
friends, loves spoiling his mum. He likes a well-cut suit, does a
dead-on Ethel Merman imitation, and gets teary listening to his
recordings of Winston Churchill's wartime speeches. But you don't
get the moniker ``Mad Harry'' by being a choirboy _ not that anyone
would call him that to his face, especially if he wanted to keep
his own face intact.
</P>
<P>
   As Jake Arnott's strikingly original debut ``The Long Firm''
begins, Harry, with perfect Merman intonation, is singing ``There's
No Business Like Show Business.'' He's also twirling a menacing
white-hot poker in his hand, which he hopes will convince an
unfortunate young man tied to a chair to reveal the information
Harry seeks. The captive, we soon learn, is Terry, the first of
five narrators recalling the life and times of Harry Starks in this
hypnotically entertaining story of crime, crooks, and assorted
crazies in 1960s London.
</P>
<P>
   What makes ``The Long Firm'' so satisfying is Arnott's ease in
seasoning his fiction with real-life events and people, especially
the Krays. Reggie and Ronnie Kray, twin brothers, thrilled and
terrified London in the 1960s as the city's most notorious
gangsters. In the book, they are Harry's rivals, though Harry
shares Ronnie's taste for handsome young men. (``I'm homosexual but
I'm not gay,'' Harry asserts.) When a criminologist asks Harry for
his thoughts on Gay Liberation, he says, ``Well, someone once
called Ronnie Kray a fat poof. Ronnie took the top of his head off
with a Luger. That's my sort of Gay Liberation. Though, to be
honest, I think it was the fat part what got to him. Ron's, well,
touchy about his weight.''
</P>
<P>
   While he ruminates on the Krays, Harry is unveiled through the
eyes of a handful of people sucked into his orbit. Terry _ the one
tied to the chair _ meets Harry in a gay bar, and soon quits his
job to become Harry's kept boy. Of course, Terry knows what Harry
does for a living, and that his money isn't earned solely from his
nightclub, the Stardust. But Terry likes the finely tailored
clothes Harry buys him, and is seduced by his benefactor's
dangerous allure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an attractiveness that went with the fierceness. He
drew people close to him. He had a sort of threatening charisma
that made you want to be close to him, an aura that you could feel
safe within. A bit like those fish that swim right up close to the
shark, you felt protected being in his slipstream.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry soon learns that swimming with sharks can be a lethal
pursuit, as does Teddy Thursby, a corrupt aristocrat in the House
of Commons whom Harry plies with beautiful young men. Thursby may
be a fictional character, but the next narrator is not. Arnott
fearlessly imagines the last days of Jack ``The Hat'' McVitie, a
mob henchman who works for Harry and does the occasional job for
the Krays. Writing in Jack's voice, Arnott reveals a man losing
control, whose open contempt and defiance of the Krays would
eventually lead to his bloody demise.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the book is violent _ a young man is hacked up and stuffed
in suitcases, and faces explode in a hail of bullets _ but the
bloodletting never feels gratuitous: It's truthful to the era and
characters. Besides, Arnott doesn't need to rely on cheap shock
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   A brazenly confident writer, Arnott perfectly nails 1960s
England in all its contradictions. You can practically hear Judy
Garland singing an encore of ``Over the Rainbow'' at the London
Palladium, and smell the gunpowder from Ronnie Kray's pistol after
he capped George Cornell in the Blind Beggar pub.
</P>
<P>
   In this swaggering story, England (with apologies to Roger
Miller) does more than swing like a pendulum do. The Beatles are
fab, the Stones are gear, and Carnaby Street is the brightest star
in the fashion universe. But on the other side, the city's seedy
underbelly, there are the rentboys, the hookers, and the men
dressed in their Savile Row best who kill with precious little
provocation. The glamorous rub shoulders with goodfellas and goons
in a sort of warped mutual-admiration society. There are cops whose
vow to protect and serve can be bought and sold, and politicians
who use their powers for their own illicit gains.
</P>
<P>
   And at the center of it all is Mad Harry, a West End gangland
boss and nightclub owner with a taste for Tin Pan Alley tunes,
Bertrand Russell books, and myriad innovative means for breaking
those who cross him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
