<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3215 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-07 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS COACHES YOUNG PRODIGIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Jim Payton could barely sleep the night before,
could barely keep his heart in his chest on the ride over to
Harding Park's golf course Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept thinking: I'm going to get a lesson from Tiger Woods, I
can't believe it,'' said Payton, who at 16 is rarely a victim of
nerves.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time Tiger came up to him on the driving range,
Payton's confidence had made a huge comeback. ``I can beat you,
Tiger,'' he told the superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Woods had a comeback of his own. ``I don't think so,'' he
corrected the cheeky teen-ager, in just the right tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That `I don't think so,''' Payton said later, ``was pretty
funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods held one of his junior golf clinics in San Francisco on
Labor Day. Accompanying him were his sense of humor, his
entrepreneurial father, Earl, and the touch of a true teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry about them,'' he told Jamila Ward, a 16-year-old
Oakland girl overwhelmed by a phalanx of cameras recording her
every stroke. ``Just listen to the sound of my voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Tiger arrived at her tee, Ward was overwhelmed by all of
the attention from the media. She couldn't concentrate. Her drives
barely left the ground. Then Woods showed up, and immediately she
began hitting balls in long, graceful arcs. He had either put her
at ease or driven her adrenaline to performance-enhancing highs.
</P>
<P>
   Ward would hit a ball, and Tiger would gently push another one
in front of her. When she dug up too much dirt, he tapped her club
clean with his own. Dressed like an elegant squire in gray wool
pants, a black sweater and black golf shoes designed like
wing-tips, Woods was utterly at the service of these youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   He replaced balls for them, shook all of their hands, tapped a
couple on the posterior with his club as friendly encouragement,
put Payton in his place and doled out flattery where appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoa, I don't hit it that far,'' he joked when Howard Oliver,
a broad-chested San Jose State freshman from Oakland, belted one
down the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Like Jamila Ward, Oliver had been hitting stray balls until
Tiger came by to watch him. Then the shaking stopped, and the
drives started soaring.
</P>
<P>
   Had he been nervous on those early shots? ``That,'' he said,
``and my hands were cold.''
</P>
<P>
   The clinic took place on the gray side of San Francisco. So
while most Americans spent their holiday under the sun, throwing
back drinks and grilling burgers, the world's most famous golfer
labored in a chill.
</P>
<P>
   This was the fifth and final clinic of the year for the Tiger
Woods Foundation. They started three years ago, shortly after he
left Stanford University to turn professional.
</P>
<P>
   This clinic was crisply organized by a bunch of efficient
volunteers. (Why couldn't these people have been at the Atlanta
Olympics?) Only one thing threw them off schedule: Tiger spent too
much time with the kids.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of these events are bogus affairs. The star puts in a
short appearance, then bows out and lets his minions do the real
work. But Tiger spoke to a large group of novices at the beginning
of the day, then spent more than 1 1/2 hours checking the swings of
about a dozen top junior players.
</P>
<P>
   The players had been selected for the clinic by their local golf
organizations, and they were evaluated again by an executive for
the Tiger Woods Foundation. The organizers want to be sure they
find the juniors who can benefit the most from Tiger's advice.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all of the young students come from ethnic groups
historically excluded from golf, children very much like Woods.
</P>
<P>
   When he first became a professional, and just as quickly became
a phenomenon, everyone promised that he would broaden the appeal of
golf, reaching out to a new generation.
</P>
<P>
   For Jim Payton, that's exactly what happened two Aprils ago,
when he watched Woods win the Masters in a record 18-under par.
</P>
<P>
   He was a tennis player at the time, but the morning after he
went to the driving range. Ever since, he has been saving space in
his closet for a green jacket like the one Woods won at Augusta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Tiger and said, `OK, I'll break that record,
20-under,''' said Payton, whose golf association flew him in from
Las Vegas for the day. In just two years he has become a star,
shooting as low as 61 at a public course in Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   When the clinic ended, Brandi Chastain, the star of the Women's
World Cup final, stopped by to say hello to her fellow Nike
endorser.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger chatted for a few minutes, but he still had a packed
itinerary in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation awarded two plaques to community leaders Alma
Jackson and Gaylon Logan, who gave two of his nonprofit group's
T-shirts to Tiger and his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't pay you $10 million to wear them,'' Logan said,
bringing a huge grin to the face of Woods, the 23-year-old
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Earl Woods unveiled plans for a new PGA event,
organized by the Woods Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Held over New Year's weekend, it will feature the top 10 golfers
in the world, plus two players to be named. They will compete for a
top prize of $1 million. In the middle of the 72 holes, on New
Year's Eve, the tournament will break for a pro-am, which the Woods
family hopes will include Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   As Earl Woods made the announcement, Tiger teased him for
confusing the dates. ``He's getting old,'' the son said into a
microphone, earning a bemused stare from dad. Later, Tiger gave his
father's shoulders a quick rub. He still had a celebrity auction
and a driving exhibition on his schedule. A 23-year-old franchise's
work is never done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
