<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VIACOM-CBS &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the acquisition of CBS by Viacom.
</P>
<P>
   VIACOM-CBS (New York) _ Ledeall: Viacom Inc., owner of MTV,
Nickelodeon and the Paramount movie studio, will buy CBS for $34.86
billion in stock, in the largest media acquisition ever. Viacom,
the fourth-biggest media company, will swap 1.085 of its Class B
shares for each share of CBS, or $48.89 a share, close to CBS's
closing price Friday. Sumner Redstone, 76, will be chairman and
chief executive of the new company, to be called Viacom. Mel
Karmazin will be president and chief operating officer and all
operations will report to him. By Lawrie Mifflin and Steve Lohr.
(1650 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   VIACOM-PROFILES (Undated) _ Profiles of Sumner Redstone and Mel
Karmazin, the two outsized personalties at the center of this deal.
By Alex Kuczynski. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   VIACOM-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ A look at the financial details
of the deal and the possibility of a bid from outside. By Floyd
Norris. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   VIACOM-CULTURES (Undated) _ Looking at the fate of CBS News and
CBS Sports, media institutions occupying a small niche in a mammoth
company. By Felicity Barringer. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   VIACOM-REGULATE (Washington) _ The regulatory issues involved in
this combination. By Stephen Labarton.
</P>
<P>
   VIACOM-REACT (Los Angeles) _ Reaction from the entertainment
industry, including film, television and radio. By Bernard
Weinraub. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   VIACOM-NEW-MEDIA (Undated) _ How the companies' new media
ventures are performing. By Saul Hansell. (650 words)
</P>
<P>
   How the new Viacom sizes up against the other media behemoths.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-UNREST (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ Developments in
violence-wracked East Timor. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-U.N. (United Nations) _ Security Council meets to consider
possible action on East Timor. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-U.S. (Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam) _ In the heart of the
old Saigon, on the site where the American ambassador fled by
helicopter from his embassy roof 24 years ago, the new United
States consulate was dedicated today, the symbol of a new but
unsure relationship of old enemies still trying to be friends. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-HEALTH (Los Angeles) _ Vice President Al Gore lays out his
vision of a health policy for the nation today, a combination of
new steps to guarantee access to affordable health insurance for
all children, even as he acknowledges that the number of Americans
without coverage had increased steadily since he and President
Clinton took office. By Robert Pear. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   QUAYLE-CAMPAIGN (Goffstown, N.H.) _ These days, Dan Quayle,
whose slingshot career allowed him to glimpse the heights and
depths of American politics before he turned 45, would seem to be
at the bottom of his personal trajectory. Yet he perseveres, with a
poignant tenacity that he and friends say is grounded in a dogged
belief in the possibility of his own political success and
redemption. By Adam Nagourney. Another in the Contenders 2000
series.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FORD-DOCUMENTS (Detroit) _ A federal court rules that Ford
cannot prevent an Internet newspaper from publishing internal Ford
documents, such as designs for new cars. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-HARASS (Chicago) _ Ford agrees to an $18 million sexual and
racial harassment settlement in a suit from workers at an assembly
plant in Chicago. Women will get $8 million and $10 million will be
set aside for training.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDEN-POND (Holderness, N.H.) _ After years of angry debate,
land deals gone sour, charges of landowner elitism and state
threats to take lakeside property by eminent domain, the state has
acquired its first public access for a boat launch in the small
channel that connects Little Squam Lake and Big Squam Lake, the
``pond'' made famous by the 1980 movie that starred Henry and Jane
Fonda and Catherine Hepburn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   VITAMIN-PRICE-FIXING (Chicago) _ The expected settlement of the
lawsuit alleging price fixing in the vitamin industry has been
expanded to cover six European and Japanese vitamin makers, which
are expected to pay more than $1.1 billion. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   MARINEAU-LEVI (Undated) _ Philip Marineau resigns as president
of Pepsico's North American beverage unit and will become chief
executive of Levi Strauss &AMP; Company. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   MARINEAU-PEPSI (Undated) _ Marineau's departure is a blow for
Pepsico and triggers a wave of executive reassignments. By
Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   HILTON-PROMUS (Undated) _ Hilton Hotels, the fifth-largest U.S.
hotel chain, agreed to buy Promus Hotel for about $4 billion to
give it hotels in almost all price ranges and reduce its reliance
on upscale, big-city hotels. Hilton will pay $38.50 a share in cash
or stock. Hilton, based in Beverly Hills, is headed by Stephen F.
Bollenbach, who was formerly chief financial officer at Promus. By
Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:55 p.m., the Dow industrial average was
down 6 points, and the Nasdaq index was up 11 points. Elsewhere,
prices slipped 0.3 percent in Tokyo and rose 0.1 percent in Hong
Kong. They fell 0.2 percent in Frankfurt, dropped 1 percent in
London, rose 0.3 percent in Brazil and plunged 2.5 percent in
Mexico. On the American debt market, the long bond at midday was
down 18/32 point, with the yield at 6.06 percent. By Kenneth N.
Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST-UNION-PENSION (Undated) _ Federal law requires that
corporate retirement plans be operated solely for the benefit of
workers, but First Union Corp., owner of the nation's sixth largest
bank, was accused in a lawsuit of scheming to profit from its
401(k) plan at the expense of its workers. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The Business Travel column. By Edwin
McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CREDIT (Mexico City) _ Two of the biggest American credit
reporting companies, the Trans Union Corp. of Chicago and Equifax
Inc. of Atlanta, are at work building files and computer systems in
Mexico that will give bankers here the same instantaneous credit
profiles that bankers in New York and Miami and Los Angeles take
for granted. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-OIL (Moscow) _ BP Amoco has tentatively agreed to hand
over its creditor's rights to the Russian oil company Sidanko to
the Russian government, apparently hoping to preserve its $500
million investment in the Russian company rather than pressing for
liquidation. By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Thomas L. Friedman's ``Foreign Affairs'' and Maureen Dowd's
``Liberties.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET _ A rundown of culture, lifestyle, sports, and
special section stories will move by 3:00 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-PAGE1-NYT-CONSIDER _ A list of stories being considered by
New York Times editors for Page 1 will move at 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ Stories scheduled for Page 1 will be
listed by 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
