<P>
   Food and dining stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Wednesday, Sept. 8:
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ The weekly wine column: All over the
world, but especially in Italy, winemakers are reaching back to
ancient grapes, in some cases varieties that had all but
disappeared. From the banks of the Rhine to the tip of the Italian
boot, from Southern France to the distant vineyards of Chile,
winemakers are rediscovering their heritage, and in doing so are
adding color and excitement to the world of wine. By Frank J.
Prial.
</P>
<P>
   The revival of ancient vines, especially in Italy
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY-RESTAURANTS (New York) _ I used to eat at home on
Sundays. But the need to dine out constantly has disrupted my
pattern _ and opened my eyes. I now routinely eat out on Sundays,
and a creeping suspicion is growing into something like a firm
conviction: for diners, Sunday is not a good bet. At restaurant
after restaurant, I have detected a slackening off, a lack of
luster, a sag and a droop on Sundays. A critic's notebook by
William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   OCTOPUS (Undated) _ Raw octopus resting on ice at the seafood
store is definitely the ugliest thing in the vicinity, a floppy,
gray, suction-cupped monster that seems to have been born with a
natural defense aimed directly at the home cook. ``I am,'' it
growls, ``too hideous to eat.'' And yet, once the octopus is
cooked, it is beautiful _ tender and mild, with just a touch of
pleasant resistance, like lobster. Lately, as its qualities are
increasingly appreciated, it has assumed a starring role at many
restaurants in unexpected dishes. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: Super-easy steamed fish
with olive oil. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   SOYBEANS (Undated) _ The joys of edamame, fresh soybeans in
season. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (Undated) _ The column: Summer succotash. By Waldy
Malouf.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   GENE-EATING-WELL (Undated) _ Americans may slowly be awakening
to the encroachment of genetically engineered food. By Marian
Burros.
</P>
<P>
   ETROG (Undated) _ Observant Jews who follow the biblical
commandment of reciting a prayer over ``the fruit of goodly trees''
for Succoth, the harvest celebration, sometimes use a magnifying
glass to choose the finest etrog. This thick-skinned citrus fruit,
which looks like a large lemon and tastes like an especially bitter
one, is thought by some to have been the true forbidden fruit in
the Garden of Eden. By Joan Nathan.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TASTING (Undated) _ A capsule wine review.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Food and dining questions answered. By
Melissa Clark.
</P>
