<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERFECT-SAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT WITH PERFECT SAT SCORE GETS BOOST FROM LATIN, PARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RICK KARLIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ For Martina Hurwitz, who scored a
perfect 1600 on her SATs (800 each in math and verbal), preparing
for the exam was like a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have some real fun,'' Dan Hurwitz, a mathematics
professor at Skidmore College, said of how he helped his daughter
study for the SATs when she was a Saratoga Springs High School
student.
</P>
<P>
   Martina would review math problems with her father and she'd
pick apart the nuances in written passages of the verbal exam with
her mother, Regina Hartmann-Hurwitz, who is an adjunct professor of
linguistics at Skidmore.
</P>
<P>
   One thing she didn't do, Martina Hurwitz said, was take one of
those high-priced preparation courses. Instead, she purchased a
work book of old exams. That way, Hurwitz said, she was able to
focus on the knowledge and reasoning skills needed for the exam,
rather than test-taking strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and it helped that Hurwitz now a freshman at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, studied Latin, which
facilitated quick answers to the vocabulary questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are aiming for the SATs, Latin is a tremendous help,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Most students won't come close to a perfect score, but for a
growing number nationally, the SAT, a standardized exam used to
help choose college applicants, is a teen-age rite of passage.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they graduated from high school in June, some 1.2
million students took the exam. The makeup of exam takers is
growing increasingly diverse. Along with that, ethnic and gender
gaps remain, according to the College Board, which administers the
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the average verbal score for males was 509 compared
to 502 for women, with average math scores at 531 for males
compared to 495 for women.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the average score was 505 verbal and 511 math _ up just
a bit from last year's average of 504 verbal and 502 math.
</P>
<P>
   And while the latest crop of SAT-takers comes from homes where
the parents are better educated than ever, the scores remain
significantly lower than those of earlier generations. Average math
scores are six points below those of 1969, with verbal scores 35
points lower _ even after the entire scoring scale was
``re-centered,'' or curved to accommodate a lower achievement level
in the early 1990s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
