<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSH-HASHANAH-SUFFERING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSH HASHANAH AND GOD'S SUFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By RABBI ELI HECHT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    It's Rosh Hashanah again. The Jewish New Year arrives on Friday
night and Jews will mark the calendar year 5760 since creation.
 &HT;    Many Jewish families will meet at prayer services and ask God
for a blessed year. At least one meal will include the customary
apple dipped in honey, symbolizing the hope for a sweet year.
 &HT;    With the holiday spirit comes some serious thinking. Why is
there so much suffering? We continue to be puzzled and shocked with
the needless shootings and killings at schools and workplaces.
Innocent children and adults are being hurt by madmen. We think,
whatever happened to God?
 &HT;    True, there are acts of God like fires and earthquakes for which
there is no understanding, but it's man's contribution to suffering
that troubles me.
 &HT;    For answers, I look at traditional Jewish writings. In the
Talmud (Megillah 29a) there is a statement: ``Wherever the Jews
were exiled, God, Divine Presence, accompanied them. When they will
return to the Holy Land, God will return with them.''
 &HT;    This means that God is with His people. Whatever happens to His
people affects God.
 &HT;    It would be correct to state that if people suffer, then God,
the Divine Presence, suffers.
 &HT;    Now the question should not be why do we suffer, but why should
God have to suffer? We experience bad things and God suffers with
us. Why?
 &HT;    In God's master plan for humankind there are provisions made for
accountability. God creates the world, then man is placed in it and
given the freedom of choice to enhance or destroy it. Think for a
moment, of the three basic things we need for existence -- water,
air and bread. Of the three, two are free and bread is an
inexpensive foods that is readily available.
 &HT;    How has humankind done with the two free gifts? Not so well. We
have poisoned the air and polluted the water. Thank God that bread
is still available.
 &HT;    Instead of taking advantage of the pure water and clean air, we
have been steadily destroying those vital gifts. How God must
suffer seeing the abuse.
 &HT;    On Rosh Hashanah, God created man. Our ancestor Adam accepted
the responsibilities of caretaker of the Earth for God. We, his
children, are responsible to care for this Earth, and each other,
in accordance with the Noachide Laws.
 &HT;    A story is told of an ancient house of prayer in Europe that
possessed an eerie sound. When entering the prayer room, you would
hear a continuous sobbing. The closer one would walk to the ark,
the stronger the sobbing was heard.
 &HT;    The old caretaker (shamus) would tell of a story he had heard
from the older shamus relating to the phenomenon dating back
hundreds of years:
 &HT;    There lived a saintly man, a tzadik, who prayed and fasted all
his life. The saint was as close to an angel as possible. One night
while in deep prayer, he heard God's voice calling to him. ``My
son, tell me what you need and I will grant it.''
 &HT;    The saintly man thought and thought. ``I have clothing to wear,
my health is good and I have a place to pray. I don't need money.
Nothing, dear God,'' the saintly man answered.
 &HT;    There was a silence and then a loud sob. Thundering and
lightning was heard outside. God's voice boomed out. ``Why did you
think of yourself, you should have thought of me. How I suffer for
My people, for mankind, and justice for the poor and needy. Why did
you not think of my suffering? Why did you not ask that my
suffering cease?''
 &HT;    The saintly man realized his sin and was too troubled to speak.
From that day on he grew weaker and weaker. On his deathbed he told
his most trusted students his tragic story. From that day on, when
entering the prayer room you could hear the sobbing, as if the
prayer room was crying about God's suffering and the lost
opportunity.
 &HT;    So, this New Year by all means enjoy yourself and family, dip
some apple in honey, pray for a good year and most of all pray for
an end of suffering: your suffering, my suffering and, most of all,
God's suffering.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    c.1999 Rabbi Eli Hecht
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Rabbi Eli Hecht is vice president of the Rabbinical Alliance of
America and past president of the Rabbinical Council of California.
He is the director of Chabad of South Bay in Lomita, Calif. and
writes a monthly Op-Ed column for the Long Beach Press-Telegeam.)
</P>
</TEXT>
