<SLUG> BC-TELEPHONE-FRAUD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEPHONES BECOME A TOOL FOR THIEVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIN McCORMICK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``Thank you for your recent purchase with Adult
Fantasies Online ToyStore. Your credit card transaction (for
$249.98) has been approved,'' said the mysterious electronic mail
message, versions of which went to more than 85,000 Americans over
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The message, sent randomly to people who had never placed
orders, urged customers with questions to call a number in the 767
area code.
</P>
<P>
   But when recipients called to protest erroneous charges, the
number connected them to a sex hot line in Dominica, in the West
Indies, and automatically added a whopping toll charge to their
phone bills.
</P>
<P>
   The scam, halted by the Federal Trade Commission in May, was
just one in an epidemic of telephone fraud that consumer watchdogs
say is bilking Americans out of millions of dollars each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some con artists have found the telephone billing and
collection system to be a fertile area to defraud consumers,'' the
Federal Trade Commission said in a report released this summer.
``Taking advantage of changes in the telecommunications industry
that began 15 years ago with the breakup of AT&AMP;T, these stealth
`operators' are arranging to put charges on a consumer's phone bill
for services that were never ordered, authorized, received or
used.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates say the problem is a side-effect of two
telecommunications trends of the '90s: deregulation of the
telephone industry and proliferation of companies that sell
information over phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   The new market has essentially turned your phone bill into a
credit card account that can be used by thousands of companies to
bill for services such as pay-per-view movies and monthly club
membership fees, sometimes when you didn't order them.
</P>
<P>
   This has opened the door to abuses so high-tech and so subtle
that many victims may not realize they're being ripped off at all.
Unscrupulous companies have left urgent messages on answering
machines telling people to call a number in the 809 area code to
get news of a sick relative or to stop cancellation of their credit
card account. The calls are routed to the Dominican Republic,
callers are kept on hold, and charges of up to $25 per minute are
billed to their phone accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard of them charging huge amounts,'' said Linda Woods,
consumer affairs manager for the California Public Utilities
Commission. ``They can charge you whatever toll they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Some companies run scams to bill unsuspecting customers for
calls to 800 or 888 phone numbers that would usually be toll free.
One California man returned a page from an 888 area code number,
was put on hold for four minutes and then got a $45 dollar charge
tagged onto his phone bill, according to the National Consumer
League, a Washington, D.C.-based nonprofit organization.
</P>
<P>
   Scam artists can do this by tricking callers into pressing 1 to
authorize the billing or essentially transferring consumer calls to
pay-per-call numbers without permission, according to the FTC.
</P>
<P>
   One notorious example of creative phone billing was a modem
hijacking scheme broken up by the FTC in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   According to the FTC's charges, Internet users who logged on to
World Wide Web sites with names like www.sexygirls.com and
www.erotic2000.com were urged to download a free computer program
that would give them access to nude pictures. Once the consumers
downloaded the program, however, it took over their computers,
disconnected from their Internet service and silently dialed a
phone number in the former Soviet Republic of Moldova. It then left
their phones connected to the international toll number until they
turned their computers off, sometimes causing them to run up
$2-a-minute charges for hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some instances, people were billed hundreds or thousands of
dollars,'' said Eileen Harrington of the FTC. ``They had no idea
they were connected to an international phone line.''
</P>
<P>
   The FTC filed charges against the principals of two New York
companies allegedly responsible for the scam. A settlement included
agreement that 38,000 customers be reimbursed for $2.7 million in
unauthorized long-distance charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
