<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUDSON VALLEY SUCCOTASH 
</HEADLINE>
  This is the last of eight columns by Waldy Malouf, the chef and an
owner of Beacon in Manhattan. His collaborator on these columns has
been Melissa Clark. Next week: Amy Scherber, the owner of Amy's
Bread in Manhattan. 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes, a good dish is really just a lucky accident. I
stumbled on the idea for my Hudson Valley succotash several summers
ago, while I was working on a cookbook. My co-author, Molly Finn,
and I had bought bags and bags of fresh vegetables at the farmers'
market and were developing recipes.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, we were surrounded. There were bowls full
of roasted corn and dappled cranberry beans, which we had cooked
earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of perfectly ripe tomatoes. And as usual when recipes
are being developed, there was also plenty of leftover chopped
onion _ in this case, sweet red onions and scallions.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of all these ingredients, I immediately thought
about making a succotash. But I was tired after cooking all day,
and our families were hungry. They were so hungry, in fact, that
they descended on the bowls of vegetables and started nibbling.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Molly and I gave up on the idea of cooking
anything else, and we all began to fill our plates. What had been
just a table full of individual vegetables was turning into a
communal feast _ an instant, self-serve succotash.
</P>
<P>
   We each scooped up exactly the combination of ingredients we
wanted. Since the late-summer vegetables were so intensely flavored
that they really didn't need any fancy dressing or preparation. It
was perfect as it was.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this succotash starts out like every other, with a
base of beans and corn, cooked separately and simply with water,
salt and butter. But everything else is left raw; the onions and
scallions contribute a sweet crunch, and as for the tomatoes, well,
in September, it seems like a crime to do anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since that summer, I've served this succotash when I could
get good, seasonal vegetables and felt like taking a day off.
There's hardly any cooking involved, and even that can be done
several hours ahead. Otherwise, the vegetables are left alone. And
so is the cook.
</P>
<P>
   HUDSON VALLEY SUCCOTASH
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   6 ears corn, shucked
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh shelled cranberry beans (1{ pounds in the pod)
</P>
<P>
   3 medium tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped basil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped red onion
</P>
<P>
   } cup chopped scallions
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring large pot of water to a boil. Add corn, and cook for 3
minutes. Drain corn, reserving \ cup cooking liquid. Let corn cool,
and then cut ears in half crosswise. Cut kernels off by standing a
half ear up on a cutting board on its flat (cut) end and scraping
off kernels with a knife. Reserve corn kernels and cooking liquid
until ready to serve. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Bring medium saucepan of water to a boil. Add beans, and cook
for about 12 to 15 minutes, or until tender. Drain beans, reserving
1 cup cooking liquid. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Cut tomatoes in half crosswise, and remove seeds. Cut
tomatoes into {-inch dice. Toss them in bowl with olive oil, basil
and salt and pepper. Put red onions and scallions in separate
serving bowls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. When ready to serve, place beans, their reserved cooking
liquid and 2 tablespoons butter in a small saucepan. Cook over
medium heat until butter melts. Season to taste with salt and
pepper. Transfer to a serving bowl. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. Place corn, its reserved cooking liquid and remaining butter
in a small saucepan. Cook over medium heat until butter melts.
Season to taste with salt and pepper. Transfer to a serving bowl. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6. Serve bowls of vegetables while beans and corn are still
warm. Let people mix ingredients on their plates as they wish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1611EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
