<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3331 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      09-07 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEAMING FILL FILLETS BY THE CLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARK BITTMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you have forgotten how delicious a great fillet of fish can
be, try this: Steam it, with nothing on it. Drizzle it with olive
oil and lemon juice. Sprinkle it with coarse salt. Eat.
</P>
<P>
   The number of ingredients and the technique may be minimal, but
the challenge is not. The fish has to be pristine, the timing
precise and the olive oil flavorful. Good salt helps, too.
</P>
<P>
   But there really is no better or easier preparation. This
technique works beautifully not only with cod but with red snapper,
grouper, striped bass, sea bass, halibut and even mackerel.
Steaming is such a fast technique that thin fillets inevitably
overcook and fall apart. So flounder is out, as are small fillets
from most fish. The best thickness for steaming is about an inch.
</P>
<P>
   Few fillets are of uniform thickness, though. For example, cod
fillets have a very thick end and a very thin end. So just fold the
thin end over onto itself to approximate the density of the thick
end.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have an Asian bamboo steamer, you may have to
jury-rig a steamer. I use a large, oval casserole with a rack that
fits inside that was actually designed for roasting meat. But since
the rack sits only about a quarter of an inch above the bottom, I
elevate it above the water by resting it on a couple of glass
ramekins.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is timing. Check the fish often _ taking care not
to scald yourself when removing the steamer's lid _ and take it out
the instant a thin-bladed knife meets no resistance when poking the
flesh.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLEST STEAMED FISH
</P>
<P>
   Total time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds cod or other fillet, in two pieces, or 1 large halibut
steak
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Juice of { lemon
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Put at least 1 inch of water in the bottom of a steamer,
cover and bring to a boil. Lay the fish on the steamer's rack,
making sure the rack is elevated above the water, and cover again.
Steam 4 to 8 minutes, or until the fish is done. (A good-size
halibut steak may take 10 or even 12 minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   2. Remove the fish to a warm platter and drizzle with olive oil
and lemon juice. Cut into serving portions, sprinkle with coarse
salt and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3328 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-CHILDREN09-     09-07 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-CHILDREN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Botanical garden's new children's attraction a joyous
exploration
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Sept. 9.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The arbored bridge is more than just a link to the
Atlanta Botanical Garden's latest attraction. The granite span
joins two worlds that have grown increasingly apart _ those of
children and adults.
</P>
<P>
   It not only connects with its new children's garden, which opens
next week, but also a techno-crazed generation of kids with a
waning appreciation of nature.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-acre Children's Healthcare of Atlanta Children's Garden is
chock full of exhibits aimed at teaching kids how plants contribute
to their sense of wellness _ a balance of body, mind and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is wonderful. It's so interactive,'' said Mary Swinn,
touring the site with daughters Emily, 3, and Rachel, 1, during a
preview last month. ``I think there's a big demand for this kind of
activity, and the kids seem to be really enjoying it.''
</P>
<P>
   The brightly colored sculptures, giant treehouse and bullfrog
pond are sure bets for luring kids into the garden. But once there,
the ``wellness'' theme may be tough lesson to comprehend. To help
them understand, the garden is designed around the idea of how
plants contribute to our abilities to ``live, laugh and learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon entering the botanical garden's gates, visitors will cross
the Flower Bridge and be greeted by the Green Man, a stylized
sculpture of the legendary mythological father of nature. To the
right is the new Trustees Court, another aspect of the garden's
ongoing five-year expansion. To the left, a giant Sunflower
Fountain beckons kids to the children's garden, a $3 million
project developed in partnership with Children's Healthcare,
formerly known as Egleston Scottish Rite Children's Health Care
System.
</P>
<P>
   The garden, designed for preschoolers through fifth-graders,
features a dozen interactive exhibits. Some concepts are obvious;
others call for a little head scratching. Not to worry: Signs
explain the ideas, and docents will be on hand to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   Kids, wear your swimsuits if you want to be showered by the cool
octopus-like Sunflower Fountain. Or you can bypass it and head for
the first stop, the Caterpillar Maze _ a ``laugh'' exhibit.
``Plants really lift our spirits, and especially the ones that
attract butterflies,'' said Cindy Reittinger, the botanical
garden's education director.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the gaping mouth of a red caterpillar, visitors travel
through its body en route to understanding how it forms a chrysalis
and finally, a butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   Next, to show how plants provide the air needed for breathing,
there's the Air Factory, a plant into which kids can go. After
watering the roots with an old hand pump, they follow the stream
into the stem and flower head, where speakers planted inside the
leaves emit sounds of inhaling; pinwheels housed in the flowers
exhale, illustrating how plants give off oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   Learning is as much fun as laughing and living at this garden.
Beatrix Potter's ``Tale of Peter Rabbit'' proves an ideal backdrop
for illustrating what plants can teach. ``The story takes place in
a garden, many generations know it, and it's a tale kids love,''
Reittinger said. There's a hollow tree trunk, where children can
huddle inside, and Mr. MacGregor's garden, where they can learn
about vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite exhibit of children who previewed the garden was the
Dinosaur Garden, illustrating how long plants have been around.
``We talked to a paleontologist to find out which dinosaurs lived
in Georgia, and found there were three,'' Reittinger said.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit includes a gingko tree, a large tree fossil from a
West Virginia coal mine and a bed where kids can dig for five
conveniently buried fossils. ``Look! I found another one,''
3-year-old Jones Maynard exclaimed while checking out the garden.
</P>
<P>
   A Creek Indian house, made of Georgia red clay and river cane,
exemplifies how Native Americans used plants, while a garden called
Grandma's Roots features plants that have been passed down through
generations.
</P>
<P>
   Passing through the door to Grandma's house, visitors enter a
contemporary exhibit of Every Day Plants, which shows their many
uses, often taken for granted. Dresser drawers spill with clothes
made of cotton, and fabricated sheep, which produce wool, graze on
grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our goals is unstructured play outdoors, not indoors in
front of the TV or computer,'' Reittinger said. ``Before children
can begin to care about the environment, they have to experience
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The garden provides that in its Bee Hive Meadow, where thousands
of live bees fly in and out while foraging among for food; the
Soggy Bog, where children are shown how conservation efforts have
rescued endangered plant species; and the Bullfrog Pond and
waterfall, ideal for doing pond studies.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Woodland, er, Treehouse, built on stilts to
avoid harming two 130-year-old trees, dubbed Grandfather and
Grandmother Oak. ``There was a lot of discussion about this exhibit
because we didn't want to damage their roots, so we built the
treehouse to the side,'' Reittinger said. ``We use the trees to
talk about what Atlanta was like before the Civil War.''
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of talking, there will be plenty of that on
Saturday mornings at a new amphitheater, where parents and children
can take advantage of a new round of educational programs offered
Sept. 25 through Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing, whether it's at home or in a public garden,''
Reittinger said, ``is for parents and children to discover nature
together.''
</P>
<P>
   I F Y O U G O
</P>
<P>
   Children's garden grand opening
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When: Atlanta Botanical Garden members, 9 a.m.-7 p.m.
Wednesday and Sept. 16; public, 9 a.m.-8 p.m., Sept. 17-19
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where: Near entrance to Atlanta Botanical Garden, 1345
Piedmont Ave. N.E.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cost: Regular garden admission (adults, $7; seniors, $5;
children 3 and older, $4)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For more information: 404-876-5859
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
