<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3330 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE09-COX     09-07 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Take the plunge, and water lily puts on a show
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Sept. 9.
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For all my gardening life, I had been content without
waterlilies. Even after I began ponding in the mid-1990s, I
eschewed the lilies. Instead, I put various water plants in the
pond over the years, growing one after another, including
horsetail, cattail, hyacinth, canna, arrowhead, rush, papyrus _
even the eager little duckweed. But no waterlilies.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I admired them greatly, often joining other visitors to
marvel at the Atlanta Botanical Garden's incredible Victoria lily,
whose pads grow to the size of royal umbrellas. So large they
invite you to walk on them, sit on them and float lazily across the
pond.
</P>
<P>
   Too, many gardener friends grew lilies, including John and
Charlotte Taylor of Rockport, Mass., who photographed theirs _
pinkish blooms floating atop dark water _ and gave Lyn two framed
pictures 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As evocative as those photographs always have been, as much as I
loved looking at waterlilies here and there, still I did not go
rushing to buy them. It wasn't time. Recently, the time came.
</P>
<P>
   Gardening is funny that way: You enjoy a plant for years, but
not enough to want to grow it. Then, one day, you just have to have
it for your own. That has happened to me time after time. With
plants ranging from abelia to asparagus fern. Once I start, I don't
want to stop. So it is with the waterlily.
</P>
<P>
   In all these cases, there is a common thread that reels me in:
the cumulative weight of having seen and loved these plants in
other gardens for so many years; sooner or later, a good plant is
going to get you. But, also, there must be some ``trigger'' that
sets me off, sending me from contented admirer to aspiring grower.
</P>
<P>
   The trigger this summer doubtless was the dry and fiery weather
that made water plants more and more attractive _ a cool
counterpoint to the heat's unrelenting drumbeat. By July, when so
much of my garden was flaming out, I had to have more water plants,
even if they provided only the illusion of relief.
</P>
<P>
   So I bought a dwarf reed and put it into a brass container,
perching the ensemble atop a grouping of stones. That was OK, but
not cool enough.
</P>
<P>
   Of course: a waterlily. There's something about a waterlily that
kicks the garden's temperature down a notch. The foliage certainly
helps. The notched leaves floating on water transport you to a cool
glade where chilly-skinned frogs hop from pad to pool _ and back
again.
</P>
<P>
   My first waterlily is a dwarf. In my postage-stamp-size garden,
only a dwarf would do. It came in a plastic pot of primeval muck. I
put the whole thing into a brass container and placed it in the
wide-open sun on the back porch, where it would get at least seven
hours of light daily. And I waited.
</P>
<P>
   As the temperatures soared, the little lily struggled mightily
to adapt to its new home in a container _ at 14 inches deep, a bit
shallower than its old one at the nursery. After a week or so, its
several buds did burst into flower, yellow with orange stamens.
Surrounded by egg-sized leaves, mottled brown and green, the
blooms, about the size of half-dollars, floated on the surface of
the water (indicating it is hardy; tropical blossoms typically
stand above the water line).
</P>
<P>
   After that initial show, the lily went into decline _ and no
wonder, given the shallow container that was a virtual cooking pot
(never mind that a foot of water was supposed to suffice).
</P>
<P>
   Trying to bring the plant back, I put it in a deeper (24-inch)
container, amputated most of its leaves and fed it a tablespoon of
blood meal. By last week, many new leaves had appeared _ followed
by a single, exceptional bloom.
</P>
<P>
   Like the others before it, this long-stemmed blossom began
rising from beneath the water's surface around noon, a tight bud
that soon started unfurling its pointed petals and by midafternoon
was fully flowered. After a few hours the lily reversed the
process, closing its petals and sinking below the water surface _
to become a bud again. This delicate performance would be repeated
for several days before the bloom would die, to be replaced by
others _ many others, I hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Such a show. More precious for its transience.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the little lily with its lone blossom is like a
bonsai, representing a larger scene in nature. I looked at the
blossom, a colorful exclamation point for the mottled leaves, and
saw a huge pond with frogs resting on pads big and strong enough
for me to walk on.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, somewhere, I may have that big pond with the big, regal
Victoria foliage and flowers. For now, I must have a few more
dwarfs. The little pond needs one; the goldfish would enjoy it. And
I just thought of an unused container that'll work real fine for a
lily on the side porch. Soon.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes a weekly column on gardening lifestyles for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail him at leemay
</P>
<P>
   (at)bellsouth.net.
</P>
