<HEADLINE>
A WINE WORTH TAKING A CHANCE ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Calamin Cuvee Speciale 1995, Vaud, Switzerland. About $24.
</P>
<P>
   Should you lay out the price of a decent bottle of Champagne for
a virtually unknown white wine from Switzerland? This is one time
when plunging into the unknown will pay off. Calamin is from the
Domaine Louis Bovard, which has been in the wine business along the
terraced shores of Lake Geneva for 16 generations. The principal
grape in most Bovard wines, including Calamin, is chasselas, long a
favorite among Swiss vintners. This is an aromatic wine in the
style of viognier. It will go with rich dishes, but I'd recommend
getting to know it first as an aperitif. The winery says Calamin
can age for 10 to 15 years. Undoubtedly it will. But why wait?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
