<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SUNDAY-RESTAURANTS-NY     09-07 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-RESTAURANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DAY THE RESTAURANTS REST: ON SUNDAY, EATING OUT GOES SOFT
FOCUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I used to eat at home on Sundays. But the need to
dine out constantly has disrupted my pattern _ and opened my eyes.
I now routinely eat out on both weekend nights, and a creeping
suspicion is growing into something like a firm conviction: for
diners, Sunday is not a good bet.
</P>
<P>
   At restaurant after restaurant, I have detected a slackening
off, a lack of luster, a sag and a droop on Sundays. The same dish
that sparkled on a Wednesday just sat there on Sunday, dull and
lifeless. The snap, crackle and pop that I admired in the service
on Saturday night became a listless shuffling on Sunday. Only the
bill remained the same.
</P>
<P>
   I first noticed this phenomenon at The Red Cat in Chelsea, a
restaurant that thrilled me on a couple of weeknight visits,
especially with a highly original sweet pea and risotto cake fitted
out with plump oysters. On an ill-fated Sunday, I took a party of
four there and coerced my fellow diners into ordering my favorite
dish. We all took a bite. Everyone looked at me quizzically. There
was nothing wrong with the thing, but it was no big deal, either.
It just reposed on the plate meekly. The rest of the meal went the
same way. No one could figure out what I was so excited about,
until chance brought two of my diners to the restaurant on a
weeknight. We had a really good meal, they reported.
</P>
<P>
   At Union Square Cafe, I sensed the same falloff. Not a
precipitous plunge, but a slight relaxation, a perceptible dulling
of the restaurant's reflexes. My lemon-pepper duck with
peach-cherry chutney and glazed carrots, for example, seemed wan,
and just a little tough and dry. Union Square Cafe? Et tu, Brute?
</P>
<P>
   What explains the malaise? I've been turning the question over
and over and have come up with a few explanations _ some
philosophical and speculative, some common-sensical and rooted in
hard economics. To start with the hard facts, many chefs take
Sunday off. On the seventh day, they rest, and in many cases, so
does the food. An eagle eye and deft hand is no longer enforcing
the letter of the law, so the food that comes out of the kitchen,
although executed well enough, slides just a notch.
</P>
<P>
   The food itself is different, too. It's older. Restaurants
cannot browse the daily market on Sunday for the freshest greens.
Fish suppliers do not deliver. The oyster with a sparkle in its eye
on Saturday can look a little blurry on Sunday. Sushi loses some of
its sheen. It's like eating food in soft focus. The flavors lose
clarity and definition. The vibrancy of the weeknight meal doesn't
vibrate quite the same way.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same with the service. A Sunday lassitude seems to
spread throughout the staff. The curious psychological power of
Sunday, which drains energy from everyone except televangelists,
may be the culprit here. There may be a dollars-and-cents
explanation as well. At most restaurants, Sunday is not a prime
night for tips, and therefore the best, most-seasoned waiters will
choose it as a day off, leaving the restaurant with
second-stringers. And the first-stringers who do work on Sunday can
be forgiven for experiencing a Sunday letdown after the tumult and
excitement of a busy Manhattan Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant-going in New York is theater, and there's no question
that Friday and Saturday nights generate an excitement unmatched
during the week. Restaurants stay open late. The mood is upbeat.
Waiters and waitresses give it their all, into the wee hours. And
then the unlucky ones have to turn around and do it over again on
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   They play to a tougher crowd. The Sunday night diner is not the
same as the Saturday night diner. Sundays are made for the
returning weekenders who are too tired to fix a meal at home, for
the pleasure seekers who want to squeeze the very last drops out of
their days off, and for the thousands of New Yorkers who look deep
into their refrigerators, then look deep into their souls and
decide that that they'd rather eat out.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a fun group. Some of them look like they're eating
their last meal. And servers, like stand-up comics or actors, feed
off audience energy. It's a lot easier to deliver a top-drawer
performance for dating couples out for a splurge, a giddy gang
looking forward to a late-night party or out-of-towners with stars
in their eyes. Sunday diners are subdued, already feeling the
shadow of the workweek. Mirth and hilarity _ and the big tips that
go with them _ belong to the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Summer does not help. Oysters are out of season. Chefs take
actual vacations. The heat adds another humid layer to the torpor,
and the very notion of Monday seems not just cruel but perverse.
Sunday dining takes a beating.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, restaurants get around the Sunday problem by closing
down for the night. Most of them stay closed Monday, too, just to
be sure. Some New York restaurants have followed suit, but most
need the cash flow. Like taxis, they keep the engine running seven
days. And the unwary diner can get taken for a ride. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
