<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRY-GADGET-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 Kitchen Appliances Allow Us to Have a Career and
Home-Cooked  Dinners, Too 
 &HT;     By Karola Saekel 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  At the danger of being summarily dismissed from
from the fraternal order of foodies, I have to make a confession: I
love my kitchen gadgets.
<P>
   And we are not talking about the reputable chef's knife (though
I couldn't cook without it), nor the unlined copper bowl (which
 &LR; does &LR;  give egg whites that billowy extra volume).
</P>
<P>
   We are talking of the untouchables: the food processor, the
blender, the microwave oven and _ shudder _ the bread machine.
Admittedly, none of them are life-or-death necessities, but they
can make existence on a hectic schedule easier, and if you use good
kitchen sense and discretion, they can make it possible to produce
a home-cooked meal when you might otherwise resort to take-out.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some recipes using some appliances that are meant to
save time _ in preparation and in clean-up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN RECIPES) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
10-MINUTE BORSCHT
</P>
<P>
   Any leftover borscht is excellent served cold the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 onion, peeled
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cooking oil
</P>
<P>
   1 red beet (5-6 ounces), peeled and quartered
</P>
<P>
   1/4 head cabbage (about 8 ounces), rinsed
</P>
<P>
   3 cups beef broth
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sour cream or plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   Coarsely chopped fennel leaves or chives (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Shred the onion in a food processor fitted with the shredding
disk. Don't clean the bowl and blade until all vegetables have been
processed. Transfer the onion to a large micro-safe bowl; toss with
the oil. Cover loosely and microwave at medium-high for 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Shred the beet in the processor. Add to the onion and microwave
at medium-high for 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the cabbage into chunks and shred in the processor. Add to
the onion/beet, along with the broth. Microwave, loosely covered,
on high for 3 minutes. Test the soup _ the vegetables should be
cooked through but not mushy. If needed, microwave up to 2 minutes
longer in 30-second increments. Taste for salt. Amount needed
depends on saltiness of the broth. Stir in the vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   Ladle into bowls and top each with a dollop of sour cream or
yogurt. If you wish, garnish with coarsely chopped fresh fennel
fronds or chives.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 70 calories, &LR;   &LR; 4 g protein, 7 g carbohydrate, 3
g &LR;   &LR; fat (1 g saturated), 3 mg cholesterol, 22 mg sodium, 1 g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
POACHED SALMON WITH HOLLANDAISE SAUCE FOR 2
</P>
<P>
   If you are cooking for more than two, increase the amounts
accordingly and increase the cooking time _ about half again as
much time for four, almost double for six.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Fish
</P>
<P>
   1 large salmon fillet, 14 to 16 ounces
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon pure maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons vodka (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh dill
</P>
<P>
   The Sauce
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons + 1 teaspoon butter, cut into chunks
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cold water
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Yolk from 1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the salmon skin-side down in a heat-proof pie plate or
other shallow micro-safe dish, tucking the thin part of the fillet
under to make an even thickness. Drizzle with lemon juice, maple
syrup and the optional vodka. Sprinkle with dill. Let marinate at
room temperature while you prepare the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The sauce:  &LR; Place 3 tablespoons cut-up butter in a 2-cup
heat-proof measuring cup or other suitable container. Microwave on
medium-high for 45 seconds, until barely melted. Stir with a fork
until all the butter is liquid. Stir in the water and lemon juice.
Add the egg yolk and beat to blend. Microwave at medium (half
power) for 12 seconds, stir with a fork.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat these 2 steps 3 or 4 times, until the sauce thickens.
Remove from the oven and immediately stir in the remaining teaspoon
of cold butter.
</P>
<P>
   Taste for salt and add additional lemon juice, if desired. Place
in a bowl filled with hot tap water and cover loosely to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Place the plate with the fish in the microwave; microwave at
medium-high for 2 minutes. Check for doneness by cutting a slit in
the center of the fillet. Cooking time will vary depending on your
oven and the thickness and temperature of the fish. In most
instances, the fish will need another 30 seconds to 11/2 minutes at
medium-high.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from the oven as soon as the center is no longer raw.
Cover loosely and let rest a couple of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Portion the fish onto serving plates and spoon the sauce over.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 570 calories, &LR;   &LR; 42 g protein, 3 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 43 g fat (18 g saturated), 288 mg cholesterol, 261 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; PEACHY ENDING
</P>
<P>
   Cold leftovers make a nice breakfast treat, topped with a little
milk.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 cups cut-up peaches, plums, apricots, pluots or a mixture (see
note)
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons sugar, depending on sweetness of fruit
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon quick-cooking tapioca
</P>
<P>
   1 cup crunchy granola
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons slivered almonds (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons butter, melted in microwave 45 seconds at
medium
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla ice cream, half-and-half or creme fraiche (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the fruit, sugar and tapioca in a deep micro-safe
2-quart bowl or casserole; toss and let stand for 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Combine the granola, brown sugar, optional almonds and the
cinnamon in a small bowl. Toss to mix; add the melted butter and
toss again.
</P>
<P>
   Loosely cover the bowl containing the fruit and microwave on
high for 5 minutes. Test the fruit. It should be cooked but not
mushy. If it's still too hard, cook in 30-second increments until
desired consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle the granola mixture on top of the fruit, spreading it
evenly. Microwave (uncovered) on high for 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Let stand a couple of minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Top with vanilla ice cream, half-and-half or creme fraiche if
desired.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; The pluot is a cross between an apricot and a plum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 195 calories, &LR;   &LR; 3 g protein, 32 g carbohydrate,
7 &LR;   &LR; g fat (5 g saturated), 10 mg cholesterol, 74 mg sodium, 3 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
