<SLUG> BC-TASTE-MEAT-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Poultry Lunch Meat Isn't Same Old Bologna  &HT;       
 By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  Last week we brought you the disappointing results
of the Taster's Choice for bologna made from pork, beef or a
combination of meats. This week's panel tasted three bolognas made
with turkey and one made with chicken.
<P>
   The poultry bolognas were lower in fat than most of the meat
bolognas, giving them a slightly more attractive health profile.
Overall, the panel liked these better than the meat versions, but
they still found most to be just as slimy and overly salty.
</P>
<P>
   Prices on the poultry bologna varied more than the meat
bolognas. Poultry bologna ranged from $1.59 for an 8-ounce package
to $3.49 for a 12-ounce package.
</P>
<P>
   The panel agreed on one favorite and gave it a decent rating.
</P>
<P>
   The winner was  &UR; Zacky Farms Chicken Bologna &LR;  (16 ounces, $2.49
at Andronico's). Four panelists liked the texture, which they
described as meaty and with ``good chew.'' But one panelist thought
the texture was grainy. Three panelists liked the spicy, peppery
taste; one of them described it as almost sausagelike. Two
panelists did not like the dark color. Two would buy it; three
might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to  &UR; Butterball Turkey Bologna &LR;  (12 ounces,
$3.49 at Safeway), which also happens to be fat free. Two panelists
liked the slight smokey quality, but all commented it had a strange
sweet flavor. Two also thought it was too salty. Three panelists
described the texture as plastic, rubbery and elastic. One would
buy it, one might buy it, and three would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Zacky Farms Turkey Bologna  &LR; (16 ounces, $2.49 at Andronico's)
came in third, but scored significantly lower than its chicken
counterpart. All of the panelists were put off by a pronounced
grainy, gritty texture, and most thought it was too salty. One
might buy it; four would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Louis Rich Turkey Bologna  &LR; (8 ounces, $1.59 at Safeway) came in
fourth. All the panelists disliked the texture, which they
described as plasticlike and ``like Silly Putty,'' and two also
pointed out a lack of flavor. None would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Panelists were Dan Bowe, associate culinary director, Center for
Culinary Development; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Roland
Passot chef-owner, La Folie in San Francisco and Left Bank in
Larkspur and Menlo Park; Kim Severson, Chronicle staff writer; and
Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are
tasted blind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1645EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
