<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETROG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CITRUS FRUIT MUST PASS A BLEMISH TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JOAN NATHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finding a perfect etrog is no easy task.
</P>
<P>
   Observant Jews who follow the biblical commandment of reciting a
prayer over ``the fruit of goodly trees'' for Succoth, the harvest
celebration, sometimes use a magnifying glass to choose the finest
one. This thick-skinned citrus fruit, which looks like a large
lemon and tastes like an especially bitter one, is thought by some
to have been the true forbidden fruit in the Garden of Eden.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jewish law, if the skin of the etrog (pronounced
EH-trog) is covered with scars, or has peeled, split or been
perforated, the fruit cannot be used. An etrog considered fit for
Succoth must come from a tree that has not been grafted; in Israel,
where most of these fruits are grown, they are supposed to be left
on the tree every seventh year, following a biblical commandment.
</P>
<P>
   Grown in small numbers specifically for Succoth, etrogs are
harvested by hand and are in demand only in the weeks before the
holiday, which this year begins Sept. 24. Good ones are sold in
stores that sell religious items and can cost from $25 to several
hundred dollars each.
</P>
<P>
   At the Esrog Warehouse in Queens, N.Y., thousands of etrogs
(also called esrog or citron) will be distributed in the region in
the next week or so. Most of the 200,000 that are exported to the
United States come from Israel, with about 10,000 from Italy and
Morocco, said Yaakov Charlap, the warehouse owner.
</P>
<P>
   The Succoth blessing is said with the etrog held in the left
hand and a date palm branch, entwined with myrtle and a willow
branch, in the right. The four items are sold as a set, and Jewish
tradition holds that incredible spiritual blessings flow upon a
person who prays over them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the etrog is both fragrant and edible, it symbolizes
Jews who are learned in Torah and who do good deeds,'' said Rabbi
Jerome Davidson of Temple Beth-El in Great Neck, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The etrog is thought to have originated in northern India or
Afghanistan, and in ancient times it was also prized for its
medicinal value; it was thought to enhance potency in men.
According to one folk belief, a woman who bites into an etrog will
become pregnant within a year.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part throughout history, etrogs have only been
candied or dried for their fragrance. Now there is a movement in
California, Florida, Arizona and Texas to grow them for food as
well as for Succoth. The etrog does not make things easy for
would-be farmers: trees do not bear fruit for four to seven years,
and the fruit has relatively little pulp for its five-inch size.
</P>
<P>
   Among these hopeful growers is Dr. David Wiseman of Dallas.
Wiseman, 39, a medical research scientist, became curious about the
etrog after a Succoth class with his rabbi. ``After we said the
traditional prayer over the etrog, I started wondering what it
tasted like,'' Wiseman said. So he cut it open and found it
``interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   He planted a few seeds in pots and put them in his garage. When
they started to sprout months later, he moved them to a sunny place
in his house. By the next summer they had become such admired
plants that he asked his fellow congregants to give him their
etrogs after the holiday was over. From six etrogs he planted 300
seeds in pots in his backyard and has since learned how to make a
vodka-based schnapps, candied citron and marmalade from the pulp.
</P>
<P>
   Wiseman has created Zaide Reuben's Esrog Farm (972-931-5596), a
company that sells etrogs from Israel, his seedlings, an etrog
booklet and T-shirts through his Web site:
members.aol.com/zrsesrog.
</P>
<P>
   But he faces a challenge. That's how it is when you seek
perfection.
</P>
<P>
   TRIPLE-CITRUS MARMALADE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 70 minutes plus overnight soaking
</P>
<P>
   1 large etrog or 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   1 orange
</P>
<P>
   1 grapefruit
</P>
<P>
   About 3 cups sugar.
</P>
<P>
   1. Wash fruit, cut in half and remove seeds. Cut fruit,
including rind, into 2-inch chunks. Place in a bowl with water to
cover. Cover with plastic wrap, and let stand overnight.
</P>
<P>
   2. Next day, transfer fruit and water to a saucepan. Bring to a
boil, then simmer uncovered for 30 minutes. Drain. You should have
about 3 cups.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place fruit in food processor, and pulse 3 or 4 times.
Transfer to saucepan. Add 1 cup of sugar for every cup of fruit.
Heat, stirring constantly, until sugar dissolves. Simmer for 30
minutes uncovered, stirring frequently, until marmalade thickens.
Pour into jars, cover and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 4 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
