A3393 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-LEARN-CORN-SFCHRON &LR;      09-07 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARN-CORN-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 LEARNING TO COOK: When Life Gets Corny, Make Soup  &HT;       
 By Marion Cunningham  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  One of the most common weaknesses we home cooks
have is buying too much produce at the farmers' market, then having
to figure out how to use the excess. Buying too much summer fruit
is easier to cope with than having an overabundance of vegetables.
<P>
   I simply cook excess fruit with sugar, ladle it into jars and
keep it in the refrigerator. This is simple to do and is easy to
serve in a number of different ways: spoon it on toast, over ice
cream, or in a small dish topped with a little cream.
</P>
<P>
   Being creative with vegetables is a little trickier. However,
I've solved the problem of what to do with too many ears of corn,
both raw and cooked. Corn Soup.
</P>
<P>
   This soup is nice served with rye crackers and a sharp cheese.
Or, try serving it with a grilled cheese and tomato sandwich for a
light summer meal. If you are new at home cooking, this
three-ingredient recipe is hard to flub.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Marion Cunningham, Bay Area cooking teacher, is the author of
``Learning to Cook,'' ``Cooking With Children,'' ``The Fannie
Farmer Cookbook'' and ``The Breakfast Book,'' among others.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; 3 INGREDIENT CORN SOUP
</P>
<P>
   This easy summer soup can be either creamy or crunchy, depending
on whether you puree it or not.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   6 cups corn kernels (about 9 ears of fresh corn)
</P>
<P>
   41/2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cutting the kernels off the cob:  &LR; Pull the outer leaves and
silky threads off each ear of corn.
</P>
<P>
   Put a large piece of waxed paper on cutting board.
</P>
<P>
   Hold each ear of corn, large end upright, on the cutting board
and, using a sharp knife, cut the kernels off the cob from top to
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Pick up the ends of the waxed paper and, using it as a sling,
transfer the corn to a heavy-bottomed saucepan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Making the soup &LR; : Add 3 cups of milk and the salt to the
saucepan. Turn the heat to medium-high and stir often until the
milk begins to boil, then reduce the heat to medium-low, so the
milk simmers, but does not boil. Simmer for 15 minutes, stirring
every few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Finishing the soup:  &LR; If you want a crunchy corn soup, just add
the remaining 11/2 cups milk, taste and add more salt if needed;
heat and serve.
</P>
<P>
   If you want creamy corn soup, pour the soup into a food
processor and process until the corn is pureed (the kernels will be
broken down into small bits, or blended completely into the milk,
depending on how powerful your processor is). Pour the soup back
into the saucepan and add the remaining 11/2 cups milk. Taste and
add more salt if needed; heat and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 370 calories, &LR;   &LR; 17 g protein, 57 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 12 g fat (6 g saturated), 37 mg cholesterol, 437 mg
sodium, 10 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; 3 INGREDIENT CORN SOUP
</P>
<P>
   This easy summer soup can be either creamy or crunchy, depending
on whether you puree it or not.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   6 cups corn kernels (about 9 ears of fresh corn)
</P>
<P>
   41/2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cutting the kernels off the cob:  &LR; Pull the outer leaves and
silky threads off each ear of corn.
</P>
<P>
   Put a large piece of waxed paper on cutting board.
</P>
<P>
   Hold each ear of corn, large end upright, on the cutting board
and, using a sharp knife, cut the kernels off the cob from top to
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Pick up the ends of the waxed paper and, using it as a sling,
transfer the corn to a heavy-bottomed saucepan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Making the soup &LR; : Add 3 cups of milk and the salt to the
saucepan. Turn the heat to medium-high and stir often until the
milk begins to boil, then reduce the heat to medium-low, so the
