<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3394 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-BOOKCROSS-SFCHRON &LR;      09-07 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKCROSS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 COOK'S BOOKS: Make Way for Matzo Ball Gumbo  &HT;        By David A. Steinberg 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; One of the hottest catchphrases (some would say
cliches) in food circles these days is ``fusion cuisine'' ergo
German blutwurst served sushi-style. So I had an undeniable
prejudice toward ``Crossroads Cooking: The Meeting and Mating of
Ethnic Cuisines _ From Burma to Texas in 200 Recipes,'' by
Elizabeth Rozin.
<P>
   It's a forgivable preconception, given that the title seems to
support the idea that this is yet another cookbook to jump on the
fusion bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   The blurb on the inside of the book jacket, however, insists
that the concept of ``crossroads'' cooking is ``very different from
self-conscious `fusion' or a `melting pot' that blurs the identity
of its ingredients. . . . (It covers) the happenstance meeting and
mating of traditions, thereby creating cuisines both diverse and
distinct.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh-huh. Sounds like a distinction without a difference to me.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong _ I am not reticent about liberally borrowing
from a variety of cuisines to make a single dish. I do have a
problem with a cookbook trying to justify its existence by claiming
to be different, while marketing itself in the same niche that it
claims to reject. But that is in many ways beside the point with
this book.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes are far from controversial, and, indeed, Rozin makes
the case that fusion cuisine is a natural process when cultures
collide at various junctures in the world. With an extensive
foreword and introductions to every chapter, she pushes this thesis
further.
</P>
<P>
   She leads the reader to believe this is practically an academic
treatise on the anthropological development of cuisines. Yet, she
doesn't offer a single scholarly reference. Instead, she makes
ad-hominim remarks and facile observations about the origins of
various cuisines and trends without supporting evidence. (Matzo
Ball Gumbo offers ``the vibrant spirit and flavor of the Louisiana
gumbo . . . refashioned within the guidelines of the biblical
dietary laws.'')
</P>
<P>
   The cookbook is more of a ``Whitman sampler'' of cultural
cuisines than anything else. Despite the haphazard premise, Rozin
offers some good recipes. The deviled crab casserole is elegant and
well worth the effort of dealing with shelling the fresh crab.
</P>
<P>
   Less appealing, though still quite good tasting as a ``feeding
the hoard'' dish, is the turkey tamale pie. More than one person
commented that this is an ideal recipe after the holidays when
you're trying to figure out how to use all the leftover turkey for
the fifth time in as many days.
</P>
<P>
   The crowning recipe, however, is the sweet-and-sour lamb satay
with coconut-peanut dipping sauce. This is an exceptionally
balanced recipe and a brilliant blending of flavors. If you or
someone in your house is a grill maven, this is a great recipe to
pull out when you are having people over for a backyard barbecue.
It can be used as either a tempting appetizer or the star
attraction as a main course.
</P>
<P>
   The book as a whole is well laid out, and the recipes are easy
to follow. But I suggest Rozin should have presented her book more
honestly. She adds nothing of substance to the fusion debate (if
you are even interested in such a thing) but rather seems eager to
ride its coattails. Sort of like having your blutwurst sushi and
eating, too.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``Crossroads Cooking: The Meeting and Mating of Ethnic &LR; 
 &LR; Cuisines _ From Burma to Texas in 200 Recipes,'' by Elizabeth &LR; 
 &LR; Rozin, (Viking, 1999; 258 pages; hardcover; $27.50). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SWEET-AND-SOUR LAMB SATAY WITH COCONUT-PEANUT DIPPING SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Although pork is the favored meat of most Asians, lamb is a
delicious alternative for many of the Malaysian Muslims whose
religion forbids the meat of the pig. The sweet-and-sour marinade
works particularly well with the full flavor of lamb. The
coconut-peanut dipping sauce is but one variety of a host of
sweet-and-spicy satay sauces.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound lean boneless lamb, cut into 1/2-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons regular soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon tamarind concentrate
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, crushed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon crushed hot pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsweetened coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons black soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons finely minced lemongrass
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   If you are using bamboo skewers, soak them in water for an hour
or two before you need them.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the lamb with 2 tablespoons of the regular soy sauce, 1
tablespoon of the brown sugar, and the tamarind and garlic. Mix
well. Let stand, covered, in the refrigerator for 2 to 4 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a small, heavy saucepan and saute the shallots,
ginger and the pepper flakes over moderate heat, stirring, for a
few minutes, until the mixture becomes aromatic.
</P>
<P>
   Add the coconut milk, the remaining tablespoon of regular soy
sauce, the black soy sauce, lemon juice, lemongrass and the
remaining tablespoon of dark brown sugar. Mix well and bring to a
simmer. Simmer, stirring, for a few minutes. Add the peanut butter
and mix until the sauce is well blended and smooth. Remove from the
heat.
</P>
<P>
   Thread the marinated lamb onto skewers. Grill over hot charcoal,
turning once, about 4 to 5 minutes on each side.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the satay with the coconut-peanut sauce for dipping.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; Any leftover dipping sauce can be stored in a covered
jar in the refrigerator for a couple of weeks. Heat the sauce to a
simmer before serving again.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; (The calories and other nutrients absorbed from &LR; 
 &LR; marinades vary and are difficult to estimate. Variables include &LR; 
 &LR; the type of food, marinating time and amount of surface area. &LR; 
 &LR; Therefore, the marinade is not included in this analysis) 500 &LR; 
 &LR; calories, &LR;   &LR; 39 g protein, 14 g carbohydrate, 33 g fat (12 g &LR; 
 &LR; saturated), 101 mg cholesterol, 944 mg sodium, 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1646EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3395 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-CRUSH99-SFCHRON &LR;      09-07 0164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUSH99-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 CRUSH '99: Harvest Is Late, But Quality Looks Good  &HT;        By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  El Ni &LR; n &LR; o and La Ni &LR; n &LR; a have dealt the California
wine industry a double weather whammy this year, backing up the
annual harvest at least two to four weeks in some areas. Even so,
it's under way in some of the state's warmer grape-growing regions.
<P>
   In Lake County, Karen Magoon of Guenoc Winery reports that grape
picking has begun in the Guenoc Valley and that grape quality looks
very good. Harvest is also under way at the Kendall-Jackson
Lakeport Winery with the arrival of Chardonnay grapes from Contra
Costa County.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of July, the California Department of Food and
Agriculture estimated this year's wine grape production would be
2.9 million tons _ up 13 percent from 1998. The report concluded,
``Growers are expecting a good quality crop due to recent warm days
and cool nights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
