<SLUG> BC-WACO-RESIDENTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECENT EVENTS PUT WACO RESIDENTS ON DEFENSIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER AUTREY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ For more than six years, Brenda Carpenter has
lived with the stigma of being from a city people associate with
renegade cults; gruesome, fiery deaths; and overzealous law
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish people would just let it rest,'' said Carpenter, 43, a
pharmaceutical technician who lives in the Waco suburb of Elm Mott.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Waco residents like it or not, the events at Mount
Carmel in 1993 will not likely let them rest for some time. The
city is in the news again after the Federal Bureau of Investigation
recently disclosed after years of denials that it used pyrotechnic
tear-gas canisters to help end a standoff at the Branch Davidian
compound.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, U.S. District Judge Walter Smith told federal
authorities to surrender to a federal clerk in Waco all evidence
related to the events at Mount Carmel or risk being held in
contempt of court.
</P>
<P>
   But these events are probably tame compared to the public frenzy
that could build in this city of 104,000 by the time the civil
trial being brought by relatives of dead Branch Davidians begins
Oct. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Already, in light of recent news stories, the number of visitors
to the compound jumped from about 30 to 40 cars on an average
weekend day to about 100 Sunday, said Amo Paul Bishop Roden, who
lives in a one-room, white-washed A-frame house at the entrance to
the property.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of days it's been absolutely wild,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For Carpenter and others, the recent events bring back memories
of April 19, 1993, when fire consumed the compound, and the bodies
of David Koresh and about 80 followers were found in the complex's
rubble.
</P>
<P>
   While Carpenter was in a south Louisiana store buying a shirt
for her husband shortly after the fire, the proprietor overheard
that she was from Waco. He tried to give her the shirt to get her
out of the store quickly because he was so unnerved that she might
be a Branch Davidian, Carpenter said.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter discussed such misperceptions while sitting in her car
at the entrance to Mount Carmel, the compound about 10 miles from
town where the Davidians died after a siege that began Feb. 28,
1993, when agents of the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
attempted to search for illegal weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of saying that she wanted the public to forget about
the debacle at the compound while visiting it herself was not lost
on Carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister wanted to see it,'' she said and shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   Many local residents have such stories.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Stovall, an M&AMP;M/Mars plant worker, said she dislikes
using her credit card with the Waco skyline when she's out of town
because it prompts too many questions.
</P>
<P>
   Melvya Collins, a retired school administrator, said she gets
similar treatment when people see Waco on her luggage tags. They
want to know if she knew any Davidians, if she's a Davidian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them, `I wasn't even there at the time. I was in
Pittsburgh, P-A,' '' she said. ``It's exasperating.''
</P>
<P>
   It also may provide fulfillment for some, Roden said.
</P>
<P>
   Roden was married to George Roden, who preceded Koresh as Branch
Davidian leader and who had feuded with Koresh. Now she serves as
part squatter, part welcoming committee for the slow trickle of
trucks, sport utility vehicles and rental cars that drive the rural
farm road for a glimpse at the infamous compound.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking, I think, for answers, or maybe just
looking,'' Roden said. ``Some want to pay their respects,
especially for the children. People have lost a lot of faith in the
government.''
</P>
<P>
   The vehicles follow the same black dirt driveway that the tanks
used to arrive at the front door of the main building in the
compound before the fire.
</P>
<P>
   There is little to see anymore. All that remains of a complex
that once included a two-story building with a four-story tower, a
gymnasium and several underground tunnels is a swimming pool of
rough concrete with some stagnant brown water in it. On the edge of
the pool, under the label ``History's Most Photographed Massacre,''
someone has painted directions pointing to where cameras from the
FBI and news media were located.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of grasshoppers jump waist high every time a visitor
takes a step, and almost everyone makes a comment about the
biblical plagues.
</P>
<P>
   Two burned-out buses are on either side of the area where the
buildings were, and one of Koresh's old motorcycles sits across the
street. The only other vertical features are typed signs covered in
glass and 80 crape myrtles. The signs, showing where the gym, the
front door, the dining room and other compound features were once
located, are apparently new, maybe driven into the ground as
recently as Sunday, Roden speculated. One refers to the upcoming
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The crape myrtles _ with not a single bloom _ stand above
granite gravestones for each of the Branch Davidians, including 20
children, found dead after the fire. Only Koresh's was set in
concrete, presumably to prevent theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take long to see everything,'' said Larry Barton,
50, of Grapevine, Texas, surveying the remains.
</P>
<P>
   For the three-day Labor Day weekend, Barton decided to take in
the sights of Waco: the Texas Ranger Hall of Fame and Museum, the
Dr Pepper Museum and, of course, Mount Carmel. The city of Waco
tourist office even gave him a map to find it.
</P>
<P>
   Barton predicted that many millions of dollars will be wasted in
further investigations of the episode and that nothing will be
resolved. His views were similar to those of several who visited
the compound Sunday, that something terrible went wrong and that
the American people will never know the whole story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the government covers up a lot of stuff, so we will
never know what the truth is,'' said Les Baldwin, 46, of Campbell,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Waco has become a symbol. And for all their
eye-rolling, even some Waco residents have to admit that the events
at Mount Carmel mean that the town's name has recognition not just
by millions of Americans but by many more around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Charley Conley knows. The Waco truck driver visited the compound
Sunday for the 10th time in six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a sensational story,'' Conley said. ``Everybody
seems to know about it and about us.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
