<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   WINE POTPOURRI: SOBs Rally 'Round Sauvignon Blanc  
   
   
 By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  About 10 years ago, wine lovers began to grumble
about Chardonnay dominating the white wine field to the exclusion
of nearly every other varietal. ``That other white wine'' (i.e.,
Sauvignon Blanc) was just beginning to gather a following, but it
needed a push.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Along came the SOBs, a group of winemakers and winery owners
anxious to see Sauvignon Blanc get more respect and attention. The
Society of Blancs' charter aimed to convince the wine trade and
wine-drinking public that Sauvignon Blanc can match Chardonnay and
Johannisberg Riesling as one of the truly noble white grape
varieties.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1990, I moderated a panel discussion by Sonoma County
winemakers, all SOB members, on ``Taming the Wild Sauvignon
Blanc.'' Wildness referred to the broad palate of aromas and
flavors that could be developed from Sauvignon Blanc, depending on
where the grapes were grown and how the wine was made.
</P>
<P>
   One attempt by the SOBs to get the word out was the Sauvignon
Blanc &AMP; Fume Blanc Flavor Spectrum. Designed like a fan, the graph
starts at the center with the three styles _ grassy, fruity and
spicy _ then fans out to show typical flavors. Grassy, for
instance, is categorized as fresh, garden herbal, floral or
flat-out grassy. The outer ring takes the flavor spectrum one step
further, with suggested flavors like mint, oregano, violet and
lemongrass. The Flavor Spectrum also lists conditions _ climate,
soils and winemaking, for example _ that influence the character of
the wine.
</P>
<P>
   However, nearly a decade after it was formed, the Society of
Blancs is on hiatus because of lack of interest on the part of the
winery members _ an odd move considering the California wine
industry still has not provided the public with a clear definition
of Sauvignon Blanc, and how, if at all, it differs from Fum &LR; e &LR; 
Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   Following the French models, a California wine labeled Sauvignon
Blanc should resemble a Bordeaux blanc, usually with a little oak
and some Semillon in the blend. A California Fum &LR; e &LR;  Blanc (a name
created by Robert Mondavi in the early 1970s from the Loire Pouilly
Blanc Fum &LR; e &LR; ) should be more like a Loire Pouilly Fum &LR; e &LR;  or
Sancerre. But the reality is that California Fum &LR; e &LR;  Blanc often is
barrel-fermented and oak-aged and may include Semillon, while some
Sauvignon Blancs never see oak.
</P>
<P>
   Add to all that the fact that many Sauvignons and Fum &LR; e &LR; s are
finished with perceptible sweetness, a characteristic that should
be alien to Sauvignon Blanc. With all this confusion, is it any
wonder that Sauvignon Blanc doesn't sell as well as Chardonnay?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Robert A. Young Honored &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Valley grape grower Robert A. Young has been selected
as the recipient of the second Wine Industry Integrity Award by a
committee of wine industry professionals for his pioneering
leadership in California wine-grape growing and his mentorship of
other growers and vintners.
</P>
<P>
   Young, a third-generation grape grower in Sonoma's Alexander
Valley, will be honored at a dinner given by the Lodi-Woodbridge
Winegrape Commission on October 27 in Lodi. Cost is $75 per person.
For reservations and information, call the commission office at
(209) 367-4727.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Wine Q &AMP; A &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Henry B. Meyer of San Francisco is the owner of the following
three old European wines and he wonders about their drinkability
and value. &QL; 
A: Zeller Schwarze Katz (Black Cat) is made from a number of
individual vineyards, around the town of Zell on the Mosel River.
It is a white wine made for early consumption, so it is unlikely
that the 1957 Schwarze Katz is still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Gilis 1933 St. Emilion Light Bordeaux is a mystery to me,
although at 66 years old, I would think that any ``light'' wine
must now be an undrinkable curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   Caraco &AMP; Benitez Malaga Oro may be the keeper of the lot. Malaga
is a sweet dessert wine from the Costa del Sol region of Spain.
Some Malagas age well, but since there is no way of knowing the
true age of your wine, I'd pull the cork. If you decide to drink
the Malaga, I'd like to hear your impressions.
</P>
<P>
   Q: C. Earlenbaugh of Oakland inherited a bottle of Charles Krug
1972 Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon and is curious about its value
and if any restaurant has an interest in adding his Cabernet to its
wine list.
</P>
<P>
   A: Not knowing the history of the particular bottle, I can only
offer general advice. Vintage 1972 was not that good in the Napa
Valley for red wines, and most of the best wines were already
tiring by the early 1990s. Since any remaining '72s are not
generally on collector's lists, I suggest gathering together a few
friends to enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, restaurants can not legally purchase wine from a
private party.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hemp Wine &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I recently read an item in The Wine Trader that renews my faith
in the ingenuity of the American entrepreneur. Nirvana Homebrews in
the Finger Lakes region of New York State is selling Hemp 'n' Wine,
red and white grape wines blended with hemp oil. Jim Castetter of
Nirvana Homebrews says it is not liquid marijuana. ``There is no
THC in our hemp wine _ none,'' he emphasizes.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on hemp wine, log on to  &LR; www.hempwine.com &LR; 
or call (888) 520-9463.
</P>
</TEXT>
