<SLUG> BC-SECRET-PLOUF-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Plouf Makes a Menu of the Bay Area's
Favorite  Seafood   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  If I had to pick the No. 1 seafood dish in the Bay
Area, it would be mussels. It doesn't matter whether the cuisine is
Chinese, Thai, Italian or French, you'll find them on just about
every menu.
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the best and most unusual preparations is Scott Barton's
version with curry sauce served at Plouf, a charming downtown
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Several things set this recipe apart _ adding curry powder and
balancing it with apple and celery; smoothing the sauce with creme
fraiche (or cream) and coconut milk; and adding a splash of
Champagne vinegar infused with chiles for a hearty kick.
</P>
<P>
   This all adds up to a marvelous dish that's easy to prepare at
home _ especially if you think ahead to make the chile-infused
vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   Plouf, a French-inspired seafood restaurant, has a way with
mussels. No other restaurant in the Bay Area has a bigger selection
_ eight different preparations on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked away on Belden Place _ a block-long alley in the
Financial District _ Plouf feels like a find. The fireplace in the
corner is great on cool evenings, and a wall of windows in front
can be thrown open in warm weather to bring the outside in. With
all the tables out front the area has become a popular after-work
hangout.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Plouf, 40 Belden Way (near Bush Street), San Francisco; (415) &LR; 
 &LR; 986-6491. Lunch weekdays; dinner Monday-Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; The sauce. &LR;  Creme fraiche, yogurt and coconut milk, paired
with a fiery chile vinegar and curry powder, work wonders on the
mussels.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; The apples. &LR;  Crisp Granny Smiths offer a clean textural and
flavor contrast to the other ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; PLOUF'S MUSSELS WITH CURRY SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 large yellow onions, diced
</P>
<P>
   3 celery ribs, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Madras curry powder
</P>
<P>
   Pinch saffron threads
</P>
<P>
   2 Granny Smith apples, peeled, cored and diced
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup creme fraiche or heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup plain nonfat yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup unsweetened coconut milk (Chaokoh brand preferred)
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Habanero Vinegar (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds Prince Edward Island black mussels, scrubbed and
debearded
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced chives
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a heavy-bottomed pot large enough to hold the
mussels. Add the onions, celery, curry powder and saffron; saute
over medium heat until the vegetables are translucent, about 9
minutes. Add the diced apples and cook 1 to 2 minutes to soften.
Season with salt and white pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the creme fraiche, yogurt, coconut milk, wine and
vinegar. Bring to a simmer, add the mussels, cover and cook until
they open, about 6 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the pan from the heat and discard any unopened mussels.
Taste and add salt and pepper as needed.
</P>
<P>
   Ladle the mussels and sauce into serving bowls. Garnish with
chopped chives.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 325 calories, &LR;   &LR; 16 g protein, 17 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 16 g fat (10 g saturated), 109 mg cholesterol, 896
mg sodium, 7 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; HABANERO INFUSED VINEGAR
</P>
<P>
   For best results, prepare the vinegar at least 1 day before
serving. You can make the vinegar the same day, but allow it to
steep at least 1 hour before using.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 habanero or jalapeno chile pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Champagne vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Stem and chop the chile. Place in a small bowl and add the
vinegar. Let steep for from 1 to 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Strain into a covered jar and refrigerate until ready to use.
</P>
</TEXT>
