<SLUG> BC-WELCOME-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 `WELCOME BACK, MR. McDONALD': GIDDY FARCE POKES FUN AT JAPANESE(EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(th) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Comedy is certainly not the first thing that comes to mind when
we think of Japanese cinema. But a few more films like Koki
Mitani's hilarious screwball farce ``Welcome Back, Mr. McDonald''
could change all that.
</P>
<P>
   This movie is ostensibly a goofy comedy about a live radio drama
that goes haywire after the imperious diva playing the lead insists
on certain last-minute changes. Her demands set in motion a
desperate chain of events that transform a sudsy romantic drama set
in a Japanese fishing village into a ludicrous action-adventure
fantasy set in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome Back, Mr. McDonald'' can be taken as pure, giddy fun
in a farcical tradition that has all but disappeared from American
movie comedy in the age of the salacious gross-out. But it can also
be taken as a good-natured invitation to Japanese culture to
lighten up. Its manic surface only partially conceals its satiric
barbs.
</P>
<P>
   As the broadcast skids out of control, the movie pokes gleeful
fun at the Japanese insistence on order and good manners at all
costs and on the rigidity of corporate politics and pecking orders.
Finally the movie ridicules Japan's envious fascination with the
gaudy detritus of American popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of this madness is Miyako Suzuki (Kyoka Suzuki), a
meek housewife whose radio play ``The Woman of Destiny'' is being
broadcast nationally after winning a bogus contest sponsored by the
station to provide cheap programming. (Her play was the only
entry.)
</P>
<P>
   After a rehearsal in which all goes smoothly, word comes down
that the lead actress, Nokko Senbon (Keiko Toda), who has
connections with the station's bigwigs, would like her character's
name changed from Ritsuko to Mary Jane and her nationality from
Japanese to American.
</P>
<P>
   After the nervous producer, Ushijima (Masahiko Nishimura),
reluctantly agrees, Nokko demands that Mary Jane be a high-powered
New York City trial lawyer. It isn't long before her competitive
male co-star begins making his own demands for script changes.
</P>
<P>
   He, too, wants an American name and occupation. Inspired by the
logo on a bag of takeout food, he chooses Donald McDonald and
insists his character be a pilot. For silly reasons too complicated
to go into, the setting is eventually moved to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   On top of everything, the station's sound effects library is
locked, and no one can find the key. In desperation the producers
call on an elderly guard who used to improvise acoustic sound
effects on old-time radio to help them out. Some of the most
uproarious scenes show radio technicians desperately executing
ideas that use everything from a flushing toilet (for a dam
bursting) to a vacuum cleaner (a rocket launching).
</P>
<P>
   Once the show goes on the air, station breaks and commercials
are juggled while sound effects are readied and the script written.
Periodically the movie cuts away to show a Japanese trucker (Ken
Watanabe) who has tuned into the program on the road and becomes
mesmerized.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of it all, who should show up in the studio but
Miyako's anxious husband (Yoshimasa Kondo), a car salesman who
assumes his wife's play is autobiographical and becomes extremely
agitated on discovering that it involves a romantic triangle.
</P>
<P>
   As Miyako, desperate to calm his fears, watches her tear-jerker
being re-made into an action-adventure yarn in which the hero is
lost in space, her ultimate concern is that the story have a happy
ending. When that ending doesn't seem forthcoming, she locks
herself in the studio in protest until a solution is devised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome Back, Mr. McDonald'' may be a one-joke movie, but the
inventive ways in which that joke is extended and embellished
insure there is never a stale moment. The fast-paced comic timing
and sharp ensemble performances that give even the minor characters
defined personalities make for a delirious comic portrait of human
vanity and ingenuity in the wonderful world of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WELCOME BACK, MR. McDONALD'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Koki Mitani; in Japanese, with English
subtitles; based on the play ``The Radio Time'' By Mitani and Tokyo
Sunshine Boys; directors of photography, Kenji Takama and Junichi
Tozawa; edited by Hirohide Abe; music by Takayuki Hattori; produced
by Chiaki Matsushita, Hisao Masuda, Takashi Ishihara and Kanjiro
Sakura; released by Viz Films/Tidepoint Pictures. Running time: 103
minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Toshiaki Karasawa (Kudo), Kyoka Suzuki (Miyako Suzuki),
Masahiko Nishimura (Ushijima), Keiko Toda (Nokko Senbon), Ken
Watanabe (trucker) and Yoshimasa Kondo (husband).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1649EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
