<SLUG> BC-TV-LATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LATER TODAY': SLICE OF `MARTHA,' DOLLOP OF `VIEW' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time and station are
for New York area; see local listings.) 
(mk) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For weeks viewers have been bombarded with promos for
NBC's new morning show ``Later Today'' (at 9, right after
``Today''), which came with a tag line either brilliant in its
simplicity or boneheaded beyond belief: ``It's like `Today,' only
later.'' When the program had its premiere Tuesday, it turned out
that the line was simply fiction.
</P>
<P>
   The three hosts, Jodi Applegate (familiar as a regular ``Today''
sub), Florence Henderson (inescapably Mrs. Brady) and Asha Blake
(the unknown) began by chatting in a kitchen. From that moment on,
it was clear that this would be less a franchise of ``Today'' than
a cross between ``The View'' and ``Martha Stewart''; this is not a
program trolling for male viewers. And in its debut ``Later Today''
was smooth, unoriginal, unexciting.
</P>
<P>
   Naming Ms. Henderson as a host was the most attention-getting
move, but Ms. Applegate is the program's likely strength. She is
engaging, witty, at times irreverent, and resists the sycophantic
manner that turns so many daytime shows into sugar-coated donuts.
She handled its most ``Today''-like segment, introducing a news
report about scientific developments that allow parents to choose a
baby's sex, and interviewing experts on different sides of the
issue. She displayed a lighter side in a taped segment about the
Senior Olympics, tossing a javelin and competing in a long-jump
contest against a white-haired granny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't beaten by a great-grandmother, I was beaten by a
grandmother,'' she said. ``That's not so bad, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Henderson's history with ``Today'' had been mentioned at
every opportunity leading up to the premiere, and again during the
opening chat. Briefly, 40 years ago, she was what was then called a
```Today' girl,'' and everyone has made progress since then. No one
has to call Katie Couric `` `Today' girl,'' and Ms. Henderson has
become a polished talk-show personality.
</P>
<P>
   She threatens to be altogether too perky, though. Rosie
O'Donnell, sometimes called the Queen of Nice but truly the Queen
of Plugs, dropped by to say a quick hello, bearing a Cuisinart
cappuccino maker. (Her motto seems to be: Never let an opportunity
to display a brand name go to waste.) After she dashed off to do
the season opener of her own show, Ms. Henderson gushed: ``She is
so neat. How many people would do that on their first day back?'' A
star stopping by to promote her own show? Who ever heard of such
generosity?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Henderson also handled a cooking segment, though everyone's
attention was deflected from the ham-and-mushroom fettuccine by the
appearance of Ann Davis, Alice on ``The Brady Bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Blake (formerly a reporter for ABC and for the NBC-owned
station in Los Angeles) was saddled with a segment so vapid it made
fettuccine look like breaking news. She talked to an editor from In
Style magazine about Kevin Costner's bedroom furniture, with
near-facsimiles in the studio. The real Costner bed, the audience
learned, is one of a kind, carved from ebony. He was not there, but
there was a framed photo of him on the duplicate bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The View'' would have had him in person. Martha Stewart would
have demonstrated how she carved the bedposts out of trees she had
grown herself. ``Later Today'' needs a style of its own.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LATER TODAY'
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m. ET Monday through Friday on NBC (Channel 4 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bass, executive producer. Jodi Applegate, host. Asha
Blake and Florence Henderson, co-hosts. Kim Gerbasi, senior
producer; Diane DeMartino, supervising producer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
