<HEADLINE>
FREEZING AND DEFROSTING  
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   By Lesli Neilson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Here are some helpful tips on freezing and defrosting products that
are conducive to freezing. &HT;    _Use airtight rigid containers, plastic freezer bags or freezer
wraps, such as heavy-duty foil or freezer paper to freeze foods.
Remember to ``burp'' all lids and tightly seal, removing all air
from bags.
 &HT;    _The colder the food is to start, the faster it will freeze and
the better it will maintain its original quality.
 &HT;    _Follow the ``first in, first out'' policy. Use a permanent
marker to write the date on the food when you freeze it. Place the
new food under food already in the freezer and use the older foods
first.
 &HT;      
 FREEZING PREPARED FOODS &HT;      
 Lasagna, casseroles, soups and stews can be easily frozen and
stored for several weeks to months in airtight containers. Remove
the food from the oven or stove and allow it to cool completely. &HT;     Casseroles:  If the food is in a casserole dish or if the
amount is small, allow it to cool at room temperature for 30 to 45
minutes before freezing. Otherwise, cool the food in the
refrigerator.
 &HT;     Soups and Stews:  Ideally, freeze soup bases (the soup before
the addition of all the liquid) rather than finished soups. Chill
the soup base or finished soup in small portions, in airtight
containers for up to six months.
 &HT;    _Finished cream soups, chowders or bisques cannot be frozen, but
the bases of these soups, before milk or cream is added, can be
frozen. Add milk or cream when reheating the soup. (Reheat gently
over low heat to avoid curdling.)
 &HT;    _Soups with a potato base often become grainy after defrosting.
For best results, make the soup base and add the potato puree when
reheating the soup.
 &HT;    _Soups with beans, such as pinto or navy, freeze well for three
to six months.
 &HT;    _For best results, freeze the meat and vegetables from stews
separately in airtight containers. Combine them when reheating,
adding liquid as needed.
 &HT;    _Cool soups and stews quickly by transferring them to tall-sided
containers and placing the containers into an ice bath in the sink.
 &HT;    _Once cooked foods are cool, transfer soups and stews to a rigid
airtight container and freeze; place plastic/ freezer wrap onto
casserole or lasagna, followed by heavy-duty foil. (This prevents
foil from sticking to food when it's defrosted.
 &HT;     Rice and Potatoes: 
 &HT;    _Leftover rice freezes well in an airtight container for up to
one year. Frozen rice may be reheated without defrosting.
 &HT;    _Baked potatoes freeze well. Once cool, wrap tightly in plastic
wrap and heavy-duty foil. Fried potatoes and potato gratins may be
frozen for up to three months.
 &HT;      
 DEFROSTING PREPARED FOODS &HT;      
 Allow one to three days to completely defrost frozen foods in the
refrigerator. &HT;    _To refresh defrosted prepared foods, add fresh herbs, grated
cheese or breadcrumbs to a dish before reheating it.
 &HT;      
 FREEZING UNPREPARED FOODS &HT;      
 Unprepared foods that may be frozen include: &HT;     Poultry:  Remove chicken from its market wrapping. Rinse the
bird and dry it well. Truss the chicken, if desired. Double-wrap
the bird with plastic wrap, then heavy-duty foil or freezer bag.
Freeze for three to six months.
 &HT;     Meat:  Remove meat from its market wrapping. Pat dry with a
paper towel. Wrap meat in airtight freezer wrap and/or freezer bags
in recipe-size portions to allow for even-freezing. Wrap each piece
individually to prevent pieces from sticking to one another.
 &HT;     Seafood:  Whole, cleaned and dressed fish may be frozen in a
freezer bag with enough water to completely surround the fish.
Carefully remove all the air from the bag, seal tightly and freeze.
Shellfish should be placed in an airtight freezer bag before
freezing.
 &HT;     Fruits and Vegetables:  Most fruit turns mushy in the freezer
except for blueberries, raspberries and cranberries, which freeze
well. Spread berries in one layer on a baking sheet and freeze for
15 to 30 minutes. Transfer to an airtight freezer bag and return to
the freezer.
 &HT;    Vegetables should be perfectly ripe for optimum freezing. Blanch
vegetables prior to freezing to set their color and retain their
texture.
 &HT;    There are two methods for blanching vegetables:
 &HT;    _ Steam blanching:  Trim the vegetables, removing any excess
leaves or unwanted pieces. Use a bamboo steamer over a pot of
boiling water or a steaming basket and pot. Blanch vegetables and
plunge immediately into an ice bath. Once cool, remove vegetables
and spread onto paper towels to dry.
 &HT;    _ Water blanching:  Prepare the vegetables as described above.
Boil a gallon of unsalted water for every pound of vegetables.
Immerse the vegetables in the water using a mesh basket or
blanching basket. Plunge vegetables into an ice bath to cool.
Remove vegetables and spread onto paper towels to dry.
 &HT;    Portion the vegetables into airtight plastic freezer bags,
remove all air and freeze.
 &HT;     Dairy:  Semifirm to firm cheeses generally freeze well
(cheddar, Swiss, provolone, mozzarella, Parmesan). Cut the cheese
into small portions and wrap it very tightly before placing it in
the freezer.
 &HT;    _Unsalted butter may be frozen for nine to 12 months; margarine
for five months.
 &HT;    _Milk, cream and eggs do not freeze well.
 &HT;     Fresh herbs:  There is some debate as to whether herbs should
be blanched before freezing. If blanching, use hearty herbs that
are still on the stalk for best results.
 &HT;    Wash delicate herbs such as basil, dill, chives and tarragon.
Pat them dry on paper towels and freeze in small portions in
airtight freezer bags.
 &HT;    Frozen herbs will darken and become limp when thawed, so add
them directly to food you are cooking.
 &HT;      
 DEFROSTING UNPREPARED FOODS &HT;      
 Thaw all unprepared foods in the refrigerator. If necessary, run
frozen food under cold water or use a microwave oven. &HT;     Cold water:  Keep the frozen food wrapped and place it either
in the sink or in a deep container. Allow cold water to run over
the product until thawed. Defrosting time will vary.
 &HT;     Microwave oven:  Do not defrost any foil-wrapped food in the
microwave. For foods wrapped in plastic wrap, follow microwave
manufacturer's instructions for defrosting.
 &HT;      
  
 PANTRY ESSENTIALS  
   
 By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
Every good cook has one or two pantry essentials _ those magic
items that can be used in a pinch to make a meal. Think canned
chicken stock, tuna or Italian white beans.
<P>
   The Chronicle Food staff asked Bay Area chefs and cookbook
authors to share what's most important in their larders. We also
opened the question to readers, who sent in an array of suggestions
_ some that echo the chefs' ideas and some the professionals hadn't
thought of.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; FROM THE PROS
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; _Dried Asian glass noodles.  &LR; With just a quick dip in hot water,
the noodles can become the base for a hot or cold supper. Stir in a
little chicken stock, soy sauce, green onion and a handful of bok
choy or other stir-fried vegetables for a hot, quick meal. Or chill
them and toss with soy sauce and sesame oil, chopped vegetables and
slivered chicken to make a cold salad. &LR;  _ Kirk &LR;   &LR; Webber,
chef/owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; _Miso. &LR;  In addition to making a quick soup, miso enlivens sauces
and adds flavor to meat, fish and vegetables. Coat fish with miso
and broil or grill, finishing with butter and lemon, breadcrumbs
and/or some fresh basil. Yellow miso is less yeasty than the red
variety, but both are handy to have on hand. &LR;  _ Alison Richman, &LR; 
 &LR; chef, XYZ, San Francisco. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; _Eggs, canned Ortega green chiles, cheddar cheese, salsa and corn &LR; 
 &UR; tortillas. &LR;  South-of-the-border scrambled eggs, quesadillas or a
baked Mexican dish can be made with these five ingredients. Store
the tortillas in the freezer for added shelf life. Also, it's nice
to have frozen shrimp, a can of coconut milk and some curry paste
on hand for quick Southeast Asian dishes.  &LR; _ &LR;   &LR; Rosalie &LR;   &LR; Wright,
editor-in-chief, Sunset magazine, Menlo Park. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; _Frozen stuffed pasta and a jar of tomato sauce. &LR;  With a little
butter and garlic and a snip of fresh herbs, a package of
good-quality frozen ravioli can be the basis for a simple, elegant
supper. A jar of pasta sauce _ the plainer the better to allow for
a cook's imagination _ is another good topping for ravioli or dried
pasta.  &LR; _ &LR;   &LR; Dan Bowe, associate culinary &LR;   &LR; director, Center for
Culinary Development, San Francisco. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; _Hard-cooked eggs. &LR;  Cook about a half-dozen at a time and store in
the refrigerator. They make a quick, protein-rich snack. Spread
with a little mayonnaise, a grind of black pepper and a dash of
salt and they can  &LR; become part of a light meal. Also, they can be
sliced into a number of dishes. Other items include orzo, because
it cooks so quickly, and lentils. Cook lentils and top with good
salsa for a fast vegetarian meal. And always have ice cream on hand
for a quick dessert. &LR;  _ Marion Cunningham, &LR;   &LR; cookbook author and
The Chronicle's Learning to Cook columnist, &LR;   &LR; Walnut Creek. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; _Olive oil, balsamic vinegar and sardines. &LR;  With these three
ingredients, you can always make a perfect salad. &LR;  _ Cookbook &LR; 
 &LR; author Peggy Knickerbocker, San Francisco. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; _Quinoa, sesame seeds, good quality canned tuna (preferably tuna &LR; 
 &UR; belly in olive oil) and nama shoyu &LR; . The quinoa cooks quickly and
sesame seeds, toasted with the quinoa before broth is added, lends
a nutty quality. Mix nama shoyu, considered the balsamic vinegar of
soy sauces, with water and put in a spray bottle to use sparingly
for flavor. For a vegan meal, spray the soy mixture over each layer
of sliced root vegetables set in a steamer.  &LR; _ &LR;   &LR; Mary Etta Moose,
co-owner, Moose's, San Francisco. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; _Canned chili con carne and corn.  &LR; With a little creative
doctoring, a can of chili can become a centerpiece for a hearty
supper. Brown a pound or so of ground beef, drain it and add it to
the chili with a can of corn, a teaspoon of toasted, ground cumin
seeds, a tablespoon or more of good-quality ground chile and salt
and pepper. Simmer the mixture at least 10 minutes to blend the
flavors. Add up to a can of water if the chili seems too thick. _
 &LR; Fran Irwin, member of The Chronicle's Food staff &LR;   &LR; and co-author
of ``The San Francisco Chronicle Cookbook.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; FROM READERS
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; _Frozen puff pastry shells.  &LR; These are perfect holders for creamed
tuna or chicken. Also, keep on hand various Chinese canned items
like bamboo shoots and fresh Chinese noodles for quick pan-fried
noodle dishes.  &LR; _ Anne Van Winkle-Denne, Oakland. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; _Dried spaghetti and canned clams. &LR;  These are the basics for
traditional white clam sauce. Simmer clams with olive oil, garlic,
white wine, parsley (dried works in a pinch), and top with Parmesan
cheese and plenty of black pepper. ``With French bread and lettuce,
there's dinner in the time it takes to cook the pasta.'' &LR;  _ Miriam
Mueller, San Francisco. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; _Canned tomatoes, either plain or Italian-style.  &LR; Throw together a
quick spaghetti sauce by sauteing an onion and a garlic clove, both
chopped, then adding Italian-style or organic canned tomatoes, some
basil and other herbs and seasoning to taste. Simmer for about 20
minutes. ``We have this at least once a week and never get tired of
it.''  &LR; _ Melodie Swiggart, American &LR;   &LR; Canyon. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; _Stale artisan bread.  &LR; Grate the stale bread into breadcrumbs, then
saute the crumbs with butter for an easy topping for pasta
embellished broccoli rabe or spinach with garlic and olive oil. Or,
use the stale bread to make stuffing, ``which is so good, I don't
know why people wait until at Thanksgiving to eat it.''  &LR; _ &LR;   &LR; Wendy
Cook, San Francisco. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; _Arborio rice and long-grain white rice &LR; . Cook the rice with broth
or stock. Risotto is good with some fresh Parmesan grated in, or
add frozen peas. ``I discovered that the time it takes me to make
risotto is exactly how much time it takes to wash a load of
laundry. I do all the prep work, take the laundry to the machine,
come back and stir and when the risotto is just done, it's time to
put the clothes in the dryer.''  &LR; _ &LR;   &LR; Jon Dickson, &LR;   &LR; Oakland. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; _Capellini.  &LR; The thin pasta cooks in about two minutes and is the
basis for almost instant pasta primavera. Chopped fresh or canned
tomatoes, frozen peas, leftover cooked carrots and/or mushrooms
sauteed with garlic, baby spinach or other vegetables provide the
sauce. If necessary to thin, add chicken broth.  &LR; _ Nancy Chirich, &LR; 
 &LR; San Francisco. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; STAPLES FOR EASY COOKING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Tara Duggan &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
The following basics will help you prepare fresh meals quickly.
Keep these stocked in your pantry and refrigerator _ and use the
checklist to shop when you run low.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; AROMATICS
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _Garlic
</P>
<P>
   _Red onions
</P>
