   _Canned chipotle peppers
</P>
<P>
   _Soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   _Sugar
</P>
<P>
   _Canned tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   _Canned tuna, packed in olive oil
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; OILS
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _Nut oils for salad
</P>
<P>
   _Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   _Asian Sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   _Vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; (BEGIN RECIPES) &QL; 
 &QL; 
FAST 5 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ORECCHIETTE PASTA WITH BROCCOLI
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds trimmed broccoli flowers
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 pound orecchiette pasta (see note)
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil + olive oil to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon crushed red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Grated pecorino cheese or toasted pine nuts (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place a large stock pot of liberally salted water over high
heat. Make sure there is plenty of water, since the pasta and
broccoli will cook together.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the broccoli flowers into tiny florettes slightly larger
than the pasta, about 1-inch pieces. Put the garlic through a
garlic press.
</P>
<P>
   When the water boils, add the pasta and cook on high heat for 1
minute, stirring constantly to keep the pasta from sticking. Add
the broccoli and bring back to a boil. Reduce heat to medium and
continue cooking, stirring often, until the pasta is al dente and
the broccoli is very soft. Remove and reserve 1 cup of the cooking
water.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the pasta and broccoli, shaking the colander vigorously to
release any trapped water.
</P>
<P>
   While the pasta is cooking, heat the 4 tablespoons olive oil
over medium-low heat in a large saute pan. Add the red pepper
flakes and the garlic, saute over low heat until the garlic just
begins to release its aroma, about 1 minute. Remove the pan from
the heat before the garlic begins to brown.
</P>
<P>
   Return the pasta and broccoli to the stockpot. Add the
garlic-olive oil mixture and the reserved pasta water. Stir over
low heat for 1 minute to combine. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the pasta with a drizzle of olive oil. Garnish with the
optional cheese or pine nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; Orecchiette pasta, which literally means ``little ears''
because of its cupped shape, is becoming much more widely available
in grocery stores. Its chewy texture contrasts well with the
softness of the broccoli, and the cups pick up the sauce perfectly.
If you can't find orecchiette, substitute fusilli.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 605 calories, &LR;   &LR; 21 g protein, 98 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 16 g fat (2 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 65 mg
sodium, 7 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; 30-MINUTE MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SMOKED TROUT SALAD WITH CHICKPEAS, OLIVES &AMP; CREAMY CILANTRO
DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Dressing
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons minced cilantro
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Dash cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   The Salad
</P>
<P>
   1 head romaine lettuce
</P>
<P>
   1/3 to 1/2 pound smoked trout (see note), flaked into bite-sized
pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pint dry-cured olives, pitted
</P>
<P>
   1 cup canned chickpeas, drained and rinsed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 red onion, sliced paper thin
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the vinegar, lemon juice, yogurt, cilantro, salt,
pepper and cayenne. Set aside at room temperature while you
construct the salad.
</P>
<P>
   Trim off and discard the 2 inches of dark bitter green at the
leafy end of the romaine lettuce. Slice the remaining inner leaves
into 2-inch pieces. Discard the stem ends, and wash and pat dry the
leaves. Place them in a large bowl with the other salad
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the olive oil into the vinegar mixture and adjust the
seasoning, making sure you have a good balance of acidity and oil.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the salad in the dressing and serve it with hearty Italian
bread.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; Smoked trout is available at Whole Foods, Real Food,
Draeger's, Andronico's and other specialty markets. Smoked salmon
or whitefish is a good substitute.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 510 calories, &LR;   &LR; 14 g protein, 19 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 44 g fat (14 g saturated), 24 mg cholesterol, 1,171
mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 4 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; NOW &AMP; LATER &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ROASTED CORN-CHIPOTLE CHOWDER
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to freeze part of this chowder, do not add the
mashed potato and cream until just before serving. Heat the
defrosted soup for 5 minutes with the mashed potato and cream.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   5 ears fresh corn, husked
</P>
<P>
   2 red bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   3 jumbo russet potatoes, peeled
</P>
<P>
   6 slices bacon, cut in small dice (optional)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, cut in small dice
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   8 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 canned chipotle chiles, removed from their sauce, seeded and
finely diced (about 2 teaspoons total) (see note)
</P>
<P>
   2 tomatoes, seeded and cut into small dice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Roast the corn either on a grill, in a heavy cast-iron pan over
low heat or directly over a gas burner, turning until all the
kernels take on a smoky hue. Cut the kernels from the cobs,
reserving 2 of the cobs.
</P>
<P>
   Roast the bell peppers on the grill or under the broiler,
turning as the skin blackens on each side. Place the roasted
peppers in a plastic bag; seal and allow them to steam while you
prepare the other ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Cut 2 of the of the potatoes into small dice; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Quarter the remaining potato and cover it with water in a small
saucepan. Cook until tender, about 15 minutes. Mash this potato
coarsely with a fork and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Fry the optional bacon in a large heavy stock pot until almost
crunchy, about 5 minutes. Drain off most of the bacon grease. Melt
the butter in the pan, add the onion and saute until translucent, 7
to 10 minutes. Add the garlic and saute a few more minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Deglaze the pan with the broth. Add the reserved corn cobs,
diced potatoes, mashed potato, chipotle peppers and tomatoes. Bring
to a boil, and season with salt and pepper. Reduce to a simmer and
cook until the potato pieces are cooked through, about 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While the soup is cooking, remove the loosened skin from the
peppers. Discard the seeds and membrane and cut the flesh into
small dice.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the cobs from the soup and add the corn kernels, roasted
red pepper and cream. Simmer until heated through, about 5 minutes.
Adjust for seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with warm tortillas or cornbread and a green salad.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; You usually can find canned chipotle chiles in the
Hispanic food isle in supermarkets. Remove the peppers from their
sauce and slice them in half. Scrape off the seeds and mince into a
pulp. Any remaining peppers, when kept in sauce and tightly
wrapped, will keep well in the refrigerator for a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 235 calories, &LR;   &LR; 6 g protein, 18 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 16 g fat (9 g saturated), 52 mg cholesterol, 99 mg sodium, 2 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
