<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
Editors' Note: Introduction followed by main story in one take.
Freezer basics, pantry essentials, hurry up tips and recipes in
another take. 
 
 THE WORKING COOK: A new game plan for cooks who want fresh flavor 
 but don't have time to fuss.   Introduction 
   
 By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Surveys continue to show that the Bay Area palate
differs from other parts of the country. We drink fewer carbonated
sodas and eat fewer canned goods than anybody else in the country.
And we love wine, fresh salads, eggs, yogurt and bottled water.
 &HT;    We also dine out more than anybody else, and we don't mind
spending a little extra to get really good food. At home and in
restaurants, fresh is our mantra.
 &HT;    However, when it comes to time constraints, we're like everyone
else. It seems that all the recent inventions _ computers, cellular
phones and faxes that have become a part of our daily lives _ only
load more burdens onto our day. And let's not even talk about the
commute to and from the office.
 &HT;    So what's a food lover to do?
 &HT;    The Chronicle's Food staff has come up with a new game plan for
getting delicious meals on the table in a hurry. The result is The
Working Cook, which debuts today. This new weekly column by staff
writer Tara Duggan offers a three-prong approach to everyday
cooking. If you use all of Tara's suggestions, a family of four can
have meals on the table five nights a week.
 &HT;    The first recipe, called Now &AMP; Later, is designed to be cooked
on the weekend; this is a big recipe _ enough to serve 12. It can
function as dinner on the night it's prepared, with enough stored
in the freezer for two future meals.
 &HT;    The 30-Minute recipe is just that _ preparation of the recipe
takes a half-hour or less. Even at that speed, with Tara's creative
twists and turns it is often special enough for a dinner party.
 &HT;    The last recipe _ called Fast 5 _ is even quicker. It has just
five ingredients, not counting salt and pepper, and can be on the
table in 20 minutes or less.
 &HT;    In addition, today's Food Section is also packed with tips,
ideas and suggestions for preparing your kitchen and pantry to
battle the clock. Just because you don't have a lot of time to cook
doesn't mean you have to compromise your taste buds.
 &HT;     
 
 THE WORKING COOK: Game Plan for Cooks in a Time Crunch 
 &HT;       
 By Tara Duggan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  Whether you're the kind who orchestrates
complicated dinner parties every weekend or who barely cares to
cook, the daily grind of coming home from work and racing the clock
to prepare a quick homemade meal can be daunting.
<P>
   A fresh meal in 30 minutes? What about in 20? And without the
likes of Hamburger Helper?
</P>
<P>
   That's the purpose of this column. Utilizing a handful of fresh
ingredients and a few simple cooking techniques, it is possible to
prepare recipes that are not only fast but delicious.
</P>
<P>
   You can broil chicken breasts in seven minutes, pan-fry salmon
fillets in under five minutes, and stir-fry tofu or steam mussels
in under four. Add to these exciting ingredients like piquant
achiote paste or wheaty Israeli couscous, and suddenly you've got a
great ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   begin trim? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Each week this column will feature three recipes, each from a
different category _ Now &AMP; Later, 30-Minute and Fast 5.
</P>
<P>
   If you follow this column, you will have five easy meals every
week, inspired by a wide range of cuisines. And each column
provides a mix of meat, poultry, seafood and vegetarian options.
</P>
<P>
   In this week's Fast 5 recipe, Orecchiette Pasta with Broccoli,
the broccoli is cut up fine and cooked at the same as the pasta.
The broccoli becomes the main ingredient in the sauce when sauteed
with the three remaining ingredients _ olive oil, garlic and red
chile flakes. The pasta, named ``little ears'' because of its
cupped shape, adheres to the sauce perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   This recipe derives from Orecchiette con Cima di Rapa, a
specialty of Puglia, a region in Italy. The traditional version
features broccoli rabe (also called rapini), a bitter, delicately
flowered cousin of broccoli. Although broccoli rabe has a
wonderfully pungent bite, you can also use regular broccoli in this
southern Italian comfort food.
</P>
<P>
   In this week's 30-Minute recipe, canned chickpeas elevate smoked
trout salad to a satisfying main course. The smoky,
melt-in-your-mouth trout is offset by complex flavors and textures
_ briny olives, crisp romaine, sweet red onions, nutty chickpeas
and a citrusy cilantro dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Roasted Corn-Chipotle Chowder, the Now &AMP; Later recipe, also
makes a hearty one-course meal. Roasted bell peppers and a touch of
fiery chipotle chiles combine for an earthy backdrop to the sweet
corn. Served with warm tortillas and a fresh green salad, it will
remind you of summer when you defrost it and serve it in the autumn
weeks ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
