<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REAL-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GET REAL': TV THAT SENDS UP TV 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time and station are
for New York area; see local listings.) 
(mk) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Get Real'' makes two obvious assumptions about its viewers:
They have watched lots of television, and they're not afraid to use
their brains a little. If the second of these isn't overly
optimistic, ``Get Real'' could get established.
</P>
<P>
   This family series, which Fox is unveiling Wednesday night,
never stops reminding you that you're watching television, not
life, and that there's nothing real about ``Get Real.'' The
white-bread upper-middle-class family _ overworked and unusually
attractive Mom and Dad, three glib teen-agers and sage, recently
widowed Grandma _ comes right out of a mail-order Make Your Own
Prime-Time Series kit. So when the younger characters start sharing
their innermost thoughts with you, you're not surprised.
</P>
<P>
   But quite early in the game, the show throws you a curve. The
brilliant daughter, the oldest of the children, doesn't merely tell
you what she's thinking. She says, ``I know what you're thinking.''
You're thinking that this is another one of those shows ``where the
kids talk to the audience, like, um, `Dawson's Creek,''' which she
declares she would never watch. Why not? ``There is nothing more
obnoxious than self-aware teens who know more about life's
mysteries than their parents.''
</P>
<P>
   But that, of course, is just what this show is lobbing you. Here
are the high school senior Meghan Green (Anne Hathaway) and her
younger brothers, Cameron (Eric Christian Olsen), the goofy
skateboarder who follows his hormones, and the sensitive Kenny
(Jesse Eisenberg), who's tortured by his. Their stressed-out
parents, Mitch (Jon Tenney) and Mary (Debrah Farentino), can't
figure out where their lives have gone, while Mary's mother,
Elizabeth (Christina Pickles), who does seem to understand where
her life has gone, looks on knowingly.
</P>
<P>
   The Greens may be suffering, but the show's creator, Clyde
Phillips, seems to be having a wonderful time. Phillips, who wrote
Wednesday night's pilot, also originated the long-running (but
ordinary) ``Suddenly Susan'' and the short-lived (but wonderfully
quirky) ``Parker Lewis Can't Lose.'' His ideas are sharp, but his
barbs, appropriately, are not lethal. His obvious affection for his
medium gives the show a knowing wink, rather than a frigid leer.
</P>
<P>
   Among the principals, the young actors, especially Eisenberg,
are quietly winning. The grown-ups succeed a little too well in
impersonating generic television characters.
</P>
<P>
   The plot is standard television fare, too: coming-of-age angst
with parental midlife crises for counterpoint. But the writing can
be surprisingly funny. When Kenny's best friend ends a pep talk
with ``Two words, amigo: Carpe diem,'' the confused Kenny asks,
``Fish of the day?''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the humor, however, comes from sending up other
television shows, including ``My So-Called Life,'' ``E.R.,''
``Seventh Heaven'' and, by extension, every turgid family saga
since ``Mama.'' When Mitch and Mary pause in their bickering, she
says, ``If this were `Cheers,' we'd be having sex right now.'' And
when Kenny is flattened by a blow from the school bully, his friend
exclaims (what else?): ``Oh, my God! You killed Kenny!''
</P>
<P>
   You have to work a bit to keep up with all that Phillips is
dishing out. While every inch of the show tells you not to take
anything seriously, he is somehow asking you to share the
characters' emotions. And in spite of yourself, you agree.
</P>
<P>
   You might want to get a look at this show soon. Once word leaks
out that there are ideas in play here, who knows what could happen?
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `GET REAL'
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday at 9 p.m. ET on Fox (Channel 5 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Clyde Phillips, executive producer. Robert Lloyd Lewis,
co-executive producer. Pam Veasey, producer. Scott Winant,
director. A production of Clyde Phillips Productions in association
with 20th Century Fox Television.
</P>
<P>
   With: Jon Tenney (Mitch), Debrah Farentino (Mary), Christina
Pickles (Elizabeth), Anne Hathaway (Meghan), Eric Christian Olsen
(Cameron) and Jesse Eisenberg (Kenny).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1659EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3426 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OLYMPIC-BUSES08-COX     09-07 2044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPIC-BUSES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Report on Olympic bid left out some details _ like 50 buses
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Billy Payne first outlined the Atlanta Olympic
bid committee's excesses for Congress, he conceded, among other
things, that it ``facilitated'' the donation of a used MARTA bus to
Lima, Peru.
</P>
<P>
   It was a generous gift presented with much fanfare by Mayor
Maynard Jackson and gratefully acknowledged by International
Olympic Committee member Ivan Dibos, a Lima councilman who would be
voting in a few months for the host city of the 1996 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the gift went over so well that on the eve of the vote
in Tokyo on Sept. 18, 1990, a far more generous offer to Dibos was
planned. How would he like 50 buses for his hometown?
</P>
<P>
   That offer was not mentioned in the Atlanta team's original June
1 report to the U.S. House Commerce Committee, which is looking
into the Olympic bid process. But it is documented in the materials
that fill three dozen boxes being pored over by federal
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   They discovered more unreported expensive gifts and favors for
IOC members and their families. Some offers of college assistance,
jobs and excursions to the city _ with side visits to Disney World
and Georgia's Augusta National Golf Club _ were not cited in the
original report to Congress. Nor were some gifts of clothing,
jewelry and art objects.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Atlanta Olympic team's lawyers at King &AMP;
Spalding are immersed in the uncomfortable task of rewriting the
report, which they say will be delivered soon.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Echols, a spokesman for Olympic officials and their legal
team, said they would not comment on specifics until the updated
report is submitted. He described the initial report as ``our first
attempt at responding to the committee's concerns. And we did the
best job we could. Now, given more time for a complete review, we
believe that our supplemental report will do the job thoroughly.''
</P>
<P>
   King &AMP; Spalding allowed The Atlanta Journal-Constitution to
review 29 of the 36 boxes last week at its offices in Washington,
D.C. The material made it clear why congressional investigators had
many more questions.
</P>
<P>
   Payne and his aides were meticulous record-keepers who discarded
little, if anything. The files contain thousands of letters, memos,
invoices and canceled checks. They trace a difficult-to-follow
trail of Payne's successful strategy that won the hearts and votes
of the 86 IOC members from around the world who had the singular
responsibility of anointing one lucky city in the quest for the
1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
   Payne's plan included lavishing first-class travel and
entertainment and personal gifts on the delegates and their
families in an exuberant display of Southern hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta officials admitted in their initial report that 38 gifts
exceeded a $200 IOC limit. The presents ranged from a collection of
surgical instruments costing $318 for the member from Cameroon to
an $875 English bulldog for the member from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But there was more, according to the new documents. A $265
camera was purchased for an Algerian, a $222 Chanel scarf for one
of the two wives of the Swaziland voter. Those gifts and others,
accumulated during shopping sprees in Atlanta by bid team hosts and
hostesses, were omitted from the original report.
</P>
<P>
   And when the bulldog, named ``Billy'' by the Cuban, died the
following spring, Payne offered a replacement. No document could be
found to indicate whether ``Billy II'' was delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Documents show that the Atlanta group circumvented the $200
limit in many instances by taking wives to several mall stores and
buying them numerous gifts, each within the allowable range.
</P>
<P>
   No gift proposal approached the scale of the 50 MARTA buses
offered to Dibos, which was documented by three letters in the
boxes that outlined the deal.
</P>
<P>
   In one, from Dibos to then-MARTA general manager Ken Gregor and
dated Oct. 12, 1990, the Peruvian thanked Gregor for his ``kind
letter'' and expressed hope that ``the city of Lima still has the
chance to acquire the 50 buses available offered ...''
</P>
<P>
   Dibos sent Payne a letter three days later and included a copy
of his correspondence with Gregor. Dibos congratulated Payne for
winning the Olympic vote and said he is ``proud that our friendship
was a strong one no matter what the outcome in Tokyo had been.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, he told Payne he was ``accepting generous offer of 50
buses'' and added that ``your assistance in expediting same will be
greatly appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   The files provided to the newspaper contained no confirmation of
the delivery of the buses, and MARTA records do not indicate that
such a transfer occurred. Gregor, reached while on vacation in
Hungary, said he did not recall the transaction. Interviewed on a
conference call with Horace Sibley, a bid team attorney, Gregor
said, ``Those letters do not ring any bells to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Echols acknowledged the offer of buses to Dibos but said he had
no record of their delivery. Echols said he believed the buses were
not a gift but offered for sale, although he did not know a price.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Atlanta Organizing Committee (the bid team) had no
involvement in setting the terms of this potential transaction,''
Echols said. ``We were merely a facilitator.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne, in a letter to then-Lima mayor Ricardo Belmont, dated
Sept. 25, 1990, thanked the mayor for his help and urged him to
``please check with Ivan (Dibos) regarding other bus information
that we delivered to him in Tokyo.'' Ironically, the documents
indicated that the offer of buses failed to reach Dibos before the
vote. Gregor's letter was either misdated or postdated Sept. 25 _
one week after the vote. Dibos did not receive the letter until he
returned to Peru.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The letter) has recently been sent to Lima together with
another group of letters not given to me by the (Tokyo) hotel at
such time,'' Dibos wrote to Gregor, apparently concerned that the
offer might no longer stand since the vote had been conducted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do hope the city of Lima still has the chance to acquire the
50 buses available offered and not getting to talk to Morris
Dillard (a MARTA official and later an Atlanta Olympic group
executive) in Tokyo for reasons above could have made you think
different,'' Dibos wrote. He went on to tell Gregor the city needed
5,000 buses, although he noted it was the ``responsibility of the
central government'' to acquire them.
</P>
<P>
   Dibos, an IOC member since 1982 who succeeded his father, denied
knowledge of the transaction when questioned by a
Journal-Constitution reporter last week even though his signature
appears on the correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a letter like that, someone has commited forgery
with my name,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The records indicate the Atlanta bid team arrived in Tokyo laden
with expensive gifts, if not buses.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 28, 21 days before the ballotting, Ginger Watkins spent
$2,694 at Tiffany &AMP; Co., collecting 10 ``rope pins with 18 kt.
accents'' at $185 each, 10 oval compacts at $70 each, a ``frog on
lilly pad'' box for $150, and other baubles.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 7, Watkins bought a jewelry box for $616 and a travel
clock for $318. The total tab at Tiffany was $3,849. The next day,
she picked up $2,449 worth of six unique sculptures from the Frabel
Gallery in Buckhead. The six gifts, wrapped and presented the day
before the vote in Tokyo, included a $424 soccer sculpture given to
Maurice Herzog of France.
</P>
<P>
   A shopping trip to Neiman-Marcus yielded several pricy Steuben
crystal sculptures, including a $457 crystal skier presented two
days before the vote to Marc Hodler of Switzerland. Hodler is the
IOC member who blew the whistle on the Olympic bribery scandal last
winter, alleging that bid groups routinely offered bribes in
exchange for votes.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th-hour bounty appears to have been documented in the
original report. Many more gifts did not exceed the $200 limit and
therefore were not recorded. They included a $172 sports coat and
shirts produced by a South Korean haberdasher for Virgilio de Leon
from Panama. The gift suggestion originated in a memo Payne wrote
in August that listed a number of ideas for last-minute items for
IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   When the memo first emerged from Olympic files this spring,
Payne denied writing it, then insisted he never sent it or acted
upon it.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, de Leon was not in Tokyo for the vote. But the
documents indicate Payne mailed the suit to him in Panama with a
letter that said, ``We would like to send to you that which we had
intended to give to you in Tokyo, custom-made clothing from our
mutual friend Johnny La in Seoul. We remain anxious to receive you
in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne and his team invited IOC members and their families to
Atlanta over and over again. A few never visited; others came
frequently. Agustin Arroyo traveled from Ecuador six times, always
with his wife. Four of the visits were before the vote, and two
were to help celebrate the victory. The Atlanta group's report to
Congress listed only three visits.
</P>
<P>
   A profile contained in his file in the Olympic records
characterized the Arroyos as ``delightful people who love to
travel, be entertained and are most entertaining themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arroyos were flown first-class, lodged at the Marriott
Marquis and feted in the city's finest restaurants or private homes
in Buckhead. The bid team chartered a luxury coach to take them and
others to a Georgia Tech-Georgia football game. They were given
tickets to the musical ``Cats'' at the Fox Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins noted in an August 1990 memo that the Arroyos never
``asked for anything while here. He paid for everything he
purchased.'' Except, apparently, a $474 ruby pin from Macy's bought
while the couple was in town earlier that month, according to the
initial report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But in another memo, Watkins noted that ``Agustin's grandson
wants to come to the Bolletierri Tennis Camp next summer. I found
out through his daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   While there is no indication that the youth received a
scholarship to the prestigious Florida tennis camp, the bidders _
at the request of IOC member Jean-Claude Ganga _ spent at least
$14,099 to train two teenagers from the Republic of Congo at the
camp, according to the original report.
</P>
<P>
   The bid team dangled tennis camp scholarships in front of other
IOC members, according to correspondence in the boxes, but there is
no indication of those being accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Despite previous denials by Payne, there is much evidence of
college assistance. Bid team officials offered their help in
admitting IOC members' relatives and securing scholarships, a
practice of 2002 Winter Games bidders in Salt Lake City that
launched the influence-peddling scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The documents did not indicate Atlanta officials paid for
scholarships, but they apparently used their connections at state
universities _ which benefited handsomely from hosting Olympics
events _ to bypass standard admissions procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Bid team member Bobby Rearden wrote in one memo that he offered
a University of Georgia tennis scholarship to the daughter of
Hungarian IOC member Pal Schmitt. The young woman wound up at a
California university.
</P>
<P>
   The son of IOC member Ram Ruhee was admitted to Georgia Tech
with the Atlanta committee's assistance. He stayed one semester
before returning home to Mauritius.
</P>
<P>
   And the favors continued after Atlanta won the Games. The
stepson of Russian member Vitaly Smirnov enrolled at Tech to attend
an English program in 1991, and then, with the help of Watkins,
secured a work permit and a job with the Atlanta Committee for the
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Payne faxed a letter to Smirnov in July 1991, saying, ``I am
delighted to inform you that our mutual friend reported to work
Wednesday morning and before he received a first pay check is
inquiring about an automobile and drivers license. What do you
think? Should I proceed to help him with this request?''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Turner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. David Pendered and Arthur Brice contributed to this
report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
