<SLUG> BC-STATES-FUND-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;   &QL;  &UR; LAWMAKERS PREPARE FOR BUDGET BATTLE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Jonathan Lipman &QL;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   States News Service &QL;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Sept. 7 -- As members of Congress streamed back into
the nation's capital Tuesday after a month-long holiday from the
inexorable math of the federal budget, supporters and critics of
the nation's space agency prepared to do battle over next year's
space programs.
</P>
<P>
   The House is scheduled to debate and vote on the VA-HUD
Appropriations bill on Wednesday. The bill sets the yearly funding
levels for independent federal agencies like the Veterans Affairs
office, the Department of Housing and Urban Development, and the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration - NASA.
</P>
<P>
   Because the NASA budget is part of this larger bill, its future
is inextricably linked to those other agencies. Under current House
rules and the 1997 budget resolution, the amount of money in each
appropriations bill cannot increase once it leaves the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, it is unlikely that the NASA budget will get
increased in the House bill from its current proposal of $12.7
billion, a nearly $1 billion cut from this year's level and the
president's request for next year. The Senate has not written its
version of the bill yet.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the national budget debate has fallen along clearly
partisan lines as the Republican Congress has pushed its tax cut
and spending priorities over President Clinton's proposed budget.
</P>
<P>
   But the partisan lines on the NASA budget have blurred. Rep.
Jerrold Nadler, D- N.Y., will introduce an amendment on the floor
to pull another $305 million from the space station budget to go
towards public housing, which he believes is ``severely
under-funded'' in the VA-HUD bill, spokesman Brett Heimov. said.
</P>
<P>
   Nadler thinks that the ISS will not really be able to run any
scientific experiments that the Shuttle couldn't run in another
form for much less money, Heimov said. Nadler is a ``space buff''
who decided this based on ``his own personal research,'' Heimov
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believes in NASA, he believes in technology development,''
Heimov said. ``He just feels the space station has gotten to the
point where it is not serving its purpose. It would be a waste of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Also crossing party lines is Rep. David Weldon, R-Fla., who in
July was one of the first to declare that he would fight the cuts.
Weldon's 15th district includes Cape Canaveral and the Kennedy
Space Center, the busiest spaceport in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there are changes to the NASA budget, he plans on
voting against the entire bill,'' said Weldon's legislative
director, Stuart Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Burns said Weldon is not sure whether he will offer an amendment
to the spending bill, but he plans to speak on the floor during the
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Weldon has already spoken to Florida Senators Bob Graham and
Connie Mack about NASA's chances once the Senate takes up the
VA-HUD bill in late September, Burns said. None of the three
Florida lawmakers will sit on the conference committee since none
is on an appropriations committee.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the pro-NASA forces will probably be Rep. Steny Hoyer,
D-Md. The 10- term congressman's fifth district includes NASA's
Goddard center, and Hoyer has always fought hard for the agency.
However, spokeswoman Debra DeShong said that while he will make a
public appeal and a speech on the floor asking for a restoration in
NASA funding, he will not offer an amendment that could do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't any money to do it with,'' DeShong said, referring
to the spending limits placed on the bill. Instead, Hoyer will make
``a number of comments'' on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``His point will be that not only does NASA do research and make
technology breakthroughs in space science, but there are so many
practical things that NASA does that we never even realize,''
DeShong said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyer is also working with a number of other Representatives in
Colorado, Texas and California, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The VA-HUD appropriations bill is scheduled for debate in the
House at the start of business tomorrow at 10 a.m. The Senate will
then draft its version of the bill later this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
