<HEADLINE>
`SAM AND COKIE' TO AIR EARLIER IN NEW YORK; BRYANT GUMBEL'S NEW
PARTNER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, N.Y.)   (bl)  
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Wake-Up Call On Sundays
</P>
<P>
   There will be no sleepy, lazy Sundays for New York viewers
accustomed to the late morning start of ``This Week With Sam
Donaldson and Cokie Roberts.''
</P>
<P>
   That 10:30 a.m. ritual, which has endured for nearly two
decades, comes to an end this weekend when ABC's second-place
Sunday morning program will be shown live in the New York area at 9
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The switch in time slots is a reflection of the changing habits
of viewers, who show a penchant for rising earlier, and the
increased competition among the Sunday morning programs like ``This
Week'' and NBC's top-ranked ``Meet the Press,'' which is broadcast
in New York at 10:30 a.m. but taped at 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tells you a lot about life styles,'' said Ms. Roberts.
``We're finding it's just too late to have the show on at 10:30
a.m. on Sunday morning for most people. They're up. They're out. At
church or out with the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC is experimenting with the new time slot in New York, but it
hopes the early morning start will spread to other affiliates if it
is successful. It also may prevent the frantic morning scurrying of
some guests, who will no longer have time to make appearances on
different programs on the same Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This probably should have been done sooner rather than
later,'' said Dorrance Smith, the executive producer of the
program, who helped create ``This Week'' in 1981 and has watched
the competition multiply to include shows on Fox, CNN and MSNBC.
``It is a very crowded field competing for a very limited number of
guests. It's clear that the news viewer is not going to wait around
with all the other competition. The environment has changed, and
we're changing with the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel's New Partner
</P>
<P>
   CBS's summerlong search for a suitable morning show co-anchor
for Bryant Gumbel has ended with the selection of Jane Clayson, a
32-year-old Los Angeles correspondent for ABC.
</P>
<P>
   The pick comes just in time for the scheduled November premiere
of CBS's revamped morning program, but the network is
diplomatically waiting to release the information, given the
expected surge of headlines about Viacom's announced purchase of
CBS for $37 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The hunt for the ``Early Show'' co-anchor was jokingly termed
Operation Glass Slipper at CBS, but the search unfolded more like a
vexing game of Clue. Ms. Clayson's name had surfaced earlier but
initially as a prospect for a news reader who could later be
promoted to co-anchor. Such a scenario presented contract problems
for Ms. Clayson at ABC, which apparently have now been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   CBS had planned to make its long-awaited announcement on Labor
Day, but it now appears that will come Wednesday. . That leaves CBS
just a few weeks to mount a recognition campaign for Ms. Clayson,
who has been an ABC correspondent since 1997. She graduated from
Brigham Young University in 1990 with a journalism degree and
worked for six years at a Salt Lake City station as a reporter and
anchor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
