<P>
   WACO-RESIDENTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ For more than six years, Brenda Carpenter has
lived with the stigma of being from a city people associate with
renegade cults; gruesome, fiery deaths; and overzealous law
enforcement. ``I wish people would just let it rest,'' said
Carpenter, 43, a pharmaceutical technician who lives in the Waco,
Texas, suburb of Elm Mott. Whether Waco residents like it or not,
the events at Mount Carmel in 1993 will not likely let them rest
for some time. The city is in the news again after the Federal
Bureau of Investigation recently disclosed after years of denials
that it used pyrotechnic tear-gas canisters to help end a standoff
at the Branch Davidian compound. By JENNIFER AUTREY. Story has
moved in ``a'' general news category. Accompanied by
BC-WACO-TRUST. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WACO-TRUST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Revelations about the 1993 Branch Davidian siege in
Waco have inevitably raised the question: Whom can you trust? The
choice isn't easy. On the one hand, there are the conspiracy
theorists, who see shadowy black helicopters and Delta Force hit
squads doing Washington's dirty work. On the other are government
officials, who seem to have worked overtime withholding the truth
or downright lying. By BARRY SHLACHTER. Story has moved in ``a''
general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BAPTIST-JEWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Southern Baptists have produced a ``Jewish
prayer guide'' urging members to pray for the conversion of Jews to
Christianity during the High Holy Days of Rosh Hashana and Yom
Kippur beginning Friday. By JIM JONES. Story has moved in ``a''
general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GULF-DEAD ZONE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COCODRIE, La. _ Fifteen miles out in the Gulf of Mexico, schools
of fish _ sheepshead, drum, even a few snapper _ make their homes
amid the massive steel legs of an offshore oil rig. From the deck
of the research vessel Pelican, the marine life appears abundant
and the water remarkably clear. Only a skyline of oil platforms off
the Louisiana coast mars the pristine seascape. But as scuba divers
plunge into the ocean and swim to the base of the hulking oil
platform, they disappear into a layer of murky water. Below the
turbid water, a sickly looking jellyfish is the only sign of life.
The divers have entered the Dead Zone, a swath of water nearly the
size of New Jersey, stretching from the Mississippi River delta to
the Texas-Louisiana border. Monitoring devices at the base of the
platform confirm what the researchers' eyes tell them _ there isn't
enough oxygen in the water at a depth of 65 feet for fish to
survive. By BILL HANNA. Story will move in ``a'' general news
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FATHER-SUB SERVICE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ My father was a quiet, introspective man who
didn't talk much about World War II and his combat service aboard a
Navy submarine. When he died of lung cancer more than 11 years ago
_ passing away three hours after the birth of my son, Ben _ he took
his stories with him. Ben and my daughter, Johanna, who was born
three years later, ask about Grandpa Baker. To them, he's an
abstraction _ a photograph on a bookshelf, a guy my mom talks about
when we visit her in Missouri. So when a friend told me the U.S.
Submarine Veterans of World War II were holding their annual
convention in Fort Worth this year, I decided to stop by _ to see
if I could answer a few questions about my dad for my kids. And for
myself. By MAX B. BAKER. Story has moved in ``a'' general news
category. (Accompanied by an info box, BC-SUB SERVICE-HAMMERHEAD.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
