<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3501 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r w BC-CONGRESS-RETURNS-TEX     09-07 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-RETURNS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS UPBEAT ON EVE OF CONGRESSIONAL SESSION
</HEADLINE>
 By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Republicans started their monthlong
summer recess determined to rally Americans behind their
legislative agenda, but the 106th Congress returns to work
Wednesday with Democrats convinced that they are in the driver's
seat.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the issue is tax cuts, health care or guns, Democrats
can point to polls indicating that voters are on their side. Their
brash confidence contrasts with the mood among Republicans and
their allies, who are bracing for a series of year-end legislative
brawls.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a very difficult Congress,'' said Thomas
Donohue, president of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, who fears that
Republican leaders will surrender to President Clinton. ``It's
going to get very hairy.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Republicans hold majorities in both the House and
Senate, their numerical advantage may be offset by splits within
the party and the power of Clinton's veto. With an eye toward next
year's elections, Clinton has signaled that he is eager to take on
Republican congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't consider himself a lame duck, that is clear,'' said
Rep. Martin Frost, D-Dallas. ``They're just heading blindly down
the path and Clinton's going to hit them right between the eyes.
They're like the Missouri mule. You've got to keep hitting them on
the head with a hammer to get their attention.''
</P>
<P>
   It may sound like gridlock as usual, but nearly every American
has a stake in the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP's far-reaching $792 billion package of tax cuts would
reduce taxes on stock profits and other capital gains, ease the
burden on married taxpayers and make it easier for self-employed
workers to get health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, Democrats say the lost tax revenue would force
big cuts in federal spending on everything from national parks to
the Head Start preschool program.
</P>
<P>
   But the dispute over tax cuts is just one item on the crowded
congressional agenda. Over the next several weeks, lawmakers expect
to deal with health care overhaul, campaign finance reform, gun
control and the federal aviation programs.
</P>
<P>
   They also face an Oct. 1 deadline to complete work on 11 of the
13 spending bills needed to keep the government operating in the
next fiscal year. Congressional leaders hope to adjourn for the
year Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   With so much at stake, House Republicans fanned out during the
August recess with ambitious plans to turn public opinion their
way. The effort, which organizers call ``Takin' It To The
Streets,'' involved more the 600 town hall meetings and other
grassroots events.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical example, House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas
underscored his opposition to estate taxes by hosting a town hall
meeting that included a visit from the Grim Reaper. But even Armey
concedes that the public relations effort did not produce a
dramatic shift in voter attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Polls consistently show that tax cuts take a back seat to Social
Security, health care and reducing the federal debt on the list of
voters' concerns. Only 7 percent of the respondents in a CBS poll
last month listed tax cuts as a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't expect to reorder the priorities of the American
people,'' Armey said. ``They say people don't want tax reductions.
That's not exactly true. They don't want it most.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey said Republicans plan to send their tax bill to Clinton
for his certain veto soon after Congress reconvenes. The veto is
expected to lead to negotiations over a scaled-back tax cut that
could increase tensions between Republican hard-liners and
moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue, the Chamber of Commerce president, is urging House
leaders to delay the fight with Clinton for a year-end showdown.
The strategy is similar to the chain of events that led to the 1995
government shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether the Congress is smart enough, in our opinion, to hold
onto this deal until the card game starts, I don't know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are also divided over how to deal with health care.
At least 20 Republicans have endorsed legislation by Rep. John
Dingell, D-Mich., and Rep. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga., that would give
consumers and doctors more clout in disputes with insurance
companies and health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the public supports our position on the patients' bill
of rights. I can't imagine the Republicans winning on this issue,''
Frost said. ``I can't believe that they haven't heard the exact
same thing in their districts, it is so uniform and so across the
board.''
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan package includes provisions that would make it
easier for consumers to take their complaints to court.
Conservatives and business groups adamantly oppose the change, but
they acknowledge that political momentum is not on their side.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a tough one,'' Armey said. ``Right now, there seems to
be a feeling that you can't pass anything that doesn't have some
form of litigation in it. I'm not happy about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither is Donohue, who contends that legislation tilted too far
toward Clinton's views would prompt some employers to drop existing
health insurance plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a very, very emotional and difficult time
on health care. If we don't get past the anecdotal emotions, then
we can really screw up the best health care system in the world,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook for gun control is more complicated. Although polls
show that most Americans favor stricter gun control, neither party
is united on the issue. Conservative Democrats tend to side with
Republicans in opposing gun controls; moderate Republicans often
join Democrats in backing restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   At times, even allies disagree on the details. Texas Gov. George
W. Bush, who generally opposes gun control, recently endorsed a
proposal to increase the minimum age for handgun purchases from 18
to 21 and to ban high-capacity ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate the presidential candidate's commentary on the
matter, but this is a legislative process,'' Armey said in voicing
his opposition.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
