<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3502 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX     09-07 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCKY STRIKE COLORS, BOTTLED WATER STORAGE, IVORY SHAMPOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Before World War II, Lucky Strike cigarettes came in a green
package, but they switched to white with the slogan ``Lucky Strike
green has gone to war.'' Did they ever bring back green?
</P>
<P>
   _ S.R.S., Westboro, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: Green packages returned briefly for a 1986 event celebrating
70 years of production, according to the Antique Advertising
Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   The change to white packages was made in 1942 ``due to the
demand for green pigment for the war effort, and pressure from
consumers that disliked the green pack,'' according to a Lucky
Strike history published by the association.
</P>
<P>
   The Lucky Strike company was founded in 1871 by R.A. Patterson,
and the name refers to the gold rush. The American Tobacco Company,
which acquired Patterson's company in 1905, introduced Lucky Strike
cigarettes in 1917. They used the same green package until 1940.
</P>
<P>
   The association has a Web site is at www.antiqueadvertising.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With all the hype about having bottled water on hand for Y2K,
I'm worried about the expiration dates on gallon jugs. Does water
spoil?
</P>
<P>
   _ D.J., LaBelle, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A: If stored properly, bottled water can be good indefinitely,
according to Bob Hirst, a director of the International Bottled
Water Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no problem drinking the water past the expiration
date,'' Hirst said. ``The date is not due to spoilage.''
</P>
<P>
   A New Jersey law requires a two-year expiration date on bottled
water sold in that state. Though Hirst knows of no other state with
a similar requirement, the use of expiration dates has been adopted
nationally by some bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   Bottled water should be stored at room temperature in a dry
environment away from chemicals such as solvents and household
cleaning products, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I reach the company that produces Ivory soap
products? I can't find Ivory shampoo.
</P>
<P>
   _ C.B., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Ivory Shampoo and Conditioner, which was introduced by
Procter &AMP; Gamble in 1984, was discontinued in January, according to
a company representative.
</P>
<P>
   To contact the company, call (800) 253-2756 or write to 1 P&AMP;G
Plaza, Cincinnati, OH 45202.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble also has an extensive Web site at www.pg.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at trivia(at)prefect.com or write him in
care of the Star-Telegram at Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0198 </DOCNO>
