<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Sept. 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unsettled weather will linger from the northern Appalachians to
the New England coast as low pressure drifts into southeastern
Canada. Mostly cloudy skies will cover the northern areas of New
York and New England where light showers and drizzle will persist,
especially over the higher terrain. Farther south, clouds will
yield to brighter skies, but scattered afternoon thunderstorms will
develop in the humid air.
</P>
<P>
   The day will begin with patchy low clouds from the eastern Great
Lakes to the Middle Atlantic States, but partly sunny conditions
will develop as drier air arrives from the west. Plentiful sun will
cover the eastern Ohio and Tennessee valleys.
</P>
<P>
   A broken band of potent thunderstorms will erupt during the
midday and afternoon near a front in the central Great Lakes
States. Some of the storms will contain damaging winds and hail.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the front, much cooler air will sweep from
central Canada into the northern parts of the Plains and
Mississippi Valley on gusty winds from the northwest. Clouds and a
few showers will dampen the eastern Dakotas and northern Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast will be very warm and humid. Most of the interior
will be dry, however, scattered afternoon thunderstorms will form
near the Gulf Coast. A cluster of locally heavy thundershowers will
erupt ahead of a cold front from northern Texas to the southern
Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, high pressure will promote abundant sunshine.
Afternoon temperatures will be several degrees above the seasonal
average in most areas.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: MOUNTAIN WARMTH
</P>
<P>
   So far September has been unusually warm atop New Hampshire's
Mt. Washington. Record temperatures have occurred on the mountain
from September 1 through 6, culminating in a 69 degree reading on
the 3rd, which is just 3 degrees shy of the highest temperature
ever recorded on the summit. Perched at an altitude of 6,262 feet,
Mt. Washington is the highest weather observatory east of the
Mississippi, and typically witnesses its first accumulating snow
during September. Cooler weather will return to the mountain later
this week, but snow is not expected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
