<P>
   DELTA-PILOTS _ ATLANTA _ Delta and its powerful pilot union open
negotiations Wednesday on a new contract, and the union is expected
to seek big wage increases and other significant contract changes.
Talks will be closely watched as Delta's new management tries to
avoid a meltdown a la american and northwest. A pre-game story with
interview with pilot union chief Chuck Giambusso. (Thurston,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/DELTA-AMAZON _ ATLANTA _ Warren Jenson, who created an
embarrasment for Delta Air Lines when a flight was delayed and some
first-class passengers pushed back to economy to accommodate
Jenson's children, leaves Delta for Amazon.com. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HBOC _ ATLANTA _ HBOC remains the nation's biggest seller of
medical billing software, despite the financial shenanigans that
were revealed after the company was purchased by San
Francisco-based McKesson. HBOC is still based in Atlanta and Miller
takes a look at how the company is attempting to rebuild its
credibility. McKesson HBOC has its annual meeting today in San
Francisco. (Miller, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   9999 _ Thursday is 9/9/99, one of the dates leading up to Y2K
that could provide some test opportunities for companies working on
their software. BellSouth, for example, plans a major test of its
systems starting today and for the rest of the week, intentionally
encompassing 9/9/99. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS _ NORCROSS, Ga. _ Norcross-based Home Wireless Networks
has a deal with British Telecom that BT says could be worth $50
million in the next year. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AGESPAN _ ATLANTA _ Atlanta-based Agespan.com to offer mature
Americans a high-end personal computer, color printer, 17-inch
monitor, special keyboard, special-click mouse, ISP, delivery and
set-up, training, unlimited support, exclusive on-line society and
e-commerce solution for a low monthly fee. Agespan.com announces a
breakthrough program for mature Americans to make the Internet work
for them. For as little as 49.95 a month, Agespan will provide
Americans over 50 the hardware, training, and information they need
to connect to the Internet. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EMPLOYEASE _ ATLANTA _ Atlanta-based Employease helps streamline
the HR process by offering online benefits selection to companies
all over the country and more specifically to MindSpring. Interview
with CEO and HR directors using their entirely Web-based service to
keep human resources costs and paperwork under control. (Katz,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN-COMPANY _ ATLANTA _ Southern Company, casting about for
ways to generate more income from its plants and wires, is testing
digital power line technology, a way to transmit data through
electric lines into residences and businesses. (Holsendolph,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-ACCESS _ ATLANTA _ Interview with the CEO of an Atlanta
company that has quietly grown to $1.2 billion, becoming in the
process one of the leaders in European long-distance. (Kanell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AMAZON-CFO _ Warren Jenson, who created a national embarrasment
for Delta Air Lines when a flight was delayed and some first-class
passengers were pushed back to economy to accommodate his children,
leaves the airline to become CFO at Amazon.com. Edward H. West, 33,
succeeds Jenson. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the
current week. This layout is now available.)
