<HEADLINE>
`BATFACE' CUPHEA KEEPS ON FLOWERING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: On a recent trip my wife purchased an interesting plant. She
was told that it is called the ``bat-faced'' plant. It has been a
good conversation piece. Any help would be appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   A: `Batface' cuphea is a drought-tolerant, sun-loving plant with
tiny blooms that resemble a bat's face. The ``face'' is purple; the
``ears'' are red. It flowers continuously spring through frost.
This low-maintenance, tough little plant will freeze back but may
return from the roots, depending on the severity of the weather.
Mature height may be 12 to 18 inches. I pinch mine so it won't be
so leggy. `Batface' does reseed somewhat, too. Kids love this
plant.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Please tell me how to care for a pineapple plant. Can the
pineapple be eaten? When do I cut it off?
</P>
<P>
   A: The pineapple is a bromeliad, and these plants like air
movement. Grow yours on the patio or deck in bright light, if
possible, during warm months. Place indoors during the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you can eat the fruit. After a pineapple flowers, fruit
will form. You know it's ready to eat when you notice a pineapple
fragrance. The fruit will give a little when squeezed and will turn
golden.
</P>
<P>
   It may take three or four years, but you can grow a pineapple
from fruit purchased at the grocery store. Buy a pineapple that
still has its top. At home, remove the top from the fruit, strip
off the bottom leaves, leaving 2 1/2 to 3 inches of solid stem.
Allow the top to dry for about three days.
</P>
<P>
   When the top has dried, plant it in a container full of good
potting soil, pushing the cut end into the medium. Keep the soil
moist, and the top should put out a good root system.
</P>
<P>
   Start with a small pot, and repot as necessary. Eventually the
plant will flower, followed by the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is this plant that is taking over our flower beds? How
can I get rid of it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The foliage you mailed in appears to be that of a dayflower.
There is a spreading dayflower and an erect dayflower. Both have
blue flowers, but the erect dayflower's bloom is about an inch wide
while that of the spreading type is about 3/8-inch. The erect
dayflower's bloom consists of two blue petals and one tiny whitish
one. The spreading dayflower has a single bloom emerging from the
boatlike spathe; the erect dayflower produces several buds in the
spathe. The foliage on the spreading dayflower may be up to 4
inches long, while that of the erect dayflower may reach 6 inches.
On both, the lancelike leaves sheath succulent stems.
</P>
<P>
   The spreading dayflower is an annual that creeps along, and the
stems root at the nodes. It reseeds, too. I pull it like crazy at
various times to keep it under control. In loose, organic soil, it
pulls up easily. Otherwise, I have to make sure I get all the
roots. You could spot-treat it with an herbicide, but since it is
growing among your flowers, this is risky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston TX 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents an individual reply to each unpublished letter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
