<HEADER>
A3525 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-BOOK-BAD-BOY-REVIEW-H     09-07 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BAD-BOY-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOPPINESS MARS COMPELLING TALE OF SERIAL KILLER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  ``Bad boy from Rosebud: The murderous life of Kenneth Allen
McDuff''; By Gary M. Lavergne; University of North Texas Press,
$29.95. 
 
By MIKE SNYDER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For his second book, Gary M. Lavergne chose a powerful subject
and plunged into his research, producing a wealth of facts,
anecdotes, observations and background. Then he sat down to
assemble this rich material into a book, and he made a hash of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad Boy From Rosebud'' suffers from sloppy editing and a level
of writing that ranges from competent to amateurish.
</P>
<P>
   This is a shame, because the story of Kenneth Allen McDuff is
significant on a number of levels. A good book about his life and
death would be an important asset to the body of nonfiction crime
literature.
</P>
<P>
   McDuff was a serial killer who achieved such depths of cruelty
that even staunch death-penalty opponents couldn't muster the will
to protest his execution last November. His release on parole in
1989 and his subsequent killing spree were important factors in
Texas' unprecedented prison-construction program and parole
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   On a personal level, McDuff inhabited a subculture of drugs,
prostitution and violence that, like other foul regions of society,
carries great literary potential. McDuff himself was a fascinating
and repugnant person, a worthy subject for a study of the internal
and external forces that create evil.
</P>
<P>
   Lavergne's first book was an account of Charles Whitman's 1966
shooting rampage from the University of Texas Tower in Austin, a
tragedy that left 14 people dead and 31 wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad Boy From Rosebud'' begins in promising fashion with a
serviceable description of Rosebud, the small Central Texas town
where McDuff grew up. Readers meet McDuff's family and learn about
his development as a childhood bully who, encouraged by a mother
who insisted he could do no wrong, consistently refused to take
responsibility for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   The narrative proceeds logically to a description of McDuff's
first killings _ the so-called ``Broomstick Murders'' of three high
school students near Fort Worth in 1966 _ and of McDuff's arrest,
conviction and death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence was commuted to life in prison when the U.S.
Supreme Court ruled in 1972 that the death penalty was
unconstitutional, and in 1989 McDuff was released on parole _ one
of a flood of dangerous prisoners released in response to pressure
to ease crowding in state prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, young women in Central Texas began disappearing.
Ultimately, McDuff would become a suspect in 15 murders.
</P>
<P>
   The book includes detailed, vivid descriptions of the two
slayings that led to capital-murder convictions and death sentences
for McDuff. The victims were Melissa Northrup, a 22-year-old
pregnant mother of two, whom McDuff abducted from a Waco
convenience store, and Colleen Reed, a 21-year-old accountant he
kidnapped from an Austin carwash.
</P>
<P>
   All of this makes for a compelling story. But Lavergne's telling
of it is marred by errors that a reader might expect to find in a
galley proof but that are inexcusable in a finished book. In at
least two instances, the past tense of ``to lie'' is expressed as
``laid'' (someone ``laid down''). In another passage, a car's brake
lights become ``break lights.''
</P>
<P>
   Occasional howlers in Lavergne's prose do nothing to improve the
reading experience. In a description of a peripheral character, he
writes: ``Below the ribs, in all directions, exploded a massive
stomach, so large that its front came to an apex at the
bellybutton, leading him as a stern sic leads a ship.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavergne also lapses into preachiness and moralism that are
hardly necessary in an account of a man whose monstrous deeds speak
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   He describes the natural beauty of Central Texas and the virtues
of most of its hard-working residents, then offers, in contrast, a
glimpse of lifestyles on the streets that McDuff prowled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who populate this subculture,'' Lavergne writes, ``live
in a world of their own _ largely unknown to the rest of Central
Texas. At first glance, the major difference between the two
cultures appears to be monetary; a closer look reveals more than
poverty. It reveals an absence of pride of any type and the lack of
social graces and any moral base upon which to gauge appropriate
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   The author's qualifications for such a sociological analysis are
not apparent. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
