<HEADER>
A3526 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-BOOK-SPACE-REVIEW-HNS     09-07 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SPACE-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVOCATE PRESENTS STRATEGY FOR SELF-SUFFICIENT INTERSTELLAR TRAVEL
IN LATEST BOOK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From time to time space buffs decry the absence of an articulate
visionary in their ranks, a guru with the infectious passion for
interstellar exploration often associated with the late rocketry
expert Werner von Braun and astronomer Carl Sagan.
</P>
<P>
   Von Braun, principal architect of the Saturn V moon rocket, died
in 1977, and Sagan's death almost three years ago left a void of
leadership and influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact they are not here right now is greatly missed,''
laments Robert Zubrin, the feisty aerospace engineer known for the
bold $20-billion, 10-year strategy he outlined in his 1996 book
``The Case for Mars: The Plan to Settle the Red Planet and Why We
Must.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But rather than say we hope we have another superhero emerge,
we should say it's up to each of us to take on the burden of
spreading the vision. Yes, I'm trying to do that, and I hope that
other people try. It's a job, not a franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as anyone, Zubrin has the imagination, the drive and the
credentials to claim the role of unofficial advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Space advocates may judge Zubrin for themselves by reading his
new book, ``Entering Space: Creating a Spacefaring Civilization''
(J.P. Tarcher/Putnam, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   Zubrin advocates a change in U.S. space policy, which currently
restricts human activity to low Earth orbit _ the reach of the
space shuttle and the prospective seven-person domain of the
U.S.-led international space station.
</P>
<P>
   He urges federal expenditures for the exploration and settlement
of Mars and for a human presence that could exploit natural
resources in the distant reaches of the solar system.
</P>
<P>
   Political obstacles loom large for the 47-year-old Denver-area
engineer, as evidenced by unresolved efforts in the House of
Representatives to trim $1 billion from the National Aeronautics
and Space Administration budget as part of a tax-cut measure.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, Zubrin is willing to fertilize the grass roots.
Barely a year old, the Mars Society (www.marssociety.org) he
founded in Boulder, Colo., sports 80 chapters, 30 of them in
foreign countries. The organization's second annual gathering in
August drew 1,000 enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   Next summer, the society expects to gin up its $1.2 million Mars
Arctic Research Station, a prototype of the habitation module
Zubrin describes in ``The Case for Mars.'' Placed in the chilly,
Martianlike terrain of Canada's Devon Island, the station is
designed to accommodate a half-dozen residents with solar-generated
electrical power, water-recycling equipment, a greenhouse and other
implements of life support.
</P>
<P>
   Zubrin says his writings, demonstrations and organizing efforts
are part of a strategy to offer the next U.S. president an
opportunity to embrace ``the case for Mars.'' At the outset, this
strategy does not require the breakthroughs in rocketry needed by
NASA's Cold War-inspired Apollo program.
</P>
<P>
   Though precluded by policy from embarking on human missions to
the moon, let alone to the Red Planet, NASA has embraced a key
Zubrin tenet in its planning for Mars: Use resources on the alien
planet to cut costs and manage risks.
</P>
<P>
   His ``live off the land when possible'' approach means
dispatching surface habitats, nuclear-power generators and
Earth-return craft well ahead of explorers rather than combining
all these elements in one large, as yet nonexistent, rocket.
</P>
<P>
   It means developing technologies to extract carbon dioxide from
the thin Martian atmosphere and to combine it with hydrogen to
produce fuel, breathing oxygen and water, rather than toting these
along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are moving ahead with our human space program at
much too slow a pace. There is some forward motion,'' Zubrin says,
referring to the space station. ``But I would hesitate to describe
the current human space program as representing anything in any way
as beyond or even as good as what we had going on circa 1970.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans are at a historic crossroads, Zubrin says, in a world
that has changed greatly since President John F. Kennedy initiated
the Apollo program as part of a Cold War effort to trump the Soviet
Union with U.S. technical prowess by landing a human on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   He outlines the choices he sees in ``Entering Space,'' borrowing
from Russian visionary Nikolai Kardashev.
</P>
<P>
   Our options in the new millennium, he says, are to remain a Type
I civilization achieving mastery over the resources of its planet
or to press ahead to become a Type II civilization, which masters
its solar system, and, eventually, a Type III civilization, which
achieves access to the entire galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Entering Space,'' Zubrin discusses technical hurdles to
creating propulsion systems for deep-space exploration, and the
potential rewards of overcoming them. He portrays a future in which
our engineers mine not only the moon but also the atmospheres of
Jupiter and Saturn for helium 3, a fuel for nuclear fusion that
could power rockets and serve as a source of electrical power.
</P>
<P>
   Zubrin envisions populated outposts midway to Neptune with the
technologies to prevent rogue comets and asteroids from striking
Earth. He dreams of technical advances that would permit humans to
direct cometlike ice-teroids from the distant Kuiper Belt and Oort
Cloud into the Martian atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Through terraforming, as the discipline is known, Mars would
gradually be converted to a warmer, wetter, more Earthlike realm.
</P>
<P>
   For those who call his vision unrealistic, Zubrin believes he
can argue its merits on terms that a prospective president could
understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will inspire the country in a positive way. This is an
invitation to adventure for every kid in the country. It will
inspire millions of our youth to get scientific educations,''
Zubrin says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a human-to-Mars program were to simply inspire 1 percent
more of them to get a scientific education, that means you get a
million additional engineers, inventors, doctors and research
biologists. They will create new industries, advance the human
condition. There is an enormous payoff economically.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
