u t BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-07 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOW SEASON' ISN'T ALWAYS A BARGAIN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reader Steve Buck struck a familiar chord with a letter about
travel in ``low season.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We recently returned from a wonderful vacation at the Acapulco
Princess,'' Buck began. ``It's one of our favorite places.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, there was one major problem. When we arrived, we
found that the main building _ the Pyramid _ was closed for the
summer, as they are reconstructing. This is the area in which we
were looking forward to staying, as we had in the past. There is
just something special to us with that building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We adjusted and had a wonderful time, as usual. (But) is this
typical that the information about this closure was kept from us?
My travel agent didn't know about the closure, and Continental
Vacations didn't know or didn't say anything to my agent. Most
important, there was nothing on the hotel Web site mentioning this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there any obligation on the hotel's part to inform
potential guests of problems like this?''
</P>
<P>
   I had an immediate flashback. Five years ago, also during late
summer or early fall _ slow periods for tourism in most of Mexico
and the Caribbean _ I, too, stayed at the Acapulco Princess and
found it an ideal vacation retreat. I wouldn't hesitate to return.
</P>
<P>
   But during that visit, one of the two principal lodging towers
was closed for renovation. Some restaurants were shuttered, too,
resulting in crowded conditions in other dining areas.
</P>
<P>
   No one had uttered a word about these closures prior to my
arrival, either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DON'T ASK, DON'T TELL? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My response to Buck's question: Yes, hotels _ and all other
elements of the travel industry _ should feel an obligation to
inform guests when even one of their regularly advertised services
or amenities will be unavailable, or when construction is ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the information is seldom forthcoming. And the
expressed reasoning for such failure to disclose usually is a shrug
of the shoulders and the explanation: ``It's low season. That's why
you're paying a discounted rate.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a factor to keep in mind as we make our vacation choices.
</P>
<P>
   During one summer many years ago, the co-pilot and I were
delighted to secure a minuscule rate at a well-regarded oceanfront
hotel on St. Martin, a Caribbean island. Our pleasure was enhanced
when, upon arrival, we were given upgraded accommodations, the
explanation being that the hotel was ``quite empty.''
</P>
<P>
   Then we inquired about dinner reservations. ``Our restaurants
are closed at the moment,'' the manager said. By ``the moment,'' he
meant the duration of our four-day stay. We soon learned that the
swimming pools also were closed (for maintenance, we were told).
The bars and gift shop, too. And although the beach was lovely, it
was shared _ no, overrun _ by guests at an adjacent nudist resort.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SAVINGS EVAPORATE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hotel's brochures had touted so many enticements that we
hadn't bothered to rent a car, figuring we'd just relax and take
all our meals on the property. We were miles from any restaurants _
at least restaurants whose diners wore clothes _ and as the week
progressed, hiring taxis to take us to lunch and dinner wiped out
any ``low season'' savings.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't surprised to learn soon afterward that this particular
hotel had been razed.
</P>
<P>
   Many travelers also write this time of year to inquire whether
bargain-basement cruise fares from late August through October _ as
low as $500 for a seven-day Caribbean sailing on some vessels _ are
``too good to be true.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not much for name-calling, but let me mention four you won't
find advertised in brochures and Internet promotions: Bret. Cindy.
Dennis. Emily. This may be ``low season'' aboard ship, but it's
hurricane season in the ocean. Chances are your trip to the Bahamas
or St. Thomas will result in smooth sailing _ and, unlike at some
land resorts, you'll enjoy the same entertainment, food and pools
as during peak season _ but are you willing to take that risk? Many
potential passengers shy away; thus rates drop in an effort to lure
business.
</P>
<P>
   Don't misunderstand, I'm not discouraging travel at off-peak
times. On the contrary, those are my favorite vacation periods. Not
only are prices lower, but you'll also find less crowding, and
local residents tend to be friendlier when not inundated by
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   During many years as a baseball reporter for this newspaper, my
vacations always fell in midwinter. Many times I would arrive in
small European towns to find bus routes curtailed, shops closed,
restaurant menus scaled back and service limited. Once in early
November, it seemed that the entire populace of Zermatt,
Switzerland, had fled elsewhere just as I arrived.
</P>
<P>
   I kept returning. But I knew what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes when there are surprises, staff attitude can make a
world of difference. When we arrived at a hotel in Lucerne,
Switzerland, and expressed dismay that the small but familiar room
we had reserved was being remodeled, management placed us in a
suite. That gesture earned our repeat business.
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance and new construction are essential. And fewer guests
are inconvenienced during off-peak periods. Practicality can
dictate cutbacks in service when demand diminishes. And certainly
hurricanes are beyond the control of cruise lines.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that doesn't excuse anyone from telling travelers up
front when ``low season'' has a deeper meaning than ``low prices.''
</P>
<P>
   I visited a local travel agent not long ago to inquire about an
Alaskan cruise this month. His first words were: ``It's the end of
the season, and there are value prices, but do you realize that
it's going to be cold there in September?''
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of honesty I appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
