</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATE
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget forWednesday, Sept. 8,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds; Adds: LICE
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CISNEROS _ WASHINGTON _ Former U.S. housing secretary Henry
Cisneros pleaded guilty Tuesday to a single misdemeanor count of
lying to the FBI, ending a four-year investigation by an
independent counsel. Cisneros will pay a $10,000 fine but will face
no jail time and no probation. (Heath, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Tuesday uses his
second school visit in two days to criticize GOP education policy,
while GOP Senate and House leaders prepare for an event at yet
another school Wednesday at which they will criticize the
Democratic approach. Clearly, both parties' leaders have seen polls
showing that education is a prime public concern. That's good news
for those who want the federal government to help the schools.
(Mollison, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ The chairman of the House Ways
and Means Committee complained Tuesday that President Clinton has
abandoned Social Security reform as a top priority. (Lipman/Deans,
Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   SSA-MAIL _ WASHINGTON _ The Social Security Administration
launched its first annual mailing of 125 million Social Security
statements. (Schultz, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPIC-BUSES _ WASHINGTON _ When Atlanta Olympic organizer
Billy Payne first outlined the bid committee's excesses for
Congress, he conceded, among other things, that it ``facilitated''
the donation of a used bus to Lima, Peru. The gift went over so
well that on the eve of the vote in Tokyo on Sept. 18, 1990, a far
more generous offer to Peru's IOC member was planned. How would he
like 50 buses for his hometown? That offer was not mentioned in the
Atlanta team's original June 1 report to the U.S. House Commerce
Committee, which is looking into the Olympic bid process. But it is
documented in the materials that fill three dozen boxes being pored
over by federal investigators. They discovered more unreported
expensive gifts and favors for IOC members and their families.
(Turner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS _ TAMPA, Fla. _ They've come to meet, mingle, and elect
a new president for their organization. But members of the National
Baptist Convention, USA, meeting this week in Tampa, will also
spend time playing, praying and trying to repair the problems
brought about by their former president, the Rev. Henry Lyons. We
spend time with a few of the 60,000 delegates and offer a glimpse
at how they spent the day. (Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CONYERS-SHOOTING _ CONYERS, Ga. _ A Rockdale County grand jury
may return indictments today against Anthony ``T.J.'' Solomon, who
shot six of his classmates at Heritage High School last May.
Rockdale's district attorney Richard Read has said he may include
in the indictments shots taken at two other students. A bookbag and
a travel book stopped the bullets from injuring the two students.
(Farber, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GORE-HEALTH _ LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore delivers a
major address on health care, part of a two-day swing through
California aimed at drawing attention away from the formal launch
of Bill Bradley's presidential campaign. (Shepard, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-HISPANICVOTE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Fresh from his success among
Texas Hispanic voters in the past fall's re-election bid, Gov.
George W. Bush has taken his Spanish-laced stump speeches to the
national stage, and the Republican Party sees him as a bona fide
crossover hit. In his bid for the presidency, Bush is energetically
courting the nation's fastest-growing voting group. And he's
creating great expectations in key states such as California, where
local GOP officers consider Bush a potential savior as they try to
patch up relations with Hispanics after former Gov. Pete Wilson's
anti-immigrant crusades. The courtship hasn't been completely
smooth. Bush has been criticized by some Hispanic groups for
skipping their national meetings, and he disappointed some Texas
border leaders who felt he didn't support their agenda during this
year's legislative session. 40. (Harmon, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ Given the enormous money advantage of the
front-runners and the jackrabbit pace of the primaries, it was
reasonable to expect the field of presidential contenders to narrow
considerably by Labor Day, the traditional start of the political
earnest season. But as the last few campaign staffers hurry back
from their beach vacations and the candidates, like dying leaves,
begin their autumn descent upon New Hampshire, politics is taking a
different direction. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   LICE _ ATLAN TA _ For Randy Foster, am Atlanta mother, fall
brings an annual tradition she loathes: comb, pick, apply the
delousing shampoo. Foster, a public relations specialist, has had
such a war with lice plaguing her daughter, Chelsea, she videotaped
part of the battle two years ago. The start of the school year is
high season for head lice -a growing problem in U.S. schools,
according to the CDC. Schools are now struggling to control
epidemics of the bugs, which are becoming increasingly resistent to
chemical treatments. A look at the problem and how to fix it.
(Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
