<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3538 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-RACES-I-2400(4TAKE     09-07 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RACES-I-2400(4TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE NETWORK `SUITS,' DIVERSITY NO LONGER PAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When producer Ralph Farquhar first pitched a half-hour comedy
featuring Kirk Franklin as a petty hoodlum turned church choir
director, the initial reaction from ABC was sheer giddiness. A
hip-hop/gospel music phenomenon with multimillion record sales,
videos airing on MTV and BET, and sold-out concerts, Franklin would
arrive on the prime-time television stage with a built-in following
of the young and hip.
</P>
<P>
   But as the first scripts took shape, Farquhar was constantly
queried by network representatives about the ``mainstream
possibilities'' of a series whose cast was overwhelmingly
African-American.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, where were the white people?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a sitcom set in a black neighborhood church,'' recalled
Farquhar, a veteran writer/producer who created ``Moesha'' and the
new sitcom ``The Parkers,'' both on UPN. ``Based on that, I turned
the question around and asked: What white characters would that be?
I remember this queasy feeling that something was about to happen.
I just didn't know what or when.''
</P>
<P>
   Farquhar found out in May, when the newly announced fall
television schedules revealed a rather disturbing pattern: Of the
38 new live-action dramas and comedies spread across the four major
networks and three upstarts, only two featured minorities in lead
roles. Nearly every cast member from the remaining series was
white.
</P>
<P>
   As black and Hispanic groups threatened legal action and
boycotts, the finger-pointing began. But there are no obvious
villains.
</P>
<P>
   This year's lily-white TV season isn't about racism.
</P>
<P>
   It's about ratings.
</P>
<P>
   For the networks, diversity just doesn't pay.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers simply prefer to watch shows with characters who look
like them. And so the networks, under pressure to halt audience
erosion and dwindling profits, have become doggedly focused on the
generally more affluent white households that advertisers seek.
Networks are afraid of alienating whites, who, despite watching 40
percent less TV than African-Americans and 30 percent less than
Latinos, still make up 70 percent of potential viewers. And if that
audience is no longer tuning in to shows with minority leads,
there's little incentive for networks to risk the millions of
dollars it costs to produce and market them.
</P>
<P>
   This helps explain how so many new series set in urban high
schools and in such diverse cities as New York and Los Angeles
feature so few black, Hispanic and Asian characters, and why a
sitcom about the adventures of a rap group has only one
African-American in a cast of four regulars.
</P>
<P>
   ``When looking at issues of race and TV programming, and looking
at the color scheme of how programs are cast, issues of green have
always been more important than issues of white, black or brown,''
said John Rash, senior vice president and director of broadcast
negotiations at Campbell Mithun Esty, a Minneapolis marketing
communications agency that last year placed close to a half-billion
dollars in TV advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not necessarily that networks want only younger,
Caucasian viewers. We need to pay closer attention to why, for
instance, there's such a lack of a shared viewing experience
between the races right at a time when most of society is becoming
more diverse.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Never has prime time been as segregated as it is today. If you
look at the most popular shows among blacks, Hispanics and Anglos,
you'd think you were looking at completely different TV schedules.
Only Monday Night Football is a Top 10 favorite among all three
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The gaps in viewing tastes are quite astonishing, particularly
when you examine TV's history. Only a generation ago, Hispanics
(with the exception of Desi Arnaz, who starred in CBS' ``I Love
Lucy'' during the '50s) and Asians were virtually absent from the
landscape. Black performers had it one step better _ they were on
TV but relegated to roles as domestics, second bananas or buffoons
on series like CBS' ``Amos n' Andy.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until 1965, when the NBC adventure series ``I Spy''
debuted, that we saw the first dramatic series with a black star.
(How ironic that Bill Cosby remains one of the few bankable black
leads today.) Three years later, Diahann Carroll portrayed a nurse
in ``Julia,'' also on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   But white audiences watched those shows, and throughout the '70s
and '80s, it was hardly an anomaly for largely black or multiracial
casts to attract mixed audiences. ``The Jeffersons,'' ``Chico and
the Man,'' ``Good Times'' and ``Sanford &AMP; Son'' couldn't have
survived without white fans. And white-oriented series like ``All
in the Family,'' ``Hunter'' and ``The Golden Girls'' had large
black and Hispanic followings.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ``The Cosby Show'' not only became the first and only
black-cast television program to reign at No. 1, but positioned
itself as the first truly water-cooler TV show, able to link blacks
and whites with themes of family, education and perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   All of that has changed dramatically. Now, only sports and
children's programming can make claims of supplying racially mixed
audiences. And NBC, once the home of the groundbreaking ``I Spy''
and ``The Cosby Show,'' didn't even consider any pilots with
minority leads for the fall season.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, NBC's new entertainment head, Scott Sassa, an
Asian-American, promised TV critics a more ethnically diverse
network, even commissioning suddenly hot producer Yvette Lee Bowser
to do a comedy pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Bowser already has a track record with NBC. The
network axed her multiracial sitcom ``For Your Love'' after one
season.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Exactly why TV viewers have become so divided along racial lines
is debatable.
</P>
<P>
   Some point to the so-called ghetto-ization of black programming
that began in the late 1980s, when the then-new Fox network
embraced black audiences while searching for a toehold. Sassy,
ethnically diverse programs like ``In Living Color'' and ``Martin''
attracted a large black and Hispanic viewer base, but many of the
shows were poorly written and relied heavily on black stereotypes
and caricatures.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-'90s Fox, wanting to expand its base, began to focus
more on the same affluent and larger white audience that the major
networks courted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was writing for `South Central' when the mandate came down
from Fox that there would be fewer shows featuring black
characters,'' said Kathleen McGee, a staff writer for the Lifetime
drama ``Any Day Now.'' ``It was a conscious direction on their
part. They wanted to segue into a more mainstream palette of
programs. So I saw that happen then and imagined that would be the
trend sooner or later with the others. It was.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, CBS, ABC and NBC were abandoning minority programming;
the two newcomers, the WB and UPN, programmed minority series
almost exclusively. But as the two new networks got their footing,
they, too, abandoned the plan. (The WB now wants young white women;
UPN targets men). Last season, the WB dropped three black-cast
sitcoms, ``Sister, Sister,'' ``The Wayans Bros.'' and ``Smart
Guy,'' to make room for more dramas based on white characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened,'' said Robert Townsend, who starred in and was
an executive producer of the WB's ``The Parent'Hood,'' ``was that
white audiences hated a lot of those shows and simply stopped
watching them. Having them all lumped together made them all easier
to avoid. So the only people watching by then were black people.''
</P>
<P>
   But Garth Ancier, president of NBC Entertainment, said that when
he ran programming at the WB, black-cast shows fared poorly when
sprinkled throughout the schedule, in part because ``white viewers
simply skipped over them. Once they started turning away and not
coming back, we had to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, all of the WB's black-oriented comedies are on
Fridays; UPN's air on Mondays.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, executives at ABC, CBS and NBC are expressing
frustration over their inability to lure mixed audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The attempted solution was a new style _ the black sitcom that
wasn't really black. The trend showed up a couple seasons ago with
shows like ``The Gregory Hines Show'' (black family with white
friends), ``Arsenio'' (black couple with white friends), ``Living
in Captivity'' (black family living in white suburb) and ``Getting
Personal'' (black professionals with white colleagues). But white
viewers still didn't show up, and the shows were quickly dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Now, apparently, the networks have entered Phase 2, a kind of
cinematic affirmative action: Put whites on existing black-cast
shows to lure white viewers and improve chances of survival.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't gone over well, either. Black producers, writers and
actors say the additions mean a change in the show's social tone,
that they are being asked to ``de-culture'' their shows, as one
writer put it, in order to make white viewers more comfortable
watching them.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: the WB's ``The Steve Harvey Show,'' which last
season was the most-watched program among African-Americans but
ranked 127 with whites, according to a study by TN Media. Two key
white characters have been added in the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, the No. 1 ranked comedy among whites,
``Friends,'' ranked seventh overall with Hispanics and 88th in
black homes.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on a network that rants and raves about the No. 1 ranking
my show has gotten over the years, but because they happen to be
numbers that feature mostly African-Americans, all of a sudden
those are not wanted numbers anymore,'' said Harvey, the show's
star and one of its executive producers. ``If any other show has
the No. 1 ranking in any other demographic, they're applauding. If
I'm `Buffy the Vampire Slayer' and get all white teen-agers, I'm
applauded. If I'm `Friends' and get all white males from 18 to 34,
I'm applauded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Us? We gotta go trolling for white folks. And I don't see any
of those white shows like `Friends' trying to `broaden' their
audience with black people. How many black people watch that show?
Two? Three?''
</P>
<P>
   Athough lauded for remaining with minority shows, UPN also moved
away from the all-minority comedy. The new ``Grown Ups,'' for
instance, actually has more white than black regular characters,
and ``The Parkers'' gave star Countess Vaughn a white girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be a narrowcaster in this business and expect to
stay in this business,'' said Dean Valentine, president of UPN.
``We focused more on black programming early on because no one else
would. But you eventually must consider the economic realities of
that decision. You need a cross section of viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   And being labeled ``a black show'' is the kiss of death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost impossible to get whites to watch,'' said Arthur
Harris, a staff writer with UPN's ``Grown Ups.'' ``It's easier to
get blacks to watch white shows. As a writer, if the show you're on
isn't crossing over, you better keep your resume circulating. And I
guess that may have something to do with that whole advertising
monster, too.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   So why aren't advertisers more interested in reaching minority
households? Possible reasons include their lesser buying power and
the fact that because blacks watch more TV than whites, advertisers
won't pay networks as much for an audience that's ``easier'' to
reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time an oversupply of a certain type of viewer exists,
yes, it will cost less to reach them,'' Rash said, referring to
black viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Smikle of Target Market News, a Chicago research firm that
monitors the African-American consumer market, estimates the
economic clout of black America at more than $400 billion. Because
of a growing black middle class, its economic power is increasing
at a faster rate than that of white households.
</P>
<P>
   But judging from advertiser response to the new season, they
haven't noticed that. Contrary to their self-proclaimed death
notices, the networks are actually thriving. Estimated advertising
revenue for the year is expected to rise among the six networks
(excluding PAX TV) to $7.25 billion, up from $6.4 billion last
year.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of money for an industry considered to be in an
irreversible decline. And perhaps it explains why the bad press
over the lack of minority-fronted shows won't be perceived as
hurting the networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``White advertisers don't value the black consumer to the extent
that they value the white consumer,'' said Bob Johnson, founder and
CEO of Black Entertainment Television. ``This has plagued black
businesses ever since they first started. It goes back to when
blacks were considered one-eighth of a person. That same value
discount still exists.''
</P>
<P>
   TV executives, as well as media buyers like Rash, routinely deny
any economic tie between race and ad rates, even while admitting a
frustration with advertisers who do have a tier system of paying
premiums to reach certain groups. (Viewers over age 50 _ of any
race _ are considered the least desirable.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any network executive _ I know certainly we
don't _ sits there and says, `Gee, if we make this show all-white,
we're going to get more dollars from Madison Avenue,' '' said Les
Moonves, president and CEO of CBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not anticipating, nor have we received any resistance
to the new (Steven) Bochco show `City of Angels,' which will be
three-quarters African-American cast. There has not been one iota
of hold-back from anybody on Madison Avenue because of the theme of
that show.''
</P>
<P>
   More-cynical observers will probably also note that ``City of
Angels'' comes from powerful producer Bochco. The midseason series,
set in a black and Hispanic neighborhood in Los Angeles and
starring Blair Underwood and Vivica A. Fox, is one of the few
projects that wasn't hurriedly pieced together in response to the
blanket criticism that surprised the networks at the TV critics'
tour in July.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   After the controversy hit, the WB, for instance, announced that
``For Your Love's'' Bowser would produce a pilot for a multiracial
family drama, a project the producer admitted had been sitting
around unwanted for four years.
</P>
<P>
   The WB is also developing the sitcom ``Loose Cannon'' with the
black stand-up comic Nick Cannon. NBC has turned to ``In Living
Color's'' Keenen Ivory Wayans for an interracial family sitcom
under the working title of ``Not the Bradys.''
</P>
<P>
   The producers of those all-white new series set in diverse
environments, like ``Manchester Prep'' and ``Wasteland,'' dashed
out to find minority actors, if only to keep the critics off their
backs. Even existing series such as ``Suddenly Susan'' became so
aggressive in their hunt for minority characters that Robert
Townsend referred to it as ``a Kmart blue light special on black
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Observing all this from the comfy set of his new series is
Farquhar, who said he'll keep pitching multicultural series like
``The Parkers.'' All-black fare _ along the lines of the
dead-and-buried Kirk Franklin project _ are relics of the past, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he'll continue to support the NAACP's legal
actions, whatever they may be. But he has his doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's something the courts can resolve,'' he
said. ``At the end of the day, which show you choose and for what
reason has nothing to do with anything that can be outlined by a
judge. Or he'd be a network executive, wouldn't he?''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3542 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-RACES-II-1200(2TAK     09-07 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RACES-II-1200(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN TV AND PEOPLE OF COLOR WON'T CHANGE SOON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every time I sit down to watch a television program that
purports to be about African-Americans, I do so with anxiety,
fearing that the characters will be false and stereotypical,
distorted into caricatures that are ignorant and cruel.
</P>
<P>
   I assume that we all want our lives to be taken seriously and
represented fully _ portrayed with power and honesty, empathy and
sympathy, pain and happiness. I can't imagine someone asking that
their life be reduced to the cardboard dimensions that often typify
prime-time television.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly that is what I find.
</P>
<P>
   And that is what I'll continue to find.
</P>
<P>
   As the new TV season approaches and the debate over on-camera
inclusion and race is revisited, networks are promising to do
better, to be better by making their casts reflect the world in
which we live. I'm not optimistic. The relationship between this
medium and people of color has always been awkward and tenuous at
best, hostile and resentful at worst, and I don't see that changing
any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   That's because TV has never known what to do with minority
characters, much the way America hasn't quite figured out what to
do with the issue of race.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the media seemed to discover this problem just this
summer, after the new season was announced and revealed a serious
lack of minority characters, I have watched it grow and manifest
itself for years, like a cancer.
</P>
<P>
   While riffling through old press kits the other day, I noticed a
photo of the original cast of ``Melrose Place,'' the one with
Vanessa Williams smiling sweetly from the left side. There wasn't a
more luckless character on ``Melrose'' than Williams, unless you
count Doug Savant's gay character, who at least stayed a few
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, it was clear that both Williams and Savant were
getting short shrift when it came to relationships on the steamy
soap. I don't know what producers feared more: a gay romance or an
interracial one. (Giving her a black boyfriend would mean bringing
on another black character.) So Williams was relegated to saying
``whassup?'' at the beginning of the show and ``see ya'' at its
end. Halle Berry had the same problems on ``Living Dolls,'' the
short-lived series about models. And the role of black nonentity
continued last season in such shows as ``Cupid'' with Jeffrey Sams
and Tangi Miller on ``Felicity.'' Neither got much to do.
</P>
<P>
   And thus lies the problem of minorities in ``white'' dramas _
writers can't seem to figure out exactly where they fit. It's why a
host of dramas, such as ``Beverly Hills, 90210,'' never introduced
a regular black character and why ``Dawson's Creek'' seems to have
dropped one without explanation.
</P>
<P>
   You have to deal with race.
</P>
<P>
   That said, we'd do well to keep in mind the deeper origins of
this problem, that the power base of network television _ those who
make the decisions about who goes in front of and behind the camera
_ are almost exclusively white, and usually male.
</P>
<P>
   How odd it was to attend the Summer Press Tour recently and
watch each network president speak glowingly about diversity
efforts. But looking at the racial makeup of the executive
decision-makers positioned to move up through their corporate
pipeline, there was little to indicate that anything will change
any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   It's a certainty that the segregated nature of TV executives and
producers has a rather chilling effect on what is programmed and
who is hired in an industry that is so powerful and influential
that its portrayals of groups and coverage of issues often
overshadow reality.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the profile of television producers and writers,
studio and network executives, and others running the industry
remains as exclusively white as it is today, alternative visions
from other groups will have a difficult time getting on air.
</P>
<P>
   Divergent views of comedy and drama will continue to be
marginalized, and people of color will largely remain trapped in
white reflections of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the black producers I've talked with would argue for
censorship or boycotts. That would only close off opportunities,
they say. But what they crave is balance, a chance to do a black
``Party of Five'' or a black ``Felicity,'' in which the characters
are struggling with sibling problems and in-laws, love pains and
resentments, like white characters do.
</P>
<P>
   The breathless advance notices for CBS' midseason series ``City
of Angels'' _ a black ``ER,'' I suppose _ is merely a reminder of
how few dramas there are about the black experience. But ``City of
Angels'' producer Paris Barclay is well-aware of the uphill climb
facing this series that has little to do with its quality. ``We
have so few projects addressing African-Americans,'' he said,
``that the tendency is going to be to expect us to address
everything. We'll have to deal with race in a certain way or we
won't be, quote, authentic, unquote. That's too much pressure on
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   Over the summer, a studio executive said that the small number
of people of color working in TV is ``a shame of our industry,''
but in saying that, he did not mean that white Americans are
incapable of producing programs enjoyed by minorities, or vice
versa.
</P>
<P>
   Both minorities and whites working in the industry have track
records that prove the opposite. ``The atmosphere has done nothing
to encourage whites to write for shows with black characters or
blacks to write for shows with white characters,'' said producer
Yvette Lee Bowser, whose WB sitcom ``For Your Love'' features two
black couples and one white couple navigating different stages of
romance. ``TV will remain segregated as long as we aren't able to
come together and do multicultural shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Correction: TV will remain segregated as long as the networks
continue to turn to the same producers for shows. It's clear that
the TV industry is seemingly unable or unwilling to recruit and
fully employ minority men and women, many of whom would bring to
the job sensibilities and experiences quite different from the
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of diversity is more than an issue of workplace equity
and fairness. Because the television industry creates images that
influence society's consciousness, the creators of those images
hold enormous power. Right now, those creators represent only a
limited segment of society; so aren't the stories they tell limited
as well?
</P>
<P>
   Today, the portrayals of minorities, and whites, too, are
created almost solely by white producers and writers. In such a
scheme, all viewers lose. White viewers lose because they rarely
see their reflection from someone else's eyes. In addition, they
are absorbing images of others that lack dimension and
authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   Black, Hispanic, Asian and American Indian viewers suffer
because the complexity and reality of their lives are distorted
into something that is unrecognizable.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the creative community, which often feels
beaten down by the weight of inequity. ``Whites will always have a
greater ease in navigating throughout the television industry,''
said Kathleen McGee Anderson, a black writer who is currently on
staff of Lifetime's ``Any Day Now.'' ``It belongs to them. It
doesn't belong to us. We do what we can in it and get what we can
out of it. But I've never felt that the sky was the limit in this
business because I'm a black female.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, networks are scrambling to add minority
characters to new and returning series this fall. Black and
Hispanic groups are planning to boycott network TV this fall,
hoping to force the issue. A few black producers have gotten new
deals to develop pilots.
</P>
<P>
   But I still find it difficult to be optimistic. Band-Aids rarely
do much for gaping wounds.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
