</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NEWSEASON-MASLIN-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GENERATION OF FILMMAKERS STUCK AT `PROMISING' 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: For release Sunday, Sept. 12.) 
(th) 
 By JANET MASLIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the year's most auspicious film season approaches, at least
this is certain: the approach of the century's end will not go
unexploited by Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   But for sheer promotional chutzpah, it may be hard to beat the
trailer for ``Lost Souls,'' which uses sci-fi ominousness to
heighten its pitch: ``They had their 2,000 years,'' one character
declares. ``Now it's our turn.'' That will be one extra reason to
brace oneself for the movie onslaught this fall.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a matter in which the M word is worth mentioning:
who will be the auteurs worth watching into the next millennium?
With the last great surge of filmmaking talent arriving in the
1970s, we have been in limbo for a long while when it comes to
newcomers who are capable of sustaining careers that are long and
varied, yet who are defined by their fundamental consistency.
</P>
<P>
   For every post-'70s filmmaker who has been able to establish
himself on those terms, from Spike Lee to Atom Egoyan, there have
been dozens who leave no creative fingerprints and seem chiefly
concerned with the short haul.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, this season will test the mettle of some recently
established filmmakers who just may turn out to have serious
staying power. David O. Russell's two previous films were so
assured, so outrageous and so different from each other that they
add up to a hard act to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has made ``Three Kings,'' which is set at the end of the
Gulf War and apparently adds a new political edge to his already
impressive range. If he can move successfully from incest
(``Spanking the Monkey'') to delirious deadpan humor (``Flirting
With Disaster'') to a film that takes a critical view of U.S.
foreign policy, his offbeat early triumphs will not be mistaken for
beginner's luck.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Thomas Anderson, the director of ``Boogie Nights,'' is at a
similar crossroads. Despite the stilted quality to ``Hard Eight,''
his first feature, Anderson made such a strong impression with the
vibrant neo-``Nashville'' panorama of ``Boogie Nights'' that his
forthcoming ``Magnolia'' warrants great anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   Reuniting some of the ``Boogie Nights'' cast (Julianne Moore,
William H. Macy, Philip Seymour Hoffman) in a film that also
features Tom Cruise, Anderson will have an opportunity to establish
which of those early films was more representative of his vision.
</P>
<P>
   With its terrific cast and mordant kamikaze humor, Danny Boyle's
``Trainspotting'' made a bracingly strong impression, even if the
subsequent ``A Life Less Ordinary'' (both of which featured Ewan
McGregor) was more mean-spirited than exhilarating.
</P>
<P>
   With ``The Beach,'' he will take on another dark novel (by Alex
Garland) and another of the world's most magnetic young actors
(Leonardo DiCaprio), inviting lightning to strike again. ``The
Beach'' is sure to attract attention on the strength of its
DiCaprio factor. Perhaps the filmmaker's impact will be even more
compelling than that.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Minghella's adaptation of ``The English Patient'' was so
inspired that it established his intuitive brilliance almost
overnight. But once again, the triumph so wholly eclipses his
earlier work that it will be fascinating to watch his next move.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Talented Ripley'' is another literary adaptation, from an
insinuating noir thriller by Patricia Highsmith, and it has the
kind of cast (Gwyneth Paltrow, Matt Damon) liable to make a
director look golden. And on the evidence of Minghella's skill with
actors in ``The English Patient,'' vice versa too.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Jordan's work varies tremendously, but it never falls short
of the surprising; this year's ``In Dreams'' was too inventively
spooky to pass for ordinary horror.
</P>
<P>
   Now Jordan, whose specialty is the drastic change of pace, has
adapted ``The End of the Affair,'' Graham Greene's novel, into what
promises to be a torrid romantic drama starring Ralph Fiennes and
Julianne Moore. Jordan has already made his mark as a serious,
enduring talent.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmaker who will be most conspicuously following in his
own footsteps is Frank Darabont. With ``The Green Mile,'' another
Stephen King adaptation, in the works after he brought such
eloquence and dignity to ``The Shawshank Redemption,'' Darabont
could well emerge as the kind of quietly durable filmmaker whose
craftsmanship and moral urgency are his strongest virtues.
</P>
<P>
   Lasse Hallstrom, whose ``My Life as a Dog'' was such an
idiosyncratic gem, and who turned ``What's Eating Gilbert Grape?''
into another coming-of-age classic, will try with ``The Cider House
Rules'' to adapt John Irving's novel into a nontreacly movie; if
anyone is up to the task, he's the one.
</P>
<P>
   And James Mangold, whose sensitive ``Heavy'' and ambitious
``Copland'' put him on the map, has filmed ``Girl, Interrupted''
with a fine cast of actresses (Winona Ryder, Vanessa Redgrave,
Whoopi Goldberg, Angelina Jolie).
</P>
<P>
   ``Being John Malkovich'' is only the first feature by Spike
Jonze, but its premise alone (unhappy filing clerk enters
Malkovich's mind) promises novelty and then some.
</P>
<P>
   And Tim Robbins, the strong, single-minded director of ``Bob
Roberts'' and ``Dead Man Walking,'' this time works on a big canvas
with his bustling 1930s tableau, ``Cradle Will Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   As for those directorial heavyweights who have achieved landmark
status, they, too, will be taking chances this fall. Martin
Scorsese, working again with a screenplay by Paul Schrader (``Taxi
Driver,'' ``Raging Bull''), has made ``Bringing Out the Dead'' in
the pressure-cooker world of a New York City paramedic, with
Nicolas Cage as the man on the brink.
</P>
<P>
   And Milos Forman, with ``Man on the Moon,'' will raise the
question of why the comic Andy Kaufman, played by Jim Carrey,
should be the focus of an ambitious biographical film. Before
Forman's last stunning film arrived, that's what we wondered about
Larry Flynt, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
