<HEADER>
A3546 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TE     09-07 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARQUAND WROTE THE SAME (GOOD) BOOK MANY TIMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Something to Say'' is the title of one of James Thurber's more
beguiling short stories _ about one Eliot Vereker, who has never
written anything but has what most people in his circle believe is
a keen mind. They support him financially and indulge his whims
because, after all, he has ``something to say'' and may someday be
an important author.
</P>
<P>
   Many authors less fraudulent than Eliot Vereker are held in
esteem by the literati, because they not only have something to
say, but have said it in print. The more serious-minded the author,
the higher the esteem. Indeed, esteem so high that the sympathetic
reader often fails to recognize the same message as replayed again
and again.
</P>
<P>
   Today's subject is not Thurber or Vereker, but John P. Marquand,
who wrote the same book many times. That really isn't unusual. Many
authors devise multiple variations on the same themes, because the
somethings they have to say are rather limited. It's an almost
perfect equation, however, because most readers, whether they know
it or not, want to read the same story over and over. Consider the
durability of the pulp romance novel. One could compose a romance
novel on a computer and edit the pilot draft 100 times, producing
100 different novels with only the names and places changed.
Readers addicted to the genre wouldn't complain.
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't about pulp romances. In his day, Marquand was
recognized as a high-minded ``litteratus'' whose novels inevitably
topped the bestseller chart. It was a long and distinguished
career, but I'm not acquainted with anyone who reads Marquand
nowadays. His novels in their matched bindings (parallel horizontal
stripes all the way down the spine) are plentiful in used
bookstores, along with other bygone Book-of-the-Month Club
selections, apparently because their owners decided they weren't
worthy of retention on the home shelves.
</P>
<P>
   John Phillips Marquand (1893-1960) was born in Delaware but grew
up in Newburyport, Mass., and continued to live there in his years
of fame. From the early 1920s to the mid-1930s he delivered several
apprentice novels in the conventional romantic and melodramatic
genres, and simultaneously appeared in the popular magazines with a
score of detective yarns featuring Mr. Moto, a Japanese sleuth in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Marquand at 44 found his literary destiny. ``The Late George
Apley'' focused on a conservative Boston Brahmin in conflict with
the changing mores of modern times. This novel, lighter in tone
than its successors from the same cookie cutter, was awarded the
Pulitzer Prize for 1937, and deservedly so, for it's altogether
charming. Then, in succession, came ``Wickford Point'' (1939),
``H.M. Pulham, Esq.'' (1941), ``So Little Time'' (1943), ``E.F.'s
Daughter'' (1946), ``Point of No Return'' (1949), ``Melville
Goodwin, U.S.A.'' (1951), ``Sincerely, Willis Wayde'' (1955) and
``Women and Thomas Harrow'' (1958). Almost without exception, these
novels sound the theme of conformity vs. personal desire. The focal
character usually is an anguished male, a New Englander entering or
in midlife. Nor is ``B.F.'s Daughter'' really an exception, because
the husband figure has the same weakness of will that characterizes
Marquand's male protagonists, and the strongest portrait is of the
father figure, B.F. himself. ``So Little Time'' seems an exception
for being largely set in Hollywood, but it restates the condition
of a man _ in this case a screenwriter _ who has sold himself out
against his creative impulses.
</P>
<P>
   Marquand, though, should have been grateful to Hollywood.
``Apley'' and ``Pulham'' made fine films, ``B.F.'s Daughter'' was
OK (she was portrayed by Barbara Stanwyck at her man-crushing
best), and although ``Goodwin'' flopped as ``Top Secret Affair,''
the author pocketed $300,000 for the rights. There was also a
well-made ``B'' series with Peter Lorre limning Mr. Moto.
</P>
<P>
   Marquand's fame crested with ``Point of No Return,'' which was
successfully dramatized by Paul Osborn, with Henry Fonda in one of
his returns to Broadway. It may even be the author's ``best''
novel, but its theme _ a banker as an involuntary slave to
materialism _ was old stuff then.
</P>
<P>
   Should you read anything by John P. Marquand? Yes, if you
haven't already. The style is polished, the structure and
development are sound, and he does get inside his characters. It
hardly matters which one you pick. Read one, you've read 'em all.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is retired books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
