<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3549 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ANTIQUES-NEWSEASON-RE     09-07 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-NEWSEASON-REIF-$ADV12-ANYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MET'S AMERICAN WING CELEBRATES 75TH ANNIVERSARY WITH A YEARLONG
EXHIBITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., R.I.)   (For release Sunday, Sept. 12)  (DW) 
 By RITA REIF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A pioneer at the outset and a trendsetter ever since,
the American Wing of the Metropolitan Museum of Art has advanced
the nation's passionate interest in American art throughout most of
this century. Now, on Nov. 10, it will mark to the day the 75th
anniversary of its opening with ``Celebrating the American Wing:
Notable Acquisitions 1980-1999,'' a yearlong exhibition of American
paintings, sculpture and furnishings of the late 17th century to
the early 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   The way the show will focus on these recent additions to its
American art collection, one of the finest and most comprehensive
in existence, is so understated that it seems a bit off the wall.
Yet it may portend things to come elsewhere. Virtually all of the
2,000 objects have been on view for months or years, surrounded by
the 12,000 others in the collection. Everything will be shown in
its usual place in the wing's 25 period rooms, 31 galleries and the
Henry R. Luce Center for the Study of American Art. The new wrinkle
will be that the objects acquired since 1980 will be flagged by
bright blue stickers the size of silver dollars, and their wall
labels will be more detailed than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exhibition should be viewed as a treasure hunt,'' said
Morrison H. Heckscher, the curator of American Decorative Arts, who
organized the show with H. Barbara Weinberg, the curator of
American Paintings and Sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this do-it-yourself review of the American Wing
mirrors what museums _ and people, too _ do in educating themselves
as they amass collections. A check of the dates on the wall labels
reveals that most masterpieces were acquired at the peak of their
popularity: Duncan Phyfe and the federal style in the 1920s and the
Esthetic and Arts and Crafts styles from 1980 on. The dates also
show that gaps in the collection were filled whenever the
appropriate pieces were found.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Heckscher said that until recently he was unable to
illustrate fully how the 18th-century furniture forms that were
developed in Boston _ high chests, kneehole desks, secretaries and
the dressing tables called lowboys _ related to those that were
later adapted and changed significantly in Newport, with carvings
of shells, leafy knees and claw feet added.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1994, he got lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple who collect American furniture _ Yvette and Thomas
Cole _ invited me to select any piece in their collection for the
museum,'' he said. ``I chose a splendid, rare example of the one
important early form of Newport furniture not in our collection _ a
small, elegant dressing table from the 1740s, with sharply edged
legs and pointed pad feet.''
</P>
<P>
   The lowboy was the key piece that enabled him to rearrange the
gallery so that the similarities and differences between the pieces
from the two cities would be obvious. The blue sticker on the
lowboy calls attention to such distinctions.
</P>
<P>
   Other objects with stickers were considered status symbols in
their day: a throne-like Great Chair of the late 17th century, a
mirrored silver centerpiece presented in 1825 to Gov. De Witt
Clinton of New York at the opening of the Erie Canal and a
Lincolnesque bust from 1874 by Augustus Saint-Gaudens, depicting
William M. Evarts, a U.S. senator. Later works include a ravishing
1892 portrait by John Singer Sargent of Mrs. Hugh Hammersley, a
London beauty, and a massive iron door produced in 1927 by Samuel
Yellin for J. Walter Thompson, the New York advertising agency. The
show's dazzler is an album quilt patterned with 360 images of
tumbling blocks, each bearing a signature written on white silk.
The quilt was made by Adeline Harris Sears of Rhode Island, whose
persistence and family connections netted her the autographs of
illustrious statesmen, industrialists, artists and writers, among
them Abraham Lincoln, Ulysses S. Grant, Horace Greeley, Ralph Waldo
Emerson and Harriet Beecher Stowe.
</P>
<P>
   Blue stickers will be most visible in the gallery of
late-19th-century objects, the only space in the American Wing that
has been enlarged and refurbished (opening on Oct. 19). The gallery
will be a repository for glowing stained glass windows by Louis
Comfort Tiffany, along with several Arts and Crafts gems _ Frank
Lloyd Wright vases, a Gustav Stickley tall clock and a George Ohr
earthenware vase.
</P>
<P>
   The elegant surprise there will be a Christian Herter cabinet,
exhibited for the first time since it was found _ blackened and
unidentified _ at a Boston-area auction in 1996 by Margo Johnson, a
New York dealer. The original gold-flecked painted ivory finish was
restored to the way it looked in 1883 in the drawing room of Oliver
Ames, a Boston industrialist.
</P>
<P>
   Today's American Wing is nearly nine times larger than it was at
its opening in 1924 and so imposing that people forget how daring
it was on completion: the nation's first permanent exhibition space
in an art museum for Early American decorative art. When the Wing
was dramatically expanded in 1980 to include the glassed-in Charles
Englehard Court, the collection was enlarged, adding American
paintings and sculpture as well as decorative art and architecture
from 1820 to 1920.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to take a look at where we are and what we're doing
so that we could move ahead,'' Heckscher said. ``We're planning for
a lot of changes to better display our treasures.'' Stay tuned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
