<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3550 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-PUERTO-RICO-H     09-07 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PUERTO-RICO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE REBUFFS HILLARY CLINTON'S CRITICISM ON CLEMENCY DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories.)   
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House spokesman on Tuesday defended
President Clinton's offer of clemency to 16 Puerto Rican members of
a terrorist group in the wake of First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton's criticism of presidential leniency.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart declined to directly
address Mrs. Clinton's objections but said the offer of
presidential clemency announced on Aug. 11 ``remains open'' until
Friday at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said he was ``not trying to avoid commenting'' on Mrs.
Clinton's criticism but instead was focusing on ``what I'm supposed
to do here _ which is talk about what the president's doing (and)
why he's doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton urged her husband on Saturday to cancel his offer
of clemency after the offer was widely criticized by law
enforcement groups and advocates of victims' rights.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans alleged that the president's clemency offer was
designed to win support among Hispanic voters for Mrs. Clinton's
possible bid for the U.S. Senate seat in New York. Mrs. Clinton's
expected rival for the Senate seat, Republican New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, has called the clemency offer ``a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said the offer should be withdrawn because the
convicted terrorists refused to meet the president's conditions for
early release or modification of their sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been three weeks and their silence speaks volumes,'' Mrs.
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 were members of the Puerto Rican nationalist group that
carried out at least 130 bombings of political and military targets
between 1974 and 1983, killing six people and wounding scores of
others. The organization is known as the FALN, based upon the
Spanish acronym for Armed Forces of National Liberation.
</P>
<P>
   None of the 16 members of the pro-independence Puerto Rican
organization was convicted of crimes stemming from individual
attacks that killed or injured people, according to deputy White
House chief of staff Maria Echaveste.
</P>
<P>
   The nationalists have served at least 14 years for crimes such
as possession of an unregistered firearm, interstate transportation
of a stolen vehicle or seditious conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's offer of clemency would require the convicts not only
to accept traditional federal parole restrictions on travel but
also to sign a document pledging to renounce violence.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of Clinton's offer, 11 of the 16 Puerto Rican
nationalists could be released from custody immediately. Two others
would remain in prison with shorter sentences. Three others would
have fines waived.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart denied the president's offer of clemency was designed
to benefit Mrs. Clinton's prospective Senate campaign in New York,
where Hispanics account for an estimated 2.6 million of the state's
population of 18.2 million, according to the Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said White House discussions of possible clemency began
at least two years ago, long before Mrs. Clinton began exploring a
possible Senate campaign to succeed retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a partisan maneuver,'' Lockhart said. ``There
have been many who have sought to inject politics, and many who
have thought to inject a motive here, and all I can say is that
they're wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said White House lawyers' discussions of the clemency
offer with lawyers for the Puerto Rican prisoners do not constitute
``negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's criticism of the clemency offer has irked Puerto
Rican political activists.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jose E. Serrano, D-N.Y., said in an interview with the New
York Times published on Monday that he was withdrawing his support
for Mrs. Clinton's prospective Senate campaign because of her
``intervention'' in the White House clemency offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm rescinding my encouragement of her candidacy,'' Serrano
said. ``This is an action that will make people go out and make
sure that she's not our next senator. Maybe it's time to go out and
find out who else is interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rican voters, the largest bloc of Hispanic voters in New
York, are a powerful constituency in New York state politics.
Puerto Ricans are U.S. citizens, entitled to vote in congressional
and presidential elections, if they are living in the mainland
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Then-Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., ousted incumbent Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato, R-N.Y., in New York's 1998 Senate race with the help of
Hispanic voters, including Puerto Ricans. Schumer carried 82
percent of the Hispanic vote, which accounted for 6 percent of the
statewide vote in 1998, according to exit polls.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, New York City's mayor, carried 43 percent of the
Hispanic vote in his 1997 re-election drive during a contest in
which Hispanic voters accounted for 20 percent of the city-wide
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Clemency for Puerto Rican nationalists is not new.
</P>
<P>
   Then-President Jimmy Carter pardoned four Puerto Rican
nationalists who were serving long prison terms following
conviction for a 1954 attack on the U.S. House of Representatives
that wounded four members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Carter also pardoned a Puerto Rican nationalist convicted in a
plot to assassinate President Harry S. Truman in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
