<HEADER>
A3553 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-GETREAL08-COX     09-07 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GETREAL08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Get real' serves up lots of familial angst
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Get Real?'' OK, let's.
</P>
<P>
   A teenage boy comes home with his face bashed up because he was
knocked unconscious by a school bully. Mom says: ``Is there any
subtext to this fight you want to tell me about?''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Dad has his business partner over to dinner, after the
partner's wife has thrown him out for having an affair with one of
the L.A. Lakers' cheerleaders. The whole family is gathered at the
table as the betrayed wife bursts in, exposes her breasts to
everyone and screams at her cheating husband: ``Take a look at
these! This is real life!''
</P>
<P>
   And the live-in grandma, who's the voice of sage wisdom,
compares her late husband to a ``stallion.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like reality at your house, right? There's nothing wrong
with ridiculous TV, but ``Get Real'' keeps reminding us how really
really real it is.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first major new fall series to debut (not counting UPN,
the ``Clueless'' network), and as if someone planned it, it's like
a one-stop-shopping overview of the entire fall TV season; what you
see here, you're going to be seeing again. These trends include a
blending of drama and comedy, lots of good-looking teenagers
getting all moody, and characters talking directly to the camera,
explaining their every thought to us. And, of course, sex. ``Get
Real's'' first scene, before the opening credits, is mom having an
orgasm. Top that, ``NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   The Green family veers between semi-functional and barely
coping. Mom (Debrah Farentino) is a professional party planner,
overwhelmed by her three closely spaced teens and rightly concerned
about her marriage. Dad (Jon Tenney) is so caught up in his work
he's oblivious to the family. Oldest daughter Meghan (Anne
Hathaway) is a brainy beauty who's chafing at following her
parents' plans; son Cameron (Eric Christian Olsen) is a
self-absorbed 16-year-old who's a walking (but not always talking)
babe magnet; and 15-year-old Kenny (Jesse Eisenberg) is still
developing, if he can keep from getting beaten up too often.
</P>
<P>
   The actors, particularly the always-great Farentino (``EZ
Streets,'' ``Storm of the Century'') are better than the material,
which is too often too cute, particularly when the teens talk to us
through the camera. ``You want everything tied up in a bow? Go
watch `7th Heaven,''' says Meghan, and the show also references
``My So-Called Life,'' ``Dawson's Creek,'' ``South Park,'' Alicia
Silverstone and Fonzie.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing more obnoxious than self-aware teens,''
Meghan says in another breaking-the-fourth-wall moment, and oh, is
she right.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy, and fun, to pick on ``Get Real,'' because it can be
so annoying. But it can also be honest and grounded, with emotional
connections among the characters that hint at depth. Creator Clyde
Phillips (``Suddenly Susan'') has an ear for adolescent dialogue
when he isn't trying so hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Real'' may have a case of pilot-itis, of trying too hard
to be different. There's potential here for a decent show if
everyone can settle down, get less cute and more real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Real''
</P>
<P>
   9 tonight on Fox
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
