<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL A FEW STATE EDUCATION PROBLEMS TO SOLVE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texans put a high priority on education.
</P>
<P>
   Education accounts for the largest expenditure from the state
budget, and its administration at the state level is governed by a
small army of elected and appointed officials, including one
governor, 181 legislators, one state education commissioner and a
15-member State Board of Education. And they don't include several
thousand other policy-makers serving on local school boards and in
superintendents' offices in Texas' 1,000-plus school districts.
</P>
<P>
   The educational bureaucracy is rather top-heavy, to say the
least.
</P>
<P>
   The elected governor and the elected state lawmakers, of course,
belong at the top of any public state policy. And numerous state
boards and commissioners, most of them appointed, assist in
carrying out thousands of laws passed by the Legislature and signed
by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   In most of those cases, however, the boards are appointed by the
governor, the commissioners are hired by the boards and everyone,
at least theoretically, is singing from the same page.
</P>
<P>
   The educational leadership is a different sort of animal _ a
two-headed animal.
</P>
<P>
   The state education commissioner, appointed by the governor,
heads the 800-plus employees at the Texas Education Agency, which
is charged with the day-to-day administration of the state's
educational policies.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas also has a 15-member State Board of Education, which
is elected independently of the governor and whose members don't
always agree with the governor, the commissioner or each other over
educational priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Political bickering on the board prompted the Legislature in
1995 to strip the panel of many of its responsibilities, including
any input into the selection of the education commissioner. Mike
Moses, who recently stepped down to accept a job at Texas Tech
University, was the first commissioner solely appointed by the
governor.
</P>
<P>
   But the board retains authority over curriculum standards, has
limited input over textbook selection and approves or rejects
applications for charter schools. It also oversees the Permanent
School Fund, a major source of public education funding.
</P>
<P>
   And the panel is an occasional source of potshots at the
education commissioner, prompted either by envy of the
commissioner's higher-profile role or by philosophical or political
differences.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Neill, a Republican board member from Fort Worth,
recently took a parting shot at Moses on the former commissioner's
last day on the job. Neill criticized Moses for developing a new
state skills test without the board's knowledge or consent.
</P>
<P>
   Moses denied the allegations. But his successor, James E.
Nelson, can likely expect similar messages whenever a board member
takes issue with one of his actions or simply wants to make a
political statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature, in recent years, has had trouble deciding what
to do with the board, which has only three staff members of its own
and has to rely on research and other work conducted by the
commissioner's staff.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, as a key part of House Bill 72 reforms, lawmakers
abolished a 27-member, elected board, which had come to be viewed
as an obstacle to needed educational improvements. Legislators
replaced it with a smaller board appointed by the governor,
believing the governor's appointees could be better trusted to
carry out the Legislature's orders.
</P>
<P>
   The 1984 law stipulated that the appointed board would be only
temporary and would be replaced within a few years by another
elected panel. But legislative leaders liked the appointed board so
much that they proposed keeping the panel appointed.
</P>
<P>
   Given the choice in a referendum, however, Texas voters
overwhelmingly said they wanted to elect board members, even though
most people don't even bother to vote in elections for their local
school boards, which have more impact on their educational tax
dollars than the state board does.
</P>
<P>
   The result is one of the most awkwardly constructed boards in
state government. The 15 members are elected from districts that
are twice as big as congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   The board, which now has a 9-6 Republican majority, has some
qualified, well-intentioned members. But since few Texans know
anything about the panel, the size of the districts also makes it
relatively easy for well-organized, single-interest candidates to
be elected. Social conservatives have been particularly successful
in winning election to the board, which offers a ready forum for
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Since the commissioner could do the board's job, some lawmakers
have toyed with the idea of abolishing the panel. But they haven't,
perhaps partly out of fear that some board members would paint them
as undemocratic, which they surely would.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
