<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3556 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-DANCE-NEWSEASON-GUSSO     09-07 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-NEWSEASON-GUSSOW-$ADV12-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEKHOV WITHOUT THE WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 12)  
(mk) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As a conceptual director, Martha Clarke is a creative
body in motion. On a recent morning in her airy Greenwich Village
apartment (many years ago the home of Marcel Duchamp), she was
brimming with activity. She was in the middle of casting ``Hans
Christian Andersen,'' her deromanticized Broadway musical version
of the 1952 movie. The show is planned for this season, and she was
still looking for an actor for the now misanthropic title role
(played in the film by Danny Kaye). The Irish playwright and
novelist Sebastian Barry, who is writing the new book for the
musical, had just arrived in New York on one of his periodic visits
to work with Ms. Clarke, and he had narrowly missed running into
Christopher Hampton on the stairway. Hampton had been there to
confer with Ms. Clarke about their projected Broadway version of
``The Blue Angel,'' a play with music based on the Marlene Dietrich
movie and the original Heinrich Mann novel.
</P>
<P>
   First in line for Ms. Clarke was ``Vers la Flamme,'' her
adaptation of five Chekhov stories, scheduled to run Wednesday
through next Sunday at the New Victory Theater as part of Lincoln
Center's Great Performers series. She was facing her usual long day
of appointments and telephone conversations about her diverse
projects. Were Chekhov to call, he would wonder what she was doing
to his classic stories. Well, Anton, it's like this....
</P>
<P>
   ``Vers la Flamme'' is an impressionistic interpretation of the
stories. As in her other work, it is an experiment in movement,
imagery, atmosphere and sound. In the show, Chekhov is seen but not
heard. There is only one word of dialogue, ``Olga,'' spoken by a
husband in an empty room in the story ``Enemies'' after his wife
has left him. In the cast are some of Ms. Clarke's favorite
performers, including Paola Styron, Margie Gillis, Felix Blaska and
George de la Pena, all of whom have made their own ensemble
contribution to the piece. Sofi, one of the director's two
Pomeranian dogs, is making her acting debut in ``The Lady With the
Lapdog'' in the Chekhov evening, and the other Pomeranian is the
understudy.
</P>
<P>
   When the 70-minute show had its premiere in April at Dartmouth
College, it was filled with striking images: snow seen fleetingly
through a window; a Monet-esque seascape signifying Yalta; an actor
climbing a wall as if fleeing into the sky painted on the ceiling
of the Michael Yeargan set. Since Dartmouth, Ms. Clarke has been
polishing the piece, adding and subtracting moments and movements.
In July, it was performed again at Jacob's Pillow.
</P>
<P>
   In the background as a throbbing motif is music by Alexander
Scriabin, more than 30 piano pieces played by Christopher O'Riley,
who is on stage with the actors. The title ``Vers la Flamme''
(``Toward the Flame'') comes from one of the Scriabin pieces.
Explaining its relevance, Ms. Clarke said: ``The Chekhov characters
always seemed to be hovering near a flame. They singe their wings
but they don't get burnt.''
</P>
<P>
   Scriabin was Chekhov's contemporary and thematic opposite, the
composer's sensuousness and volatility in direct contrast to the
writer's plangency: Scriabin the mystic, Chekhov the social
realist. The two are, Ms. Clarke said, ``odd bedfellows.'' With the
addition of the innovative director, this becomes a curious menage
a trois. For her, such a surprising juxtaposition is nothing new,
whether she is working in dance, theater or opera. Hers is often a
theater of opposites. Reading or watching Chekhov, she finds ``an
emotional fragility that's almost palpable _ like a fragrance.''
For Ms. Clarke, Scriabin fills in ``the subtext of Chekhov.'' In
other words, she is suggesting that if Chekhov had broken loose, he
might have had the obsessiveness of Scriabin.
</P>
<P>
   In her previous work, she has explored art, literature, history
and mythology, often at the same time. Beginning as a dancer and
choreographer, she sidestepped into the role of conceptual
director. She started with Kafka, then shifted to Heironymus Bosch
with her fabulistic tapestry, ``The Garden of Earthly Delights.''
After that, she reimagined the elegance and decadence of Vienna at
the turn of the century in ``Vienna: Lusthaus.'' She widened her
vision to include animal behavior and ecology in ``Endangered
Species.''
</P>
<P>
   After ``Endangered Species'' received harsh reviews in 1990 and
closed precipitously at the Brooklyn Academy of Music, she moved to
London and focused on opera (in recent seasons, she has directed
Tan Dun's ``Marco Polo'' and Gluck's ``Orfeo'' at the New York City
Opera). Along the way, she collaborated with Hampton on a
psychological tracking of ``Alice in Wonderland'' (at London's
Royal National Theater). While diversifying her range, she has
remained true to her core, approaching texts and subjects as raw
material for dramatic transformation.
</P>
<P>
   In part, her explorations have been geographic. Tracing the
origin of ``Vers la Flamme,'' she said that she wanted to do
something Russian: ``Russia was in my blood and I was very drawn to
the turn of the century. That's probably when I had another life.''
</P>
<P>
   As always, she immersed herself in research, reading about
Chekhov and the Russia of his period. At the same time she culled
the stories, choosing those with which she felt a close connection
and deciding which best suited her actors. Ms. Styron had a
particular affinity with ``The Lady With the Lapdog.'' The
director, Ms. Styron and de la Pena talked about that story, and
then, wearing makeshift costumes, the actors began improvising
movements, with Ms. Clarke leading them into new areas.
</P>
<P>
   She said about her method: ``There's a tension involved if
you're taking an emotion like fear or anger and translating it
physically. Where other people will start with a rhythm of
language, I'll start with a natural reflex, or the dancers will do
some kind of turn, and we'll build from that.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The stories deal with love, passion and betrayal. The characters
are highly strung people confronting crises, sometimes within a
moral context. One reason Ms. Clarke likes the stories, she said,
is that ``they nearly all end in ambiguity.'' For those unfamiliar
with the texts, it may be difficult to follow the narrative.
Occasionally, the director has faced irate theatergoers saying she
should insist that people read the synopses in the program before
seeing the show.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Clarke, the show should be received as if it were a
movie or a piece of music: ``I always felt that Fellini in `8{'
liberated our need to visualize and understand story. It's a bit
like stream of consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Clarke was asked the perennial what-is-it question
about her work, she said, ``I'm not sure what it is.'' Then she
explained: ``I use dancers as actors and I direct as though I'm
using text. However, there is no text. It's all done through
movement and gesture _ and the chamber music is a very big
component.'' After an interviewer suggested that the piece was
dangerously close to silent film, Ms. Clarke asked, ``What's so
dangerous about that?'' Of course a silent film has titles, while
Ms. Clarke's work leaves audiences entirely on their own, reacting
to the direct stimulus of the performance. Her hope is that
everyone, including critics, will leave expectations at the door
and meet the work on its own terms.
</P>
<P>
   About the difference between dance and movement, she said:
``Conventionally, people think of dance as dance vocabulary, based
on either a modern dance or a ballet idiom. In each piece I do, the
physical vocabulary is created for that piece and generally doesn't
make it to the next one. Obviously I have a style and a look. I
tend to think of it as minimal, because I don't like fat and I
don't like frills. Occasionally I'll sacrifice an absolutely
beautiful movement because I don't think it's really true to the
emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the conversation, however, she admitted that she
repeated motifs, which become her equivalent of a dance vocabulary:
images, for example, are often seen through windows or open doors,
as in her version of ``Alice in Wonderland'' as well as ``Vers la
Flamme.'' She said that in the new piece ``we use a way of turning
that I had started but hadn't developed in `Vienna: Lusthaus' _ a
skating turn.'' There are other moments that she characterized as
``definitely Martha.''
</P>
<P>
   With each piece, she finds herself on the firing line:
``Obviously, one would rather be loved than burned at the stake,
but the truth is that I enjoy the process so much more than I did
when I was younger.'' Theater, or at least her branch of theater,
``is not for sissies,'' she said. ``It's like people say about old
age, you have to be prepared for humiliation. It's amazing to be 55
and to think that I can still make people upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she has had a few fallow periods in her career, her
``garden'' is now full, and she can move freely from one performing
art to another. ``Hans Christian Andersen,'' which would be her
first Broadway musical, is a particular challenge. Replacing the
book of the upbeat Hollywood movie, but keeping the Frank Loesser
score and adding other Loesser songs, she wants to uncover the
darker, more complex side of the Danish storyteller.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a solitary writer,'' she said, ``who despised critics,
wept easily and had unfulfilled yearnings for unattainable women''
_ and he had an ambiguous attitude toward children. ``Sebastian and
I are trying to weave his true biography with the stories that seem
to come out of his life. In some ways, Chekhov is preparing me for
Andersen.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year she is bringing back ``Vienna: Lusthaus'' for a
national tour, and she is already committed to a project in St.
Petersburg in 2003, a piece based on Gogol. Confronted with the
chance for a new theatrical adventure, she says: ``This is
impossible. I'll do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
