u w BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY08-COX     09-07 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOPES FADING FOR SOCIAL SECURITY REFORM THIS YEAR
 &HT;    650&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN and BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There's little chance Social Security will be
reformed this year, and no agreement is likely until after the
November 2000 elections, advocates said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's dead for this year,'' said Michael Tanner, who
heads the Social Security privatization project for the libertarian
Cato Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Max Ritchman, vice president of the National Committee to
Preserve Social Security and Medicare, said Congress's attention
for the next few weeks will be focused on passing appropriation
bills and a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then they're out of here until next year,'' he said. Reform
advocates have repeatedly said they do not believe the program can
be dramatically changed in an election year such as 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bixby, policy director of the bipartisan Concord
Coalition, called failure to reform the program, expected to run
out of money by 2034, a squandered opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one moment in time. It will never come around again,''
he said. ``It's a sore subject for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, White House chief of staff John Podesta did not
include Social Security in a list of priority issues this fall, and
the chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee expressed dismay
Tuesday at that omission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you will reconsider your reluctance to saving Social
Security this year, Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, said in a letter to
Clinton. ``As president, you must choose between employing your
powerful position and leadership to achieve real progress for
America's next generation or squandering those considerable assets
on political victories in the next election.''
</P>
<P>
   While not responding directly to Archer's letter, Clinton
repeatedly mentioned the need to save Social Security in a speech
Tuesday in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to, first of all, think about the long-term welfare
of the country: save Social Security and Medicare; get the country
out of debt; invest what we have to do in education and other
things; then give the rest in a tax cut,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Reforming Social Security this year has long been a top
administration priority. In last year's State of the Union message,
Clinton set out a timetable for action. He urged spending that year
talking about the need for reform and the various options, then
convening a high-level summit of congressional leaders and the
administration early this year to adopt a plan with bipartisan
support.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen. Last year was spent in discussions, and
congressional leaders met for two days in December to discuss the
need for reform with Clinton, but the summit meetings to draft a
plan never occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened, essentially, was Monica,'' Tanner said,
referring to the scandal involving Clinton and former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky which led to the president's impeachment and
Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was real opportunity last year,'' Tanner said, noting
that Clinton had indicated a willingness to accept some version of
private investment accounts as part of a Social Security reform
plan.
</P>
<P>
   After impeachment, ``the president was forced to shore up his
left wing,'' which opposes privatization, Tanner said. And after
the Senate trial this spring, ``Republicans became unable to do
anything controversial.''
</P>
<P>
   Bixby traced the collapse of momentum to this year's State of
the Union address, in which Clinton advocated using the projected
federal budget surplus to finance the system into the middle of the
next decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea was, we were going to prepare the nation for
these hard choices'' involved with reducing Social Security
benefits, Bixby said. ``But then, having done all that, comes the
State of the Union address this year and you'd think that the whole
hard choices never existed. We're going to use budget surpluses to
fix Social Security. ... It totally took the wind out of Social
Security reform.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., chairman of the Ways and Means
subcommittee on Social Security, said he expects his panel to vote
later this month on a reform proposal he and Archer offered in May.
The plan would use the budget surplus as well as personal
investment accounts to improve Social Security's earnings and
extend its financial life without cutting benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is still a little bit of momentum,'' Shaw said,
but ``it's not a tidal wave of momentum at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said he believes the administration and congressional
Democrats are split over whether to push for Social Security reform
now or use its failure as a campaign weapon against the
Republican-led Congress next year.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said both parties are more likely to benefit _ and the
country will be better off _ if Social Security is reformed now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a joining in by the president in order to
go ahead with reform,'' Shaw said, later adding: ``I hope this
letter will shake loose some help.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
