</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-DANCE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTHA GRAHAM'S LEGACY: HOW THE DANCES WILL NOW BE DANCED
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif., Colo.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As it prepares for the opening of its new season, the
Martha Graham Dance Company has made a series of decisive moves
that it hopes will nourish and protect its founder's artistic
legacy and insure its own survival as a dynamic institution.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Protas, who succeeded Graham as artistic director on her
death in 1991, will step aside next year to devote himself full
time to running the troupe's new licensing program as well as to
the preservation work as the chief of the Martha Graham Archives at
the Library of Congress. He will continue to work with the company
as its artistic adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Protas will be succeeded by Janet Eilber, a former Graham
principal who will take over the directorship in July. And Charlene
Nederlander, the theater producer and arts patron, has agreed to
lead the Graham board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wanted to get out,'' Protas said. ``Two contiguous needs
have overlapped: my desires to have time to work with the Library
of Congress and to license Martha's work around the world. I've
been torn. I believe the Martha Graham Company needs to become more
institutionalized.''
</P>
<P>
   With Todd Dellinger in place since 1997 as the company's
managing director and with the arrival of Ms. Eilber, Protas said:
``I felt I could make this gesture. The missing element now is a
stronger board to support the vision that Todd and I and Janet have
crafted. Todd and Janet need much more support from the board than
they are getting now.''
</P>
<P>
   Protas said new members had agreed to join the board, among them
Lloyd E. Rigler, an arts patron who is the president of the Lloyd
E. Rigler-Lawrence E. Deutsch Foundation in Burbank, Calif.; and
the actress Vanessa Redgrave, who has invited the Graham company to
perform in shows she has organized in Kosovo this weekend. The
troupe's first performance is Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Graham company moved from its home of many years
on East 63rd Street in Manhattan to downtown studios opposite the
Public Theater, leased from Musical Theater Works, and offices a
few blocks away. School registration is up, Dellinger said, and
both the junior and senior Graham companies are rehearsing there
for national touring through April. In May they plan to move back
uptown to new quarters on the old site.
</P>
<P>
   Eager young staff members seem to be everywhere, and the sound
of classroom piano music filters through the temporary
headquarters. Things seem to be looking up for the company, which
has endured years of financial instability.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the company's uptown headquarters to the developer
Benedetto Caiola, who agreed to provide the company and school with
studio and office space in a new building on the site, meant that
the Graham troupe could pay off its mortgage of $1.5 million and an
operating deficit of $400,000. But now, Protas said, it needs to
raise money for its day-to-day expenses. That is why, he said,
``I've been bringing in new board members with clout.''
</P>
<P>
   The new licensing program is intended to bring in money,
although he says he sees the project chiefly as a way of making it
possible for many more audiences to see the work and for the
quality of the productions to be overseen and preserved. Protas,
who owns the dances, established the Martha Graham Trust last year
to market the works.
</P>
<P>
   Modeled on the Balanchine Trust with the assistance of Barbara
Horgan, its director, the Graham Trust leases dances to companies
and schools throughout the world and, for $1 a year, to the Graham
company itself. Prices otherwise vary depending in part on the
individual dances and on the length of the leasing contract, which
usually runs from two to three years. Companies also rent costumes
and sets from the Graham troupe or build their own with the Graham
designs as their guide and arrange for the rights to the music.
</P>
<P>
   ``At my death the dances will go to a Martha Graham Foundation
that we are in the process of forming, which will have the mandate
to protect her name and property and to continue to lease the
works,'' Protas said.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly enough, Protas has made a point of icensing the
dances to ballet troupes rather than modern dance companies. One of
the most prominent companies is American Ballet Theater, which is
featuring Graham's ``Diversion of Angels'' in its City Center
season next month.
</P>
<P>
   In this age of crossover dance, even the venerable Paris Opera
Ballet has been delving into the mysteries of ``Grahamienne''
dance, as some of the performers call it, and what makes a move or
a gesture ``vraiment Graham,'' in performances of ``Temptations of
the Moon'' and the stark signature solo piece, ``Lamentation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one at the Paris Opera Ballet wanted to do `Lamentation,'''
Protas said. ``It's only three minutes long. But they fell in love
with it once they danced it. It caught them emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   The Het National Ballet of the Netherlands has ``Acts of
Light,'' ``Embattled Garden'' and ``Errand Into the Maze.'' The
Colorado Ballet and the Joffrey Ballet will dance ``Appalachian
Spring.'' Julio Bocca has acquired ``Acts of Light'' and
``Diversion of Angels'' for his Ballet Argentino. And the ballet
company of the Teatro Municipal of Rio de Janeiro will dance
``Maple Leaf Rag.'' Five additional ballet troupes are negotiating
licensing contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Protas, who shaped the project with Jane Hermann, a former
ballet director and producer who is now a vice president and
director of dance at ICM, says that ballet dancers may be better
able to perform Graham's choreography than modern-dance companies
not rigorously trained in the Graham technique, in part because of
the structure and discipline of ballet.
</P>
<P>
   There are some works he said he would hesitate to lease, among
them the playful ``Acrobats of God'' and the dark ``Herodiade,''
which Protas describes as difficult. ``And `Clytemnestra' would be
a challenge, but I would love to see it done by a ballet company,''
he said. ``Ballet has the tradition of prima ballerina assoluta.
Martha made many `assoluta' or star roles for women. But modern
dance did not produce so many women stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martha felt that `Herodiade' revealed too much of herself.
Without the right person, the dance would fall flat.''
</P>
<P>
   The pieces will be staged by former Graham dancers like Takako
Asakawa and Kenneth Topping, who are working with Ballet Theater.
Ms. Asakawa will decide with the new dancers whether crash courses
in the Graham technique will be necessary. Protas says that not
only technique is important. ``These are works of such depth and
passion that they become melodramatic if they are not coached
properly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dancers of today have been so exposed to the Graham
technique that it will not be all that unusual. It doesn't mean
that they will perform the works exactly as I or Martha would wish.
But as I said to ABT, as long as the spirit or the gist is there
the rest will come. These are works of such depth and passion that
they become melodramatic if they are not coached properly,'' Protas
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Protas' conversation is filled with speculation on how to make
Graham's work live in a new time without violating its quality and
principles. To this end Protas has been envisioning ``the
definitive DVD of Martha's work'' at the Library of Congress. ``The
library is raising $6 million to film Graham technique for
distribution around the world, with the ballets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He has been working with Ms. Asakawa and two former Graham
dancers, Pearl Lang and Yuriko Kikuchi, on a multi-media project
for the simultaneous teaching of Graham's technique, its changes
over the years and Graham's inspirations for elements in the
technique. He has also had talks with Robert Wilson about
``contemporizing'' Graham's work. ``Not changing Martha,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The works will stay the same. It's like Shakespeare. I'm not
saying we should update `Clytemnestra' to the 1940s and bring in
the Gestapo. But there are many versions of `As You Like It.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
