<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3566 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HAYNES-BESTSELLERS-2T     09-07 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAYNES-BESTSELLERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDDLE-AGED WRITER FINDS FAME EXORCISING DEMONS VIA FICTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Miss.)   (bl)  
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND BAY, Ala. _ The trailer where Melinda Haynes found her
muse lies at the bottom of this state in the pine savannas where
sunlight and shadow mingle into a cool shade of dark jade.
</P>
<P>
   The ``manufactured home'' _ a term that Ms. Haynes considers a
more dignified description _ is not as big as a wraparound porch.
But it is roomy enough for the imagination of Ms. Haynes, a Baptist
preacher's daughter who at age 44 has written a first novel,
``Mother of Pearl.'' Her tale of small-town drama in 1950s Petal,
Miss., has transformed the circumstances of her life from the
trials of the trailer to the comforts of Country Living.
</P>
<P>
   The television signal for Oprah Winfrey's popular book club
discussions is too faint to reach her living room in Grand Bay, a
sparsely populated coastal community where reading groups are about
as plentiful as the endangered red-cockaded woodpecker. But still
Ms. Winfrey found Ms. Haynes and featured ``Mother of Pearl'' as
her summer book selection, turning a novel with a modest first
printing of 6,800 copies into a best seller with 750,000 in print.
</P>
<P>
   The literary rush came with instant prosperity that had eluded
Ms. Haynes, who says she knows what it is like to see the lights
flick off because of an unpaid bill or to lose a home to
foreclosure. Since her success she has been able to pay cash for a
freshwater-pearl necklace for a beloved middle-school teacher and
for a five-bedroom house with black shutters, 10-foot ceilings and
three porches that are bigger than the trailer she will be leaving
soon. But her tender new confidence did not come as easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like the book was going to be well received regionally,
and I was hoping there would be some ground swell,'' said Ms.
Haynes, who is barely 5 feet tall with close-clipped graying hair
and eyes the color of coffee beans. ``I never expected to sell more
than 20,000 copies.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she wrote the initial manuscript in a six-month burst
in 1997 from a back room in the trailer, where she would gaze out
on the night sky and confront yellow flies in season. Others had
urged her to plumb her life with all its dramatic tensions, but she
favored fiction, spiced with many of her emotions and anxieties.
</P>
<P>
   At night, after finishing her day job as a production manager at
The Catholic Week newspaper in Mobile, Ms. Haynes said she
retreated to her computer, where characters emerged in 1950s Petal,
the setting for her own early childhood. ``Mother of Pearl''
explores the friendship of Even Grade, a 28-year-old black man who
did not know his family, and Valuable Korner, a 15-year-old white
girl born to the town harlot who is probably better off without
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Haynes spent most of her life in Mobile, she placed
her novel 85 miles west in the Mississippi towns of Petal and
Hattiesburg because, she said, ``it was the first place I began to
feel different.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as she writes about a palette of brown shades in the river
Leaf _ 10-minute tea, steeped-too-long tea, barely tea, wet bark,
sun-baked bark, old-as-sin bark _ Ms. Haynes said she grew up with
anxieties and panic attacks that came in exotic hues and varieties.
</P>
<P>
   There was her fear of the second coming of Christ, a vision that
she took to heart from her fundamentalist upbringing. And in later
years she added new layers: fear of public speaking, fear of
crowds, fear that her ``pyloric valve'' would burst. (This last
anxiety was based on conversations overheard as a child about her
grandfather's esophageal cancer.)
</P>
<P>
   The first panic attack came during a seventh-grade math class,
she said, describing an electrical sensation that started in the
back of her neck and spread, stealing her breath away. While her
counselor advised her parents not to overreact to subsequent
attacks, Ms. Haynes said, they continued and she grew to dislike
school so much that she would ride the bus there, then turn around
and walk home. By 11th grade she left high school and was tutored
for a year to earn a diploma. She said she never went to college
because she had another fear: she wouldn't measure up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that all of her anxieties finally found a release in
her writing,'' said Ms. Haynes' mother, Patricia Braswell, a
schoolteacher who with her husband, Richard, split from the Baptist
church and helped form a charismatic church and religious academy
in Mobile. ``It's like her characters began to experience all the
things that she's experienced herself. I think this has been a
healing thing for her. She has always been sensitive. When she was
little, she didn't want us to leave her. She was afraid we would
lose her in the library.''
</P>
<P>
   When she was 18, Ms. Haynes made a choice that started her slide
down from the middle class. She married a minister's son in a union
that she said grew out of another anxiety. She thought she was
pregnant, but she wasn't. The marriage collapsed after 19 years and
three children and financial burdens that led to bankruptcy and
what Ms. Haynes delicately describes as her ``crash'': a suicide
attempt through an overdose of antidepressants.
</P>
<P>
   Through those years she helped support her family by painting
portraits in oil and watercolors, but she put down the brush after
the suicide attempt. The vivid colors did not emerge again until
she took up writing in the mid-1990s after converting to
Catholicism and marrying a retired marine, Raymond Haynes, who
liked to say that she wrote like a tall woman.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Haynes, always a passionate reader of Southern writers like
Eudora Welty and William Faulkner, said her new husband set up a
computer for her and encouraged her to write and ultimately to
publish her first two short stories, which included a tale about an
elderly black woman, Joody Two Sun, who later took up residence in
her novel as a mysterious seer.
</P>
<P>
   With her characters, Ms. Haynes confronted her own fears. She is
afraid of bridges, so she placed one character in the middle of a
span between Hattiesburg and Petal. Later she traced his fictional
footsteps on the same bridge. ``They say you can only teach what
you need to learn,'' Ms. Haynes said about the writing that became
a journey of sorts. ``I wrote what I needed to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband secretly sent her short stories to The Crescent
Review, a journal that he discovered by thumbing through copies of
Poets and Writers magazine for potential outlets for her work. The
journal prompted the couple to send early chapters of ``Mother of
Pearl,'' then called ``Even Grade,'' to a New York literary agent,
Wendy Weil, who was the subject of a profile that noted that she
read unsolicited manuscripts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I often say this little prayer when a manuscript comes in
unannounced,'' Ms. Weil said. `` `Please stay good. Please stay
good.' And they don't always, but this one stayed good. She has
this wonderful ear for language and this big heart and sense of
humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney's Hyperion bought the book for about a $100,000 advance
in April 1998, which gave Ms. Haynes enough of a cushion to quit
her day job to write full time. With the halo from Ms. Winfrey's
book club, Ms. Haynes' royalties could easily climb to more than
$1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Her sudden literary celebrity has brought her attention around
Mobile, where she has made bookstore appearances and lectured. For
these engagements she rehearsed at home with a small podium and
microphone that her husband built to ease her fears of public
speaking.
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama her book has generated everything from unabashed
pride to mixed reviews. The Mobile Register featured Ms. Haynes in
two front-page stories, but its book review editor took the rare
step of publishing a negative and a positive review of ``Mother of
Pearl'' after the first reviewer panned the novel, complaining
among other things that it was long-winded and meandering with
slang and wording that often seemed inauthentic for the 1950's.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are mixed feelings about this book,'' said John Sledge,
the Register's book editor. ``There are people who think it's
problematic and difficult, but yet there are other people who are
moved by it.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, Roy Hoffman, in The New York Times Book Review,
described Ms. Haynes' language as ``profuse and vigorous'' as the
kudzu vine, providing a portrait of a Southern town that ``still
has its edgy charm.'' He continued: ``Summer here may be
sweltering, but there's enough going on to keep the beauty parlor
abuzz. And Haynes will surely be one of the last authors of this
century to take us back to the small-town South of its middle
years.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ms. Haynes' circle of family and friends, readers have come
away with varying interpretations, particularly because their
experiences and anecdotes sometimes seeped into the novel.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Richard Braswell, marveled at the power of her
observations and poetic descriptions of a familiar river in
Mississippi but confessed some shock at her occasional use of
``vile language.'' Her parish priest, the Rev. Louis Russell Biven,
who inspired a character who is also a Catholic priest and named
Russ, found the book ``certainly insightful, careful and
precious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was bold, this little gal writing this book,'' he
continued. ``And that it would be published, and people would be
reading it, it absolutely amazed me. I always thought she was
bright and talented.'' But he added, ``I can't say I understood the
book entirely.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Haynes is working on a second book for Hyperion, tentatively
titled ``Chalktown.'' But for now she is devoting more time to
promoting ``Mother of Pearl.'' (Her second appearance on Ms.
Winfrey's show is scheduled for tomorrow.)
</P>
<P>
   With the windfall of publicity, Hyperion is sending Ms. Haynes
on a tour of bookstores from New York to San Francisco, a literary
ritual that forces her to conquer yet one more anxiety: fear of
flying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1811EDT &QL; 
