a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV14-     09-07 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV14-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAST IMPLANT CONTROVERSY FAR FROM OVER
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Tuesday, Sept. 14)  
(nk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A woman with new implants was raving over her new breasts like
others do over the perfect haircut and fitting into a smaller jeans
size. She doesn't want to hear that there could be trouble ahead.
</P>
<P>
   She's a mature woman and this is something she chose after
nursing three children took a toll on her body image. It's her
body. Maybe she and her new breasts will live happily ever after.
But who knows. There are skeptics out there like former implant
wearer Jody Fischer who think they all eventually fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet she doesn't go to her grave with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest salvo in the breast implant debate sounded this
summer when a government-requested study concluded that silicone
implants don't make women seriously ill. Implants can rupture and
lead to infections or scarring, but they do not cause lupus,
arthritis and other systemic diseases, said a panel of 13
scientists for the Institute of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dow Corning _ which had to file for bankruptcy
because of the number of breast implant lawsuits against it _ has
agreed to pay $3.2 billion to 400,000 American women with silicone
implants. This should be the end of it, say some. Not for the women
who hurt, say others.
</P>
<P>
   Some women will go away with money in their pocket _ an amount
still to be determined by a judge _ but it may not be enough to
live on, says Fischer, 68, of Santa Rosa, who is ready ``to stir up
something.''
</P>
<P>
   She's part of the global suit against Dow and worries, ``We'll
get patted on the head, given a little and told to go away.'' She
thinks she'll have to keep pushing for fair and adequate
compensation and, just in case, she's kept the evidence. Parts of
the implant that her doctor fished out of her body are stored in
preservative in a container in her garage.
</P>
<P>
   Jody can't stand the idea that people think the implant
controversy is dead and that women should be ashamed for ever
making a stink. When she heard a late-night talk show host calling
women like herself fraudulent, she literally sprang from her bed
and began writing letters to the media, government officials and
every former implant wearer.
</P>
<P>
   Jody had her first silicone implant in 1978 after a mastectomy
for breast cancer. It never felt right. Four years later her doctor
replaced it with a second silicone implant. Ten years later the
tissue became inflamed and swollen and a hard casing formed around
the implant. Her doctor removed it and Jody said silicone was found
embedded in her right breast tissue and chest wall.
</P>
<P>
   Jody feels like a ``sick test animal,'' and says, ``I recovered
from breast cancer, but I can't recover from silicone.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the studies say _ and this last one is considered
pretty definitive by medical writers _ there are hundreds of
thousands of implanted women with matching symptoms, who have
lupus, arthritis, fatigue and memory problems. Jody has had bouts
with all of them, which forced her to quit the real estate job she
loved. ``I used to be very high energy and highly organized. For
women like me there is no controversy over implants.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet others still see new breasts as what they need to turn their
lives around.
</P>
<P>
   A good economy is said to be good for the cosmetic surgery
business, and breast augmentation is still on a lot of wish lists.
It's the most common cosmetic surgery for women ages 19 to 34.
Teen-age girls request them for graduation presents. You can buy
them on the installment plan. And even though many now choose
saline implants, which are presumed to be safer than silicone, the
National Women's Health Network says there's no research on the
long-term safety and effects of saline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish women could learn to be satisfied with what we have,''
says Jody. The chances of which are probably even less than her
getting enough from Dow to stop writing letters.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com. The
Press Democrat is part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
