<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3569 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FILM-NEWSEASON-HOLLYW     09-07 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NEWSEASON-HOLLYWOOD-$ADV12-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST RUSHES OF A HOLLYWOOD SLOW-DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 12)  
(DW) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Someone contemplating the list of films for most
recent movie seasons might have been forgiven for wondering whether
Hollywood had a hole in the bottom of its ideas bucket. Strip away
the sequels, pare away the remakes, ignore the big-screen versions
of television chestnuts, discard the book adaptations and the
(increasingly rare) play adaptations and often there was not much
left.
</P>
<P>
   Add to this the anxiety in Hollywood over recent waves of cost
cutting at the studios _ some making fewer movies, others sharing
the risk of big productions between a pair of studios or between a
studio and an independent production entity, much of the digital
filmmaking being done outside the Hollywood orbit in San Francisco
and elsewhere, shooting more and more films in Canada or New
Zealand or any place cheaper than Hollywood, asking whether that $3
million shot of a tanker ship exploding is really necessary to make
the audience happy _ and there is a very real sense of unease here.
People wonder whether Hollywood will still make offbeat and
sophisticated films, or even survive as anything more than a
financing source and distribution-and-marketing service for other
peoples' risky visions.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood, bent and twisted by all of these financial,
technological and artistic pressures, is clearly in the process of
becoming something else, but becoming what? It's a guessing game.
But perhaps we are beginning to see, with this year's fall and
holiday lineup, just what kinds of movies Hollywood studios and the
major independents are going to be making in response to all of the
corporatizing and cost-cutting and hand-wringing.
</P>
<P>
   To this newcomer to Los Angeles _ and a newcomer to the task of
covering movies and the movie industry _ this sense of creative
unease and financial anxiety seems to seep into every conversation.
Yet more than 30 recent interviews with studio executives,
producers, writers, directors and, yes, bean counters reveals a
growing, if sometimes tentative, hope for Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those interviewed remarked, sometimes with apparent
wonder, how good much of this year's fall and holiday lineup looks.
Of course, they're paid to say things like that, at least about
their own films, and there is always a certain amount of
breast-thumping about any approaching movie season, leading to
inevitable speculation about how such a period of cost-cutting
could have produced such a roster. When the bean counters come in
and the budgets go down, shouldn't the movies suffer?
</P>
<P>
   Though many of the films are still in the finishing stages,
others have begun to make the rounds either in final form, in rough
cuts or in small snippets screened for a select handful. ``This
fall looks much stronger to me than last fall,'' said Mark Gill,
president of the Los Angeles division of Miramax Films, whose
``Shakespeare in Love'' won the Best Picture Oscar last year.
``Just look at the range of films, how many more things there are
that appear to be genuine Oscar contenders.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the season has its share of sequels (``Scream 3''),
remakes (``The House on Haunted Hill''), long-running series (``The
World Is Not Enough,'' the 19th and latest James Bond adventure)
and more than a dozen book adaptations, the evidence also shows
that despite fears that cost cutting would make studios timid and
shave the sharp edges from quirky films, the reality is oddly
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a surprisingly unpandering-to-the-mainstream
movie season coming up,'' is the way Amy Pascal, president of
Columbia Pictures, put it.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Hollywood had just one film (``Jerry Maguire'')
among the five contenders for the Academy Award for best picture.
This year, that will not be the case, executives vow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studios are back,'' said Stacey Snider, co-chairman of
Universal Pictures. ``That's the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the beginning of almost every movie season _ especially
the fall and holiday season, when so many movies are pitched toward
older audiences and Oscar voters _ seems to promise more joy than
it eventually delivers. The financial anxiety at the studios may be
creating a bumper crop of wishful thinking. But even if half of
these films turn out to be turkeys, it will still be a formidable
roster.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to assess those films they have seen _ in either
finished form or rough cut or in sufficient clips for them to make
what they consider a sound judgment _ or those films about which
they have heard detailed descriptions in the etherlike buzz on
which Hollywood floats these days like a hydrofoil, those
interviewed came up among them with a list of more than a dozen
films that they believe will be fighting it out for the top Oscar
nominations early next year. (Note: when asked this question,
almost everyone of course mentioned either their own film or the
films from their studio; all such votes were discounted.)
</P>
<P>
   The films mentioned most frequently (that is, by more than 10 of
those interviewed) were ``The Green Mile,'' the director Frank
Darabont's adaptation of Stephen King's Death Row tale starring Tom
Hanks; ``Three Kings''; David O. Russell's story of three GI's
searching for buried loot in the waning days of the Gulf War; ``The
Talented Ripley,'' Anthony Minghella's adaptation of Patricia
Highsmith's classic dark thriller; ``The Insider,'' Michael Mann's
retelling of the clash between a tobacco industry whistle-blower, a
``60 Minutes'' producer and the forces of big tobacco and big
media; ``The Hurricane,'' Norman Jewison's film starring Denzel
Washington, and ``American Beauty,'' the theater director Sam
Mendes' inaugural Hollywood effort, about the emotional damage
caused when a married man develops an infatuation with one of his
teen-age daughter's young friends.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad _ if it's true _ for an industry that sometimes sounds
like it's on life support.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1813EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3570 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FILM-NEWSEASON-HOLLYW     09-07 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NEWSEASON-HOLLYWOOD-$ADV12-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
 
HOLLYWOOD: life support.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The story of the movie business' financial woes, particularly in
the last several years as top star salaries rose above $20 million
and production and marketing costs also soared, is like an old,
favorite set of worry beads that Hollywood people like to finger in
the gathering gloom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The town has become much more cost-conscious,'' said Robert G.
Friedman, vice chairman of the Paramount Motion Picture Group. ``We
have become aware over time that the economics of the movie
business are tougher and tougher, and the only way to make that
better is to make your movies cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   But how can this possibly translate into better films?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it results in new voices and new ideas and new ways to
tell stories in a way that's actually really exciting,'' Ms. Snider
said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that something happened over the last several
years; the cost of making a movie has skyrocketed, both because of
higher salaries for the top actors and directors and other ``above
the line'' talent and for the physical, ``below the line'' costs of
actually making the film. The old formulas (star-studded big-budget
explosion pictures, for instance, built on macho images and
paper-thin characterizations) don't work reliably enough to be
worth the money they cost, and even a summer as successful as the
one just passed, with more than a half-dozen movies surpassing $100
million at the box office, isn't enough for the studios to turn a
sufficient profit to satisfy their corporate bosses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business is broken,'' said Bill Mechanic, chairman of 20th
Century Fox. ``The business fell apart when the budgets of pictures
went running sky high.'' The only answer, he and others said, is to
cut costs, so that's what the studios, to varying degrees, have
been trying to do. While a few stars will earn astronomical fees,
secondary stars are earning less (``the $10 million sidekick,'' is
how one insider put it), and the studios are always on the lookout
for cheaper, younger talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost of a movie is too high to recoup its investment,''
Mechanic said. ``A film that used to be $15 million is now pushed
up to $50 million, but the return is the same as if you'd made it
for $15 million. It means you're only going to lose money.''
</P>
<P>
   Some filmmakers and studio executives said they believed one
reason the coming season looked to be strong was that in order to
get top-name actors and directors to work for less than their
normal fees, producers were pushed toward the kind of projects that
such artists would find appealing rather than those projects that
the studios' marketing departments might find appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that will attract people to do it for less
money is something that's more interesting in terms of material,''
said Mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor that is driving the studios toward finding new
voices and richer films is the perception that the audience is
revolting against the familiar and the formulaic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something happening out there,'' Mechanic said.
``People have just rejected seeing the same thing time in and time
out. It's a rejection of the mainstream, in a way, of the same old
way of telling stories. I mean, they're booing trailers out there
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The full impact of having fewer films in the pipeline won't be
felt until around the middle of next year, executives say. Projects
that might have been made in the past will hit a brick wall, unless
their makers can come up with a way to do it cheaper. ``I think
we'll find that the holes in the sieve are getting smaller,'' said
Dick Cook, president of the Walt Disney Motion Picture Group.
</P>
<P>
   All of the filmmakers interviewed said they had felt the
economic crunch at the studios in one fashion or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you make a film that's off the beaten path, there's an
enormous amount of pressure to make it for a price that makes sense
to the studio,'' said Sydney Pollack, whose romantic drama ``Random
Hearts'' opens next month with Harrison Ford and Kristin Scott
Thomas. ``It costs so much money to market a film today, the
advertising costs and the marketing costs are often times more than
the cost of the negative. That would have been heresy 20 years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Stone, whose gritty football drama, ``Any Given Sunday,''
will open on Christmas Day, has noticed the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an eternal battle that goes back to the beginning of the
movie business, but certainly it's getting tougher,'' Stone said.
``I liken our jobs, that of the film's director and its marketing
director, to co-directors these days. They both spend sometimes the
same amount of money. The marketing director has enormous power
here.''
</P>
<P>
   For some of the directors, the change has been not so much in
the drive to save money as in the growing sense that a corporate
mind set is taking over the studios. All of the major Hollywood
studios are now owned by larger conglomerates, for which the movie
business is just one segment of a multi-faceted business empire,
and the recent appointment of several top executives who were seen
as more from the corporate side than the creative side has also
increased some filmmakers' wariness.
</P>
<P>
   Lasse Hallstrom, whose adaptation of John Irving's novel ``Cider
House Rules'' is due for release on Dec. 10, said he had given up
trying to understand. ``I am not as well educated as I ought to be
about all of the financial side of the movie business,'' he said.
``It's still a mystery to me, what happens behind those closed
doors. You're always trying to find someone who has the
responsibility to make a decision, but it is sometimes impossible.
All these mysterious reasons, and you never get to the truth of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who have been at it longest feel the corporate creep more
strongly. ``The big change for me as a filmmaker, making films
since 1961, is that I used to be able to get an answer on stories I
wanted to tell as a filmmaker very quickly,'' said Norman Jewison,
whose film about the incarceration and eventual exoneration of the
boxer Ruben Carter, ``The Hurricane,'' is set for an Oscar-aimed
limited release on Dec. 29. ``Over the last 10 years it's become
more and more of a corporate decision. You get the feeling that
some of these people think that they are making a product. Good
films have never been a product. They are individual statements of
their makers, pieces of a very, very fragile vision. I have never
felt there was any equation between money and art.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the studio executives just shrug off these kind of
complaints. ``Movies have always been a business,'' one said. ``We
have all decided to go into a very expensive art form; we didn't go
into finger-painting or poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   The puzzle is this: There were fears that when studios responded
to this _ and to increased pressure from higher-ups in the
corporations that own all of the studios _ there would be a rush to
the mainstream, seasons of little more than sequels, formulaic
comedies, teen-age sex romps and remakes of every television show
ever made. How then to explain this coming season?
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly looks like it's going to be a good final quarter,
maybe even a great one,'' said one producer and former studio boss.
``And it's coming on the heels of a very lucrative summer, when
there were successful movies all over the place, in almost every
genre. But people still feel uneasy because, no matter what they
tell you, they really don't know what's coming next.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
