<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3572 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-NEWSEASON-BURNS-$A     09-07 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWSEASON-BURNS-$ADV12-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELLING THE STORY OF THE WORLD'S GREATEST CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 12)  
(mk) 
 By CHARLES STRUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A word to the National Endowment for the Humanities,
corporate underwriters like Chase, the Corporation for Public
Broadcasting and viewers like you: Ric Burns is running out of
space.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he's complaining. It's just that as his production
company, Steeplechase Films, grows into a purveyor of ever-larger
documentary sagas _ from an hour to three hours to 10 hours and
more _ the need for Lebensraum increases. But public television
budgets and the Upper West Side of Manhattan being what they are,
Steeplechase now operates out of two small suites in two separate
buildings a block apart, off 72nd Street and Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something to be said for this cordon sanitaire,''
Burns said, referring to the production team in one building, the
editing team in another and the artistic negotiations that can
create occasional friction. Especially now, in the frenzied final
weeks of assembling Burns' most ambitious solo work to date, ``New
York,'' an admiring portrait of the city from Henry Hudson's
arrival, in 1609, to the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   More than five years in the making, ``New York'' is 12 hours in
six equal parts, or as Burns puts it, the story of Prometheus
retold from era to era. The first five parts will be broadcast in
November (Sunday through Thursday, Nov. 14-18, 9 p.m.). A sixth
episode, scheduled for the spring, will focus on the last 60 years
of the century.
</P>
<P>
   When Burns' co-writer, James Sanders, an architect and
historian, and his co-producer, Lisa Ades, sat down at the start of
the decade to map their plans, it quickly became clear that New
York was indeed Promethean. It had also proved to be a city
perpetually engaged in creative destruction _ the process of
tearing down the old and rebuilding, in many cases, bigger and
better.
</P>
<P>
   It was the ultimate harbor, the ultimate trading post, the
ultimate real estate deal and, most important, a crucible of
democracy and capitalism like no other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the simple core of the story, stealing fire from the
Gods,'' Burns said. ``This city in the New World, from the very
beginning, felt that there was no enterprise too lofty, too
difficult for human beings not to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 19th century, in a particularly intense way,'' he said,
``the powers that were previously thought to be _ metaphorically
anyway _ divine came within the grasp of human beings, transforming
the physical, political, social and cultural shape of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds like the kitchen sink approach, it is. It's also
the quintessential Burns approach. Why compose a short story when
you can film ``Middlemarch''?
</P>
<P>
   The son of an anthropologist, Burns, 44, is a polymath with a
narrative mission, at 24 frames per second. His conversation
bristles with literary references and allusions, as befits a former
doctoral student at Columbia University. In his dissertation, he
said, he intended to trace the nature of revolutionary ideas in the
19th century and, at the same time, ``bring all the qualities of
modern literature into focus _ Carlyle, Flaubert, Dickens, Rimbaud
_ in explaining the transformation of cultural, political and
social authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he fell in step with his older brother, Ken, and helped
to produce the 11-hour 1990 PBS series ``The Civil War.'' That was
the end of the dissertation, but the start of even more research
that led him to documentaries like ``Coney Island'' (the name
Steeplechase Films is derived from Coney's famous amusement park)
and ``The Donner Party.'' Even now, he has begun work on a
three-hour film about Eugene O'Neill, collaborating with O'Neill's
biographers Barbara Gelb and her husband, Arthur, a former managing
editor of The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   On his decision to switch to film, Burns seems to harbor few
doubts: ``I could have spent 50 years as an academic writing four
books for an audience of 3,000 or a life spent telling stories for
a larger audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepping through the office's dormlike clutter, Ms. Ades, whose
next project is the history of the Miss America Pageant, remarked,
``We're all hunter-gatherers.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiding out at the New-York Historical Society, Ms. Ades
(pronounced AD-us) pored over uncounted thousands of prints and
photographs. ``What keeps me awake at night is thinking that I
might have missed one.''
</P>
<P>
   For fans of Burns brothers documentaries, the format will be
familiar: passionately written but with low-key narration.
Interspersed with contemporary video of New York are close-ups and
pans of etchings, paintings and historical maps as well as early
photographic stills; original musical themes repeated in rhythms
and keys both joyful and mournful; and the voices of actors and
writers breathing life into the words of those who watched or
commented on history as it was being made.
</P>
<P>
   There are also ``witnesses,'' contemporary experts whose
comments amount to a Greek chorus on the theme. They include Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., Martin Scorsese, Ada Louise
Huxtable, E.L. Doctorow and Fran Lebowitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Stern compared the city to the greatest fireworks you ever
saw,'' Burns said, referring to the architect Robert A.M. Stern.
``Out of each cascade comes yet another, higher, higher and louder
still. Narratively, this aspect of the city's history is a gift. At
each stage along the way it seems to be saying, `You ain't seen
nothin' yet.' And you haven't.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider this bit of synthesis. ``When New York was founded at
the dawn of the modern age,'' says the narrator, David Ogden
Stiers, ``London and Paris were already 1,500 years old; Rome and
Beijing, 2000; Jerusalem, 4,000. And yet somehow, in the centuries
to come, the tiny colony on the edge of the world would rise to
become the greatest city on earth _ the undisputed cultural and
economic capital of the world _ and the supreme laboratory of
modern life.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   What follows is stunning, though not because New York turns out
to be unique in all the ways he and others say it is. It's that the
New York story, from raunchy Dutch trading post to luminous global
icon, seems to be all of a piece these last 350 years. The more it
changes _ and New York is forever changing _ the more it stays the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York City was founded by the Dutch,'' says Brendan Gill,
the New Yorker writer and preservationist who died in December
1997. ``The Dutch didn't give a damn about anything except making
money.''
</P>
<P>
   New York _ crowded, dirty, noisy, disorganized and often violent
_ was home to more people of more different ethnic and religious
backgrounds than anywhere else. Yet its blend of frontier democracy
and greed acted as a growth hormone of frightening power. It still
does.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding on Gill's terse observation, John Steele Gordon, a
historian who has written the ``Business in America'' column in
American Heritage magazine for the last 10 years, said: ``New York
was founded for no other reason than to make a buck. The Puritans
came to New England to worship God as they saw fit. The Catholics
came to Maryland, the Quakers to Pennsylvania. The Dutch came to
Manhattan to get beaver skins.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so devoted were they to making a profit,'' Gordon said,
``that they didn't get around to even building a church for 17
years. And ever since, you know, however big the city has gotten,
somewhere deep in its soul it is always New Amsterdam. Where modern
capitalism was invented.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything right down to the Manhattan street grid, adopted in
1811, seems in retrospect to have been designed uncannily to propel
the city into yet another era of growth, prosperity and power.
</P>
<P>
   And then, just 200 years after the city's founding, DeWitt
Clinton proposed what Stiers, the narrator, describes as a
``363-mile-long ditch that if completed would transform forever New
York's relation to the entire American continent'': the Erie Canal.
</P>
<P>
   When it was completed in 1825, ``it made New York the only
American city that connected Europe on one side with the heartland
of the continent on the other,'' Stern, the architect, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that has been New York's strength ever since,'' he
continued. ``It still is the major port of entry and transfer point
for people flying from Europe to the rest of the country. You see
New York, and then you see America.''
</P>
<P>
   What you really see, Burns said, is something he recalled from
Ezra Pound, writing about the city in 1913. He recited it from
memory:
</P>
<P>
   ``And is New York the most beautiful city in the world? It is
not far from it. No urban nights are like the nights there. I have
looked down across the city from high windows. It is then that the
great buildings lose reality and take on magical powers. ...
Squares and squares of flame set and cut into the ether. Here is
our poetry, for we have pulled down the stars to our will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
