   NJ-WHITMAN-SENATE (Trenton, N.J.) _ Summary from wires: New
Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman, in a blow to Republican prospects in
2000, has decided not to run for the Senate after months of
preparation for the campaign. Republican officials, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said earlier Tuesday that Whitman's
political team was contacting GOP officials throughout the country
to notify them of her surprise decision. Republican sources said
Whitman's surprise decision was based in part on the enormous
fund-raising demands of a Senate race. One candidate seeking the
Democratic nomination is former Goldman Sachs chairman Jon Corzine,
who can tap into a personal wealth in the hundreds of millions of
dollars. By Paul Zielbauer.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-HEALTH (Los Angeles) _ Vice President Al Gore lays out his
vision of a health policy for the nation today, a combination of
new steps to guarantee access to affordable health insurance for
all children, even as he acknowledges that the number of Americans
without coverage had increased steadily since he and President
Clinton took office. By Robert Pear. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   CISNEROS-PLEA (Washington) _ The case against Henry Cisneros, a
former Clinton Cabinet officer ended in a virtual collapse as he
pleaded guilty to a simple misdemeanor on the day he was to go on
trial on 18 felony counts involving statements he once made as to
how much money he paid a former mistress. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-UNREST (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ As international pressure
mounted on Indonesia on Tuesday to halt a continuing surge of
violence in East Timor, analysts here were stumped by two
fundamental questions: who is orchestrating the carnage and why? It
has become clear that irregular militias backed by the Indonesian
military are carrying out a planned and organized campaign of
terror that involves widespread killings, arson and the forced
evacuation of tens of thousands from the remote territory of
800,000 people. What is not clear is what the campaign is meant to
achieve and what degree of control the government in Jakarta has
over the people who are carrying it out. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
