<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deal may have big impact on wireless networkingBy Michael E.
Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Wireless Networks has landed what could be a
breakthrough deal in which British Telecom next year will sell the
Norcross, Ga. company's systems for connecting devices in houses
and offices.
</P>
<P>
   Sales from the deal, culminating a year-long joint development
effort, are expected to reap more than $50 million in the United
Kingdom, according to BT. There is no guarantee that those
projections will be met, but reaching them would dramatically
recast Home Wireless, far outstripping revenues thus far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is exceedingly important to Home Wireless
Networks,'' said John Taylor, co-founder, president and CEO. ``In
fact, in our market space, it is the biggest deal ever announced.''
</P>
<P>
   Home Wireless makes systems that provide a wireless way for a
user to connect many of the gadgets in either a home or office _
linking phones, faxes, printers and computers. The systems permit
use of several phones or computers via the same outside line. They
let a user tie together computers on a network. And a user would
not need to rewire any machine that is moved.
</P>
<P>
   The company's small system, which can connect three outside
lines and eight ``devices,'' retails for less than $1,000. A system
that can handle five outside lines and 16 home devices costs about
$2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Home Wireless has pegged its hopes to a growing demand for
wireless communications, as well as increasing popularity of
phones, computers and the Internet. Adding to the wave is the
growth of telecommuting and small businesses that want the same
technology options as large companies _ but can't afford the same
number of phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   In the United Kingdom, BT expects more than 5 million consumers
to buy such systems in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Home Wireless is unable to simply sell its current product line
through British Telecom, since the technology standards for
wireless transmission are different from that in United States.
Joint development produced a system for the British market.
</P>
<P>
   Home Wireless now sells its systems in the United States through
four distributors, including Alltel and GT, as well as through the
Internet. Results so far are promising, but not spectacular, Taylor
said. ``It is doing okay, but nothing stellar _ nothing compared to
the BT deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The BT agreement gives the company, still privately traded, a
headstart on the eventual surge of wireless communications, Taylor
said. ``You basically have the world. There are not many start-ups
who can do this out of the gate.''
</P>
<P>
   Home Wireless Networks was jump-started in 1996 with a large
investment from Lucent Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Company backers include Grotech Capital Group, Alliance
Technology Ventures and Klaus Krone of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The company has burgeoned from Taylor and two partners to about
130 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
