<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3582 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-LICE08-COX     09-07 1404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LICE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Outbreaks, possible resistant strains have public health
officials scratching their heads
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Decatur, Ga., mother Randy Foster had done all the
typical things to get rid of the head lice in her daughter's hair.
She bought the chemical cream rinses, vacuumed the carpets, bagged
the toys and picked out the eggs, known as nits, with a metal comb.
</P>
<P>
   None of it worked. After more than six weeks of frustration,
Foster tried a decades-old treatment _ Vaseline, slathered on the
scalp _ to smother the lice. It worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody warned me about how hard it was going to be to get rid
of them,'' Foster said. ``No one told us how this was going to turn
our lives upside down.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster said she believes her daughter, Chelsea, may have been
infested with lice that had developed resistance to typical
chemical treatments _ a trend that may afflict scores of families
and schools, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Although scientists are unable to say how widespread the problem
of ``super lice'' may be in the United States, other countries have
documented a rise in resistant lice. And researchers at the Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta acknowledge that they
are seeing significant anecdotal evidence of tougher bugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a lot of frustrated parents, lots of frustrated
physicians and lots of frustrated school nurses,'' said Sue
Partridge, spokeswoman for the CDC's Division of Parasitic
Diseases. Lice outbreaks _ whether due to ``super lice'' or just
widespread, inconsistent follow-up care _ are now ``a major concern
for school nurses,'' Partridge said.
</P>
<P>
   With the first weeks of school behind them, teachers and public
health workers are bracing for a bumper crop of head lice this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always seen some cases,'' said Tammy Hamilton,
spokeswoman for the Cobb County Board of Health. ``But in the past
few years, we've noticed a dramatic increase.''
</P>
<P>
   Many metro Atlanta schools are trying to control the insects
with new no-nit policies, which require students to leave school
immediately if a nit, or lice egg, is found. And public health
workers are stepping up prevention efforts, urging parents to check
their children's scalps every Friday night and suggesting that some
schools bag hats or coats as students walk into the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta public schools, Parent Teacher Association meetings
are planned to discuss strategies to eliminate lice, said Jayketa
Singleton, a health services clinical adviser to the district. In
Cobb County, the health department has a designated nurse who
travels the district to educate school nurses and parents about
lice.
</P>
<P>
   And at Westchester Elementary School in Decatur, Principal
Cheryl Kuebler lets parents borrow nit combs, including the
Robicomb, a electric tool that kills lice with a satisfying zap.
Kuebler, fondly known to faculty and students as the Lice Lady, is
more prepared than most. A few years ago, her school struggled with
a near epidemic of lice and took several approaches to end the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot, and I became very proactive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Kuebler recommends such family activities like Friday night
lice checks, writes articles about lice for the school newsletter
and personally does class checks _ bringing youngsters to the
classroom windows and gingerly poking around their hair with a
pencil. ``I'm pretty good at finding the things at this point,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is the school has not seen any more widespread
outbreaks _ ``knock on wood,'' she said. But many metro Atlanta
schools _ and parents _ will not be so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, a public relations manager for the accounting firm KPMG,
never dreamed that an itty-bitty bug could be so persistent. Foster
doused Chelsea's hair in over-the-counter lice products. They
didn't work. She went through Chelsea's hair with a metal comb,
looking for nits, or lice eggs. When that didn't work, she picked
out nits strand-by-strand and cut them out.
</P>
<P>
   She cleaned the house, the toys, the clothes and the linens _
repeatedly. And after researching books and Web sites, she finally
slathered Chelsea's hair in Vaseline, videotaped the special moment
for posterity, and capped her hair overnight. That finally killed
the bugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really long and ugly and exhausting,'' said Foster, who
said she kept Chelsea, then 3 years old, still for the daily
inspections through stacks of videos and ``lots of bribes'' for six
weeks. ``I put my poor kid through hell. She was a real trooper.''
</P>
<P>
   Singleton said Foster's story is not uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   When talking to PTA groups last year about how to combat lice,
she said she heard parents repeatedly vent their frustration over
fighting lice.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone, regardless of economic status, can get lice. Even
Cleopatra owned a nit comb.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not children with dirty hair,'' Thompson said about
the cases she's seen. ``These are children well cared for, with
clean hair.''
</P>
<P>
   But girls tend to have higher numbers of lice and nits, because
they often have longer hair and they tend to do more head-to-head
activities that promote the spread of the insects, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   And lice tend to attack whites, Asians and Hispanics more than
African-American boys and girls, experts say. The reason: The
texture of African-American hair makes it difficult for nits to
attach. And often, boys and girls have hair styles that are either
extremely short or tightly braided, both factors that discourage an
infestation.
</P>
<P>
   When a lice outbreak occurs, things often degenerate into a
blame game, which can complicate efforts to solve the problem.
Parents blame the schools for not being aggressive enough in
stopping infestations by keeping common areas of schools free of
lice and sending infested students home. Schools blame parents for
inconsistent follow-up treatment for lice. Public health workers
say once a child has lice, the parents must be diligent about
shampooing, nit-picking, cleaning and vacuuming their homes for at
least a month to make sure all bugs are dead.
</P>
<P>
   A second complication is that lice treatment can be expensive.
Americans spend about $100 million a year on cream rinses and
shampoos that contain delousing agents, according to the National
Pediculosis Association. And Nix, the No. 1 lice treatment, has
raked in more than $40 million each year since 1997, when annual
sales of the over-the-counter product doubled, according to its
distributer, Warner Lambert. A family can easily rack up a $60 to
$70 bill to treat a single lice infestation. Chemical cream rinses,
which need to be used twice within one week, cost between $10 and
$20 a pop per person. And fine-toothed nit combs cost between $10
and $15.
</P>
<P>
   But the greatest hurdle to combating lice in the past decade has
been that more parents are finding that typical treatments _ such
as permethrin, the active ingredient in Nix _ don't seem to be
working anymore.
</P>
<P>
   A survey taken at the 1998 annual meeting of the National
Association of School Nurses found, for instance, that more than 80
percent of the respondents reported an increase in the failure of
chemical treatments to stop lice outbreaks in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   And a recent unpublished Harvard University study found more
than 200 lice, harvested from the heads of 57 children, survived in
petri dishes treated with permethrin. In contrast, the researchers
showed that 67 lice from children in the Philippines, who use
chemical treatments far less frequently, quickly died after
exposure to permethrin, except one, which apparently escaped. The
CDC has not seen definitive evidence of ``super lice'' in the
United States, although they have been identified in other nations.
But the experts acknowledge lice studies are rare, since the bugs
are neither glamorous nor dangerous and only live on humans, making
laboratory studies of lice virtually impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Parents and school nurses say they don't need scientists to
confirm what they see every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are definitely seeing something new,'' said Thompson of
Fountain Elementary, who said about 20 percent of her student body
contracted lice last year. ``And it's causing real nightmares for
everyone involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
