<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3591 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-HEALTH08-COX     09-07 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-HEALTH08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE PROPOSES BROAD EXPANSION OF HEALTH COVERAGE
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore vowed Tuesday to provide
health care coverage to about 11 million uninsured children by 2005
as a first step toward making affordable coverage available to all
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me be crystal clear on this point: if you elect me
president, I will ensure that by the year 2005, every single child
in our country has full access to fully affordable health care
coverage,'' he told a room of health care workers at Children's
Hospital, one of America's major pediatric centers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's promise seemed to be a response to weeks of criticism by
former Sen. Bill Bradley that the Clinton-Gore administration has
not done enough for children in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore's timing, on the eve of Bradley's official announcement
of his candidacy for the Democratic presidential nomination,
appeared to be a reaction to recent public opinion polls suggesting
that interest in Bradley's campaign is growing rather than fading.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore did not mention Bradley by name, the vice
president contrasted his health care proposal to the universal
coverage the former senator is expected to embrace in the coming
weeks. ``Some ... will tell you that the only acceptable answer is
a one-size-fits-all solution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid the kind of controversy that the ill-fated Clinton
health care reforms generated in 1994, Gore cautioned that he would
pursue a wide-ranging package of reforms ``carefully, realistically
and step by step.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all learned that we cannot overhaul the system in one
fell swoop,'' the vice president said. Still, he added, ``we cannot
rest until every single American has affordable health care.''
</P>
<P>
   The first step in that direction, he said, would involve the
expansion of the Children's Health Insurance Program, enacted in
1997 to provide federal funds to the states to pay for health care
coverage to children in working families.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the CHIP program allows coverage of children in
families that earn up to 200 percent of the federal poverty level.
But under Gore's proposal, the eligibility cap would be raised to
250 percent, or about $41,000.
</P>
<P>
   Some states, such as California, already have raised the cap to
250 percent. Some states, such as Texas, have tried to lower the
cap below 200 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the CHIP program, the Children's Health Fund, an
advocacy group, estimates that some 11 million children still have
no health insurance. And Gore, promising to spur the states into
greater efforts, took a dig at Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the
current front-runner for the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some states _ Texas springs to mind _ one quarter of all
children are still out in the cold,'' he said. ``That is
unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore would also allow families who currently do not qualify for
CHIP and do not have access to health coverage through their jobs
to buy into the program, so that their children can have access to
coverage regardless of their parents' income.
</P>
<P>
   Gore never addressed the issue of cost, other than to say that
any public expenses should be ``fiscally responsible.'' His
spokesman, Chris Lehane, said the cost would be addressed later
``in the context of a balanced budget'' and not in terms of a tax
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Although campaign officials had billed the speech as a major
policy address, many of the reforms cited by Gore on Tuesday had
already been proposed:
</P>
<P>
   _ An ``enforceable'' patients's bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   _ Allowing people with disabilities to keep Medicare or Medicaid
when they returned to the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   _ Encourage small businesses to band together to negotiate rates
for their workers' coverage by providing a 25 percent tax credit to
the firms.
</P>
<P>
   _ Improving privacy safeguards for patients.
</P>
<P>
   _ Encourage insurers to cover mental illness as they do other
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Gore drew the most applause when he criticized health
maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am certainly not satisfied when life or death medical
decisions are made by HMO bureaucrats at the other end of a
telephone line,'' he said. ``They don't have a licence to practice
medicine, and they don't have a right to play God.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
