<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3597 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-FSU-WEINKE-COX     09-07 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FSU-WEINKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FSU's Weinke leaves injury behind and faces season openerBy Tony
Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Ten months ago, Chris Weinke lay in a
hospital bed wondering if his football career might be over.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida State quarterback ended up in that bed courtesy of a
jarring, blindside hit from Virginia's Patrick Kearney. As Weinke
fell to the ground, his head hit the leg of a Florida State
lineman, and he fractured a vertebra in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   If the break had occurred a few inches in another direction,
Weinke could have been paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Four days later, Weinke had neck surgery to fuse two vertebrae
to provide stability. Afterward, a nurse talked to Betty Weinke, a
very anxious mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please,'' the nurse said. ``Don't ever let your son play
football again.''
</P>
<P>
   As a mother, that was Betty's wish. But she knew better. Her son
had come too far to see his dreams end that way.
</P>
<P>
   So it's fair to say Betty Weinke will be the most nervous person
among the 80,000-plus who will pack Doak Campbell Stadium on
Saturday night when No. 1 Florida State plays No. 10 Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Weinke has recovered from the November surgery, and on
July 26, doctors pronounced him fit to play. He has been tested in
a game, taking several good hits in Florida State's 41-7 win over
Louisiana Tech in its opener Aug. 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel fine,'' said Weinke, the 27-year-old junior who
returned to college football in 1997 after five years in
professional baseball. ``It was good to take a few shots just to
show people that I could survive it and play. I think I'm ready to
put this behind me and go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving on hasn't been easy for Weinke, because of the
seriousness of the injury, sustained in Florida State's 10th game.
After the surgery, he was in the hospital bed for six weeks unable
to move. The 6-foot-5 Weinke had weighed 240 pounds, but he lost 30
pounds. He had to have follow-up surgery in January to repair a
spinal fluid leak near the point where the vertebrae were fused; a
titanium clamp is still there.
</P>
<P>
   By March, Weinke could throw without pain, but he saw limited
action in spring practice and had no contact. This summer, he
remained in Tallahassee and worked with the Seminoles' receivers.
Even though doctors gave the OK, Florida State coaches would not
let him get hit in preseason practice. As a result, Weinke was
nagged by one question: ``How are you going to act when you get hit
for the first time?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard it a million different ways, but it was always the
same thing,'' Weinke said. ``It was like nobody wondered if I could
really throw the ball or not. They just wondered if I could take a
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is yes. Weinke completed 20 of 32 passes for 242
yards and two touchdowns against Louisiana Tech. Early in the
second quarter, he broke the ACC record held by Matt Blundin of
Virginia for consecutive attempts without an interception, 231.
Weinke extended the record to 237 before getting intercepted at the
end of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little nervous at first, but after that, I settled
down, and it felt pretty good,'' Weinke said.
</P>
<P>
   As painful as neck surgery was, it was not as bad as watching
Florida State lose the national championship game to Tennessee in
the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   This Seminoles team has all the weapons it needs to win a
national championship, as long as Weinke stays on the field. That's
why he worked so hard in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is certainly the fastest and most talented team we've had
since I've been here,'' said Weinke, who threw for 2,487 yards and
19 touchdowns last season. ``I really wanted to be their
quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   He will be Saturday, in his biggest test since the injury. And
Betty Weinke will be there for every heart-pounding play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing her,'' Weinke said, ``she'll have her eyes closed the
entire game.'' CHRIS WEINKE BIO BOX
</P>
<P>
   Birthdate: July 31, 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: St. Paul, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   Class: Junior.
</P>
<P>
   Major: Sports management.
</P>
<P>
   His past: He signed with FSU from high school and spent four
days in August 1990 on the Florida State campus before signing a
professional baseball contract with the Toronto Blue Jays, who had
made him a second-round draft pick. He spent six years in the Blue
Jays organization before going to Florida State in the spring of
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
