<HEADER>
A3602 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-RAC-SARATOGA-HNS &LR;      09-07 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SARATOGA POSTS RECORD YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM WILKIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ The starting gate slammed shut for the
season at Saratoga Race Course Monday afternoon, signifying the end
to another glorious summer.
</P>
<P>
   And what a summer it was.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive season, the New York Racing
Association had a record-setting six weeks with the thoroughbreds
at the ancient and tradition-laden Spa.
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga exceeded 900,000 in on-track attendance for the first
time in the 131 years racing has been held here.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 920,218 fans poured into the Spa gates this year, an
average of 25,562 per day and a 3.7 percent increase from last
year. Also, on-track handle rose 5.4 percent, to $111,969,548.
Daily on-track handle surpassed $3 million, registering in at
$3,110,265.
</P>
<P>
   With incoming simulcasts, the daily average handle reached
$14,869,743, 17 percent more than the 1998 figure of $12,697,170.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bill Nader, director of broadcasting communications
and promotions for NYRA, there were 865 sites that carried the
Saratoga signal. He said there were 43 states that simulcast the
Spa races, and they also were available in Canada, Mexico and the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Nader said, there were 810 outlets that had Spa
races.
</P>
<P>
   On the track, Jerry Bailey established himself as the Spa jockey
of the '90s and Bill Mott did the same as the top trainer of the
decade. They won the titles of leading rider and leading trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Saratoga set records in total on-track attendance
(887,752) and one-day attendance (61,190). Both of those marks were
squashed. A crowd of 66,194 was announced on Aug. 15, the day the
track gave away Saratoga steins for a single admission.
</P>
<P>
   Another record that fell was the single-day attendance of a
non-giveaway day. That came on Travers Day, when 51,371 came to see
Lemon Drop Kid win the Midsummer Derby. That surpassed the old
record of 50,359, set on Travers Day in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very happy with what we did up here this year,'' said
Terry Meyocks, NYRA's president and chief operating officer. ```We
are ecstatic that we beat our numbers from last year, but now we
have to try and beat these numbers next year. We are pleased, there
is no question about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The dates for next year's Spa meet have already been announced.
It will remain at 36 days and start on July 26 and, again, end on
Labor Day (Sept. 4).
</P>
<P>
   Meyocks said he does not expect the meet to grow in duration
anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to say never but we have always said, that
right now, everyone feels that 36 days is a perfect number. I think
it would be unfair to the people of Saratoga and our horsemen.
People up here (who rent their homes) are away for six weeks and
our horsemen are away from home that long. I think if you made the
meet longer, you would lose some of the mystique that is Saratoga.
If you go longer than that, you lose some of that.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the third season Saratoga Race Course had a 36-day
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey won his fifth riding title in the last six years. Mott
has won four training titles this decade and shared the trophy two
other times.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, 42, dominated the rest of the jockey colony right from
the start of the meet and ended with 47 winners in 169 starts.
Bailey had a chance to tie or pass his all-time record of 48
winners, set in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   However, two of his mounts were scratched. He finished fourth
aboard 8-5 favorite My Jan in the first race and was second with
even-money choice Tree House in the second. He got his only winner
in the sixth race, when he guided 4-1 Amelia's Song to victory.
Ironically, that victory clinched the training title for Mott. He
and D. Wayne Lukas entered the final day tied with 14 winners. Mott
also trained the winner of the eighth race, Dream For A Moment, to
end the season with 16 winners.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas did not have any horses entered on Monday's card. He left
town Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good meet,'' Bailey said while sitting outside the
jockeys' room after the third race Monday afternoon. ``I was able
to stay in one piece, make a few dollars and come out of here with
a smile on my face.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey was never seriously threatened in this race. The
competition was for second place.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Prado, riding his first full Spa meet, had 36 winners, one
more than Jorge Chavez. Shane Sellers was fourth with 31 trips to
the winner's circle, and John Velazquez, last year's champion with
31 winners, had to settle for fifth place with 28 winners, the same
number Pat Day had.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey won the Whitney aboard Victory Gallop, took the Alabama
with Silverbulletday and the Go For Wand with Banshee Breeze.
Bailey took a back seat to no one on the grass, winning 18 of the
60 races that he was on the turf for an average of 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good just to survive the meet,'' Bailey said. ``Right
now I am very tired, but it's a good kind of tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Mott was happy with his meet as well. He did not have any major
stakes wins _ his grass star Yagli was upset in the Sword Dancer _
but he was the most consistent trainer. He was second in the
Travers with Vision and Verse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always nice to win a meet like this,'' Mott said. ``In
this game, winning is the name of the game. When you prove you can
win, then you are going to get people that send you horses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
