<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3605 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-07 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAME OLD, SAME OLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the refreshing summer pause behind us,
Congress and President Clinton are back on the job, still accusing
each other of lying shamelessly about practically everything and
arguing bitterly about tax cuts, spending priorities and other
tiresome issues.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven help us. It will be a long 14 months until voters can
register their impatience with this intractable mess in the 2000
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Unrealistic hopes of fresh cooperation to build a bipartisan
record of achievement promptly evaporated with the anger that
erupted again over what happened in 1993 during a 51-day standoff
between law enforcement officials and the Branch Davidians near
Waco, Texas. The siege ended with the burning of the cult compound
and the death of some 80 people trapped inside.
</P>
<P>
   This recycled crisis has familiar earmarks. The FBI suddenly
discovered proof that it had done something bad that it had
consistently denied doing.
</P>
<P>
   During the Clinton era long-missing, politically charged
documents have had a weird way of turning up belatedly. Conspiracy
theories abound. And it all turns out to be much ado about nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Hillary Clinton's law firm billing records,
inexplicably found inside the White House two years after being
subpoenaed by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr? Despite a
congressional probe and Republican cries of obstruction of justice,
the mystery of their disappearance and recovery has never been
solved.
</P>
<P>
   Yet after much huffing and puffing, Starr didn't indict the
first lady for illegal shenanigans and is not expected to do so.
Former Sens. Alfonse D'Amato of New York and Lauch Faircloth of
North Carolina, the most aggressive GOP pursuers of Whitewater
rumors, ridiculed Mrs. Clinton. Faircloth once joked sarcastically,
``The butler did it!'' Both were defeated for reelection last year.
</P>
<P>
   Once again we have a similar phenomenon with documents, this one
involving suspected hanky-panky by the FBI, supposedly condoned by
the Justice Department. What happened is that the FBI _ after six
years of denials _ finally produced two videotapes proving that its
agents had launched potentially flammable tear gas canisters at an
underground bunker 50 yards from the cult's wooden compound.
</P>
<P>
   This time there is no way to drag in Bill or Hillary Clinton. So
Attorney General Janet Reno gets the dubious honor of being the
designated fall guy. Senate Judiciary Committee chairman Orrin
Hatch of Utah, a Republican presidential candidate, and Texas GOP
Sen. Phil Gramm rushed to judgment last weekend, calling for Reno's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said the FBI may have sent a memo about the canisters to
someone in the Justice Department, and if it hadn't reached Reno,
that would indicate the department was ``poorly run.'' Ergo, it was
her fault she hadn't caught on right away that the FBI was lying,
not the FBI's fault for lying in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm complained that Reno ``either lied or allowed herself to
be lied to'' about the incident. The FBI is accountable to the
Justice Department, but, encouraged by Congress, it has long
enjoyed a formidable reputation for independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's always the last person to know,'' Gramm scoffed,
forgetting that when President Ronald Reagan was the last to know
about an illegal war in Nicaragua run from the White House
basement, a similar information lapse was considered an asset.
</P>
<P>
   Reno had sworn to Congress that no incendiary device had been
used. She says she relied on what the FBI told her.
</P>
<P>
   Neither senator called for the resignation of FBI Director Louis
Freeh, who is in direct charge of the lying agency but who has won
over the congressional GOP leadership by pandering to their efforts
to bring down the Clinton administration. Freeh was not FBI
director at the time of Waco. The job was then held by William
Sessions, father of Rep. Pete Sessions, R-Texas. The congressman
has already won the 1999 grand prize for self-serving prejudice by
calling immediately for Reno's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, this is a typical partisan firestorm more
indicative of overheated politics than any potential expose of
dangerous wrong-doing. A Republican-controlled House probe several
years ago concluded that the Branch Davidians set the fire in a
final, convulsive act of mass suicide and murder. There is plenty
of evidence to support that finding.
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill, refusing
to advocate new House hearings, has suggested that an independent
commission look into the case again, which seems okay with
congressional Democrats. Fortunately, Hyde is displaying the common
sense for which he was noted before he was tarnished by the
feverish fanaticism that swept the House during Clinton's
impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The smell of another Clinton administration witch hunt, however,
is in the congressional air. Rep. Dan Burton, GOP chairman of a
House committee with oversight duties, has already issued subpoenas
preparatory to holding hearings. Burton is an embarrassment to his
party and his country, but he is free to rant and rave at will.
</P>
<P>
   He has called Clinton a ``scumbag'' and threatened to hold Reno
in contempt of Congress for failing to appoint an independent
counsel to look into alleged Democratic fund-raising abuses similar
to those of which he has been accused himself. When he released
transcripts of former Associate Attorney General Webster Hubbell's
prison conversations, Burton selectively edited out Hubbell remarks
suggesting that the first lady was innocent of the Whitewater
charges.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to imagine civility returning to the partisan
legislative wars in a wacko Waco atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The president is winning the public relations war over the size
of any projected tax cut, but the Republicans who control Congress
show little sign of accepting that reality, let alone negotiating a
compromise. So stalemate it probably is. There are worse outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties have always known they face two choices this fall.
Go for a record or go for the issues. A record of positive, joint
accomplishment would be good for the country. But issues that are
unresolved are good for candidates' campaigns next year.
</P>
<P>
   And campaigning comes before governing. Too bad, but that's the
order of things.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
