<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPUBLICANS TRY TO SHAKE FEAR THEY'D CUT EDUCATION AID
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress comes back to work _ and back to school _
Wednesday, with Republicans scrambling to convince the public that
they don't want tax cuts so much that they are willing to risk
cutting federal aid to public schools.
</P>
<P>
   GOP support for education is the theme of a two-day, five-state
tour by Rep. J.C. Watts, chairman of the House Republican
Conference, which began early Tuesday in Cincinnati and will
conclude in Allentown, Pa., on Wednesday afternoon. At each stop,
local GOP members of Congress join Watts for an event at a local
school.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., a former high school
teacher and coach, plans to do the same thing on Capitol Hill as he
leads a congressional delegation to a nearby public charter school
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert plans to publicize the tax bill's provisions for
tax-protected education savings accounts and to spotlight
``Straight A's'' legislation proposed by Sen. Paul Coverdell,
R-Ga., and Rep. Bill Goodling, R-Pa. The legislation would end the
system under which the federal government tells states how their
federal education aid must be spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to emphasize that Straight A's does not
subtract from any of the currently federally funded education
programs,'' said a fact sheet distributed by Coverdell. ``It simply
allows them to be put into a 'flex-fund' to be used by each state
as each sees fit.''
</P>
<P>
   When they left Washington in early August, the Republicans hoped
to stir up a public rebellion against Clinton's vow to kill their
$792 billion tax-cut bill when they send it to him later this
month.
</P>
<P>
   But as they return, they are instead defending themselves
against Clinton's repeated charges that the tax cuts are so deep
that the federal government wouldn't have enough revenues left for
education and other popular programs.
</P>
<P>
   In his latest attack, delivered Tuesday at a school in
Washington's Maryland suburbs, the president said: ``If their
budget passes with the tax cut, it will require us to reduce our
investment in education, in Head Start, early reading and other
programs by about 50 percent over the next 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year alone, the cuts could be nearly 20 percent, Clinton
said. Bruce Reed, director of Clinton's Domestic Policy Council,
suggested that Congress could avoid education cuts by reviving the
president's moribund proposal for an increase of 55 cents per pack
in the tobacco excise tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our budget we set it aside to offset federal health
costs,'' Reed said. ``But we'd like to see the Congress take a look
at this for any purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Myers, general counsel of the nonprofit Campaign for
Tobacco-Free Kids, reacted favorably. ``Substantial prices
increases in tobacco products are the quickest way to reduce
tobacco use among children, therefore we would strongly support an
effort to significantly raise the excise tax on tobacco products,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans shuddered at the notion of raising any kind of
taxes. ``It sounds like the president is he president is reverting
back to the old tax-and-spend days of Jimmy Carter and George
McGovern,'' said Hastert's press secretary, John Feehery.
</P>
<P>
   Individually, Republicans scoff at Clinton's charges. ``Saying
that government programs are threatened if we return a sliver of a
$3 trillion surplus to taxpayers is like saying that cooking is
threatened by Betty Crocker,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who
heads the tax-writing Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past month, those views have been drowned out by the
flood of attention to the views of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Watts wryly summed up the competition this way: ``The Democrats
have one master salesman with a megaphone. We have 222 vice
presidents for sales.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
