<SLUG> BC-WACO-RANGERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS AGENCY RECEIVES EXTENSION TO COMPLY WITH SUBPOENA IN WACO
PROBE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas Department of Public Safety has
received an informal extension until Friday to comply with a
congressional subpoena for records relating to the 1993 federal
agents' assault on the Branch Davidian compound in Waco.
</P>
<P>
   DPS spokeswoman Tela Mange said Texas Rangers sought an
extension to prepare a report and gather records pertaining to the
use of tear gas on the Branch Davidians prior to the April 19 fire
in which leader David Koresh and more than 80 followers died. The
fire ended a 51-day standoff with federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   The House Government Reform Committee subpoenaed the documents
following recent disclosures that FBI agents, contrary to what the
agency has been contending for the past six years, did indeed fire
pyrotechnic devices into the compound prior to the start of the
fire.
</P>
<P>
   The use of pyrotechnic devices is a key factor in a pending
wrongful death lawsuit filed by survivors against the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials have insisted that the military tear gas
lobbed at an underground bunker at the compound did not cause the
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Mange said the Rangers' report and tear gas records will be
forwarded to the House Committee on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Washington, committee spokesman Mark Corallo said
the panel is not likely to release the DPS records or report until
after the committee has conducted public hearings into the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   The Government Reform Committee has subpoenaed documents from
other agencies regarding their involvement in the incident.
</P>
<P>
   DPS also is awaiting instructions from a federal judge on where
to send the tons of evidence collected at the Davidians' former
home site.
</P>
<P>
   DPS has maintained physical custody of the evidence since 1993,
but the U.S. Justice Department has retained control of the
materials.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Walter Smith has ordered the evidence be
turned over to him. Mange said the judge has not decided though
whether the material should be held in Waco or in San Antonio,
where the chief clerk for the District Court is located.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
