<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY YIELDS RISE AS INVESTORS AWAIT INFORMATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury yields rose Tuesday as investors awaited an
inflation report scheduled for release on Friday and braced for
speeches by Federal Reserve officials.
</P>
<P>
   Government securities were also under pressure from coming
issues of corporate debt, which are expected to compete with
Treasuries for investors' cash.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year bond fell 26/32, to 100
23/32; the yield, which moves in the opposite direction of the
price, rose to 6.07 percent from 6.01 percent on Friday. The
Treasury market was closed on Monday in observance of Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Light trading continued to plague the market throughout the day,
exaggerating shifts in buying. Analysts noted that the bond market
had shown a penchant for volatility lately with plenty of obstacles
to choke off a sustained rally, including a busy calendar of Fed
speeches and a steady stream of economic data.
</P>
<P>
   This week's appearances at the podium by the Fed chairman, Alan
Greenspan, and two Fed governors, Laurence Meyer and Roger
Ferguson, ``have the power to send the bond market scurrying for
cover,'' said Adam Blankman, Treasury market analyst for Standard &AMP;
Poor's MMS, a market research and analysis firm in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices slumped Tuesday in what traders described as an
uneventful session. Blankman noted that supply was weighing on the
market, though estimates of the corporate debt this month are being
reduced from about $60 billion to the range of $30 billion to $40
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The firms managing corporate bond sales often hedge against
possible losses by selling government securities before the
corporate issues are sold, then buying back the Treasuries after
the corporate issues are in the hands of investors.
</P>
<P>
   Market participants looking for signs of the Fed's position on
the economy and the direction of interest rates will be paying
particular attention to the Fed officials' remarks this week and to
a government report on producer prices, or inflation at the
manufacturing level, on Friday. Analysts expect the report to show
a rise of .3 of 1 percent in August after a gain of .2 of 1 percent
in July.
</P>
<P>
   Blankman said that Greenspan and the other Fed officials
speaking this week were helping to keep buyers sidelined.
</P>
<P>
   The only exception was the three-month bill, which was the
session's top performer. ``Thanks to the laws of supply and demand,
this is the only instrument on the yield curve that is above water
today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury's bill auction was well received. The three-month
issue was awarded at 4.72 percent, a little better than expected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1852EDT &QL; 
