<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3615 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CISNEROS-GUILTY-HNS &LR;      09-07 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-GUILTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISNEROS PLEADS GUILTY TO MISDEMEANOR COUNT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Housing secretary Henry Cisneros, whose
earlier political career was derailed by an extramarital affair,
pleaded guilty Tuesday to a single misdemeanor count of lying to
the FBI about the money he paid his mistress.
</P>
<P>
   In a plea agreement, Cisneros, who had faced 18 felony counts,
will pay a $10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing in federal court, a somber Cisneros admitted that he
``knowingly and falsely'' told FBI agents that he gave his former
paramour, Linda Jones, only about $2,500 per month between 1990 and
1992. The agents were conducting a background check leading to his
Cabinet selection in President Clinton's first administration.
Federal prosecutors alleged, and Cisneros conceded, that the dollar
figure was much greater _ more than $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The plea agreement forestalled what could have been an
embarrassing monthlong trial on charges that Cisneros not only lied
to the FBI but obstructed justice and illegally conspired in an
effort to prevent his payments to Jones from becoming public. The
trial was to start Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Independent counsel David Barrett and his team of prosecutors,
who have spent more than $10 million on their investigation, were
prepared to introduce at trial surreptitiously recorded audio tapes
of conversations between Cisneros and Jones that detailed their
financial arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros' lawyers were prepared to paint Jones as an unreliable
witness who had doctored the tapes and then lied about it.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, who faced up to 15 years in prison on the original
charges, admitted that he lied to FBI agents Jan. 7, 1993.
Cisneros, in entering his guilty plea, told U.S. District Judge
Stanley Sporkin that he lied in an effort to protect Jones and his
wife, Mary Alice, from embarrassment and also because he was caught
up in ``the fog of the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin, however, showed little sympathy for Cisneros'
explanation. ``You knew you were not being candid with the FBI,''
Sporkin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's correct,'' Cisneros responded.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, who served as mayor of San Antonio from 1981 to 1989,
chose not to seek re-election after his then year-long affair with
Jones became public in 1988. The affair ended by early 1991, and he
has since reconciled with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, who resigned from the Cabinet in 1996, told the judge
that the four-and-a-half years he was under investigation were ``a
difficult time for me and my family.'' He said the guilty plea
would ``let us proceed with our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $10,000, Cisneros agreed to pay a $25 special
assessment to the court as required under federal law. In return,
the independent counsel agreed to drop all other charges against
Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin, before accepting the guilty plea, expressed sympathy
that Cisneros' personal life had become public. Calling the
investigation ``a long and sometimes nasty saga in the life of
Henry Cisneros,'' Sporkin told the defendant that ``I believe you
deeply regret the pain you have caused your loved ones.''
</P>
<P>
   But, the judge said Barrett acted properly in pressing ahead
with the prosecution of Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that future public servants learn from your ordeal,''
Sporkin told Cisneros. ``We cannot let an individual lie his way
into public office.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, in a statement released after Sporkin accepted the
guilty plea, expressed remorse and presented himself as an example
of what government officials should not do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret my lack of candor and accept responsibility for my
conduct,'' he said. ``I hope that all who follow me in public
service learn the lesson that truth and candor are important in the
process of selecting our leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros also defended his work in the Clinton administration,
adding that his lies were limited to events in his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased to say that after four-and-a-half years of
investigation there has not been any allegation that my service at
HUD was affected in any way,'' he said. ``I ... hope that when the
final chapter is written on my service at HUD, the focus will not
be on what I said in an interview prior to nomination, but on what
I did to improve the lives of those who need help the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros has moved far from Washington, serving as president of
Univision Communications Inc., a Los Angeles-based Spanish-language
television network.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, in a prepared statement, defended his investigation and
prosecution of Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (guilty-plea) disposition should in no way be viewed as
minimizing the serious ethical breach by Mr. Cisneros,'' Barrett
said. ``Deception by public officials and those seeking public
office erodes trust and must be addressed and sanctioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, a just disposition of any prosecution must include an
evaluation of the defendant's overall conduct,'' he said. ``In this
case, the conduct, while egregious, was committed by a person whose
life has been otherwise dedicated to public service, and this fact
must season the final decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, using Jones' secret tape recordings of Cisneros, was
prepared to argue at trial that Cisneros paid Jones more than
$250,00, including $73,000 after he became HUD secretary in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But Cisneros' veteran defense attorneys were equally prepared to
challenge the validity of the tapes, arguing that Jones was not a
person who could be believed. Jones, through her own actions, had
put her own credibility in question, making the job easier for
Cisneros' lawyers, Barry Simon and Brendan Sullivan, who gained
fame 12 years ago with his vigorous defense of Oliver North during
the Iran-Contra scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is serving a three-and-a-half year prison sentence after
pleading guilty last year to fraud for initially misrepresenting as
originals the copies she made of her recorded conversations with
Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who went by her married surnamed Medlar until her 1989
divorce, also accepted $15,000 from ``Inside Edition'' in return
for her 1994 appearance on the syndicated television show. That
appearance, during which portions of the tapes were aired, helped
convince Attorney General Janet Reno to ask a panel of three
federal judges to appoint an independent counsel to investigate
Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   But Sporkin, accepting Cisneros' plea, said the widely
anticipated trial will not occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over,'' Sporkin said to Cisneros. ``Good luck.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
