<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3616 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBO-BIGGAME-COX     09-07 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-BIGGAME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High school's Little Big Man on Campus
 &HT;    By Michael Lee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLQUITT, Ga. _ Take a swipe at Don Calloway on the football
field, and you might end up with a face full of grass.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, he'll make you miss _ badly. Calloway, a
senior running back for Miller County, isn't big. He is listed at 5
feet 8, 175 pounds, but he actually is closer to 5 feet 6.
</P>
<P>
   But Calloway can fly. His 4.4 speed in the 40-yard dash doesn't
tell the whole story. His feet never stop, and they move with the
rhythm and grace of a tap dancer.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to tackle what you can't grasp.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's unbelievable,'' Miller County coach Ronnie McNease said.
``His entire career, he's made cuts, and I have no idea how he made
them. I won't know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanier County still doesn't. His line for just one half against
Lanier on Friday was remarkable by Sony PlayStation standards: 15
carries, 476 yards and eight touchdowns. It was 115 yards short of
his season's rushing total as a sophomore and half as many
touchdowns as last season, when he rushed for 2,077 yards in 10
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That cat was rolling,'' his father, Arthur ``Pop'' Calloway,
said, shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   The record yards didn't startle Don much. He predicted it
earlier in the day. Calloway's older brother, Selma Calloway,
called around noon to ask Don what he expected to do later that
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ought to get about 500 yards,'' Don said.
</P>
<P>
   Selma, who played at Georgia 1993-98, laughed and cautioned him,
``Hey, don't concern yourself with that. Just run as hard as you
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Pardon Don's ambition. He isn't the arrogant, flashy type. When
he scores, he usually just drops the ball and heads to the
sideline. But he just had a feeling that against Lanier County _ a
program in its second season of varsity football _ it might be his
only opportunity to bump brother Selma from the top of Miller
County's single-game rushing yards record, 413 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Lanier County defenders spent most of the night flailing and
swinging at his shadow. To tackle him, which didn't happen much,
required at least three or four players. After one quarter, he had
201 yards and touchdown runs of 68, 25 and 75 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second period, the Miller County stat man told
McNease that Calloway was closing in on Cartersville tailback Keith
Henderson's 15-year-old single-game rushing record of 423 yards and
that he wasn't far from breaking the touchdown record of seven,
held by five others, including Selma.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates kept feeding him the ball, even sacrificing their
own stats. Midway through the second quarter last week, junior
quarterback Derrick Bush had a clear path for a 30-yard touchdown.
But halfway during his run, Bush turned and flipped it to Calloway,
who handled the rest. ``I knew he was going for a record,'' Bush
said. ``I said, `It ain't going to mean nothing to me.' I love
watching him run.''
</P>
<P>
   Calloway broke both records on his final carry _ a 77-yard
scamper on which he was obviously winded but huffed and puffed his
way to the score. Then, he tossed the ball to the ground and
rested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tired,'' Calloway said. ``But none of this would've been
possible without my hogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he's a member of Future Farmers of America and has won
a few awards for showing swine at livestock shows, Calloway was
referring to his Miller County offensive linemen. After the game,
Calloway hugged each one and thanked them.
</P>
<P>
   The next day he was in Athens, watching Georgia beat Utah State
and saw highly heralded freshman Charles Grant, whom he reluctantly
backed up for two seasons. In a limited role his freshman season,
Calloway had 100 carries for 1,224 yards. ``He had something in
him,'' McNease said. ``If Charles didn't play here, (Calloway)
would've been starting.''
</P>
<P>
   Calloway thought he'd get more playing time as a sophomore, but
Grant had a monster 1997 season. Grant rushed for 2,530 yards and
tied Herschel Walker's single-season state record with 45
touchdowns. Calloway did make all-state that season _ at nose
guard.
</P>
<P>
   But Grant knows what Calloway does best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, Don, you can't teach what he does. He knows how to run
with the football,'' Grant said. ``I said, `You only had 16
touchdowns all last year, and you've got half that after one game?'
He ought to be able to break my record.''
</P>
<P>
   Who's going to doubt somebody who actually caught rabbits as a
kid?
</P>
<P>
   When Don went on hunting trips with his father, Pop Calloway
wouldn't let him hold a gun, so one day Don, then 12, came back
with a rabbit. Pop didn't believe he caught it, until Don returned
with two more.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was better with his feet than I was with a gun,'' Pop
Calloway, 60, said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Don Calloway laughs when the subject turns to his fleet feet.
``Yeah, one of the coaches always tells me, my feet move faster
than my brain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Calloway carries an 84 average at Miller County, but doesn't
have the SAT score necessary to qualify. But that isn't what is
keeping recruiters from some major schools away.
</P>
<P>
   The knock on Calloway is that he is too short for Division I.
Calloway, who has a tattoo of a Bulldog on his left arm, is
considering Georgia, Auburn, North Carolina, N.C. State, Nebraska
and Clemson. Calloway said Auburn is the only one of the six that
hasn't made an issue of his height.
</P>
<P>
   He's heard it all his life. When he was little, Pop Calloway
told him, ``You ain't going to be tall, so you be the best.''
</P>
<P>
   And he listened.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the biggest heart I've ever seen,'' McNease said
about Calloway, who benches 435 pounds and squats 665. ``His height
is a liability, but he can play on any level he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   No need to tell Calloway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's saying to me, 'I'm too short, too short,' ''
Calloway said, rolling his eyes. ``Hey, we all buckle 'em up the
same. I'm going to prove to everyone around here that small people
can do big things.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
