A3618 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-9999-COX     09-07 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-9999-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Companies to test 2000 readiness when 9/9/99 arrives
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Much of corporate Atlanta will conduct a drill of its
Y2K readiness this Thursday, courtesy of another potential
date-related glitch involving computers.
</P>
<P>
   The date is 9/9/99, and no, it's not the designation of some
devilish cult. It is a date that programmers for years used as the
expiration time for thousands of data archives. The fear is that,
once this date is reached on Thursday, these programs will shut
down.
</P>
<P>
   Many big companies have prepared for this problem as they
readied their systems for 2000. Few corporate information managers
expect any problems Thursday. Still, many of them see the day as a
good test of their preparedness for Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of folks are resting their Y2K fixes on Thursday and it
is smart of them to do it,'' says Ted Fisher, a Y2K consultant who
is secretary to the Governor's Y2K Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   One of those using Thursday as a test of Y2K contingency plans
is BellSouth. The phone company's test is set to run Wednesday
through Saturday to coincide with Sept. 9
</P>
<P>
   ``Our network elements and computer systems are ready for the
9/9/99 date,'' said Rick Harder, the BellSouth vice president with
overall responsibilities for the corporation's Year 2000 program.
``We expect everything to work as normal, but this gives us a
perfect opportunity to drill our contingency plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Harder said this week's drill would be the first ``live'' test
of BellSouth's Y2K plans.
</P>
<P>
   The company has set up a Corporate Information Center in Atlanta
to monitor how all of the company's units fare. Those units include
local telephone service, cellular service and Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   The units will report any problems to the center, which will
move quickly to correct them.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, BellSouth will share its results with other
telecommunications companies, which is an industry first.
</P>
<P>
   ``By sharing information with other telecommunications
companies, we will have the best brains in the business examining
any possible problems that may pop up,'' Harder said. ``In the
unlikely event a problem does occur, the industry will be able to
address and fix the problem quickly and consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
