<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3623 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-LYCOS-QUOTECOM-BOS &LR;      09-07 0282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-QUOTECOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYCOS BUYS QUOTE.COM INC. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the latest effort to extend its network of popular Web sites,
Lycos Inc. of Waltham, Mass. will pay $78.3 million in stock to
acquire Quote.com Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Quote.com, of Mountain View, Calif., delivers stock quotes and
other financial information. About 616,000 Internet users visited
the site in June, according to Media Metrix, a Web site ratings
service.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos chief executive Bob Davis called the Quote.com deal ``a
very logical extension of what is our existing network strategy.''
Davis wouldn't say whether privately held Quote.com is currently
profitable. But, he said, ``Lycos is profitable and I don't expect
that to change because of this acquisition.'' A report from
Hoover's Inc. estimated that Quote.com had $12 million in revenue
during its 1998 fiscal year, which ended last September.
</P>
<P>
   Quote.com relies on three revenue streams. The free version of
the service is supported by advertising, but the company also
offers a subscription service that provides financial planning
assistance and real-time stock quotes. Subscriptions range in price
from $25 to $80 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Quote.com also operates a service that provides real-time stock
quotes to the Web sites of other financial companies. About 150
firms subscribe to this service, including Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. and
Bank of America Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said Lycos will build chat rooms, message boards, and
other features linked to Quote.com in order to create a community
of loyal users who will rely on Lycos as a primary source of
financial information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
