<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH STRESSES LOCAL CONTROL IN OUTLINING EDUCATION POLICY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILFORD, N.H. _ Republican presidential candidate George W.
Bush, who last week proposed a new federal hammer for forcing
improvements in public education, took pains Tuesday to insist he
was still a local control man at heart.
</P>
<P>
   In stops in three southern New Hampshire towns, the front-runner
for the Republican presidential nomination said his plan to take
federal dollars from poorly performing public schools was not an
attempt to put local schools under federal control.
</P>
<P>
   ``My education policy is, first and foremost, trust the people
of New Hampshire to make the right decisions (for their schools). I
keep saying that,'' Bush told about 300 people in a campaign stop
at the Milford fire station.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is that one size should not fit all when it comes to
federal education policy.``
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the differences in educational needs between two
states, such as Texas and New Hampshire, could be large, he added:
``Those who look to the federal government to solve our educational
problems are misguided. So, step one is to pass power back from
Washington to local jurisdictions``
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Milford audience applauded the message, which Bush also
delivered during visits to an elementary school in Bedford and a
high-tech facility at Nashua.
</P>
<P>
   In a Los Angeles speech last week, Bush laid out proposals for
reforming public education that could transfer millions of dollars
from failing public schools to private and religious ones.
</P>
<P>
   His plan would require all states receiving federal education
dollars to test their pupils and report the results to Washington.
If a school was rated low-performing for three years in a row under
Bush's plan, parents could withdraw their children and take the
school's federal Title I money to help pay for educations in
charter or private schools.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was immediately attacked by political opponents. Some
said it would increase the federal government's control over
education. Others attacked it as a voucher plan, which Bush has
been unable to convince the Legislature to approve in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Tuesday more accountability was needed over the
expenditure of federal education funds to ensure that tax resources
were not wasted and that every American child had an opportunity to
receive a quality education.
</P>
<P>
   But he insisted that ``local control'' was still an important
part of his plan because the individual states would design their
own student tests to determine which schools were passing or
failing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm against a national test. I believe a national test will
undermine local jurisdiction,'' the Texas governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spent about two hours in Milford. In addition to his stop
at the fire station, where he fielded numerous questions on a
variety of subjects from New Hampshirites, he got a light, but
well-photographed trim at Joe's Barber Shop, dropped in on the
lunch crowd at the Riverhouse Cafe and shook dozens of hands along
downtown streets.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, a fifth-grader at the Peter Woodbury Elementary
School in Bedford turned the tables on Bush, who has made
educational improvements a high priority of his campaign, and asked
if the would-be president had been an outstanding student.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not particularly,'' Bush replied. ``I was a pretty good
student. I was interested in things I really loved, for example,
history.``
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked hard, but I wasn't what you would call a great
student ... Some people say, and I agree, that if you can get a C
average, you can end up being successful in life,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
