<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3632 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-07 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE MEAN SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ For the past decade, Australian strategists
have referred to the Southeast Asian nations to their north _
Indonesia, Malaysia, Thailand &AMP; Co. _ as Australia's ``strategic
shield.'' Today, Australian strategists refer to Southeast Asia as
``the arc of instability formerly known as Australia's strategic
shield.''
</P>
<P>
   They have a point. When you look up at Asia from down under,
what you see today is a region more explosive than at any time
since the Vietnam War. For years it has been widely assumed that
all these countries, even China, were in ``transition'' from
underdeveloped to developed, from confrontation to multilateral
cooperation and from closed political systems to more open ones. It
was going to be the Pacific Century.
</P>
<P>
   But today it is now the fear of implosion, not the inevitability
of transition, that dominates political discussions here. It starts
with Indonesia. For the past 25 years Indonesia has been the
keystone holding together Southeast Asia as a pro-Western,
free-market bloc counterbalancing China. Today that keystone is
crumbling.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia is the Yugoslavia of Southeast Asia. Its economic
downturn has weakened the center, and civil wars have erupted at
both ends of the Indonesian archipelago, from Aceh in the north,
where Muslim separatists want to secede, to East Timor in the
south, where 80 percent of the population voted for independence
and the Indonesian military simply won't let go.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and the United Nations are right to lay down
an ultimatum to the Indonesian government: Either stop the gangs
marauding East Timor, and permit a U.N. peacekeeping force to go in
_ which the Australians would gladly provide the forces for _ or
Indonesia will be treated as a pariah state and its tentative
economic recovery aborted. (The Aussies are ready to put troops
into Timor because they know if Indonesia implodes, the boat people
are heading for Australia.)
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this is not the only problem in the neighborhood.
``Whether it is Indonesia, or the Korean Peninsula, or Taiwan, or
the South China Sea or India-Pakistan _ all the most sensitive hot
spots today are in Asia,'' remarked Gerard Henderson, director of
the Sydney Institute. America's role in the region has gone from
containing communism to containing chaos. The Pacific Century is
now officially on hold.
</P>
<P>
   It need not be forever, though. There are still positive trends
here that have a lot of human energy and aspirations fueling them.
Look at Thailand. Its central bank, responding to the Asian
economic crisis, just announced a whole new strategic approach
``emphasizing new values of honesty and integrity, teamwork,
competence, accountability and efficiency.''
</P>
<P>
   Next door, Singapore's government, which has always kept a very
tight lid on what its citizens can read and say, indicated it may
ease up a bit because it realizes this is the only way to attract
more brains to Singapore. The Asian Wall Street Journal quoted
Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong as saying, ``We have to create a
Silicon Valley state of mind in Singapore _ creative and willing to
take risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Korea's government is dismantling Daewoo, one of the
four bloated family-controlled conglomerates in Korea that helped
sink the country in a pool of foreign debt. China has even
restarted talks on joining the World Trade Organization, which
would open and regulate its economy as never before.
</P>
<P>
   But then, when you look closer, you see that even these silver
trends have cloudy linings. Korea may be dismantling Daewoo, but it
isn't actually closing down any of its companies, for fear of
unemployment, so they will limp along. There have been several
unexplained bombings in Chinese cities, and billions of hot dollars
are being smuggled out of China.
</P>
<P>
   It is no accident that the two countries that emerged unscathed
from the Asian economic crisis also happen to be the two most
democratic in Asia, with the freest media _ Australia and Taiwan.
The others are like kids who spurted up economically, but never
adjusted their political clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Well, now they are, and that adjustment is going to produce
stresses and even implosions throughout this region. And that's why
this yin and yang, between positive and negative trends, is going
to be with us in Asia for a long time. So welcome to the ``New
Asia'' _ the arc of instability formerly known as Australia's
strategic shield.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1916EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3633 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-2000-HNS &LR;      09-07 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE UNVEILS HEALTH-CARE PROPOSAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Trying to avoid the missteps of the early Clinton
years, Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore unveiled a modest
health-care proposal Tuesday that would ensure universal coverage
for children and provide some adults with more access to medical
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a Los Angeles hospital, the vice president pledged
to make health care accessible to every child by 2005, to give
adults under retirement age the ability to buy into Medicare, and
provide tax credits to small businesses and individuals to defray
the cost of purchasing health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also endorsed efforts to give patients in HMOs more rights
to challenge decisions made by their insurers and to see
specialists.
</P>
<P>
   The health-care announcement reflected how unusually early the
presidential campaign is heating up, with candidates under pressure
to give detailed presentations of their proposals more than a year
before the election. Last week, Republican front-runner George W.
Bush spelled out his education agenda during a campaign swing in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Gore may also have wanted to grab some attention on an issue
dear to many Democrats a day before his rival for the party's
nomination, former U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley, is expected to announce
his candidacy in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   But even as he rolled out a health-care agenda aimed at
placating more liberal voters, the vice president seemed intent on
proposing a plan that bore no resemblance to the complicated and
massive health proposal devised by President Clinton and first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton during the president's first term.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans successfully characterized their plan as an effort
by the Clintons to have government take control of the largely
private health care system. Voter dissatisfaction with that plan,
aimed at guaranteeing universal coverage, contributed to the GOP
winning control of Congress in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made it clear he was not going to make the same mistake,
saying he preferred the incremental approach taken by Congress and
the president after the 1993 debacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have learned that we cannot overhaul the system in one fell
swoop,'' he said. ``Experience has taught us that there is a way to
keep what is right, while fixing what is wrong with America's
health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's most dramatic proposal, guaranteeing health care coverage
for children, would rely largely on the expansion of the Children's
Health Insurance Program, approved by Congress in 1997, to help
states provide medical coverage for young people.
</P>
<P>
   Currently children in families who earn up to 200 percent of the
poverty level are eligible. Gore proposed increasing the limit to
250 percent of the poverty level, or $41,000 a year for a family of
four.
</P>
<P>
   Gore estimated that raising the cap would add about 1 million
children to the program. He also said states must do a better job
of tracking down eligible children who have not yet enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   And in a jab at Bush, Gore singled out Texas for what he called
a poor job of providing health coverage for impoverished children.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some states _ Texas springs to mind _ one quarter of all
children are still out in the cold,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said that the CHIPs program in
Texas will cover 423,000 of the 1.4 million uninsured Texas
children by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, during the legislative session that ended in May, pushed
for a lower income cap on the Children's Health Insurance Program
than what legislators passed.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor's office wanted to cover children living in
families that earn up to 150 percent of poverty level, $25,200 a
year for a family of four. The Legislature agreed to, and Bush
eventually embraced, a cap of 200 percent of the poverty level, or
$36,600 for a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first opportunity the Texas Legislature and Governor Bush
had, they enacted the CHIPs program, which increased Medicaid
eligibility for children up to 200 percent of the poverty level,''
Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president did not detail how he would pay for the
additional coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokeswoman Kiki Moore said the vice president was
``convinced that this can be paid for ... within the context of the
balanced budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plans for covering adults was far less comprehensive than
his plans for children.
</P>
<P>
   To help those forced into early retirement he backed a plan
already proposed by Clinton that would allow people between the
ages of 55 and 65 to enroll in Medicare if they were willing to pay
the premium costs that are subsidized by the government for those
over 65.
</P>
<P>
   To make health care more affordable to those who work for small
businesses, Gore proposed tax credits for small businesses that
band together to buy insurance for their employees and to
individuals who are forced to buy health insurance without the help
from employers.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing an issue that is dear to his wife, Tipper, Gore said
he would require Medicaid to pay for treatment of mental illness,
such as depression.
</P>
<P>
   He also touched on a hot topic now in front of Congress by
vowing to support efforts to give patients in HMOs more ability to
challenge health plans decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he supported HMO reform that ``will hold health care
plans accountable for unfairly depriving patients of coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore did not directly address the most controversial issue
of whether consumers should be allowed to sue their managed care
plans for malpractice. Democratic lawmakers and some Republicans
support such legislation while the GOP leadership, along with
health insurance companies, adamantly opposes it.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how much of a dent Gore's proposals would make in
the approximately 43 million uninsured Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But one health care expert said the vice president has to walk a
fine line.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's at real risk of sounding like he's got Hillary's plan all
over again,'' said Bob Blendon, professor of health care policy at
Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Blendon said, ``He's got to propose something
because people are worried about health care, particularly on the
Democratic side,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Blendon said Gore has to worry about defections from those
Democrats who care deeply about health care and may be tempted to
vote for Bradley, who in his stump speeches talks about supporting
universal health care. However, Bradley has not has not provided a
detailed plan for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
