<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3636 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CISNEROS08-1STLEDE-CO     09-07 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS08-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CISNEROS PLEADS GUILTY TO MISDEMEANOR, ENDING CONSPIRACY CASE
 &HT;    Eds: In graf 4, corrects date affair started to 1987.
 &HT;    By JENA HEATH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former housing secretary Henry Cisneros pleaded
guilty Tuesday to a single misdemeanor charge, ending a four-year,
$9 million federal investigation into his extramarital life and
allegations that he lied to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers, reporters and onlookers who had gathered in U.S.
District Court for the start of jury selection in Cisneros's
long-delayed trial instead saw Cisneros plead guilty and agree to
pay a $10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret my lack of candor and accept responsibility for my
conduct,'' Cisneros said in a prepared statement. ``I hope that all
who follow me in public service learn the lesson that truth and
candor are important in the process of selecting our leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, 52, a former San Antonio mayor, had faced a possible
90 years in prison on 18 felony counts stemming from an affair he
began in 1987 with fund-raiser Linda Medlar, who now uses her
maiden name, Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, he will get no prison time or probation and
could apply for a presidential pardon. A felony conviction could
have kept Cisneros from running for office again.
</P>
<P>
   The plea agreement also saves Cisneros from the public airing of
most of the contents of 26 recordings Jones secretly made of her
conversations with him.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros pleaded guilty to telling an FBI agent in 1993 that he
lied when he said he paid Jones about $2,500 a month over a
three-year period. He paid her considerably more, in excess of
$250,000, according to federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros lied during an FBI background check pending
confirmation of his appointment as secretary of the Department of
Housing and Urban Development. He stepped down from the post in
1996 and is now president and chief operating officer of Univision,
a Los Angeles-based Spanish-language television network.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who earlier pleaded guilty to similar charges stemming
from the case, is serving a 3-1/2 year federal prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros told U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin that he wasn't
sure how much he had been paying Jones because he never calculated
a total. He said his wife of 30 years, the former Mary Alice Perez,
didn't know how much he was paying his former mistress. Cisneros
said he lied to the FBI in ``the pressured and confused fog of the
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't good enough for Sporkin, who pressed Cisneros to
admit guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know ... you were, in effect, not being candid with the
FBI?'' Sporkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros responded: ``That's correct.''
</P>
<P>
   The significance of the outcome, Sporkin said, is that ``we
cannot permit an individual to lie his way into high public
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by independent counsel David M. Barrett, a Republican
activist and lobbyist, the federal government spent at least $9
million on the Cisneros investigation. The final cost won't be
known for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The probe was part of the closing chapter of the independent
counsel law, which expired June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the outcome was worth the time and money spent to
pursue Cisneros, Barrett said: ``Ask me in a week.'' He otherwise
declined to comment, as did Cisneros and all the lawyers involved
in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Di Genova, a former federal prosecutor and independent
counsel, called the misdemeanor plea ``a win for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Sporkin decided to let the tapes in, Cisneros had his
back against the wall,'' Di Genova said. ``He had to make some very
important decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   And while he said Cisneros's lie to the FBI was ``a very serious
matter,'' Di Genova also criticized the independent counsel
statute, calling it a ``very bad law that created a lack of
confidence in federal white-collar law enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   At home, Cisneros supporters were crowing over what they
considered a clear victory for the charismatic man who electrified
Democrats at their 1984 national convention and who was once talked
about as a possible first Hispanic president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, he's paid the equivalent of a white-collar parking
ticket,'' said Austin political consultant George Shipley. ``I
think it's clear the government could have ended this case years
ago, perhaps with an apology.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cisneros's reputation, although tarnished, is intact,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Shipley is mentioned 33 times in tape-recorded conversations
between Jones and Cisneros. He wouldn't say if he tried to help
Jones in an effort to get her to leave Cisneros alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of Henry's friends were concerned about Linda, but she
refused all offers of help,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jena Heath can be reached at jenah(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
