A3640 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELTA-AMAZON-COX     09-07 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-AMAZON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta loses finance chief to Amazon.com
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was a short ride at Delta Air Lines for Warren
Jenson.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based carrier's executive vice president and chief
financial officer resigned Tuesday, 16 months after arriving.
</P>
<P>
   Jenson, 42, will become finance chief at Amazon.com, the
Internet retailer. Although his tenure at Delta was marred earlier
this year by an incident involving his family's free-flying
privileges, Jenson was regarded as a savvy and aggressive finance
chief.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wasn't considering leaving until approached by
Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those rare opportunities _ once in a generation
_ to play in a field where history will be made,'' Jenson said.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be succeeded as Delta's CFO by Edward West, 33, a senior
vice president who's been at the airline five years. West won't
carry the executive vice president title.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Chief Executive Leo Mullin noted that West, despite his
youth, has already held several key financial jobs at the airline
and was briefly interim CFO before Jenson was hired.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin added he has no plans for an outside CFO search.
</P>
<P>
   Jenson came to Delta in April 1998 from NBC, the first of
several outsiders brought in as Mullin retooled top management.
</P>
<P>
   He is credited with strengthening Delta's finance department
through several lower-level hires. He also cut a lucrative deal for
stock purchase rights in Priceline.com in return for Delta's sale
of seats at the site. The rights now are worth about $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Jenson was tarnished by a flap last spring involving his
children's use of flight passes.
</P>
<P>
   A Delta flight at Hartsfield was delayed 24 minutes after three
of Jenson's children and a friend, driven to the airport by his
secretary, arrived late. The secretary had agents seat the youths
in first class, while passengers who'd been upgraded got vouchers
and seats in coach.
</P>
<P>
   After flight crew complaints became public, Jenson relinquished
his family's flying privileges and paid the airline more than
$1,000 for the vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Jenson said the matter played no role in his departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely nothing in my decision process that
related to anything negative about Delta,'' he said. ``I loved my
time there and loved working with Leo and the rest of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Delta stock fell $2.56 1/4 to $50.12 1/2 on a down day for
airline shares.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
