<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3644 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILM-NEWSEASON-MCKELL     09-07 1383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NEWSEASON-MCKELLAR-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE END' OF THE WORLD AS FILMED BY DON MCKELLAR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, Brazil, Taiwan)   By DAVID MERMELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As we barrel toward the millennium, there's something bothering
the writer and actor Don McKellar: the dearth of good,
old-fashioned end-of-the world movies. McKellar was so perturbed
that he decided to make his own. The result, his feature-film
directing debut, is cheekily titled ``Last Night,'' and opens Nov.
5.
</P>
<P>
   Modestly budgeted at $2 million, the movie, which was released
in McKellar's native Canada in 1998, boasts none of the special
effects that characterize films like ``Deep Impact'' and
``Armageddon,'' two blockbusters from last summer in which the
earth was threatened. On the other hand, those films lack the
intellectual and emotional heft of ``Last Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans are probably unfamiliar with McKellar. But in
Canada, his work as an avant-garde playwright and actor had brought
him to the attention of the Toronto independent film community. He
was co-writer, with Francois Girard, of ``Thirty Two Short Films
About Glenn Gould'' and ``The Red Violin''; he appeared as an actor
in Atom Egoyan's widely acclaimed ``Exotica'' and more recently in
David Cronenberg's ``Existenz.'' Like Cronenberg and Egoyan,
McKellar brings a wry, offbeat sensibility to his work. That
quirkiness seems the perfect way to approach the imminent
destruction of the planet in a post-modern age.
</P>
<P>
   McKellar, who is 36, had made a short film, ``Blue,'' when he
was approached in 1997 by Haut et Court, a French production
company with the grand ambition of having 10 directors from 10
different countries make movies about the turn of the millennium.
(Walter Salles of Brazil, Hal Hartley of the United States and Tsai
Ming-Liang of Taiwan were among the other filmmakers selected.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this strange, unnatural pressure on me,'' McKellar
said by telephone from his home in Toronto. ``People kept asking
when I would direct a full-length film, and this just seemed the
right opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was so excited about his new project (he wrote the
screenplay as well) that he forgot to ask if there were any
guidelines. In fact, there were, but he learned of them only after
his film was completed. ``I guess I disobeyed some of the rules,''
said McKellar, ``including the one that specified that the action
was to take place on Dec. 31, 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, McKellar avoided setting his film on any particular
date. He even went to some length to disguise Toronto, where the
story takes place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Night'' recounts how a random, though interconnected,
group of ordinary Torontonians spends its final six hours on earth.
At the film's center is Patrick, a snide, insular architect played
by McKellar himself. After enjoying a final dinner with his parents
(Roberta Maxwell and Robin Gammel) and sister (Sarah Polley), he
retreats to his apartment to await the apocalypse alone. But his
plans come a cropper when he finds Sandra (Sandra Oh), a complete
stranger, despondent on his doorstep because she cannot get home to
her husband before the world ends.
</P>
<P>
   McKellar is wary of calling his film science fiction, for these
days the term connotes expensive, action-packed pictures. He hoped
that by avoiding certain topics _ ones often dealt with in science
fiction movies _ he could get his audience to focus on more
important issues. As a result, ``Last Night'' never answers, or
even poses, the question, ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that on the last day, people would be beyond
discussing the reason,'' McKellar said of his decision not to
explain how the world is ending in his film. ``I didn't want people
wondering what Bruce Willis would do under the circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Other factors also contributed to what some may see as a glaring
omission.
</P>
<P>
   McKellar wanted to steer clear of blaming someone or something
for the catastrophe, fearing that moralizing would dilute the
content of his picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to point a finger at corporations or the Chinese
or global warming or something,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So, rather than focus on the causes of the world's demise,
McKellar has trained his lens on the disaster's human impact. ``It
sounds very corny,'' he said, ``but the film is about living, and
about allowing yourself to be open around others despite the
restrictions.''
</P>
<P>
   The openness that McKellar refers to is a theme refined from his
days on the stage, when his primary creative outlet was the Augusta
Co., a theater collective with which he is still associated.
</P>
<P>
   During those years, the late 1980s and early 1990s, McKellar
wore several hats simultaneously and began to think about the
creative process in ways that would shape his future endeavors.
``It was there that I began to get these disciplines _ acting,
writing, directing _ confused,'' he said. For the theater, McKellar
advances an imagistic esthetic, but his foray into film required a
shift to naturalism that he says better suits movies.
</P>
<P>
   Cronenberg, whose unconventional films have inspired McKellar,
plays a supporting role in ``Last Night.'' He calls the movie
``quietly brilliant.'' Naturally, he has his own interpretation of
the picture's message.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has an eccentric emotional power that kind of sneaks up on
you,'' Cronenberg said. ``If an American writes an end-of-the-world
story, it's `Armageddon.' Don's take is so innately human. It
really deals with mortality in a way those others don't. They
pretend to, but they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Mortality is central to any film dealing with an apocalypse, of
course. But for McKellar, the issue was more personal. He traces
his fascination with the subject to his youth. ``I obsessed about
the end of the world a lot when I was a child,'' he said. In those
years, McKellar suffered from nightmares, and the destruction of
the planet was a recurring theme. Once, he became so agitated that
he ran from his parents' house to warn neighbors that the end was
nigh. ``I thought I could do something,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Night'' touches on that sort of domestic drama in scenes
of family farewells and last-chance indulgences, recalling such
films as ``On the Beach'' (1959) and ``Miracle Mile'' (1989). In
those movies, the world ends in nuclear annihilation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope my film resuscitates some of those themes,'' he said.
``Pictures like `On the Beach' and `Dr. Strangelove' meant a lot to
me growing up, and I wanted to recapture the tone of those films.''
</P>
<P>
   McKellar, who will be the subject of a retrospective at the
American Museum of the Moving Image on Oct. 23 and 24, has chosen
to evoke the past. Though clearly set in the present _ cellular
phones and computer chat rooms drive some of the action _ ``Last
Night'' overflows with design elements from the 1960s and 70s. Cars
like the Pacer, furniture made from plastic and garish clothes
signal bygone times. Yet for McKellar, these things are symbols of
the modern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of it as retro-futurism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Musically, too, ``Last Night'' poaches from the past. The
soundtrack mixes pop songs from the 70s with an orchestral score
that recalls the 50s. The songs, like ``Takin' Care of Business,''
were in the air when McKellar was a child, and the associations
remain important to him. ``They have an optimistic,
pre-adolescent-angst quality for me,'' he said, only half-jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   For the score, McKellar relied on the husband-and-wife team of
Alex Pauk and Alexina Louie, two Canadian composers. Though Pauk
insists that he and Ms. Louie avoided imitating a specific style,
he acknowledges that they drew on a ``vast pool of musical
memories'' to create a score full of foreboding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don was quite actively involved in the scoring process,'' said
Pauk. ``In some cases, he even dampened our romantic impulses for
something more restrained. It's all about trying to extend the
director's imagination in sound, not just mood supporting
emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   All the characters in ``Last Night'' die by the end of the film.
But McKellar sees them as valorous nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a heroism to these people,'' he said. ``The kind of
heroism it takes just to continue living.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
