<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3651 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FILM-NEWSEASON-PACINO     09-07 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NEWSEASON-PACINO-$ADV12-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AL PACINO: NONSTOP PERFECTIONIST OF FEW WORDS AND MUCH WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By KAREN DURBIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Compact and loose-limbed, with the energy level of
someone much younger _ say, the average 3-year-old _ Al Pacino
practically bounces around the kitchen of his office suite high
above midtown Manhattan. He lives in Los Angeles and suburban New
York, but this is his working base, Chal Productions, the company
he started with the acting teacher Charlie Laughton, his friend and
mentor.
</P>
<P>
   Chal's motto could be Men at Work. There are men on the job in
every room, from editors and producers working on Pacino's
independent film projects to his longtime personal assistant to the
young acting student who serves as receptionist and all-around
helper. Even Pacino's hair looks busy, springing out in various
directions from what might once have been a brush cut, and the big,
brown, sad-sack eyes glint with humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shots of hot chocolate,'' he announces, setting out cups on a
green-topped poker table by a floor-to-ceiling bay window, site of
the long-running game he plays with a group of cronies.
</P>
<P>
   An ebullient host, Pacino has assembled our afternoon repast:
bottles of spring water and the first of two large thermos carafes
of the cocoa he likes to sip instead of coffee or tea. (Hours
later, he will apologetically exclaim, ``Food!'' and produce a bag
of potato chips.) He doles out the Swiss Miss in two-finger drafts,
explaining that he's not being stingy; it's just that if he pours
more at one time, it won't stay hot.
</P>
<P>
   As the conversation warms up and his own chocolate cools below
the desired Fahrenheit, he dumps it into an extra mug he has
brought to the table and pours himself a fresh dose: the Mad
Hatter's cocoa party.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the extent of my eccentricity,'' Pacino says, sounding
more hopeful than convinced. He's known for the intensity and
obsessive attention to detail that he brings to his work, and
sometimes he is kidded about it.
</P>
<P>
   While we sit by the window, with its sweeping views of the
Hudson River and Central Park, two men are at work in another room
editing a film. The film is ``Chinese Coffee,'' from a play by Ira
Lewis that Pacino performed on Broadway in 1992 and then decided to
make into a movie starring himself and Jerry Ohrbach. Shooting
ended more than two years ago. Editing proceeds apace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're heading into three years on `Chinese Coffee,''' he says,
adding with a laugh, ``If I'd shot it right in the first place, we
might be done already.''
</P>
<P>
   That sort of self-deprecation is a minor motif in Pacino's
otherwise exuberant conversation. But however ``Chinese Coffee''
turns out, he has already demonstrated that when you marry
intensity and obsession to great talent, the results can be
spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Pacino took four years to make ``Looking for Richard,'' his
star-strewn, multilayered investigation into the mysteries of
playing Richard III and bringing Shakespeare fully alive for a
contemporary audience. He also managed to act in three other films
and two plays during that time, but even if he hadn't, it would
have been time well spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking for Richard,'' which won the Independent Spirit Award
in 1996 for best documentary, is one of the smartest and funniest
movies ever made about art, audiences and the creative process.
It's also a rare window on the deep work of acting, as Pacino
struggles to burrow his way into the soul of one of the theater's
darkest villains. He gets there in the end, with bells on, but not
before the process has left him gasping on the ground in
not-quite-mock despair.
</P>
<P>
   Pacino is the sort of nervy actor who's prepared to go all the
way down _ or right over the top _ if he thinks that's what a part
requires. Out of the spotlight, however, his shyness is the stuff
of legend. I once saw him come into a party, find a quiet corner
and plant himself there for the duration.
</P>
<P>
   He chatted with anyone who had the nerve or a better reason to
sit beside him; the rest of the time he gazed at the floor. He
famously dreads interviews, even the kind that don't try to poke
into his private life (girlfriend: the actress Beverly D'Angelo;
children: a 9-year-old daughter, Julie, whom he is close to).
</P>
<P>
   But those days, apparently, are behind him. This time around, he
couldn't be warmer or more engaging, talking through the long
afternoon with obvious pleasure and sometimes touching eloquence
about his work.
</P>
<P>
   Rather like Borges' metaphysicians of Tlon, he describes his
learning years as a series of amazements: seeing a traveling
production of ``The Sea Gull'' at age 13 in a nearly empty
vaudeville theater in the South Bronx; dropping out of the High
School of Performing Arts at 16 to go to work, only to end up a few
years later as a grateful, unpaid stagehand for Julian Beck and
Judith Malina's fearlessly experimental Living Theater (``It was
like walking into somebody's heart _ the thing was that alive'');
and, finally, winning lifelong membership in the Actors Studio,
whose most famous acting teacher, Lee Strasberg, would make his
film debut years later at Pacino's urging in ``The Godfather Part
III.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacino regularly interrupts his own film career to ``walk the
wire,'' as he puts it, of live theater. Acting in all its forms is
his life's passion and its organizing principle. Quoting a
particularly heart-stopping bit of ``Othello,'' he likens his
discovery of it 40 years ago to finding love:
</P>
<P>
   ``Perdition catch my soul, but I do love thee.
</P>
<P>
   When I love thee not, chaos is coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuckling over the telephone, Oliver Stone says: ``I hate that
you should hear it from me, but Al is a very sensitive person. He's
got a reservoir of feeling.'' Pacino most recently tapped the
reservoir for a couple of big new films, playing a hard-driving
television journalist in Michael Mann's ``Insider,'' opening Nov.
5, and an aging professional football coach who must contend with a
changing sports world in Stone's ``Any Given Sunday,'' opening on
Christmas Day.
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes are a new breed of worldly young players and a
team inherited by the widowed Ann-Margret and managed by her
daughter, Cameron Diaz. To prepare for the role, Pacino immersed
himself in the world of pro football, meeting at length with two
coaches, Bill Parcells of the Jets and Mike Shanahan of the Denver
Broncos, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sieves football coaches,'' Stone says. ``He sieves them
into the character, and the character grows out of him. He's the
filter. Al has a sense of authenticity about that. He can't always
tell you how he would do it, but he can tell you what's wrong if it
doesn't feel right.'' The director says making a film with Pacino
is like having a fellow explorer to struggle along with in the
search for meaning.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mann says: ``Some directors may or may not view actors as a
necessary pain in the neck. I don't come from that place. I have
tremendous regard for what they do; it's incredibly brave. I'm
talking about great actors.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, he's talking about Pacino, who stars opposite
Russell Crowe in Mann's controversial, fact-based thriller about
unbridled corporate power.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe plays Jeffrey Wigand, the head of research and development
at Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp. who became a whistleblower
after he was fired for protesting the company's decision to abandon
the search for a safer cigarette. Pacino plays Lowell Bergman, the
``60 Minutes'' producer who persuaded Wigand to blow the whistle in
the first place by sitting for an interview with Mike Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Brown &AMP; Williamson is portrayed as launching a pre-emptive
strike, first with a campaign of intimidation against the Wigand
family and then with one of disinformation to destroy Wigand's
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   When CBS ordered the interview pulled and ``60 Minutes''
acquiesced, Bergman went into overdrive to restore Wigand's
reputation and force the interview into the light.
</P>
<P>
   Some prominent people at CBS and ``60 Minutes'' are unhappy with
the way they're portrayed in ``The Insider,'' including Wallace,
who comes off looking less than stalwart.
</P>
<P>
   They accuse Mann of unduly glorifying Lowell Bergman, but the
director says he and Pacino worked hard not to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were many times when some vintage Al Pacino moments were
happening and I'd look at him and he'd look at me and we'd both
reject it. He'd say, `I felt myself acting, it's no good, let's do
it again.'''
</P>
<P>
   As played by Pacino, Bergman is forceful but unglamorous, a
typically aggressive muckraker who prides himself on getting there
first and protecting his sources. Pacino may be the movie's biggest
star, but he lets the attention go to the man at the center of the
story, Crowe's tormented Jeffrey Wigand.
</P>
<P>
   Pacino is arguably one of the best American actors of this
century. He's also, on occasion, such a shameless hambone that a
variety show called ``Cartoon Planet'' on the Cartoon Network,
which includes fake Italian lessons with a space alien as a host,
translates ``actore hamboni'' as ``Al Pacino.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the show's creators had in mind his raucous Satan in
``The Devil's Advocate,'' or the tangoing, suicidal, blind Lt. Col.
Frank Slade in ``Scent of a Woman'' (for which the much-nominated
actor won his only Oscar).
</P>
<P>
   Pacino can make a good thing out of extravagance, as anyone who
saw him as the violent, chaotic Teach in David Mamet's ``American
Buffalo'' can attest. I still carry a 30-year-old mental snapshot
of his shambling, charismatic young junkie in his Tony-winning
Broadway debut, ``Does a Tiger Wear a Necktie?''
</P>
<P>
   But on screen, at least, Pacino's greatest work is his quietest.
In 1972 he embarked on his most famous role, the Harvard-educated
Michael Corleone in Francis Ford Coppola's ``Godfather'' trilogy,
with such elegant minimalism that it was nearly taken away from
him.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Pacino's cool, unreadable young Sicilian in the
dailies, Paramount executives hounded the director to fire him,
only backing off after viewing the scene in which Michael avenges
his father and commits his first murders. It is an extraordinary
piece of work.
</P>
<P>
   Pacino shoots two men at close range _ they're his dinner
partners _ but the real action of the scene has already happened.
As he tries to summon the nerve to stand up and start firing,
Pacino's dark eyes dart around frantically in his otherwise
immobile face, creating a tension so intimate you feel as if you're
inside his head. The character's whole future, his rise to power
and incalculable loss of humanity, is anticipated in that moment.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he matched that performance with its reverse
image in Mike Newell's ``Donnie Brasco,'' one of the best movies in
recent memory. Instead of the supremely powerful, soul-destroying
young don, Pacino plays Lefty Ruggiero, an aging and not terribly
bright Mafia foot soldier who, in a misbegotten act of loneliness
and thwarted ambition, takes Johnny Depp's character, an undercover
FBI agent, as his protege and surrogate son.
</P>
<P>
   In laying out this tragi-comic blunder of a relationship, the
movie doesn't fudge Lefty's reality. We see him dutifully bludgeon
someone to death and then cut the body up afterward for disposal.
Like good soldiers everywhere, he does what's asked of him.
</P>
<P>
   But in Pacino's beautifully detailed performance, he is a figure
of unsentimental pathos: the little man as moral grotesque,
sandbagged by his own stupidity, deformed by the choices he's made,
yet with a fugitive core of generosity, even integrity.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, when Lefty dutifully waits to be killed, Pacino
keeps the moment small: he doesn't look anguished; he looks miffed
and depressed. Just before he goes out the door, he pauses to
remove his only valuables, a ring, a watch, the money from his
pocket and a chain he has trouble pulling over his head. He places
them neatly in a dresser drawer. At the last minute he thinks to
leave it slightly ajar, so his unsuspecting girlfriend will be sure
to look inside.
</P>
<P>
   Pacino talks about this work with typical self-deprecation. He
says he would gladly have changed his performance in ``The
Godfather'' to placate Paramount, but he couldn't figure out how:
``I saw Michael as a kind of enigma. I had a beeline on him and I
thought, I can't see doing it any other way.''
</P>
<P>
   And he credits Coppola for getting him through the ordeal: ``I
mean, he wanted me to play that part like nobody has ever wanted me
to play a part, ever. He wanted me to do it so much more than I
wanted to.'' As for Lefty, he insists on calling it ``an
actor-proof role'' and credits Paul Attanasio's excellent script,
pointing out that it was nominated for an Oscar. It deserved to be,
but so did Pacino.
</P>
<P>
   Certain American actors _ alpha males like Clint Eastwood and
John Wayne, sensitive boy-men like Montgomery Clift and James Dean
_ excel at being able to convey what it is to be a man navigating
the Byzantine, frequently brutal hierarchies of masculine power.
One thinks of an impossibly tender-looking James Dean playing
chicken in ``Rebel Without a Cause,'' Wayne and Clift battling it
out in ``Red River'' or Eastwood's astonishingly acute critiques of
his own myth in ``Tightrope'' and ``Unforgiven.''
</P>
<P>
   It's Pacino's singular gift to be able to play both ends of the
spectrum equally well. His losers and little guys are as convincing
and as detailed as his kingpins. When I ask him about this, I don't
just get modesty; I get incomprehension: ``You're saying something
about masculinity or something? Macho? Oh, gee. I have no idea what
you're talking about, but that's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough that Pacino should do such work; he doesn't have to
explain it, too. But perhaps in answering another question, he
already has. At one point, we joke about the mystery of his
vanishing shyness _ he has, after all, just spent several hours
answering questions with ease and forthrightness. Pacino assures me
that his shyness is innate and still there somewhere in the bottom
of his psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he says, ``I think there comes a point where you have
to state who you are. You can't run away, you can't hide, really.
Finally, you just have to say here I am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
