<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3654 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-TIMOR-Q-AND-A-COX     09-07 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-Q-AND-A-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Questions and answers on the East Timor crisis
 &HT;    By Keith Graham and Moni Basu
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Aug. 30, residents of East Timor voted on whether to become
independent from Indonesia. Since then, violence has exploded,
forcing tens of thousands to flee their homes. Here is a quick look
at the territory, the referendum and the crisis that has followed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has caused the crisis?
</P>
<P>
   A: Trouble has been brewing in East Timor for a quarter-century.
Portuguese sailors first reached the island in 1512, and Portugal
long governed it. But in 1975, Portugal abruptly ended its colonial
rule. Indonesia invaded that December and later annexed the
territory, an action never recognized by the United Nations. But
Indonesia has had to fight a separatist insurgency ever since,
resulting in the loss of some 200,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Shouldn't the election have resolved the problem?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not many people expected this process to go smoothly. In the
days before the vote, pro-Indonesia militias carried out violent
attacks in an effort to influence the outcome of the referendum.
After the vote, violence erupted.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What were the results of the vote?
</P>
<P>
   A: Independence was the choice of nearly 79 percent of the
450,000 registered voters. The vote still must be ratified by the
Indonesian Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who are the main participants in the crisis?
</P>
<P>
   A: The long-time leader of rebel, pro-independence forces has
been Jose Alexandre ``Xanana'' Gusmao, who was released from house
arrest this week after being held since 1992. He is widely expected
to be elected president of an independent East Timor. The
anti-independence, pro-Indonesia militias now causing most of the
havoc are believed to have been created with help from the
Indonesian military. Eurico Guterres is one of the most flamboyant
and feared of the militia leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How does the Indonesian government stand on this issue?
</P>
<P>
   A: It says it is trying to quell the violence. To its credit,
the government of President B.J. Habibie did allow the referendum _
giving voters a choice between independence and an autonomous
relationship within Indonesia _ to go forward. But witnesses say
the Indonesian military has been aiding the anti-independence
militias, and Habibie really might not be able to control them.
Many generals reportedly resent the idea of surrendering the
province and fear East Timor's secession will encourage separatists
in other regions of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where is East Timor anyway? Geographically, should it be
considered part of Indonesia?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Indonesia, the world's fourth most populous nation, is an
archipelago in the Indian and Pacific oceans, stretching one/eighth
of the Earth's circumference, according to the Encyclopedia
Britannica. It is composed of about 13,700 islands. Timor is one of
the islands, lying 1,250 miles east of Indonesia's capital,
Jakarta. East Timor, with a population of about 800,000, covers
about 5,600 square miles of the island. The western part of Timor,
like most of Indonesia, was colonized by the Dutch, while the
Portuguese long ruled the east.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Didn't someone from East Timor win a Nobel Peace Prize?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. In 1996, East Timor's Roman Catholic Bishop Carlos
Ximines Belo and exiled independence activist Jose Ramos Horta
jointly won the prize for ``self-sacrificing contributions to a
small but oppressed people.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Wasn't the Carter Center involved in monitoring the election?
</P>
<P>
   A: A 15-person team from the Carter Center was among the
numerous international observers monitoring the election. Former
President Jimmy Carter, who did not go to East Timor, later issued
a statement praising the high turnout and the peaceful conduct of
the election. Carter also has called on the Indonesian government
to maintain order.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Should international peacekeepers intervene?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Clinton administration and several other governments have
urged Indonesia to quell the disorder or invite in outside forces
to keep the peace. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said if the
violence continues ``the international community will have to
consider what other measures it can take.'' Australia and some
other countries have volunteered to send in peacekeepers. But the
Indonesian government has so far been unwilling to accept them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So what happens next?
</P>
<P>
   A: If peace is restored and the Indonesian Parliament ratifies
the independence vote, East Timor still faces a hard road. During
the years of occupation, Indonesia provided the territory's
administration, schools, utilities and police force. East Timor has
few people trained for such tasks. Jose Ramos Horta, the Nobel
winner, has said the United Nations should administer the territory
for a three-year transition period.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Graham and Moni Basu write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
