u a BC-BAPTISTS-COX     09-07 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Political battle brewing over new church leader
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ It's fitting that members of the National Baptist
Convention USA are holding their annual conference this week in an
arena used by a hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty thousands delegates are expected by today, braced for a
punishing political battle as they prepare to elect a new leader
Thursday for one of the nation's largest black church
denominations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect it to be very tense, even more than that, electric,''
said Riggins Earl, a convention member and professor of ethics and
theology at Atlanta's Interdenominational Theological Center.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the tension is due to the organization's tumultuous
history, filled with bitter schisms and rioting delegates. One
member actually died during the 1960 convention after a group of
preachers became angry and traded blows.
</P>
<P>
   This year's session, held in the Ice Palace arena, home of the
National Hockey League's Tampa Bay Lightning, comes with fresh
drama.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the organization's last president, the Rev. Henry
Lyons, resigned and was imprisoned on charges of grand theft,
racketeering, tax evasion and bank fraud.
</P>
<P>
   He was convicted of swindling millions from corporations wanting
to market products to members of his denomination. He also was
found guilty of stealing more than $200,000 donated from the
Anti-Defamation League to help rebuild burned black churches.
</P>
<P>
   Despite pleas of mercy from some convention members, a Florida
judge recently declined to reduce Lyons' 5 1/2-year state sentence,
which he is serving concurrently with a federal sentence of four
years and three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through a nightmare,'' said the Rev. Cameron
Alexander, a member of the convention's transitional committee and
pastor of Antioch Baptist Church North in Atlanta. ``Before, the
Baptist Convention was probably at arm's length with a lot of
Baptists. Now it (the Lyons scandal) has raised the consciousness
of the black pew.''
</P>
<P>
   And many are demanding change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus is going to be on the election of the new president,
and that is very critical to how National Baptists can regain our
credibility,'' said Warren H. Stewart Sr., executive secretary of
the Home Mission Board. ``All of our focus will be on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many candidates claim to be the frontrunner, with so
many in the race _ there are 11 announced candidates, more than
double the 1994 number _ it is hard to determine who is the real
favorite, said the Rev. John Chaplin of Washington, the
convention's vice president at large and chairman of its electoral
commission.
</P>
<P>
   However, three often cited as frontrunners for the five-year
post are the Rev. W. Franklyn Richardson of Mount Vernon, N.Y., a
former NBCUSA general secretary; the Rev. William J. Shaw of
Philadelphia, a former president of the Pennsylvania Baptist State
Convention; and the Rev. E.V. Hill of Los Angeles, a former NBCUSA
vice president, vocal supporter of Lyons and prominent
African-American in predominantly white evangelical circles.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the mood of delegates will decide who will become
the new president. The question, yet to be decided, is do the
majority of delegates want a reformer or someone who answers only
to God.
</P>
<P>
   Earl said many delegates actually prefer an ``imperial'' leader.
A reformer, he said, will have to battle this notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not going to be a cakewalk ... followers have been so
conditioned by an imperialistic personality,'' he said, ``that they
will see democratic leadership as a sign of weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, however, is optimistic about the convention's future.
</P>
<P>
   The National Baptist Convention will eventually rebound from
this year's scandal, he thinks, much as it has moved on from the
stormy politics of its past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The convention is so resourceful,'' Alexander said. ``We
realize that the nightmare is over.''
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
