<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3659 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELTA-PILOTS-COX     09-07 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-PILOTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pilots, airline begin negotiations in hopes of avoiding
nastiness of previous talks
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fasten your seatbelts. What's expected to be a long
and bumpy contract negotiation between Delta Air Lines and its
powerful pilot union gets under way today.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based airline and its only major union exchange
opening proposals on a deal to replace the last contract, signed in
1996. Both sides hope to avoid the kind of meltdown that led to a
strike last year at Northwest Airlines and a sickout at American
Airlines last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's Air Line Pilots Association unit, which represents the
carrier's 9,000 pilots, will seek significant boosts in pay rates
and other contract changes, said Chairman Charles Giambusso.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the Delta pilots to be the best paid, have the best
working conditions and the best benefits,'' said Giambusso, a Salt
Lake City-based Delta captain who became ALPA chairman last year.
</P>
<P>
   He said many pilots feel ``tricked'' by the 1996 deal, which
included 2 percent pay rate cuts at a time when Delta was on the
verge of record profits. The cuts, which were offset by stock
options, were rescinded this year.
</P>
<P>
   Delta spokesman John Kennedy read a brief company statement on
the eve of the talks, which will run for at least several months
and could go longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``As with all employee groups, Delta is committed to an
industry-leading compensation package for pilots commensurate with
top performance and productivity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If recent history is any guide, the gap between the two sides'
opening positions could be yawning.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, in talks over pay rates for the new Boeing
777, Delta offered $239 an hour, which it said is 5 percent above
the highest rate paid by any other carrier flying the plane. ALPA
wanted $319 an hour, based on a calculation of the plane's
productivity. Delta shelved its 777 buying plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Triple 7 fiasco highlights the extreme expectations of the
pilot group and reinforces our expectation that these will be very
difficult negotiations,'' said Samuel Buttrick, veteran airline
analyst at PaineWebber.
</P>
<P>
   Pay won't be the only big issue. ALPA also is expected to seek:
</P>
<P>
   -- New limits on how much flying Delta's regional affiliate
carriers can do on behalf of the airline. Unions view the use of
regional affiliates to augment their schedules as a form of
outsourcing, since pilots at regionals are paid less.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has intensified with regional airlines' burgeoning use
of small jets capable of flying longer routes. Delta's current
contract restricts affiliates to aircraft of 70 seats or less but
imposes no other limits.
</P>
<P>
   -- A voting union seat on Delta's board of directors. ALPA got a
non-voting representative in the 1996 deal. It sought a voting seat
in 1998 as a condition for allowing a domestic marketing alliance
with United Airlines, but Delta rejected the demand and shelved the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   -- Elimination of lower pay scales for newly hired pilots or
those working for Delta Express, a Florida-based low-fare division.
Giambusso said any form of two-tier wage scale is ``illegitimate''
in ALPA's view.
</P>
<P>
   The talks come as Delta's new management team, led by CEO Leo
Mullin, seeks to repair the airline's culture and stave off union
organizing efforts among other workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure there is a culture at Delta right now,'' said
Giambusso. ``It's a business.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the outcome of the pilot talks may not establish one but
added, ``This negotiation has the potential to turn around the
level of dissatisfaction the pilot group has right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Giambusso said relations between ALPA and Delta are ``cordial
and professional,'' but added: ``This management is still finding
its way in how to deal with a pilot union.''
</P>
<P>
   Kit Darby, president of Atlanta pilot career counseling firm AIR
Inc., said the industry's prolonged profit upturn works to ALPA'S
advantage. Delta has logged $2.1 billion in profits in its last two
fiscal years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pilots want their share of the pie and right now the pie
is fully baked,'' he said. ``It's a great time to be negotiating.''
</P>
<P>
   But Darby added the Delta pilots complaints about the 1996 deal
may be overblown. It came after a grueling financial slump, during
which pilot pay rates had risen three times under the previous
six-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, compared to other airlines where the cutbacks were
deeper, their pilots have done pretty well through the '90s,''
Darby said.
</P>
<P>
   Base pay for Delta pilots ranges from $33,400 for a first-year
hire to $209,300 for senior captain, according to Darby's firm.
Despite the 2 percent cuts in the 1996 deal, pilots who advanced to
bigger airplanes or to a higher rank have still received raises.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Delta doled out 10 million stock options to pilots _
about 1,100 each _ in three disbursements under terms of the 1996
contract. Delta's recent stock slide has deflated their value but
analyst Buttrick said the average pilot still will net thousands of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 contract doesn't expire but becomes amendable next May.
Under laws governing airline labor, it will remain in force until
an agreement is reached. Federal mediators would have to declare an
impasse before pilots could strike.
</P>
<P>
   Talks are opening about six months earlier than usual at ALPA's
request.
</P>
<P>
   Giambusso said he hopes that's ``an indicator that the company
may be motivated to get to work and have a deal done by May.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
