<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3663 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WORLD-ACCESS-COX     09-07 1732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-ACCESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CEO rises with long-distance industry
 &HT;    By Michael Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He talks fast, flips through papers on his desk,
whirls in his seat, pats the phone and gestures toward the model
airplanes on the shelf behind him _ one a miniature version of the
Citation Ultra that he owns _ then he nods toward Executive Vice
President Tod Chmar, laughs and then talks some more.
</P>
<P>
   He has reason to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   John D. ``Jack'' Phillips, 56, has, during his 17 years in
telecommunications, seen his own career parallel the business of
the alternative long-distance industry, which has surged from a
tiny footnote to multibillion dollar markets in both the United
States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips has roared through a series of companies starting with
Transcall America and and is now president and chief executive
officer of Atlanta-based World Access Inc., a provider of
long-distance telephone service in overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been on a tear, reporting a series of
acquisitions _ and promising more.
</P>
<P>
   World Access has become one of the largest alternative
long-distance companies in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   With the recently announced purchase of Facilicom International,
World Access will become the largest in a crowd of competitors
angling for the $70 billion-a-year business in international
long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term, the company is positioned so that its largest
shareholder, MCI WorldCom, just might be interested in buying the
whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom, the telecommunications giant headquartered in
Mississippi, is not only a backer, occasional competitor and
sometimes customer to World Access, but is also potentially a
suitor _ if, a few years down the road, World Access has amassed a
global network with the right kind of breadth and clout.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, World Access is on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Stephen Shook of Wachovia Securities recently wrote:
``The international telecom market is highly fragmented, with
significant consolidation expected over the next few years. We
expect (World Access) to capitalize on this trend.''
</P>
<P>
   With Facilicom in the tent, World Access will have annual
revenues of about $1.2 billion as it vies for the rapidly growing
market.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips doesn't want to stop there.
</P>
<P>
   He took the helm in late 1998 after the company he headed,
Resurgens Communications Group, was merged with World Access in a
transaction arranged by MCI WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips began his long, crowded career in telecommunications
when he founded Transcall America in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   His intention was to sell long-distance service at a time when
AT&AMP;T's domination of the market was near total.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Phillips engineered a merger with Advanced
Telecommunications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   About 35 acquisitions followed as ATC grew to about $160 million
in revenue by 1988.
</P>
<P>
   That year, ATC merged with Microtel, a subsidiary of Alltel, to
whom Phillips sold his interest.
</P>
<P>
   The company was later acquired by LDDS.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Phillips was part of a group that took control of
Central Corp., a pay phone company that was then reorganized and
renamed Resurgens Communications Group.
</P>
<P>
   The company grew through a series of purchases, and in 1993, was
merged with Metromedia Communications Corp. and LDDS, which became
WorldCom and later, MCI WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   Now he presides over his growing empire from his office in the
Resurgens building near Lenox Square.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said his company was at one time the only tenant.
</P>
<P>
   When he was searching for a name for a reorganized company, he
hit on using Resurgens _ making it look like the building was named
for the company, rather than the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke with the Atlanta Journal-Constitution there recently
before taking off for his farm in Virginia where he raises horses
and cows.
</P>
<P>
   Q&AMP;A: JACK PHILLIPS
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is it that you could do all you've done and still be
relatively obscure in your hometown?
</P>
<P>
   A: I never did run for ``CEO of the year'' or those type of
things. I never had anybody running the traps (for public
relations) here. Most of my transactions required higher visibility
elsewhere in the world. So I am better known in New York than I am
in this town.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Just what are we going to see in the next few years _ in the
industry and from World Access?
</P>
<P>
   A: The rest of the world has begun to deregulate, so the
situation is like the early '80s in the United States. Like when it
became apparent that AT&AMP;T no longer had the monopoly and other
people could get into it. What I see is an opportunity to
consolidate. To grow the same internally would take longer and cost
a lot more ....
</P>
<P>
   ... But the opportunities _ On my desk right now are (Phillips
flips through a stack of papers) one, two, three, four, five
transactions with companies across the world. We are in
conversations, negotiations, talks about mergers or acquisitions.
Europe, Asia, Australia ... (He pats the stack of papers.) These
five represent maybe $700 million, $800 million, maybe $1 billion
(in deals). The moment that someone looks like a winner, suddenly
everybody else wants to get in. It's happening to us right now ....
</P>
<P>
   ... Within the next 18 months to three years we will exceed $3
billion in revenue, and it will come from consolidation of
companies that exist out there today. The pieces are there. As
companies grow, they can reach a certain level and then stall out.
Everything from $20 million companies to $300 and $400 million
companies _ those are opportunities for us ....
</P>
<P>
   ... It took MCI WorldCom 15 years to become what it is today _ a
$40 billion company. Well, this is going to happen much faster _ at
mach speeds _ because it has already been done in the U.S., so
people know how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the genesis of World Access? It's not very old to
have such big plans.
</P>
<P>
   A: This company, we really started in October of 1997, when
WorldCom (the chief stockholder) asked me to take over. Basically
we had no revenue, and now we have created a company with
approximately $1.2 billion (counting the recently announced
purchase of Facilicom) ....
</P>
<P>
   ... This company in three to five years will be one of the
largest in Georgia. How many are there that have more than $1
billion in business? Not that many. We may not have the historical
heritage that some of them do, but at least one of 'em _ Home Depot
_ didn't exist a few years ago either.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why are you holding on to the equipment business when your
service side is where the growth is?
</P>
<P>
   A: The equipment side is a cash cow. It keeps me from being held
hostage to the whims of the market, if suddenly the service side
has a problem. I can always monetize (the equipment) business and
back up my service play.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the main obstacle to (World Access) success?
</P>
<P>
   A: Execution. Making sure that you have the graybeard talent
in-house. You buy a company _ He's got 500 people, you've got 500
people _ but you don't need 1,000. You have got to be very
decisive, cut what needs to be cut. You have to work the street.
You have to make sure you don't lose the focus of the two
companies. You put together a SWAT team of people to go out and do
due diligence and then help with the integration, too. It takes a
separate group, a group to have day-to-day responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Don't you have problems doing so many acquisitions and
needing to run the businesses as well?
</P>
<P>
   A: Problems? It's like the common cold. You are going to get one
now and then. You have to have picked some key people from the
companies you are buying now and then, too. On Thursday, every
week, we have a (video) conference call. At 11 a.m., we do the
equipment side of the business and at 1 p.m. we do the service
side. Anywhere you are in the world, you phone in.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But what is your management style?
</P>
<P>
   A: It takes an old warlord like me, and he (cocking his chin
toward Executive Vice President Tod Chmar) is my pacifist. I'm the
old sumbitch. You've got to love 'em, and you've got to kick 'em,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How fast is consolidation happening? Isn't alternate
long-distance still pretty fragmented?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are 400 companies operating (in alternate
long-distance) just in Europe. Those are the opportunities. It has
all grown so fast. Telecom was a sleepy business that your
grandmother invested in, and now there are multibillion-dollar
companies being founded overnight. Just look at Global Crossing.
</P>
<P>
   There will be _ in the next three to five years _ maybe
half-a-dozen multibillion international long-distance companies. We
are going to lead that effort. And with that last transaction
(Facilicom), we are the largest of the wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   The international long-distance business is a $70 billion-a-year
business and it is growing 15 per year. But it is Pac-Man. There
are predators out there. As soon as someone has enough presence,
enough base, enough infrastructure, all of a sudden they look
strategic to someone else. It's the food chain.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But what gives World Access any advantage?
</P>
<P>
   A: No company has a deeper pool of graybeard, been there, done
that, got the T-shirt mentality and knows how to run a telecom
company better than we do. I know how to consolidate companies, and
I run 'em until they become significant enough to sell 'em to
somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you run a global business from Atlanta?
</P>
<P>
   A: I do it with faxes. I use this (pats the phone). I have my
plane when I need to go somewhere _ use it about 350 or 400 hours a
year. That plane shrinks the world, like the telephone shrinks the
world. But I have worked all over the world, and the hardest thing
for me is to put on a necktie. I can sit here and look at the
Atlanta skyline, and I pick up the phone and call the U.K. or
Russia, and I am efficient.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you comfortable with the pace of change, the path you are
on ... ?
</P>
<P>
   A: You either change with it or it changes you. And eventually
everything will be merged and bought into about a half-dozen
mega-mega companies. How long? Three years, maybe five. That is
all. The technology is here. It's affordable, so everybody in the
world can afford television, cable and telephone. It is coming.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
