<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3665 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VIACOM-AD-COLUMN-985&AMP;     09-07 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIACOM-AD-COLUMN-985&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: A BEHEMOTH CASTS ITS SHADOW ON MADISON AVE. 
</HEADLINE>
  (With VIACOM-CBS) 
(mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Reaction Tuesday along Madison Avenue to the news of
the blockbuster deal that will bring together under a single
ownership many powerful media brands _ among them CBS, MTV, The
Nashville Network, Nickelodeon, Paramount, Simon &AMP; Schuster, VH1
and, well, Blockbuster _ ranged from outrage to outright
acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal call for CBS Corp. to be acquired by Viacom
Inc. in what would be the largest media takeover ever. By one
calculation, the combined advertising revenue of the behemoth
merged company, encompassing properties across the television,
radio and outdoor media, would be close to $11 billion for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of revenue from national TV networks, the merged
entity, which will go by the Viacom name, would be ranked first,
according to Joe Mandese, editor of The Myers Report, a media
newsletter. The broadcast and cable networks to be controlled by
the new Viacom have national revenue of $5.5 billion, he estimated,
ahead of Walt Disney Co., owner of networks like ABC and ESPN, at
$4.9 billion, and the NBC unit of General Electric Co., at $4.8
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not good for advertisers in terms of negotiating
clout,'' Mandese observed, ``because of the control of assets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``CBS already has a stranglehold on the radio marketplace,'' he
added, referring to its Infinity Broadcasting Corp. division. ``The
new Viacom will own more local TV stations than any other entity as
well as cable networks popular with kids, teens and young adults
and CBS, the leader in household viewers among the broadcast
networks.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, consolidation has been a constant in the media world
for the last decade, as evidenced by the creation of giants like
Time Warner Inc. It was a previous owner of Paramount, Gulf &AMP;
Western, that inspired the comedian Mel Brooks to mock the media
mega-merger trend with the derisive sobriquet Engulf &AMP; Devour.
</P>
<P>
   But to some leading agency executives, the continuing
concentration of the strongest media brands in fewer and fewer
hands is no laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of CBS by Viacom is ``obscene,'' said Jean Pool,
executive vice president and director for North American media
services at J. Walter Thompson in New York, part of WPP Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an incredible amount of power being concentrated in
one person's hands,'' she added. ``It's a bad idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Her reference was to Mel Karmazin, the longtime radio industry
maven who rose to become chief executive of CBS, engineering
expansion moves that included the purchase of Outdoor Systems, the
out-of-home advertising powerhouse. While Sumner Redstone will
remain chairman and chief executive of Viacom, Karmazin will become
president and chief operating officer of the merged company, with
all operating units reporting to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's getting such control, you can't buy around him,'' Ms.
Pool said of Karmazin. ``It's unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the media policy council of the American
Association of Advertising Agencies, the trade association, Ms.
Pool has been outspoken on the subject of consolidation in the
realm of radio. In some cities, CBS controls as much of 50 percent
of ad revenue in the market by owning multiple stations with
various programming formats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Concentration of station ownership in individual markets
drives media buyers nuts,'' said John Kamp, a Washington-based
senior vice president of the agency association, known as the Four
A's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will work with the Justice Department and the Federal
Communications Commission to make sure those agencies do what they
are supposed to do,'' he added, in terms of scrutinizing media
mergers.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS-Viacom deal ``is just the first you'll see in the next
couple days,'' Kamp predicted, as media companies rush to take
advantage of a recent liberalization of rules intended to limit
concentration of ownership of TV stations in local markets.
</P>
<P>
   That forecast was also forthcoming from several agency
executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you ask, `What else could happen?' something
does,'' said Jon Mandel, co-managing director of Mediacom in New
York, the media services unit of Grey Advertising Inc. He too said
he expected more mergers that would bring under one roof disparate
media properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a company, Viacom can now compete for any budget in just
about any medium for just about any demographic group,'' Mandel
said, ``from the 2-year-olds who watch Nickelodeon to the
90-year-olds who watch `Touched by an Angel' on CBS.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``it will be difficult to offer `cross-platform' deals''
that span the variegated Viacom properties, he added, because ``how
many brands want to go from two to 90?''
</P>
<P>
   ``To steal a quote from Jon Nesvig,'' Mandel said, referring to
the top sales executive at the Fox Broadcasting Co. unit of News
Corp., ```Rupert Murdoch thinks if I sell you everything, I can
charge you more, and you think if you buy everything, you can pay
less.'''
</P>
<P>
   That issue was on the minds of others apart from Mandel.
</P>
<P>
   ``History says that cross-selling has almost never worked,''
said Alan Gottesman, managing director at West End
Communications/Consulting in New York, because ``the customer is
under no compulsion to use the medium'' that is being offered in
tandem with sibling media by huge conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, what tends to ``drive up rates is that the smarter,
stronger media companies tend to do whatever it takes to make their
properties more attractive to consumers, which tends to make them
work harder for advertisers,'' he added. ``So if they cost more,
they cost more.''
</P>
<P>
   Alec Gerster, chairman at Mediacom and another member of the
Media Policy Council of the Four A's, said: ``The challenge for
merged companies is to rationalize their collections of assets. And
for all the combinations and cross-marketing, each individual
property still has competitors, so we can still play people off one
against the other.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bill Konigsberg, president and chief executive at Horizon Media
Inc. in New York, a leading independent media services agency, said
that cross-promotion may be as important an aspect of the deal as
cross-selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``If CBS wants to target the 18-to-49-year-old,'' Konigsberg
said, referring to the viewer most preferred by marketers, ``there
are tremendous vehicles to promote new shows via the Viacom cable
properties: Nickelodeon, MTV, VH1.''
</P>
<P>
   Most CBS fare currently appeals to older consumers, requiring
the network to prospect elsewhere for younger viewers for
youth-oriented programs like coverage of the Grammy Awards or the
Miss Teen USA pageant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The keys for any great brand are great distribution, an
ability to sell the product and an ability to promote and market
the product,'' Konigsberg said. ``Now they'll have it all.''
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite end of the spectrum from Ms. Pool was Jim
Dougherty, the analyst at Prudential Securities in New York who
follows the agency industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean to sound flip, but my answer to questions about
the merger is `So what?''' Dougherty said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been convinced it makes a lot of difference who
owns the media,'' he added. ``What sets prices is not how many
properties are united under one corporate banner but supply and
demand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
