<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3672 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FILM-NEWSEASON-MCKEE-     09-07 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NEWSEASON-MCKEE-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: BRITAIN)  
 GINA MCKEE TAKES THE ROAD TO STARDOM, QUIETLY AND CAREFULLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Sept. 12)  
(DW) 
 By MATT WOLF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Gina McKee played Bella, Hugh Grant's disabled friend,
in the recent hit ``Notting Hill,'' so it seems appropriate that a
movie obsessed with stardom should find Ms. McKee well on the road
to it herself. It helps, of course, to possess Ms. McKee's
singular, decidedly unglamorous beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Even rarer is the quiet integrity of her performance as Bella,
which commands attention without relying on histrionics or bathos.
``It's there without comment,'' Roger Michell, the film's director,
said of Bella's confinement to a wheelchair. As Ms. McKee plays the
role, her director said, ``she's no martyr to her disability.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Winterbottom, director of Ms. McKee's forthcoming film,
``Wonderland,'' spoke in turn of her compellingly transparent
presence. ``She seems quite still, quite retiring,'' he said.
``Once you become absorbed by her, you're able to project your
hopes and emotions onto her; she makes you feel for her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderland'' and ``Women Talking Dirty,'' due in the coming
months, should find Ms. McKee, at 35, confronting her own increased
celebrity. A charming conversationalist who draws a firm if polite
veil around matters not pertaining to her job, Ms. McKee, one
senses, is in it for the work, not the trappings _ interviews
included. ``When I first started, I used to think, `Well, why do
you want to know?''' Ms. McKee said of the interview process,
speaking over tea one brisk morning at the top of Hampstead Heath,
a short drive away from the Crouch End home in north London that
Ms. McKee and her husband share.) ``I suppose it's because I come
from an environment where you didn't really examine what you
thought and did; you just sort of moved on.''
</P>
<P>
   That's precisely what Ms. McKee has done, moving on from her
working-class roots in County Durham, northeast England, to the
relatively classless community of British actors. At 18, she
followed her brother to London and began taking the requisite
courses to hone her craft. Ask her if the move felt brave, and she
deflects the implicit compliment: ``It felt absolutely right; I was
impatient for it to happen.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Ms. McKee won a best-actress Bafta award, the British
equivalent of the Emmy, for playing Mary Cox, the downtrodden
housewife who is elected to Parliament in the nine-part BBC drama
series ``Our Friends in the North.'' Among the admirers of her
performance was Michell, who saw Ms. McKee at the very start of
casting ``Notting Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a quality of unaffected goodness which is pleasantly
un-nauseating,'' said Michell. ``In real life, she's the reverse of
the slightly saintly presence she can have on screen; she's bubbly
and mischievous.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to ``Notting Hill,'' ``Wonderland'' and ``Women
Talking Dirty'' grant the actress the leads. In ``Wonderland,''
Michael Winterbottom's odyssey through a London far from the chic
capital of ``Notting Hill,'' Ms. McKee plays Nadia, a cafe worker
whose nascent compassion breaks through the bleak circumstances of
what seems, at first glance, a loveless life. ``Women Talking
Dirty'' casts Ms. McKee and Helena Bonham Carter as two Scotswomen
whose friendship is dramatically tested over time. (Both movies
will be shown at this month's Toronto Film Festival.)
</P>
<P>
   Coky Giedroyc, the director of ``Women Talking Dirty,'' said Ms.
McKee was ``not frantic to please like so many, particularly
younger actresses are. You just felt that she would wrap her arms
around a part, that it would feel safe with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McKee is now wrapping her arms around the next phase of her
career, having recently done the Los Angeles rounds for the first
time and acquired American agents in the process. ``I literally
stepped off the plane and was recognized instantly,'' Ms. McKee
said of her time on the West Coast. ``Everyone was terribly
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Ms. McKee, about a profession whose growing respect for
her she is keen to repay. ``I really love acting,'' said Ms. McKee,
``even if what I'm doing is the most difficult thing to portray.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
