<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3674 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-TV-REAL-SPI &LR;      09-07 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GET REAL' WOULD WORK A LOT BETTER IF IT TRIED TO BE LESS
SELF-AWARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early in Wednesday night's premiere of ``Get Real'' on Fox,
Meghan Green, the eldest of the three Green children, says to the
audience, ``I know what you're thinking: This is another one of
those smart-ass shows where the kids talk to the audience like on
`Dawson's Creek,' which, actually, come to think of it, I'm not
even sure does voiceovers. See, personally, I wouldn't be caught
dead watching it because there's nothing more obnoxious than
self-aware teens who know more about life's great mysteries than
their parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, after we've gotten to know every shade of Green
imaginable, Meghan says: ``You want everything tied up in a bow? Go
watch `7th Heaven.'''
</P>
<P>
   Since The WB network spends none of its ad budget on the rival
Fox network, The WB's executives are probably delighted to have two
of their series plugged by the competition, even if they are being
body slammed. As they say in show biz, bad publicity is better than
no publicity at all.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, ``Get Real'' is more like Fox's own ``Ally McBeal,''
with lots of fantasy/dream sequences, extreme close-ups and clever
lines that are supposed to make us sit up and pay attention. For
example, here's another one from the ever-quotable Meghan, talking
about her mom and her younger brother, Cameron: ``It's not easy
being the mother of a sexually active teenager, especially when
he's the only one in the house who's getting any.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's this little exchange between Cameron, the
promiscuous one, and a bimbo who's having an affair with the best
friend of Cameron's dad:
</P>
<P>
   Cameron: ``You have excellent breasts.''
</P>
<P>
   Bimbo: ``Thanks. They were a gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Which prompts Meghan to whisper to her mother: ``My God! You
could hide Ann Frank in that cleavage!''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so some precocious TV teens know less about life's mysteries
and more about where to find a quipmonger. If the producers of
``Get Real'' are hoping their dissing of the heightened reality in
``Dawson's Creek'' and the cloying sweetness of ``7th Heaven''
makes their show the de facto authentic portrayal of the American
family, then they're as confused as Mary Green.
</P>
<P>
   Mary is the nonplused mother of 17-year-old Meghan, 16-year-old
Cameron and 15-year-old Kenny; the frustrated wife of Mitch, and
the insecure daughter of Elizabeth. Mom, Dad, kids and Grandma all
live together in a lovely house with a renovation contractor who
frequently helps himself to breakfast. While open warfare hasn't
broken out, let's just say the lines of communication are
experiencing technical difficulty. Cameron (Eric Christian Olsen)
is having sex in his bedroom. Meghan (Anne Hathaway) is rebelling.
Kenny (Jesse Eisenberg) is getting beaten up at school. Mitch (Jon
Tenney) isn't paying attention. And Mary (Debrah Farentino) is
having a hard time dealing with any of it. (Grandma Elizabeth,
played by Christina Pickles, is the only one not likely to get an
ulcer.)
</P>
<P>
   It's Farentino's best performance since ``EZ Streets.'' And the
kids, especially Hathaway and Eisenberg, are refreshingly honest.
But if ``Get Real'' really wants to look real, it's going to have
to try to be less self-aware.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, another Fox series, ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' which
isn't scheduled to debut until January, is essentially the same
show in a half-hour format _ and far more real.
</P>
<P>
   Get Real. Hourlong comedy/drama about a family struggling to
stay functional. Starring Debrah Farentino, Jon Tenney, Jesse
Eisenberg, Anne Hathaway, Eric Christian Olsen and Christina
Pickles. Series premiere Wednesday night on Fox. Parental guideline
rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
