<HEADER>
A3676 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TIMOR-VIOLENCE-BOS &LR;      09-07 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN CONSIDERS PEACEKEEPING ROLE AS EAST TIMOR VIOLENCE SURGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ With the capital city ablaze and gunfire shattering
the night, systematic violence escalated in the disputed territory
of East Timor Tuesday despite Indonesia's announcement that it had
imposed martial law.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the movement seeking independence for the region,
along with a Catholic bishop who is a Nobel Peace Prize winner,
begged the international community to send in peacekeeping forces
to restore order despite continued opposition by Indonesia, which
annexed East Timor 23 years ago and insisted Tuesday it could
maintain control.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian authorities said they had ordered soldiers to shoot
on sight anyone violating an unspecified curfew. But a week after
79 percent of the people of East Timor voted in favor of
independence from Indonesia, rogue elements of the military
appeared to be intensifying a campaign to destroy the region's
infrastructure and forcibly relocate its people.
</P>
<P>
   The UN Security Council said it would make no decision on a
peacekeeping force until it heard from five UN ambassadors sent to
Jakarta last weekend to persuade Indonesia either to control the
violence or invite in foreign peacekeepers. Once authorized, forces
from volunteer nations could be deployed within 72 hours, said UN
spokesman Fred Eckhard.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has told Australian and United Nations
officials that it is ready to commit troops to a peacekeeping
force, a Clinton administration official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very quietly, we said we would assist them if the
international community wants to move,'' said the US official.
``Australia would probably be the lead country, and we told them we
could possibly throw in with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The official said while exact numbers of US troops haven't been
decided, the most likely ground troops to participate would come
from the Okinawa island base. The official said US aircraft would
be available from central Japan. A second option for ground troops
would be a small US army division in Hawaii, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This situation is going to be very tricky,'' the official
said. Indonesian President B.J. ``Habibie is in a really shaky
position, . . . and there's concern now that this could lead to
much greater destabilization in Indonesia if the violence in East
Timor continues to erupt.''
</P>
<P>
   Australia offered to lead a peacekeeping force and contribute
2,000 to 4,000 soldiers. Portugal, France and Britain also said
they would support a UN force, but no one seemed willing yet to
deploy troops against the wishes of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses in Dili, the capital of the disputed island territory,
said armed men believed to be linked to the military torched the
university, the court house, and telecommunications facilities.
Soldiers marched thousands of East Timorese to Dili's docks, firing
shots over their heads and forcing them to board ships leaving the
province, the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know what the difference is'' under martial
law, said a UN official interviewed by telephone from Dili, who
spoke on condition of anonymity. The military was ``in control
before, and they are in control now.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian military commander General Wiranto again rejected
calls for an outside force, saying, ``We have all the capability to
handle the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats were increasingly skeptical, however, and some likened
the deployment of more Indonesian troops to sending foxes to guard
the chicken coop. Wiranto's inability to curb the violence, they
said, hinted at a split within the military and a campaign by rogue
elements to overturn the vote _ or to cripple East Timor to the
point where independence would be irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   As the international community considered its response and gave
Indonesia 48 hours to stop the violence, a quarter to a third of
East Timor's population of 870,000 was fleeing or being forced out
of the territory, said a UN spokesman in Dili.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees poured into the neighboring province of West Timor at a
rate of 1,000 per hour on Monday, the International Committee of
the Red Cross said. Reports of mass killings surfaced repeatedly
but could not be verified.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from New York, Nobel Peace Prize winner and resistance
leader Jose Ramos Horta accused gunmen associated with the military
of ``a Serbian-style emptying of villages.'' He said an Indonesian
source told him, ``One day when you come back to your country, it
will be a country of widows.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wiranto is getting ignored'' by the military's special forces
branch, Kopassus, which is led by rival generals, Ramos Horta
asserted. ``If the US does not intervene forcefully, there is going
to be a major humanitarian catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   The Australian Navy said Tuesday it dispatched a catamaran
carrying an estimated 100 troops into international waters off East
Timor, 400 miles north of Australia, to evacuate Australian
nationals if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian police, meanwhile, fired automatic weapons at the
United Nations office in the eastern town of Baucau, UN officials
said. The Associated Press said 200 UN workers and 2,500 East
Timorese were trapped inside.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 UN staff and aid workers, as well as the
territory's spiritual leader, Roman Catholic Bishop Carlos Ximenes
Belo, were airlifted out of Baucau to Darwin, Australia Tuesday,
but a UN spokeswoman said the gunmen prevented any UN workers who
were East Timorese natives from boarding the flight.
</P>
<P>
   Belo, who shared the 1996 Nobel Peace Prize with Ramos Horta,
said he would fly to Rome to meet with Pope John Paul II. ``Now,
more than ever, we need an international peace force,'' Belo said.
</P>
<P>
   Belo's home was shot up Monday and thousands of people who had
sought shelter there were herded away. Sources said the home of
Baucau Bishop Basilio de Nascimento was burned Tuesday, but the
report could not be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   A UN official interviewed by telephone from Dili said all eight
regional UN offices had been forced to close, and 300 international
UN staff, of an original 1,200, remain. They were hunkered down
with 1,500 East Timorese refugees and a handful of journalists in
the UN headquarters in Dili, where electricity and telephones were
cut off.
</P>
<P>
   In Jakarta, Indonesia freed East Timorese rebel leader Jose
Alexandre ``Xanana'' Gusmao Tuesday after seven years of a 20-year
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promise as a free man I will do everything to bring peace to
East Timor and its people,'' said a beaming Gusmao, 53, a former
priest, poet and guerrilla considered the likely first president of
an independent East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a suit and tie instead of his customary guerrilla
fatigues, Gusmao moved temporarily to the British Embassy in
Jakarta, rather than return to Dili and almost certain death while
anti-independence gunmen are in control.
</P>
<P>
   One pro-Indonesia militia leader Herminio da Silva Costa,
speaking from the West Timor capital of Kupang, told Reuters news
service, ``We will burn (East Timor) down and start all over again
. . . we are ready to go the jungles for 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Donnelly of the Globe staff contributed to this report from
Washington.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3678 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WACO08-COX     09-07 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RENO ASKS DANFORTH TO HEAD WACO PROBE
 &HT;    550&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART and JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno has asked retired
Republican Sen. John Danforth _ an Episcopal priest and former
attorney general of Missouri _ to investigate FBI actions during
and after the 1993 assault on the Branch Davidian compound near
Waco, Texas, a Justice Department official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stressing that the job offer was informal and ``no final deal
has been reached,'' the official said details of the scope of the
independent probe are still being worked out, but that the
appointment could be announced within the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has recently talked to several potential investigators and,
for now at least, Danforth ``has emerged as the guy,'' said the
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Reno promised an outside investigation after new evidence
emerged that FBI agents fired pyrotechnic tear gas grenades as it
ended a 51-day siege of the religious sect. For six years, federal
officials had denied that the military-issue canisters were used in
the April 19, 1993, assault that ended in deaths of Branch Davidian
leader David Koresh and 75 of his followers, including 21 children.
</P>
<P>
   As Danforth emerged as a top candidate for the job, many
commentators have said he could bring credibility to a case fraught
with religious and ideological suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, 63, was regarded as politically independent during his
three terms in the Senate. After serving for two years as
co-chairman of the Bipartisan Commission on Entitlement and Tax
Reform, he left the Senate after the 1994 election.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his reputation as a non-partisan moderate, Danforth was
a central figure in one of the Senate's most bitter political and
ideological partisan battles of the decade _ the confirmation of
Clarence Thomas to the Supreme Court. A longtime personal friend of
Thomas, Danforth served as the nominee's principal sponsor during
the televised hearings before the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Danforth could quiet Republican calls for
congressional hearings into the Waco incident.
</P>
<P>
   But that would be a mistake, said Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., a member
of the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``An inquiry run by the Department of Justice _ no matter who is
named to head it _ is not substitute for public hearings before
Congress,'' said Barr.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had suggested Atlanta attorney Griffin Bell for the
job, Barr said he has ``no problem'' with Danforth heading the
outside probe. But Barr stressed that Congress must also act.
</P>
<P>
   Any investigation ``conducted predominantly behind closed
doors'' would not ``assure the American public the truth is being
told about Waco,'' said Barr. ``In fact, it would have the opposite
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   In announcing her search for an outside investigator last week
amid Republican calls for her resignation, Reno said she was
looking for someone who ``has no conflicts, would be well-received
and has the time to handle the task in an appropriate manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Danforth would appear to fit the bill. Before entering the
Senate, he was attorney general in Missouri for eight years before
entering the Senate. Upon leaving Capitol Hill, he returned to St.
Louis and has practiced law and served as chairman of St. Louis
2004, a regional revitalization project.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In another development in the Waco case, a former CIA official
has sought congressional protection from alleged government
intimidation as a whistle-blower.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Cullen, who publicly charged that secret Army Delta Force
personnel were present during the assault on the Davidian compound,
has appealed for assistance from Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, who
chairs the Senate Judiciary subcommittee that oversees the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Grassley has not decided whether to take Mr. Cullen
under his wing, but he has agreed to talk to him,'' said the
senator's press secretary, Jill Kozeny. ``If his story is credible
and if he's being pressured for any reason that's improper, then
Senator Grassley would work to protect him.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator has a history of defending whistle-blowers. However,
Cullen would need a vote of the full Judiciary Committee to be
granted immunity from charges of breaking his secrecy agreement
with the CIA.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Dallas Morning News last month, Cullen
said he had worked with three members of the Delta Force who gave
detailed descriptions of their role in the tear-gas assault on the
Davidians. A direct military role would be in conflict with federal
law forbidding U.S. troops to participate in civilian law
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
