<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DONTASK-EDITORIAL-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDITORIAL: Refined gay policy is not enough
 &HT;    (EDS: CORRECTS to reflect Atlanta Constitution in tagline.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pentagon's recent refinement of its ``don't-ask,
don't-tell'' policy regarding homosexuals in uniform is the
equivalent of slapping paint on an old wreck of a house. In neither
case does the prettifying hide the basic unsoundness within.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-year-old policy, an ill-conceived compromise between
President Clinton and Congress, was intended to put a stop to the
harassment of gays and lesbians in the armed forces so long as they
kept quiet about their sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that policy's basic premise is that homosexuals, by their
very nature, are inimical to good order and cohesion within the
services. That is tantamount to condemning a segment of Americans
as outcasts unfit to defend their country, without proof or due
process.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, the ``don't ask'' portion of the policy isn't
being observed at all. Judging from the rising number of complaints
about the pursuit and harassment of suspected gays and lesbians in
the services, persecution may be even worse than it was before the
policy went into effect. It is especially galling to learn that,
more often than not, service personnel who report anti-gay abuse
are themselves targeted for investigation and dismissal, while
those who perpetrated the abuse go unpunished.
</P>
<P>
   Though still short of the mark, two of the new policy changes
should curb this kind of maltreatment _ that is, if the Pentagon
proves serious in carrying them out.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to subject all investigations of suspected
homosexuals to top-level review should minimize low-level witch
hunts. And inculcating strict no-harassment guidelines from boot
camp onward ought to reduce the incidence of gay-bashing within the
services. One such outrage was the ordeal of Army Pfc. Barry
Winchell, who was badgered for days on end and eventually
bludgeoned to death in July in his barracks at Fort Campbell, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Paranoia over the presence of gays within the armed services
certainly seems misplaced. Considering the nature of recent
military sex scandals, it appears that heterosexuals are a far more
common threat to good discipline and cohesion than homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon brass ought to find these embarrassing escapades
instructive. What should matter in a properly functioning military
organization _ and what should be covered by its regulations _ is
the conduct of individuals, not their sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   This editorial originally ran in The Atlanta Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
