A3680 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-FAA-EDITORIAL-COX     09-07 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAA-EDITORIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Air travel at low point
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For frequent flyers, this has been one long, hot summer.
</P>
<P>
   Delays have been more numerous and of greater duration than
ever. Once aloft, overcrowded airplanes feel more like a Calcutta
transit bus than the airline experience of now-fading memory.
</P>
<P>
   It's not your imagination: The Federal Aviation Administration
reports that delays through August were up 20 percent over the same
period last year. July was particularly brutal for air travelers,
who saw a 70 percent increase in delays over July 1998. (Any flight
more than 15 minutes late is considered delayed.)
</P>
<P>
   The airlines have blamed the mess on the FAA and its management
of the air traffic control system. The FAA, until last week,
staunchly defended its creaking system and instead blamed the
weather.
</P>
<P>
   Weather is, indeed, behind about 75 percent of the delays. But a
Sept. 1 report from the FAA indicates that the agency itself is
behind a large share of the remainder.
</P>
<P>
   The study of 34 air traffic control operations, done in
conjunction with the airlines, cites a number of factors, including
poor communication between regional control centers and the
agency's national command center in Herndon, Va.; plans to avoid
severe weather that were too slow to be implemented and poorly
coordinated; controllers who space planes dozens of miles apart not
for safety reasons, but for their own convenience.
</P>
<P>
   The report is an eye-opener, making plain the true miracle of
modern aviation: Given antiquated technology and the continued
adherence to a 1960s route structure designed for far less traffic,
it's a wonder the system can handle its 56,000 daily flights at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it,'' Delta CEO Leo Mullin says bluntly. ``The
aviation system right now ain't working.''
</P>
<P>
   But the airlines aren't by any means blameless for the passenger
discontent. The major carriers continue to deliberately overbook
flights, knowing some passengers will get bumped and that those who
do fly will be cramped. They still cancel flights with little
notice when flights are underbooked. Meals these days come not on
warm plates but in cold paper bags not unlike those dispensed for
less savory purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA can and should work to increase dramatically the
efficiency of air-traffic management. FAA Administrator Jane Garvey
took a step in that direction last month by shifting authority from
regional centers, which sometimes caused nationwide backups by
focusing too narrowly on their own sectors, to the national center.
But more dramatic action is needed, including a complete rethinking
of traffic management that will allow airlines to take advantage of
new technology making it possible for pilots to choose their own
fastest, safest route under FAA guidance.
</P>
<P>
   The American public also must acknowledge the role played by its
own, often unrealistic, expectations for air service. We want it
safe, but we want it fast. We want it cheap, but we want the
roominess of half-empty planes. We not only want the right to
carry-on steamer trunks, we also expect seats to swell in concert
with our expanding posteriors. (A recent New York Times piece
suggests that coach seats on the large jets are, in fact, a tad
wider now than in years past.)
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that air passengers and Congress should not
continue to press the FAA and airlines for the greatest, most
customer-friendly efficiency possible. But sooner or later _ and
more likely, sooner _ we'll have to come to grips with the fact
that as long as the economy is good and air fares relatively cheap,
air-traffic jams and crowded seating will be a permanent fact of
life.
</P>
<P>
   This editorial originally appeared in The Atlanta Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
