<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-HARASS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND FORD SETTLE HARASSMENT CASE
</HEADLINE>
  (With FORD-DOCUMENTS) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Ford Motor Co. reached a settlement on Tuesday
with the U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, agreeing to
pay nearly $8 million in damages to as many as 900 women who
complained of racial and sexual harassment at two Ford factories.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement is the largest the commission has reached with an
automaker based in the United States and the fourth largest in the
commission's history. It also calls for 30 percent of the
supervisory positions at the plants, which are in Chicago and
Chicago Heights, to be held by women within the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   The commission began an investigation based on harassment
complaints by 19 black, white and Hispanic women at the two plants.
The women said they had been subjected to a hostile work
environment, including obscene graffiti, verbal and physical
harassment by fellow employees and retaliation against women who
reported such conduct. The complaints dated back to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's agreement calls for Ford to set up a $7.5-million
fund, which will pay damages to settle complaints by up to 900
women. In addition, Ford has pledged $10 million to further train
its employees nationwide on preventing job discrimination and
harassment. Two of the original 19 women whose complaints prompted
the investigation have agreed to the settlement and will split an
additional $250,000. The other 17 rejected the deal, saying they
intend to sue the automaker.
</P>
<P>
   James J. Padilla, Ford's group vice president for manufacturing,
said, ``This agreement further strengthens Ford's longstanding
policy of zero tolerance and will help move us toward our goal of
zero occurrence of harassment of any kind in our facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Ida L. Castro, chairman of the commission, said the agreement
``will not only better the lives of the female employees at Ford,
but will also serve as a model to employers nationwide who are
committed to providing harassment-free environments to their
workers.''
</P>
<P>
   A three-member panel will oversee the agreement. The panel,
consisting of one Ford appointee, one commission appointee and a
member chosen by the first two appointees, will award damages to
women who file claims.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is the second major harassment case that the
commission has settled with automakers in two years. Last year, the
Mitsubishi Motor Corp.'s American subsidiary agreed to pay $34
million to workers in Chicago, the largest such settlement with the
commission.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At a news conference announcing the settlement, Padilla was
confronted by one of the women who had complained of harassment. He
responded, ``Certainly to the extent that any one of our employees
has felt an environment that treated them with less than full
dignity, we apologize.''
</P>
</TEXT>
