u f BC-VICAOM-CBS-BOS &LR;      09-07 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICAOM-CBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIACOM-CBS UNION CREATES WORLD-CLASS MEDIA PRESENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest media marriage in history Tuesday brought together
Viacom Inc. and CBS in a $37.7 billion merger that creates a new
global conglomerate with a vast presence in television, movies,
radio, books, and billboards.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling a sweeping consolidation in ownership of the production
of entertainment and news, Viacom, founded by Newton, Mass. native
Sumner M. Redstone, will join Time Warner, Disney-ABC, and Rupert
Murdoch's empire as a top-ranking world media titan.
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust rules may force Viacom to unload an undetermined
number of television stations, and perhaps its 50 percent stake in
the UPN network.
</P>
<P>
   But CBS and Viacom officials were bullish the merger will go
through early next year. They said they will be in Washington
Wednesday to lobby federal regulators to ease rules that would
require divestment of TV stations and UPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will create an $80 billion giant,'' Redstone told reporters
at a New York news conference Tuesday, calling the combination ``a
momentous occasion in the life of the media industry.''
</P>
<P>
   In Viacom's Paramount unit, CBS will get a major TV and film
studio to create shows for broadcast. The combined company will
also have multiple outlets _ billboards, radio, and television
stations _ to cross-promote offerings that brought in combined
revenues of $21 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, CBS shareholders will get 108.5 shares
of Viacom class B stock for every 100 shares they own. Redstone
will be chairman and chief executive and control a majority of
voting stock, with current CBS chief executive Mel Karmazin chief
operating officer and heir apparent when Redstone, 76, retires.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street reacted enthusiastically. CBS shares rose 1 3/4 to
50 11/16 in New York Stock Exchange trading, while Viacom's Class B
shares jumped 1 7/8 to 46 15/16. At that price the deal is worth
$50.93 a share for CBS shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just slapping two big companies together to make a
bigger company _ they complement each other very well,'' said Bruce
Leichtman, an analyst with The Yankee Group in Boston. ``CBS really
missed the boat on cable, and Viacom has a strong presence there,''
Leichtman said, while the CBS network provides wider outlets for
the entertainment content Viacom creates.
</P>
<P>
   The move represents a reunion of sorts. Federal regulators
forced CBS to divest its Viacom stake in 1971 when it was a
television syndication company, ruling it was illegal for a
broadcast network to control reruns. Viacom's roots go back 90
years to a small chain of drive-ins and cinemas founded by
Redstone's father; Sumner Redstone bought Viacom in 1987 for $2.3
billion and began building it into a multifaceted media juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   One trigger for the Viacom-CBS deal was the recent announcement
by the Federal Communications Commission that it would relax rules
that have forbidden a single company from owning more than one
television station in a market.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company would have two stations in six markets and
at least one station in 18 of the top 20 US TV markets, Karmazin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, however, their viewership totals about 41 percent of
American television watchers, 6 percent above the FCC limit. Also,
FCC rules forbid a company from owning two TV networks, although
there may be some wiggle room for Viacom to assert that UPN is not
a true network and thus should be exempted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have for a long time said those (FCC) rules are outdated,''
Karmazin said. ``It's almost like like having black-and-white rules
in a color environment. Those rules need to be modified.'' FCC
officials made no comment other than a standard promise to review
the merger carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin would not say where the company might look to sell off
stations to get below the 35 percent cap, but said, ``Obviously, we
like bigger markets better than smaller markets. The population is
there, the advertising is there _ we want to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin, the hard-nosed former radio executive who brought CBS
back to top ratings last year, approached Redstone two weeks ago to
discuss a merger of their television stations as a result of the
proposed FCC ownership rule change.
</P>
<P>
   From there, talks took off. ``He seduced us,'' Redstone said of
Karmazin. ``I was originally a little bit skeptical, but as I heard
and began to see . . . this guy is the master salesman.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men emphasized that their companies were strong enough that
they did not need to merge, but they saw huge possibilities in
combining. ``This was a deal I wanted to make I think from the time
I was bar mitzvahed,'' Karmazin said.
</P>
<P>
   Redstone, who has been in the process of unloading assets to
improve Viacom's balance sheet, including its stake in the
6,000-store Blockbuster video-rental chain, said the new company
would have the financial power to consider additional takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   Redstone's top two lieutenants, deputy chairmen Tom Dooley and
Philippe Dauman, will step down but continue to serve on Viacom's
board, Redstone said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the prospect of layoffs or cutbacks, Karmazin told
reporters: ``You're too hung up on cost savings. The reason for
this deal is putting this set of assets together and growing
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
