<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3683 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-GULF-DEADZONE-1100(2T     09-07 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULF-DEADZONE-1100(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS, FISHING INDUSTRY WORRY ABOUT BARREN AREA IN GULF OF
MEXICO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COCODRIE, La. _ Fifteen miles out in the Gulf of Mexico, schools
of fish _ sheepshead, drum, even a few snapper _ make their watery
homes amid the massive steel legs of an offshore oil rig.
</P>
<P>
   From the deck of the research vessel Pelican, the marine life
appears abundant and the water remarkably clear. Only a skyline of
oil platforms off the Louisiana coast mars the pristine seascape.
</P>
<P>
   But as scuba divers plunge into the ocean and swim to the base
of the hulking oil platform, they disappear into a layer of murky
water. Below the turbid water, a sickly looking jellyfish is the
only sign of life.
</P>
<P>
   The divers have entered the Dead Zone, a swath of water nearly
the size of New Jersey, stretching from the Mississippi River delta
to the Texas-Louisiana border. Monitoring devices at the base of
the platform confirm what the researchers' eyes tell them: There
isn't enough oxygen in the water at a depth of 65 feet for fish to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   The oxygen-depleted area, known to scientists as a ``hypoxic''
zone, has not yet had an economic effect on the $680 million Gulf
fisheries industry, but officials are watching the growing Dead
Zone with alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 7,000 square miles of trollable space lost to shrimpers _
regardless of what state they're from,'' said Wilma Anderson,
executive director of the Texas Shrimp Association. ``Shrimp don't
follow manmade boundaries, and neither do shrimpers. It's an area
that's essentially off-limits to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dead Zone is fed by the Mississippi River, which drains
farmlands, prairies and cities from the Appalachians to the
Rockies. The zone first captured national attention in 1993 _ the
year of the last great Mississippi River flood _ when its size
doubled. Scientists say that runoff from the nutrient-rich
Mississippi River watershed, which encompasses about 40 percent of
the United States, triggers a complex series of events that has
caused the zone to expand.
</P>
<P>
   Nitrogen-rich fertilizer tops the list of factors believed to be
contributing to the zone's growth. Hypoxia, or oxygen depletion,
occurs when excess nutrients, such as nitrogen and phosphorus,
accumulate in a body of water and cause algae to flourish into
algal blooms. These blooms thrive on nitrates and phosphates and
deplete the water of nearly all dissolved oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is strongly challenged by farm groups, which point to
other factors cited by scientists for creation of the Dead Zone.
These include the containment of the river within levees, loss of
wetlands to development and the interaction of fresh water with
salt water.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the constantly changing Dead Zone covered 7,700
square miles, the biggest it has ever been.
</P>
<P>
   One of the divers, Nancy Rabalais, a marine biologist who has
studied the Dead Zone since 1985, has been trying to understand the
forces that cause the oxygen-deprived area to expand and how to
control it. But as research data indicate a link between fertilizer
runoff in the Midwest and expansion of the zone, the debate has
become increasingly strident and political.
</P>
<P>
   A White House Task Force is preparing a report that is expected
to be released in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   While the debate has raged in Congress, in the Farm Belt states
and on the Louisiana coast, Texas has been largely on the
sidelines. Texas officials contend that the conditions causing the
zone are unique to the Louisiana coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a dog in this hunt,'' said Bruce Moulton, a
technical specialist with the Texas Natural Resource Conservation
Commission. Moulton also serves on the advisory panel of the Gulf
of Mexico Program, a multiagency group set up to encourage
cooperation on Gulf environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Texas officials agree. Larry McKinney, senior director
of aquatic resources for the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department,
said the state would be foolish to ignore the Dead Zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a dog in this hunt,'' McKinney said. ``Now that dog
may be far off and not at the top of my plate, but this dog could
get big in a hurry. And if it gets bigger, the currents are going
to bring it farther toward Texas. There's not much we can do as a
state on our own _ it's too big an issue for any one state to
tackle alone _ but I would be very interested in working with the
federal government.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabalais, a Texas native and a professor for the Louisiana
Universities Marine Consortium in Cocodrie, has not had the time or
the funding to monitor Gulf waters off the Texas coast, but she
said Texans should be concerned. This year, for example, her
eight-day survey of the Dead Zone stopped at Sabine Pass for lack
of time. It's likely, she said, that the zone extended farther west
along the Texas coast.
</P>
<P>
   Aboard the 105-foot Pelican, operated by the Louisiana
consortium, Rabalais and her team of scientists were making their
monthly cruise to nine offshore monitoring sites that extend about
30 miles into the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   At each of the stations, tests showed that the dissolved oxygen
level was close to 2 milligrams per liter, the level at which
marine life is scarce. At some stations, readings were nearer to 1
milligram per liter, the level at which fish die.
</P>
<P>
   Close to shore, the oxygen-depleted zone may be only a couple of
feet deep. Farther out to sea, the band may be much thicker.
</P>
<P>
   What all this means to the Gulf's fisheries _ which account for
about 40 percent of all commercial fish brought to U.S. shores,
including much of the nation's shrimp _ is as murky as the Gulf's
waters.
</P>
<P>
   Shrimpers in both Louisiana and Texas have mixed opinions about
whether the zone affects them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother Nature makes our shrimp _ you can't predict it,'' said
Rocky Pavia, captain of a large shrimp boat based in Port Arthur.
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3684 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-VIACOM-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      09-07 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIACOM-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MARRAIGE OF OPPOSITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the past few years, as the rest of the television
industry turned itself inside out in a race to become young,
younger, and youngest, CBS stubbornly clung to its identity as the
one network where viewers could actually find characters with gray
hair.
</P>
<P>
   But in merging with Viacom Tuesday, CBS paired up with a lively
young dance partner that could teach the old network some new
steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beavis and Butt-head meets Dan Rather,'' was the waggish
description of one analyst on CNBC. Or, in the words of Viacom
chairman Sumner Redstone, `` `Blue's Clues' meets `60 Minutes.' ''
</P>
<P>
   While we won't see MTV's Beavis or Nickelodeon's Blue anchoring
the evening news, CBS is a good bet to develop a more youthful
profile now that its solid family base is united with the hipper,
fleeter, and much more cable-savvy Viacom. If younger is better in
the TV universe, so is bigger, and the merger results in an
Goliath-like entity that is now ``on that upper tier with Disney
and Time-Warner,'' according to Bruce Leichtman, director of media
and entertainment strategies for the Yankee Group.
</P>
<P>
   But will UPN, the struggling broadcast network half-owned by
Viacom, remain in the family long enough to benefit from corporate
and creative synergy? That depends on the Federal Communications
Commission, which has a rule against companies owning more than one
broadcast network.
</P>
<P>
   More immediately, the merger illustrates the financial clout
that a media company can build nowadays if it targets and captures
the right niche audience, and if it knows how to operate in the
cable universe.
</P>
<P>
   CBS has been notably lacking on the latter count, but not so its
new partner: Viacom boasts a large stable of successful cable
channels. Nickelodeon is the top-rated network among children aged
2 to 11, MTV is a must-see channel among teenage rock fans, VH1 is
a magnet for nostalgic baby-boomers, and Showtime has carved its
own slice of the audience by specializing in what programmers like
to call ``edgy'' movies and sitcoms.
</P>
<P>
   CBS, meanwhile, has hewed to a more traditional
family-programming path that brought the network to the top of the
overall household ratings last season, but only to fourth place
among the 18- to 48-year-old viewers advertisers pay a premium to
reach. ``While they were the No. 1 network last year, everybody
sort of wrote it off,'' observed Leichtman.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Viacom's cable holdings, CBS can enjoy the revenue
streams and cross-promotional opportunities that NBC and ABC have
had with their far-flung cable properties. ``In large part, the
network is the primer of the pump for the rest of the product,''
said Leichtman.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is also expected to turn to Viacom-owned Paramount as its
in-house production studio for new prime-time programs. Paramount
produces ``Frasier'' for NBC, the sort of cosmopolitan comedy CBS
has had trouble developing _ and the sort of sitcom that gets
especially strong ratings in big cities. CBS owns stations in most
of the major cities, but has tended to focus much of its
programming energies on shows with strong rural appeal (``Walker,
Texas Ranger,'' ``Touched by an Angel).
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an opportunity to send a message out that we didn't
have before,'' said one CBS insider. ``There will be more sampling
of us by younger viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger will also result in Viacom control over a vast amount
of syndicated programming ranging from ``Wheel of Fortune'' to
``The Oprah Winfrey Show'' to ``Hollywood Squares.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond drawing from the Paramount pipeline, CBS can also use its
added financial strength to outbid rivals for the best new shows
from the hottest producers. CBS chairman Mel Karmazin Tuesday said
the merger will result in ``a bigger investment in programming'' by
the network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be the major television broadcasting company,''
proclaimed Karmazin.
</P>
<P>
   Still unclear amid all the trumpet blasts of hype, though, is
what the merger will mean for UPN, a network that had begun to show
the first faint signs of a turnaround. FCC rules prohibit a company
from owning more than one broadcast network, meaning that Viacom
could not own both CBS and UPN, and also does not permit ownership
of TV stations that collectively reach more than 35 percent of the
country (Viacom will now reach 41 percent of the country).
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin and Redstone said they will be in Washington Wednesday
to try to persuade FCC regulators to change those rules. If they
cannot, Viacom would have to divest itself of UPN and of some local
stations.
</P>
<P>
   Redstone hinted that if he was forced to divest some local
stations, he would look to enhance opportunities for minority
ownership at the stations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
