<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Sept. 12,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moving in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FALL SEASON: A SPECIAL REPORT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEAD FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-NEWSEASON-BRANTLEY (Undated) _ Where, you may well ask,
do you find hope in a field of ashes? That would seem to be the
landscape of the Broadway musical at the moment, at least as seen
from the vantage point of the end of last season. Hope, however,
springs as buoyantly in the hearts of the genre's diehard fans as
it does in an uptempo Irving Berlin song. And there is indeed the
bright flicker of promise in the slate of musicals that begin
opening this fall. By Ben Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-NEWSEASON-MASLIN (Undated) _ As the year's most auspicious
film season approaches, at least this is certain: the approach of
the century's end will not go unexploited by Hollywood. But for
sheer promotional chutzpah, it may be hard to beat the trailer for
``Lost Souls,'' which uses sci-fi ominousness to heighten its
pitch: ``They had their 2,000 years,'' one character declares.
``Now it's our turn.'' That will be one extra reason to brace
oneself for the movie onslaught this fall. By Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   TV-NEWSEASON-JAMES (Undated) _ Here is the season's only
foolproof advice: take a deep breath and wait until January. That
brings the debut of what promises to be one of the most engaging
new series, ``Malcolm in the Middle'' and the return of ``The
Sopranos.'' By Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PREVIEW-NEWSEASON (Undated) _ Stephen Holden offers a brief
look at the 140 new films opening this season.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-NEWSEASON-PACINO (Undated) _ Al Pacino famously dreads
interviews, even the kind that don't try to poke into his private
life (girlfriend: the actress Beverly D'Angelo; children: a
9-year-old daughter Julie to whom he is close). But those days,
apparently, are behind him. This time around, he couldn't be warmer
or more engaging, By Karen Durbin.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-NEWSEASON-RUSSELL (Hollywood) _ His first film was about a
young man's relationship with his mother. His second was about a
young man's relationship with his mother and his other mother. His
third is about a young director's determination not to make three
films in a row about his mother. Whether biting off something
inoedipal is more than David Russell can chew will become apparent
when ``Three Kings'' opens on Oct. 1. By Bruce Newman.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-NEWSEASON-DIRECTORS (Undated) _ Cinema history is
punctuated by the work of visionary mavericks who will go to any
lengths to get their films made, and who require their
collaborators to share their obsessive dreams. The latest would-be
member of this club is Harmony Korine, the prodigiously talented
writer of ``Kids'' (1995) and writer-director of ``Gummo'' (1997)
and ``Julien: Donkey-Boy,'' which will be screened at the New York
Film Festival prior to its Oct. 15 release. By Graham Fuller.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-NEWSEASON-WINSLET (London) _ Kate Winslet likes to say that
she is not one for planning ahead _ which is probably a good thing,
since she could hardly have expected to land a lead role in the
biggest money-spinner of all time just four years into her screen
career. On the other hand, once ``Titanic'' thrust global fame upon
her when she was all of 21, it was soon apparent that this
strong-willed young Englishwoman was not about to allow stardom to
dictate her life. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-NEWSEASON-MCKEE (London) _ Gina McKee played Bella, Hugh
Grant's disabled friend, in the recent hit, ``Notting Hill,'' so it
seems appropriate that a movie obsessed with stardom should find
Ms. McKee well on the road to it herself. It helps, of course, to
possess Ms. McKee's singular, decidedly unglamorous beauty; as has
been pointed out frequently by the British press, she looks as if
she could have been painted by Modigliani. Even rarer is the quiet
integrity of her performance as Bella, which commands attention
without histrionics or bathos. Michael Winterbottom, director of
Ms. McKee's forthcoming film, ``Wonderland,'' spoke in turn of her
compellingly transparent presence. By Matt Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-NEWSEASON-HOLLYWOOD (Hollywood) _ The jury is still out and
a healthy sense of skepticism is advised, but perhaps we are
beginning to see with this year's fall and holiday lineup, just
what kinds of movies the Hollywood studios and major independents
are going to be making in response to the cost-cutting and the
hand-wringing. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
</P>
