<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3688 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FLEET-FED-BOS &LR;      09-07 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-FED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED APPROVAL LAUNCHES MERGED FLEET-BANKBOSTON VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as SOVEREIGN-FLEET)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Federal Reserve Board Tuesday approved Fleet
Financial Group Inc.'s acquisition of BankBoston Corp., clearing
the way for the creation of the nation's eighth-largest banking
company, to be known as Fleet Boston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's 5-0 approval of the Fleet-BankBoston deal, in an
afternoon meeting, came hours after Fleet had signed an agreement
to sell 278 branches in four states _ Massachusetts, Rhode Island,
Connecticut, and New Hampshire _ to Sovereign Bancorp for $1.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed, in a short statement, said it approved the formation of
Fleet Boston Corp. after a review of lending, market activity, and
community investments of the two banking companies. ``To address
competitive concerns, Fleet is required to divest'' branches and
deposits totaling $13 billion as a condition of the Fed's approval,
the agency said. Most of those branches and deposits are slated for
sale to Sovereign.
</P>
<P>
   With Sovereign's agreement in place and Fed approval in hand,
Fleet is now through the most difficult work required in putting
together the complex merger.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet officials hope to finalize the deal within weeks, possibly
by early October, but full integration of the two banks' operations
will not occur until the the second quarter of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's chief executive Terrence Murray, in a statement Tuesday,
predicted Fleet Boston Corp., with $170 billion in assets, would be
a ``world-class financial services institution that can grow and
compete in the global financial world of the new century.''
</P>
<P>
   After a weekend of negotiations with Fleet, Sovereign on Sunday
night agreed to pay $1.4 billion for the package of business, which
would transform Philadelphia-based Sovereign virtually overnight to
the third-biggest banking operation in Massachusetts and a dominant
institution throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   Sovereign said it agreed to retain 3,500 employees of Fleet and
BankBoston in four states as part of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty critical day,'' Charles ``Chad'' Gifford,
BankBoston's chief executive, said Tuesday. Sovereign's agreement
to hire employees of the branches on the sale block ``was a huge
plus to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The divestiture to Sovereign was a condition placed on the
merger by the US Department of Justice last week to ensure
competition. Justice also carved out a smaller piece of
Fleet-BankBoston's operations for sales to small community banks in
Massachusetts. Fleet is negotiating with several community banks to
sell them 28 branches.
</P>
<P>
   In selecting Sovereign to buy the banking operation, Fleet
effectively hand-picked its competition. But Sovereign has
fashioned a deal that gives it a strong foothold in Fleet's turf in
New England.
</P>
<P>
   Sovereign currently operates in New Jersey, Delaware, and
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Sovereign chief executive Jay S. Sidhu, announcing the deal
Tuesday in a press conference, immediately began what is expected
to be an aggressive campaign by the out-of-state bank to retain or
win customers in this market.
</P>
<P>
   Sovereign plans to close the deal and assume the
Fleet-BankBoston branches by April 2000. Sovereign's banking
operation in New England will be based in Boston and will be called
Sovereign Bank New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our vision that within a short period of time, New
Englanders will find Sovereign Bank New England as a household
name,'' Sidhu said. Sovereign hopes to deliver its services with a
``small-bank touch'' and by ``not treating people like numbers at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street liked the deal. Sovereign's stock, which has sagged
in recent weeks, gained 1 1/16 and closed at $11 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Sovereign officials hope their biggest advantage will be
employees inherited from Fleet or BankBoston _ veterans of the
region's banking market.
</P>
<P>
   Sidhu also named a Sovereign banker based in Boston to run its
new operation in New England. Joseph Campanelli, Babson College
graduate who started his banking career at Hartford National Bank
and previously ran Fleet's auto-loan business, will become
president of Sovereign Bank New England.
</P>
<P>
   Sidhu disclosed in an off-the-cuff remark that he hoped to
recruit long-time Fleet executive Thomas Lucey, who is overseeing
Fleet's divestiture of branches, after the branch purchase is
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Sovereign's encroachment on Fleet's territory is so complete
that the out-of-state banking company is assuming Fleet's lease of
five floors of office space at the gold-trimmed 75 State Street
building, which once served as Fleet's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, Sovereign would retain some 3,500
employees _ from tellers to loan officers _ who currently work in
the branches and offices being acquired. To ensure their commitment
to Sovereign, Sidhu said the employees would be offered stock
options or retention bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, analysts said it will be difficult for Sovereign
to move into the region. Any time a bank buys branches, it takes a
risk that some of the branch's business _ whether a small business
with a loan or a customer with a checking account _ may choose to
migrate back to the original owner, said James Moynihan, senior
vice president of Advest Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But Moynihand said Sovereign would be ``well-positioned'' under
the Justice Department-approved plan. ``The most difficult thing is
to maintain their current loan and deposit base, and I think that's
doable,'' Moynihan said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 176 branches and 116 ATMs being purchased by
Sovereign in Massachusetts are currently owned by Fleet; Sovereign
also is acquiring BankBoston's back-office operation in Dorchester.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut (39 branches) and Rhode Island (50 branches),
Sovereign is mainly buying branches currently owned by BankBoston.
Also included in the deal are BankBoston's consumer lending and
telephone banking centers in Providence.
</P>
<P>
   If Fleet and BankBoston employees agree to become Sovereign
employees, they would ensure his company ``retain the customers and
make sure we don't miss a beat when'' the Fleet's branches are
finally divested, Sidhu said.
</P>
<P>
   Sovereign will also honor all existing loan agreements or
certificates of deposit. As for fees on ATMs, Sidhu said, ``There
is no way Fleet-BankBoston is going to charge less than us.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, until Fleet's sale of branches is completed, Sovereign will
be in the odd position of allowing its biggest future competitor to
run its operations, one banking insider noted.
</P>
<P>
   Sovereign is no newcomer to such deals, having completed 19
acquisitions over the past decade. After buying 93 branches from
CoreStates when CoreStates merged last year with First Union,
Sovereign made $600 million in new loans in the first six months of
business, Campanelli said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We totally understand why you need local decision-making,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
