<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3689 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-2     09-07 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Rick Lyman. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FILM-NEWSEASON-MENDES (Hollywood) _ An interview with Sam
Mendes, the 34-year-old Englishman who directed the Broadway hits
``Cabaret'' and ``The Blue Room,'' and who is now the director of
the dark, phantasmagoric view of suburban life revealed in
``American Beauty.'' It's the story of a desperately dissatisfied
middle-aged man married to a grasping, equally dissatisfied real
estate broker. Their family life is a sham, their teen-age daughter
despises them and her sultry best friend has the father's sexual
fantasies going full-time. The movie, with Kevin Spacey and Annette
Bening in the lead roles, opens on Sept. 15. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-NEWSEASON-MCKELLAR (Undated) _ As we barrel toward the
millennium, there's something bothering the writer and actor Don
McKellar: the dearth of good, old-fashioned end-of-the world
movies. Indeed, McKellar was so perturbed that he decided to make
his own. The result, his feature-film directing debut, is cheekily
titled ``Last Night,'' and opens Nov. 5. By David Mernelstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-NEWSEASON-GUSSOW (Undated) _ As a conceptual director,
Martha Clarke is a creative body in motion. On a recent morning in
her airy Greenwich Village apartment (many years ago the home of
Marcel Duchamp), she was brimming with activity. She was in the
middle of casting ``Hans Christian Andersen,'' her deromanticized
Broadway musical version of the 1952 movie. By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-NEWSEASON-KISSELGOFF (Undated) _ There is one thing you
can say about the Swedish choreographer Mats Ek: at his best, he is
outrageous. The provocative image, its basic truth leavened with
absurdity and dark humor, is his forte. ``Carmen'' and ``Solo for
Two'' make up the all-Ek program that the Lyons Opera Ballet from
France will perform at the Brooklyn Academy's Harvey Theater from
Oct. 19 to 24. Other troupes that dance Ek's works have already
shown why he is one of Europe's most talked about choreographers.
By Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART/ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ART-NEWSEASON-KIMMELMAN (New York) _ The painter James Ensor,
the great Belgian eccentric of 19th-century art, developed his
style looking at Bosch and Bruegel. He was thoroughly European.
Jose Guadalupe Posada, his contemporary, a native of
Aguascalientes, Mexico, apprenticed in the workshop of a renowned
Mexican broadsheet publisher, Antonio Vanegas Arroyo. He became a
printmaker of big, cheap, mass-produced engravings in Mexico City.
Neither Ensor nor Posada seems to have had the slightest idea that
the other existed. But they are to be paired in ``Modern Starts''
at the Museum of Modern Art, a giant exhibition that opens Oct. 7.
By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-NEWSEASON-REIF (New York) _ A pioneer at the outset and
a trendsetter ever since, the American Wing of the Metropolitan
Museum of Art has advanced the nation's passionate interest in
American art throughout most of this century. Now, on Nov. 10, it
will mark to the day the 75th anniversary of its opening with
``Celebrating the American Wing: Notable Acquisitions 1980-1999,''
a yearlong exhibition of American paintings, sculpture and
furnishings of the late 17th century to the early 20th century. By
Rita reif.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-NEWSEASON-BURNS (New York) _ More than five years in the
making, ``New York,'' an admiring portrait of the city from Henry
Hudson's arrival, in 1609, to the millennium, is 12 hours in six
equal parts, or as Ric Burns puts it, the story of Prometheus
retold from era to era. The first five parts will be broadcast in
November (Sunday through Thursday, Nov. 14-18, 9 p.m.). A sixth
episode, scheduled for the spring, will focus on the last 60 years
of the century. By Charles Strum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POPMUSIC-NEWSEASON-PARELES (Undated) _ What has been missing for
some time amid pop's puppy love and acting up is a mentality that
was a staple of early-1990s rock: brooding, questioning,
self-lacerating angst. But in the 1999 season, angst is going to
try for a comeback. By John Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-NEWSEASON-PRINCE (Undated) _ The Artist, the tag by which
he's come to be known, after being formerly known as Prince, is now
41. An interview. By Anthony DeCurtis.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ One hundred bands in Leipzig; royal
barges in Bangkok; Tito Puente in Trinidad, marathoners in Venice.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Custom tours for those seeking
