<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3704 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-CHRISTINA-AGUILERA-LA     09-07 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTINA-AGUILERA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER MOUSKETEER AT TOP OF CHARTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Pop music's teen dream machine has delivered
another star _ and she's got a mouse in her closet.
</P>
<P>
   Like fellow chart-topping thrush Britney Spears, 18-year-old
Christina Aguilera is a graduate of the Disney Channel's ``New
Mickey Mouse Club.''
</P>
<P>
   But the new kid in town has range, and nobody's begun accusing
her of mutiny on the high C's.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Aguilera's unexpectedly broad singing voice is the
element mentioned most when talking about her smash single, ``Genie
in a Bottle,'' or her No. 1-reaching self-titled debut album.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't have Britney's teen queen look, so she's different
that way,'' observes Michael Steele, music director at Top 40 radio
KIIS-FM (102.7). ``But this girl's a talent. I've seen her live,
and her voice is as big as Whitney Houston or Mariah Carey. Not
only that, but the album is the real deal. It's not just candy pop.
There are some very clever songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Aguilera, who has lived in Japan, Florida and Texas and is now
based in New York, appeared on TV's ``Star Search'' at age 8, four
years later beginning a stint on Disney's cheery fantasy factory
alongside Spears, Justin Timberlake and J.C. Chasez of 'N Sync, and
the star of ``Felicity,'' Keri Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Early last year, Aguilera cut ``Reflection'' for the ``Mulan''
soundtrack, garnering a Golden Globe nomination for best original
song in a motion picture. The same week, RCA Records heard her
demo, invited her to audition a cappella and signed her. Label
executives have taken to calling her ``our Streisand.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon its release two weeks ago, fans snapped up 252,800 copies
of Aguilera's album, beating the new Puff Daddy disc to the top of
the Billboard 200. The record includes sassy pop-r&AMP;b tunes like
``Genie in a Bottle'' and midtempo ballads such as ``So Emotional''
and the Diane Warren-penned ``I Turn to You.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up an Army brat in suburban Pittsburgh, Aguilera, who's
half-Ecuadorean and half-Irish, sang along with cast albums of
roof-raising show tunes. She also had a thing for blues belters
Etta James and B.B. King.
</P>
<P>
   We caught the petite Aguilera, who turns 19 in December, as she
dashed from the airport to a Los Angeles studio to cut a Christmas
song.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you predict ``Genie in a Bottle'' would do as well as it
did?
</P>
<P>
   Aquilera: I could only hope. I had a good feeling about it. When
it was released, I did all I could to make sure. But I never
expected it to stay at No. 1 for five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What were those ``New Mickey Mouse Club'' years like?
</P>
<P>
   Aquilera: Being a Mouseketeer was definitely an experience. To
be around so many kids who were so passionate and driven and
serious about their careers was great for me. There was such
energy. I'm not surprised at the success of my fellow cast members.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did you come across ``Genie in a Bottle''?
</P>
<P>
   Aquilera: Well, we already had all the songs we wanted when
``Genie'' came in at the last minute. My a&AMP;r (artists and
repertoire) guy brought me into his office and said we should
record this. He said it had a very good chance of being a hit. I
was a little unsure and didn't want to release it as a single
because it was too similar to what's going on in pop right now. I
had my doubts, but I have no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What !ital!do you think of the pop scene at the moment? &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Aquilera: I think a lot of pop today lacks real soul.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did you get into blues and r&AMP;b?
</P>
<P>
   Aquilera: I grew up hearing Aretha Franklin. Me and my mom and
grandma would go to used record stores and find old Billie Holiday
songs and blues records and sift through them and check them out.
Blues was definitely a huge influence on me. It's probably my first
musical love. I just connect with it somehow. Even as a younger
child, I was a weird kid who would take B.B. King records and ad
lib over his guitar licks. I really connected with it. And Etta
James is my favorite blues singer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your relationship with Britney Spears? Are you
friends? &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Aquilera: We were very close on the ``New Mickey Mouse Club,''
but it's hard to keep connected. We really bonded back then. She
was 11 and 12, and I was 12 and 13. So we were the babies of the
cast. I miss her now. She's a sweet girl. People always want to
make out that there's competition between us because of our age,
but there isn't any. Really.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've played some pretty big shows. What does it feel like
to look out there and see a sea of faces singing along? &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Aquilera: That's the most amazing feeling ever. I can't even
describe it. Performing is what I like most. I find the studio very
confining. You can do a lot in there, and you get the opportunity
to try again and again. But on stage you have the adrenalin going,
and you've got one shot and the energy is so intense. You can't
help but give it all you've got.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Speaking of the stage, would you ever lip-sync in concert? &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Aquilera: I would never do it. But I can understand why people
do, because you have to dance and sing at the same time. And that's
hard.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since you've become such a hit, how have your friends back
home been treating you? &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Aquilera: I haven't seen a lot of them because I haven't had a
lot of time. But my friends have been nothing but supportive. I'm
sure my true friends won't treat me differently. I learned the hard
way a long time ago who were my friends. It's sad, because I don't
hear from them often, and they get mad because I'm so busy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How are you spending New Year's Eve?
</P>
<P>
   Aquilera: It's one of my dreams come true. I always watched Dick
Clark live from Times Square on TV, and I'm going to be hosting
something with MTV at their Times Square studios.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was your reaction when you heard you'd beat out Puff
Daddy for No. 1 in the albums chart? &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Aquilera: Amazed. It's like dancing on air. I didn't believe
it. I still don't believe it. I haven't seen it on paper yet, so
I'm just waiting for someone to call up and say it was all a big
mistake, they added the numbers wrong. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
