<HEADER>
A3708 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VIACOM-MARKETPLACE-NY     09-07 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIACOM-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: CBS AND VIACOM HOPE FOR NO OTHER BIDDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With VIACOM-CBS) 
(mk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The biggest deals of Sumner Redstone's life have
featured bitter takeover battles, lots of debt and some of the
strangest securities ever seen on Wall Street. But now, he says,
things will be different.
</P>
<P>
   Doing deals the old way enabled the 76-year-old Redstone to
parlay control of a chain of movie theaters first into control of a
cable empire, then into control of a company that is a leader in
everything from book publishing to motion pictures. Along the way,
there were periods when it looked as if the debt taken on to do the
deals might overwhelm the company.
</P>
<P>
   But his latest deal, in which his Viacom Inc. will take control
of CBS Corp., is supposed to be completely different. The
transaction announced Tuesday calls for the company to borrow not
even one dollar and involves no security more unusual than
nonvoting stock.
</P>
<P>
   Redstone was preaching the virtues of fiscal conservatism
Tuesday with all the fervor of a newly baptized convert. He
reminded Wall Street that he had once promised that Viacom would
never go deeply into debt again. Now the combined company will have
the money to invest in expanding the business and in continuing to
buy back stock. That tune played well on Wall Street, and the
shares of the two companies rose nicely on the news.
</P>
<P>
   But whether or not Redstone can deliver that vision depends on
whether he can get away with acquiring CBS without offering any
premium over the stock's market price. And that in turn depends on
whether other bidders surface.
</P>
<P>
   CBS and Viacom are trying to discourage any such offer. The deal
includes a $1 billion breakup fee that would have to be paid to
Viacom if anyone else took over CBS. And Mel Karmazin, the CBS
chief executive, said in an interview that he would quit if another
buyer got control of CBS. He added that he knew of no other
companies that were interested.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the way the stocks traded Tuesday suggests that
investors are not expecting another bid. The speculation centered
instead on Chris-Craft, Viacom's partner in owning the UPN network.
It leaped $5.5625, to $57, on the hope that it might be acquired as
well. Redstone allowed that he would be talking to Chris-Craft, but
declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, another bid for CBS is possible, perhaps from an
Internet company blessed with a high stock price _ and a desire to
acquire some assets that actually bring in cash. If a new bidder
does appear, Redstone will have to decide whether to fight. His
history says he is not one to walk away from a battle.
</P>
<P>
   The history of Viacom began in 1971, when it was spun off from,
of all places, CBS. In those quaint days, it bothered people when
companies owned too many media properties, and CBS, owner of one of
the three major television networks, was forced by the Federal
Communications Commission to unload its cable television and
syndication operations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, the management of Viacom tried to buy the company in a
leveraged buyout, only to have Redstone appear. After a bidding
war, his National Amusements, the movie theater company, won
control in a highly leveraged transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1993, Redstone set out to expand the company with
another huge transaction. He reached a friendly deal to acquire
Paramount Communications, whose assets included the Paramount movie
studio and Simon &AMP; Schuster, the publisher. Martin Davis,
Paramount's chairman, was to be chief executive of the combined
company, with Redstone as chairman, and Viacom was to take on
little debt, as most of the deal was financed with stock.
</P>
<P>
   Then the bidding war began, as QVC, a cable television company
run by Barry Diller, a former Paramount executive, entered the
bidding. When the smoke cleared, Viacom had gone deeply in debt and
issued some very odd securities, with names like contingent value
rights, whose value depended on how Viacom stock traded. Davis
ended up out of a job, the promised chief executive's role having
vanished.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's deal, Karmazin negotiated as much job security for
himself as could be hoped for _ given that Redstone will control 66
percent of the votes in the new company, although he has only 13
percent of the total stock. Karmazin has promises that CBS
directors will hold eight of the 18 board seats, and that the votes
of 14 directors would be needed to change his duties _ which
include supervising all operations of the combined company _ any
time before 2003. If Redstone should step down as chief executive
while Karmazin is on board, he is promised the chief executive's
job. But the reality will be that his job is safe only as long as
Redstone is happy with him.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no bidding war, the most interesting fight will come
in Washington. Redstone and Karmazin say they will abide by
whatever the regulators say, but they will travel to the capital
Wednesday to try to water down or eliminate the few rules remaining
on media concentration. They want to be able to own stations that
reach 41 percent of the country, rather than the 35 percent now
allowed, and they want to be allowed to retain control of both the
UPN and CBS television networks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
