 Tuesday, Sept. 7, 1999     
 Editors     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the following for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ADDS: RENO-WACO; GORE-2000; BUSH-2000; WACO-RANGERS; and
BBN-ASTROS.)
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PUERTO-RICO (Washington) _ In the wake of Hillary Rodham
Clinton's criticism of her husband's offer of clemency for 16
imprisoned Puerto Rican nationalists, White House Press Secretary
Joe Lockhart defends the offer, saying there were no political
considerations involved in it. By STEWART M. POWELL.
(1stld-writethru filed; also filed in the ``p'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   RENO-WACO (Washington) _ A Justice Department source says former
Missouri Sen. John Danford is the leading choice to head the
independent inquiry into six years of FBI denials that it used
incendiary devices during the federal siege of a cult compound in
Waco, Texas. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   CISNEROS-TRIAL (Washington) _ Former Housing Secretary Henry
Cisneros pleads guilty to a single misdemeanor charge of lying to
the FBI about money he had paid to his former mistress. Under a
plea agreement with prosecutors, Cisneros must pay a $10,000 fine
but will serve no prison time for lying to the investigators who
were checking on his background after he was nominated to President
Clinton's Cabinet in 1993. By GARY MARTIN.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-2000 (Washington) _ Vice President Al Gore proposes
incremental changes in the way health care is handled in a major
health-care policy speech and says he has learned the lesson of the
Clinton administration failed health reform drive in 1993. The
Democratic presidential hopeful proposes expanding a children's
health insurance program and creating a ``Patient's Bill of
Rights.'' By BENNETT ROTH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Milford, N.H.) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who last
week proposed a new federal role for forcing improvement in public
education, takes pains to insist he is still in favor of local
control of schools. The Republican presidential hopeful tells a New
Hampshire audience that ``one size should not fil all when it comes
to federal education policy.'' By CLAY ROBISON. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WACO-RANGERS (Austin, Texas) _ The Texas Rangers get some extra
time to comply with a federal subpoena for the records related to
the siege at the Branch Davidian compound in Waco, Texas. The
Department of Public Safety was ordered to turn over its final
report on what investigators found after the fire at the Branch
Davidian compound, as well as any documents related to the use of
pyrotechnic tear gas devices. By KATHY WALT. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Philadelphia) _ The Houston Astros aim for their
fifth consecutive victory as they face the Philadelphia Phillies in
the second game of a four-game series. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Now that Congress and President
Clinton are back on the job, heaven help us all. Not much changed
during August. We can expect the same old arguments about tax cuts
and spending priorities and the same old bad tempers as before. So
confrontation is more likely than cooperation. By MARIANNE MEANS.
(Already filed.)
</P>
