A3714 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SOUTHERN-COMPANY-COX     09-07 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-COMPANY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern Co. seeks tech skills to fill 3,000 jobs
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Southern Co., the huge Southeast utility, is hiring
more than 3,000 new employees for deployment throughout its growing
market, many of them engineers and technicians.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Womack, senior vice president for human resources at
Southern Co., said the changing shape of the company has required
more people and new kinds of skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Power generation businesses, which we are acquiring, building
and operating around the country, drive much of our hiring,''
Womack said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we also require other skills such as information
technology and financial specialties.''
</P>
<P>
   Womack said the search for new talent _ it is hiring the
equivalent of nearly 10 percent of its work force of 32,000 _ has
been tough because the hunt puts Southern up against a national
demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we have had to use many resources, including
search firms, we have managed to hire about 2,000 people and expect
to complete our hiring by the end of the year,'' Womack said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the people will be put to work in Georgia, but many will
be employed in New England, California and in the Midwest, where
Southern is now doing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the new forces are being employed in the design,
construction and operation of the latest and most efficient power
generation plants we can bring online,'' said Womack.
</P>
<P>
   Southern consists of traditional power companies such as Georgia
Power, which sell electricity on a regulated basis.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also competitive in electricity generation right
in the back yards of other power companies.
</P>
<P>
   New endeavors also include unregulated businesses, such as the
division that concentrates on communications and may eventually
include data transmission via electric lines.
</P>
<P>
   Like a few other companies, Southern has the capability to train
and retrain employees at its teaching campus in Peachtree City.
</P>
<P>
   This flexibility allows the company to contemplate new
businesses outside its traditional role of generating and
distributing electric power.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have special needs we can install courses, and move
employees into residential quarters on the campus and teach in a
concentrated way,'' Womack said.
</P>
<P>
   The facility could become a key factor if Southern Co. should
decide, after the trial run, to offer Internet connections to homes
by way of electric power lines.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
