<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PLEASURES AND TRAGEDIES OF LIVING DANGEROUSLY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a letter from the editor in the latest issue of National
Geographic's newish Adventure magazine,  &UR; John Rasmus &LR;  discusses the
spirit of adventure and the accident that killed &UR; John F. &LR; 
 &UR; Kennedy Jr. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Because the magazine was new, Rasmus had been interviewed by
MSNBC just before the tragedy. He said then that adventurers'
accidents were usually caused either by experienced adventurers
pushing their limits or by beginners who didn't understand their
limits. Pieces of that interview were played again during the
coverage of the Kennedy death.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the New York Times quoted him as saying, ``We are going
to do as many of those stories as we can.'' The headline on that
piece: ``Fatal Adventures Bolster Sales of Magazines.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are drawn to stories of tragedy,'' writes Rasmus in the
letter. ``Consequently, disasters probably do increase book and
magazine sales and TV ratings. But to me that's a measure of the
importance of these stories.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have been worth the risk, he says, for  &UR; George Mallory &LR; 
to unsuccessfully attempt to climb Mount Everest in 1924. But
``John Kennedy didn't have to risk his life to get to Martha's
Vineyard. If we don't have to, let's not.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GEORGE W. AND THE WAR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; George W. Bush &LR; , who served in the Texas Air Guard during the
Vietnam War and thus avoided service overseas, says he did not use
pull to get into the Air Guard. But according to the Washington
Monthly, Bush had some notable companions.
</P>
<P>
   Among the others serving in the Texas Air Guard at the time: the
sons of politicians  &UR; Lloyd Bentsen  &LR; and &UR; John Connally  &LR; and ``at
least seven members of the Dallas Cowboys,'' said the Washington
Post.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SITCOM STRATEGIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The Times of London says Secretary-General &UR; Kofi Annan &LR;  is
hoping to ``turn around the public perception'' of the United
Nations, and to that end has hired a public relations agency. One
of his ideas, says the newspaper, is the creation of a
``MASH-style'' sitcom set at U.N. headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
   _ Publishers Weekly describes the forthcoming ``Seinfeld and
Philosophy: A Book About Everything and Nothing'' (Northern
Illinois University; $30), in which editor  &UR; William Irwin  &LR; has
collected essays loosely focused around such premises as the German
translation of the word Seinfeld: field of being.
</P>
<P>
   Among the essays are `` &UR; Plato &LR;  or  &UR; Nietzsche &LR; : Time, Essence and
Eternal Recurrence in `Seinfeld,' '' and ``The Costanza Maneuver:
Is It Rational for George to `Do the Opposite'?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Roman Polanski &LR; 's new movie, ``La Neuvieme Porte'' (``The
Ninth Gate''), opened in Paris last week to less than sparkling
reviews. MSNBC quotes Liberation, which said the movie would be ``a
byword in the cinematic history of insane s_,'' and Le Monde, which
called its most dramatic scene ``perfectly ridiculous.'' The movie
stars  &UR; Johnny Depp  &LR; as a rare-book dealer looking for works about
demons.
</P>
<P>
   _ The latest Internet jargon: ``Bricks-and-Mortar.'' The term is
used by Internet marketers to describe retailers who occupy
three-dimensional premises rather than Web sites.
``Clicks-and-Mortar'' describes business that sell from stores AND
Web sites, says the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sotheby's in New York is planning an October auction of the
stuff found in  &UR; Allen Ginsberg &LR; 's apartment. Up for sale will be
letters, photographs, the poet's meditation beads, fountain pens
and ``even his wallet,'' says artnet.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ British tabloids are reporting that  &UR; Madonna &LR; , who has been
house-hunting in London, has put her 2-year-old daughter,
 &UR; Lourdes &LR; , on the waiting list for the Lycee Francais Charles de
Gaulle School in London. As to why the American would choose to
send her kid to a French school in England, the Sun said she wanted
to give her the ``opportunity to be immersed in a different
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to have the sense of humor of the Ayatollah to take
this movie (``Dogma'') all that seriously. It's clearly farcical.
... It's nice to be in a movie that feels like it has substance,
when so many movies are so homogeneous. It raises the issue of
personal responsibility and accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ben Affleck demonstrates a flexible point of view, in Teen
People magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
