<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-DOCUMENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD LOSES BID TO KEEP DOCUMENTS OFF THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Asserting that an Internet site has the same
free-speech rights as newspapers and other traditional media, a
federal judge ruled here on Tuesday that the Ford Motor Co. could
not stop the owner of the site from using information that he had
gleaned from confidential Ford documents.
</P>
<P>
   Ford had requested a preliminary injunction barring Robert Lane,
the owner of the site about the company, from using, copying or
disclosing the documents, which Ford described as containing trade
secrets. But U.S. District Judge Nancy G. Edmunds ruled that free
speech under the First Amendment took precedence over Ford's
secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers and magazines have won various cases over the years
preventing corporations from exercising so-called prior restraint
on the publication of sensitive information. Tuesday's ruling adds
to a small but growing number of court decisions granting the same
constitutional protection to Internet sites, said Mike Godwin, a
lawyer specializing in free-speech issues on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an important case because it further establishes the
scope of First Amendment protections in cyberspace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The first cases involving prior restraint on the Internet were
filed by the Church of Scientology in an effort to stop the
electronic posting of church documents, Godwin said, adding that
the church had prevailed in some cases and lost in others.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Edmunds couched her decision Tuesday in broad language. ``In the
realm of law, we are only beginning to grapple with the impact of
the communications revolution, and this case represents just one
part of one skirmish _ a clash between our commitment to the
freedom of speech and the press, and our dedication to the
protection of commercial innovation and intellectual property,''
Edmunds wrote. ``In this case, the battle is won by the First
Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmunds did grant Ford a preliminary injunction barring Lane, a
32-year-old nursing student, from infringing Ford's copyrights.
This could prevent Lane from posting Ford documents in their
entirety on his Web site, as Lane had done until Ford sued him two
weeks ago. But the copyright decision had little legal
significance, several First Amendment lawyers said Tuesday, because
Lane's lawyer had already promised the court last week that his
client would not post any more Ford documents on the site. Land can
write about the documents and quote them extensively without
worrying about copyright issues, the lawyers added.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's lawsuit, accusing Lane of violating its trademarks,
copyrights and trade secrets, is still pending and could result in
financial damages against Lane. Lane's lawyer, Mark Pickrell, also
agreed in court last week that his client would tell Ford whatever
he knew about who provided the internal documents. But Lane said in
court last week that he did not know who had mailed the documents
to his post office box or dropped them off at his home, so this
agreement may not help Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Lane's site, www.blueovalnews.com, is named for Ford's corporate
logo, a blue oval with the Ford name inside. Lane started the site
last year to provide news for Ford Mustang fans, but broadened it
this summer after Ford became critical of some of the news he
posted.
</P>
<P>
   Pickrell welcomed Tuesday's ruling as a victory for free speech.
Ford said that it was pleased that Lane's constitutional rights had
been respected but also glad that its copyrights would be
protected. Ford lawyers want to discuss the ruling with Pickrell,
and have not yet decided whether to appeal, said Terry Bresnihan, a
Ford spokesman.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The case is particularly awkward for Ford because many of the
secret documents say the company may someday be able to build
automobiles, particularly sport utility vehicles, that emit less
pollution and have better fuel efficiency than current models. Yet
the company is lobbying against tighter emission and fuel economy
regulations as unrealistic. The company does build the least
polluting sport utility vehicles on the market, although not the
most fuel-efficient.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency has proposed new rules that
would crack down on tailpipe emissions from sport utility vehicles
in particular. Separately, the Senate is considering whether the
administration should be allowed to raise fuel-economy standards
for sport utility vehicles, pickups and minivans.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Bresnihan, a Ford spokesman, said Tuesday that the company
had been frank in discussions with the EPA about the feasibility of
designing lower-emissions vehicles. Documents regarding fuel
economy describe technologies that may not be feasible for
technological and marketing reasons, Bresnihan said.
</P>
<P>
   EPA spokesman David Cohen declined to comment on the documents
because of the lawsuit. But he added, ``We're convinced that the
rules we've proposed and the final standard will be the toughest
ever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
