u s BC-HKN-THRASHERS08-COX     09-07 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holan skating for new lease on life
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Milos Holan left his family in Ostrava, in the
Czech Republic, last week, setting out to add another miracle to
his life. Holan kissed the wife who had to give birth while her
husband was in another hospital bed struggling for his life. He
kissed the son he couldn't hold for six months and the daughter who
can't fully grasp what happened a few years back.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is 7, so doesn't understand what leukemia means,'' Holan
said Tuesday, his English fighting through a heavy Czech accent.
``But she understands that something happened to me. When I came to
USA for this training camp, she said, `Don't get hurt again.' She
knows I was sick. But she thinks I was hit in the stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   This Thrashers training camp marks either the beginning of a new
career for Holan or the final chapter of the old one. The
28-year-old is trying to earn a roster spot on a free-agent tryout
_ four years after being diagnosed with chronic leukemia, which led
to radiation, chemotherapy, a bone-marrow transplant and resulting
infections and complications that nearly ended his life.
</P>
<P>
   It is no wonder, then, that Holan says, ``I want to play hockey,
of course. But if I don't, it doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   A former most valuable player of the Czech Elite League and a
defenseman with the Philadelphia Flyers and Anaheim Mighty Ducks,
Holan was out of hockey for nearly two years. He was invited back
to training camp with the Mighty Ducks last year but was cut
without even being allowed to play in an exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really upset,'' Holan said. ``They invited me to camp,
but for what? I mean, I was very grateful for what they did for me
before it happened. But I came to play, not watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Holan returned home and played 30 games in the Czech League,
scoring nine goals and 13 assists in 30 games. He decided to give
his NHL career one last chance, and the Thrashers obliged. Although
deep in numbers at defense, general manager Don Waddell said Holan
probably will get some ice time in exhibition games, the first of
which is Saturday against Nashville in Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``You watch him here, and it's clear his skill level is at the
NHL level,'' Waddell said. ``What you lose is timing and tempo.
Three years is a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight months can be longer. That was the length of Holan's stay
in a Southern California hospital. ``You wake up in the morning,
you are nauseous, and every day something happens that you never
thought could happen to you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holan's medical history would fill a book. And it does. He wrote
his life-and-near-death story in a book that was published in the
Czech Republic last month. In it, he tells how he was first
diagnosed in a routine preseason physical in 1995. Doctors told him
he needed a bone-marrow transplant, because the levels of radiation
and chemotherapy required to kill the cancerous cells in the blood
also would destroy his own marrow and immune system.
</P>
<P>
   But Holan had to wait four months for a donor with enough
genetic similarities to be found. In the meantime, he actually
played 16 games for the Ducks in 1995-96. He finally left the team
in January '96, and he had the transplant a month later. He was
released from the hospital that April but returned soon after
because of complications. He had numbness in his limbs, his gall
bladder was removed, and he developed pneumonia. He lost more than
50 pounds. During that time, his wife, Irena, gave birth to Milos
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Holan thought often about death. But in time, he grew strong
enough to be released from the hospital. He wanted to thank the
donor but was told that it is standard to keep the identity secret
for at least a year. He eventually had a telephone conversation
with Robert Stransky Jr. of Jessup, Md., and met him for the first
time only two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   He notes that Stransky is a nuclear engineer. ``So I will be
smarter on the ice,'' he said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Holan says if he doesn't make the Thrashers, he will retire and
take a coaching job in the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing to lose,'' he said. ``I am here. Everything
else is just a bonus in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   MILOS HOLAN FILE
</P>
<P>
   Age: 28.
</P>
<P>
   Home: Bilovec, the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Position: Defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   Status: Free-agent getting tryout with Thrashers after being
diagnosed with chronic leukemia in 1996 with Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Career: Drafted by Philadelphia in 1993. Traded to Anaheim in
1995 and played 49 games in two seasons before his illness. Played
in the Czech Republic last season.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
