<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD CHAIN: SORTING PEPPERCORNS; MYSTERIOUS PECTIN; SAFFRON
SUBSTITUTE; SAFE `RAW' FISH; TASTES OF HUNGARY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Are all peppercorns, regardless of color, from the fruit of
one plant at different stages of ripeness? And why do some recipes
call for white pepper?
</P>
<P>
   A. Black, green and white peppercorns are all berries of the
same plant, the climbing vine Piper nigrum (so-called pink
peppercorns are not actually members of the peppercorn family).
</P>
<P>
   Black peppercorns are picked when the berries are almost ripe,
then dried until the outer skin turns black. Green peppercorns are
picked when the berries are even less ripe, and they have a fresh
but pungent flavor. Since they are very perishable, green
peppercorns are sold either in brine or freeze-dried.
</P>
<P>
   If the berries are left to ripen completely, they develop a
bright red skin that has to be removed to reveal the white
peppercorn. Since most of the berry's heat is contained in the
skin, white peppercorns are the mildest of the three peppercorns.
They are especially useful for those who want to maintain a
pristine white sauce, unmarred by black pepper specks, or for those
preferring a more mellow pepper flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Mysterious Pectin
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to make jellies and jams, but I can't find
pectin in my supermarket. What is it exactly, and where can I buy
it?
</P>
<P>
   A. Pectin is a naturally occurring water-soluble substance that
is found in some ripe fruits like apples and plums, especially in
the skins and seeds. When pectin-rich fruit is boiled with sugar
and a bit of acid, the pectin reacts and causes the mixture to gel.
Extracted and sold in powdered form, pectin can be added to those
fruits that do not have enough pectin to gel on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan supermarkets tend not to carry pectin, but you can
usually request that it be ordered. Dean &AMP; DeLuca (560 Broadway at
Prince Street; 212-431-1691) sells one-ounce packets for $4, enough
for 10 pints of jam. It also has a mail-order service.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of using commercial pectin, you can simply mix fruits
that are naturally high in pectin, like apples, plums, cranberries
and red currants, with fruits low in pectin, like strawberries,
peaches, cherries and blackberries. For jams, which need not gel as
much as jellies, you can also just cook the fruit and sugar
together until the desired consistency is reached. The jam may be a
bit runnier than commercial jams but will still be delicious.
</P>
<P>
   Saffron Substitute
</P>
<P>
   Q. In a traditional French soupe de poisson, is there an
alternative to the inordinately expensive saffron?
</P>
<P>
   A. One little-known substitute is dried marigold petals. They
have a similar musky flavor and will also impart that
characteristic golden hue. Substitute marigold for saffron in equal
measure. The petals, called calendula, are 55 cents an ounce at
Aphrodisia, 264 Bleecker Street (at Seventh Avenue; 212-989-6440).
</P>
<P>
   Safe `Raw' Fish
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does marinated raw fish, like herring fillets, pose a danger
to humans because of a risk of infection by parasites? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Although marinated fish are technically indeed raw, they have
been soaked in a highly concentrated solution of vinegar and salt,
which kills any lurking parasites and cures the fish in the
process. Once cured, the fish are removed from the pickling
solution and rinsed well, then packed in a very dilute pickling
solution.
</P>
<P>
   Tastes of Hungary
</P>
<P>
   Q. Having just returned from Budapest, I'd like to know where to
find Hungarian specialties, like paprika sauce or goulash.
</P>
<P>
   A. The Yorkville Packing House, 1560 Second Avenue (81st Street;
212-628-5147), sells a wide array of Hungarian specialties,
including an authentic Hungarian goulash and paprika sauce. It also
has a mail-order service.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about food and cooking can be sent to Food Chain, the
Dining section, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd Street, New York
10036-3959, or by e-mail to dining(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
