u i BC-KOSOVO-POLICE-ART-NYT     09-07 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POLICE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMUNITY POLICING TAUGHT BY AMERICANS IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VUCITRN, Yugoslavia _ Kosovo's police school began training its
first cadets on Tuesday, with only one Serb among a sea of
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   The American officials in charge conceded that they were failing
to create a multiethnic force for the province.
</P>
<P>
   There were to have been 200 men and women starting five weeks of
classes on Tuesday in the former Serbian-run police school here in
northern Kosovo. But of the 26 Serbs selected for the first course,
only one showed up.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear why the others did not appear, but Garry Day,
the U.S. police officer in charge of recruitment, suggested that
there may have been intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from the U.S., I never realized what intimidation
really means,'' he said as the recruits headed for the classrooms
after hearing opening speeches. ``We will be sending people out
straightaway to their homes to see why they did not turn up today.
It may be first-day jitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Serbian applicants were threatened, and even assaulted, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet if they cannot manage to come today,'' he said, ``how are
they going to cope with the job of being policemen?''
</P>
<P>
   Selection for the Kosovo Police Service has been the school's
thorniest problem, and it delayed the opening by a week. The
absence of the Serbs on the first day was a reminder of the losing
battle that peacekeepers are waging to create a multiethnic Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The first class, of 105 recruits, has ended up dominated by
Albanians, more than half of whom are former members of the Kosovo
Liberation Army. Kosovo's other minorities are also poorly
represented, with just four Turks and three Gypsies in the first
class. There are more than 40 women, a fact the organizers are
proud of.
</P>
<P>
   The men in charge of the training face an unusual task. The
students will be taught ``democratic policing,'' including lessons
on community relations and human dignity, along with normal police
duties and crime investigation, a training program document shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to change the way people think about the police in
their country,'' the school's director, Steve Bennett, an ex-Marine
and former director of the Board on Public Safety Standards in
Oregon, said of the recruits. ``They know that and they are proud
of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The school is run mainly by Americans but is part of a broad
international effort to reconstruct Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   After five weeks in the classroom, the cadets will go through 19
weeks of field training, each patrolling the streets of Pristina
alongside a U.N. police officer. The goal is to train a police
force to take over when the U.N. force departs.
</P>
<P>
   The men and women selected have been given background checks,
but Bennett said he expected some ``bad apples'' to emerge during
the training.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the 30 Serbs originally selected were dropped following
accusations of involvement in war crimes. Some Albanian applicants
were sidelined when allegations arose that some had worked for the
Serbian secret service. Since the secret service was infamous for
abuse, Bennett said, the men were passed over until further checks
could be made.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Serbs who applied was disappointing, he said, but
even one or two success stories may help others come forward in the
future. ``One of the necessities is to mobilize the moderate
majority of people of Kosovo who aren't being heard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Recruitment is only one of the technical difficulties in postwar
Kosovo. Police uniforms, donated by Denmark, have yet to arrive, so
the recruits were dressed in a motley of jeans and track suits on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The school premises are rudimentary, and the weapons the police
will be trained to use _ 9mm Glock handguns to be donated by
Austria _ were also not in evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the mood was optimistic. Many of the recruits were
experienced men, in their 30s and 40s, and some served in the
Yugoslav police force until 1989, before Albanians were dismissed
from public service. They were glad to be back in a job.
</P>
<P>
   Two senior KLA commanders were among the class, as well as a
number of former members. They spoke of ``serving the people,'' a
common refrain among fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Among the class was Nejmeddin Kastrati, 28, a former Yugoslav
army officer and brigade commander of the Kosovo Liberation Army.
The entry test was easy, he said, and working alongside Serbs will
not pose a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think who and what someone is,'' he said. ``I am
going into this as a professional. And of course they have not
taken on the criminals, who will be dealt with in the international
courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, decked out in cowboy boots, said, ``There are a lot of
things to be optimistic about.'' By next September he said he
expected to have 3,500 police officers trained. ``In two years we
will have provided the foundation,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
