<HEADLINE>
SWISS PHARMACEUTICAL GROUP NAMES PRESIDENT OF US UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Ares-Serono Group of Geneva, Switzerland, a leading
developer of pharmaceutical products for female reproductive
health, has named Ellen R. Frank president of Serono Laboratories,
its US subsidiary in Norwell, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Frank is among only a handful of women who have risen in the
biotechnology industry to the chief executive level.
</P>
<P>
   She succeeds Hisham Samra, who had been president since 1992 and
has now been promoted to director of clinical development and
regulatory affairs for the entire company in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, who has been with the company for seven years, served as
executive vice president of metabolic and immune therapy, the
biotechnology operation that has enabled the company to expand into
making drugs for some AIDS patients.
</P>
<P>
   Serono Laboratories is best known for marketing hormone growth
deficiency products to help women with infertility problems.
</P>
<P>
   Under Frank, the company developed a drug to help seriously ill
AIDS patients from losing their strength and body mass.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which employs 250 people in Massachusetts, also
plans to break ground in January on a 200,000-square-foot corporate
resesarch and development and new US headquarters facility in
Hingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an excellent product pipeline and are poised to see
major growth in the coming years,'' said Frank Tuesday, noting that
this year, Serono Laboratories should post about $300 million in
sales _ about one-third of Ares-Serono's anticipated revenues of
nearly $1 billion worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The new construction comes after Serono shut down its
three-year-old manufacturing operations in Randolph, Mass. last
year, dismissing 100 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The company moved production to Switzerland, Spain, and a new
manufacturing facility in Puerto Rico that opened in February.
Frank said there are no plans to produce any drugs in the Bay
State.
</P>
<P>
   Frank takes over a company that has lost several significant
legal challenges from US rivals that were first to market new
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Serono tried to enter the US market for multiple sclerosis drugs
against Biogen's Avonex, but was prevented from entering because
the Cambridge biotech company had a seven-year market protection
from rivals under the Orphan Drug Act.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Serono tried to sell Seizen, its human growth hormone
drug, but was blocked under the Orphan Drug Act by Genentech Corp.
of South San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Serono lost a US Court of Appeals case when it tried
to thwart generic drug maker Ferring Pharmaceuticals Inc. of
Tarrytown, N.Y., from marketing a bioequivalent version of
Pergonol, Serono's 30-year-old infertility drug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
