<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-PLEA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISNEROS ENTERS SURPRISE PLEA IN 4-YEAR FEDERAL CASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARIA E. RECIO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros pleaded
guilty Tuesday to a federal misdemeanor for lying to the FBI about
payments he made to a former mistress.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise plea agreement with federal prosecutors brought to
an end a four-year investigation by independent counsel David
Barrett. The cost of the inquiry was estimated at more than $9
million.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plea bargain, Cisneros agreed to pay a $10,000 fine in
return for prosecutors dropping an 18-count felony indictment
against him. He will not have to serve any time in jail or on
probation.
</P>
<P>
   A trial on the charges of conspiracy and lying was to have
started Tuesday in U.S. District Court.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, 52, a former mayor of San Antonio and once the
nation's best known Hispanic political figure, did not speak to
reporters. But he issued a statement expressing regret that he had
concealed information from the FBI during his background check for
the Cabinet post.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros was secretary of housing and urban development from
1993 to 1997 during President Clinton's first administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``During my background investigation, I was not candid with the
FBI about a personal matter,'' Cisneros said. ``I regret my lack of
candor and accept responsibility for my conduct. I hope that all
who follow me in public service learn the lesson that truth and
candor are important in the process of selecting our leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Stanley Sporkin said that he was
initially reluctant to approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there will be some second-guessing about this plea,''
he said in accepting the plea agreement. ``There will be some who
will say that the sanction is not tough enough and others who will
say, `Here is more evidence of the Independent Counsel Act as not
serving the public interest.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``We cannot permit an individual to lie his way
into high public office. ... The work of the independent counsel in
this case reaffirms the importance of telling the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett said, ``This disposition should in no way be viewed as
minimizing the serious ethical breach by Mr. Cisneros. Deception by
public officials and those seeking public office erodes trust and
must be addressed and sanctioned.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``in this case,'' the independent counsel said, ``the
conduct, while egregious, was committed by a person whose life has
been otherwise dedicated to public service, and this fact must
season the final decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The ending of a multimillion-dollar investigation with a guilty
plea on a single misdemeanor conviction was seen by critics of the
now-expired Independent Counsel Act as evidence that the
legislation was flawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, Cisneros shouldn't have been made to suffer as
much as he did for his alleged crime,'' said Bruce Buchanan,
professor of government at the University of Texas at Austin. ``He
was lying to the FBI about an embarrassing personal matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, now president of Univision Inc., a Spanish-language
television network, was facing a protracted trial over charges that
he and his former mistress, Linda Medlar Jones, conspired to
conceal the amount of payments he made to her. Friends of Cisneros
say his legal defense cost more than $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The former San Antonio mayor had publicly acknowledged his
relationship with Jones in 1988. He told FBI agents vetting him for
the Cabinet post that, after the affair ended, he paid her $2,500 a
month out of compassion.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros formally acknowledged Tuesday in his plea that he had
understated the amount. He had told the FBI that his payments
amounted to about $60,000 when they actually totaled more than
$250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has been serving a 31/2-year sentence at the Federal
Medical Center prison in Fort Worth for bank fraud in a related
case brought by Barrett. She was to have been the government's star
witness against Cisneros and was expected to receive a reduction in
her sentence in return for her cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had secretly taped conversations with Cisneros in which
the former housing secretary spoke of the FBI inquiry into his
relationship with her. Jones sold some of the tapes to a television
tabloid program, ``Inside Edition,'' for $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   In pre-trial motions this summer, Jones testified that she had
made 88 tapes but also revealed that none of the tapes were
originals. She told the court that she had copied all the tapes and
deleted portions of a few of them because the conversations were
either personal or could expose her to charges of threatening
Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros' lawyers denounced the tapes as tainted, but Sporkin
ruled that most of the 26 tapes the government wanted to use
against the former housing secretary were admissible.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contended that the payments amounted to hush money
and that the tapes provided proof that Cisneros intended to lie
about the size of the payments. Barrett initially charged two of
Cisneros' aides but dropped the case against them this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was also under indictment in the Cisneros case but Barrett
dropped the two counts against her Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion of the Cisneros investigation came amid
widespread disillusionment over the Watergate-era independent
counsel statute engendered by the protracted inquiry of President
Clinton's behavior by independent counsel Kenneth Starr. Congress
allowed the statute to expire at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this really what we had in mind when we passed the
independent counsel law?'' asked Katy Harriger, a Wake Forest
University professor who wrote a book about independent counsels.
``I think it was a good thing it expired. It was over-used and the
Cisneros case is a good example of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Independent counsels are still investigating the activities of
Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and Labor Secretary Alexis Herman.
Another independent counsel, Donald Smaltz, lost a case against
former Agriculture Secretary Michael Espy but is still wrapping up
his investigation.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 2045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
