<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3746 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r w BC-CISNEROS-ANALYSIS-TEX     09-07 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-ANALYSIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISNEROS' POLITICAL CAREER MAY BE IRREPARABLE
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanies BC-CISNEROS-PLEA) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Henry Cisneros ended his legal problems by
admitting that he lied to the FBI, but his once promising political
career may be beyond repair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say he's pretty tainted,'' said James Riddlesperger,
who is on leave from Texas Christian University to write a book on
presidential transitions. ``It's another in a long saga of the
very, very high cost of being in public service.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, 52, offered no hints of his plans as he pleaded guilty
Tuesday to a single federal misdemeanor count of lying about his
payments to former girlfriend Linda Medlar Jones. Prosecutors said
Cisneros wanted to hide more than $250,000 in payments from the FBI
because he feared it would derail his 1993 appointment as secretary
of housing and urban development.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the plea bargain, Cisneros will pay a $10,000
fine, but will not be subjected to jail time or probation.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, who resigned from HUD in 1996 to become chief
executive at Univision, the Spanish-language television network,
has given no indication that he would like to return to politics.
But one close friend expressed confidence that the former San
Antonio mayor could win statewide office in Texas despite the
guilty plea.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a white-collar parking ticket,'' said Democratic
consultant George Shipley, who worked on all of Cisneros' political
campaigns. ``I think the path is clear for Henry to come home to
Texas and run for whatever he wants to run for.''
</P>
<P>
   Shipley, who said he thinks of Cisneros ``like a brother,'' said
Cisneros has never talked to him about returning to politics.
</P>
<P>
   For most political observers, the guilty plea was another
reminder of what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   Until his affair with Jones became public in 1988, Cisneros had
been one of the brightest stars in Texas politics. As one of the
most successful Hispanic politicians, his future seemed almost
limitless.
</P>
<P>
   ``He clearly would have been the first Mexican-American governor
or senator. I think that was almost a certainty,'' said Jerry
Polinard, a political science professor at the University of
Texas-Pan American in Edinburg, Texas. ``He so clearly was the
anointed one. This was the future of Texas politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Polinard is not alone in dating the Democrats' current political
difficulties in Texas to October 1988, when Cisneros confessed what
he called his ``close personal friendship'' with Jones, then known
as Linda Medlar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a loss that had a major ripple effect,'' Polinard said.
``They really had hitched their wagon to his star. There was no one
else there to step up to the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many of Cisneros' allies thought that he could overcome
his personal indiscretions. By the end of 1989, he had reconciled
with his wife, Mary Alice, and seemed to restore his family ties.
He got another chance at political rehabilitation when newly
elected Bill Clinton nominated him for the HUD job.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone conversation secretly taped by Jones, Cisneros
speculated about the impact that his new job would have on his
political future. The tapes, which included talk of Cisneros'
payments to his former girlfriend, led to the indictment that cut
short his HUD appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this job takes me out of circulation in Texas because,
I mean, you know, this agency is thought of as a minority agency,
(a) black agency, a big-city agency, (a) housing projects agency,''
he said in mulling over the nomination. ``It doesn't have any
stroke in Amarillo (or) Midland.''
</P>
<P>
   In another phone call, Cisneros acknowledged the pull of
politics when Jones asked him about rumors that he planned to
challenge Republican Sen. Phil Gramm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't particularly want to be in the United States Senate,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, you want to be governor,'' Jones replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you know I would if I could,'' Cisneros conceded, ``but
I see John Sharp ahead of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharp, the former Texas comptroller, lost a race for lieutenant
governor last year.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Cisneros could re-start his political career, he might
not want to give up his lucrative private-sector job, especially in
light of his legal bills. Univision's stock has been soaring since
he became the network's top executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people, when they get caught in this kind of thing,
lose their fire for politics. They feel burned,'' Riddlesperger
said. ``This is a guy with really great talent. He's bright, he's
articulate, he ambitious. He had everything going for him. It's a
human tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Polinard speculated that Cisneros has probably reached a similar
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine that in the loneliness of night, sometimes when he's
sitting by himself, there's a point where what might have been
comes to mind,'' he said. ``I don't know how you'd prevent that. It
must be difficult to look up and say, not only what might have been
for me but what might I have been able to do for others.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
