<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3747 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ART-NEWSEASON-KIMMELM     09-07 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NEWSEASON-KIMMELMAN-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 MOMA SHOWS GRASP THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Belgium, Mexico, The Netherlands)   (For release Sunday, Sept. 12) 
 &HT;    (DW) 
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The painter James Ensor, the great Belgian eccentric
of 19th-century art, developed his style looking at Bosch and
Bruegel. He was thoroughly European. Jose Guadalupe Posada, his
contemporary, a native of Aguascalientes, Mexico, apprenticed in
the workshop of a renowned Mexican broadsheet publisher, Antonio
Vanegas Arroyo. He became a printmaker of big, cheap, mass-produced
engravings in Mexico City.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ensor nor Posada seems to have had the slightest idea
that the other existed. They lived far apart. They didn't really
belong to the same profession, considering that Posada was part of
the Mexican graphic tradition of newspaper satire, and Ensor,
although he made prints that closely paralleled Posada's, was never
an illustrator in a journalistic sense. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But they are to be paired in ``Modern Starts'' at the Museum of
Modern Art, a giant exhibition that opens Oct. 7. The first in a
series of three shows, each of which will occupy the entire museum,
``Modern Starts'' will focus on art from 1880 to 1920. The two
subsequent shows will cover 1920 to 1960 and 1960 to now.
Altogether, they extend into the winter of 2001, a vast enterprise,
and include works from the museum's own collection and commissions.
``Modern Starts'' has commissioned works from Sol LeWitt, Michael
Craig-Martin and Maria Fernanda Cardoso. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the Modern having embarked on its latest expansion, the
exhibitions are experiments in preparation for the new building,
which won't be completed for several years. The museum wants to
test ways of displaying the history of modern art to supplement the
version that it has stuck to pretty much for as long as it has been
around, which is now the classic account of modernism, with one
historical movement succeeding another, from Impressionism to
Cubism to Abstract Expressionism to Pop and so on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every version of history being tendentious, the Modern's story
has left out a lot of what took place in the past, an elegant
narrative, too pat for some tastes. ``MOMA 2000,'' as the three
combined exhibitions are called, is an attempt to appease the
critics, expand the museum's account of the past and exploit its
own resources: by putting Ensor with Posada, for example, two
artists not generally on view.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Modern Starts'' is being organized by a team of curators from
different departments _ already a novelty at a museum historically
so balkanized that simply exhibiting paintings with prints, mixing
media overseen by different departments _ is a radical move. John
Elderfield, the museum's chief curator at large, who did the recent
Matisse and Bonnard shows, has teamed with Peter Reed, a curator of
architecture and design, Mary Chan, a curatorial assistant in the
department of drawings, Elizabeth Levine, from the department of
painting and sculpture, Maria Carmen Gonzalez, from the department
of education, and George Bareford, an assistant to Elderfield. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, they have decided to split the exhibition into
three categories: people, places and things. The layout won't be
chronological or by style, medium or nationality. Good works will
occasionally be with not such good ones. The show won't even stick
strictly to its period: Cezanne's male bather is twinned with a
1993 photograph by Rineke Dijkstra, a Dutch photographer, showing a
boy on a beach, the idea being that the two works be seen to share
a common source in the academic tradition of posed models and a
similarly awkward interpretation of it.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The other day, in an office he is occupying during the museum's
renovation, Elderfield shuffled Xeroxed pictures of the works in
the show around a bulletin board, figuring out their arrangement.
Tacked to a wall were pictures of an 1894 poster of ``Hamlet,''
with Picasso's ``Harlequin'' from 1915 and Andre Derain's
``Rehearsal'' from 1933. A photograph by Cartier-Bresson,
``Alicante, Spain,'' of three gesturing women, hung a foot away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elderfield wondered aloud whether the photograph might be put
with the Derain and the ``Hamlet'' poster, as examples of
theatrical gesture in the people section. The works wouldn't
normally be presented together, of course, being separated by time,
medium and style, not to mention quality, but having created a
subcategory called actors, dancers and bathers, the curators found
that disparate works fit more or less in a group. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cartier-Bresson photograph seemed to go particularly well,
Elderfield decided, with the Derain. Cartier-Bresson, a modernist,
and Derain, who was pretty much a reactionary as a painter, knew
each other and belonged to a social circle in Paris that also
included Balthus. Linking them _ or, for that matter, linking
Matisse with Picasso or Posada with Ensor _ may ultimately be more
relevant to understanding the past than pairing Cartier-Bresson
with Atget or Matisse with Dufy or Picasso with Metzinger,
according to style.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether an unusually improvisatory
experiment for the Modern will turn out to look just vague from an
outsider's perspective. Like displays of the permanent collection
before, it promises to be mostly French. There won't be much
Surrealism, or much Italian Futurism or Russian Constructivism _
even less than usual. American artists are thin on the ground. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But at the end of a century whose history of art the museum has
significantly defined, ``Modern Starts'' at least suggests that the
Modern is preparing to think in terms of a new perspective for the
next millennium. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
