<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3748 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-THEATER-NEWSEASON-BRA     09-07 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NEWSEASON-BRANTLEY-ART-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 CROSSING FINGERS, BROADWAY SINGS A HAPPY TUNE  (ART ADV: Photo,
graphic and map are being sent. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 12)  By   BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Where, you may well ask, do you find hope in a field
of ashes?
</P>
<P>
   That would seem to be the landscape of the Broadway musical at
the moment, at least as seen from the vantage point of the end of
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Running a short gamut from the merely proficient (the bloodless
anthology revue, ``Fosse'') to the simply appalling (``Footloose,''
``The Civil War''), from ambitious exercises in earnestness
(``Parade'') to spirit-crushing revisions of classics (``Annie Get
Your Gun''), the song-and-dance shows that opened during the
1998-99 theater season indicated that this most American of popular
art forms was dangerously low on oxygen at the end of the century
in which it was born.
</P>
<P>
   Hope, however, springs as buoyantly in the hearts of the genre's
diehard fans as it does in an uptempo Irving Berlin song. There is
the bright flicker of promise in the slate of musicals that begin
opening this fall, enough to make us all look past such pre-sold
theme-park hits as the mechanical stage version of ``Saturday Night
Fever.''
</P>
<P>
   First, two words guaranteed to inspire optimism: Stephen
Sondheim. No single artist has done more to extend the boundaries
and forms of the musical over the last several decades, and that
this composer and lyricist will again be represented on Broadway,
with his first new offering since ``Passion'' (1994), is
automatically cause to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wise Guys,'' the story of two archetypal American dreamers and
schemers of the 1920s, the Mizner brothers, would seem to offer
especially fertile terrain for Sondheim: a chance to again
anatomize both all-American ambition (as he did in ``Merrily We
Roll Along'' and ``Assassins'') and the show business legacy of
vaudeville (as in ``Follies''). It should be added that few
performers today embody that legacy with the style and swagger of
Nathan Lane, who will be playing one half of the fraternal team of
the title. (His co-star is another nicely seasoned pro, Victor
Garber.)
</P>
<P>
   That Lane, who was temporarily marooned in the world of film and
television, still has what it takes to capture a theater audience
was amply demonstrated when he appeared last season in the brief
run of ``Do Re Mi,'' part of the priceless Encores series of
vintage American musicals in concert at City Center. It is also
heartening that one of the actors with whom Lane shared the stage
in ``Do Re Mi,'' Brian Stokes Mitchell, will also be on the boards
again in the revival of Cole Porter's ode to Broadway narcissism,
``Kiss Me, Kate.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, who registered as an intense dramatic presence in
``Ragtime,'' demonstrated a self-parodying suaveness and vital sex
appeal in ``Do Re Mi'' that should translate ideally into the
backstage (and onstage) posturings of ``Kate,'' which is directed
by Michael Blakemore and choreographed by Kathleen Marshall, the
inventive artistic director of Encores.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another seriously talented performer who sparkled
seductively in a recent Encores production (``St. Louis Woman''),
Vanessa Williams, is expected to return in the New York Shakespeare
Festival's production on Broadway of ``The Wild Party,'' the
composer Michael John LaChiusa's adaptation of Joseph Moncure
March's narrative poem about Prohibition-era hedonism. Ms. Williams
will not necessarily walk away with the show entirely, however,
given that its other stars are likely to include Mandy Patinkin,
who has rarely met a scene he couldn't steal, and the eternal,
slinky siren Eartha Kitt.
</P>
<P>
   LaChiusa, one of the more intriguing descendants of the School
of Sondheim, will also be represented by the Lincoln Center Theater
production of his ``Marie Christine.'' This American retelling of
``Medea'' stars the incandescent Audra McDonald, the young
three-time Tony winner and arguably the finest vocal interpreter of
the new generation of theater composers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McDonald's presence alone turns ``Marie Christine'' into an
Event, just as the presence of a star of another but equally
alluring stripe, Carol Burnett, makes an Event out of the Broadway
show in which she stars, ``Putting It Together.'' That, by the way,
is a revue of songs about relationships by Sondheim, who bids fair
to own the forthcoming season, the last of this century. Given that
he has done more than any other individual in recent years to keep
the American musical breathing, this seems entirely appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
