<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-WHITMAN-SENATE-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN STUNNING ANNOUNCEMENT, WHITMAN SAYS SHE WILL NOT RUN FOR
SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Facing the daunting task of raising the millions
of dollars needed to mount a campaign for the U.S. Senate, Gov.
Christie Whitman reversed course Tuesday and said she no longer
planned to run for the seat being vacated next year by Sen. Frank
Lautenberg, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's announcement stunned leaders of both political parties
and sent New Jersey Republicans scrambling to identify another
candidate capable of beating either of the two leading Democratic
candidates: Jon S. Corzine, the former chairman of Goldman Sachs &AMP;
Co., or former Gov. James Florio, whom Whitman narrowly defeated in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Haytaian, head of New Jersey Republican Party, said
Whitman's move ``leaves us in a position without a front-runner for
the nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference at the New Jersey Statehouse, Whitman said
she had made the decision while on a recent family vacation after
determining that a race would be ``a distraction from finishing the
work New Jersey voters had asked me to complete.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about whether I can run for the United States
Senate and at the same time fulfill my duties as governor,''
Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters after the announcement, Whitman said that
she was also concerned about ``the amount of money that needs to be
raised and just the time that it takes to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In private conversations with aides and associates, Whitman was
said to have acknowledged that the demands of fund-raising, and the
prospect of needing to outspend Corzine, who is estimated to have a
net worth of $300 million, had become a factor in her decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her heart wasn't in the grueling prospect of raising money and
facing up to a multimillionaire,'' said a Republican political
consultant from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's announcement surprised some of her campaign advisers,
who said she had had little trouble raising money _ more than $2
million so far.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, who has never run for public office and is virtually
unknown in state political circles, has said he will spend whatever
is necessary of his personal fortune to be competitive. He has
already given his campaign $500,000 in seed money.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at the Newark offices of his Senate exploratory
committee, Corzine said that Whitman's departure would sharpen his
battle with Florio for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does raise the intensity and focus that falls on the
Democratic primary,'' Corzine said. ``The Republicans will
undoubtedly come up with a formidable and well-financed
candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was clear Tuesday that Whitman's decision instantly
reversed the political momentum, prompting Democrats to predict
easy victory in next November's election while sending Republican
hopes into a political freefall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Governor Whitman in the race, the Democratic nominee
clearly becomes the favorite,'' Sen. Robert Torricelli said in a
telephone interview Tuesday afternoon. ``It greatly increases our
chances of gaining control in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Independent polls taken over the summer showed that Whitman was
faring well with the state's voters. A Quinnipiac College poll
released in July showed Whitman leading Florio by 52 percent to 35
percent in a possible race, and leading Corzine by 56 percent to 22
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The politics were very much in her favor,'' said Roger A.
Bodman, a Republican political strategist who was advising
Whitman's exploratory committee. ``But campaign fund-raising is
enormously time consuming. She just found that it would interfere
too much with her gubernatorial duties.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of her remarks Tuesday, Whitman refused to concede
her decision has left her party reeling for a substitute, saying,
``I don't think I'm the only Republican who could win this seat.''
</P>
<P>
   She declined to suggest anyone in particular, but within minutes
of her announcement, the names of several possible replacement
candidates began bubbling in Republican circles, among them Lewis
M. Eisenberg, chairman of the Port Authority of New York and New
Jersey; Rep. Robert Franks; Jim Treffinger, the Essex County
executive; Rep. Frank LoBiondo, and state Sen. William Gormley.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Whoever the candidate is, Democrats and Republicans said, he or
she will need to raise a large amount of money to compete with
Corzine. And Florio, an old-line Democrat who, though voted out of
office six years ago, can boast of years of experience as governor.
``The Republican campaign is going to have build $10 million in a
little over 12 months,'' Torricelli said. ``It could be done, but
it's never been done before.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's election to the Senate in 2000 was hardly a sure
thing. In a state with more registered Independents than Democrats
or Republicans, Whitman won both her gubernatorial elections by a
combined margin of some 26,000 votes. And she has never been tested
in a campaign held in a year of national elections, when turnout
among Democrats is usually highest.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, rumors about other reasons for Whitman's
abrupt turnabout surfaced in Trenton, ranging from concern over her
health to her availability to become Texas Gov. George W. Bush's
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Neither rumor carried a shred of truth, Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers said they were apprised of Whitman's decision
during a brief telephone conversation shortly before 3 p.m. as Bush
rode through New Hampshire in a multistop presidential campaign
tour.
</P>
<P>
   Asked his reaction, Bush said, ``I was surprised. I told her I
was sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the race to fill Lautenberg's Senate seat, Whitman's
decision also has profound impacts on New Jersey's gubernatorial
race in 2001. If Whitman had won the race, state Senate President
Donald T. DiFrancesco would have become acting governor and the
likely frontrunner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a disappointment,'' DiFrancesco said Tuesday.
``From a personal standpoint, sure it would have been kind of neat
to be there as acting governor. Now we need to rally around another
candidate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 2054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
