<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3750 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-WACO-INQUIRY-NYT &LR;      09-07 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER SENATOR LIKELY TO INVESTIGATE CULT SIEGE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Texas)  (rk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno has all but decided to
select Republican former Sen. John Danforth of Missouri to head an
independent investigation into the FBI's disastrous assault on the
Branch Davidian compound in 1993, law enforcement officials said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials continued Tuesday to review
Danforth's background and deliberated the breadth of the legal
mandate for the re-examination of the ill-fated tear-gas operation
and deadly fire that swept through the ramshackle building near
Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and her aides have concluded that they have little
alternative but to grant Danforth wide latitude to fully explore
every aspect of the Waco operation, the officials said. He is
likely to be granted full prosecutorial power to summon witnesses,
seek documents, videotapes and other materials, and convene a
federal grand jury should he determine that one is needed to
complete his inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Reno had been close to offering Danforth the job over the
weekend, and Danforth had said he would accept the position, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But she wavered and at one point considered dropping him as a
candidate when Justice Department officials learned that Danforth _
when he was a senator _ had contacted the Justice Department on
behalf of a company with a legal matter pending before the agency.
But the contact was deemed to be a routine inquiry, not an effort
to interfere with the process.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Reno was said to have settled on Danforth and was
preparing to offer him the job, the officials said, in part because
initial feedback from Republicans in Congress, who have been most
critical of Reno, was positive and suggested that Danforth would
bring immediate credibility to what is almost certain to be a
controversial inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth's associates would not discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Reno's motives in selecting Danforth seemed clear, his
reasons for taking the job were less apparent. An Episcopal priest,
with a long commitment to public service, Danforth was known in the
Senate as a principled politician and moderate conservative. He
once said that what he liked most about the chamber was a ``a
fight, a big fight.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Waco inquiry he would face a fractious battle and fierce
partisan rivalries. Waco has become a battle cry among
anti-government critics who blame the FBI for the deaths of about
80 people, including children, in the Branch Davidian compound,
even as an official inquiry by the Justice Department concluded
flatly that the evidence showed overwhelmingly that the Davidians
were responsible for igniting the deadly fire.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, who is 63 years old, was once attorney general in
Missouri. He served three terms in the Senate and retired in 1994
to return to a private law practice in St. Louis. In the upper
chamber, Danforth was an ardent defender of Clarence Thomas during
a tumultuous confirmation battle in 1991 when Thomas was accused of
sexual harassment before the Senate narrowly confirmed him to a
seat on the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Reno prepared to give the job to Danforth after she endured a
week of withering criticism over disclosures that FBI agents had
fired combustible tear gas canisters on the morning of the April
19, 1993, siege. For years, Reno and FBI officials insisted that
they had done nothing that could have ignited the fire that ravaged
the cultists' compound.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has been under intense pressure to seek a Republican
outsider to head the inquiry since the FBI acknowledged last week
that it had found in its files infrared videotapes which showed
that agents had sought and received permission to fire the
flammable tear-gas rounds from Richard Rogers, the former commander
of the Hostage Rescue Team, the FBI's elite paramilitary unit which
carried out the assault.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials have said that they cannot explain why the tapes
did not surface earlier. But they added that the new information
does not change their conclusions about who started the fire.
</P>
<P>
   They said that the agents shot the combustible tear-gas rounds
hours before the fire broke out. They said the round bounced
harmlessly off a concrete bunker many yards from the main compound
and that only nonburning tear gas was used during the assault on
the main compound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
