<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF: GERMANY; FRANCE; RUSSIA; IRAN; MEXICO;
BRAZIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: PESSIMISM ON PEACE
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Northern Ireland's smaller parties gave former Sen.
George Mitchell little encouragement in the second day of his
mission to mediate the deadlocked peace settlement. The accord has
stalled over Protestant politicians' refusal to let Sinn Fein take
part in the province's new government unless its Irish Republican
Army allies start to disarm. Eileen Bell of the non-sectarian
Alliance Party said, ``I can only hope that at the end of the day
common sense and decency will prevail, but there is little sense of
either at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: BASQUE PRISONER TRANSFER
</P>
<P>
   The government will transfer 105 Basque prisoners to jails
closer to their homes in northern Spain, in a move to try to revive
the stalled Basque peace effort a year after the separatist group
ETA declared a cease-fire. It is the largest transfer ever of
Basque prisoners, affecting a quarter of the 405 Basque militants,
convicted or awaiting trial, in Spanish jails.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: SCHROEDER ON SLAVE TALKS
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting with leading German industrialists, Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder said financial claims from American and German
lawyers representing forced laborers exploited by the Nazis were
``completely unrealistic.'' His remarks suggested that a settlement
under which German companies and the government would compensate
victims of slave labor and forced labor is not imminent. The
companies made an initial offer of about $1.7 billion, which has
been met by claims for over $20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   EGYPT: 4 MILITANTS KILLED
</P>
<P>
   The police said they killed four members of the banned Islamic
Group faction in a shootout in Cairo, a day after security officers
with President Hosni Mubarak in Port Said shot to death a man they
said had struck the president's hand with a sharp object. The
incidents were unrelated, according to the police, who said the
slain Port Said man had no known criminal record or radical
political affiliations.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: PEACE FEELERS
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to restart peace talks with the Zapatista rebels in
Chiapas, the government announced that it would investigate attacks
on Zapatistas by government supporters, free some jailed rebels and
create a new team of mediators. Interior Minister Diodoro Carrasco
also called on the Senate to hold hearings on Indian rights.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   NORTH KOREA: BERLIN TALKS OPENING
</P>
<P>
   Delegations from the United States and North Korea met in Berlin
for talks aimed at easing tensions and persuading North Korea to
abandon its missile program. The discussions, part of a series
started three years ago, will be the first since North Korea said
it would use force if necessary to defend a unilateral extension of
its territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: PREMIER PICKS HIS TIME
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee filed his papers to contest
the Oct. 3 election from his district in the city of Lucknow in
Uttar Pradesh at 12:25 p.m., precisely the time that astrologers
had told him would be the most auspicious for his bid. The
72-year-old Vajpayee has won in Lucknow in all three elections
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: KASHMIR CANDIDATE KILLED
</P>
<P>
   Ghulam Hyder Noorani, who was seeking a seat in Parliament from
Kashmir for the Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, was
killed in a land-mine blast as he was driving 30 miles south of
Srinagar. The Sept. 18 election scheduled for the district has been
postponed. Separatist militants have called for a boycott of the
elections.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: SCHOOLS CLOSED IN PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Catholic schools across the state of Orissa closed to protest
the killing of a Catholic priest in a remote hamlet by a mob firing
bows and arrows.
</P>
</TEXT>
