<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIACOM-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS SEE DEAL AS ACT I IN WAVE OF CONSOLIDATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With VIACOM-CBS, VIACOM-NEW-MEDIA, VIACOM-MARKETPLACE,
VIACOM-AD-COLUMN) 
(th) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ To top entertainment industry executives and talent
agents, the acquisition of CBS by Viacom is not merely the largest
media marriage ever. It also accelerates the pressure and momentum
for further deals in the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will bring about a new wave of consolidations, make these
companies even bigger,'' said David Geffen, a partner at the film
and music company Dreamworks SKG. ``It's a very powerful merger.
They always come in waves. Everyone becomes competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Howard Stringer, chairman and chief executive of Sony
Corporation of America, said in a telephone interview from New
York, ``After a deal like this, the urge to merge becomes feverish.
And right now temperatures are soaring all over the city.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC, owned by General Electric Co., is now the only major
network left without a film studio and an entertainment industry
partner. By contrast, Walt Disney Co. owns ABC, News Corp. owns Fox
Broadcasting and now Viacom has a pending deal with CBS. Even
before Tuesday, there had been industry rumors of talks between NBC
and Time Warner. Executives said the talks had only reached a
preliminary stage and never got off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Among the television station properties that are also possible
merger targets are Paxson Communications, USA Networks, the Tribune
Broadcasting Group and Hearst-Argyle.
</P>
<P>
   Even more significant, several entertainment industry giants,
including Universal and Sony, are without television networks that
are almost crucial as outlets. But Sony, a Japanese company, is
hampered by government restrictions on foreign ownership of
broadcast networks, while Universal, a unit of Seagram Co., has
sharply diminished its television business to focus on films and
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like musical chairs,'' said Jeff Logsdon, an
entertainment analyst at Seidler Cos. ``You keep taking away one
more chair. There's a scarcity issue now. Disney has ABC. Warner
Brothers starts their own network and is in a fledgling stage of
success,'' he added, referring to Time Warner's WB network. ``CBS
now merges with Viacom. So NBC is sitting there. Whom do they go
after?''
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment industry executives generally applauded the
Viacom-CBS deal as a good fit, especially in terms of television
programming and distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, CBS, the nation's No. 1 network in household
ratings and total viewers, will be allied with Viacom's Paramount,
a television and film studio that will most certainly provide
programs for its network.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount has several shows on CBS, including ``JAG,''
``Becker'' and ``Nash Bridges.'' Another show, ``Diagnosis
Murder,'' is produced by Viacom Productions, another unit of the
company. And in the season that starts this month, two shows are
co-produced by CBS and Paramount, ``Now and Again'' and ``Love &AMP;
Money.''
</P>
<P>
   Viacom, in turn, gains access to a major network to promote its
films and cable programs. Less clear is how the merger will affect
top television executives at both companies, as well as the fate of
UPN, a network that is 50 percent owned by Viacom and has not found
its niche yet among television audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's positive for both of them,'' said Lee Gabler, the top
television agent at the Creative Artists Agency. ``It's no secret
that UPN has been struggling and trying to build a network, and CBS
is looking for a younger demographic. It gives CBS a studio that
they've been lacking.''
</P>
<P>
   Another top television executive said that the deal should help
shield Viacom and CBS from the vagaries of film and television
production.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie side of Paramount was an albatross around Viacom's
neck, and the CBS network was an albatross around CBS' neck,'' said
the executive, who insisted on anonymity. ``They've now created a
company so big that the relative performance of next week's new
movie and next week's television show is diminished. You've
insulated the stock from weak performance.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive added, ``You now have a bunch of businesses with
more predictable earnings flow. This takes the volatility out of
what you're doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
