<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     09-07 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GUGA LEAVES SORE BACKS IN HIS WAKE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Watch out for Gustavo Kuerten. He is the most gentle
soul on the tennis tour _ a trace of the samba in his walk, a hint
of a Brazilian beach in his smile _ but watch out for him, all the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Just by being on the same court with them, he has dispatched two
players from the U.S. Open, with sudden pain in their lower backs.
</P>
<P>
   First, he sent Pete Sampras home from a practice session before
the tournament ever began. Then he disrupted Magnus Norman's
alignment in one set Tuesday in the round of 16, without setting a
pick or tackling anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Kuerten is the human version of the killer artificial turf at
Giants Stadium, which disabled a Jets football receiver and a
MetroStars soccer midfielder in the past week without being touched
by friend or foe. In all, seven players have retired from Open
matches with injuries and three others withdrew beforehand, but
Kuerten is leading the league with two notches on his racquet.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't look like the poltergeist type. Known as Guga in the
one-name Brazilian fashion, Kuerten doesn't seem to have a mean
bone in his body. Or any bones at all. Willowy at 6 feet 3 inches
and allegedly 167 pounds, he seems a throwback to an age when most
tennis players could not be imagined committing any other form of
sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``How come you never became a soccer player?'' somebody asked
Kuerten Tuesday , a reasonable question of a man from the spiritual
home of the world's most popular sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never watch me play soccer,'' he said with a laugh that
caused reporters to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Guga has that impact on people. Still two days short of turning
23, he has lived with his image of the onetime wonder who sambaed
his way through the 1997 French Open and supports a school for poor
children in his hometown, but has not won a Grand Slam event since.
``You know, I'm play a lot of match,'' Kuerten said Tuesday in
charming English. ``I won four match here in the Open. I don't have
to be worry about the surface anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   He came here as the fifth-seeded player and was practicing with
Sampras when Pete suddenly lumbered off the court, later to be
found to have a herniated disk in the lower back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I think sometimes you get injuries just that happen,''
Kuerten said. ``Like you drive your car, you have an accident. It's
the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   He had the same effect Tuesday on Norman, who felt a pain in his
back late in the first set and retired after losing the tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's things that can happen to your body,'' Kuerten said. ``We
all human. We have to know that these things can happen. Just try
to pass over and come back next time.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a wonderful relaxed attitude that may very well be
popular in Brazil _ except when the Selecao, the national soccer
team, loses a game. Somebody asked Kuerten if he had heard any
Brazilian fans in the stands, and he said: ``Not today. It's too
early.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazilians all party yesterday,'' he said, referring to Labor
Day. ``Nobody came,'' he added about Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He did have a big crowd Sunday night when he knocked off the
fading Croatian blaster, Goran Ivanisevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before this match against Ivanisevic, it was great
atmosphere,'' he said. ``A lot of people there. They was going
crazy. People start to go for Ivanisevic, the Americans, because
they saw there was a lot of Brazilians. That's the way I think it
should be.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled having a Brazilian band show up in staid Cincinnati
for a Davis Cup meeting with the United States, but he added:
``Normally, I don't know, it's kind of big to bring over. I don't
know if they allow to get on court with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennis would surely be different with the ubiquitous
do-it-yourself samba band that follows the Brazilian soccer team
all over the world. ``Yeah, a lot of fun,'' he said. ``Changeover,
they keep dancing. It's nice.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked his views on the national soccer team, he showed far
more animation for his favorite club in Brazil, Avai _ ``like
Hawaii. You don't know my team, is in the second league now. I like
my team players, but they not famous.''
</P>
<P>
   Temperamentally, Guga said, he likes the strikers like Ronaldo
and Romario and Rivaldo, the geniuses who create goals, but in this
tournament he has had more in common with Dunga and other defensive
stalwarts who leave opponents sprawling and stricken.
</P>
<P>
   His next opponent is Cedric Pioline from the country that beat
Brazil in the World Cup final in 1998. The bongos might return for
this one. And Pioline just might want to watch his back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0351 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3785 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-VIACOM-CBS-ART-2NDTAK     09-07 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIACOM-CBS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the middle.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new company will be called Viacom, but the CBS television
network and all its units will continue to be called CBS. And
viewers will not suddenly find music videos appearing on CBS;
indeed, both Redstone and Karmazin said Tuesday that CBS News, CBS
Entertainment and CBS Sports will continue to be run much the way
they have been, under the leadership of Leslie Moonves, who is to
continue overseeing them.
</P>
<P>
   But the merger could mean, for example, that Viacom's MTV and
VH-1 music cable channels will find new outlets for their
programming on CBS' rock radio stations around the country _ just
as CBS' own cable channels, Country Music Television and The
Nashville Network, now provide programs for some of CBS'
country-music radio stations. And each will heavily promote its
sister networks.
</P>
<P>
   And promotional spots on MTV or VH-1 could induce some younger
viewers to sample shows on CBS, helping the broadcast network
eventually attract more of the 18-to-49-year-old audience that
advertisers pay the biggest premiums to reach.
</P>
<P>
   The merger could also mean that Nickelodeon _ the most
profitable children's network, whether broadcast or cable _ would
provide programming to help bolster CBS' little-watched
Saturday-morning children's lineup.
</P>
<P>
   On the new media front, several of Viacom's networks, notably
MTV and Nickelodeon, have well-established and very popular Web
sites. Karmazin said Tuesday that it was his goal to make
Viacom-CBS one of the leading new media companies, adding that this
goal could be given a substantial boost by the promotional
opportunities available through the company's television and radio
networks and its outdoor advertising unit, the largest in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The new company will have to divest itself of some broadcast
properties, or seek waivers from federal regulations. Redstone and
Karmazin said they would visit the Federal Communications
Commission Wednesday to appeal for changes in certain rules.
</P>
<P>
   The most important, to them, is the cap on television station
ownership, which restricts any company to owning stations that
reach no more than 35 percent of the country's population.
</P>
<P>
   With Viacom's 19 television stations and CBS' 15, the combined
company would own stations in 18 of the nation's top 20 markets and
reach 41 percent of the population. If the cap is not raised,
Karmazin said, the company will probably sell some stations to
comply with the regulations.
</P>
<P>
   But Karmazin and Redstone spoke of their eagerness to create new
business opportunities out of their six potential duopolies _
ownership of two stations in the same market. They have six such
potential duopolies, in Philadelphia, Boston, Detroit, Dallas,
Miami and Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom also owns half of the UPN broadcast network, with
Chris-Craft, and under FCC rules that stake must be reduced to less
than one-third (unless an FCC waiver is granted).
</P>
<P>
   Redstone took pains to point out that UPN, which has struggled
with small audiences for most of its existence, has been ``doing
much better'' with a new focus on young male audiences.
</P>
<P>
   For the CBS television network, an important Viacom asset is
Paramount, the studio that produced the film ``Titanic'' and the
television show ``Frasier'' (on NBC), and that will now undoubtedly
create more television shows for CBS.
</P>
<P>
   But Moonves said Tuesday that he saw the model being more like
the Fox network's relationship with its corporate sibling,
Twentieth Television, than like ABC's dealings with Disney. Disney
recently combined management of its television studio and broadcast
network, with the goal of producing more hits for ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's sister studio, in contrast, produces shows for all the
networks, and Moonves said he expected Paramount to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we did feel like a second-class citizen,'' he said, ``when
we saw the advantages ABC-Disney had, and Fox had, and even the WB
had, having a direct link to a studio.'' The WB network is linked
to the Warner Brothers studio, and both are owned by Time-Warner.
</P>
<P>
   NBC is now the only one of the six major broadcast networks
without a major production studio in its corporate family.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
