u f BC-MARINEAU-LEVI-NYT &LR;      09-07 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINEAU-LEVI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN EFFORT TO REVITALIZE, LEVI STRAUSS HIRES OUTSIDER AS TOP
EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill.)  (See also MARINEAU-PEPSI) 
(DW) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an effort to revitalize an iconic brand that has lost some of
its cachet, Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. has gone outside its controlling
family for a leader for only the second time in its 146-year
history.
</P>
<P>
   The company said Tuesday that Philip Marineau, the executive
given credit for helping to bring new energy to the Pepsi brand,
would take over as president and chief executive on Sept. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Although successful at the cola giant, Marineau, the president
and chief executive of Pepsi-Cola North America, had a mixed record
as a marketer at the Quaker Oats Co., where he worked for 23 years.
Robert Haas, the family member who has been most closely involved
in running Levi Strauss over the last decade, will continue as
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Levi, the maker of Slates, Dockers and Levi 501 jeans, has been
engaged in a desperate and mostly unsuccessful battle to reverse
the shrinking of its market share. In 1998, revenue dropped 13
percent, to $6 billion, largely because young people were
abandoning Levi's five-pocket button-fly jeans in favor of designer
brands like Tommy Hilfiger or cheaper private-label brands like the
Arizona line sold by J.C. Penney. In February, the company, which
prided itself on making blue jeans in America when many other
manufacturers had moved production overseas, closed half its sewing
plants in North America and laid off 5,900 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Levi has been looking for a president since January, when Peter
Jacobi announced his retirement. The company has made no secret
that it was looking outside of the company for an executive with
experience in consumer products instead of fashion. Still, the
company, which is feeling a bit burned by recent media coverage of
its problems, issued a terse statement hinting at what it hoped to
accomplish by selecting Marineau. `` Marineau is highly regarded as
a talented brand builder and an innovative leader with a track
record of expanding market share in competitive environments,'' the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   Marineau made his reputation at Gatorade, a division of Quaker
Oats. During his 23 years with the company, he was part of the
executive team that expanded sales of the brand to more than $1
billion from $85 million when it was acquired in 1983. Marineau was
also a key player in the decision to buy Snapple, the quirky maker
of noncola drinks, for $1.7 billion in 1994. Poor marketing and
disastrous repositioning caused loyal consumers to abandon the
brand and Quaker was forced to sell it for a $1.4 billion loss to
Triarc in 1997. Marineau, who left Quaker in 1995, was blamed by
many for the fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   After serving as president of Dean Foods Co., the dairy and
vegetable processor in Franklin Park, Ill., for 10 months, Marineau
joined Pepsi where he quickly set about reinvigorating a tired
brand. He is credited with two marketing coups that might be
relevant to his new role as Levi chief. First, he helped create
Pepsi One, a new diet soft drink. ``The rollout of Pepsi One was
very effective,'' said John Sicher, editor and publisher of
Beverage Digest, who says the 1.4 percent market share the cola has
achieved is impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Marineau's other noted achievement was scrapping the
``Generation Next'' advertising campaign, which had an
unconventional tone that was supposed to appeal to those younger
than 25, in favor of a more broadly focused ``Joy of Cola''
campaign. It is too soon to say whether the new campaign will make
a difference with consumers, but it is popular among the company's
analysts and bottlers. Levi's advertising is now focused on
recapturing the youth market, but it is unclear whether Marineau
will make widening the appeal a new priority.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the announcement of the new chief executive, Levi
has taken several steps to revitalize its brand. Last month, it
opened a new flagship store in San Francisco that featured
attractions like a hot tub where teen-agers could hang out to
shrink jeans and a custom-design embroidery station. In Europe, the
company recently introduced an ``engineered'' blue jean that has
pockets lower down the pants leg than traditional jeans and side
seams that bend to fit the way legs move.
</P>
<P>
   While consumer products executives have been successful at
leading fashion companies before _ Paul Charron moved from Procter
&AMP; Gamble to Vanity Fair and then to Liz Claiborne _ many Levi's
analysts think that Marineau's lack of experience in the fickle
world of teen-age clothing tastes could be a real drawback.
``Apparel no matter how basic has a minimal shelf life'' said Harry
Bernard, a senior partner with Colton Bernard, a marketing
consultant based in San Francisco. ``That means you have to come up
with a new Pepsi One not once, but season after season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 2127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
