<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3801 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-PUERTO-CLELMENCY-BOS &LR;      09-07 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTO-CLELMENCY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENCY ACCEPTANCES THREATEN RODHAM CLINTON CANDIDACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A group of Puerto Rican nationalists convicted for
a series of terrorist bomb attacks have accepted a presidential
offer of clemency, ending their lengthy imprisonment but leaving
behind a political firestorm that threatens the Senate candidacy of
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The White House announced Tuesday that 12 of the 14 inmates, who
were part of a Puerto Rican group called FALN, for Armed Forces of
National Liberation, had agreed to renounce violence _ a condition
of the clemency offer. Two inmates are expected to reject the
offer, and two others, who are not in jail but could have their
fines reduced, have until Friday to respond.
</P>
<P>
   The case of the FALN members, convicted of committing more than
100 bomb attacks in the 1970s and 1980s, divided the Clintons and
created a political upset among key political forces in New York,
where Mrs. Clinton is exploring a US Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, Mrs. Clinton called for her husband's clemency
offer to be revoked, a move that plays well with New York's
law-and-order crowd but infuritated Puerto Rican activists in New
York City. Representative Jose Serrano, a Democrat of the Bronx,
was so angered by Mrs. Clinton's annoucement that he said he was
considering withdrawing support for her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The president, too, is taking heat for his offer of clemency.
Senator paul Coverdell, Republican of Georgia, said Tuesday he
would hold hearings to examine the ``departure from longstanding US
policy on terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mrs. Clinton's political aspirations, her statement last
weekend ``was not a good move,'' said Lee Miringoff of the Marist
Institute for Public Opinion, based in New York state. ``This did
not go over well with one of her core group'' constituencies, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mrs. Clinton and New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani have a
strong love-hate factor in their expected candidacies, Miringoff
said: People tend to feel very strongly about the very
strong-minded, strong-willed candidates.
</P>
<P>
   That makes the ``undecided'' vote smaller, and the need to fire
up core voter constituencies even more critical. Speaking out
against the convicted felons might win her a few points among law
enforcment, but Giuliani, a former federal prosecutor, already has
an edge in that arena, Miringoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton cannot afford to alienate Latino voters, an
important voter consituency that is likely to react more strongly _
and negatively _ to her comments about the FALN inmates, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, spokesman for Mrs. Clinton's exploratory
campaign, said the first lady ``understands that her friends feel
very strongly about this issue, but she stands by her statement.''
</P>
<P>
   The FALN issue isn't the first, and likely won't be the last,
issue that could separate her politically from her husband. On
matters ranging from foreign policy to budget issues, the first
lady will be forced to either defend or deride Clinton
administration policies that affect New York.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Mrs. Clinton has said she favors moving the Israeli
capital to Jerusalem from Tel Aviv (the administration opposes it),
and supports a dairy policy that would prop up milk prices in New
York. The US Agriculture Department opposes it.
</P>
<P>
   She is also being asked to pick sides on her husband's budget,
which would drastically cut federal spending for teaching
hospitals. New York would lose $5.2 billion over five years because
of the proposed cuts, and hospital administrators want Mrs.
Clinton's backing for a bill that would restore some of the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would expect New York state's senators to defend us to the
`nth' degree in Washington,'' irrespective of family connections,
said Ken Raske, president of the Greater New York Hospital
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Vice President Al Gore on the campaign trail
compicates things further, since Mrs. Clinton may be forced to
publicly disagree with the Democratic presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor Al Gore,'' said Miringoff. ``He has to run with one
Clinton, and against another.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Hope, chairwoman of the New York State Democratic Party,
said she didn't think Mrs. Clinton would suffer from her policy
disagreements with the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Clinton realizes that . . . the administration's policies
(sometimes) depart from what is in the best interests of New
Yorkers. When that happens, she might speak out. I think that's
what New Yorkers expect of her,'' Hope said.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the decision to offer
clemency ``was made on the merits,'' and was not intended to help
Mrs. Clinton's popularity among Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there have been many who sought to inject politics,
and many who have sought to inject a motive here, and all I can say
is that they're wrong,'' Lockhart told reporters Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
