<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3806 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     09-07 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COETZEE LEADS WAY FOR BLACK SOUTH AFRICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jeff Coetzee doesn't regard himself as a historic
figure. But he is one.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want to do,'' he says, ``is play tennis _ hopefully for
my country in Davis Cup _ get better, and be able to send some
money home to my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing unusual about that. What is unusual and makes
22-year-old professional Jeff Coetzee a pioneer is that it couldn't
have happened in his country, South Africa, only a few years ago.
You see, Coetzee is not a white man, and people of his shade did
not play games internationally for South Africa in the bad old days
of apartheid that ended in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But Coetzee is the breakthrough guy in tennis, the only South
African of color to compete in a major championship (Wimbledon, the
US Open), and to win a match: three here in doubles alongside white
countryman Brent Haygarth.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting across the table in a dining room at the US Open, he
reminds me of a rhyme that erstwhile poet Muhammad Ali used to
voice: ``I ain't got the right connection because I'm the wrong
complexion.''
</P>
<P>
   A slight but wiry 150-pounder, the 5-foot-8-inch Coetzee finds
that now his complexion is acceptable for export, and it is similar
to Ali's: caffe latte, complemented by a brief goatee, amiable
olive eyes, and close-cropped black hair.
</P>
<P>
   He reminds me, too, of a night in Johannesburg in 1973 when
Arthur Ashe _ previously unwelcome _ had won a diplomatic battle to
be included in the South African Open. Ashe, with skin resembling
Coetzee's, was startled by some resistance within the black
community. He had been scolded by a black journalist: ``You
shouldn't have come, Arthur. Nothing will change. They'll still be
kicking our ass after you leave, but the government will look good
for letting you in.''
</P>
<P>
   However, that night, we also encountered a genuine poet, Don
Mattera, considered a subversive by the government. Mattera
consoled Ashe: ``You were right to come, if only so our children
can see that a black man can be the equal or better than whites _
in your case, tennis. Someday apartheid will end, and the children
will have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The chance has come for Jeff Coetzee, and he has been making the
most of it lately. He and Haygarth attained the quarterfinals in
doubles, losing Tuesday, 6-3, 6-3, to the Swedish-Zimbabwean
coalition of Jonas Bjorkman and Byron Black.
</P>
<P>
   As gales lashed Flushing Meadow, Bjorkman caught the jet stream
with a winning lob on match point. Coetzee chased it vainly, almost
climbing the back fence of the Grandstand Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Jeff,'' Haygarth commends. ``He competes, he has heart.
He's not a heavy hitter, but he's smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Another white South African player, John DeJager, says, ``Jeff's
really coming along (up from nowhere to No. 109 in doubles, 217 in
singles) and it's good to see. He's on the Davis Cup squad, and I
think he'll play doubles soon. But he wants to be given nothing.
With our government now there's some sentiment that some guys of
color should be included on national teams whether they merit it or
not. Jeff would never accept that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll play only if he knows he belongs. When I started in
tennis, there would have been no chance for him. Even now it's
unlikely because they've started so far behind.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coetzee story is indeed unlikely. One of eight children of a
copper miner in the small town of Okiep (``no stoplights, two
tennis courts, beautiful wildflowers'') in the Northern Cape, Jeff
couldn't have emerged from a less promising background.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody in our family knew anything about tennis,'' said
Coetzee. ``But we saw Wimbledon on TV, and my brothers sawed some
wooden boards in the shape of rackets and made a net from onion
bags in the backyard. We got a rubber ball somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I finally got a racket, I was 9, and it was too heavy.
That's how I got my style,'' he said, explaining his
double-barreled strokes from both sides. ``An older brother would
drive me to Cape Town, about 350 miles, for junior tournaments, and
I started to win. They gave small prizes of cash, so I had to win
to pay for the petrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trouble? Some tournaments refused me because of color. And I
was called `kaffir' (a racial epithet) a few times. But I didn't
want to go where I wasn't wanted, and . . . well . . . names . . .
I put it out of mind. Things weren't bad in Okiep. I am considered
`colored,' and the colored are the majority there.''
</P>
<P>
   Coetzee got noticed, and he left home at 12, for good, on an
odyssey, first to live in Johannesburg with a friendly family and
hone his skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wound up for a while at John Newcombe's Tennis Ranch in New
Braunfels, Texas, and graduated from New Braunfels High,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Nike has helped him with clothing, Dunlop with rackets, and MTN,
a phone company, is something of an angel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm struggling to make ends meet but it's fun,'' he says.
``I'm getting around, and I love the game. I'll be representing
South Africa in the All-African Games at Johannesburg. Davis Cup
would mean a lot to me, to prove I really belong in this game. I
was stunned when Haygarth asked me to play here, and pleased. He's
world class.''
</P>
<P>
   Coetzee and Haygarth opened by beating the second-seeded
US-Netherlands alliance of Jared Palmer and Paul Haarhuis. They
were on their way to ``unimaginable'' prize money, beams Coetzee,
splitting $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I can send more home to mom. As a colored, I'm sort of in
the middle at home, between blacks and whites. Sometimes I wonder
who I am, but I don't care as long as I can be a tennis player.''
</P>
<P>
   He's that all right, and a historic figure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
