<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3809 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VIACOM-NEW-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      09-07 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIACOM-NEW-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW FORCE IN DISTRIBUTING MUSIC ACROSS THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (With VIACOM-CBS, VIACOM-REACT, VIACOM-MARKETPLACE,
VIACOM-AD-COLUMN, VIACOM-REGULATE, VIACOM-PROFILES) 
(th) 
 By MATT RICHTEL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The proposed merger of Viacom Inc. and CBS would create a
formidable force in the sale, distribution and promotion of music
over the Internet, industry analysts said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The merger would marry Viacom's MTV Interactive, the parent of
two popular Web sites, MTV.com and VH1.com, with the music
properties of CBS, which include Country.com, one of the most
popular country-western music sites. The merger also involves 163
radio stations owned by CBS' Infinity Broadcasting subsidiary
(though many of those are talk or news formats).
</P>
<P>
   For record companies, that translates into a union of two of the
predominant sources of album promotion, namely, the powerful MTV
brand and one of the nation's largest chains of radio stations,
said Jordan E. Rohan, online media analyst at Wit Capital, an
online investment bank in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a company wants to promote, market and sell music on line,
it needs to deal with the new Viacom,'' Rohan said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mooradian, an analyst with Jupiter Communications, a New
York-based market-research firm, said the merger could be a boon to
the MTV brand in particular _ both online and off. He said MTV's
already tremendous influence over record companies could grow with
access to CBS' television network, affiliate stations, radio
presence and outdoor advertising. ``MTV now has this unprecedented
reach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Butterworth, president and chief executive of MTV
Interactive, declined to comment on the potential benefits of the
merger. However, at a news conference announcing the deal Tuesday,
CBS Chairman Mel Karmazin said the deal envisioned creating
relationships between the CBS-owned country-western networks, CMT
and TNN, and Viacom's MTV and VH1.
</P>
<P>
   In one aspect of music promotion, CBS thus far has been an
Internet laggard: it has declined to make available over the
Internet the audio from any of its 163 radio stations. It has
stated repeatedly that it would not do so until it could find a
profitable business model.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts said, however, that the merger offered some
possible new business models given potential cross-marketing and
sharing of content with the MTV brand. In fact, SonicNet.com, owned
by Viacom, a music news, information and technology company,
assists radio stations in offering their programming over the
Internet, in effect giving CBS strong in-house expertise.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS spokesman, Dana McClintock, said the day was drawing
nearer when CBS would permit its stations to put its audio content
online.
</P>
<P>
   More generally, Viacom's chairman, Sumner M. Redstone, said he
expected the new entity to be a formidable new media company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 300 million worldwide households to drive traffic to
all of our sites,'' he said, adding that while it was too early to
give specifics, the company considered the Internet a strong part
of the puzzle. ``As we've already told the financial community, the
Internet is not an add-on; it's a major giant new growth
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Mooradian said both companies have told Wall Street they intend
to spin off parts of their Internet business in separate public
offerings. During Tuesday's news conference, Karmazin suggested
those plans had not changed, alluding to Viacom's stated intention
to spin off MTV Interactive in a public offering in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies own or have an interest in Web sites visited
by millions of Internet users each month. According to Media
Metrix, Viacom's sites, including the Nickelodeon sites, received
6.5 million unique visitors in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
