<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3811 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GOLDEN-POND-ART-NYT &LR;      09-07 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDEN-POND-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL REACHED TO GIVE PUBLIC ACCESS TO SQUAM LAKE, THE FAMED `GOLDEN
POND' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLDERNESS, N.H. _ Things are finally a little more neighborly
on Golden Pond.
</P>
<P>
   After years of debate, land deals gone sour, accusations of
landowner elitism and state threats to take lakeside property by
eminent domain, the state last month reached an agreement to
acquire its first public access to Squam Lake, where the 1980 movie
``On Golden Pond'' was filmed. Katherine Hepburn and Henry Fonda
won Oscars in 1981 for their performances in the movie, which also
starred Jane Fonda.
</P>
<P>
   There is no shortage of people taking credit for the deal that
has now officially provided everybody, including tourists, their
first beachhead from which to play on New Hampshire's
second-largest lake, after Winnipesaukee.
</P>
<P>
   There is the Squam Lakes Association, which helped broker the
donation of less than a half-acre of land, a boat ramp, four boat
slips and a dilapidated boathouse off State Route 113 to the New
Hampshire Fish and Game Department. There is the state Department
of Transportation and the private Science Center of New Hampshire,
which coordinated plans to move Route 113 farther from the shore
and make land available for parking.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Holderness itself, a town of about 1,700 people in
central New Hampshire that has come to terms with the inevitable,
despite ``misguided fears,'' in the words of the late Sydney Howe,
a neighbor and lake activist, ``that the great unwashed public will
harm Squam.''
</P>
<P>
   But the parties involved in the deal, which will allow the state
to build a boat launch in the small channel that connects Squam
Lake with Little Squam Lake, have not always been so neighborly.
</P>
<P>
   Squam is surrounded by private homes and cottages and unspoiled
wilderness. Locals say the lake is great for swimming, boating and
fishing. There are islands and loons, and the water is so clear
that you can see the bottom in some places.
</P>
<P>
   So townspeople can imagine, Selectwoman Sue Webster said, that a
``hot dog crowd'' of tourists may bring fast boats and fast times
here and devalue properties that can fetch $2,000 or more per foot
of shore front.
</P>
<P>
   ``People know that a place can get loved to death,'' Ms. Webster
said. Tourists, she added, ``love to come up to some place because
it's the way it is, and then they change it into something that's
not the thing they came up for in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Squam Lake, like its smaller sister, today looks much the way it
did when the Preston family took its first camping trip to the lake
more than 100 years ago, a few decades before the Prestons bought
their lakeside camp in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Preston, the current landowner and a member of the Squam
Lakes Association, which he served previously as both a vice
president and board member, donated three boat slips to give the
state nearly $100,000 worth of land and docks along Route 113.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard for years, `Why is the second largest lake in the
state not available to the public?''' Preston said. ``There was a
perception that this was a private lake. We all speak of `our lake'
if you have a place there, but it belongs to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Vetter, executive director of the New Hampshire Fish and
Game Department, said the department thought it could secure access
to the lake more than a year ago, but a group of landowners stepped
in to block the state's bid for about six acres on Squam.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bought the property right out from under us and for
$50,000 more than the state was prepared to pay,'' Vetter said.
</P>
<P>
   The state started exploring its eminent domain options, but then
the Fish and Game Department forged a partnership of sorts with the
Squam Lakes Association, which worked with Preston to arrange the
donation of land and docks.
</P>
<P>
   On an informal basis, Ms. Webster said, the public has had
access to the lakes for some time, with the cooperation of local
marina operators and the lakes association, which allowed some
public access from its Route 113 property.
</P>
<P>
   But Vetter said private interests really controlled public
access. ``The Squam Lakes Association at any time could shut off
access,'' he said, adding that ``there was always somebody standing
there with their hand out, looking for a donation'' from
out-of-town boaters.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Vetter said, ``the association really pulled
together,'' and now both private and public interests are building
good relations.
</P>
<P>
   The lakes association, the Fish and Game Department,
conservationists and interested townspeople will begin meeting this
week to develop plans for the a launching ramp and parking spaces
that will probably be constructed next spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
