<HEADLINE>
THESE A'S WERE BORN TO BE WILD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The 1999 Oakland A's appear to be direct
descendants of the old Oakland Raiders of Ken Stabler, John
Matuszak, and Ted Hendricks.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday's game against the Red Sox, the first of a
crucial two-game set, the A's locker room was a study in chaos.
Nirvana blared from a clubhouse stereo, volume set on 11. Guys with
mustaches and tattoos dressed in front of their lockers, or
slouched on sofas eating burgers and fries from McDonald's. Young
players wore their caps backward, and autographed photos of pro
wrestlers dotted the walls. This must be what it looks and sounds
like when the Hell's Angels pull into a truck stop.
</P>
<P>
   How did these guys miss Rod Beck?
</P>
<P>
   Veteran catcher Mike Macfarlane, one of the well-groomed and
mild-mannered A's, sat in the corner, observed his teammates, and
said, ``To a certain extent, the guys here aren't aware of what's
going on. You're not looking at a bunch of rocket scientists, but
they know how to play and they play hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty impressed looking at the Red Sox team and how
they're doing it. They're more fundamentally sound than we are.
We're a bunch of softball players, fun-loving guys that play hard,
go home and forget about it, then come back and do it again the
next day.''
</P>
<P>
   The A's have captured the attention of baseball America. One of
the scourges of baseball in the 1990s is the hopelessness of
low-budget franchises. Only top-payroll outfits have made the
playoffs in recent years, but the A's offer hope for the poor and
disheveled. Oakland's payroll is $22 million, fifth-smallest in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``People across the country know what this team is about,'' said
traveling secretary Mickey Morabito. ``Unfortunately, the people
here haven't caught on. We'll do well if we draw 20,000 tonight,
and half of those will be rooting for Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   The A's trailed the Sox by three games going into this series.
With 23 games remaining, the schedule favors Oakland. The Red Sox
still have to go to New York and Cleveland and have another series
with Toronto. After Wednesday, Oakland plays only three more games
against teams with winning records.
</P>
<P>
   They're paying attention to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got some tough teams coming up and we just have to
keep playing good baseball,'' said Jason Giambi (.317, 28 HRs, 103
RBIs).
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be lying if we said we weren't watching them,'' added
Macfarlane. ``We're asked about it constantly and sure, there were
some cuss words when we saw (Jason) Varitek hit the two-run homer
(actually, it was a three-run homer) in Seattle Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give the Red Sox credit,'' said Oakland manager
Art Howe. ``They find ways to win. (Rod) Beck has pitched under
pressure and a guy like Nomar (Garciaparra) can carry your whole
team on his shoulders. It seems like it's somebody different all
the time. But hopefully, this will be a tough trip for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez is the name that comes up most when you mention
the Red Sox in the A's clubhouse. Players know. They know that
Boston counts on a win every five days, and this is something the
A's don't have.
</P>
<P>
   But they do have free swingers (204 homers, second in the
majors) and free spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having a ball,'' said Giambi, an Olympic teammate of
Garciaparra in 1992. ``We're really not supposed to be here. People
said we were going to lose 100 games.''
</P>
<P>
   Howe said, ``The worst scenario now is that we had a great run
and have something to build on. We'd like to sweep this series, but
if we lose two, we're still in it. And I think we've gained a lot
of support around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Stairs (33 HRs, 92 RBIs), who along with Macfarlane played
with the Red Sox in 1995, said, ``There is no pressure on the
Oakland A's. Whatever happens, we're having a great year and it's
been good for baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Red Sox have been a terrific story. Mocked throughout
the offseason, projected by most to be out of the running, they
have been in contention since April, playing a noble brand of
fundamental baseball. They have demonstrated uncommon resilience
and skillfully veiled their weaknesses. They are the front-runners
for the final American League playoff spot and there's a New
England fantasy that says any team with Pedro can win a short
series against a stronger foe.
</P>
<P>
   But the hand-me-down A's are the feel-good movie of the baseball
summer, worthy winners if the Sox should falter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
