<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINEAU-PEPSI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RESURGENT PEPSI, A CHANGE AT THE TOP CAUSES CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y., N.J.)   (See also MARINEAU-LEVI)  (DW) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a fresh and catchy advertising program, some successful
brands and what appears to be a steady climb in market share,
Pepsi-Cola North America had been shaking off its recent
underperforming history when its president and chief executive,
Philip Marineau, abruptly resigned Tuesday to take the top job at
Levi Strauss &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said the loss of Marineau, who joined Pepsi
less than two years ago and had been widely admired by marketers
and bottlers, who rarely agree on anything, was an unfortunate
development for the No. 2 soft-drink maker. During Marineau's brief
tenure, Pepsi developed a more aggressive market strategy both in
the way it pursued business and in the way it followed through, in
what is known as ``execution'' in the soft-drink business and where
Pepsi so often fell down on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a substantial loss,'' said Andrew J. Conway, a beverage
analyst for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``Unfortunately he could
not fulfill his mission at Pepsi. I know he was very much embraced
by the bottler community, and his most significant contribution was
that he was beginning to instill what I call fact-based marketing,
rather than seat-of-the-pants marketing, which is what Pepsi had
done in recent years. Even Coca-Cola will tell you, he was doing
the right things.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Pepsi's biggest bottlers also voiced concern. ``Phil was
a great marketer, and we're all going to miss him,'' said Harold
Honickman, chairman of the Honickman Organization, which holds
franchises for bottling Pepsi in New York and parts of New Jersey.
``He was a very honest guy, who shot really squarely with the
bottlers.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Marineau's first acts as president was to shut down what
bottlers regarded as an unpromising campaign, ``Generation Next'' _
its final set of television commercials, in January 1998, included
one set to the Rolling Stones song ``Brown Sugar.'' The marketing
executive who devised the campaign, Brian Swette, resigned a couple
of months after Marineau came aboard. The replacement slogan, known
as ``Joy of Cola,'' was developed with Dawn Hudson, Pepsi-Cola's
senior vice president for marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Roger A. Enrico, the chairman and chief executive of Pepsico
Inc., said Marineau's work had been important but that Pepsi would
not collapse without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil is a talented guy who made an important contribution
here,'' he said, ``but I would point out that the transformation of
Pepsico began three and a half years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he was sure that Gary Rodkin, the head of
Tropicana who has been tapped to succeed Marineau, would also do
well. Rodkin has no experience in the carbonated soft-drink
business, and neither did Marineau, whose main achievement had been
building Gatorade into a billion-dollar brand for the Quaker Oats
Co.. Steven S. Reinemund, who in July had been named president of
Pepsico, was elevated further Tuesday to chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street reacted negatively to the news, as well as to
continuing worries about volume growth at both Coca-Cola and Pepsi.
Shares of Pepsi fell 93.75 cents, to $33.6875, while Coca-Cola fell
$2.75, to $54.625. Coke warned last week that its long-heralded
turnaround in the second half of this year was not on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   John D. Sicher, the publisher of Beverage Digest, a trade
newsletter, said the resignation of Marineau ``is not an event that
will stop their momentum,'' noting that by now most of the planning
for next year was already in place. What happens after that,
another analyst pointed out, remains to be seen. ``The fact that
Roger feels confident filling these positions internally shows an
evolution from a year and a half ago, when they were going outside
the company,'' said the analyst, Marc Cohen of Goldman, Sachs.
Still, he added, ``the proof will be in the pudding.''
</P>
<P>
   Some industry observers said the spinoff of Pepsi's bottling
operations limited Marineau's power within the company to build the
Pepsi brands. The Pepsi-owned bottling franchises were separated
into a different publicly traded company at the end of May. That,
combined with turf battles with other Pepsi executives and the
continuing active role played by Enrico at Pepsi-Cola, may have
proved too much for Marineau, who could not be reached for comment
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil had his hands tied,'' one beverage expert said. ``Roger
is still running Pepsi, and I don't think Phil has been able to
control the business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
