<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3822 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-BELFAST-POLICE-BOS &LR;      09-07 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELFAST-POLICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL RECOMMENDS SWEEPING CHANGES FOR ULSTER POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN AND JOHN O'FARRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ A commission appointed to reform the
force that polices Northern Ireland will recommend Thursday that
the Royal Ulster Constabulary change its name, recruit many more
Catholics, and demilitarize its attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 200 recommendations contained in the 300-page report
commissioned by the British government are expected to be highly
controversial. While the report calls for sweeping change in the
way the the force interacts with the public and recruits new
officers, it rejects the demand by hard-line Catholic nationalists
that it be disbanded altogether.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it categorically states, the Royal Ulster Constabulary
``should not be disbanded.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the recommendation that the 13,500-member force change
its name to the Northern Ireland Police Service and strip away
British trappings that Catholics find offensive will outrage
Protestant unionists, whose loyalty to all things British is often
more strident than sentiments expressed in England, Scotland or
Wales.
</P>
<P>
   Dropping ``Royal'' from the police force's name as well as the
oath that its officers take to the British monarch, and barring
portraits of Queen Elizabeth II from police stations, would bring
Northern Ireland in line with police services in other parts of the
United Kingdom. Those reforms are considered essential to increase
the recruitment of Catholics, who make up 43 percent of the
population but just 7 percent of the police force.
</P>
<P>
   Unionists have attacked the idea of a name change as an insult
to the memory of the 302 officers killed and the more than 10,000
injured by paramilitary groups, primarily the Irish Republican
Army, over the last 30 years. The first ``Save the RUC'' rally is
planned for Thursday night in the Ulster Hall in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   Shrinking the force to reflect the scaled-down threat to public
safety, while increasing the percentage of Catholics to reflect
their proportion in the population, will be a more daunting task
than a name change. The report calls for the Constabulary to turn
over to an outside agency the responsibility for recruitment,
another move aimed at chipping away Catholic resistance to joining.
An elaborate package aimed at encouraging early retirement, and
allowing for more Catholics to join, is recommended.
</P>
<P>
   The report, according to a British parliamentary source who has
seen it and read parts of it to the Globe, will please and dismay
both sides. It will be criticized by some Catholic nationalists,
who seek unity with the Irish Republic, as not going far enough.
And it will be criticized by some Protestant unionists, who want to
remain British citizens, as being an ungrateful slap at those who
held the line against terrorism for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   While the political bickering has started even before the
report's publication, Kathleen O'Toole, the former Massachusetts
secretary of public safety who is one of the eight members of the
Independent Commission on Policing who wrote it, pleaded Tuesday
for a fair reading.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, O'Toole declined to make specific references to
the report's recommendations before their publication, but she
dismissed as inaccurate and inflammatory claims in some British
newspapers that ``terrorists will be doing community policing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing about terrorists having day to day
responsibility for policing is absurd,'' said O'Toole, who is now
an administrator at Boston College. ``The press reports in recent
weeks have troubled me because my hope has been and continues to be
that people will look at this objectively, that they will put the
political posturing aside and look at this as a model of excellence
for policing.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Patten, the last British governor of Hong Kong who chairs
the commission, made O'Toole his deputy as the commissioners broke
into two groups, criss-crossing Northern Ireland to ask people what
they wanted in a police force. O'Toole said the report is based on
that input and the ideas and practices of leading international
criminologists and police departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never claimed to be an expert on politics in Northern
Ireland, but I do know how police departments should operate in a
modern democracy,'' said O'Toole, who was a senior officer in the
Boston Police Department and Massachusetts State Police. ``I can't
predict how Northern Ireland politicians will react to the report,
but progressive police managers will recognize it for what it is.
It was meant to create a new beginning for policing in Northern
Ireland, and I think we've done that.''
</P>
<P>
   The report will call for ``a comprehensive programof reform to
focus policing in Northern Ireland on a human rights-based
approach,'' replacing the old oath to the crown with ``a new oath
for old and new officers with an explicit commitment to upholding
human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The Constabulary has over the years been criticized by various
human rights groups for inhumane treatment of suspects,
heavy-handed tactics and the use of plastic bullets to control
crowds, and alleged collusion with loyalist paramilitary groups.
The report will not recommend the outlawing of plastic bullets, an
omission that will be attacked by nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   Unionists who oppose cross-border cooperation with the Irish
Republic will be outraged by the recommendation for ``more
structured cooperation with the Garda Siochana,'' the Republic's
police force, ``to be tested by cross-border exercises.''
</P>
<P>
   While some unionists see this as the ``slippery slope'' of
sliding into the Republic, cross-border cooperation among police in
Europe is increasingly common. The antiterrorist units of the Garda
and the Royal Ulster Constabulary have worked together closely for
years.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the report, called for under the Good Friday
Agreement of 1998, comes as that same agreement is on the verge of
collapse. It also comes as George Mitchell, the former US Senate
Majority Leader from Maine, returned to Belfast this week in an
effort to save the agreement he helped broker.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell decided to end three days of meetings with party
leaders Wednesday, suspending his review of the agreement until
next week, knowing the political fallout from the report will
dominate public debate for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Implementation of the Good Friday Agreement has been stalled
over a dispute between the Ulster Unionists, who represent
middle-class Protestants, and Sinn Fein, political allies of the
IRA. The unionists refuse to sit in local government with Sinn Fein
until the IRA begins turning in its weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
