u f BC-TIMOR-INDONESIA-ECON-     09-07 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-INDONESIA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST TIMOR CHAOS IS SEEN AS IMPERILING INDONESIA RECOVERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARK LANDLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ A failure to quell the chaos in East Timor could
strangle Indonesia's fragile economic recovery, government
officials and independent analysts warned on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As the violence takes on every appearance of a military-backed
terror campaign, officials fear that foreign lenders will shun
Indonesia while local business will lose confidence in the
government's authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are not able to overcome this, the recovery could slip
away and we could fall into another deep crisis,'' said Umar Juoro,
an economic adviser to Indonesia's president, B.J. Habibie. ``We've
got to be very careful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jakarta stock market, after plummeting on Monday, leveled
off on Tuesday. But Indonesia's currency, the rupiah, continued
weakening, reaching a rate of 8,250 to the dollar in Asian trading
and settling in New York later at 8,245. Analysts regard an
exchange rate of 8,000 rupiah to the dollar as a psychological
benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   Juoro said his greatest fear was that foreign lenders like the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank would cut off
billions of dollars in aid. Although these two agencies have not
directly threatened such action, both have expressed shock at the
flood of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're terribly concerned and worried about the East Timorese,
and we're following the situation closely,'' said Ben Fisher, the
World Bank's deputy director and country program coordinator in
Indonesia. ``For the entire international donor community, this is
a very difficult issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund said on Tuesday that it would
consider canceling a planned trip to Indonesia by its senior
officials to review its program. ``The IMF continues to view with
grave concern the deteriorating situation in East Timor,'' it said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said foreign donors had little choice but to
continue pouring money into Indonesia. Without the aid, they said,
the government would default on its debt and the country would be
ripe for further social unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Japanese officials said on Tuesday that they were not
considering halting their aid to Indonesia. All told, international
organizations have pledged $47 billion to Indonesia since the onset
of the Asian crisis in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The money is going toward rebuilding Indonesia's shattered
banking system and aiding tens of millions of people thrown into
poverty by the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important than the money is the message. If the IMF
and other groups suspend their programs, Juoro and other analysts
said, it will drive away prospective foreign investors, who regard
the aid as a stamp of approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would really be a signal for foreign investors to get away
from Indonesia,'' Juoro said. ``It would also cause Indonesian
capital to flee the country again. If they stop the support, it
would be a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the aid, the cou~try's economy has followed a
haphazard course. After contracting 14 percent last year, the
economy showed a few glimmerings of life. Exports began growing in
April for the first time in a year. In June, the stock market and
the rupiah soared after Indonesia held peaceful elections, the
first voting contested by candidates from more than one party in
four decades.
</P>
<P>
   But the euphoria dissipated the next month. Investigators
discovered that one of Indonesia's leading private banks, Bank
Bali, had diverted about $70 million in public funds to a top
official of Habibie's ruling party, Golkar. The money was
apparently intended to help gain support for a plan to keep Bank
Bali afloat. And it fed suspicions that Habibie's government was
guilty of the same corruption that marked his fallen predecessor,
Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bank Bali scandal was a big blow to confidence,'' said
Mari Pangestu, an economist at the Center for Strategic and
International Studies in Jakarta. ``Now, East Timor is dealing
another blow.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pangestu said the events in East Timor were particularly
damaging in the intangible, but important area of business
confidence. If executives doubt the government's ability to control
even a small province, she said it would discourage them from
making new investments in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, dispatching a United Nations peacekeeping force
to East Timor might steady nerves. But other analysts warned that
such a move could harm foreign companies with operations in
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be an anti-foreign backlash,'' said James W.
Castle, an American consultant with the Castle Group in Jakarta.
``In general, that hasn't been a problem here. But this could bring
it to the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
