<HEADER>
A3826 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-ENCEPHALITIS-NYT &LR;      09-07 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ENCEPHALITIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY MOSQUITO CONTROL IS POOR, EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City has one of the least aggressive
mosquito-control programs in the region, with virtually no
preventive maintenance and a budget that is less than 6 percent of
that in nearby Suffolk County, whose human population is only
one-fifth the size of New York's.
</P>
<P>
   As City Health Department officials continued to distribute
pesticides in parts of the Bronx and Queens Tuesday in response to
last week's deadly outbreak of St. Louis encephalitis _ and to
field thousands of worried phone calls from residents _ mosquito
experts raised questions about whether New York's war on the
dangerous pests had come too late. They noted that the species
linked to the outbreak is particularly prevalent in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at Flushing Hospital said they feared that hundreds more
people in northern Queens might be infected, and said a third death
might be linked to the encephalitis.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike nearby suburbs in Connecticut, New Jersey and Long
Island, New York does not routinely spray to kill mosquitoes, and
does not set traps to keep track of local mosquito populations,
leaving city officials without crucial information about viral
patterns. When the encephalitis was confirmed last week, the city
had to call in experts from Long Island and even borrow malathion,
the pesticide sprayed over the weekend, from Suffolk County's
Department of Vector Control, the agency that battles
disease-spreading pests.
</P>
<P>
   New York officials sprayed malathion from a helicopter again
late Tuesday in areas of the Bronx, but had not expanded their area
of concern to other parts of the city. They are still awaiting the
results of lab tests on 33 suspected cases, in addition to the five
cases already confirmed, which includes the two elderly residents
of Queens who died last month after contracting the virus.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said the main areas of concern remained in Queens
and the eastern edge of the Bronx.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
