<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3829 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-FEDERAL-GRANT-COX     09-07 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEDERAL-GRANT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio city the recipient of federal grant to rebuild
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Standing in the courtyard of a public housing
complex, U.S. Rep. Tony Hall, D-Dayton, Tuesday announced an $18.3
million federal grant to help ``a neighborhood come back.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Urban Development has chosen Dayton to
receive an $18.3 million grant to tear down three public housing
complexes, build more than 100 homes and rehab dozens more in the
Old Dayton View neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The area, which Hall called one of Dayton's first ``suburbs''
and home to early-century millionaires, is now one of the poorest
in the city. The city failed three years in a row to earn HUD
grants for similar proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Local sources have pledged $26 million more to the rebuilding
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that kind of money we can make a difference with this
neighborhood and we can make a difference with Dayton and
Montgomery County,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   The complexes to be demolished and replaced with other housing
are Edgewood Courts, where Hall made his announcement; Metro
Gardens and Metro Annex. Officials estimate 300 residents will be
need to be relocated for the project.
</P>
<P>
   The grants are part of a $571 million effort this year by the
federal government to tear down aging public housing facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot allow hard working American families to be left out
in the cold because of insufficient or inadequate housing,'' Vice
President Al Gore said in Los Angeles Tuesday. ``These grants are
aimed at the heart of Dayton's public housing communities _
bringing change that will work to improve living conditions and the
lives of working families.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's wife, Tipper, is visiting Dayton today and will take part
in a rally in celebration of the grant. The rally, which is open to
the public, will be at Omega Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Omega, one of the region's fastest growing and largest religious
congregations, has pledged to build a $5 million sanctuary along
Salem Avenue as part of the four-year redevelopment project.
</P>
<P>
   The church is also putting up $2 million for the construction of
a family life center, where church-run classes and activities will
be held for neighborhood residents and church members, said church
pastor the Rev. Daryl Ward.
</P>
<P>
   The work will coincide with several other efforts in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The city is spending $3 million to rehabilitate homes along
Lexington and Grand avenues, north of the housing complexes. The
Alliance for Education, a local charter schools proponent, is
studying whether to build a new charter school on the site of
Summit Courts, a fourth Dayton Metropolitan Housing Authority
complex, not far from the project area, that also is slated for
demolition.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton View revitalization effort will be the first major
local effort in the national trend to demolish large public housing
complexes and relocate the poorest residents throughout
communities. The grants, called Hope VI, have pumped billions into
urban centers to demolish public housing.
</P>
<P>
   The grant would replace the 213 public housing units that are
going to be demolished. In their place, DMHA would build a smaller
complex for senior citizens, as well as new homes and rental
duplexes. Sixty homes will be bought outside of the city for
current public housing residents to move into as new owners or
renters, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Roland Turpin, DMHA's executive director, said the shift may be
difficult for some residents but that it will help them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we don't have unanimous support but the residents have
to be encouraged,'' Turpin said. ``We have to work diligently that
every resident who sets some goals with us achieve their goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Some residents Tuesday in Edgewood Courts said the housing
complex is filled with drug users and is unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can get that out of the way, the neighborhood will
come back together,'' said Regina Wiggins, 22, a two-year resident
of the complex.
</P>
<P>
   Koneta Cochran, 47, who has lived in Edgewood Courts for six
years, said the concentration of poverty and crime makes it
impossible to raise a family there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just so thankful when I moved here my children were grown
and gone,'' Cochran said.
</P>
<P>
   The surrounding neighborhood already has turned its back on the
public housing complex.
</P>
<P>
   North of Edgewood Courts, across an alley, the backyards to
homes on Superior Avenue are protected by fences that in some
places rise 10 feet. The parking lot to the Dayton Fifth District
police station is fortified with a wall and fences where it abuts
Edgewood Courts.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than hide the situation from federal officials, DMHA put
a photo of the police station's wall in its grant request to HUD.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Sen. Mike DeWine praised HUD for selecting Dayton's
proposal and praised the effort to turn Dayton View around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dayton residents can now look forward to a revitalized,
vibrant community where they have access to affordable, safe, and
decent housing for their families,'' DeWine said. ``By issuing this
grant, HUD has recognized that the Dayton Metropolitan Housing
Authority, as well as the entire Dayton community, is committed to
improving the living conditions of the citizens living in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bebbington writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
