A3831 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-COX     09-07 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hingis cruises against Huber
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The depth of women's tennis and good health on the
men's tour were called into question Tuesday at the U.S. Open as
Martina Hingis won 12 straight games in a 6-2, 6-0 rout of former
top-five player Anke Huber, and Magnus Norman became the 11th man
to withdraw or retire because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis trailed 2-0 against Huber, who had beaten Jana Novotna
and Amelie Mauresmo in straight sets and offered some promise of a
competitive quarterfinal. Instead, Huber made 39 errors, one more
than the total points she won, and Hingis was flawless in chasing
the German side-to-side on a windy afternoon inside Arthur Ashe
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess her game suits me well,'' Hingis said. ``She's not
going for the lines or big shots. She's playing behind the service
lines, like little angles. I always was able to get there and do
something with it.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, Huber plays the grinding game of the early-'90s, when
she got up to No. 4 in the world without a weapon and was never a
match for the game's superstars. Huber was 0-10 against Graf, and
she's 0-9 vs. Monica Seles and 1-9 vs. Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis spent most of her post-match interviews talking about
more interesting things, like the difference between Florida and
New York. Earlier this year, Hingis moved from Switzerland to
Wesley Chapel, Fla., to be near the Saddlebrook Resort, where she
trains, and to escape Swiss taxes. Her assessment won't amuse the
Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida is very laid-back, easy-going; you don't really care
what kind of car, what restaurant you go to, what clothes you
wear,'' Hingis said. ``In New York, it's more snobby. You want to
always go to Bergdorf Goodman or Saks Fifth.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hingis, the tournament begins in earnest Thursday with a
semifinal against Venus Williams, a 6-4, 6-3 winner over Barbara
Schett.
</P>
<P>
   The first men's match of the day between Norman and fifth-seeded
Gustavo Kuerten was remarkable only in its ending, with Norman
retiring with a back injury following the first-set tiebreaker, won
by Kuerten 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   Norman, a young Swede who won two clay-court tournaments in
July, had break point at 5-5, 30-40 when he felt a click in his
back that preceded ``an unbelievable amount of pain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it's a shame because I'm playing the best tennis of
my life at the moment,'' Norman said.
</P>
<P>
   Norman, who beat Andre Agassi at the AT&AMP;T Challenge a couple of
years ago, is the seventh men's player to retire injured during a
match at this U.S. Open, and that represents one-eighth of all
men's matches played thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Four other men, all quarterfinalists a year ago _ Pete Sampras
(back), Patrick Rafter (shoulder), Mark Philippoussis (knee and
ankle) and Thomas Johansson (viral infection in his heart) _
withdrew before it began. Three other '98 quarterfinalists _ Carlos
Moya (back), Magnus Larsson (knee) and Karol Kucera (wrist) _ have
retired during their matches.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hale is 30-year-old Cedric Pioline, the 1993 runner-up
who beat 15th-seeded Tommy Haas 6-4, 7-5, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Pioline will play Kuerten in Thursday's quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   T Holcomb writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
