<HEADER>
A3832 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-DAGESTAN-ART-N     09-07 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DAGESTAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN DERIDES HIS MILITARY FOR `CARELESSNESS' IN DAGESTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By MICHAEL WINES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin on Tuesday mocked the Russian
military's handling of an Islamic rebel invasion of Dagestan as
inexcusably careless, joining a chorus of critics who say the
nation's commanders appear to have learned nothing from their
humiliating defeat by rebels in Chechnya three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, palpably angry, appeared on national television as his
security council debated what to do about the rebels, who seized
villages along the border with Chechnya over the weekend and blew
up an apartment complex housing Russian military families.
</P>
<P>
   At least 64 people died in the bombing, which occurred hours
after Russian military leaders and Prime Minister Vladimir Putin
confidently declared that they had subdued all rebel insurrections.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did we lose a whole district in Dagestan? Why are there
more terrorist acts in military compounds than in other places?''
Yeltsin asked, then answered himself: ``This can only be explained
by the carelessness of the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin said after Tuesday's security council meeting that the
military would take quick action to quell the insurrection. A
spokesman for the Russian Interior Ministry said troops were locked
in battle with rebels Tuesday night in the Dagestan town of
Karamakhi, and that a decisive battle could occur on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's major state-owned television network broadcast undated
film clips Tuesday night depicting torture and execution by Chechen
militants, suggesting that the government may be trying to prepare
citizens for heightened military action.
</P>
<P>
   It was already too late, however, for the military to avoid
scorching criticism of its performance in the latest uprising. The
Moscow daily newspaper Izvestiya declared in a banner headline
Tuesday that Russian generals ``slept through the war.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear already that the steps taken by the Russian
generals and Prime Minister Vladimir Putin were insufficient to
handle the threat adequately,'' the newspaper stated.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of the article, as well as others, was that Russian
generals had misread the strength and intentions of Islamic rebels
during a series of battles that ended with the withdrawal last week
of Chechen rebels from Dagestan. The Chechen forces, led by the
commander Shamil Basayev, have said they plan to establish in
Islamic fundamentalist state in Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   By the reasoning of critics, the military prematurely declared
victory over the Chechens and turned its attention to suppressing a
separate movement in central Dagestan by the Wahhabis, a
puritanical Islamic sect.
</P>
<P>
   That proved disastrous: the Wahhabis struck back with the
terrorist bombing of Russian military barracks. And Basayev's
rebels in Chechnya, who apparently had only been testing the
readiness of Russian troops in previous weeks, regrouped and moved
by the thousands into Dagestani territory.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Russian troops are now fighting a two-front war.
Reports Tuesday told of heavy fighting outside Khasavyurt,
Dagestan's second-largest city and the town that Basayev's movement
has declared the new capital of an Islamic republic in Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow newspapers were speculating Tuesday on the possibility,
unthinkable even a month ago, that a new war on the scale of the
Chechnya campaign may be beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Putin did little to discourage such thinking Tuesday, saying
Russia ``must brush away the syndrome of guilt developed in
previous years,'' an obvious reference to the Chechnya debacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been attacked,'' he said, ``and if no cardinal
measures are taken, the bandits will manage to penetrate into a
third district of Dagestan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 2151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
