<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3835 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-RUSSIA-OIL-NYT &LR;      09-07 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-OIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREDITORS ACCEPT MOSCOW'S TERMS IN OIL COMPANY BANKRUPTCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By NEELA BANERJEE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ BP Amoco and other foreign creditors said on Tuesday
that they had accepted an offer by the Russian government to
resolve the bankruptcy of the oil company Sidanko, a move that
could bolster BP Amoco's yearlong effort to preserve its
$571-million investment in the troubled company.
</P>
<P>
   BP owns a 10 percent stake in Sidanko and is among its major
creditors, along with a consortium of Western lenders led by
Dresdner Bank of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the preliminary agreement, the main creditors
would turn their claims against Sidanko over to the government,
which would then take the lead in sorting out bankruptcy
proceedings brought against Sidanko and its three most important
operating units.
</P>
<P>
   The creditors said they welcomed the government's plan because
it would keep Sidanko and its subsidiaries together, rather than
auctioning off the units to pay debts. ``The major creditors and
shareholders of Sidanko have offered a turnkey solution for
Sidanko,'' a BP vice president, Peter Charow, said. ``The
government is providing the key. When it's turned, all the
companies will move out of bankruptcy.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is unclear what specific steps the government would take
to try to save Sidanko, one of Russia's largest oil companies, and
the country's first big industrial bankruptcy. Because bankruptcy
is so new, the process is particularly murky.
</P>
<P>
   Sidanko lost $1.9 million in the first six months of 1999,
according to preliminary figures from the company.
</P>
<P>
   The creditors say they are surrendering their rights with no
preconditions and little more than a promise by the state that it
will act in their interests. Spokesmen for the government and for
Sidanko were unavailable for comment on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sidanko creditors are scheduled to meet with a first deputy
prime minister, Viktor Khristenko, on Wednesday to begin
discussions on how to actually transfer their rights to Sidanko
debt to the state, and on the detailed terms of a final agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The creditors say they will not sell their interests to the
government. Instead, the handover would presumably entail some sort
of trust agreement. Officials made the offer to the creditors late
last month, motivated perhaps by a desire to improve Russia's image
among foreign investors, analysts said. ``This case is a litmus
test for foreign investment in Russia,'' said Stephen O'Sullivan,
co-chief of research at United Financial Group, a brokerage house
here. ``It's very high-profile. So far, this has been a bad P.R.
case, and the government wants it to be resolved amicably.''
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco officials have asserted that the proceedings were being
manipulated by a rival Russian oil company as part of a hostile
takeover bid for Chernogorneft, a crucial Sidanko operating unit.
Without Chernogorneft, which accounts for a third of Sidanko's
production, the parent company would cease to function, BP has
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, creditors can initiate bankruptcy proceedings to
recover debts from a profitable company. A small, unknown creditor
did just that to Chernogorneft in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco officials think that the Tyumen Oil Co. is behind the
Chernogorneft bankruptcy. Court rulings regarding Chernogorneft
have gone against its creditors, the largest of whom favor BP
Amoco.
</P>
<P>
   Tyumen Oil has said that it wants to acquire Chernogorneft, but
has denied it has been involved in bankruptcy proceedings against
it. Outside managers installed by the courts have taken steps to
aid Tyumen Oil in its bid to take over Chernogorneft, but Tyumen
says it has no relationship with the managers.
</P>
<P>
   The creditors run the risk that an agreement with officials in
the current Russian Cabinet might be abrogated by a new one, often
the case in Russia and one of the reasons behind the nation's
dismal foreign investment record.
</P>
<P>
   The key, analysts said, is for BP Amoco to have as many
guarantees as possible that Sidanko will remain whole. ``The word
to have in here is that Sidanko survives as a viable company,''
O'Sullivan said. ``For that, keeping Chernogorneft as part of
Sidanko is vital.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
