<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3836 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VIACOM-REGULATE-ART-N     09-07 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIACOM-REGULATE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REGULATORS: WIDE BELIEF U.S. WILL LET A VAST DEAL GO THROUGH
</HEADLINE>
  (With VIACOM-CBS) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If there were a nursery character to symbolize this
year's corporate deal-making, it would almost certainly be a
variation of Humpty-Dumpty, in which he was finally put back
together again.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 30 years ago, Viacom Inc. became an independent company
after regulators forced CBS to sell its cable television and
syndication units. And about 60 years before that, the government
ordered the breakup of John D. Rockefeller's Standard Oil, which
led to the creation of Exxon and Mobil, two of the world's largest
oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   Now regulators in Washington are nearing completion of their
review of the proposal by the Exxon Corp. to buy the Mobil Corp.
just as other officials begin their examination of Viacom's plan to
buy CBS in the richest merger of media companies in history.
Earlier this year, the regulators once again approved a merger of
two of the regional Bell telephone companies, companies that had
been created as part of the antitrust breakup of the AT&AMP;T Corp.
</P>
<P>
   While experts agreed Tuesday that CBS and Viacom may have to
shed a handful of television stations and other assets to complete
the deal, there is a widespread consensus that at the end of the
day Washington will bless the acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   What has made all these corporate deals, which would have been
unthinkable a generation ago, possible?
</P>
<P>
   The short answer is that the companies and the economics of the
industries they serve has changed sharply and as a consequence, so
has the regulatory climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling is that the winds of competition are blowing and
therefore anything can happen,'' said Professor Eleanor Fox, an
antitrust scholar at the New York University School of Law. ``The
perception is that markets are more open than earlier times and
that barriers are lower. In any of these markets, firms are more
under the gun to survive growing competition. And of course, the
philosophy of regulation has changed. It used to be there was a lot
of socio-economic concern for the concentration of power in a few
hands. The concentration of power used to be seen in a dark light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' Ms. Fox added, ``the concern is that businesses be free
from regulation in order to compete in the global marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite these changes, executives at CBS and Viacom Tuesday
conceded that important obstacles remain to the completion of their
deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission generally has the
authority to approve or disapprove any telecommunications merger to
make sure it is ``in the public interest.'' The FCC, which has not
yet been formally notified by the companies, said in a statement
that its policy ``is to evaluate mergers to see if they meet the
public interest standard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will certainly evaluate this one when it is filed with
us,'' the agency statement said.
</P>
<P>
   But three regulations in particular limit the ownership
concentration of networks and television stations. As a result, CBS
and Viacom will have to either persuade the regulators to change
the rules, seek waivers or, more likely, sell some of their
interests in television stations and one of the two networks that
the two companies own.
</P>
<P>
   So it was hardly surprising Tuesday when Sumner M. Redstone, the
chairman of Viacom, and Mel Karmazin, chief executive of CBS,
announced that they would spend Wednesday huddled with top FCC
officials to both explain the deal and criticize some of the
problematic broadcast ownership rules, some of which the agency
announced only five weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   One older regulation that is of particular concern to the
executives prohibits a company from controlling more than 35
percent of the television broadcasting market. The cap used to be
25 percent but was raised to 35 percent as part of legislation that
largely deregulated the telecommunications industry three years
ago. CBS already owns stations reaching 32 percent of American
households, and its acquisition by Viacom would increase that to 41
percent. But the FCC has indicated it is now reconsidering the cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have long said that those rules are outdated and those
rules need to be modified,'' Karmazin said at a news conference
Tuesday. ``But at the end of the day, this merger will take place
and we will be in compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   A second FCC rule prohibits a company from owning two networks,
which is a problem because Viacom has a 50 percent interest in the
UPN network.
</P>
<P>
   A third rule, adopted last month, substantially relaxes the
limits that had restricted ownership of television stations for
most of the century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
