<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-MOTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Government asks judge to bar plaintiffs' expert witnesses in
Davidian trial
 &HT;    By Mark England and Tommy Witherspoon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The federal government Tuesday asked U.S. District
Judge Walter S. Smith Jr. of Waco to bar all the plaintiffs' expert
witnesses from testifying at next month's Branch Davidian civil
trial or grant both sides a continuance.
</P>
<P>
   Government attorney Marie Louise Hagen, who signed the U.S.
Department of Justice motion, argued that plaintiffs' attorneys
have turned over scant information on the qualifications of their
expert witnesses as well as the nature of their testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defendant has been prejudiced because plaintiffs' delay
and failure to disclose required information has impaired the
defendant's ability to obtain appropriate expert (rebuttal)
testimony,'' the motion stated.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Mike Caddell of Houston, who represents several
plaintiffs, said the government only has itself to blame for the
incomplete reports on expert witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it a little disingenuous for the government to complain
about not having complete reports from our experts when they've
stonewalled us for six years and refused to allow us to see the
evidence in this case,'' Caddell said. ``If they had given us
access as they should have, we would have had our expert reports
completed a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   An Oct. 18 trial date is set for the lawsuit filed against the
government by surviving Branch Davidians and relatives of those who
died during the 1993 standoff.
</P>
<P>
   Hagen cited Wayne D. Niemeyer _ who, according to the motion,
may testify for the plaintiffs about the pyrotechnic nature of
munitions recovered from Mount Carmel _ as an example of an expert
witness who is a mystery to it. The government said it wasn't told
Niemeyer's qualifications, the source of the material he is
testing, nor how his tests will impact the issues before the court.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said the plaintiffs gave the government as much
information on their expert witnesses as can be expected under the
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a vicious circle,'' Caddell said. ``It's
difficult to finalize the reports of our experts until they have
access to the evidence. The truth is that access to the evidence
through a filmmaker or a newspaper is not enough. We can't put on
experts who say, ``I saw this in Mike McNulty's new film, and I
have this opinion on it.''
</P>
<P>
   McNulty produced the new film ``Waco: A New Revelation.''
</P>
<P>
   The government asked Smith, if he doesn't strike the plaintiffs'
expert witnesses, to grant a continuance to ``allow adequate time
for trial preparation by both sides to this litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagen noted that Smith has already struck down two government
requests for continuances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevertheless, the United States respectfully urges the Court
to allow the parties sufficient time to prepare this substantial
case for trial, particular(ly) in light of the importance of expert
testimony,'' her motion stated.
</P>
<P>
   The government isn't the only one seeking a continuance. Caddell
himself filed for one a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's appropriate to have a short continuance,''
Caddell said. ``We've asked Judge Smith to delay the trial until
Dec. 6 or Jan. 10. He's had our motion for a while. I hope that
means he's considering it. He's usually pretty prompt. He doesn't
let grass grow under his feet when making a decision. I think a
short continuance would be fair to both sides. It would let us see
the evidence and prepare our experts' reports. It would let them
get their experts ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said he will file another motion today asking for a
status conference to be held between Smith and the parties in the
lawsuit. He wants to discuss if it's realistic to go to trial next
month, Caddell said, and when the plaintiffs can see the evidence _
now technically in Smith's custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need answers to some of these issues,'' Caddell said.
``Judge Smith issued his ruling Aug. 9 on custody of the evidence.
Here we are a month later, and, as I understand it, he hasn't
gotten a scrap of paper yet. We need to know when we're going to
see the evidence. Otherwise, how can we get ready for trial? I
fully expect Judge Smith to grant a short continuance.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark England and Tommy Witherspoon write for The Waco
Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
