u a BC-NJ-TURNPIKE-SHOOTING-     09-07 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-TURNPIKE-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 NEW JERSEY STATE TROOPERS INDICTED IN TURNPIKE SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Two state troopers were indicted Tuesday on
attempted murder and assault charges in a shooting after a routine
traffic stop on the New Jersey Turnpike in 1998 that left three of
four unarmed young black and Hispanic men injured.
</P>
<P>
   The incident focused national attention on decades-old charges
that the police often stopped drivers solely on the basis of race _
a practice known as racial profiling. That attention led to a
series of policy and political turnabouts, including an
acknowledgment by Gov. Christie Whitman that racial profiling was
commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   The indictments against the troopers, John Hogan, 29, and James
Kenna, 28, who are both white, were handed up Tuesday by a grand
jury in Trenton. Prosecutors say that on April 23, 1998, the two
troopers stopped a van carrying three young black men and a
Hispanic man on the turnpike near Washington Township and fired 11
shots at them. The troopers have said that the driver of the van
had backed up in an attempt to hit them.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment charges the two troopers with the attempted
murder of Daniel Reyes, a passenger in the van, and with aggravated
assault for wounding Reyes, 21, of Queens County, N.Y., and two
other passengers, Leroy Jermaine Grant, 24, and Rayshawn Brown, 21,
both of Manhattan. The driver of the van, Keshon Lamonte Moore, 22,
of Manhattan, was not shot. The troopers face a maximum prison term
of 20 years on the attempted murder charge and 10 years on the
assault charge.
</P>
<P>
   The indictments came nearly 18 months after the shooting, and
five months after the two troopers were indicted on 19 misdemeanor
charges of falsifying their activity logs to conceal the
disproportionate number of minority drivers they are accused of
stopping. State prosecutors charged at the time that this method,
referred to as ghosting, in which white drivers who were not
stopped were added to the logs, was a way the two troopers and
others covered up the practice of racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman issued a statement calling the indictments ``serious and
troubling,'' but added that they were ``only allegations, not
convictions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect the judicial process to be fair and impartial, and
must allow the system to work as it was intended and withhold any
comments of judgment or speculation on the outcome,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnnie L. Cochran Jr., the lawyer representing Grant in a civil
suit against the state police, applauded Tuesday's indictments as
``the first step on the road to justice.'' He called the state
investigation and grand jury presentation, which included a
re-enactment by law enforcement officials along the turnpike,
``thorough and methodical.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident began when the two troopers stopped the van near
Exit 8 for speeding. The four young men in it, all between 20 and
23 years old, were on their way to North Carolina Central
University for a basketball tryout.
</P>
<P>
   The two officers have said they began firing on the van on the
highway's shoulder when it continued to roll backward toward one of
them, despite their order to stop. The van's occupants have said
that they were not speeding when they were stopped and that the van
rolled slowly after the stop because it had been mistakenly put in
gear rather than in park.
</P>
<P>
   The incident became the focal point of what proved to be a
significant upheaval in state policy and politics. In the wake of
the shooting, Carl A. Williams, the former head of the state
police, was dismissed by Mrs. Whitman after he made racially
insensitive comments.
</P>
<P>
   It also was at the center of pressure from a New Jersey black
ministers' group and black legislators opposing the appointment by
Mrs. Whitman of her then-Attorney General, Peter G. Verniero, to
the state's highest court. Many insisted that Verniero and the
Governor had willfully ignored and dismissed allegations of the
racial profiling, and that as a result, Verniero was unfit to sit
on the court. He was confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   As the appointment was running into trouble in the State
Legislature and Federal civil rights agencies were descending on
the state for an ongoing inquiry into racial profiling, state
officials ended their long denials of the practice. Verniero and
Mrs. Whitman unveiled the findings of a two-month study that
concluded that minorities were three times more likely to be
stopped than whites, because of a culture in the state police that
rewarded zealous pursuit of suspected drug traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The study ended the state's long defense of its practices in a
pending civil suit alleging racial profiling and led officials to
drop charges in a number of criminal cases growing out of turnpike
traffic stops.
</P>
<P>
   Fallout from the incident has continued as minority members of
the state police, in addition to offering evidence of the racial
profiling charges, have claimed there is an oppressive atmosphere
of racial discrimination and intimidation in the department.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
