u w BC-CISNEROS-PLEA-1STLD-W     09-07 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-PLEA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISNEROS PLEADS GUILTY TO LYING ABOUT PAYMENTS TO FORMER MISTRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS that last four inquiries ended in setbacks from prosecutors
in 3rd graf; OUTLINES recent cases in grafs 16-18 beginning:
Tuesday's plea agreement...) (ATTN: Calif., Texas) (rk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Henry Cisneros, President Clinton's former housing
secretary, pleaded guilty Tuesday to a misdemeanor count of lying
to the FBI about payments to a former mistress, Under a plea
agreement that brings to an abrupt end the four-year, $10 million
investigation that led to his resignation, he avoids both a trial
on 18 felony charges and jail time.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros would have faced up to five years in jail on each of
the counts in what probably would have been the last criminal trial
conducted under the independent counsel law.
</P>
<P>
   The plea agreement also means that the last four cases brought
by independent counsels ended in setbacks to three prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the plea agreement with the independent counsel,
David Barrett, Cisneros agreed to pay a fine of $10,000 and will
serve no jail time or probation. ``I accept responsibility for the
conduct as outlined,'' Cisneros said in federal court Tuesday.
Cisneros, a former mayor of San Antonio and secretary of Housing
and Urban Development, added that future aspirants to public office
should learn that ``truth and candor are important.''
</P>
<P>
   He left the courthouse without talking to reporters but later
issued a statement through his lawyer saying that he ``was not
candid'' in statements he made to FBI agents doing a background
check on his suitability to serve in the Clinton Cabinet. But he
said that he hoped he would be most remembered for his actions as
housing secretary for three years at the beginning of the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros told the agents that he paid the former lover, Linda
Jones, about $60,000 over the years. Ms. Jones, once known as Linda
Medlar, secretly tape-recorded some 88 telephone conversations with
Cisneros, who is heard acknowledging that the actual figure was
closer to $250,000 and that he had not been honest with
investigators about the payments.
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection was set to begin Tuesday in the trial that was
expected to last more than a month. Instead Barrett told reporters
outside the courthouse: ``We are just glad to have this over and
done with.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released by his office, Barrett defended the
investigation and suggested his decision to end the case was based
on compassion and sympathy for Cisneros, who had a long career of
public service and once was considered a rising political star.
Cisneros is now the president of Univision, the Spanish-language
television network based in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This disposition should in no way be viewed as minimizing the
serious ethical breach by Mr. Cisneros,'' Barrett said in the
statement. ``However, a just disposition of any prosecution must
include an evaluation of the defendant's overall conduct. In this
case, the conduct, while egregious, was committed by a person whose
life has been otherwise dedicated to public service, and this fact
must season the final decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But many lawyers viewed the case against Cisneros as deeply
flawed, a judgment seemingly confirmed by the prosecution's
decision Tuesday to end the matter. The main problem for Barrett
was that his chief witness against Cisneros was Ms. Jones, who has
been portrayed as a liar not only by Cisneros' defense lawyers but
also by Barrett's office.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones is serving a 42-month sentence in federal prison for a
bank fraud case brought by Barrett's office related to the money
she received from Cisneros. Prosecutors also exposed as a lie her
assertion that the audio tapes of her conversations with Cisneros
were untouched originals. In fact, the prosecution showed they were
copies, many of which had been altered by her to conceal some of
her statements.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros' lawyers had tried to have the tapes ruled inadmissible
at trial. But Judge Stanley Sporkin, who was to preside over the
trial, ruled that the jury would be told the tapes were doctored
and its members could decide what to make of them.
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin said that the plea agreement was appropriate and that it
upheld the principle that, ``We cannot allow an individual to lie
his way into office.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lawrence G. Barcella, a former federal prosecutor,
characterized the result as ``basically a wipe-out, a prosecutorial
implosion.'' Barcella, who is a prominent white-collar defense
lawyer in Washington, said the result shows that the independent
counsel law has sometimes led to prosecutions that are ``gigantic
wastes of time and money.''
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel law was allowed to expire in June by a
Congress troubled by the controversy wrought by the law and
especially wearied after the impeachment of President Clinton that
resulted from the investigation by Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's plea agreement also means that none of the several
independent counsels deployed in the Clinton administration have
achieved a major conviction of their principal targets. Mike Espy,
Clinton's former agriculture secretary, was acquitted on charges he
accepted favors and bribes. The independent counsel investigating
Bruce Babbitt, the interior secretary, is on the verge of ending an
investigation into whether he improperly intervened in the matter
of a gambling license for an Indian tribe. An independent counsel
investigating Commerce Secretary Ronald Brown ended his inquiry
when Brown was killed in a plane crash in Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   And Starr has decided not to seek indictments of Clinton or his
wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, law enforcement officials said. The
last two cases brought by Starr, against Susan McDougal in Arkansas
and Julie Hiatt Steele, ended in mistrials and dismissals.
</P>
<P>
   The only remaining open investigation by an independent counsel
is that of Labor Secretary Alexis Herman on charges of influence
peddling in obtaining federal contracts before she assumed the
post.
</P>
<P>
   In accepting the plea agreement Tuesday, Sporkin said that he
anticipated that it would lead to much second-guessing. He said his
first impression upon hearing the proposed agreement was that the
penalty was far too light for the time and money expended.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he has concluded that what ultimately occurred was
wholly appropriate and that Barrett did not ``have much choice in
the matter.'' Barrett and his associates ``had an obligation to
maintain the integrity of their oath of office and in pursuing this
matter they did.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sporkin said he believed that matters should have been
concluded more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent inability or unwillingness of the prosecutor to
achieve anything near what he charged follows other setbacks for
independent prosecutors. Mike Espy, the former agriculture
secretary, was acquitted on charges he accepted favors and bribes.
The last two cases brought by Starr, against Susan McDougal in
Arkansas and Julie Hiatt Steele, ended in mistrials and eventual
dismissals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
