<HEADER>
A3858 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-NEWSEASON-JAMES-$A     09-07 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWSEASON-JAMES-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BE PATIENT: THE BEST MAY BE LAST, AFTER THE FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 12) 
(jt) 
 By CARYN JAMES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is the season's only foolproof advice: take a deep breath
and wait until January. That brings the debut of what promises to
be one of the most engaging new series, ``Malcolm in the Middle,''
and the return of ``The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly about a taken-for-granted middle child who turns out
to be a genius, ``Malcolm'' (Sundays at 7 on Fox) is actually about
his refreshingly imperfect family, brotherly conversations (``You
shut up.'' ``No,  &UR; you &LR;  shut up!'') and the often politically
incorrect disasters of everyday life. Malcolm doesn't know what's
worse: that his mother has set up a play date for him with a kid in
a wheelchair or that he has to go into the smart class with the
geeky students. Frankie Muniz plays Malcolm with a maximum of
little-boyish, eye-rolling exasperation and a minimum of the cutes.
At least in the pilot, the family dysfunction is handled with a
finesse that recalls that other irreverent but lovable all-American
clan, the Simpsons.
</P>
<P>
   It's in the nature of series television, of course, that you
can't judge a show by its promise, its pilot or, especially this
season, its name. Two new shows come with the mind-muddling titles
``Once and Again'' and ``Now and Again.'' (What high-level
executive discussions went on here? ``You change your name.'' ``No,
 &UR; you &LR;  change your name!'') That's bad enough. It seems demonic that
the male stars of these shows look astonishingly alike, as if they
were ready-made examples of television's pathological fear of
anything new.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Once and Again,'' a mature romantic comedy from Edward
Zwick and Marshall Herskovitz (the creators of
``Thirtysomething''), Bill Campbell plays Rick, a guy with a
congenial smile, cropped hair and lean good looks that are
ever-so-slightly bland. A divorced father of two, he falls for Lily
(Sela Ward), a divorced mother of two, and schemes to see her,
though he is often thwarted by his nagging adolescent children.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Now and Again,'' a sci-fi romantic comedy from Glenn Gordon
Caron (the creator of ``Moonlighting''), John Goodman plays Michael
Wiseman, who goes splat in front of a subway, only to have the
government transplant his brain into the body of another man (now
played by Eric Close). OK, so the shows do not share a sense of
gritty realism. Still, Michael wakes to find he is a guy with a
congenial smile, cropped hair and lean good looks that are
ever-so-slightly bland. Forbidden to contact his wife and his
daughter (Margaret Colin and Heather Matarazzo), he schemes to see
them, though he is often thwarted by his nagging government handler
(Dennis Haysbert).
</P>
<P>
   Pessimistic viewers may not get past the doppelgaenger titles,
but that would be too bad. The shows' divergent plots are more
revealing than their weary names. Though ``Once and Again'' is
already being called ``Fortysomething,'' it has an unexpected
tartness; the series is as much about the obstacles to romance as
it is about finding a second love. The future of ``Once and Again''
is fraught with uncertainty, though. After a six-week-run in the
``NYPD Blue'' time slot (ABC, Tuesdays at 10), it will vanish for a
couple of months, then return after football season (on Mondays at
10). A bigger question is: once Rick and Lily get together, what
will prevent the series from turning into ``The Brady Bunch''?
</P>
<P>
   A major problem also hovers over ``Now and Again'' (CBS, Fridays
at 9). The show has a slick, intriguing first episode. But will its
mixture of action-adventure and romantic longing create a fresh new
style? Or will the series turn into one of those
everything-but-the-kitchen-sink disasters?
</P>
<P>
   The track record of a series' creator guarantees nothing. With
``Wasteland'' (ABC, Thursdays at 9), its creator's past does offer
a broad hint, though. Kevin Williamson takes the small-town,
gossipy sensibility that made his ``Dawson's Creek'' an addictive,
smart soap opera and transplants it to New York City, where college
friends now in their 20s are trying not to grow up. This group
includes a closeted gay soap opera star, a bottom-rung lawyer in
the District Attorney's Office and a graduate student who has
managed _ even she doesn't quite know how _ to become a 26-year-old
virgin. Let's assume that a 34-year-old writer who is a master at
churning out successful teen-age flicks like ``Scream'' knows
something about arrested adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   And even if every promising fall series self-destructs before
our eyes, January will bring one sure thing, the second season of
``The Sopranos'' (HBO, Sunday nights), the most talked-about show
of this year and the most anticipated of the next. Coming up for
Tony Soprano (James Gandolfini), the mobster-with-a-midlife-crisis:
one of his sisters returns to New Jersey. Continuing the series'
terrific casting choices, she is played by Aida Turturro, who
should be a powerful match for their dear old murderous mom. With
the Sopranos, ``You shut up!'' ``No,  &UR; you &LR;  shut up!'' might pass
for family endearments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
