<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CARDINALS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rally in 9th as Braves Battle back
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Braves fans have come to expect a couple of things
from a St. Louis-Atlanta game over the past two weeks _ empty
swings from Mark McGwire and a close game.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the teams' past four meetings have been decided in the
ninth inning or beyond, and that's what it took Tuesday night for
the Braves to earn a 3-2 victory, their sixth in a row over the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Minor-league call-up Howard Battle played the hero this time
with a bases-loaded pinch single to left on the first pitch he saw
from Darren Oliver in the bottom of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had scored only one earned run off Oliver in 15
innings over two starts before the ninth. Jose Hernandez singled to
right field with two out to start the rally, and Brian Hunter
followed with a single to bring up Eddie Perez, whom Oliver walked
to bring up Battle.
</P>
<P>
   Battle came through for the second time in two at-bats since
returning to the Braves from Richmond this month.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Mulholland, who has a 2.63 ERA over his past eight games,
including five starts, limited the Cardinals to two runs in seven
innings and left with a 2-2 tie. Mulholland gave up two early runs
to unlikely run-producers before settling into a groove.
</P>
<P>
   Placido Polanco, called up from Class AAA on Tuesday and a late
addition to the lineup because shortstop Edgar Renteria was sick,
led off the game with a home run, only the second of his 117-game
big-league career. In the second, with two outs and runners at
first and third, Mulholland allowed a RBI single by Oliver that
gave St. Louis a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver gave up four hits in the first four innings but
repeatedly pitched out of jams, using three double plays to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan singled in the fourth, breaking a streak of 15
hitless at-bats, and scored to tie it 2-2 on a botched play by
shortstop Luis Ordaz on Jose Hernandez's double-play grounder.
Ordaz was charged with two errors on the play, one for a bobble and
the other for a wild throw to second, allowing Jordan to score and
Andruw Jones to take third base.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez had another opportunity with Andruw Jones at second
two innings later but lined out to Mark McGwire, who threw to
second for a double play. That made the Braves 0-for-7 with runners
in scoring position for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
