<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-WACO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO SEEKS FORMER SENATOR TO LEAD WACO INVESTIGATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
and CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Sen. John Danforth has emerged as Attorney
General Janet Reno's top choice to head an independent
investigation into the fiery climax of the 1993 standoff at the
Branch Davidian compound near Waco, government sources said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Republican responded favorably to Reno's request
that he lead a team of investigators, and he is negotiating with
her deputies about the scope of the inquiry, according to Justice
Department officials who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth ``is clearly the only person (Reno aides) are talking
to right now,'' one Justice Department official said. ``But there
is no final deal, yet.'' An agreement and subsequent announcement
are expected this week, possibly Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Reno aides are considering appointing a second person, possibly
a Democrat, to help share the top investigator's job and give the
inquiry bipartisan balance, according to an Associated Press report
citing unnamed congressional sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not at the point where we can comment on the progress of
the search'' for an independent investigator, said Justice
Department spokesman Myron Marlin.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, 63, was state attorney general of Missouri for eight
years before he was elected to the Senate. He retired from the
Senate in 1995 and has been practicing law in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth was a ranking member of the dwindling group of
Republican moderates in the Senate. But at the end of his three
terms he was perhaps best known for his strong defense of the
nomination of conservative Clarence Thomas, a former aide, to the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a week, Reno has been searching for someone to
oversee an independent investigation into the FBI's recent
disclosure of information that conflicts with sworn testimony by
Reno and bureau officials about the April 19, 1993, assault.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans _ some of them calling for Reno's
resignation _ are demanding explanations from the attorney general
and FBI Director Louis Freeh about how evidence, including video
and audio tapes, from the siege were withheld for six years despite
congressional and court inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, which turned over the tapes last week, now acknowledges
that potentially flammable tear gas canisters were fired at the
compound, an action that violated Reno's orders that incendiary
devices not be deployed during the assault.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure has not changed long-held positions by Reno and
Freeh that members of the Branch Davidian religious sect, not the
bureau's hostage rescue team, were responsible for setting the
fires that engulfed the compound. More than 80 people, including 25
children, died during the assault.
</P>
<P>
   When Danforth announced that he would not seek re-election in
1994, he said he was leaving because ``I didn't want the claim of
government, the claim of politics, to be total.''
</P>
<P>
   Danforth is also an ordained Episcopal priest. He is an heir to
the Ralston-Purina fortune and had a blue-chip education, including
undergraduate work at Princeton and law and divinity degrees from
Yale. In the Senate, Danforth was on the Finance, Commerce and
Intelligence committees.
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving the Senate, Danforth has been associated with a
Missouri-based law firm, Bryan Cave LLP. With 550 lawyers, the firm
is one of the largest 25 in the nation, its Web site says. The firm
lists Danforth as active in its international and real estate
development practices. Four of the firm's seven overseas offices
are in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The former senator also is on the Dow Chemical board of
directors. Anne Ainsworth, a spokeswoman for the Midland,
Mich.-based chemical giant, said Tuesday Danforth was elected to
the chemical giant's board in 1996 and re-elected in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't make a lot of end-use products,'' Ainsworth said,
adding that she did not know whether Dow chemicals figured in the
devices at issue in the Branch Davidian case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
