<HEADER>
A3867 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-NOTES-CO     09-07 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Johnson: Collins doubtful to face Broncos Monday
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ Jimmy Johnson took the optimism Cecil Collins has
been spreading around the locker room about a return for the season
opener and doused it with the dreaded d-word.
</P>
<P>
   Doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins' coach Tuesday said that Collins, the rookie
running back who was one of the bright spots of training camp
before injuring his ankle Aug.28 in an exhibition game against
Detroit, likely will miss Monday's opener at Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks real iffy,'' he said. ``If he is ready to go, it's
not going to be at full speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins hasn't practiced since being injured. And with only
three practices remaining before the game _ the Dolphins take today
off, then work out Thursday, Friday and Saturday _ the chances of
him being ready are dwindling.
</P>
<P>
   Collins no longer is on crutches. And in recent days, he has
been telling reporters he thinks he could be ready for the Denver
game.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, however, sounded pessimistic Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he'll be able to work (Thursday),'' Johnson
said. ``I do not expect him to be 100percent for game. I'd say
right now he's doubtful.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some good injury news. The Dolphins' other rookie
tailback, J.J. Johnson, continues to rebound from a hamstring
injury sustained in a scrimmage against Tampa Bay four weeks ago.
And it looks like fullback Stanley Pritchett, who sprained a knee
in the exhibition finale, will be able to play at Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like we're going to be able to get some of these
players back,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Johnson's mood has suddenly turned cheery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our injury situation may be better,'' he said, ``but it's
still not good.''
</P>
<P>
   Huard OK with company: A year ago, backup quarterback Damon
Huard admits, he might have been nervous if the Dolphins had traded
for a quarterback who was a former No.1 draft pick. But now he
insists he is ready for the competition that comes with the trade
for Jim Druckenmiller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a year under my belt as far as being the backup guy
and the pressure associated with being ready to go,'' he said. ``My
confidence is high. ... It will be good to have a good player like
him to come in and push me and Dan. It will be good for all of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Teaching old dogs: Kevin Gogan and Kevin Donnalley are trying to
get used to the plan to have them alternate starts and split time
at right guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really tough situation because we've never done it
before, neither of us,'' Gogan said. ``I think it's going to take a
little bit of feeling out, seeing how many plays you go in a row.
Do you go quarters? Do you go halves? You don't want to get a
player out of the groove.''
</P>
<P>
   Transactions: The Dolphins waived safety Rayna Stewart and
brought back four players who had been released to the practice
squad: fullback Kantroy Barber, guard O'Lester Pope and receivers
Derrick Steagall and Kevin McKenzie.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Woods writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
