<HEADLINE>
MILLIONS FOR THE TWO COMPANY CHIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With VIACOM-CBS, VIACOM-REACT, VIACOM-NEW-MEDIA,
VIACOM-MARKETPLACE, VIACOM-AD-COLUMN, VIACOM-REGULATE,
VIACOM-PROFILES) 
(th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The top two executives of Viacom Inc. and CBS Corp.
have been given identical compensation packages, and the two Viacom
vice chairmen who are stepping down are also set to profit
handsomely, Viacom disclosed Tuesday night in a filing with the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Sumner M. Redstone, the Viacom chief executive, and Mel
Karmazin, the CBS chief executive who is to become chief operating
officer of the combined company, are each to receive salaries of $1
million a year, plus $2 million in deferred compensation, and a
bonus of up to $10 million in 2000, with the figures rising in
later years.
</P>
<P>
   They will each also receive options to buy 2 million Viacom
shares at the market price of the stock when the deal is completed
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas E. Dooley and Philippe P. Dauman, the Viacom vice
chairmen who Redstone said decided to remain on the board but leave
their jobs at the company, will each receive at least $34 million
in cash if they step down at the beginning of next year. They would
also retain their rights under the company's stock options and
other benefit plans.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Karmazin said the compensation was
somewhat less than he expected to receive, had he signed a new
contract at CBS.
</P>
</TEXT>
