r f BC-Y2K-Y2K_SFCHRON &LR;      09-07 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-Y2K </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   It's Not Y2K, But 9/9/99 May Hit PCs 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Benny Evangelista &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
Banks, airlines, electric utilities and corporations will be
keeping a close eye on their computer systems tonight as the
calendar date rolls over to ``9/9/99,'' a combination of four nines
that could trigger software problems.
</P>
<P>
   In a glitch similar to the Y2K problem, some fear that computers
may read Sept. 9, 1999, as a ``9999'' stop-program command. But
most experts think that tomorrow should just be another day at the
office.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many programmers are keeping a close eye out for
potential malfunctions. Officials from San Francisco's PG&AMP;E, for
example, will be up late testing backup communications as part of a
nationwide Year 2000 computer problem drill for the electric
utility industry. The drill was timed to coincide with the
potential ``9999'' computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   And the Coast Guard last night went into a special 48-hour alert
mode to be prepared for computer-related malfunctions with maritime
traffic in San Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Fears about a computer meltdown due to the 9/9/99 date are ``all
hype,'' said Herbert M. Gottlieb, founder, president and CEO of
Attest Systems Inc., a Novato company that makes software to track
down potential Year 2000 problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone got it into their craw there was going to be a problem
and I've been laughing at that for months,'' Gottlieb said.
</P>
<P>
   Decades ago, when computer data was punched into paper data
cards, programmers used a string of ``9s'' to signal the end of a
program. That led to fears that computers reading the date tomorrow
might shut down. The Year 2000 problem is similar because computer
systems that were programmed to read only the last two digits of a
year may misread the year 2000 as the year 1900.
</P>
<P>
   But Gottlieb and other computer experts say the danger of the
9999 problem is overstated since most modern software no longer
uses that coding. And even if ``9999'' were a problem, computers
will read the date as ``090999,'' which wouldn't trigger anything.
</P>
<P>
   Similar fears were raised about the date April 9, 1999 _ the
99th day of the 99th year _ but that date passed uneventfully.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Martin, coordinator of Y2K consulting work for Mitre
Corp. of Bedford, Mass., said there were legitimate worries about
9999 at the start of the year. Mitre, which does Y2K consulting for
government organizations and private companies, last year even
issued a list of upcoming critical Y2K dates to watch, including
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   But the work done this year to stamp out potential Y2K problems
has also helped eradicate most if not all 9999 problems, Martin
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not hype, because there have been a lot of systems where
we found this problem, such as military and government systems,''
Martin said. ``Most organizations have been treating this very
seriously and it will be a nonevent because they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Summit Bank President Mike Ziemann said his Oakland institution
has completed testing of its computer systems. The bank tested its
systems by setting the date forward to September 9 and didn't find
any problems. Ziemann, though, personally plans to keep a watch on
computer system reports tonight and tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't anticipating any problems, I say with my fingers
crossed,'' Ziemann said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3873 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-IMOTORS-IMOTORS_SFCHR     09-07 1458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMOTORS-IMOTORS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Locating Used Vehicles Online
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Peter Sinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
IMotors.com of San Francisco plans to announce today a new way to
purchase used cars over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Most online car sites act like a referral service, connecting
prospective buyers with dealers and private sellers.
</P>
<P>
   IMotors goes much further. It takes customer orders and delivers
vehicles matching their precise specifications on year, model,
options and mileage. It also offers fixed prices and will even
install custom leather upholstery.
</P>
<P>
   Raoul Wertz of Mill Valley spent three months researching the
purchase of a used van before buying a 1995 Ford Club Wagon from
iMotors this summer. He paid $14,200, about $5,000 below the Kelley
Blue Book retail value. ``The model I got actually exceeded my
specifications and expectations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   IMotors has buyers around the country to find and acquire
vehicles that match customers' wishes. It sends the cars to a
reconditioning facility near Sacramento before they are delivered
to the buyer for hundreds or thousands of dollars below the blue
book value.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicles come with a three-month, 3,000-mile warranty. But
if a customer doesn't like the car after driving it for one week
and up to 700 miles, he or she can return it and retrieve the full
$250 deposit.
</P>
<P>
   IMotors' business model may be risk-free to consumers, but some
auto industry veterans who were told of the company's bold business
plan suspect that it could have a tough time turning a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a large supply of late-model used vehicles, which
could diminish the need for this service,'' suggested Chris Denove,
director of consulting for J.D. Power &AMP; Associates. ``And the
concept of centralized reconditioning centers was tried by
AutoNation and failed because it increased distribution costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, venture capital firms have invested $21 million in
iMotors and plan to commit an additional $50 million later this
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an Internet company, we've done away with expensive
inventory, costly retail outlets and commissioned salespeople,''
said iMotors CEO Adam Simms, who has spent the past 16 years in
automotive retailing. ``IMotors allows shoppers to order the car
they desire instead of trying to switch them to something a dealer
has in stock.''
</P>
<P>
   The company offers consumers a chance to order a car from a
``virtual lot'' of 1.8 million used vehicles that are on the U.S.
market at any given point. The company will buy and deliver
vehicles from current models to 5 years old. Initially, the service
is only available in the Bay Area and Sacramento, but iMotors plans
to expand nationally over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the process works:
</P>
<P>
   _A prospective buyer logs onto www.imotors.com and specifies the
year, make, model, options, color choices and mileage of the
desired vehicle. To secure the order, the consumer pays a
refundable deposit, signs an agreement to have iMotors find the
vehicle at a guaranteed price and provides proof that he or she has
sufficient funds or financing to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   _IMotors has about 10 veteran buyers around the country who go
to auto auctions, look for cars in the Southeast where prices for
used foreign cars are comparatively low and employ other techniques
to find and buy specified cars.
</P>
<P>
   _Vehicles are sent to iMotors' vehicle certification center in
Elk Grove (Sacramento County), where 50 employees inspect and
repair each vehicle to ensure it is in excellent shape. That
includes making mechanical repairs, taking out dings, repainting
panels and replacing worn tires.
</P>
<P>
   _IMotors schedules delivery initially at three sites in the Bay
Area _ Foster City, San Ramon and Santa Clara _ as well as
Sacramento. Customers receive a complete history of the car called
an ``AutoBiography,'' finalize paperwork, inspect and drive the
vehicle, and take off with a no-risk return policy.
</P>
<P>
   Before launching iMotors on the Internet, Simms ran a used-car
superstore in Fresno called Auto Choice. Since March of last year,
he tested many of the concepts such as offering fixed prices for
used vehicles, letting shoppers specify what they were looking for,
finding the prescribed vehicle for them within two weeks and basing
sales peoples' pay on customer satisfaction rather than
commissions.
</P>
<P>
   In designing iMotors, Simms used Dell Computer's model of
building products to match customer specifications and cut down on
expensive inventory. He also looked at Federal Express' efficient
hub-and-spoke distribution system and plans to eventually have
vehicle inspection and repair facilities at strategic locations
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   So far, about 3,000 cars have gone through iMotors' Elk Grove
facility, and Simms said less than 1 percent of customers have been
dissatisfied and have returned their cars. (One was a woman who
discovered she could not see over the dashboard of the vehicle she
ordered.)
</P>
<P>
   IMotors realizes that to make it financially it must operate
with assembly-line efficiency and high volume. The company declined
to disclose how many vehicles it needs to sell to make a profit.
But by the end of this year, iMotors expects to be refurbishing and
selling 1,000 cars a month.
</P>
<P>
   Among the company's advantages are its rental costs. It pays $1
per square foot per month at its 4-acre inspection and fix-it
facility _ a fraction of what an urban dealer might have to pay.
Its average labor cost is about $15 per hour, which also is low by
industry standards. And perhaps most importantly, iMotors only buys
used cars when it has a firm order so it only has to finance
inventory for a week or two, versus two months or more for the
typical used-car dealer.
</P>
<P>
   While Simms knows about selling cars, iMotors hired Internet
expert Beth VanStory as president. She previously built and managed
OfficeDepot.com's profitable Web site as well as the Weather
Channel's online business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan is to change the used-car buying experience and, like
Nordstrom, delight the customer,'' she said. IMotors iMotors &LR;   &LR; has
cut out the high-pressure sales tactics and bait-and-switch
techniques employed by many car dealers and also the hassle and
risk of dealing with private sellers.
</P>
<P>
   IMotors has agreements with Napa Auto Parts for parts and
service. Besides the Internet route, iMotors is offering its
used-car buying service by toll-free telephone number and at kiosks
at four Costco stores in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Before discovering Auto Choice, the predecessor of iMotors,
Wertz, the Mill Valley resident who bought a vehicle from iMotors,
visited dealers and private sellers and also checked out online
used-car sites like Auto Choice, Autobytel and Auto Trader Online.
</P>
<P>
   He initially balked at having to have his bank disclose that he
had the financial capability to make the purchase. But he is glad
he went through with the deal and bought the 4-year-old Ford Club
Wagon with 63,000 miles on it for only $1,450 above its $12,750
trade-in value. ``With dealers and private sellers, the best price
I saw was more than $16,000,'' said Wertz.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Larson, a Southwest Airlines pilot who lives near Auburn
(Placer County), also is happy with the 1994 Chevy Suburban with
76,000 miles that he bought for about $18,500 last month. ``It was
less than what car lots were asking for older models with more
mileage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   IMotors' financial backers are enthusiastic, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of e-commerce companies have billion-dollar market
caps (stock market values) and iMotors could be one of them,'' said
Gus Tai, a general partner of Trinity Ventures, which has invested
in Starbucks, BabyCenter, NextCard and other successful startups.
</P>
<P>
   ``The used-car business is a $350 billion market, but it's hard
to find consumers who enjoy interacting with dealers or buying from
a private seller and taking the risk the car doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some consumers might try to take advantage of iMotors'
risk-free purchasing plan, Tai maintains that Americans are
generally trustworthy. Beyond that, there are a lot easier ways to
get a test drive.
</P>
<P>
   But there are risks. ``Offering a free seven-day trial shows
confidence in your product but is sticking your neck out big
time,'' said Jon Price, who sells high-end, used imported cars and
sport sports  &LR; utility vehicles through his A.M.M. Services in San
Rafael and charges a 4 percent sales commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The logistics problems could be humongous,'' he added. ``There
are a lot of used cars in the middle-price range, and going head to
head with AutoNation, the biggest chain of used-car dealerships,
could be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
