<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILTON-PROMUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILTON TO BUY PROMUS CHAIN, CREATING ONE OF BIGGEST HOTEL GROUPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Tenn.)  (th) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hilton Hotels Corp. said Tuesday that it had agreed to acquire
Promus Hotel Corp. for $3.1 billion in cash and stock, creating one
of the largest hotel companies in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will combine Hilton's 275 luxury hotels in North
America with Promus' Doubletree Hotels, Embassy Suites and Hampton
Inns. The combined company will have 1,700 hotels, 290,000 rooms
and 85,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton will pay $38.50, or the equivalent in stock, for each
Promus share, a 23 percent premium on the closing price of Promus
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by shareholders of both companies, the merger would
be completed by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen F. Bollenbach, president and chief executive of Hilton
Hotels, said Tuesday that Hilton and Promus were a ``perfect fit.''
A merger, he said, would help reduce Hilton's dependence on its 10
largest hotels, including the Waldorf-Astoria and the New York
Hilton in Manhattan. At the same time, he said, the move will help
Hilton compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important in our industry to have size and scale,''
Bollenbach said, ``and this will make us as big as our two closest
competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Those competitors are Marriott International, which now has more
than 1,600 hotels and 324,000 rooms, and Starwood Hotels and
Resorts Worldwide, which has more than 670 hotels and 217,000
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   But the stock market, which had already driven down the price of
Hilton's shares by 13 percent this year, did not react favorably to
the news. Shares of Hilton fell 62.5 cents Tuesday, to $11.1875,
while Promus rose $3.4375, to $34.8125.
</P>
<P>
   Some Wall Street analysts said they feared that Hilton was
paying too much for Promus, which disappointed investors earlier
this year when it lowered its estimates of what it would earn in
the future quarters. It earned profits of $154 million last year on
revenues of $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenges that Promus faced don't go away with this
merger,'' said Keith A. Mills, a lodging analyst at Paine Webber.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said that the next 12 to 18 months could be difficult for
Hilton. He said he was advising investors to wait at least a year
before investing in the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years from now,'' Mills said, ``this could prove to be a
profitable transaction.''
</P>
<P>
   One benefit of the acquisition is that it will lessen Hilton's
dependence on profits from the luxury hotels it owns.
</P>
<P>
   Now, about 60 percent of Hilton's revenue _ $1.8 billion last
year _ comes from its 10 largest hotels. And, only about 13 percent
of its revenue comes from franchise fees earned from hotels owned
by others.
</P>
<P>
   The franchise fees serve as a more stable form of income for
hotel companies than revenue earned on owned hotels because the
franchise fees are most often calculated as a percentage of total
revenue rather than profits. Thus, the franchise fees are paid even
if a franchised hotel is not profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with Promus' hotel franchises, about 30 percent of
Hilton's revenue would come from franchise fees, a Hilton spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Hilton will pay cash for 55 percent
of Promus' shares and stock for the rest. It will also take on
about $900 million of Promus' debt.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton's headquarters will remain in Beverly Hills, Calif., but
the companies said that they would still have significant
operations in Memphis, Tenn., where Promus is now based.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton estimates that the merger will result in $55 million in
cost savings and additional revenue next year. After that, the
company estimates the merger will lift its bottom line by $90
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those figures, Hilton still expects its earnings to fall
slightly next year because of the amortization of goodwill that
will result from accounting for the Promus acquisition on Hilton's
financial books.
</P>
<P>
   Bollenbach was chief financial officer at Promus from 1986 to
1991. The company was then called Holiday Corp. He later worked for
Donald Trump, for Marriott, and for Walt Disney Co. He was hired by
Hilton about three years ago, and since then, has made several
unsuccessful attempts to acquire major hotel companies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, he pursued a hostile takeover of ITT Corp., which then
owned the Sheraton hotels and Caesars World casinos. He ultimately
lost the bidding war to Starwood.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Bollenbach and other Hilton executives held
unsuccessful acquisition talks with Patriot American Hospitality
Inc., the company now called Wyndham International Inc. In 1996,
Hilton purchased Bally Entertainment Corp., and last year spun off
the casinos into a new company, Park Place Entertainment Corp.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
