r f BC-CARSIDE-CARSIDE_SFCHR     09-07 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARSIDE-CARSIDE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Used-Car Shopping Traffic Is Picking Up on Internet
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Peter Sinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Before buying a car, most car buyers like to kick the tires rather
than take a virtual test drive on the information superhighway.
super highway.  &LR; Nevertheless, more Americans are using the Internet
to shop for new and used cars.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, the percentage of people buying new vehicles
through online buying services more than doubled _ from 1.1 percent
to 2.7 percent _ and may go as high as 5 percent by next year,
according to a report last month by J.D. Power &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the number of new-vehicle shoppers using the Internet
to gather information to help them decide what model to buy
increased from 25 percent to 40 percent in the past year and is
projected to reach 65 percent by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Power found that the average Internet shopper visits six
automotive Web sites and spends more than four hours researching
what make and model to purchase and at what price.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular automotive Web sites for new-car buyers,
according to the Los Angeles market research firm, are Kelley Blue
Book, which provides pricing information for new and used cars
(www.kbb.com) and Autobytel (www.autobytel.com), which accounts for
45 percent of all new vehicles sold through an online service.
</P>
<P>
   AutoNation, the country's largest car dealer
(www.autonationdirect.com), recently teamed up with Priceline.com,
which is best known for its ``name your own price'' airline
tickets, to offer a similar Internet buying service for new cars.
</P>
<P>
   Several new-car buying services such as CarsDirect.com and
Carorder.com are often willing to buy cars from dealers for
hundreds to thousands of dollars higher than the price they sell to
consumers. In essence, these services are subsidizing the purchase
of vehicles to build awareness and sales in new markets.
</P>
<P>
   While new cars are basically commodities and low price is the
chief concern to many buyers, used cars are unique because they
vary so much in mileage and condition.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, 26 percent of used-vehicle buyers log onto the
Internet for assistance during the shopping process, according to
J.D. Power, which recently surveyed 10,000 consumers who purchased
1994 through 1999 used vehicles. Buyers increasingly are going
online to research prices, reliability and safety data.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always risks associated with buying used vehicles,
but the Internet provides easy access to the information people
need to avoid buying a lemon,'' said Chris Denove of J.D. Power.
``Despite the fact that online vehicle-locator sites are in their
infancy, we were amazed to find that some already offer a wider
selection of used vehicles than the typical newspaper
classifieds.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers should realize that local dealers pay cash to online
services to advertise their cars and make sales.
</P>
<P>
   According to J.D. Power, favorite sites for used-car information
include Kelley Blue Book and Consumer Reports
(www.consumerreports.org), Autobytel and such online buying
services as Edmund's Online (www.edmunds.com); Auto Trader Online
(www.traderonline.com); Microsoft CarPoint (www.carpoint.com);
autoweb.com (www.autoweb.com) and cars.com (www.cars.com).
</P>
<P>
   While iMotors claims to have a unique model for delivering used
cars online, most other sites let consumers cull dealer and private
party listings for particular makes and models within so many miles
of their home.
</P>
<P>
   Autobytel and several other services also offer money-back
guarantees on used vehicles if buyers return them undamaged within
three days after driving no more than 300 miles.
</P>
<P>
   And Auto Choice (www.theautochoice.com) offers ``Build a Car''
service where consumers can fill out a form if they can't find the
vehicle they want in the listings and have the company's buying
staff scour the country for vehicles that match their requests
</P>
<P>
   Online auctions also are expanding their automotive offerings.
EBay, for example, lists about 1,500 vehicles a week and two weeks
ago signed an agreement with collector-car expert Kruse
International to set up a new online showroom of more-exotic
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
