<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PODESTA-PODESTA </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 S.F. Florist Gets Plucked by National Chain
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Peter Sinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Another legendary San Francisco business has been picked off by a
national chain.
</P>
<P>
   Podesta Baldocchi, which has been peddling flowers in San
Francisco since 1871, has been sold to Gerald Stevens Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Lauderdale, Fla., marketer of flowers and related gifts
announced yesterday that it has acquired 31 specialty florists with
$22 million in combined revenues, including Podesta's $3 million in
annual sales and Azzaro's of Fresno, which has three locations and
about $1.8 million in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its campaign to create the nation's largest flower
retailer, Gerald Stevens completed its acquisition of San
Francisco's Calyx &AMP; Corolla catalog retailer of flowers last month.
</P>
<P>
   Podesta Baldocchi now operates from Fourth Street South of
Market. But for most of the century, it operated in the heart of
San Francisco's Union Square shopping district. Every December for
decades, it was a Grant Avenue destination with its gorgeously
decorated Christmas trees.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Podesta has changed hands. Five years
ago, Michael Guelfi and his brothers Mark and Matt bought the
legendary San Francisco florist shop from Steve Podesta. Gerald
Stevens is not expected to change the Podesta Baldocchi name.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has a great game plan,'' said Podesta Baldocchi
President Guelfi. ``It is buying well-known florists around the
country and setting up a hub and spoke system, so business stays
within the company-owned network.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Gerald Stevens received its first $7 million in private
capital in May 1998 from an investment fund set up by two top
executives of Blockbuster Entertainment, it has grown quickly. In
the past 10 months, it has acquired 231 florists, including
publicly traded Florafax, whose name it changed to Gerald Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   Another key acquisition for approximately $10 million in stock
was Calyx &AMP; Corolla. During the past decade, this company pioneered
the market for next-day delivery of flowers shipped directly from
the grower. It has the most widely circulated floral catalog, with
12 million copies mailed last year, as well as a growing online
business.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Stevens Chief Administrative Officer Adam Philips said
Calyx &AMP; Corolla appeals to ``higher-end customers'' with its
fresh-picked bouquets, plants or bonsai and custom-designed
packages delivered by Federal Express. The company generated $20
million revenues last year, and its average sale is $70 compared
with $40 for the typical florist, Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Stevens is intent on delivering floral and related gift
products wherever consumers want them _ by phone, mail order,
Internet, direct from grower or visiting a store.
</P>
<P>
   Guelfi and Phillips declined to discuss the acquisition price
for Podesta Baldocchi, but industry sources estimate it sold for
about $1.4 million. Last month, Gerald Stevens also bought Jory's,
which has stores in Concord and Walnut Creek and revenues of about
$1 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3879 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-EBAY-EBAY_SFCHRON &LR;      09-07 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-EBAY </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 No Joke, Capitalism Goes Wild on eBay
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By David Lazarus &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
First it was guns. Then human kidneys. Now it's babies. Is there
any limit to what can be listed for sale at online auctioneer eBay?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, in a nutshell, is no.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way you could run a viable business by screening
300,000 new items a day,'' insisted Rob Chesnut, eBay's associate
general counsel. ``It just would be too expensive to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's why a kidney, followed by assorted other body parts,
made their way onto the site last week, and why three different
listings for babies popped up over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Without any sort of screening or filtering system in place,
eBay's nearly 6 million users are free to list any item they
choose, no matter how weird, goofy, illegal or just plain
fraudulent.
</P>
<P>
   As for eBay's legal liability, the jury's still out. But current
interpretations of the law suggest that the company cannot be held
accountable for the contents of its site.
</P>
<P>
   EBay relies for the most part on its users to police the site
themselves. When someone comes across a suspicious listing among
the nearly 2.7 million items for sale, he or she reports it to the
company, which might then close the auction.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened with the first of two kidneys posted for
sale last week, although the auction managed to avoid detection for
nearly a week and attracted no fewer than seven separate bids, the
highest reaching $5.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   EBay officials aren't saying that this was a hoax necessarily,
and they note that law-enforcement authorities in Florida, where
the seller resides, are looking into the case.
</P>
<P>
   But Chesnut said subsequent listings for other kidneys, livers
and ``a barely used brain'' were obviously ``joke auctions.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the babies, one of which drew an offer of $109,100, ``Of
course they're kidding,'' Chesnut said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the press picked up the story about the kidney, we had
lots of other people putting up similar things,'' he observed.
``One item breeds copycats.''
</P>
<P>
   Case in point, nearly a dozen other kidneys were listed for sale
as of yesterday afternoon, with one going for as much as $10
million.
</P>
<P>
   Although eBay says it can do without such publicity, Steve
Weinstein, an analyst with Pacific Crest Securities in Portland,
Ore., said reports of body parts and babies for sale only drive
more traffic to the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `Gosh I want to see that,''' he pointed out.
``It's like slowing down for a traffic accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Franco, an analyst with U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray in San
Francisco, said most eBay users haven't been fazed by these
repeated blows to the site's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like day trading,'' he said. ``You have to understand
what the risks are.''
</P>
<P>
   And eBay users are nothing if not fiercely loyal to their
favorite online flea market. EBay's chat rooms had no criticism of
the questionable sales yesterday, although there was considerable
carping about a brief interruption in the site's service on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Although eBay does not screen items before they are put up for
sale, Chesnut admitted that eBay takes steps to filter listings
after they are posted _ a fact that previously had not been
acknowledged by the company.
</P>
<P>
   But he wouldn't give any details. ``There are things we do that
we don't talk about,'' Chesnut said. ``I wouldn't want a user to
know what we look for and how we look for things.''
</P>
<P>
   Sara Zeilstra, an analyst with Warburg Dillon Read in New York,
said eBay may be reluctant to filter prior to posting an item
because this could make them responsible for vetting all listings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they police one thing,'' she said, ``they would be legally
liable for policing all things.''
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Samuelson, a law professor at the University of
California at Berkeley, cited recent cases involving online
services that established a service cannot be held accountable for
content on its site, but only as long as the service is not
actively screening material up front.
</P>
<P>
   How such precedents apply to an operation like eBay, however,
remains anyone's guess, she observed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lot of questions coming up for which there are no
certain answers,'' Samuelson said. ``Once they go down the
filtering path, how much filtering they do, and what their
responsibilities are, open up a whole can of worms.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
