<SLUG> BC-FBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEASON OF LOSERS, SOMEBODY MUST WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The 1999 NFL preview magazines are out _ I think
some were out while the 1998 season was still going on _ and
they're all picking different teams to win the Super Bowl. Sports
Illustrated likes Jacksonville, The Sporting News likes Minnesota,
and Pro Football Weekly goes with Miami (over Minnesota in its
early-summer edition, over Green Bay in its ``kickoff'' edition).
</P>
<P>
   The surprise is not that the experts pick different teams. The
surprise is that they pick anybody.
</P>
<P>
   With the Denver Broncos taken down by John Elway's retirement
and the Green Bay Packers poorer for Reggie White and Mike
Holmgren's departures, the league is sinking into a new era of
``parity,'' loosely translated as ``hey, SOMEBODY has to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Picking a super team in the NFL this season is harder than
picking a Disney Sports employee of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Some you can rule out immediately: Carolina, Chicago, Cincinnati
and the venerable expansion franchise in Cleveland. ``C'' is a
failing grade this semester.
</P>
<P>
   Others deserve no more than second glances: Philadelphia,
Detroit, Baltimore and San Diego. The Chargers felt good about
drawing ``bye'' in week one until ``bye'' was installed as an
8{-point favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the perennial underachievers: Buffalo, Kansas
City, New England and Washington. Don't waste your time with them.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with continuing this process of elimination is that
before you know it, you've eliminated everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona? It was a summer of car crashes, practice-field injuries
and contract holdouts. Quarterback Jake Plummer is ripping
management for haggling with top touchdown receiver Rob Moore.
Cinderella just called a cab.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta? With Tony Martin gone, Chris Chandler's receivers are
all 5-foot-11 and under. They'll ride a Derby winner before they
return to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas? Chan Gailey was credited with a good job as the rookie
head coach, but how long before ballhandlers Troy Aikman, Emmitt
Smith and Michael Irvin begin pining for their first coach _ Amos
Alonzo Stagg?
</P>
<P>
   Denver? Head coach Mike Shanahan has written a book on the keys
to success, with chapter titles like ``Preparing,''
``Sacrificing,'' ``Learning,'' ``Believing'' and ``Persevering.''
He left out the key to his own success: ``Having John Elway on Your
Team.''
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay? It's back to the post-dynasty days of 1968. Minus the
actual dynasty this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis? Two-thousand-yard rusher-receiver Marshall Faulk
is gone. Rookie Edgerrin James is the new ballcarrier. The Colts
can whip UCLA, but that's it.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville? Head coach Tom Coughlin has been blowing his stack
at reporters who pick the Jaguars to win it all, and players are
grumbling about his intensity. I'm happy to do my part to lower
Coughlin's blood pressure and say I give the Jaguars no shot.
</P>
<P>
   Miami? It's Don Drysdale's joke about the '60s Dodgers applied
to football: ``Did you hear? The Dolphins shut out New England.''
``Did they win?''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota? The Vikings are a couple of key injuries away from
Jeff George at quarterback and Eleanor Mondale at linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans? Mike Ditka will be gone before his Ricky Williams
gamble pays off.
</P>
<P>
   New York Giants? They'll have to improve on last year's 8-8
record to win the NFC East; 8-7-1 might be good enough in that
division.
</P>
<P>
   New York Jets? Going back to the Super Bowl III uniforms
coincided with a freakish season for 35-year-old Vinny Testaverde.
They'll need the second comings of Joe Namath, Emerson Boozer and
Heidi to overcome the league's second-strongest 1999 schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland? The Raiders will play THE strongest '99 schedule. The
good news for everybody is that they won't play it in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh? New offensive coordinator Kevin Gilbride will try to
do for Kordell Stewart what he did for Ryan Leaf last year in San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis? Head coach Dick Vermeil isn't long for this job. He
used to cry only when announcing major career decisions. Now he
cries when players get injured. Next he'll be breaking down at
``Don't Walk'' signs.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco? Signing Lawrence Phillips was the beginning of
the end for a great organization. Today you ignore your traditional
standards, and tomorrow you're the '99 Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle? Seahawks players wanted to dump the Gatorade on
Holmgren after their first exhibition victory with the new coach;
he talked them out of it. When a franchise has never won a thing,
and a city hasn't won a thing in 20 years, they must long for any
chance to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay? Two words: Trent Dilfer.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee? The team changed its name, clothes and address after
going 8-8. It didn't work _ they're still the Oilers and they're
still going 8-8.
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be an 8-8 kind of year up and down the league.
There's not a great team in the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Which might be why the NFL didn't give Los Angeles a franchise
this season. It was afraid we'd win the Super Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
