<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3881 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-VISA-VISA_SFCHRON &LR;      09-07 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISA-VISA </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Visa Shuffles Its Cards
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Sam Zuckerman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Under pressure from its bank members to slash fees, Foster City's
Visa International, the giant credit card association, soon will
begin the most dramatic reorganization in its 25-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for Visa International to cut its budget 15 to 25
percent, jettison 100 to 200 Bay Area jobs, overhaul its
organization chart and fundamentally alter the way it delivers
products and services to its six regional operating organizations,
association officials said. The savings from these changes are
unknown because Visa International's finances are not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The association's board is scheduled to consider the plan at the
end of this month. Details remain to be worked out, but the
outlines of the reorganization are already set.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the current one-size-fits-all approach, Visa's
regional affiliates, including organizations covering the United
States and European Union countries, will be able to choose from a
menu of debit and credit card systems and services, giving them
more flexibility over what they, in turn, offer the association's
21,000 bank members worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   While Visa International will continue to provide basic product
categories such as credit and debit cards, the regions will have
more freedom to develop and market their own specific products.
</P>
<P>
   The new system will be roughly analogous to cable television, in
which subscribers can pay just for a basic offering or get
additional channels by choosing from several levels of premium
service. ``Right now, we have all sorts of things bundled into Visa
International,'' said Malcolm Williamson, the association's British
president and chief executive. ``This will give people choices, so
they can decide what they want.``
</P>
<P>
   The shakeup at Visa International, which has roughly 2,500
employees locally, won't include the separate regional
organizations, including Visa U.S.A., also headquartered in Foster
City. The U.S. affiliate cut 50 positions earlier this year when it
combined separate sales functions.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring of Visa International comes at a time of
ferment in the credit card industry as large issuers, mainly U.S.
companies such as First USA and Citigroup, demand lower fees and
more control over the products they offer.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Citigroup, the world's second-largest credit
card issuer, shifted most of its new business to MasterCard after
complaining that Visa rules limited its ability to promote its own
brand and forced it to pay for advertising that pushed Visa's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a lot of restless members out there that are
becoming more concerned about their own identities,'' said James
Daley, editor of the trade magazine Credit Card Management.
</P>
<P>
   By letting regions offer members choices in products and
pricing, the reorganization responds to some of the demands of
large issuers. But Visa International also will continue to offer
complete packages to those regions that aren't prepared to do their
own product development.
</P>
<P>
   The shakeup follows a history of tension between Visa
International and its stronger regional organizations, especially
Visa U.S.A. For decades, International and U.S.A. have vied for
power, often duplicating each other's functions.
</P>
<P>
   By agreeing to move certain operations such as product
development to the regional level, Visa International is, in
effect, negotiating a peace treaty. In exchange, the regions will
recognize its authority to market the Visa brand worldwide and
provide the systems support for products developed at the regional
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be much greater clarity about Visa International's
role, and that will reduce the possibility of friction,``
Williamson said.
</P>
<P>
   Visa International's plan calls for the creation of a new
subsidiary, named ``shared services,'' that will house the computer
systems that process payments for members around the world.
Regional affiliates will have choices in pricing and service plans
when using shared services.
</P>
<P>
   International will keep centralized activities such as finance
and global marketing. The regions will pay an obligatory fee for
these common functions.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, such operations as research and development
for new products will shrink at Visa International and grow at the
regional organizations. The regions will be able to choose what
level of service they want in these areas.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization is the brainchild of Williamson, who came to
Visa International 11 months ago after serving as chief of
Britain's Standard Chartered Bank, where he helped pioneer
smart-card technology that uses an embedded computer chip to keep
track of transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson has been advocating an overhaul of Visa
International's service and fee structure since he arrived. ``He's
doing what he said he would do,'' Daley said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
