<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3976 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-PUERTORICO-CLEMENCY-1     09-07 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTORICO-CLEMENCY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
12 PUERTO RICAN NATIONALISTS ACCEPT CLEMENCY OFFER, WHITE HOUSE
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS lede to change tense, `had accepted' sted have; CORRECTS
middle name of second sister to accept clemency offer to Ida Luz
Rodriguez, sted Luis; hyphenates Camacho-Negron ;  gives name of
elder Escobar in 2nd take.) 
 (nk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House announced Tuesday that 12 jailed
members of a Puerto Rican nationalist group had accepted President
Clinton's conditional offer of clemency. Eleven will be eligible
for release within days while the 12th had his 55-year sentence
drastically reduced and will be paroled in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Two other members of the radical group, known as FALN, the
Spanish initials for the Armed Forces of National Liberation,
refused to accept the president's offer to commute their sentences.
Clinton demanded as a condition of their release that they renounce
the use of violence to achieve their aim of independence for the
Caribbean commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   Another two FALN members, who have been released from jail but
still owe tens of thousands of dollars in fines, have not yet
responded to the president's offer to forgive their penalties. They
have until Friday to accept the terms of the grant, the White House
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president expects all those who accept the conditional
clemency grant to abide fully by its terms, including refraining
from the use or advocacy of the use of violence for any purpose and
obeying all the statutory conditions of parole,'' Joe Lockhart, the
White House press secretary, said in a written statement issued
Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The acceptance of the clemency offer further roiled an emotional
political debate that has pitted Hillary Rodham Clinton against her
husband and riven the Democratic party in New York. Mrs. Clinton,
who has all but announced her intention to run for the Senate from
New York, announced her opposition to the commutations on Saturday,
saying that the Puerto Ricans had shown insufficient contrition for
their acts and those of their comrades in the independence
movement.
</P>
<P>
   The Puerto Rican nationalists are serving sentences of as long
as 90 years for offenses including sedition, possession of
unregistered firearms, interstate transportation of a stolen
vehicle, interference with interstate commerce by violence and
interstate transportation of firearms with intent to commit a
crime. None of those whose sentences Clinton planned to commute was
convicted of crimes that resulted in deaths or injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has not spoken publicly on the matter, said through
a spokesman that the sentences were out of proportion to the FALN
members' offenses and that the prisoners, some of whom have already
served 18 years in prison, deserved to be released if they forswore
future acts of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 members of the group who accepted the clemency offer,
originally announced on Aug. 11, did so after consultation with
their lawyer, Jan Susler of Chicago, who said at a news conference
Tuesday evening she was ``elated by the prisoners' impending
release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a tremendous victory and accomplishment for the
Puerto Rican people and people who love justice,'' Ms. Susler said.
</P>
<P>
   But she and another lawyer for the FALN members, Michael
Deutsch, added that they were concerned that after their release
the nationalists would be subjected to harassment by law
enforcement officials and denied the right to peaceable political
activity.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said they planned to create a network of monitors in
the United States and Puerto Rico to assure that the freed
prisoners' rights are not abridged.
</P>
<P>
   The two FALN members who rejected the president's grant of
clemency and who will remain in prison are Oscar Lopez Rivera and
Antonio Camacho-Negron.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez Rivera was convicted in Chicago in August 1981 of numerous
charges, including weapons violations and conspiracy to transport
explosives with intent to destroy government property, and was
sentenced to 70 years in prison. Clinton offered to reduce his
sentence to 44 years.
</P>
<P>
   Camacho-Negron was convicted in Connecticut in June 1989 of
conspiracy to rob a bank and foreign transportation of stolen
money. He was sentenced to 15 years in prison, which Clinton
offered to commute.
</P>
<P>
   The acceptance of the commutations further fueled the uproar
over the president's actions, which has been opposed by most law
enforcement agencies, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., numerous other lawmakers and victims of
acts of terror committed by pro-independence Puerto Ricans.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said on Saturday that the president should rescind
the clemency offer because the tardy response from the Puerto
Ricans ``speaks volumes'' about their continuing advocacy of
violence as a political weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Her opposition to the president's position angered many Puerto
Rican elected officials in New York, who accused her of betraying
them in order to appear tough on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, spokesman for the first lady's exploratory
committee, said that Mrs. Clinton understood the strong emotions on
the issue but she ``stands by her statement'' of Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said Tuesday that the Puerto Ricans have never
expressed remorse for their acts or those of their comrades in the
nationalist movement, which has been involved in more than 100
bombings of political and military installations in the United
States in the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor _ a Republican and the first lady's likely opponent in
a race to succeed Moynihan in the Senate _ said that the president
has undercut his own government's efforts to combat terrorism and
called upon the president to release files on the cases and the
recommendations from federal law enforcement officials, who
virtually unanimously opposed the grants of clemency.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can emotionally be on one side or the other of this
issue,'' Giuliani said, ``but to say that it doesn't raise some
very serious and legitimate questions and now to see his own
political allies and close associates abandoning him like a sinking
ship, you wonder what's going on here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee,
said the panel will hold hearings next week to review the clemency
offer, which he opposes.
</P>
<P>
   Some friends and relatives of the jailed Puerto Ricans were
grudging in their thanks to the president and highly critical of
Mrs. Clinton's opposition to the clemency grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an olive branch that the president has extended in the
process of reconciliation between the United States and Puerto
Rico, but it's a very scrawny one,'' said Gloria Quinones, one of
hundreds of activists and religious leaders who worked for the
release of the Puerto Rican nationalists. Ms. Quinones, of New
York, was a childhood friend of Dylcia Noemi Pagan, convicted of
conspiracy and firearms violations in 1981 and sentenced to 55
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Quinones was critical of the president's condition that none
of the prisoners meet or mingle after their release, particularly
citing the fact that two of the prisoners, Alicia Rodriguez and Ida
Luz Rodriguez, are sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way sisters should be kept away from one
another,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Quinones called Mrs. Clinton's repudiation of her husband's
clemency grant ``a real insult'' to the nearly one million Puerto
Ricans living in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``She thinks that we are politically expendable, insignificant
to her campaign,'' Ms. Quinones said. ``We'll just see about that
Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   Josefina Rodriguez of Chicago, the mother of the two sisters who
accepted the commutation of their sentences, said she was trying to
ignore the political controversy ignited by the prisoners' release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want them to come home,'' Mrs. Rodriguez said. ``I
really don't care if Hillary Clinton wins or loses.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Eli Escobar, a 24-year-old disc jockey in New York and son of
one of the prisoners, Elizam Escobar, a painter who has been in
jail for 19 years, said the prisoners and their families have been
in ``purgatory'' since the president announced the clemency grant a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the minute we found out it was a mixed reaction of
disappointment and excitement,'' Escobar said. ``We have been
waiting a long time for that but when it came there were strings
attached.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that his father has not changed his views on Puerto
Rican independence but no longer believes that terrorism is the way
to achieve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different time,'' Escobar said. ``They have gotten
older and wiser. It was more than 20 years ago. They have all
renounced violence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
