<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BINGE-DRINKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD CAMPAIGN FOCUSES ON BINGE DRINKING BY COLLEGE STUDENTS
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Pa., Ill., Mass., Ariz., N.C.)  (nk) 
 By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Along with back-to-school sales on mini-refrigerators, plastic
crates and halogen desk lamps, parents will soon be seeing an
advertisement about another dorm accessory: binge drinking.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisement, signed by 113 colleges and universities, is
scheduled to run in 17 major newspapers around the country
beginning on Friday. The National Association of State Universities
and Land-Grant Colleges, which directed the campaign, is aiming the
advertisement at parents and legislators in what it calls the first
large-scale effort to take the issue off-campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``About one-third of college students started drinking in high
school,'' said Graham Spanier, the chairman of the association's
Kellogg Commission on the Future of State and Land-Grant
Universities and president of Pennsylvania State University. ``We
hope that people will realize that it's not a problem created on or
by universities.''
</P>
<P>
   Binge drinking on campus has had its share of publicity in
recent years, after incidents like the death of a freshman at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology and drunken riots near Penn
State last year.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisement, framed as a promotion for a mock brew called
Binge Beer, alludes to such accidents: ``Who says falling off a
balcony is such a bad thing? And what's an occasional riot? Or even
a little assault between friends?''
</P>
<P>
   Colleges and universities are combating the problem of binge
drinking in a variety of ways, including banning alcohol from
fraternities and sororities. Penn State sponsors all-night
alcohol-free activities at the student union.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 survey from the Harvard School of Public Health reported
that almost 43 percent of college students said they had engaged in
binge drinking. For the study, binge drinking was defined as having
five or more drinks in succession at least once in the two weeks
before the survey, four or more drinks for women.
</P>
<P>
   Not all institutions agree with those statistics. Some colleges,
in fact, are making it a point to tell students that overindulging
is not as common as they may think. The University of Arizona is
spreading the word that most of its students have four or fewer
drinks when they party. The university hopes students will feel
less pressure to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   The University of North Carolina released a report in August
that suggested modest levels of drinking at its Chapel Hill campus.
The Highway Safety Research Center at the university administered
Breathalyzer tests to 1,800 students as they returned to their
dorms or apartments after an evening out, and found 70 percent had
no alcohol in their blood.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Foss, the manager of alcohol studies at the center, said
more studies were needed to understand how and why students drink
before placing blame or using tactics that might not work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The research just hasn't really been done yet,'' Foss said.
``In the past few years, suddenly there are a lot of efforts to
study this phenomenon. Unfortunately, people are wanting to do
something now, not to wait for the knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   The university promoted the accuracy of its Breathalyzer tests,
compared with survey interviews in which students can brag, by
distributing posters that read, ``It's not what they say, it's what
they blow.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Haines, coordinator of health enhancement services at
Northern Illinois University and a proponent of the ``social
norms'' theory of using positive peer pressure, said he did not
think the solution was scare tactics, either on campus or off.
``It's a political move to bring attention to a problem that is
being exaggerated,'' Haines said.
</P>
<P>
   In Spanier's view, politics has indeed played a role, but it has
been to keep the issue out of the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today there are some who don't want to talk about it because
they feel it would bring bad PR to the campus,'' Spanier said. ``If
they openly acknowledge there is a problem, they are afraid it
might disturb parents, that their applications might go down.''
</P>
<P>
   Spanier also sees little need for hyperbole.
</P>
<P>
   As if to mark the beginning of the school year, a Penn State
student was hospitalized last month after taking 21 shots of
alcohol in two hours, shooting her blood-alcohol level up to more
than six times the legal limit. She was celebrating her 21st
birthday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
