<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VIACOM-PROFILES-ART-2     09-07 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIACOM-PROFILES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW CBS' KARMAZIN SEDUCED VIACOM'S REDSTONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With VIACOM-CBS) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Sumner Redstone, the 76-year-old chairman and
chief executive of Viacom Inc., stepped from an elevator in the St.
Regis Hotel in midtown Manhattan on Tuesday, the man right next to
him, Melvin Karmazin, 56, president and chief executive of CBS,
appeared to be temporarily distracted.
</P>
<P>
   But after a polite second or two watching Karmazin accept the
congratulations of onlookers, Redstone turned, his eyes plainly
beseeching his new partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm right behind you, Sumner!'' Karmazin said, rushing past a
throng of photographers.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, that moment captured the complex new relationship
that now unites the two men. For while Redstone may be buying CBS
to add to Viacom's media empire and will remain as chief executive,
he is clearly depending on Karmazin to run the company for him.
</P>
<P>
   Not a man known for puppy dog-like eagerness, Karmazin, who will
serve as chief operating officer and will have all units reporting
to him, is the aggressive former radio ad salesman now widely
considered the media world's most ruthless manager and cost
slasher. Redstone, an eminence grise of the media world, is the
tireless builder who grew up in a Boston tenement during the
Depression and who transformed a handful of bedraggled movie
theaters into the country's largest privately held theater chain,
eventually buying Viacom in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The $37.3 billion deal joins not just two enormous media
companies but two oversized corporate personalities in a marriage
that was consummated after a two-year flirtation and a brief but
painstakingly intense two-week prenuptial discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seduced us,'' Redstone said of Karmazin Tuesday. ``This
began as a deal involving some television stations. Then he started
talking about cable networks. Then I could see it coming. He is a
master salesman, and he began to turn me on.''
</P>
<P>
   Raised in a housing development on Long Island, Karmazin is the
son of first-generation Americans. His father, now dead, drove a
taxi and his mother, with whom he is still very close, worked in a
curtain-rod factory. After high school, Karmazin worked days at a
tiny advertising agency and earned his undergraduate degree at Pace
University by night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is unencumbered by convention, and even running this
company has not seduced him,'' said a Los Angeles television
executive who is a close friend to Karmazin. ``He has gone from
being an ascetic who lived in a small apartment to an ascetic who
lives in a big apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   After a stretch at CBS Radio, Karmazin worked for John Kluge at
Metromedia Inc., managing radio stations in the 1970s. In 1981, he
founded Infinity Broadcasting, the broadcast company that now
distributes the shows of Don Imus and Howard Stern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call Mel the zen master,'' said Imus. ``He is a Christ-like
figure in our lives. He is the real deal. I had an opportunity when
I re-signed here a few years ago to go elsewhere for more money and
I did not even consider it. There was the loyalty factor. Mel is
enormously loyal, and so am I _ to Mel.''
</P>
<P>
   When CBS acquired Infinity in 1996, Karmazin was part of the
package. At first, he ran the combined radio operations of
Infinity, Westinghouse and CBS, along with its outdoor advertising
business. After Michael H. Jordan, then the chairman and chief
executive of CBS, appointed him to head CBS' station division,
Karmazin then became chief operating officer of the company, and in
October 1998 forced Jordan's resignation and assumed his title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mel has done this before,'' said a television executive close
to Karmazin. ``He went to Mike Jordan and said, `I want to buy your
radio stations.' Jordan said no. So Mel said, `Buy me.' This time,
he went to Sumner and said, `I want to buy Viacom.' Sumner said no,
and Mel said, `Well, then buy me. Or merge with me.' And when
Redstone is no longer CEO, Mel is there.''
</P>
<P>
   As chief executive of CBS, Karmazin trimmed the already weakened
news division's budget by 10 percent and ushered in a new round of
company-wide layoffs. He has been known to loudly question what he
perceives to be excessive lunch tabs on expense accounts. His
self-composed entry in ``Who's Who'' is brief: just under five
lines.
</P>
<P>
   While members of Karmazin's public-relations team are eager to
quash any notion that Karmazin is simply a cost-cutter, he made
several pointed references to his tight-fisted reputation. Redstone
and Karmazin, for example, said they planned to fly to Washington
Wednesday morning to meet with officials of the Federal
Communications Commission. Karmazin remarked, ``He'll fly on his
jet, and I'll take the shuttle.'' Redstone owns a Gulfstream III
jet.
</P>
<P>
   But Karmazin is not just a penny pincher. ``I have been working
with Mel for two years,'' said Leslie Moonves, the chief executive
of CBS Television, ``and he has never denied me any of the money it
took for me to get something on the screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Redstone is an equally ambitious entrepreneur who is also from a
less-than-wealthy background. His father, Max Rothstein, began a
nightclub business by buying New York City's Latin Quarter
nightclub from Lou Walters, Barbara Walters' father. (Rothstein,
not Redstone, changed the family name, said Carl Folta, a Viacom
spokesman.)
</P>
<P>
   With a degree from Harvard Law School, Redstone bought and began
to turn the National Amusements movie theater chain into a thriving
business in the 1950s and 1960s, acquiring pieces from Columbia,
MGM/UA and Loews after the studios were required to divest
themselves of theaters.
</P>
<P>
   He eventually gathered enough resources to take over Viacom in
1987, which was then an ill-defined hodgepodge of cable, broadcast
and syndication divisions. When the company was struggling, rather
than cede to pressure from advisers to sell MTV and Nickelodeon,
Redstone reduced debt by selling off assets like Madison Square
Garden and several cable systems, radio stations and book
publishers. That included an educational division of Simon &AMP;
Schuster that went to the British company Pearson PLC for a price
tag that stunned the industry: more than $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The swiftness and certainty with which the CBS-Viacom deal was
concluded confirms that both men had been eyeing each other for at
least two years, said several executives involved in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Karmazin said he first approached Redstone seriously right
after the FCC proposed in early August to relax the rules limiting
media concentration. According to executives involved in the deal,
Karmazin and CBS' chief financial officer, Fredric Reynolds, began
seeking advice the very day the FCC made its announcement.
Karmazin, a Viacom executive said, wanted to be the first to take
advantage of the new regulatory climate.
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin first suggested that CBS acquire Viacom, an executive
close to the talks said. Redstone said that he was not interested,
but that he might be willing to consider an agreement that would
keep him in control. He invited Karmazin to lunch at Viacom
headquarters in Times Square during the third week of August.
</P>
<P>
   The second meeting between the two men took place only a few
days later, and this time they were joined by Thomas Dooley and
Philippe Dauman, Viacom's deputy chairmen, who both encouraged
Redstone to seriously consider the merger. Both, paradoxically,
have now resigned, effective as soon as the merger is completed in
the early part of 2000. (But they each, a Viacom executive said,
will receive buyout packages so generous that they will be able to
buy their own Gulfstream jets.)
</P>
<P>
   After three lunches and several other meetings at Karmazin's
apartment overlooking Central Park _ at least one stretched late
into the night _ Redstone and Karmazin agreed to proceed with the
merger on Tuesday, Aug. 24, two weeks before the deal was announced
publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom's board convened twice last week to discuss the deal _
once on Thursday, and then again on Sunday over the Labor Day
weekend, when the Viacom board approved the deal.
</P>
<P>
   An executive close to the talks said that the most troublesome
point was from the legal perspective of who would run the company.
The agreement from the beginning was that Viacom would have more
board members than CBS, ``and that Sumner would be in control of
the company,'' said another executive close to the talks. ``What
the negotiations were about was how do you turn that into something
legally enforceable? `You've got day-to-day responsibility and I am
the CEO' sounds simple, but what does it really mean?''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most telling about the level of trust between the two
men is that the terms of the deal were worked out between Karmazin
and Redstone to the exclusion of almost all others; the two men
handed off their plan to the teams of lawyers and financial
advisors to allow them to thrash out the final details. As a
result, the investment bankers involved in the deal are expected to
earn only about $50 million, a relatively small sum for a merger of
this magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal would not have happened unless Mel were involved,''
Redstone said, adding that he insisted that Karmazin be chief
operating officer from the beginning of the negotiations. ``He is
brilliant. He is an entrepreneur and so am I.''
</P>
<P>
   Redstone would not comment on how long he would stay at Viacom
but suggested that he was not planning on leaving for a long time.
``I'm feeling pretty good and I have a lot of fun working at
Viacom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is fair to say that this man has not lost his
fastball,'' Karmazin said. But his glee was clearly in evidence at
Tuesday's press conference. ``This is the deal I have wanted to
make from the time I was bar-mitzvah'ed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 2318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
