u f BC-MICROSOFT-HOTELS-NYT     09-07 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-HOTELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT TO START NET HOTEL-PRICING SERVICE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imitating a competitor's patented approach, the Microsoft Corp.
is introducing an Internet service that lets consumers name their
own prices for hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The concept was an innovation of the heavily promoted
Priceline.com service, which last year introduced a system to let
people enter the prices they would be willing to pay for airline
tickets. It has since expanded to hotels, cars and mortgage loans.
</P>
<P>
   On both Priceline and the new Price Matcher service that
Microsoft is introducing Tuesday on its Expedia travel site,
consumers specify the city, dates, room rate and hotel rating (one
to five stars) they are seeking. The service picks the individual
hotel, and automatically charges the amount of the full stay to the
buyer's credit card. No refunds or changes are allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have become so enamored by the potential of this
system that Priceline, which went public last year, has a market
value of some $9.9 billion, more than any airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is looking for a way to hook onto Priceline's coat
tails,'' said Kenneth J. Orton, chief strategist at Cognititive, a
San Francisco consulting firm, and former chief executive of
Preview Travel, an Internet travel service. He said Microsoft's
move was meant to appeal more to investors than to travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while Wall Street is devoted to Priceline, consumer
reaction has been more tepid because of the restrictions that the
system imposes. If the service can find a hotel room or plane
ticket at the specified price, the consumer must buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Barton, the general manager of Expedia, said that such
restrictions are necessary to get the hotels to agree to take lower
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good for consumers because they can get great deals,''
he said. ``And it's good for hotels because they can put people
into rooms that may go empty while protecting their published price
structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Barton declined to say whether Microsoft would introduce a
similar system for airline tickets and car rentals, but he said
there was no reason that it would not if the hotel offering was
successful.
</P>
<P>
   One factor, however, that might impede Microsoft is that
Priceline has been granted a patent on the central mechanism of its
system: the concept of a ``conditional purchase offer'' in which a
consumer is committed to buy something if the seller can meet their
specifications.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Ek, a spokesman for Priceline, said that the company had
not licensed its patent to Microsoft and that the company was still
studying the Microsoft site to see if it was an infringement on its
patent.
</P>
<P>
   Barton, of Microsoft, declined to comment on Priceline's patent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both Priceline and Expedia buy blocks of hotel rooms at
wholesale rates and then sell them to those who bid higher prices.
There is a well-developed market for such bulk purchases of hotel
rooms, since hotels are willing to take less money in return for a
volume purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Meristar Hotels and Resorts, which operates 218 hotels under the
Hilton, Sheraton, Radisson and other brands, now sells 1 percent to
2 percent of its rooms through Priceline, said David McCaslin, its
president. It will also take part in the Microsoft program, but
McCaslin said he did not expect such a sales approach to dominate
the hotel industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do your job properly, you will create your own
demand,'' he said. ``But I don't think any hotel is so good they
are selling out at full rate 365 days a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Expedia already books reservations online through more
conventional models. In the second quarter, it sold $183 million
worth of air travel, hotel rooms and car rentals. In addition to
receiving commissions on those sales _ often $5 or $10 for airline
tickets _ it sells advertising and other promotional opportunities
to travel providers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 2325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0421 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3995 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-VIACOM-CBS-1STLD-WRIT     09-07 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIACOM-CBS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIACOM SET TO ACQUIRE CBS IN BIGGEST MEDIA MERGER EVER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS: Inserts `president and' in 3rd graf; rewrites 4th graf;
inserts stock values in 5th graf; inserts closing stock prices in
10th graf; inserts new 12th graf, bgng The boards of...)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphics are
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Viacom Inc. said Tuesday that it would acquire CBS
Inc. for $37.3 billion, a deal that is the biggest media merger yet
and would create the world's second-largest media company after
Time Warner Inc.
</P>
<P>
   For Viacom and its 76-year-old chairman, Sumner Redstone, who
will run the combined companies if the merger is completed, the
deal adds a major broadcast television network, 15 CBS-owned
television stations and the nation's biggest group of radio
stations to a media portfolio that includes the highly profitable
MTV, VH1 and Nickelodeon cable networks, the Paramount film studio
and the Blockbuster video-rental chain.
</P>
<P>
   CBS' 56-year-old chief executive, Mel Karmazin, will become
Redstone's second-in-command and heir apparent, as president and
chief operating officer, and all units of Viacom and CBS will
report to him.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition signals another change in the ownership of the
three once-independent major broadcasting networks. NBC has been
owned by General Electric since 1985, and ABC was bought in 1995 by
Walt Disney Co. for $19 billion _ the previous record for a media
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps even more significant than Viacom's ascension to
second-largest media company _ with a stock market value of about
$72 billion, compared with Time Warner's $80.5 billion _ Viacom
could very likely emerge as the world's largest seller of
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the television and radio properties, Viacom's
acquisition includes CBS' pending deal to acquire the billboard
giant Outdoor Systems Inc. Analysts estimate that a combined
Viacom-CBS would generate $11 billion a year in advertising _
nearly twice that of the current leader, Rupert Murdoch's News
Corp., which sells $5.8 billion in annual advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom's cable networks are popular with children, teens and
young adults, while CBS' emphasis on television news and prime-time
fare like ``Touched by an Angel'' have tended to attract older
viewers. Bringing the children's program ``Rugrats'' and the
sophisticated news magazine ``60 Minutes'' under a single corporate
nameplate is meant to offer advertisers one-stop shopping to reach
audiences of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be global leaders in virtually every facet of the
wonderful, diverse media and entertainment industry,'' predicted
Redstone, who has built Viacom into one of the world's most
successful entertainment companies since acquiring it 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   CBS shareholders will get 1.085 Class B shares of Viacom stock
for each share of CBS, an offer worth about $50.93 a share at
Tuesday's closing price of Viacom stock, and including no premium
above CBS' current market value. Viacom will assume about $1.4
billion of CBS debt.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies' stock prices rose on Tuesday's news. CBS gained
$1.75, to $50.6875; Viacom's class B shares rose $1.875, to
$46.9375. And analysts almost universally lauded the deal, not just
for its size and global scope, but for the complementary fit
between the young-skewing audiences of Viacom's cable networks and
the older audiences of CBS.
</P>
<P>
   As Fred Moran, an analyst at the investment firm ING Barings,
said, ``You can literally pick an advertiser's needs and market
that advertiser across all the demographic profiles, from
Nickelodeon with the youngest consumers to CBS with some of the
oldest consumers, and with the Country Music Network, the Nashville
Network, MTV and VH1 right in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   The boards of both companies unanimously approved the deal, but
CBS shareholders must still vote on the merger. Redstone has
control of Viacom's class A stock, which are the voting shares. The
companies expect the deal to be completed early next year, assuming
the Federal Communications Commission signs off on the merger.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The new company will be called Viacom, but the CBS television
network and all its units will continue to be called CBS. And
viewers will not suddenly find music videos appearing on CBS;
indeed, both Redstone and Karmazin said Tuesday that CBS News, CBS
Entertainment and CBS Sports will continue to be run much the way
they have been, under the leadership of Leslie Moonves, who is to
continue overseeing them.
</P>
<P>
   But the merger could mean, for example, that Viacom's MTV and
VH-1 music cable channels will find new outlets for their
programming on CBS' rock radio stations around the country _ just
as CBS' own cable channels, Country Music Television and The
Nashville Network, now provide programs for some of CBS'
country-music radio stations. And each will heavily promote its
sister networks.
</P>
<P>
   And promotional spots on MTV or VH-1 could induce some younger
viewers to sample shows on CBS, helping the broadcast network
eventually attract more of the 18-to-49-year-old audience that
advertisers pay the biggest premiums to reach.
</P>
<P>
   The merger could also mean that Nickelodeon _ the most
profitable children's network, whether broadcast or cable _ would
provide programming to help bolster CBS' little-watched
Saturday-morning children's lineup.
</P>
<P>
   On the new media front, several of Viacom's networks, notably
MTV and Nickelodeon, have well-established and very popular Web
sites. Karmazin said Tuesday that it was his goal to make
Viacom-CBS one of the leading new media companies, adding that this
goal could be given a substantial boost by the promotional
opportunities available through the company's television and radio
networks and its outdoor advertising unit, the largest in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The new company will have to divest itself of some broadcast
properties, or seek waivers from federal regulations. Redstone and
Karmazin said they would visit the Federal Communications
Commission Wednesday to appeal for changes in certain rules.
</P>
<P>
   The most important, to them, is the cap on television station
ownership, which restricts any company to owning stations that
reach no more than 35 percent of the country's population.
</P>
<P>
   With Viacom's 19 television stations and CBS' 15, the combined
company would own stations in 18 of the nation's top 20 markets and
reach 41 percent of the population. If the cap is not raised,
Karmazin said, the company will probably sell some stations to
comply with the regulations.
</P>
<P>
   But Karmazin and Redstone spoke of their eagerness to create new
business opportunities out of their six potential duopolies _
ownership of two stations in the same market. They have six such
potential duopolies, in Philadelphia, Boston, Detroit, Dallas,
Miami and Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom also owns half of the UPN broadcast network, with
Chris-Craft, and under FCC rules that stake must be reduced to less
than one-third (unless an FCC waiver is granted).
</P>
<P>
   Redstone took pains to point out that UPN, which has struggled
with small audiences for most of its existence, has been ``doing
much better'' with a new focus on young male audiences.
</P>
<P>
   For the CBS television network, an important Viacom asset is
Paramount, the studio that produced the film ``Titanic'' and the
television show ``Frasier'' (on NBC), and that will now undoubtedly
create more television shows for CBS.
</P>
<P>
   But Moonves said Tuesday that he saw the model being more like
the Fox network's relationship with its corporate sibling,
Twentieth Television, than like ABC's dealings with Disney. Disney
recently combined management of its television studio and broadcast
network, with the goal of producing more hits for ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's sister studio, in contrast, produces shows for all the
networks, and Moonves said he expected Paramount to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we did feel like a second-class citizen,'' he said, ``when
we saw the advantages ABC-Disney had, and Fox had, and even the WB
had, having a direct link to a studio.'' The WB network is linked
to the Warner Brothers studio, and both are owned by Time-Warner.
</P>
<P>
   NBC is now the only one of the six major broadcast networks
without a major production studio in its corporate family.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and television industry executives were struck by
Redstone's solution to what had been a longstanding problem at
Viacom, the absence of a clear successor to the founder.
</P>
<P>
   Although Redstone has no plans to retire (and Karmazin said,
``Believe me, this guy still has his fastball''), the older man
said the merger was contingent upon Karmazin's consent to become
his heir apparent.
</P>
<P>
   That decision forced Redstone's two longtime deputies, Philippe
Dauman and Thomas Dooley, to resign. Both men urged him to make the
deal, Redstone said, and will stay on the new Viacom's board of
directors, but not as employees.
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin and Redstone said they expected no layoffs to result
from the merger.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, Karmazin is admired for combining tight
financial controls with a willingness to take entrepreneurial bets.
Analysts note that he has sharply improved the financial
performance of the CBS TV stations and affiliates, while also
aggressively increasing the CBS investments in Internet properties.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Reif Cohen, an analyst with Merrill Lynch, and
Christopher Dixon, an analyst at Paine Webber, both predicted that
the new company would be one of the fastest-growing media companies
in the world, because of its blend of assets and its relatively low
debt, which would enable it to invest in expanding its assets,
acquiring new ones or buying back stock.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom and CBS, other analysts noted, are following the lead of
earlier deals like Disney's purchase of Capital Cities/ABC Inc. and
Time Warner's acquisition of Turner Broadcasting. The merger
impulse is driven by the belief that at a time of increasing
uncertainty in the media business, there is an advantage in owning
both the programming and the distribution networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are bet-hedging mergers in some ways,'' observed David
Nadler, chairman of Delta Consulting Group Inc., a management
consulting firm. The challenge ``is how to make these very large
companies with complex sets of relationships work in ways that pay
off,'' Nadler said. ``Just owning a bunch of different properties
doesn't mean you get the profit-making synergies that executives
talk about when they announce these mergers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
