<DOCNO> NYT19990907.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4005 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-SOSA-ART-2TAKES-N     09-07 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SOSA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT HOMER RACE, II: SOSA LEADS THIS TIME
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ They start three hours before game time, behind the
ivy-covered wall of Wrigley Field, under the right-field bleachers,
in the batting cage. This is where home run swings are built.
</P>
<P>
   It's just two men, Sammy Sosa and his hitting coach, alone
except for the shotgun sound of white ash on horsehide. Between
underhand tosses from eight paces, the coach, Jeff Pentland, passes
on the mantras he learned from studying Ted Williams. ``Stay
back.'' ``Give yourself time to recognize the pitch.'' ``Stay
within yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   In his white pinstriped uniform pants and a blue sleeveless
T-shirt, Sosa swings intently but easily, driving the ball into the
net. It's five more swings, then two more, then end on a good one.
</P>
<P>
   ``How was that?'' Sosa asks. Pentland answers through his
chewing tobacco, ``Ninety-nine percent.''
</P>
<P>
   A once-a-generation event is happening for the second straight
year. The sluggers who entertained baseball fans and the nation
last summer, Mark McGwire of the St. Louis Cardinals and Sosa of
the Chicago Cubs, are again within reach of the record for most
home runs in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time the leader is Sammy Sosa. With less than one
month to go, Sosa leads McGwire, 58 to 54. No one-hit wonder, Sosa
is excelling on a team so dreadful that Cubs fans have changed that
old baseball lament to ``Wait till next century.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's just warming up. Sosa, who did not homer in a
doubleheader against Cincinnati on Tuesday, needs to hit a home run
every other day to reach McGwire's record of 70; that's just what
he has done over the past month. If he were to hit as many in the
Cubs' remaining 24 games as he has hit in the past 24 games, Sosa
would finish with a record 73.
</P>
<P>
   The McGwire-Sosa reprise provides a second chance for those who
rooted for Sosa _ because he was the underdog, or because he wasn't
pumping up his muscles with questionable substances, or just
because he was having so much fun.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago on Sept. 7, McGwire bested Babe Ruth's 1927 mark of
60 home runs. The next day, he made obsolete Roger Maris' 1961
record of 61. Then began the friendly competition with Sosa, who
finished at 66 homers while McGwire pushed on to 70.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is a perennial, but few expected Sosa to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   Before this season, 43 baseball fans in Chicago, mostly office
workers in the downtown Loop, got together in a home run pool. In
picking their roster of players, they were limited to only one of
last year's leaders. Out of 43 fans, in Chicago, only six chose
Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe he's done it again this year,'' said one of
the entrants, Mike Olah, 28, who works for an investment firm.
``The winds seemed to be blowing the Cubs' way last year, and I
figured that was the case for Sammy, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans saw how Sosa spent his vacation: throwing out the first
pitch at the World Series, parading through New York City, helping
the victims of a hurricane in his native Dominican Republic,
lighting the national Christmas tree, touring Japan, sitting with
the first lady at the State of the Union message and joking with
Jay Leno.
</P>
<P>
   And fans see Slammin' Sammy's exuberance during the game. How he
starts the game sprinting to his position in right field, swapping
salutes with the Bleacher Bums. How, in the first inning, he taps
the umpire and the catcher on the back of the leg with his bat,
just to say hello. How he follows a home run pop with a hop high in
the air, and then, back in the dugout, blows kisses to the camera
for his family.
</P>
<P>
   Fans do not see Sosa's preparation for the game. Before noon,
hours before an afternoon game at Wrigley, this is usually the time
for rookies and old men. At third base, 23-year-old Cole Liniak is
taking groundballs, hoping his first week in the majors won't be
his last. At the gate on Waveland Avenue, Marty Mahinsk, 77, is
stacking up programs to sell, as he has since 1939.
</P>
<P>
   In the cage, the 30-year-old Sosa is working on his swing, as
Pentland's mantras continue. ``The hands,'' he says, ``are the
communicators to the ball.'' The batting practice on the field just
before the game is for timing. But the time in the cage is for the
swing.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the time to shed bad feelings after a strikeout or
another Cubs loss. For Sosa is in danger of breaking another
record: Never has a player hit more home runs than his team has won
games. So far, Sosa leads the Cubs by two.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very emotional person, and he tends to be moody,''
Pentland said. ``When he's in a bad mood, he wants to be by
himself. But it doesn't affect his production on the field. He has
incredible inner drive. The greater the pressure, the greater his
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a most dismal year in a dismal century for his
last-place Cubs. Everyone is being nice to the manager, because
he's not expected to be back next year. The problem areas seem to
be pitching, hitting and fielding.
</P>
<P>
   During a game this summer, as fans tell the story, a Bleacher
Bum in right field called over an usher. ``These guys are bothering
me,'' he said. ``Which guys?'' the usher asked. The fan pointed to
the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Not all great home run hitters have played on great teams. For
every Ruth and Maris and Mickey Mantle, there is a Ralph Kiner of
the Pittsburgh Pirates of the 1940s, a Jimmie Foxx of the
Philadelphia Athletics of 1932 and a Willie Mays of the New York
Giants of 1955.
</P>
<P>
   Even playing for losers, Sosa and McGwire are drawing the
largest crowds on the road. But there is no mania, no bidding for
the home run balls, no tax ruling from the Internal Revenue Service
on what they might be worth. It's as if the nation has been
inoculated against outright home run fever.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is possible the home run is being devalued by its frequency,
the product of weak pitching in an expanding league. In a single
game on Friday night in Philadelphia, the Cincinnati players hit
nine home runs. In more than a century of baseball, only 29 times
has a player hit 50 or more home runs in a season; 12 of those
seasons have happened in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But home run inflation doesn't explain why Sosa and McGwire are
one-third ahead of the other players in baseball. In their National
League, Jeff Bagwell of Houston was third in home runs with 39
before Tuesday's games. In the American League, Rafael Palmeiro of
Texas and Ken Griffey Jr. of Seattle had 42. No one is close to
``those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good'' is Billy Williams' short explanation. Williams,
a Hall of Fame player and Sosa's first hitting coach with the Cubs,
has a longer answer, too: ``They're strong. They're quick. And
every pitcher is told to keep the ball down, to guard against the
home run. Those guys are low-ball hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   A fan can compare their swings six more times this season.
McGwire's Cardinals and Sosa's Cubs play three games in Chicago,
Sept. 20-22, and the last three games of the season, Oct. 1-3, in
St. Louis. (That first game will be played on McGwire's 36th
birthday.) Both managers say they will pitch to the other team's
slugger, if the other team pitches to their guy.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball statisticians believe a new home run record is
attainable. The detail: Sosa has 24 games to go. Extrapolation: In
his previous 24 games, he has hit 15 home runs (result: 73).
Extrapolation: In his final 24 games last year, he hit 11 (result:
69). McGwire has 22 games to go; in his previous 22 games, he has
hit seven (result: 61); in his final 22 games last year, he hit 11
(result: 65.)
</P>
<P>
   The failure of both teams has brought criticism of Sosa and
McGwire from some fans and commentators, who suggest that their
spectacular performances have somehow hurt their teams. While Sosa
and McGwire are among the league leaders in RBIs, Sosa leads in
strikeouts, with McGwire not far down the list.
</P>
<P>
   Strikeouts are common for home run hitters _ Ruth had 1,330,
enough to fill three full seasons _ but some suggest the two
players are a little selfish, swinging for the home run when a more
cautious swing for a single might help the team more. Or perhaps
their excellence is distracting their teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa doesn't follow that logic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pay me to do my job,'' he said. ``Just because the team
is struggling, it doesn't mean I have to be struggling. If
everybody had 57 home runs right now, we would be in first place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 2348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
