<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATADORS HOPE KEY DEFENDERS MAKE TRIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ In a few days, the Cal State Northridge football
team will be getting on a plane to Kansas. Whether Mel Miller or
Kaleon Green will be on that flight remains in question.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, CSUN's starting cornerback last year, and Green, a
starting linebacker in 1997 who sat out all of last season with a
broken leg, haven't been cleared to join the Matadors. Miller is
waiting to become academically eligible and Green hasn't heard from
the NCAA regarding his appeal for a sixth season of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN needs to have Miller and Green _ two of the Matadors' best
defensive players _ against the Jayhawks. Kansas features senior
quarterback Zac Wegner, who ranks seventh in school history in
passing yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The paperwork for (Miller's) scholarship hasn't been processed
yet,'' CSUN interim head coach Jeff Kearin said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin is optimistic both players will play at Kansas; their
names are among the 58 Matadors who are on the traveling roster for
KU. Miller didn't attend practice Tuesday, but Green did.
</P>
<P>
   Green, a senior who attended Missouri for the spring 1997
semester but quit after he felt the Tigers' coaches were giving
preferential treatment to another player, has been eying the Kansas
game for his return to action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know (Missouri coaches) are going to be looking at that game
film,'' Green said last week. ``I'm going to be doing some extra
pushups to get ready for Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Now, like Miller, all Green can do is sweat out the next two
days.
</P>
<P>
   __ Slight scare: Sophomore quarterback Marcus Brady hurt his
right ankle late in CSUN's season-opening win over Western Oregon
but will be ready to play Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Brady) was limping a little Sunday, he was limping a lot
Monday,'' Kearin said. ``We're going to go easy on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady's ankle appeared to be holding up, but he said he might
not practice today.
</P>
<P>
   __ Tough loss: After sitting out almost two weeks of practice
after straining his right hamstring in August, sophomore safety
Hassan Abdul-Malik thought he was completely healthy for Western
Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   But Abdul-Malik only made it through two series before
aggravating the injury. He missed the rest of the game and isn't
expected to return for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I practiced hard the whole week,'' Abdul-Malik said. ``I felt
good. (But) that was the first full contact I had. I have to take
it day by day now and see how it feels.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Homecoming: Terrance Johnson, CSUN's linebackers coach, is
from Kansas City and was a Jayhawks recruit in the mid-1980s before
going to Colorado. Johnson said he's hoping to have 30 or 40 family
members and friends come to Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how many ``depends on how many passes I can get,'' said
Johnson, who added his father is flying in from Delaware for the
game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
