<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4021 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TRUMP-U.N.-TOWER-ART-     09-07 1366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMP-U.N.-TOWER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICH NEIGHBORS FIGHT TRUMP OVER RESIDENTIAL TOWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Visions of a very tall building are tormenting
Alberto W. Vilar, whose name is not often in the papers and who
likes it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense of proportion, my sense of esthetics, my sense of
landscape for New York just said this is wrong!'' declared Vilar,
an investment manager who runs a $5 billion high-tech fund and a
philanthropist who recently gave more than $30 million to the
Metropolitan Opera.
</P>
<P>
   If it goes up as planned, the cause of Vilar's torment will be
the tallest residential tower in the world. Rising now on First
Avenue between East 47th and 48th Streets, it is the latest
neck-wrenching, glass-skinned, marble-lobbied condominium
confection of Donald Trump, the developer who loves to get his name
in the papers and who says he takes particular pleasure in
tormenting rich people like Vilar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who the hell is Trump to go around changing the landscape of
New York?'' asked Vilar, who has put up $100,000 for a campaign
against the 72-story building, called Trump World Tower. In league
with his East Side neighbors, many of whom are also enormously
rich, Vilar vows that he has just begun to write checks.
</P>
<P>
   Another unpleasant thing about Trump World Tower: It would block
Vilar's view of the Empire State Building as seen from the living
room of his 30-room four-plex apartment. The obstructed view,
though, is ``no big deal,'' Vilar said. ``To me it is a question of
esthetic outrage.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump, upon learning of Vilar's esthetic outrage and his
troubled view, squirmed with delight. ``Rich people don't like
losing their view _ that is pure and simple what this is all
about,'' said Trump, who lives atop Trump Tower on Fifth Avenue in
a triplex with commanding views of Central Park and southern
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Squabbling among people of means over private views and public
space is perhaps Manhattan's longest-playing and highest-stakes
sport. It has sculptured the skyline of a city that has more tall
buildings than any other place on earth. The very rules of the
sport _ New York City zoning law _ have been written in response to
sharp-elbowed disputes over tall buildings like the one that is
swirling around Trump World Tower.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The city's first zoning law was prompted, in large measure, by a
tall-building fight that foreshadowed the dispute over Trump's
building on First Avenue. The principal player in that pre-World
War I fight was a vainglorious developer, T. Coleman Du Pont, who,
in a prescient imitation of Trump, boasted that his buildings were
the biggest and best in the world.
</P>
<P>
   When moneyed opponents of Du Pont's planned 39-story Equitable
Building on lower Broadway offered him $2.5 million to cap
construction at eight stories, he laughed. Du Pont prevailed, but
his hulking office building and his braggadocio speeded passage of
the city's first zoning law in 1916.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Trump has won approval from city agencies for his building,
although opponents contend that the city misread its own complex
zoning laws in approving such a tall building in a residential
neighborhood. So far, he has put up two floors of it.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the Giuliani administration proposed a major overhaul
of zoning laws that would impose limits on the height of
skyscrapers. The law, if passed, will not affect projects already
approved, like Trump's. But if the law had been in effect when
Trump proposed his new project, it would have been ruled illegal,
said Joseph B. Rose, chairman of the city Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Trump World Towers, though, has not quite yet managed to slip
past the gate. There is one last municipal obstacle, a hearing this
month before the Board of Standards and Appeals, prompted by the
building's opponents.
</P>
<P>
   If Trump prevails there, as seems likely, opponents of the tower
say they will go to court and spend whatever it takes, for as long
as it takes, to stop the building from rising to its planned 861
feet or, if need be, to lop off some of its top floors after it is
built.
</P>
<P>
   The principal strategic problem for Trump's adversaries is that
they showed up late for the fight. Trump obtained city approval of
the tower without public hearings or environmental studies. He
quietly bought air rights from nearby buildings in a way that
allowed him to increase his tower's height without public approval.
After a period of uncharacteristic quietude, Trump reverted to
form, boasting about his cleverness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I don't know who this man is,'' Trump said in reference
to Vilar. ``But if his views are blocked bad enough and if he has
got enough money, I hope he can buy an apartment in my new
building, or perhaps it will be sold out before he gets a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The opposition did begin haltingly. Vilar and his neighbors
were, at first, stunned by the proposed size of the tower, which
would dwarf all the other buildings in the area, including the
nearby 39-story U.N. complex.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It took the opposition leaders a few months to mobilize their
neighbors. But they have since assembled the standard arsenal for
all-out real-estate war in the city: celebrities, a
public-relations firm, architectural groups, lawyers and a pot of
money.
</P>
<P>
   The opponents have raised and spent nearly $400,000, said
Seymour Flug, president of the Beekman Hill Association, former
chairman of Diners Club and chief organizer of the stop-Trump
effort. Besides Vilar's promise of ``whatever it costs,'' Flug (who
lives next door to Vilar, but whose view would not be affected by
Trump's tower) said opponents of the tower expected money from
wealthy supporters, many of whom live in the same luxury co-op
building, U.N.Plaza on 49th Street, across First Avenue from
Trump's building.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the building include David Koch, the oil
billionaire; Victoria Newhouse, wife of the publisher S.I.
Newhouse; Walter B. Wriston, the former chairman of Citibank, and
William H. Donaldson, the founding partner of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette Securities. All oppose Trump's tower.
</P>
<P>
   The household name in this fight is Walter Cronkite. When
Cronkite, the retired CBS News anchorman, testified as the first
witness against the tower at a city hearing in June, a lawyer for
the opposition introduced him as ``one of the most beloved men in
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite, 82, lives in an apartment on the 25th floor of 870
U.N. Plaza and concedes that he ``won't like it'' when the tower
blocks his view of the Chrysler Building. But his opposition to
Trump, he said at the hearing, was based on much more than the loss
of a view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most importantly, this protest is supported by a whole lot
more less-than-wealthy folks who are sharply offended by the
unnecessary grossness of this project,'' Cronkite said at the
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Trump accuses Flug of ``wheeling out Cronkite and using him to a
fare-thee-well. Walter is a man of prestige and Sy Flug isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Trump has leaned on business associates to
disassociate themselves from his opponents. He called executives at
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, which often does work for his
company, and complained about Donaldson's opposition. ``I was
surprised that a man in that firm would be doing it,'' Trump said.
``I never took work away from them or threatened them in any way,
shape or form.''
</P>
<P>
   What angers many opponents of the Trump building is the silence
of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. He has refused to venture any opinion on
the issue, saying it is a ``very complicated legal question'' that
will end up in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a mayor who takes an outspoken position on every issue
that comes in front of him,'' Flug complained. ``But on this he has
nothing to say. The mayor's silence is a way of absolutely repaying
Trump, who is a huge contributor.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked for comment, the mayor's office called Flug's statement
``an unfortunate mischaracterization.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-99 2358EDT &QL; 
